<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL-ROCKED GOPHERS GO DOWN GAMELY AGAINST GONZAGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Minnesota went by the book.
</P>
<P>
   No homework, no mercy, no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   For the Golden Gophers, the NCAA West sub-regional Thursday was
double-elimination: First the hint of impropriety stopped them,
then Gonzaga. The former was a far more convincing foe.
</P>
<P>
   This much can be said. For 48 hours in Seattle, the Big Ten
entry made things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota returned home a 75-63 first-round loser, but not
before it had drawn national headlines for scandal and exhausted
every possible means for an improbable upset.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before tipoff, the Gophers suspended four players amid
allegations of long-term academic fraud in the program. Injury the
day before robbed them of yet another body.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the eight-man basketball carcass that remained _ mostly
freshmen and sophomoresn _ was able to squeeze a 21-point deficit
to just two with 1:43 remaining at KeyArena. Finally, the Gophers
were put out of their misery by their free-shooting opponent from
Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of my team,'' embattled Minnesota coach Clem
Haskins said. ``We competed and we did not quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Gophers study in an appropriate manner, according to
reports in the St. Paul Pioneer Press and verified by school
officials. And this startling revelation, that an academic
counseling employee took tests and wrote papers for players for
several seasons, could cost them a coach and a return trip to the
NCAA tourney any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, emerging from this vitriolic mess was Gonzaga with its
first NCAA postseason victory and its first win over a Big Ten
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags, improving to 27-6 and advancing to the next round
against Stanford, never trailed and gradually built a 51-30
advantage. They bombed away from the 3-point line, with guard
Richie Frahm hitting 5-of-11 trey attempts en route to a game-best
26 points. But he and his teammates nearly let it all slip away at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead just 65-63 with 1:43 remaining, Frahm took a big chance.
The 6-5 junior from Battle Ground let one fly near the Gonzaga
bench. The net rippled. That sent the Zags on a 10-0 run to finish
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still shocked that I shot it,'' Frahm admitted later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He willed that one in,'' said fellow junior guard Matt
Santangelo, who added 14 points to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   There were awkward moments from start to finish. The Gophers
took the floor amid boos and catcalls. Gonzaga students held up a
sign that said: ``Zags write their own papers!''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's four suspended players, including normal starters
Kevin Clark and Miles Tarver, sat glumly at the end of the bench.
Each was dressed in black and white sweats, which clashed
noticeably with the rest of the team's maroon and gold warmups.
Kind of like inmate garb.
</P>
<P>
   The Gophers replaced their regulars with 6-7 freshman Dusty
Rychart and 6-2 sophomore Mitch Ohnstad. Each had started one game
previously. Rychart had scored just 57 points all season. For subs,
Minnesota turned to little-used freshmen Terrance Simmons and John
Aune, who had appeared in 15 and three games, respectively. Aune
had scored just one point. Not exactly Final Four material.
</P>
<P>
   Things got comical at times. Freshman Nick Sinville, caught
underneath the basket, panicked and threw one over everyone's heads
for a midcourt violation. Quincy Lewis, the Gophers' leading scorer
and lone senior available, connected on just 3-of-19 shots, often
firing wildly and with no conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what would happen,'' Ohnstad said.
</P>
<P>
   Rychart, however, stepped up to the surprise of virtually
everyone. The walk-on from Grand Rapids, Minn., got stuffed a
couple of times underneath, but kept battling. He scored 23 points
and grabbed 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually contribute by playing good defense and getting
hustle points,'' he said. ``Tonight, the rules changed a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not the best choice of words, considering Minnesota's
predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The Gophers eventually lost starters Joel Pryzbilla and Kevin
Nathaniel on fouls, to finish with just six players. It wasn't a
fair fight, but they hung in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' Lewis said. ``Basically, those were three or
four seniors we lost. Let's just leave it at that. I was glad to be
part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskins was shaking hands with Gonzaga coach Dan Monson before
the buzzer sounded, apparently eager to distance himself from a
lost week in Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
