DiMAGGIO MET THE `CHALLENGE' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Media mayhem while attacking March Madness through
CBS SportsLine (updates every 90 seconds on Auburn's runaway
against Winthrop) and Broadcast.com (to drop in on a radio listen
of Louisville-Creighton) with an eye on the CBS (the Arkansas-Siena
generic feed) and, frantically, over to DirecTV (for Gonzaga's
shot-fest against Minnesota that CBS wouldn't show after the first
half):
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone: Imagine what it would take in today's media
climate to lure a retired superstar athlete to stop by and
participate on a TV sports trivia quiz show.
</P>
<P>
   The closest we seem to get is an occasional ``Wheel of Fortune''
with Kevin Greene.
</P>
<P>
   But back in the early '70s, Dick Enberg hosted the syndicated
``Sports Challenge'' for three years, drawing guests like Joe
DiMaggio, Mickey Mantle, Muhammad Ali, Sugar Ray Robinson, Bill
Russell, Joe Namath and Paul Hornung. All they were given was a
ride from the airport to the KTLA studio in Hollywood and a
$1,000-a-show stipend.
</P>
<P>
   The media-shy DiMaggio appeared on a couple of ``Sports
Challenge'' episodes that have aired on ESPN Classic this week in
tribute of the former New York Yankees great _ and that's something
even Enberg has a tough time believing could be ever pulled off
again with an athlete of DiMaggio's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have up to 20 former greats in that green room, some
waiting to go on, some who already (had been) on, some the mystery
guests, and they all enjoyed the camaraderie,'' Enberg said from
his home near San Diego before jetting off to do NBC's PGA coverage
of the Honda Classic in Coral Springs, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'd be DiMaggio kibitzing with Johnny Unitas and Joe
Louis. We would bring about 100 kids into the studio to watch the
shows because they'd cheer loudly. But we didn't let fans come in
(the green room) and there were only a few producers. I think they
looked forward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what a treat for me to meet all my heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   Those reunions, Enberg reminded, were what led directly to the
creation of the Curt Gowdy-hosted series ``The Way It Was.''
</P>
<P>
   Enberg believes it was the coaxing of former Yankees teammate
Tommy Henrich that led to DiMaggio's appearance, as well as his
brother, Dom, coming on with some Red Sox teammates to compete
against the Joe McCarthy Yankees. The mystery guest that show,
incidentally, was the DiMaggios' other brother, Vince.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN Classic has another airing of the ``Sports Challenge'' when
DiMaggio's Yankees competed against the 1956 Yankees with Mantle,
Billy Martin and Hank Bauer at 12:45 p.m. on Saturday, which is in
the middle of a six-hour DiMaggio tribute block (9 a.m. to 3 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Those shows, looking at them now, were really ahead of their
time because of the rear-projection image behind the two panels
showing the film highlights as the players watched,'' Enberg said.
``No one had ever done it then. I'm pleased with the way they
really hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Enberg-DiMaggio moment: When Enberg was the Angels'
play-by-play man, one of his duties was to do three eight-minute
interviews in a minimal-production half-hour pregame show leading
up to the telecast.
</P>
<P>
   During an Angels game in Oakland in 1968, Enberg got to sit down
with then-A's batting instructor DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the few times I was truly tongue-tied,'' said
Enberg. ``I'm trying to introduce him, and finally I had to stop
and look into the camera and say, `Folks, this one of my heroes,'
and we just did the interview from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, I thanked him for coming on. And he said, `Was I
OK?' I'm thinking, `Were (begin ital)you(end ital) OK?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget how his greatness always befuddled him and
he never seemed comfortable wearing it. It was only as he grew
older and matured into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Postscript: This is how Life magazine described the young
DiMaggio in a 1939 profile:
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he learned Italian first, Joe, now 24, speaks English
without an accent and is otherwise well adapted to most U.S. mores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of olive oil or smelly bear grease, he keeps his hair
slick with water. He never reeks of garlic and prefers chicken chow
mein to spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   Try writing (begin ital)that(end ital) today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   The March 22 issue of Forbes offers its first ``Power 100''
celebrity list, an attempt to rank how income plus ``media buzz''
(exposure on the Web, radio and TV, magazine covers and press
clippings) determine what celebs have the best future earnings
clout. Meaning that, even though Jerry Seinfeld was far and away
the show biz's wage-earning champ with $267 million last year, he's
got no juice next to one of sports' most recent retirees. Among
those sports figures on the list who made the top 25 power
ranking: &QL; 
1. Michael Jordan: Made $69 million last year to rank seventh, but
with more than 40,000 press clips and seven magazine covers, he's
the man. &QL; 
18. Tiger Woods: Made $26.8 million in '98 to rank 44th, but had
28,301 press clips, twice as many as Leonardo DiCaprio and fourth
to Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Jordan. &QL; 
23. Mark McGwire: A measly $10 million was 83rd on the list, but
47,000 press clips and 900 TV/radio hits and seven magazine covers
pushed him up). &QL; 
24. Dennis Rodman: Surprised? His $15.3 million income was only
56th, but the media hype propelled him almost 50 places above his
new Lakers teammate and fellow thespian. &QL; 
Among the others: &QL; 
33. Sammy Sosa: His $10 million tied McGwire for 83rd, but 29,000
newspaper clips and 579 radio/TV hits from the home run chase made
a big push. &QL; 
56. Gary Sheffield: Based only on his $17.2 million income, which
was actually 54th. &QL; 
58. Mo Vaughn: His $11.9 million was 70th, and he'll be better off
next year in Anaheim. &QL; 
68. Oscar De La Hoya: Another surprise, because he's so low. His
$18.5 million income was 50th. &QL; 
70. Shaquille O'Neal: The athlete who seemingly defined the
cross-over artist made $9.8 million last year (87th on the list),
which wasn't quite enough. Wait'll next year. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
_Realizing that the fight probably won't sell itself, TVKO has a
massive ad campaign for the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis
pay-per-view business meeting Saturday night (6 p.m., $49.95),
which goes beyond Holyfield making the usual boast of a third-round
knockout during every media stop this week. Microsoft has a Web
site set up (http://www.holyfieldlewis.com) and the Home Shopping
Network has fight merchandise and Don King peddling it. TVKO hopes
to get as many as 1 million buys before it rebroadcasts it on HBO,
most likely next Friday. &QL; 
_When it hit the Associated Press wires, the AM-1150 news updates
Wednesday night wouldn't credit all-news KFWB-AM (980) for breaking
the story on the FBI point-shaving investigation into UCLA's
football program. Yup, Joe McDonnell broke it. &QL; 
_ Bob Costas , who thankfully, for the first time in five weeks,
isn't doing a Rodman-bashing Lakers broadcast Sunday. He's at New
Jersey-Miami because of the Stephon Marbury trade to the Nets while
the Lakers play at Sacramento for KCAL. Costas has been given
permission by NBC to do a handful of baseball games on ESPN. His
hope is that he'll be able to work off some rust before the
postseason starts, which for NBC is a cherry-pick of the NLCS and
World Series this season while Fox does the regular season. The
probable truth is that he deep down needs the exposure on the cable
network so that, when Robert Quinlan (his real name) begins his
campaign for the office of commissioner, there'll be no mistaking
the face. &QL; 
_The Angels' spring training broadcasts from Arizona continue to
get technically tangled up on KLAC-AM (570), but there was nothing
like the first game last Saturday when botched commercials and
other miscommunication from the start resulted in play-by-play man
Mario Impemba 's exasperated profanity making it on the air. &QL; 
_If you're on the subscriber list to ESPN The Magazine, expect a
postal solicitation from the boys over in Anaheim gauging your
interest in one of their 21-game season-ticket packages. It's
called Disney synergy, folks. It might not be so tacky, except the
letter begins with the presumptuous salutation ``Dear Angels
Fan.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
