<HEADLINE>
NEW MARINER PITCHERS FLEX ARMS AGAINST ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ There's no Cactus League road trip longer than
Peoria to Tucson, which is 140 miles each way. Veterans Ken Griffey
Jr., Alex Rodriguez, Jay Buhner, Edgar Martinez and David Segui had
permission to sleep in while the Mariners boarded their 7 a.m. bus
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But those were the front-line Colorado Rockies in the other
dugout at Hi Corbett Field, and two Mariner newcomers did a
credible job of handling them. Starter John Halama and reliever
Eric Weaver allowed one run in five combined innings in the M's 3-0
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've both done a real excellent job so far,'' said Mariners
pitching coach Stan Williams. ``They've done everything we've asked
them to do. The run off Halama today was the only one off either
one of them all spring. They're throwing strikes and both are good
competitors who know how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama and Weaver came to the Mariners quietly in early October.
Halama was the player to be named later from July's Randy Johnson
trade with Houston; Weaver was acquired from Los Angeles for
minor-leaguer Scott Prouty. Now, both find themselves with
reasonable chances at making the M's opening day roster.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Halama has been a starter the last three years,
making six starts last April for Houston, but he could fit in as a
reliever for Seattle. The Mariners have no established left-handed
relievers on their roster, and the one with the most experience,
Greg McCarthy, gave up two runs on three hits in one inning
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was fighting for the fifth spot (in the Astros'
rotation), and this year, from what I understand, there are two
open spots,'' Halama said. ``I don't know how many bullpen spots
are available, but I might be a reliever here. I'm basically a
starter, but I relieved one year in the minors and I could do that
also.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have eight pitchers who should make the team
barring trades or injuries: Jeff Fassero, Jamie Moyer, Ken Cloude,
Mark Leiter, Bobby Ayala, Jose Paniagua, Jose Mesa and Butch Henry,
who, like Halama, could fill the left-handed relief role. That
leaves three open spots, at least one in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   That job could be won by Weaver, a 6-foot-5 right-hander who was
2-0 with an 0.93 earned-run average in seven games with the Dodgers
last year. A starter in the minors from 1992-97, Weaver became a
full-time reliever in '98, striking out 63 in 612/3 innings at
Class AAA Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   He credits learning a split-finger fastball with rejuvenating
his career. Weaver developed the pitch near the end of the '97
season with coach Claude Osteen, and found it the ideal complement
to his 88-92 mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just took off,'' said Weaver. ``It was like a new toy _ it
made pitching fun again. I had reached a point where I was spinning
my wheels with Albuquerque, and with the split-finger, I knew I had
a pitch to put guys away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama's best pitch is his change-up, which earns him frequent
comparisons to Moyer. He also throws a curveball and two kinds of
fastballs, and Williams likes the assortment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can throw off-speed and locate, it's the way to
pitch,'' he said. ``Most of the guys in this league can handle
fastballs better than anything else. If you can change speeds and
move the ball, you can have success here.''
</P>
<P>
   MARINER NOTES: A strong wind was blowing in much of Thursday,
and Mariner pitchers said it helped them. But they also showed good
command, issuing no walks after allowing only one on Wednesday and
two in each of the previous two games. ``I hate walks, and I guess
I've gotten the point across,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hitting coach Jesse Barfield said rookie second baseman
Carlos Guillen is one of those rare switch-hitters with the same
mechanics from both sides of the plate. ``About 70 percent of
pitchers are right-handed now, so obviously he's going to get a lot
more at-bats left-handed,'' Barfield said. ``But he's outstanding
from both sides. He's a player.'' Guillen went 2-for-4 with a
perfect bunt and is hitting .571 this spring.
</P>
<P>
   -- Guillen was developed as a shortstop, but he won't play there
for the Mariners unless Rodriguez has to stay out of the lineup for
an extended length of time. On Rodriguez's routine days off, David
Bell will replace him at shortstop, as he did Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   -- A day after he blanked the Brewers for two innings, Freddy
Garcia was still earning praise in the Mariners' dugout. ``He was
overpowering,'' said catcher Tom Lampkin, who was working with
Garcia for the first time. Lampkin said Garcia's curveball and
mid-90s fastball already are major-league quality, and his revamped
changeup is nearly there. Manager Lou Piniella said Garcia earned
himself a spring start with the outing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Before being shut out Thursday, Mariners hitters were leading
the majors with a .376 average. ... Non-roster right-hander Melvin
Bunch was re-assigned to minor-league camp ... The latest major
leaguer to dye his hair? Red-coiffed Rockies strongman Dante
Bichette. ... Fassero starts Friday against the pride of Yakima,
Todd Stottlemyre, as the Mariners host the Arizona Diamondbacks at
12:05 (KIRO 710-AM).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
