<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7506 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOKE-FRENCH-BANK-MERG     03-12 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOKE-FRENCH-BANK-MERGER-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNP'S PARIBAS-SOCIETE GENERALE TAKEOVER: COMEDIE FRANCAISE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This timely, excellent 700-word ``separate buy'' article is from
the current (week beginning 13 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hostile takeover in France? And not of one company but two?
And in the banking industry at that, where deals are made over long
lunches after a nod from the finance ministry? Something is going
on.
</P>
<P>
   BNP, which, on March 10, bid for Paribas and Societe Generale to
create a bank that would be worth FFr340 billion ($56 billion),
would have you believe that this something is a restructuring of
the French banking system.
</P>
<P>
   It ``is the transaction the market has been waiting for,'' said
the bank. No it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   There will be many who say that the simple fact of a hostile bid
is remarkable in itself in a country where such things are as rare
as a bottle of 1928 Chateau Petrus.
</P>
<P>
   Ignore, for a moment, that hostile takeovers in banking are
unlikely to work, and that attempting two at once is, shall we say,
ambitious. This is a hostile takeover with little rationale, and
even less hostility.
</P>
<P>
   BNP promises to sack nobody (costs will cut through natural
attrition), close no branches, and keep all the banks' brands
intact. So what is the point?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps BNP felt left out: it courted Societe Generale
unsuccessfully for two years only to see the bank fall into the
arms of Paribas. Perhaps it felt desperate: its investment-banking
business has been poor; with Paribas and SocGen on board it might
rise to mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspicion is that BNP wants to be too big to be taken
over, and that it would relish the title of national champion of
French banking.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this deal fails to come off (and it is still a long way
from succeeding), it will lead to talk of the long-overdue
consolidation in European banking now that the euro is here.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation is certainly needed. Europe has too many
unprofitable banks with too many branches _ as it happens, twice as
many branches per head as in America. Sadly, however, what this bid
tells you is not how much consolidation there will be, but how
little.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for a start, hard for European banks to merge. Germany
and to a lesser extent France and Italy are dominated by mutually
owned and state-owned institutions. In Germany, three-quarters of
the banking market is in the hands of such banks.
</P>
<P>
   Unless countries privatize and mutuals convert into stockholding
companies, the scope for consolidation is limited.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope: ten years ago in Italy 70 percent of the
country's banking system was in public hands; now, thanks to
privatization, the figure is about 20 percent. Yet elsewhere,
particularly in France and Germany, things remain far more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   There is worse. In America and Britain, once banks have clinched
a merger, they can then set about closing branches and sacking
people; this, indeed, is often the rationale for the deal in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Not in most European countries: strong labor laws and strongish
unions make that awkward.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the pains that Societe Generale and Paribas went to in
February to emphasize that there would be few, if any, job cuts
domestically. And hence the pains that BNP has gone to now to say
the same, only more so.
</P>
<P>
   It talks of ``multi-branding'' (keeping the existing banks
almost exactly as they are) and of ``cost-cutting synergies''
(technology, possibly; and sacking foreigners, very probably). It
talks, to be blunt, nonsense: BNP can't cut costs at home and it
knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border mergers are doubly difficult. There is little
overlap between banks from the different countries and the logic
here is different: less cost-cutting, more revenue generation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is precisely why banks are hesitant. Buying a bank in
another country with another language and another legal system is a
risk that few want to take.
</P>
<P>
   There have been one or two attempts, but full mergers have
proved difficult. Deutsche had a tilt at Credit Lyonnais and
Societe Generale, but was sent away with a flea in its ear.
</P>
<P>
   Every European country seems to want strong banks, but until
they can live with layoffs, foreign shareholders and less
nationalistic regulation, they will be disappointed. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 700-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
