<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7510 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHY-NEW-NATO-NEEDED-E     03-12 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-NEW-NATO-NEEDED-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE AND AMERICA NEED EACH OTHER, MORE THAN EVER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This excellent 1,050-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 13 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are a European, the agenda for this year's Ides of March
should make you gulp.
</P>
<P>
   This coming Monday, March 15, is the day when a committee of
investigators will say whether it thinks that members of the
European Commission have been culpably careless with the taxpayers'
money.
</P>
<P>
   More worryingly, in the wider world, it is also the day when the
Kosovo negotiations begin again, and Europeans will have to decide
whether they are ready to be as tough as Americans with Slobodan
Milosevic in order to get Serbia off the Kosovars' backs.
</P>
<P>
   And, to rub home the transatlantic point, the World Trade
Organization will on Monday be expecting both Europe and America to
show some sign of willingness to settle the blush-making banana
war, which Europe started but the Americans have now made sharply
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Beware the Ides, indeed. It is not surprising that on both sides
of the Atlantic the glummer sort of ``realist'' _ the sort whose
``realism'' is based on looking backward rather than forward _ is
predicting the end of the Euro-American partnership that repeatedly
saved the 20th century from disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Cold-War solitary American superpower, say many
Europeans, has to be held in check, lest it create an unacceptably
Americanized world.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty dollar needs to be balanced by the gallant young
euro. The spread of American popular culture must be slowed, even
if it is popular outside America too.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans should be discouraged from demonizing Iran (here
America's critics may be right, if last month's local elections in
Iran further strengthen President Khatami's liberalizing hand).
</P>
<P>
   The Americans should also stop bombing the armory of Saddam
Hussein's praetorian guard (but here the critics are wrong, unless
they can come up with a better way of bringing a
germ-warfare-capable Iraq back under sane leadership).
</P>
<P>
   What many of these Europeans do not realize is that their
grumblings are drowned by the growlings of frustrated Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just that Bosnia's agonies were prolonged by the
Europeans' unwillingness to recognize that a just peace required
the serious threat of force (and that the same thing could yet go
wrong in Kosovo); or that the banana war began with Europe's
reluctance to respect the rules of free trade.
</P>
<P>
   The arthritic economy of continental Europe, say angry
Americans, leaves it to them to bear most of the burden of helping
recession-hit Asia and Latin America, by buying more imports from
these regions and thereby making their own trade deficit even
worse.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union, though richer than the United States,
provides a tiny and diminishing proportion of the high-tech
military equipment that NATO depends on if it is to be able to
fight wars without an intolerable number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Europe no longer has to worry about Hitler's Germany or
a communist Russia, conclude these exasperated Americans, Europe
can be left to its own devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep structural forces,'' says Stephen Walt in the current
issue of the National Interest, are ``beginning to pull Europe and
America apart.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the sky is not quite that black: a few gleams of
sunshine peer through the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of NATO goes ahead this spring without any of the
awful consequences _ an uncontrollably furious Russia, a sharp
increase in the democracies' defense budgets _ that the pessimists
had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The continued American and British bombing of Iraq has not been
supported by other Europeans but neither have they (or most Arabs,
be it noted) strongly objected to it.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the gloomsters could yet prove right. The Atlantic
alliance may indeed collapse, unless both Europeans and Americans
look forward rather than backward: unless they base their plans not
on memories of the past 50 years but on a reasonable calculation of
what the next 50 years will bring.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States were indeed going to remain the world's
only great power as far ahead as the eye can see, people who like
this newspaper believe in the danger of monopoly and the need for
competition would draw the necessary conclusion: Europe should
provide a counterbalance to this overwhelming American power.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not in fact what the future really holds. If the
European part of NATO raises its eyes beyond its own borders, and
sees what will probably happen out there in the next generation or
so, it will understand why it still needs America and _ even more
important _ why America increasingly needs Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The one-superpower world will not last. Within the next couple
of decades a China with up to 1 billion people, a strongly growing
economy and probably a still-authoritarian government will almost
certainly be trying to push its interests eastward into the Pacific
and westward into Central Asia, whose oil and gas this energy-poor
China will badly need.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later some strong and honest man will pull
post-Yeltsin Russia together, and another contender for global
influence will have reappeared on the scene (unless fear of China
sends a horrified Russia running into NATO's arms).
</P>
<P>
   The Islamist superpower that nervous people predicted a few
years ago will probably never come into being, but the Muslim world
will certainly continue to produce localized explosions of
ideological wrath and geopolitical envy.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the alliance of the democracies needs not only new
members but also a new purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance can no longer be just a protective American arm
around Europe's shoulder; it also has to be a way for Europe and
America to work together in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   And those who hope to construct a politically united Europe
should recognize that this must be done _ if it can be done at all
_ in partnership with America, not to separate Europe from America.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO was what NATO seems to Cold-War nostalgics, how soon
we'd drop her. But, as Kipling would be the first to explain, it
ain't.
</P>
<P>
   A new Atlantic partnership will be more than the Cold-War NATO.
Through the squabbling about bananas and the head-scratching about
Kosovo, the shape of a 21st-century alliance of the democracies at
last begins to emerge. &QL; 
