<HEADER>
A7512 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN     03-12 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARATHONER OVERCOMES ILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She's not supposed to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   She's fought cancer three times.
</P>
<P>
   She (begin ital)will(end ital) finish Sunday's L.A. Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll crawl,'' she said, ``if I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Uliantzeff, 39, is a soft-spoken, slender blonde who rarely
discusses her past. But what a past it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a beacon of light for everyone to do well. I don't know
a better way to say it,'' said Pat Connelly, coach of the Road
Runners track program that prepares athletes for the L.A. Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see her and all that she's been through, and she's
right there with them. It really makes their pain and discomfort
seem insignificant and helps them keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Uliantzeff, an interpreter for the Superior Court, was first
diagnosed with breast cancer 10 years ago. Cancer also claimed the
lives of her brother and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' she said. ``Everyone I knew
who had it, had died. I wasn't ready to die. That's why I stayed
active and kept doing as much as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a lumpectomy and six months of radiation and
chemotherapy, all while she was training for her first L.A.
Marathon, melanoma was discovered on her leg. She finished that
race.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, in 1993, her breast cancer had spread to both
lungs, and she was given less than a 20 percent chance of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Her cancer is now in remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a quitter,'' she says. ``I know there are limits you
hit when you do have to stop, but I truly believe God made us very
strong and wants us to keep pushing. I don't think a lot of people
realize that, and they quit when it starts hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   When she recovered from the cancer, the deeply religious woman
returned to volunteering for the St. Innocent Orphanage in Tijuana,
Mexico, and the Project Mexico outreach program.
</P>
<P>
   This year she's running to raise money for the orphanage, which
she visits monthly. Many of its boys are traveling to see the race
and cheer for Uliantzeff and their friend Ismeal Valadez, a
16-year-old who Uliantzeff has helped train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both have different battles,'' Uliantzeff said, ``and it
shows if you have faith and keep persevering, dreams can come
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Uliantzeff's dedication to others, as well as her own bravery,
earned her this year's Patsy Choco Courage Award. L.A. Marathon
officials established the award in honor of a cancer victim whose
last wish was to complete the marathon, which she did, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   While a recent bout with the flu has jeopardized Uliantzeff's
goal of finishing the marathon in less than five hours, she won't
be ready for a rest after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to go out dancing and have a margarita,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
