<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWN'N'OUT-JAPAN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAD SUNSET OF TOKYO'S DAY LABORERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 625-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 13 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ It is hard to believe that the streets of San'ya, a
Tokyo neighborhood of liquor shops and cheap hotels, could once be
controlled only by riot police.
</P>
<P>
   The police are still there, holed up in the ``Mammoth,'' a
multi-story police box that overlooks the biggest of San'ya's
flophouses. But they get no trouble these days.
</P>
<P>
   San'ya has aged with its residents, old men with creased faces
and missing teeth who squat and smoke on the pavements, drift from
bar to bar, or sleep it off in the winter sun on cardboard and
plastic matting.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them will spend the night on the street, too. San'ya has
more than 1,500 homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Homelessness is rising fast in Japan's big cities. Most Japanese
blame the recession. Everyone has a story to tell about the
white-collar ``sarariman'' who lost his job and then his family,
and who now lives in a cardboard box on the station concourse,
still reading the financial pages every day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most of Japan's homeless have never set foot inside an
office, let alone read the Nikkei newspaper. However, the recession
has played its part in the recent surge in vagrancy in Japanese
cities, especially with the collapse in demand for day laborers.
</P>
<P>
   San'ya is one of Japan's biggest ``yoseba,'' a neighborhood
where day laborers gather early in the morning to pick up work on
construction sites. At its most prosperous, during the construction
boom in the run-up to the 1964 Tokyo Olympics, San'ya was home to
15,000 day laborers. There are now only about 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The state pension begins at 65, but after a day laborer turns
55, says Takao Yamauchi, who runs a local welfare center, his
chances of picking up work are slim. The average age of San'ya's
day laborers is 56.
</P>
<P>
   Once they have exhausted their savings, says Yamauchi, they are
out on the street. Some have stayed in the neighborhood. Others
live in train stations and under the blue-sheet tents that are
spreading through Tokyo's public parks.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by the Tokyo city government, 60
percent of the city's homeless say their last job was as a day
laborer.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s San'ya was enjoying a second construction
boom, thanks to soaring land and stock prices. The most skilled
workers, the athletic ``tobi'' who handle the scaffolding for
high-rise buildings, were then able to earn several hundred dollars
a day.
</P>
<P>
   But like the economy, it was a bubble that only masked the
long-term decline of this way of life.
</P>
<P>
   More and more construction companies are now hiring cheaper
foreign workers, both legitimate and illegal, who come from
Southeast Asia and the Asian subcontinent. They are also
mechanizing more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As the day laborers bear the brunt of the job cuts, San'ya's
community has collapsed. Yamauchi says that only a couple of
hundred workers turn up for the morning labor markets, compared
with several thousand a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing a bit of food, temporary shelter and medical
care, the Tokyo government has started a new job scheme for
San'ya's workers, employing them to clean government property, weed
the parks and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this, some of the homeless earn enough to sleep in a
flophouse at least one night a week, though not enough to qualify
for unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
   When they were younger, these men took to the streets to fight
their exploitation by the ``yakuza,'' the organized crime
syndicates which still run the local labor-broking and gambling
rackets. But the old men of San'ya have no fight left in them. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 625-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
