<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON PART OF ANGELS TRADE TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Talk around the Cactus League is that the Angels
may be nearing a deal that involves outfielder Garret Anderson for
a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   For what pitcher and to what team remain to be seen, but it is
believed the Angels are becoming more and more convinced that
keeping four outfielders won't work.
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson is traded, that would free up the DH spot for Todd
Greene, whose ailing shoulder is still preventing him from
catching. Hitting, though, hasn't bothered Greene. Greene is
hitting .333 (5 for 15) with a homer and two RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays are shopping pitcher Pat Hentgen, but Blue
Jays general manager Gord Ash has implied that Anderson would not
be enough for Hentgen.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, though, could be packaged with minor-leaguers, like
pitcher Scott Schoeneweis, who started Thursday's game against the
Oakland A's. Schoeneweis was impressive, giving up two runs and
four hits in three innings against the A's major-league lineup. He
struck out Matt Stairs and Ben Grieve in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who is used to trade rumors, said it doesn't bother
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' Anderson said. ``There's nothing to
comment on. It's hard to talk about something that hasn't happened.
You just wait and see.... It's not like I have one year in the
majors, so I'm not worried about anything. I've established myself
at this level. They (front office) control the business. I control
what I do on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley update: Pitcher Chuck Finley (muscle strain upper
back/neck) threw Thursday and is expected to throw off the mound
for the first time on Saturday. He's scheduled to make his first
Cactus League start Tuesday against the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Third-base battle: Troy Glaus had a good day Thursday in his bid
to win the starting job at third base. Vying for the spot with Dave
Hollins, Glaus made a nice play on a chopper hit by the A's Ryan
Christenson, fielding the ball on an in-between hop and throwing
out Christenson with the bases loaded and two out in the second.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Glaus ripped a double to the fence in right-center
field to drive in Matt Luke and Tim Salmon, giving the Angels a 6-2
lead on their way to a 16-15 win at Tempe Diablo Stadium. In the
fourth, Glaus drove in two more runs with a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing good,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``He's
swinging the bat good.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Hollins will start the next three games at third.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of offense: Glaus, though, wasn't the only hitter to have
a big day. The two teams combined for 37 hits in what Collins and
others termed an ``ugly game.'' It got so bad that at one point,
three Angels pitchers _ Reid Cornelius, Darrin Winston and Geoff
Edsell _ combined for 100 pitches in 11/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels nearly blew a 16-3 lead, as the A's scored four in
the seventh and eight in the eighth before the Angels finally
closed it out. Luke threw out the A's Mike Neill at the plate from
right field in the ninth to keep the game from going longer than
the three hours and 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A's manager Art Howe came out to argue the call, and wasn't the
only person to believe that Neill was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked safe to me,'' Luke said. ``But I was a mile away.
The ump (Derryl Cousins) called him out. That's all that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
