</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENZUELA'S LAWYER CLAIMS MISTAKEN IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPLE CITY -- A simple case of mistaken identity landed jockey
Pat Valenzuela in jail on charges he robbed a cabbie at gunpoint,
Valenzuela's attorney said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 36, once one of the nation's top jockeys, was
arrested Feb. 26 in Rosemead, outside a Garvey Avenue bar on
suspicion of armed robbery. He is being held at Men's Central Jail
in lieu of $75,000 bail. He is due in court Monday for a
preliminary hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty doggone clear that this is a case of mistaken
identification,'' said Valenzuela's attorney, Don Calabria. ``It's
a real tragedy that he's been arrested in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is convicted, Valenzuela could be sentenced to four years
in state prison. He pleaded not guilty at his arraignment March 2.
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports, Jose Valdez, a driver with the
Green Valley Cab Company, was dispatched Feb. 24 to an undisclosed
address in Rosemead where he picked up a male passenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man outside the residence gets in the cab and robs it at
gunpoint,'' Sheriff's Lt. Stuart Heller said. ``The cab driver
calls the police and gave description of a small statured man,
wearing a baseball cap and jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Late the next evening, Valdez was dispatched to Spikes Bar and
Restaurant on Garvey Avenue in Rosemead, Heller said. The location
is a few blocks from where the robbery occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the bar, he's approached by this small guy who asks, `Are
you the taxi cab driver? I want to go El Monte and I'll give you a
$1 to take me there,''' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   At some point during the conversation, Valdez began to believe
he was talking to the same man took his money the night before,
Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point (Valdez) phoned the Sheriff's Department and
identified (Valenzuela) as the guy who robbed him,'' Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   It is what then happened that leads Calabria to believe
Valenzuela is not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, the victim was not able to pick (Valenzuela) out
of a photo line up,'' Calabria said. `'Also there was no gun found
in (Valenzuela's) possession.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Calabria said Valenzuela has an alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of (the robbery) he was at a friend's house and
they watched the Emmys or something of that nature,'' Calabria
said. ``They watched it together.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend was not identified. The Grammy Awards were on
television the night of the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Heller said the Sheriff's Department is still investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be more than happy to find out that (Valenzuela's)
innocent,'' Heller said. ``We are continuing to look into this.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem Valenzuela will have to overcome is public
perception. He won the 1989 Kentucky Derby and was one of the top
riders in the nation. But the jockey has had several highly
publicized bouts with drug abuse. Two years ago he was accused of
spousal assault.
</P>
<P>
   Calabria acknowledged Valenzuela's past drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope he's got that under control at this point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary hearing is scheduled to get under way at 9 a.m.
it will likely be postponed until Wednesday, Calabria said.
</P>
<P>
   `` He didn't do this,'' the attorney said. ``I know I'm going to
win this case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
