<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-ROUNDUP12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing finer than ... Weber
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Weber State ended the first day of the NCAA Tournament
Thursday with a stunning upset that might be remembered as one of
the biggest surprises ever in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, the No. 14 seed in the West Regional, shocked
third-seeded North Carolina 76-74 in Seattle. It was only the sixth
NCAA Tournament victory in school history for Weber State, the Big
Sky Conference champion, while the loss ended an remarkable
postseason streak for the Tar Heels, who had advanced to the Final
Four the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina had not lost a first-round game since the
tournament expanded to 64 teams in 1985 and it was the first time
since 1980 that the Tar Heels had not won at least one tournament
game.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina was the only high seed to lose on opening day.
Auburn, the top seed in the South Regional, routed Winthrop 80-41
in Indianapolis, extending the streak of victories by No. 1 seeds
against No. 16 seeds in the tournament. Since the tournament
expanded to 64 teams in 1985, the No. 1 seed has won 57 consecutive
games in the 1-16 matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The South's top four seeds cruised on opening day as Maryland,
St. John's and Ohio State joined Auburn with victories. Maryland
eliminated Valparaiso, last season's Cinderella which advanced to
the Sweet 16, while St. John's routed Samford and Ohio State downed
Murray State.
</P>
<P>
   There were two games in the South Regional in which
higher-seeded teams lost as No. 9 Oklahoma State edged No. 8
Syracuse and No. 10 Creighton upset No. 7 Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
