<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS STILL HAVE QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ The big pieces are in place for the Dodgers: The
pitching rotation, the starting shortstop, the backup catcher.
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks into spring training, and with three weeks
remaining, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson has questions that need to
be answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy is sore, I want to know who is going to play where,''
Johnson said. ``And I want them to know what their role is.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Johnson's questions:
</P>
<P>
   Who's the backup first baseman?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that (Scott) Livingstone and (Dave) Hansen could play
over there,'' Johnson said. ``But could Todd (Hollandsworth) play
over there?''
</P>
<P>
   Who's the best long-term backup outfielder?
</P>
<P>
   ``If something happens to any one of my outfielders, who's my
best left fielder, center fielder, right fielder?'' Johnson said.
``My contingency plans... what's my backup plan?''
</P>
<P>
   When will the bullpen work itself out?
</P>
<P>
   ``By next week I want to know who's going to be doing what so I
can get that going,'' Johnson said. ``Then I can begin setting that
up.''
</P>
<P>
   No thanks, still: Montreal manager Felipe Alou and Johnson, also
known as choices No.1 and No.2 for the Dodgers manager's job, met
behind the batting cage and talked before Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Alou took a few moments to state he had no regrets
about turning down the offer to manager the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm over 60. When you make a decision at this age, it's a
decision you're sure of,'' Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Alou also said he wanted to remain in Montreal until the
ownership squabble concludes. There is speculation Expos president
and general partner Claude Brochu will move the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see this storm brewing many, many years ago,'' Alou
said. ``I always said I didn't want to see this from a distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's spring training: Kevin Brown pitched four innings,
yielding one run on five hits against the Expos. A good
performance, but not anything to get excited about, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is getting innings in, pitches in, and walking out
healthy,'' Brown said. ``I don't put too much emphasis on (spring
training starts).''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna update: Johnson said right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna,
who had elbow surgery in September, is still a week away from
pitching in a game. Osuna has thrown off the mound a few times but
will need a few more outings on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still plenty of time,'' Johnson said. ``I may not get him
stretched out like I want to get him stretched out, but he should
be able to get his arm strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hitters... and pitchers: Shortstop Jose Vizcaino was
scheduled to make the trip to Jupiter but needed another day to
rest the bruised back of his knee.... Closer Jeff Shaw is scheduled
to return to Dodgertown today and could pitch in a spring training
game as early as Sunday, Johnson said.... Outfielder Hiram
Bocachica was the right fielder against the Expos, his first action
since colliding with Trenidad Hubbard on Monday. Hubbard, whose
right thumb remains swollen, said he's hoping to return Sunday or
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
