<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT WIZARDS, 98-86 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Knicks turned over the couch cushions,
emptied the ashtrays and found some loose change for Marcus Camby
on Thursday. It was not big money, not the $70 million maximums his
1996 draft peers have received over the last few weeks. But it was
a contract extension nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   He was set. Camby had financial security after signing a
six-year deal that guaranteed him $40 million and another $8
million in incentives. Instead of reclining on his newfound wealth,
Camby leaped off the bench and delivered the kind of effort that
left him looking like a bargain for a night.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was more than a valuable plug-in for the injured Patrick
Ewing as the Knicks pulled away for an easy 98-86 victory over the
Washington Wizards on Thursday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   With grace that left him appearing more fluid than frail, Camby
was able to dribble and drive for finger rolls, as well as slip
back-door and spring up for dunks on his way to a season-high 19
points. With uncharacteristic aggression, he tore away loose balls
as he collected a season-high 12 rebounds in 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Season-high night. Season-high feeling.
</P>
<P>
   `'I think it was just a coincidence that I had a good game after
signing my contract,'' said Camby, who can opt out of his deal
after five years. `'I haven't been going out and trying to play for
a contract. I just love to play. Now, I just have to stay focused.
I am not going to go out there and get lazy. You can't be lazy in
this market.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby had the crowd calling for his name when he was resting on
the bench. He has come a long way from the newcomer who had his
work ethic questioned by Coach Jeff Van Gundy in training camp. He
has come far, but the Wizards are not exactly the measuring stick
for Camby or the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks moved the ball well and leaned on Larry Johnson (17
points) and Allan Houston (19 points) just as they did last season,
when Ewing missed 56 games with a wrist injury. But the impact of
Ewing's absence _ which could extend another week or longer because
of tendinitis in his Achilles' tendon _ was not felt that much
against the center-less Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the injured Rod Strickland was not around to toy
with the Knicks and that the Wizards' undersized center, Terry
Davis, left the game after he was kicked in the jaw early in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks have made easy nights difficult this season.
After losing three 1-point games in the last week _ and losing five
of their last seven games before last night _ the Knicks were
thrilled to build a 17-point lead in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Third quarters had been their undoing this season. But with
uncanny efficiency _ 29 assists to 10 turnovers on the night _ the
Knicks savored their chance to assemble a rare double-digit lead.
They also enjoyed an infrequent night of out-rebounding an
opponent, 44-34.
</P>
<P>
   `'It was a good, solid win,'' Van Gundy said. `'This is a
totally different group'' _ than the Knick team that survived
without Ewing last season _ ``but we had the balance and
determination that are going to be critical as we try to get
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby had that edge, as did Kurt Thomas. After not scoring in
the Knicks' loss to Milwaukee Tuesday, Thomas found his game again
and tied his season high of 17 points. Suddenly, the maligned front
court of the Knicks was doing exactly what the forwards were paid
to do: take over.
</P>
<P>
   Camby did his part. He made himself look like a bargain at $48
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played well,'' Van Gundy said. ``He kept the ball alive on
the offensive boards and he defensive rebounded better than he has
been, which is good. I thought he guarded Juwan Howard well in
concert with Larry Johnson and then Chris Dudley. We needed all the
scoring we could get. So to get 19, that's great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
