<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMS SERVICE SAYS MEXICAN TROOPS FIRED FROM U.S. SOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A customs officer sent to check a pre-dawn border alarm at a
remote desert crossing this week found himself ducking gunfire from
a Mexican military unit he says had crossed into Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadowy world of the border, where it's sometimes
impossible to tell the drug smugglers from the good guys, the
customs officer didn't assume it was accidental fire.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, according to the Customs Service, he retreated about a
mile from the border south of Sells, linked up with more customs
officers and returned to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican troops then told customs officers that they had been
in Mexico when they fired warning shots while chasing two
drug-laden vehicles. They denied entering the United States at the
border crossing southwest of Tucson on the Tohono O'odham
Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican consular official in Nogales, Sonora, backed his
military's description of events. But customs officials, in a
carefully worded statement, suggested the Mexican soldiers had
crossed the border.
</P>
<P>
   Customs spokesman Roger Maier in El Paso declined to elaborate
on the investigation or speculate on motives for the alleged
crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Daniels, a spokesman for the Border Patrol's Tucson sector,
said such border crossings are a recurring problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Daniels said U.S. law enforcement agencies increasingly suspect
that some of the crossings occur not because traffickers are being
chased, but because they are being protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had situations occur in Nogales, in Naco and in
Douglas,'' Daniels said. ``More times than not, it's Mexican
military, but it can be police, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Burgos, spokesman for Mexican consul Roberto Rodriguez
in Nogales, called those suggestions ``very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They must be ready to prove it,'' he said. ``People shouldn't
base these statements on suspicions.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject is a sensitive one in the wake of President
Clinton's decision late last month to recertify Mexico as ``fully
cooperating'' in the U.S. fight against trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did so despite some opposition in Congress, and even
among members of his own administration. The Drug Enforcement
Administration has publicly said that deep corruption riddles
Mexico's anti-narcotics corps.
</P>
<P>
   According to the customs statement, an unidentified officer
responded about 6:30 a.m. Tuesday to reports of an unlawful
crossing at the San Miguel gate on the border south of Sells.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed an embankment and saw headlights ``of what appeared
to be a military Humvee north of the border and a man in an olive
drab uniform walking near a dirt road'' on the U.S. side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   A Humvee is a rugged, all-terrain vehicle designed for military
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer heard a rifle shot and then a bullet strike the
embankment,'' the customs statement said. ``The officer heard two
additional bullets pass above his head.''
</P>
<P>
   He took cover and heard a vehicle cross the metal cattle guard
at the gate on the border. He retreated about one mile north of the
border and linked up with other customs officers. They returned to
the San Miguel gate, where they met up with one Mexican military
officer and four soldiers, all of whom were on the Mexican side of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican army officer told customs officials that the
Mexican army Humvee had chased two vehicles north and caught one at
the gate,'' the customs statement said. The military group showed
U.S. officers a pickup full of marijuana and two prisoners, and
explained the shooting as warning shots fired into the air. They
denied crossing into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Burgos said the lack of clear border markings in the rural area
could have led to confusion about where the military was.
</P>
<P>
   However, the customs statement said its officers saw apparent
Humvee tracks and fresh boot tracks leading about a quarter-mile
into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials in Washington, D.C., were unaware of
the incident, as was Jane Gray, principal U.S. consular officer in
Nogales, Sonora. &QL; 
Pat Flannery can be reached at 444-8629 or at
pat.flannery(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
