<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7546 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESTATE-AZR &LR;      03-12 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$8.3 MILLION FOR MCCAW'S PARADISE VALLEY ESTATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 and CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of living large just went up _ by nearly $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   At $8.3 million, last week's sale of an 8,000-square-foot
mansion on Camelback Mountain is the priciest home deal ever
recorded in Arizona, topping billionaire Bennett Dorrance's $5.5
million home sale last year.
</P>
<P>
   The rambling estate _ in Paradise Valley, of course _ comes with
a six-car garage and parking for 50 close friends, a private movie
theater, floor-to-ceiling windows facing Mummy Mountain, a guest
house and a bathroom to bedroom ratio of 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly owned by Seattle sports mogul John E. McCaw, the
house's new inhabitants are somewhat mysterious. Paperwork lists
the purchaser as a corporate entity formed for a family trust.
</P>
<P>
   The sale continues a trend in home-buying in metro Phoenix,
where prices have surged in the past five years. The number of
homes selling for seven-digit prices has tripled since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, almost 170 homes sold for at least $1 million, which
set a record for million-dollar deals.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those were in Paradise Valley, where the land alone can
command a seven-figure price if it's nestled against one of the
town's landmark mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sale price for the 10-acre McCaw estate was a
record in Arizona for a single-family resale home, it isn't the
most expensive listed in Paradise Valley.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction goes to one of the former homes of the Queen of
Mean, hotel diva Leona Helmsley, who has had her 10-acre estate on
Mummy Mountain listed for $25 million for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hassett of Russ Lyon Realty, who handled the sale of the
McCaw estate for the buyer, said he has been ``sworn to secrecy''
about the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
   The seller's name was found in public documents. McCaw is a
publicity-shy sports enthusiast who owns part of Major League
Baseball's Seattle Mariners and the NBA's Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of one of the country's richest families, the son
of John Elroy McCaw, radio and cable TV pioneer, and brother of
cellular phone guru Craig McCaw.
</P>
<P>
   The Information Store, a company that collects real estate sales
data, lists the buyer as MICI, a Phoenix company. Public records
say MICI is managed by Garth Price, and that the Regency Family
Trust plays a role in the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear who will be living in the home. Efforts to reach
Price for comment were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Ellie Shapiro of Coldwell Banker Success Realty, who represented
the seller, also declined to identify the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Hassett would not reveal his commission on the $8.3 million
sale, but said, ``It's a real nice feeling to sell something like
this.``
</P>
<P>
   The former McCaw property has fountains and pools set amid lush
vegetation. Electric security gates bar intruders. An entertainment
room with a projection screen hidden in the ceiling keeps residents
and visitors entertained. And a wet bar along with a heated pool
and spa has the potential to keep them wet. &QL; 
Catherine Reagor can be reached at 444-8040 or at
catherine.reagor(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
