<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TEXAS-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS' MUONEKE STILL PAYING PRICE FOR MISTAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Texas forward Gabe Muoneke fully expects CBS television
commentators working today's NCAA Tournament game against Purdue to
rehash the history of the volatile nature that led to his one-game
suspension in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commentators are still saying something about it,'' Muoneke
said, shaking his head. ``That's their business and they'll do what
they want regardless of what anyone else tells them. But I'm going
to keep playing basketball regardless and just let things roll.''
</P>
<P>
   As observers use terms like ``war'' to describe today's East
Region battle between No. 7 seed Texas (19-12) and 10th-seeded
Purdue (19-12), it would be natural that the fiery all-Big 12
inside force be mentioned. Especially when the Boilermakers have a
6-foot-8 counterpart in forward Brian Cardinal, whose fearless
manner of play resulted in the moniker, ``Citizen Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   UT's Kris Clack has seen tape of Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two very emotional players,'' Clack said of Muoneke and
Purdue's leading rebounder and second-leading scorer. ``Hopefully,
there won't be any sparks flying and everyone will keep his cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know the type person Gabe is. I knew once he just
started playing and quit worrying about the refs, he was going to
be/Rtough/S to guard and he has been. It's been tough on him, but
Gabe's a good person and I can see the adjustments he's made.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke and Cardinal appear to have mutual admiration. Their
descriptions of each other's ability are similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see how we go at each other,'' said
Cardinal, who, like Muoneke, plays off the glass or can step out
and shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabe had a terrific year. I know he goes out and plays very
hard, similar to me. He's a hard worker who does what it takes for
his team to win. He does a lot of little things people don't see. I
know our coaches think he's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke was perhaps most impressed by something he didn't see
while watching tape on Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never see him slack off,'' Muoneke said. ``He plays a big
part on their team. He's tough. He doesn't do anything to hurt them
and sometimes that's the best way to help your team, by not doing
anything to hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies part of Muoneke's lasting value to the Longhorns.
By focusing his energy after being suspended for throwing a couple
of punches during the Kansas game on Jan.19, he's ceased being a
distraction. That, even though he has been the focus of some verbal
abuse from opposition fans and has on occasion been baited by
opposition players.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who questioned whether Muoneke would still be a
part of this team at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have admiration for what he's done,'' UT coach Rick
Barnes said. ``We've been on the road a lot and I hear what people
have said to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say it's not fair, but I told him it's something he
brought on himself, that he had to deal with it and he has. It
hasn't been easy, but he's been able to get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke said that when he realized he was embarrassing his
family, his attitude changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's reaction was all it took,'' Muoneke said. ``From
then on, I had the mindset that I'd rather play bad and make them
proud than play good and disappoint them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
