<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-FLORIDA-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA A&AMP;M HAVE FUN LAUGHING AT ITSELF AND FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ If you think you're having a bad day, week,
month or year, consider Florida A&AMP;M. The Rattlers' misfortune goes
way beyond being a mammoth underdog to king-of-the-hill Duke in
today's first-round East Region game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we're going to get beat by the largest margin in
NCAA history,'' Florida A&AMP;M coach Mickey Clayton said. ``We don't
have time for me to tell you about all this team has been through.
We look at it like this: We've already faced all the adversity a
team can face.''
</P>
<P>
   Just coach speak? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, 7-foot-2 shot blocking center Jerome James
left a year early for the NBA. Then two starters suffered
season-ending injuries _ in the same preseason pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season, the wrong game times were printed in the
local paper. There were 12 people in the stands when one of those
games started and because the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference
office had the wrong game time, officials didn't show up for the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Florida A&AMP;M played 12 of its first 14 games on the road. During
one of those road trips, the basketball training room was
burglarized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember saying that all we could do is leave the bad times
in 1998 and hope for better things in 1999,'' senior guard and
leading scorer Monroe Pippins said, recalling a New Year's
resolution/wish/prayer.
</P>
<P>
   During a January road trip, sports information director Alvin
Hollins slipped on ice and tore up his knee.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 28, the bus scheduled to carry the team to the airport
for the MEAC tournament didn't show. On his way to the airport,
Clayton's car was broadsided. The coach and student trainer Thomas
Ray walked away, but Ray had to be cut out of the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   And Ray can't practice. Oh, yes, by the way _ the Rattlers have
nine healthy players and Ray can't serve as the 10th. Around
Tallahassee, this A&AMP;M team will be forever known as the Noble Nine.
</P>
<P>
   After going through all this, Florida A&AMP;M's reward is Duke. A
No. 16 seed has never defeated a No. 1 seed in 58 NCAA games. And,
the Rattlers are the 15th team to make the NCAA Tournament field
with a losing record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have no problems motivating ourselves for this game,''
said Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, whose team probably will be
without injured senior guard Trajan Langdon. ``We prepare the same
for every opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke has the nation's longest winning streak (27 games) and is
the only team to go 16-0 in Atlantic Coast Conference (19-0
counting three ACC tourney wins). Florida A&AMP;M's 0-10 start was the
worst in school history and the Rattlers became the lowest-seeded
(seventh) Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference to win the conference
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a true-life David and Goliath story,'' Clayton said. ``We
spent most of the week searching for rocks big enough to hit 'em
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke has seven McDonald's All-Americans. Florida A&AMP;M's favorite
restaurants on road trips feature the golden arches. Duke is
winning by an average margin of 25 points. The Rattlers are
45-point underdogs. No hope, no chance, no way.
</P>
<P>
   At yesterday's news conference, Pippins, Morris Scott, Kevin
George and Jamaal Rhodes met the media. (Pippins' name card was
spelled Pippens). The foursome was asked if they have dreamed the
dream. What happens if they beat Duke. Four hands shot in the air,
anxious to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure if we win, we'll be on Jay Leno, Oprah,'' Scott said.
``We'd be getting the big hype.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, do we have to play another game,'' Pippins said.
``I'm really hoping they'll give us those 45 points to start.''
</P>
<P>
   For condemned men, the Rattlers are taking their sentence with
smiles and good humor. It starts with the coach. Clayton's three
daughters all survived difficult, life-threatening births. Playing
Duke? After all that and the travails of this season? Bring it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we do is easy,'' said Clayton, whose 15 minutes of
good-natured humor earned him applause from the usually stoic
media. ``We got to the airport to fly here, I didn't have a ticket.
I had to buy a ticket. Don't laugh, that's true. We tell people and
they say that didn't happen. We got to Charlotte, we didn't have a
bus. I'm just glad to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 250 teams at home who would love to be here.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
