</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS CROSS DOOMSAYERS WITH SENSATIONAL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excuse the radical and outrageous opinion, but somebody needed
to finally say it, and I've bravely nominated myself.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you read it here first:
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are having a sensational NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   By taking this dramatic personal plunge, it goes against about
seven months of learned hockey wisdom involving some local, some
national, and some Canadian precincts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past baseball season, the Yankees played at a .700
percent clip, stirring many to declare, or at least compare, this
to the greatest clubs of all time.
</P>
<P>
   In this hockey season, the Stars are playing at a .770 percent
clip, and what's the reaction? Mainly, that it's a team facing the
eve of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, it has been repeatedly reported since October
that a disaster in Dallas is waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   So, where is that locker-room rebellion by the players against
mean ol' coach Hitch? This fairy tale hit national print at least
twice. And the angry star who was going to slug Ken Hitchcock _
what happened to Mr. Ali?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the left-handed shot at left winger the Stars
absolutely had to have to round out the top two lines. Bob Gainey
sitting on his front-office butt, not pulling the trigger on that
deal _ just wait 'til March. Yes, the Stars were supposed to be
suffering about now without a southpaw in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   It's March, the Stars are 11-2-2 in their past 15 games, even
with the injured Brett Hull missing the past seven.
</P>
<P>
   And Eddie Belfour _ when does The Eagle start choking? And Roman
Turek _ trade him right now for that left winger. Why have the
luxury of two good goaltenders?
</P>
<P>
   Plus, don't forget that bad slab of ice at Reunion. Nobody can
win playing on that mush.
</P>
<P>
   On and on and on, the bogus information and opinions have piled
up around the Stars. All they've done thus far is establish
themselves as the NHL's very best. And there isn't even a close
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of a time when I was part of a pretty good
team,'' said Gainey, the general manager who was a Hall of Fame
winger in Montreal's dynasty days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were beaten at home one night,'' Gainey continued, ``and
the next morning, the team received great admonishment in the
newspapers for that performance. We had a lead over the rest of the
league that was very substantial, but at practice that morning, the
coach told us he wanted to have a team meeting there on the ice to
address a serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The shocked Montreal players gathered around Scotty Bowman,
expecting a verbal wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick and tired,'' Bowman began, ``of the way you guys keep
blowing out the hair driers in the locker room. Those things cost
the club sixteen bucks apiece, and I want this to stop right now.''
Pausing, Bowman then finished with, ``Other than that, our team
doesn't have any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the Stars. Not now. The playoffs, of course, are
coming, and if there's no Stanley Cup being paraded through
downtown Dallas streets in June, then all the criticism will come
back home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   But first had to come the regular season. Based on everything
the Stars have accomplished to date, there is no team better
prepared to tackle the Stanley Cup grind. In fact, late April can't
get here fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey admits to being irked at times over how the Stars are
portrayed in the media, and particularly the early season stories
on locker room rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do realize it's part of the territory,'' he said. ``We want
to be on top, but with that comes more attention. And with that
comes an attitude among some media of how can I look at it
differently, or what do I see with this team that others don't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have difficulty with a little controversy. And when
you take the strong personalities on this team, there are going to
be conflicting opinions and clashes. That is part of the process
when you put a group of talented people together for nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   But in digging through both media reality and fabrication,
Gainey attempts to keep the ice level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can take it for what it's worth,'' he said, ``as long as
you remain confident in who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Hitchcock drives this club hard. But who
says too hard? If it's certain players, so what? Players are always
the first to complain. And nobody is perfect. Like Gainey and the
front office making an apparent preseason mistake by not re-signing
left-handed winger Juha Lind, who returned to Finland in a money
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But overall? Let both the record and a season of misinformation
speak to that.
nn
</P>
