<HEADLINE>
ARKANSAS' HOOD MAY MISS GAME WITH IOWA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Derek Hood, Arkansas' leading rebounder, aggravated a
recurring lower back strain during the team's 94-80 victory against
Siena and is questionable for tomorrow's second-round game against
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Hood, a 6-foot-8 forward, left the court in pain three times
during the second half and sat out the final five minutes. He took
heat and ice treatments after the contest, which ended with Hood
grabbing three rebounds, well below his average of 10.5.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers list him as questionable for the Iowa game, but coach
Nolan Richardson said he expects Hood to see at least limited
action against a Hawkeyes' team that is taller and more physical
than the Razorbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may not be full-strength, but he'll be ready to play at
least a little bit,'' Richardson said. ``We need him. When he's
out, we have trouble getting any rebounds. Without him, our chances
of winning become very questionable a lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hood hobbled, Siena outrebounded Arkansas, 41-35.
OLIVER'S GUTSY EFFORT
</P>
<P>
   Iowa omitted point guard Dean Oliver from its starting lineup
for the first time in 56 games, but the sophomore came off the
bench to score 15 points in 19 minutes in a 77-64 victory against
Alabama-Birmingham. Oliver made 5 of 7 shots, including both of his
3-point attempts, despite battling a respiratory infection that
made him doubtful until pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a courageous, courageous effort. Dean told me
\RWednesday\S that he'd play, but the way he looked, I wasn't so
sure,'' said Iowa coach Tom Davis, who gave Ryan Luehsman his first
start of the season at the point.
</P>
<P>
   Luehsman contributed five points and two assists in 22 minutes,
allowing Oliver ample time to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get out on the court, you forget about being sick,''
Oliver said. ``I thought coach did a good job limiting my minutes
and keeping me fresh.''
PASSING MAYBERRY
</P>
<P>
   By dishing out 10 assists against Siena, Arkansas point guard
Kareem Reid surpassed Lee Mayberry as the school's career record
holder. Reid, a senior, has 737 assists. Mayberry, who played from
1988-92, had 729.
</P>
<P>
   The record is especially meaningful, Reid said, because he is a
member of the only senior class in Nolan Richardson's 14 seasons at
Arkansas that has not won at least a division championship in the
Southeastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people talk about how we haven't won any rings, so
it's nice to have the record. This is a great accomplishment,''
Reid said. ``Lee Mayberry was a great player. But he had eight or
nine people he could pass it to. Most of mine have come from
getting the ball to Pat Bradley.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
