<SLUG> BC-BKC-MISSOURI-NEW-MEXICO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG'S LATE JUMPER LIFTS LOBOS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Finally, there has been a Kenny Thomas sighting during
crunch time of a New Mexico game in the NCAA men's basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   And there is now evidence that the Lobos, who joined the 64-team
field despite the worst Ratings Percentage Index of any at-large
invitee in tournament history, may be worthy of the faith shown in
them by members of the NCAA selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   But neither would have been a topic of second-round discussion
among college basketball fans if not for a driving, pull-up jumper
that Lobos' guard Lamont Long sank with six seconds remaining last
night to give New Mexico a 61-59 victory over Missouri at McNichols
Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Long's shot, which he lofted over two Missouri defenders, sent
the Lobos (25-8) on to tomorrow's second-round matchup against the
winner of last night's late game between Connecticut and UT-San
Antonio. Missouri, runner-up in the Big 12 during the regular
season, ends its year at 20-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get fouled,'' said Long, who drove left
against Tigers' guard John Woods, then floated the ball over the
outstretched arms of 6-foot-11 center Monte Hardge , who stepped up
to form a double-team. ``I didn't get fouled, so I threw it up
there and it just fell for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The play was identical to the one the Lobos ran to defeat Rice,
51-49, with 10.2 seconds remaining in the opening game of last
week's WAC tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good play,'' said New Mexico coach Dave Bliss. ``So we
thought we'd run it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Long's game-winner allowed the Lobos to survive an implosion
down the stretch. Up by 59-54 with 2:01 remaining, New Mexico
suffered two turnovers and failed to score again until Long's
basket. The momentum appeared to swing to Missouri when Thomas (20
points, 10 rebounds) fouled out with 1:31 remaining and guard Keyon
Dooling tied the game, 59-59, with a pair of free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, however, missed their final four shots, including a
breakaway layup by Dooling and a follow-up dunk attempt by Albert
White at the 1:13 mark. Long eventually landed the telling blow as
a means of vindication for the Lobos, who entered the game with an
RPI of 74, and for Thomas, an All-America center who had averaged
just 9.0 points and 5.5 rebounds in six previous NCAA tournament
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about time I was able to step it up in an NCAA game,''
said Thomas, who had almost as many fouls (nine) as points (15)
during the 1998 tournament, hastening the Lobos' second-round exit.
``I wanted to show people I could stay in the game and not foul out
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Long (17 points, 12 rebounds) answered most of them.
But that did not prevent a controversial ending.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
