<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-MAGIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS RISE UP TO CUT DOWN MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After 20 previous attempts, the Mavericks finally
racked up a victory against a quality team.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, what a convincing win it was.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks totally outhustled Orlando and played with a lot
of energy en route to whipping the Magic, 93-76, before 14,553 last
night at Reunion Arena. The win snapped a four-game losing streak
and pushed the Mavericks' record to 7-14.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando, among the top four teams in the Eastern Conference,
dropped to 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have led at halftime seven times this season, and
have come away winners on six occasions. That statistic didn't go
unnoticed by Mavericks coach/general manager Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley said Nelson challenged his team at halftime to
maintain the slim 46-44 lead they mounted at intermission. The
Mavericks heeded Nelson's words and went out and ripped apart one
of the best teams in the NBA with a solid all-around effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and we competed for 48 minutes and I think because
of that we had the outcome that we had,'' said Finley, who scored
18 points. ``I think the guys took it upon themselves to go out
there and just try to destroy Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the most part, guys just went out there and put
all they had and the results were a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were aggressive at both ends of the floor and the
76 points were the fewest they have allowed in a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for the second time this season, the Mavericks had three
players post double-doubles. Gary Trent led the parade with 21
points and 10 rebounds, A.C. Green contributed 13 points and 11
rebounds, and Shawn Bradley collected 10 points and 10 boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any offensive rhythm we got into tonight was a deep second to
the way we played defense tonight,'' said Steve Nash, who just
missed a double-double with 9 points and 11 assists. ``For the most
part, defense is the key to our success.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16-4 run at the outset of the fourth quarter provided the
Mavericks with a comfortable 84-65 lead with 5:20 remaining in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pack was back in the lineup to help energize the
Mavericks with his mercurial speed. Pack, who refused to play in
Tuesday's game against Phoenix because he deemed the playing
surface too slippery, jump started a second-half rally and got back
on the fans' good side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot has been made out it,'' Pack said of Tuesday's
game. ``I've moved on from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pack slipped once during the second half and came up with a
slight limp. His teammates were having fun with that piece of
irony.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said that the 12-rebound advantage the Mavericks enjoyed
_ not to mention limiting Orlando to .388 shooting from the field _
was the type of stuff he'd like to see on a game-by-game basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played like a real team tonight,'' Nelson said. ``I
was very proud of the guys; they just beat \Rone of\S the best
teams in the East and beat them handily.''
</P>
<P>
   Magic coach Chuck Daly was ejected with 1:34 remaining in the
third period when he ran onto the court to protest a call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody tried to do whatever they could do to
scratch a win out, and we did it,'' Nelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
