<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARKANSAS-SIENA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIENA FAILS TRYING TO MIMIC ARKANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Siena basketball coach Paul Hewitt admits he borrowed
the blueprint that carried his team to its first NCAA Tournament
berth in a decade from Arkansas counterpart Nolan Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt learned yesterday that he remains a long way from
duplicating the original.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on its pressure defense and an early salvo of
3-point shots, Arkansas built a 21-point lead in the first eight
minutes and breezed to a 94-80 victory in the first round of the
West Region at McNichols Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Razorbacks scored 18 of their first 20 points from beyond
the 3-point arc and led, 29-8, with 11:30 remaining in the first
half. Arkansas (23-10), the No. 4 seed in the West Region, never
let the lead dip below double-digits the rest of the way in setting
up tomorrow's second round matchup against Iowa (19-9), a 77-64
winner over Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Siena (25-6), the No. 13 seed, was one-and-done in its first
NCAA appearance since 1989. Hewitt said he learned plenty from his
first up-close-and-personal encounter with the Razorbacks, who
showed no ill-effects from playing on three consecutive nights in
last week's Southeastern Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people put a 3-point barrage like that on you, there's
nothing you can do,'' said Hewitt, who watched Arkansas hit 50
percent from 3-point range (15-of-30) and force 24 turnovers. ``To
be honest, I didn't think Arkansas could shoot like that or keep up
the tempo they did. I thought they might show some tired legs from
having a long week at the \RSEC\S tournament. But they never did.
They're in great shape.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
