<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO RANGERS, CLEMENS, IT'S BAD KARMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Surveying the night's marquee, you had Roger
Clemens _ old No. 12 _ pitching for the team in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   You had flowers being laid at the Joe DiMaggio monument outside
of the ballpark. You had 10,382 fans, standing in silence for a
thank-you message from the cancer-stricken manager, Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   You had, in other words, enough bad karma for the Rangers last
night to make them think they were the Washington Generals.
</P>
<P>
   Four innings of air balls against Clemens completed the scene.
Roger, the mighty morphing almost-Ranger, looked much the same in a
New York uniform as he did in Boston or Toronto duds.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared unhittable. The scoreboard, clogged with
Clemens-crafted zeroes, supported as much.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens started and pitched four innings, silencing the Rangers
without a hit. He walked one, struck out three, lathered himself
into a sweaty, post-workout froth, and then returned to the
clubhouse to assess what otherwise could be considered a spring
training masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a ton of work to do,'' Clemens announced.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd around Roger's locker stall blinked at the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitch I did leave over the middle they hit hard,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   I doublechecked my scorecard. The only thing faulty about
Clemens' showing last night appeared to be his eyesight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw all of his pitches for strikes,'' said Rangers left
fielder Rusty Greer, who struck out against Clemens in the first
inning but did manage to line out hard to center in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked normal to me. I don't know how he feels, but from a
hitter's standpoint he looks pretty sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another reminder of how larcenous the February trade
was that brought Clemens to the Yanks. The New York clubhouse was
already lined with stars _ from Bernie Williams to Derek Jeter to
David Cone to even the backup left fielders.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees prevailed because of tradition, wealth, power and
pin-striped persuasion. Did the Rangers ever really have a chance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there definitely was some consideration there,'' Clemens
said last night.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to be helpful, recounting the saga that led him from
Toronto to George Steinbrenner's roost. But Clemens' agents, the
Hendricks brothers, Alan and Randy, apparently have the whole
sequence reduced to a series of they-said-he-saids, and Roger just
parrots it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, out of nowhere, I got the call about the deal with New
York,'' Clemens said, delivering the punch line.
</P>
<P>
   So was he almost a Texas Ranger or not, inquiring minds wanted
to know?
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I have a lot of family there,'' Clemens answered.
``My wife was born there. I know a lot of their guys. I love the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``And eventually, when the boys are grown, I might find myself
up in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, great. At age 50 or thereabouts, Clemens will move to
Arlington. Buy your season tickets now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team would want Roger Clemens,'' the Rangers' Greer
continued. ``He's a guy who is going to help every ball club that
he's on. He's almost a guaranteed 20 wins, and he gives
everything's he's got.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to have him on our team, but ... we didn't
get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens suggested that ``at the 12th hour,'' the Rangers upped
the ante _ ``offered that Mateo kid,'' he said _ but by then it was
already too late.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket was asked about reports that Rangers owner _ and
fellow Texas alum _ Tom Hicks nearly made an orange-laced power
play to secure Clemens' services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had a chance to meet him one time,'' Clemens said.
``It was pretty cordial. We have a good relationship. I heard all
about him and what he had been doing with the hockey team. My
agents spoke highly of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we had a chance to visit, maybe, 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rangers fans may insert sighs here).
</P>
<P>
   On a night when foul karma abounded and when manager Johnny
Oates even trotted out the first-string lineup, the Rangers were
overwhelmed by Clemens and the Yankee machine again.
</P>
<P>
   The scary part is that Clemens says he's just getting started in
this first spring in Yankeeland. He's not nearly in as fit shape,
he said, as he eventually wants to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all, not at all,'' Clemens protested. ``I've got quite
a bit of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to power-pitch a little more and to drive
the ball a little harder.''
</P>
<P>
   I doublechecked my scorecard. Bad eyesight.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
