A7577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-UTSA-HNS &LR;      03-12 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-UTSA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ Early on, they were hanging close and feeling good about
things. The score stayed close longer than anyone expected. For a
moment or two, they could even dream a little.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then, with 15 minutes left, the Texas-San Antonio Roadrunners
were hitting both the wall and the oxygen bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The image of the latter was telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got a little tired,'' Connecticut's Richard
Hamilton said. ``We might have worn them out a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' 91-66 victory in the first round of the West
Regional certainly attests to that, but UTSA had some fun before
the evening went sour. The game was tied at 19 with just over 11
minutes left in the first half, in fact, before UConn went on a
33-8 run to make it 52-27 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were outmanned, especially inside,'' Roadrunners coach Tim
Carter said. ``But I was proud of our guys. They gave it all they
had.''
</P>
<P>
   As first-round NCAA games go, this one was such an apparent
mismatch that the coach of the top seed could afford to take the
night off. Connecticut's Jim Calhoun stayed back at the team hotel
after coming down with virus-like symptoms earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out about 20 minutes before the game coach
Calhoun would not be with the team, I was happy because I knew that
meant the food I sent over to his hotel got to him,'' Carter joked.
``I was hoping it would get to about five or six of his players,
but it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, who also missed an early season game against Hartford
with an intestinal bug, probably didn't see much on television to
make him feel any worse _ at least not after those few queasy
moments at the start. By halftime, Hamilton already had 17 points,
while Kevin Freeman added 10. UConn had recovered to make 20 of 38
shots (52.6 percent) while forcing 14 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With associate head coach Dave Leitao taking over for Calhoun,
the top-seeded Huskies never looked back, and the rest was pretty
much a formality, though the beauty of that clearly was in the eye
of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we had 39 and they had 39,'' Carter said.
``If it hadn't been for that big run, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton finished with 28 points, while Freeman had 16. Steve
Meyer led UTSA with 18, but the Roadrunners made only 41 percent of
their shots (to UConn's 55.2).
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our game plan was that we could wear them out with
numbers,'' Leitao said. ``We got a little winded, too, but over the
course of the game, it was to our advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   So UConn (29-2) goes on to Saturday's second round against New
Mexico, while UTSA (18-11) goes home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
