<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAT FINDS A SWEETHEART DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's take a pit bull break and catch up on the
life of Riley now being enjoyed in Simi Valley by the most faithful
feline in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Sweetheart, and you might remember her from a couple
of columns I wrote back in November 1996 that got a lot of national
attention.
</P>
<P>
   She's the cat who refused to believe that her owners would not
return to their earthquake-ravaged Sylmar condo after the big 1994
Northridge shaker, which sent her running away for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   When she returned, no one was there. So, for almost three years,
this cat camped out on the front porch of the red-tagged condo,
patiently waiting for a reunion that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   People walking and driving by the Foothill Boulevard complex
began noticing the cat's daily vigil and a few of them began
throwing some cat food over the fence to her because she was
getting pretty skinny scrounging around for food on her own.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Bill Marrujo, living down the block, even tried to
give her a home, but the cat would have no part of it, running away
after one day _ back to the red-tagged condo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hits you hard, just watching her sitting out there, waiting
for them to come home, day after day,'' said Marrujo, who nicknamed
the cat Sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   After I wrote about the cat's dedication, the red-tagged condo
turned into a shrine. Hundreds of cat lovers showed up trying to
coax Sweetheart to come home with them.
</P>
<P>
   They all failed, but, by then, it was too late. Sweetheart was a
local celebrity. Dozens of people stopped by every day to feed her.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, skinny Sweetheart looked like a prime candidate for
Jenny Craig. The only thing missing from her contented smile was a
toothpick.
</P>
<P>
   Then, one day about a week later, Sweetheart was gone. Just
disappeared into thin air. All the neighbors were hoping she had
finally found a good home.
</P>
<P>
   And, she had. At least that's what the handwritten sign that
appeared one morning a few days later in front of the red-tagged
condo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry about Sweetheart, she now has a good home,'' it
read.
</P>
<P>
   Who wrote it, and where the cat was taken has been a mystery for
more than 2 years now, until this week.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetheart's humanitarian catnapper finally made contact.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Jennifer Dowdall, and she lives with her widowed
father, Owen, in Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   They were among the hundreds of people who initially tried
coaxing Sweetheart to come home with them. But Jennifer was more
diligent. She and her dad went back after the crowds died down and
``catnapped'' the cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt so bad for it,'' she said Thursday. ``One night, we
went back and my dad pulled the fence down while I grabbed
Sweetheart and put her in a cat cage I had in the back seat of our
car. She didn't put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first week or so after we brought her home she was
very frightened,'' Jennifer said. ``She got out the screen door
after about the fifth day, and I thought she was gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after about an hour, she came back in our back yard and
has been with us every since,'' Jennifer said. ``I think she was
finally tired of waiting for her old owners to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after taking Sweetheart, the Dowdalls realized a lot
of people were probably wondering what happened to the cat, so they
returned and put up the sign saying she was fine and in a good
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been doing wonderful,'' Jennifer said, adding she
finally came forward after running across the 1996 columns and
figured I might want to know whatever happened to the country's
most faithful feline.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's treated like a queen around here. She sleeps on my bed
all the time and knows that's her room, too. She goes to the vet
for checkups, and to get all her shots. And she loves to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We leave the back screen door unlatched and she pushes it open
when she wants to go out and lay in the grass or on the patio for
an hour or so. When she wants to come back in, she pulls the door
open with her paw and comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have squirrels and birds that come in our back yard
everyday to be fed, but Sweetheart never bothers them. She just
lays on the grass and watches them, but never tries to chase or
hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I call a wonderful cat,'' Jennifer said.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to reach Bill Marrujo Thursday to give him the good
news, but he wasn't around. Hopefully he'll read the column today
and smile.
</P>
<P>
   The country's most faithful feline has made out just fine. She's
living the life of Riley in Simi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
