<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     03-12 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BOSTON _ He sat by himself on the top row at Hofheinz Pavilion, by
all appearances a lonely, disconsolate figure. He spurned at least
one offer to join the party in a private suite behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, DeLoss Dodds didn't feel like having fun. The
University of Texas basketball team, in its first game under a new,
young coach to whom Dodds had paid a lot of money, was in a
disheveled state and would, in fact, lose to a bad University of
Houston team that was being coached by a local folk hero working
practically for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Drexler's Cougars would not have a better evening all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Barnes' Longhorns would not have a worse one, although a
couple of games in the weeks ahead would definitely be in the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters for Dodds, of course, was a lingering
sentiment among some UT fanatics that the athletic director had
unfairly, even cruelly, railroaded previous coach Tom Penders out
of a job he had done rather well, a most recent down season and
controversial offseason notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Penders had not gone gently into the good night. He was
ripping Dodds to pieces at every turn, and he continues to do so. A
few exes probably still believe Penders has every right to spew
invective and point to his making the NCAA Tournament field in his
first season at George Washington as proof of his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Dodds can comfortably occupy his seat at Fleet
Center tonight for the Longhorns' game against Purdue and feel
quite OK about his decision to change coaches. It was the right
move. Absolutely. Without a doubt. No question about it.
</P>
<P>
   In a somewhat amazing development considering the season's early
tough sledding, Texas won the Big 12 regular-season title and
earned a No. 7 seed in the East Regional. Surely the AD feels fully
vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never gotten into vindication,'' he says, and the
conversation about Penders stops right there. Barnes he will talk
about, however. With delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick's better than I thought he would be,'' Dodds insists,
``and I thought he was really good. He's been able to step in and
pull the team together, and the kids seem to be enjoying what
they're doing. They're playing as a team, and with some success. He
has done a better job than I thought possible in the first year, so
I'm pleased with it. I think we have one of the best young coaches
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is the anti-Penders in terms of basketball philosophy,
personal style and ingrained work ethic. While Penders was himself
a godsend for the Horns when he arrived on the Forty Acres in 1988,
taking a program in ruins to a modest level of national prominence
almost on the strength of his fast-talking, glad-handing and
high-profile scheduling, he had suffered a precipitous loss of
momentum lately.
</P>
<P>
   The fault was his, no one else's. He got lazy. And he got fat.
</P>
<P>
   So did his team. Barnes' first workout with the surviving
Longhorns, a 6 a.m. ordeal designed to test the players'
conditioning, came the day after he signed on last April. He was
mortified by the physical shape they were in. These were the
Runnin' Horns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh, my, my, my,''' Barnes recalls. ``I thought
about calling (Clemson athletic director) Bobby Robinson and
asking, `Did you fill my job yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   With the defections of guards Luke Axtell and Bernard Smith,
there weren't enough players to scrimmage five-on-five. Also, the
core of the team was split in half. Kris Clack and Chico Vazquez,
strong Penders-backers, held lingering grudges about the role Chris
Mihm and Gabe Muoneke played in turning Dodds against the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes couldn't have walked into more convoluted circumstances.
At $700,000, more money than any of his Big 12 peers was making, he
probably felt underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   At 3-8, he also felt rather unloved. But because he was teaching
fundamentals and preaching togetherness _ and because the X's and
O's upon which any revival would ultimately rest were solid _ the
Longhorns won 16 of their next 19 games before finally hiccuping in
the Big 12 tournament semifinals against Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   They were tired. They still aren't deep enough, and Barnes
drives them hard. No one is complaining, though. Definitely not the
boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see lots of individual improvement,'' Dodds said after the
regular-season title was secured. ``He's made a team out of them.
From what it was when he walked in to what it is today, it's just a
remarkable transformation. It's a different feeling altogether.
Never in my wildest dreams did I expect this.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes didn't just succeed. He made himself a legitimate
coach-of-the-year candidate, although Auburn's Cliff Ellis, Miami's
Leonard Hamilton or Michigan State's Tom Izzo is likely to finish
ahead of him in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The AD may not be into the vindication thing, but
vindicated he is. Whatever happens in Beantown over the weekend,
Dodds is free and clear. He needn't feel like a lonely guy anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
