<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAWEST-MISSOURI     03-12 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAWEST-MISSOURI-UNM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ It wasn't exactly the second coming of Tyus Edney, but for
the Missouri Tigers, it was eerily familiar just the same.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once more, Norm Stewart's team exits the NCAA Tournament under
peculiar circumstances, and this time, the officials even got into
the act.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Tigers had no quarrel with Lamont Long's lean-in
jumper with six seconds left _ the winning points in New Mexico's
61-59 first-round victory in the West Regional on Thursday night.
What happened next, however, left confusion and a bitter
aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   After a made basket in the final minute, the clock is supposed
to stop until the ball is put back into play. Instead, it kept
running as the Tigers inbounded quickly and pushed the ball
upcourt.
</P>
<P>
   How much a lost second or two mattered after Brian Grawer's
desperation 35-footer was deflected with a little more than a
second left is open to debate. Stewart admitted that he didn't want
a timeout after Long's basket, so that was not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Tigers, the No. 8 seed, clearly lost time that might
have allowed for a better shot. Just as clearly, the bizarre ending
heightened Missouri's frustration in its first NCAA game since
UCLA's Edney beat the Tigers with that length-of-the-floor drive at
Boise, Idaho, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows the rules and what we can say, so I can't
answer that for you,'' Stewart said, alluding to NCAA regulations
prohibiting comments on officiating. ``If we keep going, we'll get
to where you can ask me my name and I can give it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was quick to note that his team had contributed
significantly to its own demise. Long's winning shot came after the
Tigers missed three chances to break the tie _ two on drives by
freshman guard Keyon Dooling, the other on a missed follow-up dunk
by Albert White on Dooling's first miss.
</P>
<P>
   Long then dribbled into the left side of the lane, went up in
traffic and nailed the jumper. Missouri got the ball in so quickly
that no one noticed that the clock kept running.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake is correctable, but not after the officials leave
the floor. Later, referee Frank Scagliotta issued a statement
regarding the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't correct it unless we have definite knowledge (there
is an error). No official noticed it, no one noticed it hadn't
stopped because the ball came in so quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we leave the floor, the game is over. There is no way to
correct anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened,'' Stewart said. ``I'm sure that won't happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   For Missouri, that came as little consolation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
