</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA UPSET BY DETROIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For five months, the UCLA Bruins talked of new
blood and a better attitude. They had a refreshing, tenacious
style. They wore bold, black uniforms and splattered the cover of
their media guide with the phrase, ``There's a New Dawn in
Westwood.''
</P>
<P>
   But when dusk fell Thursday and their season disappeared into
the frigid Midwestern night, what remained looked eerily familiar _
like Tulsa, like Princeton, like all the other early exits and
underachieving finishes the program has produced this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Bruins lost to No. 12 Detroit Mercy 56-53
Thursday night in the RCA Dome, and in so doing proved why this was
the most popular upset pick in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA wasted leads of nine and six points in the second half. It
lost star guard Baron Davis to fouls, and it scored just five
points in the last six minutes, failing to execute against a zone
defense just as it failed against Stanford two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The end came on Daniel Whye's difficult 18-foot jumper with 12
seconds left, which gave the Titans a 53-50 lead and sealed defeat
for the Bruins in the same building they lost to Princeton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It was their third first-round loss in six years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (22-9) were the most popular upset pick in the first
round _ a sentiment based in part on UCLA's youth and
inconsistency, in part of Detroit's reputation and style. The
Titans, who beat St. John's in the first round last year, play a
grinding tempo the Bruins detest.
</P>
<P>
   In his pregame comments, UCLA coach Steve Lavin seemed to be
preparing his team and fans for defeat. Lavin bemoaned the Bruins'
inconsistency, he called Detroit ``the most dangerous team in the
tournament.'' Lastly, he said the Bruins _ with 11 national titles
and four McDonald's All-Americans _ felt like the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans (25-5) had UCLA well-scouted and played the only way
they could to survive: by slowing the tempo to a crawl. They used a
deliberate attack that forced UCLA to play defense for extended
periods. They did not take bad shots, which limited UCLA's fast
break opportunities. And they handled the ball like a newborn
against UCLA's full-court pressure, which also prevented the
Bruins' break from revving.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Detroit played a compact zone that shut off the
penetration and passing lanes into the low post. This forced the
Bruins to rely on the weakest aspect of their game _ perimeter
jumpers. Of UCLA's 50 shots, 27 were 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only way Detroit could play _ the way Princeton
played, the way Miami played last year, the obvious way.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were precise and productive _ for four minutes. Davis
and Earl Watson connected on 3-pointers to give UCLA a 9-3 lead,
but then Detroit switched to its zone and the Bruins' offense shut
down. Four scoreless UCLA possessions later, Detroit had pulled
even.
</P>
<P>
   Defense dominated the middle portion of the half. The Bruins
secured their defense and held Detroit without a field goal for
nearly seven minutes, but they made little progress offensively.
Davis missed a long 3-pointer, Watson missed two free throws, and
Matt Barnes clanked a 3-pointer he should never have attempted.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon Rush finally converted for UCLA, hitting a 3-pointer from
the left wing. The teams exchanged baskets in the last two minutes
_ a rare display of offense that ended with UCLA leading 32-30.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins emerged from halftime appearing more comfortable with
the tempo and their plan. Watson found Davis for a 3-pointer,
converted a Davis miss and then deflected a loose ball downcourt to
Ray Young for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   With a 40-31 lead, UCLA was in control _ or so it seemed. Rashad
Phillips steadied Detroit with a 3-pointer, then Davis committed
his third and fourth fouls in a 30-second span. The fourth, a
charge on the fast break, was questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Davis hit the bench for two minutes _ two scoreless minutes for
UCLA _ and that was all Detroit needed. Jermaine Jackson made four
free throws and Phillips hit a mid-range jumper with 9:28 left to
erase the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins used a wild sequence to grab a 48-42 lead with 6:12
left, but Detroit tightened its defense in the stretch and claimed
a 49-48 lead with 1:53 left.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:19 remaining, Davis fouled out, and UCLA bowed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
