<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOWARD'S FUTURE IN DOUBT AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward has been AWOL from
the Trojans football program for several weeks, and his future for
next season remains in doubt, according to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, a potential All-American who just two months ago
declared he would return for his senior season, has not attended
USC winter practices since early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I just don't know. That's the situation. It's
kind of out of my hands,'' said his father, Rodney Soward. ``Let's
just wait and see. He's all right. I don't really want to talk
about it. It should come to light in the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett refused comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Soward was told by coaches he could be
kicked off the team if he did not start attending practices, but he
still skipped Thursday's team meeting and practice, which was the
final official gathering before the Trojans disbanded for next
week's spring break.
</P>
<P>
   USC coaches had not spoken to Soward for two weeks until an
assistant coach showed up at one of his classes Wednesday. Soward
said he would come to Thursday's team meeting, but did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Soward will return to USC next season, his father said:
``I guess he'll be there. We're going to have to wait and see. It's
just unfortunate right now. It's bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, Soward has mentioned to friends the
possibility of applying for the NFL's supplemental draft, which
usually takes place in June or July. An NFL spokesperson said
Thursday that players are not expected to submit applications until
at least two month's after April's regular draft.
</P>
<P>
   Soward has also sporadically attended classes during USC's
spring semester and there is some question over whether he will be
able to retain his eligibility, even if he does intend to play for
the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Hackett suspended Soward from the season opener
against Purdue because of poor academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Soward could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   He and Hackett have had some turbulent times the past 12 months.
Soward was not happy over his role in the offense last season. When
he announced he was staying for his senior season in January,
Soward alluded to his frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and coach, we're going to sit down and have a lot of
planning to make things a lot better,'' Soward said. ``We're going
to come up with different ways to get me the ball. I'm going to be
a big part of this offense. I'm probably the biggest part of this
offense coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   USC tight end Antoine Harris saw Soward on Wednesday, but the
pair never discussed Soward's status.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same old R. Jay,'' Harris said. ``We didn't even talk
about it. We went bowling.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Hackett has interviewed former Washington assistant Steve
Morton to coach tight ends. Morton has coached the offensive line
at Washington since 1992....
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Kevin McLaughlin of Hart High has been given a
medical redshirt and will no longer play football. McLaughlin
injured his shoulder last spring and did not play in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
