<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-12 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ORLANDO, Fla. _ As they like to say up the road at Walt Disney's
Magic Kingdom, it's a small world after all.
</P>
<P>
   So tiny when a team such as George Washington can have its
offense run by a point guard named Shawnta Rogers who stands all of
5 feet, 4 inches.
</P>
<P>
   So very small when Colonials coach Tom Penders can spend most of
his first season on the job seizing every opportunity to take
another cheap shot at his ex-boss at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe we should call this DeLoss Dodds' revenge as Penders
team came up positively miniature in a 108-88 first-round NCAA
Tournament loss to Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   It was Penders who spent the last half of his 10-year tenure at
Texas sitting around fat and happy on his reputation. But to hear
it now, it was somehow Dodds' fault that the Longhorns' program was
running in place.
</P>
<P>
   It was Penders who alienated a large part of last year's Texas
team, resulting in a mutiny that eventually produced his
resignation. But the revised version sold all of this season to a
new audience is that Dodds lit the fuse that blew the whole thing
up.
</P>
<P>
   Penders spouted his vitriol to any open notebook or live
microphone, and Dodds never once responded. Now, the silence is
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   For no matter what happens to the Longhorns in their first-round
meeting with Purdue in the East Regional tonight, thanks at least
to the Big Dance schedule-makers, Texas will be waltzing at least
one day longer than Penders.
</P>
<P>
   This could have been billed as the bombast matchup of the South
Regional. To get a couple of objects more full of hot air than Bob
Knight and Penders going head-to-head in the first round, the NCAA
would have had to stage a blimp race inside the Orlando Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, as usual, hit the ground running his mouth with nonstop
complaints, most of them having to do with the late (10:05 p.m.
EST) starting time of the game. He took his usual shots at NCAA
officials, the media, bus drivers, anybody at all who could provide
a target and deflect attention from the fact that the Hoosiers had
been bounced from the Dance in the first round three times in the
past four years and hadn't won as many as two Tournament games
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Penders, meanwhile, took a team that went 24-9 last year under
Mike Jarvis, guided the Colonials to a 20-9 record and into the
Tournament, and convinced the gullible nation's capital that it was
a remarkable turnaround. Travelin' Tommy has spent the season
telling anybody who will listen that he's so glad to be out of
Texas and back on the East Coast, where everybody knows the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to draw up diagrams for people anymore,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe a few plays would help.
</P>
<P>
   Now when he isn't at the tanning salon or preening like a
peacock on the sidelines, Penders is blaming everything except the
fall of the Japanese economy on Dodds, the Texas athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing that we were able to accomplish everything that
we did in our time there,'' Penders moaned. ``That guy undermined
practically everything we did for the last seven years. When I
think of all the wins and television appearances, and it's a wonder
we were able to accomplish any of that with him there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a wonder that Penders has been able to peddle this
same offensive show as something that is cutting-edge rather than
simply undisciplined for all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Penders ran a team out onto the floor that looked like the
General Assembly of the United Nations. He had two players from
Belarus, two from Spain and one each from Israel, Portugal, Brazil,
Central African Republic, Canada and the Netherlands, and, as
usual, the concept of playing defense or taking anything other than
the first jump shot was a foreign concept.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, same old Tom.
</P>
<P>
   To watch the Hoosiers play, one would not have thought that
Indiana was only a mediocre 5-8 against ranked teams this season or
that its last outing was an 82-66 thumping by last-place Illinois
in the Big Ten tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoosiers were sloppy with the ball, turning it over six
times in the first four minutes. But the Colonials were even more
of a mess. They were one quick jumper after another that clanked
off the rim, and they were a defense with no ability to stop on the
interior, allowing Indiana's Kirk Haston to carve them for 27
points and Luke Recker for 20.
</P>
<P>
   GW put up 90 shots to only 56 for Indiana but still made four
fewer field goals. Rogers took 31 shots and made only 10. The
Colonials shot 37.8 percent. The Hoosiers made them pay. Somehow,
Dodds will get the blame.
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Penders, it's always a small, small world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
