<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO (Warsaw, Poland) _ When Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic formally join NATO on Friday, it will be the return of
three nations, and not merely their militaries, to the center of
European civilization. At the start, these three countries will not
add much to NATO's military capacities. In fact, they have just
managed to meet the alliance's minimum military requirements for
integrated air defense, security procedures and language-training.
By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND-ABORTION (Dublin) _ The forcible occupation of a Dublin
family planning clinic by a group of American anti-abortion
militants has reignited the highly emotional issue of abortion in
this overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Tel Aviv, Israel) _ New centrist party vying to
be in middle of Israeli politics. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-SECURITY (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ As modern science
becomes an overwhelmingly international enterprise, a clash has
intensified between the scientific value of sharing information and
the national security need to keep secrets _ including advanced
designs of nuclear weapons. Scientists and engineers who have
watched their world evolve from a small club of male elites into a
yeasty mix of men and women from every continent say that the
balancing act has grown extraordinarily difficult. By Sandra
Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER (Undated) _ Pressured by patient groups and
media leaks, researchers agree to move up their release of studies
of bone-marrow transplants as treatment for breast cancer. The
studies are the first large-scale tests of the expensive and
controversial treatment. Their early release, reported in The Wall
Street Journal, poses a difficult political issue for the American
Society of Clinical Oncology and the National Cancer Institute,
which is sponsoring two of the studies. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLT-GUNS (West Hartford, Conn.) _ For more than 150 years, the
story of Colt guns has been intertwined with the history of
America. But there is no peace these days at Colt's Manufacturing
Co., which has suffered from a boom-and-bust history and is just
now rebounding from a 1994 bankruptcy. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-BUSINESS _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. recently felt obliged to
apologize to Thailand after one of its reports drove down the
shares of the nation's largest bank and angered the finance
minister. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   UAL-HEADHUNT (Undated) _ Ending one of the most closely watched
executive searches, UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, has
narrowed its hunt for a new chief executive to two candidates,
according to two people close to the search. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   JONES-9WEST-MARKETPLACE _ Jones Apparel Group Inc. and Nine West
Group Inc., the two fashion companies that plan to waltz down the
aisle soon, have much more in common than aiming to sell chic
clothing and shoes to the same high-spending career women. By
Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   METLIFE-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ As Metropolitan Life Insurance
Co. prepares to go public, the insurance giant is starting to show
its public face in a very different way, playing down cartoon faces
in favor of human ones. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman on the loyalty
factor in the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A.M. Rosenthal on diplomacy and
deception.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sports of The Times column
on Joe DiMaggio's funeral. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-MUSEUMS (New York) _ Of all the love-hate relationships
that roil the art world, none is more fraught or stimulating than
that between artists and museums. This makes perfect sense, since
the two occupy opposite ends of the art world food chain. Artists
make art; museums select some of that art for their collections,
where it is preserved, elevated and, most of all, displayed. Once
on view, it offers other artists inspiration, helping them unlock
their own talents, which brings the food chain full circle. This
fascination fuels ``Museum as Muse: Artists Reflect,'' a remarkable
exhibition that opens Sunday at the Museum of Modern Art. By
Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH-FILMS (New York) _ Having to consume the $40 million
buckets of toxic popcorn Hollywood churns out month after month can
throw a film critic into a state of hand-wringing despair. Why has
an industry with the potential to enrich our lives sunk into a
soul-deadening wasteland of cartoonish violence and adolescent
pranks? And where can you go to find a cinematic semblance of
flesh-and-blood people with complicated emotions; where can you
find movies with characters who think as well as act. There is an
answer, and it can be summed up in one word: France. A look at the
annual series Rendez-Vous With French Cinema Today. By Stephen
Holden.
</P>
<P>
   LION-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Lion in Winter,'' a
revival, at the Roundabout Theater. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Baby Geniuses'': Bob Clark,
director; with Kathleen Turner, Christopher Lloyd, Kim Cattrall,
Peter MacNicol, Dom DeLuise, Ruby Dee, Kyle Howard. Reviewed by
</P>
<P>
   CORRUPTOR-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Corruptor'': James
Foley, director; with Chow Yun-Fat, Elizabeth Lindsey, Mark
Wahlberg. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   DEEP-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Deep End of the Ocean'': Jlu
Grosbard, director; with Michelle Pfeiffer, Treat Williams,
Jonathan Jackson, Whoopi Goldberg. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   DEVIL-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Devil's Island'': Fridrik Thor
Fridriksson, director; in Icelandic, with English subtitles.
Reviewed by Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
<P>
   HARMONISTS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Harmonists'': Joseph
