<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEGAPLEX-MARKETING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER OWNERS EYE SNACK-SELLING PLOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS -- In a few months, while buying your tickets to
``Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace,'' you'll also be able to
buy popcorn, soda and a hot dog at the ticket window.
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the ploys the nation's top-grossing
megaplexes are cooking up to entice customers to open their wallets
even wider despite the sky-high prices for snack-bar food.
</P>
<P>
   John King Jr., manager of the year-old Winnetka 20 in Los
Angeles, told attendees Thursday at the ShoWest convention in Las
Vegas that parent Pacific Theatres is actively considering
launching such a plan, which would offer three or four of the most
popular snack combinations.
</P>
<P>
   The option would give customers the convenience of reaching for
their pocketbook only once rather than twice. Patrons who pay for
snacks in advance would receive a separate ticket to turn in at the
concession stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to get a popcorn and Coke into the hands of every
customer,'' King told about 300 executives and managers during a
panel on the working of the nation's leading megaplex theaters.
``This could cut down on sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   King said Pacific likely would start the program at the Winnetka
20 or the Beach Cities megaplex in Redondo Beach, adding he hopes
to launch prior to the May 19 opening of ``Episode I.''
</P>
<P>
   King also indicated the food option would be available for
advance tickets purchased through the ETM Entertainment Network,
which has started selling tickets at its kiosks in malls and
supermarkets. ``We think there are going to be a lot of people who
want to avoid the lines at the box office when `Star Wars' comes
out,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive to the audience, however, was King's disclosure
that the Winnetka 20 had sold 89,000 pounds of popcorn, 22,000
gallons of soda and 175,000 Pink's premium hot dogs since it opened
in February 1998. The frankfurters, the first sold outside Pink's
stand in Hollywood, comprised a surprising 10 percent of concession
revenues, well above industry averages.
</P>
<P>
   Other panelists strongly endorsed the concept of broadening
snack-bar menus with items such as chicken strips, pizza, espresso
and buffalo wings. Valerie Baty, manager of a 20-screen megaplex in
Plano, Texas, said customers have been highly enthused about her
theater's policy of allowing them to take food from the lobby's
restaurant, such as chicken-fried steak, into theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want people to forget about everything and have fun,''
she said. ``We want them to have a `wow' experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Snack bars are a powerful profit engine that drives. Theaters
make profits of more than 80 percent on concession revenues,
compared with less than 50 percent on box office revenues.
Megaplexes have become popular among chains because the massive
concession stands and staggered start times boost spending by
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe per-patron food spending is around $2 per
customer at megaplexes but high-profile destinations with
out-of-the-ordinary items such as the Universal City 18-screen
megaplex can take in as much as $3 per patron. Operators stressed
the industry needs to overcome its resistance to change in order to
continue competing for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Urrutia, manager of a 20-plex in Southfield, Mich., that
offers extensive auto-themed promotions, declared, ``The heart and
soul of our business is movies and popcorn but we must look outside
the box.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
