r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     03-12 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAGS RELISH PAYBACK, DESPITE CIRCUMSTANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They waited 365 days for this game.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was going to keep Gonzaga from relishing it, not after
the Bulldogs were snubbed by the NCAA selection committee in 1998;
not after they sat home last March at their Spokane outpost and
watched as teams from the bigger, more prestigious athletic
conferences were awarded at-large bids _ bids these Bulldogs knew
they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   So, with all that in mind, you expected sympathy?
</P>
<P>
   You expected nice, little Gonzaga to think twice about the
problems the big, ol' University of Minnesota basketball team
apparently heaped upon itself, when four current players were
implicated in allegations of academic fraud?
</P>
<P>
   No chance in hell, which, if you recall, was just about the same
odds the NCAA selection committee gave Gonzaga one year ago, when
they did not invite the Bulldogs to dance.
</P>
<P>
   Snubbed once, Gonzaga was hardened against any proposition that
their first-round victory Thursday at KeyArena was anything less
than deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room to mess up. No one ever offered to write a
paper for me,'' Gonzaga 3-point specialist Richie Frahm said, just
moments after Gonzaga escaped with a 75-63 win. The resurrection of
Frahm's deadly outside shooting, just in the nick of time, was one
of the keys to the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I said (before the game when the Gopher
suspensions were announced) was that I didn't want to talk about it
at all,'' Gonzaga coach Dan Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to beat Minnesota in the NCAA tournament by
40 points, regardless of who they have on the floor. We'll take the
12-point win.''
</P>
<P>
   The message from the intense Gonzaga coach? All is fair in love
and war and single-elimination basketball. There is no gray area
when it comes to the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Win, you keep going. Lose, you go home. No quibbling. The
no-haggle rule is definitely in effect.
</P>
<P>
   By these pressurized, March madness standards, of course Gonzaga
earned it _ the Bulldogs' first NCAA tournament victory ever. No
apologies. No talk of a tainted win, even if their first-round
opponents, the Gophers, were anything less than golden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming in that (Minnesota) coach (Clem) Haskins would
have his team ready to go,'' Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had had five guys to suit up, they would have been
ready, so no, it did not change our approach.''
</P>
<P>
   With this homework-cheating scandal hanging over them, it was
correct that Minnesota university officials suspended the four
Gophers allegedly involved. The university's risk of forfeit later
was too great. So, too, was the risk of having to hand back a nice
chunk of CBS money, should the allegations prove true.
</P>
<P>
   One question, though: If the players could not play in case
wrongdoing is later verified, what about the coach?
</P>
<P>
   You begrudgingly understand a big-time football coach making
excuses that he can't possibly keep track of 80 or more
``student-athletes'' and all their business when allegations of
NCAA cheating occur. But a dozen players on a basketball squad?
That is harder to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   That was the atmosphere surrounding this game, one that even
diehard Gopher fans said was embarrassing to the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing to hear about something like this,''
said one Twin Cities resident who flew in with 80 other Gopher
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have two sets of standards, one that says regular
students have do to one thing and athletes get to do something
else.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Gopher basketball program is finding out there is no
way someone else can write your term papers and take your tests for
you, as alleged by a former university employee, the Bulldogs had
their moment of reckoning, too _ something they will no doubt keep
in mind tomorrow, when their next opponent is Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   To everyone's knowledge, the Cardinal players have all done
their homework.
</P>
<P>
   What the Bulldogs learned, though, is that it doesn't matter how
much of a lead you have at half-time _ no one is going to make your
jump shots. No one is going to make your threes. No one is going to
come in and give you a boost of confidence to make sure you pass
this NCAA tournament test.
</P>
<P>
   After reeling off a first-half barrage of jumpers and treys by
shooting 55.6 percent, Gonzaga opened the second half and found out
just what March madness is all about.
</P>
<P>
   The Gophers closed to within four, 58-54, with less than seven
minutes to play. They made it 65-63 with just over two minutes
left. It was tough not to imagine just what would have happened if
starters Miles Tarver and Kevin Clark had not been suspended
because the `Zags reeled under the pressure _ at least until Frahm
hit a huge three to make it 68-63, after he missed three shots
before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first appearance in the big dance and we were a
little tentative,'' Santangelo said. ``I'm probably the most
guilty. I got tentative. When our shots stop falling, we got a
little timid and started wondering, `What the heck is going on?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the basketball gods had started off with a script
that called for the forces of good prevailing easily over the
forces of not-so-good, they almost ran out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga, in the end, snuck out its first NCAA win as the
underdog in a game loaded with extenuating circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Bulldogs gave it a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
