<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-BULLS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BULL: SONICS SURVIVE MISTAKES TO BEAT CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Some may believe it was simply being in the right
place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   You are supposed to beat this version of the Chicago Bulls,
right? But nothing has been promised to the Sonics lately. And the
past 10 days have been anything but easy.
</P>
<P>
   So beating the Bulls, 92-83, Thursday night at United Center was
actually, well, sort of a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The victory finally gave the Sonics (10-9) something to relish
after drudging through a five-game losing streak. Although the
Sonics finished 1-2 on the road trip, which had them playing three
games in three nights, they were relieved to end their worst skid
since the 1990-91 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we've been finding ways to lose, it feels good just to
get a win,'' forward Detlef Schrempf said. ``It hasn't been a
pleasant 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sonics coach Paul Westphal: ``We've been having some
heart-breaking losses. We just needed a win.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting 6-0, the Sonics had lost nine of their past 12
games. Thursday night was the third time in the past four games the
Sonics were battling for the win in the fourth quarter. They lost
three of those in the final moments. This time, the Sonics
concentrated down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls (5-14) were coming off an impressive 103-87 victory
against New Jersey on Tuesday night. It was just the second home
win for Chicago, but the struggling Sonics got all they could
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinging to an 85-82 lead with a minute left in the game, Gary
Payton sealed the win by calmly connecting on his fifth 3-pointer
with 44.7 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Payton scored eight of his team-high 25 points in the fourth
quarter. He made 9 of 17 shots, including 5 of 10 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need to get back home and fine-tune our whole game,''
Payton said. ``We're still not clicking on all cylinders. We're
struggling in all areas _ offense, defense and attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the Sonics recovered some of what they lacked most
during their skid: confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good team,'' forward Vin Baker said. ``Now we have
the schedule to get right back into it. We're not out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The week ahead is comfortable for the Sonics. They play the Los
Angeles Clippers at KeyArena on Sunday. Then the Sonics face
Vancouver, Golden State and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expected to win a lot of ball games. So this isn't a
celebration,'' guard Dale Ellis said. ``But when you lose five
games in a row, it's getting the monkey off your back. . . . Nobody
was really down. Everybody was just disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one was more devastated by the team's fall than
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   After being held out of the fourth quarter the past two games
because of his poor play, Baker began to show his frustrations. He
vented displeasure with his late-game benching after Wednesday's
loss at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   However, Baker changed his tune and attitude Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some intensity and a lot more enthusiasm,'' Baker said.
``It wasn't a personal thing. I knew I had to come out and play
well. I had to just put aside the thoughts of my bad play and do
what I could to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker finished with 18 points on 7-of-17 shooting. But his
biggest contribution came on defense. He switched defensive
assignments and guarded Toni Kukoc after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc mostly kept Chicago afloat with 21 points by halftime. He
finished with 28 points, and the Bulls managed just one point in
the last 2:27 of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us play small ball for a good part of the game,''
Westphal said. ``Vin accepted the challenge to play Kukoc. The way
he played tonight, I'd say he is back. He made some clutch shots
and his free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got out and covered Kukoc. He gave up some quickness, but
he denied him the ball and stopped him from going left. That
defense plus Gary and Detlef playing well tonight was the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, the Sonics were in the same position as many of the
Bulls' opponents. Chicago has played hard despite its record. The
Bulls have been particularly scrappy at the beginning of games and
led 52-49 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sonics dominated the offensive glass, 9-2, and used the
extra shots to stay in the game. The team benefited greatly from
Schrempf's 18 points and 10 rebounds off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Schrempf ignited a second-half surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we just have to put another streak together,'' Schrempf
said. ``If we win five or six games in a row, all of this will be
forgotten _ all of the problems, the meetings, everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
