<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-II-NYT &LR;      03-12 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-II-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN TAKES CARE OF BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Connecticut's destination may be the Final Four, but to
get there, the top-seeded Huskies must take care of pesky matters
like their first-round game against 16th-seeded Texas-San Antonio.
Every long and magical journey starts with a first, sometimes
perfunctory, step and that is what on Thursday night's 91-66
victory was for UConn.
</P>
<P>
   With their head coach, Jim Calhoun, watching the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament game from his hotel room
because of an intestinal virus, the Huskies overcame a lethargic
start to frustrate and annihilate the Roadrunners in the West
Regional.
</P>
<P>
   The game stopped being competitive when Connecticut ended the
first half with 15 straight points to construct a 25-point lead,
52-27, at McNichols Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun missed his second game this season with a virus, but
even the demanding coach could not scream at the television after
Connecticut (29-2) used its pressure defense to tame Texas-San
Antonio (18-11) and create numerous opportunities on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton, one of several Huskies who shaved his head
before the game, paced Connecticut with 28 points, and Kevin
Freeman added 16.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a blowout, as expected, so UConn's trip through
March will continue, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we're peaking at the right time,'' Freeman had said on
Wednesday. ``We're confident coming into this game. We want to play
well. We got a lot of challenges ahead of us. This is the first
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Before UConn's rout, Lamont Long made an 8-foot jumper in
traffic with six seconds left to lift ninth-seeded New Mexico past
eighth-seeded Missouri, 61-59; fourth-seeded Arkansas nailed 15
3-pointers in silencing 13th-seeded Siena, 94-80, and Iowa kept Tom
Davis' coaching career with the Hawkeyes alive for at least one
more game with a 77-64 victory over Alabama-Birmingham. Davis is
being pushed out after 13 seasons, but he is enjoying his last,
bittersweet ride.
</P>
<P>
   UConn will oppose New Mexico (25-8) and Arkansas (23-10) will
play Iowa (19-9) in the second round on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun was replaced for the second time this season by his
associate head coach, Dave Leitao. Leitao also filled in for the
Huskies' 95-58 victory over Hartford on Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just spoke to Coach Calhoun and he's feeling a little
better,'' Leitao said. ``He's happy that we played the way we
played and did the things that we talked about doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin, who had a career-high 10 assists for
Connecticut, said: ``Coach's spirit was there and Coach Leitao did
a great job. It seemed like Coach Calhoun wasn't even missing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a knowing nod, Calhoun acknowledged on Wednesday that the
first 10 minutes of Thursday night's game would be critical.
Connecticut needed to show Texas-San Antonio why its defense is so
suffocating, why its transition game stifles teams and why it is
seeded first in the regional.
</P>
<P>
   Why was this so important? Because the worst thing a heavily
favored team can do in the tournament is give the underdog reasons
to believe an upset is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the score,'' Calhoun had explained, ``but the way you
play.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Leitao closely monitored how Connecticut reacted
against the 16th-seeded Roadrunners for the first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were sluggish at the outset, playing just well
enough to stay ahead of Texas-San Antonio. That is exactly what
Calhoun was worried about. Hamilton had 9 points as the Huskies
snagged a 15-14 lead, but Ricky Reed hit a 3-pointer to put the
underdogs up by 19-17 with 11:50 left.
</P>
<P>
   In his hotel room, Calhoun was probably squirming. But El-Amin
made a 3-pointer and had a steal and a layup to key an 11-0 spurt
that gave the Huskies the lead at 28-19. There were just under 10
minutes left and Calhoun's critical test period was over. Had
Connecticut left enough of an imprint to sink the Roadrunners?
Maybe not, but that damaging punch came soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies kept antagonizing Texas-San Antonio (14 turnovers)
and used their pressure defense to ignite their transition game
while scoring 22 of the last 25 points in the half. Hamilton, who
had 17 points, drilled a runner at the buzzer to enable the Huskies
to trot to the locker room with a 52-27 bulge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never think about losing,'' Hamilton had said on Wednesday.
``Every time we step on the court, we think we're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, as expected, UConn did.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon session, reality slapped Siena in the face
early and often. Because the Razorbacks hung out beyond the 3-point
arc, because Siena tried to sprint with Arkansas and stumbled to 24
turnovers and because the Razorbacks were too athletic and too
deep, Arkansas cruised.
</P>
<P>
   Siena's chances for an upset started to fizzle as five
Razorbacks hit 3-pointers in the first six minutes and Arkansas
rumbled to a 21-point lead nine minutes into the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
