<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-TEXAS-SAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTSA BEST MEDICINE FOR UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
 ANTONIO-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As the Connecticut Huskies drove to McNichols Arena
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, associate coach Dave Leitao couldn't help but
wonder to himself, ``Why now, why me?'' Leitao was left to lead the
top-seeded Huskies into their NCAA Tournament West regional
first-round game after head coach Jim Calhoun developed a
gastro-intestinal virus so severe it prevented him from attending.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter. Calhoun had so well prepared his team for the
worst in the days leading up to Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's contest, he made
Leitao's job virtually worry free. Scrappy, 16th-seeded Texas-San
Antonio initially frustrated UConn with its 3-2 zone defense and
reckless up-tempo attack. But UConn (29-2) responded with pressure
defense to outscore the opposition, 33-8, over the last 11:18 of
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, it was evident which coach had brought his
squad to town three days in advance to adjust to the mile-high
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun's presence wasn't necessary Thursday &UR;  &LR; night. His team
was a living testament to the Boy Scout motto, and its preparation
led to a 91-66 Huskies' triumph that could have served as a sleep
aid to their coach, who watched from his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Leitao said he spoke to Calhoun immediately following the game
and Calhoun was pleased with what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit of a different circumstance with him not
being here. We just hope to have him back for (Saturday's) game,''
said Leitao, who used 10 players Thursday &UR;  &LR; night (with six playing
at least 24 minutes) to wear down the Roadrunners (18-12).
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players in the locker room that we are the best
defensive team in the country,'' he added. ``We can stop you in a
lot of different ways with a lot of different people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way for the Huskies was forward Richard Hamilton (28
points), who scored 17 in the first half. Forward Kevin Freeman
added 16 points and had a team-high eight boards, and Khalid
El-Amin added 7 points and 10 assists for the Huskies, which scored
at will over the last 10 minutes of the first half. Jake Voskuhl
led UConn's interior defense with four of the team's 10 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kept the pressure on them, they got tired and later on
in the first half we showed we had spurtability,'' said El-Amin,
whose terminology prompted laughter from his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But he was correct in that UTSA (18-11) did suffer from fatigue
trying to keep up with UConn. With 15:51 left, UTSA's Reggie
Minniweather, Jerome Riley, and Ricky Reed all required oxygen
during a timeout, with the Huskies leading, 54-35. It didn't get
much better when play resumed _ the fresh Huskies staged a 7-2 run
for a 61-37 advantage with 13:46 left.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hamilton, ``The thing that helped us was that we practiced
at the Air Force Academy where it was about 2,000 feet higher than
it was here (at McNichols, which is 5,280 feet above sea level).
And we pushed ourselves, so we didn't get fatigued.''
</P>
<P>
   UTSA coach Tim Carter praised his team for continuing to play
hard even when it appeared so bothered by fatigue it didn't score a
field goal over the last 6:24 of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take away their run late in the first half, and who knows
what could have happened,'' said Carter, whose team trailed by as
many as 67-40 with 11:25 left before taking advantage of UConn's
sloppiness to cut the lead to 18.
</P>
<P>
   Carter joked that when he was told Calhoun wouldn't attend the
game, ``I was happy because I knew the food I sent over to his
hotel had gotten to him. I was hoping a few of his players would
have eaten some, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Meyer led UTSA with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   As for Calhoun's status for Saturday's second-round contest
against No. 9 New Mexico (25-8), trainer Jeff Anderson said he gave
the coach a shot to relieve his symptoms and said Calhoun usually
is back on his feet after 24 hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
