<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIAR END FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ For five months, the UCLA Bruins talked of new
blood and a better attitude. They had a refreshing, tenacious
style. They wore bold, black uniforms and splattered the cover of
their media guide with the phrase, ``There's a New Dawn in
Westwood.''
</P>
<P>
   But when dusk fell and their season disappeared into the frigid
Midwestern night, what remained looked eerily familiar _ like
Tulsa, like Princeton, like all the other early exits and
underachieving ends the program has produced this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Bruins lost to the 12th-seeded Detroit 56-53
Thursday night before 27,959 in the RCA Dome _ their third
first-round defeat in six years.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, they proved why this was the most popular upset
pick in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't complain, they just stopped us,'' UCLA guard Baron
Davis said. ``All year, we were inconsistent. We took some teams
lightly and we didn't prepare right for the good teams. Tonight, it
caught up with us.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA lost despite taking a nine-point lead with 15 minutes left
and holding the Titans to 24 percent shooting in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins lost Davis to fouls, failed to grab crucial
rebounds, missed free throws, committed silly fouls and scored just
five points in the last six minutes _ all the things they've done
before.
</P>
<P>
   When it mattered most, the Bruins made two of their last 11
shots and failed to execute against a zone defense, just as they
failed against Stanford two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst feeling I've ever felt in my entire life,''
forward Sean Farnham said. ``We competed the whole game, but there
were a couple situations in regards to rebounds, loose balls and
being more solid on offense that cost us the game. We should have
gotten better shots. Our defense was phenomenal. When you hold a
team to 32 percent shooting, you should win.''
</P>
<P>
   The end came on Daniel Whye's difficult 18-foot jumper with 12
seconds left, giving the Titans a 53-50 lead and sealing defeat for
the Bruins in the same building they lost to Princeton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The finish substantiated the belief that without Davis on the
floor, the Bruins lack the experience, patience and structure to
win big games. His departure with 1:19 left _ on a non-shooting
foul 15 feet from the basket _ was devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really drained us emotionally, because he's our floor
leader,'' forward JaRon Rush said.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans (25-5) had UCLA well-scouted and played the only way
they could to survive: by slowing the tempo to a crawl. They used a
deliberate attack that forced UCLA to play defense for extended
periods.
</P>
<P>
   They did not take bad shots, which limited UCLA's fast-break
opportunities. And they handled the ball like a newborn against
UCLA's full-court pressure, which also prevented the Bruins' break
from revving.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Detroit played a compact zone that shut off the
penetration and passing lanes into the low post. This forced the
Bruins to rely on the weakest aspect of their game _ perimeter
jumpers. Of UCLA's 50 shots, 27 were 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Bruins committed 17 turnovers _ the equivalent
of 30 turnovers in a game of normal pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense prevailed,'' Titans forward Bacari Alexander said.
``We were able to keep them below their scoring average and keep
their percentages low. That's our type of game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only way Detroit could play. It was the way Princeton
played, the way Miami played last year, the obvious way. And it
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no mystery in terms of why we lost,'' coach Steve
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins emerged from halftime appearing more comfortable with
the tempo and their plan. Earl Watson found Davis for a 3-pointer,
converted a Davis miss and then deflected a loose ball downcourt to
Ray Young for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   With a 40-31 lead, UCLA was in control _ or so it seemed. Rashad
Phillips steadied Detroit with a 3-pointer, then Davis committed
his third and fourth fouls in a 30-second span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, if we could just execute a couple times, we've
got them,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   He hit the bench for two minutes _ two scoreless minutes for
UCLA _ and that was all Detroit needed. Jermaine Jackson made four
free throws and Phillips hit a mid-range jumper with 9:28 left to
erase the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins used a wild sequence to grab a 48-42 lead with 6:12
left, but Detroit tightened its defense in the stretch and claimed
a 49-48 margin lead with 1:53 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then Davis fouled out in what was probably his last game. And
UCLA bowed out.!end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
