<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS LIKELY TO TURN PRO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Sophomore guard Baron Davis has played his last
game for UCLA and will enter the NBA draft, according to a non-UCLA
source close to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the family and friends are hoping the Lakers get him,''
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who is expected to be one of the top players selected,
hinted at his plans when he waved to the crowd and hugged his
teammates in the final seconds of the regular-season finale Feb. 27
against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a 56-53 loss to Detroit on Thursday, Davis had 16 points and
four assists before fouling out. Afterward, he hugged teammates and
proffered advice, but refused to confirm his plans.
</P>
<P>
   He has said a decision will come soon after the season, but the
Bruins consider the issue closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone, and he probably would have left last year if he
hadn't gotten hurt,'' a UCLA source said, referring to the knee
injury Davis suffered in the 1998 second-round game against
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bruins have evaluated several high school
seniors, including Compton's Tito Maddox and Verbum Dei's Marlon
Parmer, but probably will not sign a point guard this year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they'll use Earl Watson and Ryan Bailey next season
while pursuing several top prep players _ the current juniors _ for
the 2000-01 season.
</P>
<P>
   Shall we dance? The Bruins waited (and waited) for their 10 p.m.
(EST) tipoff. The Ohio State-Murray State game ran late, then a
malfunctioning shot clock delayed tipoff an additional 10 minutes _
to 10:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   To get the blood flowing, the Bruins had a brief practice at the
RCA Dome and then held a short walk-through in the hotel ballroom _
a practice made popular by Indiana coach Bob Knight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic change from last year, when the Bruins passed
on the practice, sat around for 10 hours and played lethargically
against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Making a point: Some of the nation's best point guards have
gathered in the RCA Dome, and several of them have Southern
California connections.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's Jason Hart played at Inglewood High School and signed
with the Orangemen when UCLA didn't offer a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State's Doug Gottlieb is a Tustin native who originally
enrolled at Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   There's UCLA's Baron Davis, who played Pop Warner football with
Hart.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. Auburn's Doc Robinson, Murray State's Aubrey
Reese and Detroit's Jermaine Jackson are among the best in their
conferences. And don't forget Ohio State's Scoonie Penn, who
transferred from Boston College and was named Big Ten co-Player of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Dome doings: The RCA Dome has been the site of several memorable
tournament games this decade, with UCLA contributing twice.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1991, Duke stunned unbeaten UNLV 79-77 in the national
semifinals and then beat Kansas to win the first of its
back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, Princeton shocked defending national champ UCLA 43-41
in legendary coach Pete Carril's last NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1997, underdog Arizona slayed No. 1 seeds North Carolina
and Kentucky in the Final Four to win its first championship.
</P>
<P>
   _ And, now, UCLA's loss to No.12 seed Detroit on Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
