<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A SMALL TOWN AND ITS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are worse things than being from Beverly Hills. It was
thus disconcerting to learn that Monica Lewinsky regards my
hometown as the source of her anguish and our long national
nightmare. In ``Monica's Story,'' Andrew Morton blames Beverly
Hills' ``obsession'' with status, money and thinness for Ms.
Lewinsky's eating compulsions and self-destructive behavior. In
third grade, it seems, she was devastated not to be invited to Tori
Spelling's birthday party, featuring Michael Jackson and the
world's smallest pony.
</P>
<P>
   Of course this episode tells less about the snubber than the
snubbed. But Beverly Hills has always been a world unto itself.
When I was growing up in the 1950s and early 60s, it had many
features of other affluent suburbs along with a make-believe
quality that set it apart.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, it was largely a town of lawyers, doctors and
business people like my father who moved there after the war
because of its school system. The many people in the entertainment
business put on coats and ties in the morning, like everyone else,
and went to the studio to work, even as the studio system was
collapsing. Rodeo Drive had a bridle path down the middle, a relic
of a sleepier time, and the commercial center featured modest
stores like Newberry's, a five-and-dime, and Uncle Bernie's Toy
Menagerie, with a tree that dispensed lemonade.
</P>
<P>
   We all knew that our town was not normal, however. My
recollections include banal pleasures like seeing Jack Benny being
driven past my house each day, to and from Hillcrest Country Club.
As a kid, I used to sneak with my pals into the abandoned hilltop
estate of Harold Lloyd, the silent-movie star, for elaborate war
games amid the palatial terraces, fountains and crumbling statuary.
Oscar season? No big deal, but when the father of a school friend
won for best screenplay, I remember another friend joking that ``my
dad produced your dad's picture.'' Like many a high school, mine
had a Career Day, except that it had a comedy workshop with Joey
Bishop, Groucho Marx, Carl Reiner and Steve Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills, like everywhere else, changed forever when it
became engulfed by drugs and rebelliousness in the late 1960s. Then
came the California taxpayer revolt that dried up resources for the
school district. The financial squeeze led a few years ago to
alumni being asked for money to repair the high school ``swim
gym,'' memorably featured in ``It's a Wonderful Life,''when the
floor opens up and Jimmy Stewart and Donna Reed fall into the pool.
</P>
<P>
   But while these changes were occurring, Beverly Hills' status
went from famous to mythic. The entertainment industry became
consumed with itself, the public was eager to go along, and Beverly
Hills followed suit. Today the average American high school student
knows about the weekend film grosses, and Hollywood's
self-referential path has gone from ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' to
``Beverly Hills Cop'' to ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' a television hit
created by Aaron Spelling, of the 56,500-square-foot mansion (in
nearby Holmby Hills), and featuring his grown-up daughter, Tori.
</P>
<P>
   The town is now in what Charles Rosin, a Beverly Hills High
School graduate and former executive producer of ``Beverly Hills
90210,'' refers to as the post-Rodeo-Drive era. The center is still
headquarters to lots of show-business companies, but the population
has changed with the influx of wealthy Iranian immigrants. Indeed,
30 percent of the city speaks Farsi. Most residents do not shop
downtown, and they are less interested in the glamour than in the
fact that the police force takes only three minutes to respond to
emergencies. March Schwartz, longtime publisher of The Beverly
Hills Courier, feels that Monica Lewinsky's scathing attack on
Beverly Hills is a smear against a town that has had to endure more
than its share. ``We have always had errant students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it is interesting to speculate whether the events of the
last year would have occurred had Ms. Lewinsky grown up on the West
Side of Manhattan rather than in Los Angeles. Rosin, the television
producer, notes that the success of ``Beverly Hills 90210'' partly
derives from its portrayal of ``a serene external image of glamour
that covers up the inner turmoil and insecurities of the
characters.'' You can envy their lives and still see that they are
a mess. He said Ms. Lewinsky was ``a vintage Beverly Hills story''
and that ``she could have easily been a character on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   That actually sounds like a great sequel. Monica and Tori,
together at last. Did someone mention closure?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7628 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     03-12 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS AVOID BREAKING RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Clippers win, so help us. Clippers win.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry; it means the same thing in English.
</P>
<P>
   Now call your bookie about Charley Brown pitching that
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In defeating the Sacramento Kings 106-92 Thursday night in front
of 7,884 at the Sports Arena, the Clippers proved that some records
aren't meant to be broken, just tied.
</P>
<P>
   In a grim departure from 1999 tradition, their game faces didn't
end up covered with pie. Coach Chris Ford, the former Celtic, can
exhale, because he claimed a Clippers win before St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   And for those of you living in treehouses or on billboard
runways, it was the Clippers' very first victory in 18 dates this
season. In winning, they failed to break a deadlock with the
1988-'89 Miami expansion team that previously held the league
record for consecutive defeats to begin a season (ahem, 17).
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for a unification bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys have faced a lot of adversity,'' Ford said, ``but the
streak is over and hopefully it's the beginning of something new
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. At press time, ``The Tonight Show'' was attempting to
book the entire team for today's taping. Other than the NBA draft
lottery show, it would be their only NBC appearance this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clippers got what they deserved tonight,'' Kings coach
Rick Adelman said, ``and we got what we deserved.''
</P>
<P>
   In freezing history by becoming the only team to lose to the
Clippers so far this season, the 9-11 Kings caught Lorenzen Wright
on the rebound. Wright, who reclaimed the starting center role when
rookie Michael Olowokandi sprained his left ankle two weeks ago, is
one of those guys the Clippers didn't unload before Thursday's
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   All he did against Sacramento _ in the Clippers' third game in
as many nights _ was squeeze 20 rebounds... in the first half. He
completed the rebounding masterpiece with 26, the league's top mark
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to go out and get every rebound,'' said Wright,
who only tracked down 30 percent of the missed shots available.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings provided juice for the crowd through the relentless
razzle-dazzle of rookie point guard Jason ``White Chocolate''
Williams. Williams captured many imaginations and stuffed the stat
sheet with nine points (he missed 10 of 14 field-goal attempts) and
four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Clipperville, seven players scored in double figures.
Lamond Murray (15 points) and starter Tyrone Nesby (13) combined
for 28 points at small forward. Eric Piatkowski came off the bench
for eight points in each half. The Clippers' bench scored 50
points; the Kings' subs went for 35.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers point guard Darrick Martin led the Clippers with 18
points, 11 assists and one measly turnover. He demonstrated that _
at this stage of his career _ the offensively gifted Williams might
have difficulty guarding a mime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player and he's going to have a great career in
this league,'' Martin said of Williams, adding that the rookie's
attendant hype was no motivation. ``I just play as hard as I can no
matter if it's Jason Williams or Stephon Marbury.''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates are adopting a similar attitude. To extend their
current streak on Saturday, they'll have to defeat the Portland
Trail Blazers, who have the league's best record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
