<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 02:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METLIFE-AD-COLUMN-NYT     03-12 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METLIFE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEANUTS' GANG WILL NO LONGER BE MET LIFE'S MAIN REPRESENTATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company prepares
to go public, the insurance giant is starting to portray itself in
a very different way, playing down cartoon faces in favor of human
ones.
</P>
<P>
   For almost 15 years, campaigns by Young &AMP; Rubicam New York for
Met Life, as the company is often called, have featured Snoopy, the
anthropomorphic beagle, and other characters from the popular
``Peanuts'' comic strip. But in a revamped campaign that begins on
Sunday, they are being reduced to cameo roles as the agents and
customers of Met Life get top billing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in the initial series of commercials, Snoopy
appears just briefly, glimpsed on a television or computer screen
or smiling at the end. In a print ad, Snoopy turns up only in the
lower right-hand corner.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is indicative of the efforts necessary to freshen
long-running campaigns to avert consumer boredom and stay abreast
of important corporate events. Met Life announced in November that
it would take the first steps in a one-to-two-year process of
reorganizing into a stock-based corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Met Life is about to undergo a change that is perhaps more
significant than any in its 130-year history, becoming a public
company,'' said Bill Green, executive vice president at Y.&AMP; R. New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without totally abandoning the high recognition that Snoopy
and the `Peanuts' characters have given us,'' he added, ``we want
to marry the past, present and future of this company, if you will,
to announce we're changing and to build the Met Life brand as
strongly as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Conway, executive vice president and executive creative
director at Y.&AMP; R. New York, said: ``Believe me, when you've got
icons like the `Peanuts' characters working for you, you think very
carefully before stepping away from that. On the other hand, we
felt the need to talk about the history, because consumers like
hearing a part of the Met Life story they've not heard before,
especially with the changes Bob Benmosche is planning.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to Robert H. Benmosche, chairman, president
and chief executive at Met Life in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was too much Snoopy,'' Benmosche said of previous
campaigns, adding: ``When you talk about Met Life, you say, `That's
Snoopy's company,' and that's important. But we also want the ads
to begin to remind people why to do business with Met Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Results from consumers in focus groups were ``very clear,'' he
said, in revealing that the previous campaigns ``did a wonderful
job of getting people to think about Met Life when they saw
Snoopy.'' He added, ``What they didn't do was tell you what the
company did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason you come to Met Life and get paid is because it's a
strong company,'' he said. ``When things get tough, we have staying
power, and we can live up to guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   So gone are whimsical ``Peanuts'' tales centered on a Snoopy
treasure hunt, symbolizing the search for retirement income, or a
dive into Snoopy's water bowl by the diminutive bird Woodstock,
symbolizing the need for financial planning ``when you take the
plunge into'' major life changes like home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   While the longtime theme ``Get Met. It pays.'' continues, the
slogan now follows vignettes reminiscing about the company's
heritage. They are interwoven with contemporary tales about agents'
sales of products like insurance and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Benmosche traced his interest in Met Life's history to his
``joining the company three and a half years ago'' from Paine
Webber and before that Chase Manhattan; he is not a career
insurance executive like his predecessor, Harry P. Kamen, who
worked for Met Life for 39 years.
</P>
<P>
   As he studied his new company, Benmosche recalled: ``I was
amazed how many things Met Life had done. I would go around telling
people, `Did you realize the Plaza Hotel was built with Met Life
money? Or that in 1897 the company built a gym for its employees?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the country today remembers what people knew
years ago,'' he added, ``how substantial a company Met Life is.''
</P>
<P>
   Green agreed that Benmosche's being ``intensely interested in
the history of Met Life'' played a role in the campaign's new
direction. But, he added, ``because of the millennium, consumers
out there are more interested in the past than they were 10 or 15
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the new campaign concentrates on recounting the Met
Life role in founding an Immigrant Service and Citizenship Bureau,
helping save farms during the Depression and buying bonds during
World War II. Those stories are told by actors of diverse
backgrounds portraying Met Life agents in three disparate cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one big happy family, so you love the differences,''
says the actor playing a Met Life agent in Brooklyn, who mingles
with immigrants from around the world and describes himself as ``a
quarter Italian, a quarter Portuguese and an eighth Spanish.'' An
Asian-American actress playing a Met Life agent working in a
Chinatown neighborhood asserts: ``America still has a frontier. San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my town,'' an African-American actor declares in a third
commercial as he drives through Rock Falls, Ill., 114 miles west of
Chicago, visiting farmer customers.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call on Thursday to the Met Life office nearest to
Rock Falls, in Sterling, Ill., was answered by a woman who said
that the office there had two agents, neither black; Benmosche said
the spots were meant to be ``illustrative'' in imparting the
``message this is an incredibly diverse company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're strongest in people who just came to this country,''
Benmosche said, adding that in 1997-98, ``30 percent of our sales
to individuals were to people who are in this country but not born
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The spots will first appear during a rebroadcast of the film
``Schindler's List'' on NBC, which will be sponsored by Met Life
and the online company Snap. The first print ad will run on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign extends through April with a budget of $7 million;
Met Life typically spends $20 million to $25 million a year on
advertising. The spots will return at least two more times in 1999,
Green said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0244EST &QL; 
