A7635 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN     03-12 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LET THEIR GUARD DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Bruins knew Detroit was good. They knew
Detroit's guards were good. But not this good, no way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their guards were way better than I expected,'' UCLA forward
Travis Reed said. ``I mean, I knew they were good, but man, I
didn't think they were that good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had the best guards on the floor Thursday night in
their 56-53 upset of No. 5 seed UCLA, before 27,959 at the RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers confirm it: Jermaine Jackson and Rashad Phillips
combined for 33 points, six assists and seven turnovers. UCLA's
Baron Davis and Earl Watson combined for 25 points, 11 assists and
eight turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, Jermaine and I told each other
that every time we go out on the court, we'll go after the other
backcourt,'' Phillips said. ``That's what we came to do to Davis
and Watson.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans' tandem outrebounded their counterparts 10-9. They
hit 10 of 12 free throws, and they stayed in the game. The Bruins'
backcourt was 0 of 4 from the line _ as a team UCLA was 5 of 12 _
and Davis fouled out with 1:19 remaining, taking UCLA's hope to the
bench with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Us fouling and them going to the line kept them in the game,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a senior and the Midwestern Collegiate Conference MVP,
led all scorers with 17 points. Each time the Titans needed a
basket _ or a free throw _ he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, I smelled blood for whoever was guarding
me,'' he said. ``I had to go to my strength, and that's driving to
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we didn't feel we had to prove anything. Rashad and I can
play with any backcourt in the nation. I guess everybody has seen
the results. We're not saying we're better than anybody, but we can
play with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half proved it.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans made just five field goals but 14 of 16 free throws.
They shot 24 percent from the field, trailed by nine and six points
on separate occasions, but they never panicked, not once.
</P>
<P>
   Foul shooting and defense were the difference. The Titans
tightened their zone and smothered center Jerome Moiso, UCLA's only
accomplished low-post scorer. In the second half, he took one shot
_ an errant (and difficult) turnaround in the final minute _ and
made zero impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a great job inside,'' Moiso said. ``They were
swarming us, and I couldn't get the ball. It was hard going
inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 0250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
