   &UR; FOR THE LOVE OF MARS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TWO COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By OLIVER MORTON &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace engineer, author (``The Case for Mars'') and
controversial planetary visionary Robert Zubrin convened the
founding convention of the Mars Society in Boulder, Colo. His
mission? To tell the world that Mars exploration is scientifically
vital and technologically feasible. But the membership, united in
their ideal of a frontier utopia on the Red Planet, is fiercely
divided on the nature of a Martian society they would create.
Oliver Morton writes about science and technology and their effects
for The New Yorker, Science, Nature, and the Financial Times. He is
currently working on a book about Mars.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-MARS-SOCIETY-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRST AMERICANS: ORIGINS OF MAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By KAREN WRIGHT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Exciting new evidence suggests that the first humans in the New
World were not, as previously believed, mammoth hunters from
Siberia who crossed the Bering Strait at the end of the Ice Age.
Who, when, where and how the first North Americans came to the
continent is an evolving mystery with some new, compelling and
evolving answers. The surprising remains of Spirit Cave Man in a
museum laboratory outside Carson City, Nev., offer startling clues
as to the origins of mankind. Karen Wright is a free-lance writer
and editor.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-FIRST-AMERICANS-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
