<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAPETREE13-COX     03-12 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPETREE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The gospel according to Grapetree
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ The Lord works in mysterious ways, and it's
hard to say which of the ways he works with Grapetree Records is
the most mysterious:
</P>
<P>
   That there would even be such thing as a Christian gangsta rap
record label. That there would be a Christian gangsta rap label,
and it would gross about $2 million in 1998. That there would be a
Christian gangsta rap label, and its owner and CEO would dress in
cowboy boots, hat and Wranglers, and have a handlebar mustache. Or
that there would be a Christian gangsta rap label, and it would be
based in Round Rock.
</P>
<P>
   These are the odd circumstances surrounding Grapetree Records, a
label specializing in CDs by former street thugs who are pushing
Jesus these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them were in jail, some of them were shot _ whatever
it was, the Lord touched them deeply,'' explained Knolly Williams,
the 28-year-old president, founder and cowboy wannabe of Grapetree,
which just signed a distribution deal with industry giant EMI
Records that could make it the best-selling label of Central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   No, seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating a market for this kind of music,'' Williams
said. ``And maybe, just maybe, we're putting Round Rock on the map.
That's the thing in rap these days. You've got Master P from Baton
Rouge, and Too Short from Atlanta. It's cool to be from some place
other than New York or Los Angeles. We could make it so that it's
cool to be from Round Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Cool or not, the label's offices are out there on Texas 79, on
the easternmost edge of town. Past all the new chain restaurants.
Past the old churches, and the farmer's field where the new
baseball stadium is being built. Up a gravel road. Near a pond. In
a sprawling, two-story ranch house that could have belonged to a
neighbor of J.R. Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The home actually belongs to Williams and his wife, Josie, and
the ground floor is where their seven full-time employees work. The
couple bought the house two years ago with the intention of making
it Grapetree Central and, just a few months ago, they purchased
another house that will be a state-of-the-art recording studio.
It's in Round Rock, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually like it out here,'' said Grapetree publicist Vivian
Pascu-Neirth, who commutes from Austin. ``It's quiet and isolated,
which helps us focus on (the label).''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and his staff _ whose voice-mail greetings all start
with a music sound-bite and end with ``Thank you, and God bless'' _
are proud to say they run the No. 1 Christian gangsta-rap label in
the country out of their Round Rock offices. They're not too proud,
though, to answer one of two questions that always follow such a
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there really any other Christian gangsta-rap labels?''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, ``Why Round Rock?''
</P>
<P>
   Grapetree actually started at Williams' old home in Austin,
where he moved at age 18 to get away from the evils of his native
Los Angeles. A rapper himself who performs under the name Rubadub,
he was releasing his own cassettes and CDs by age 22 _ recordings
that loudly and proudly featured the Christian beliefs he said
touched him after he almost went to jail. When he started Grapetree
in 1992, Williams really didn't know if there were many other
Jesus-led rappers, but he found out after simultaneously starting a
fanzine called Heaven's Hip-Hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys who were also doing Christian rap started
calling me up,'' Williams said. ``It was clear there were other
people as serious about this music as I was, but they all said,
`Man, if we only had a record label.' ''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 26, Rubadub had a bona fide record company
with more than a dozen artists and plenty of overhead. That's when
he decided to buy a house and combine it with his offices to save
on rent. Round Rock gave him the best real-estate deal, and the
setting fit his self-described ``Texan-ized'' image.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago rapper Prime Minister, one of the 22 performers on the
Grapetree label, remembers his first taste of that image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Man, this guy really must have money, because only
a rich rancher would dress like that,''' he said. ``Eventually, I
realized it was just part of his trademark.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams and almost every performer on the Grapetree
roster, Prime Minister has a story about being fed up with the
gangsta life and turning to the Bible for help. He said he was
jailed for stabbing a rival gang member in the mid-'80s, and
eventually wound up with ties to the Chicago mob. ``I was bad
off,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   As with mainstream rappers, it's hard to establish whether any
Grapetree artists may have fabricated their gangsta backgrounds.
The difference, though, is that with most of these rappers, such a
story wouldn't necessarily help their careers. Until now, those
careers have involved modest to good CD sales, but mostly in
Christian book stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grapetree definitely makes up most of our rap section,'' said
John Parker, music buyer at the Shepherd's Shoppe in North Austin.
``I don't think a lot of our customers know what to make of it,
except for the ones who know what is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole gangsta thing can really turn a lot of people off,''
said Diamante Music representative Mark Cummings, whose Newport
Beach, Calif.-based company distributes Grapetree's CDs to
Christian stores.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings should be excited about Grapetree's output. Last year,
Grapetree became Diamante's best-selling label out of some 30 other
companies, averaging 10,000 to 25,000 copies per disc. Those sales
figures helped the label earn four of the six rap/hip-hop
nominations in the 1999 Dove Awards, the Grammys of Christian
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grapetree has cornered the Christian rap market,'' Cummings
said. ``There are bigger labels that might dabble in it, but
there's nothing like Grapetree. (Williams) is certainly the only
one who makes sure his product is on par with mainstream rap
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Grapetree fashions itself after the big boys by using a
lot of the same recording equipment and CD artwork, with album
covers that resemble those done by the Master P-favored Pen &AMP; Pixel
Graphics in Houston. And like Master P's No Limit Records, the
rappers on Grapetree come from all over, offering all kinds of
names, including Houston's Lil' Raskull, Denver's Preachas In Tha
Hood and the Miami-based D.C.P. (Demon Cap Peela). There are even
two offshoot labels now, the R&AMP;B-based Phat Boy Records and the
Hispanic-geared GT Latin, both Christian-oriented. Said Williams:
``I believe that our artists and our CDs can compete with any of
the CDs on the market, if given the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The distribution deal with EMI is that chance. EMI Christian
Music Group president Bill Hearn praised Grapetree for
``communicating the gospel to a music buyer that the Christian
music industry has not previously addressed,'' and promised them
distribution across the United States and in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Williams, Grapetree's CDs will be available in ``the
Wal-Marts, the Kmarts, and 4,500 music stores nationwide.'' The
question is, of course, whether anyone will buy them once they're
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are fed up with (mainstream gangsta rap),''
said Prime Minister, who used to be a rapper of that ilk. ``It was
a complete fluke that this music that's about degrading women and
killing people has survived for so long. It's over, done.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who plans to release 30 CDs this year, is banking on
the idea that people are more than just sick of all the curse
words, sexist lyrics and violent overtones in popular gangsta rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they want more,'' he said. ``Most of the rap music out
there now is about portraying the problems of the ghettos and
inner-city life. Well, that's easy to do. How about providing the
solutions in addition to the problems?''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Inner-city solutions from the gospel
according to Round Rock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
