</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD13-COX     03-12 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More on making a bookcase
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We'll assume we now have all the pieces cut for our
adjustable shelf bookcase, and we've routed the slots in the
uprights to hold the strips for the shelf supports.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to cut the rabbets for the 1/4-inch plywood
back. You can best do this with a router, on a table if you do it
before assembly, freehand if you do it afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute _ you say you don't know what a rabbet is?
Obviously, it is neither a cuddly furry creature nor the call of an
amorous bullfrog. Rabbet is a word coined by people who evidently
had a hard time saying rebate, and is now commonly used in the
trade to indicate the edge of a plank that has been cut back into
an L-shape.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably you've already drawn out a rough picture of your
bookcase, and decided whether you want the top fixed shelf to be
flush with the top of the uprights, or a few inches below the top.
I prefer the latter for two reasons _ it makes for a somewhat more
secure joint in general, but more importantly, it gives you a
perfectly useful shelf. You need to make that decision now, because
you don't want to run the rabbets on the uprights higher than the
top shelf. Since we're putting a toe kick under the bottom shelf,
you can go ahead and rabbet all the way to the bottom; it won't be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   So, select the uprights, mark the outside face on each of them,
and pick your top shelf. Mark the ``up'' side of it clearly.
</P>
<P>
   If you're putting the top shelf below the top of the uprights,
mark the spot where the shelf will go on each upright. I would
probably go ahead and cut the rabbets _ 1/4-inch wide and 1/4-inch
deep _ before joining the top and bottom shelves.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is no good reason not to wait until the case is
assembled and the glue is dry, and then run the rabbets around the
inside of the back using the router fence.
</P>
<P>
   That choice out of the way _ now or later _ it's a good time to
attach the solid oak trim. One hopes that you carefully selected
this wood for straightness and for thickness as close as possible
to the 3/4-inch thickness of the plywood. A hair thicker is okay;
thinner is a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   You need two pieces as long as the uprights, and one piece for
each of the shelves. An inch to 3/4-inch is sufficient width.
</P>
<P>
   Take the plank and joint one edge with a jointer/planer. If you
don't have one of these, and you don't have a jointer, you can set
up your router with a straight bit and a dependable metal
straightedge to get the edge straight. Using this nice square and
flat edge against the tablesaw fence, cut the first strip. If the
cut was good, you won't need to joint again before you cut the
second. Keep on cutting until you've got enough strips to do the
job, then cut them to length.
</P>
<P>
   The upright edges really need to be the same thickness as the
uprights themselves; otherwise things are going to get caught on
the protruding edge. If the edging is too thick, plane it or
carefully rip it to size. Very slightly oversize edging is OK on
the shelves as long as you make sure the overhang is at the bottom,
and not the upper surface, of the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Using plenty of clamps, glue the edging to the front edge of all
the plywood pieces. Don't forget to use pads under the clamp jaws,
and wipe up glue squeeze-out with a damp cloth. Once the glue is
dry _ give it at least 16 hours _ soften all the edges to taste,
either a little bit with a block plane or a lot with a round-over
bit in the router.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
