<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ ``Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an
occasional series in which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior
writer Joe Murray their memories of growing up in small-town
America: When my two cousins from Chicago started spending their
summer vacations at our house in the little town of Tiskilwa, Ill.,
life became an adventure. (Hynes, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY
FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Along with the general
store and the train depot, the church was a center of community
life in the rural South. It was either Baptist or Methodist. When
the Inman Methodist Church, already in adolescence when the Civil
War began, had a homecoming, J.C. Lovett, one of the faithful,
asked me to write a piece recalling my memories of growing up in
the congregation. I have quite a few. (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The real message of Rep. Bob Barr's legislation
to block lawsuits is that the gun lobby, for all its contrary
boasting, worries that the suing cities just may have a legal point
or two. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ the Republican effort to attach blame to the
Clinton White House for an appalling breakdown in security during
the Reagan and Bush administrations is so off-base as to be
laughable. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
