 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, March
13, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0312 _ A young woman faces the formidable task
of beating bulimia and anorexia nervosa after six years. But she
wants her personal suffering to help others recover from eating
disorders. ``I want to go around to high schools and talk,'' she
says, and she's establishing a foundation to help people pay for
the expensive treatment that health plans rarely cover. (Lamb,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITES -- A list of Web sites dealing with eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   SCANNER -- Besides decreasing the drugs and increasing the
comfort for fidgety children, the Aquilion scanner will enable the
radiation department to streamline its schedule and sooner
accommodate people without emergencies. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   ARTHRITIS DRUG -- Thousands of arthritis patients nationwide are
being prescribed Enbrel and two other new medicines for their
condition that control pain and swelling with fewer side effects,
such as stomach and kidney distress. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). (EDS: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for
the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   DENTISTS-LASERS _ Painless dental work is taking a major leap
with the introduction of lasers for tooth drilling. The new
process, tested for years, soon will be in your dentist's office.
That's one of the advances dentists will be discussing at the
annual Hinman Dental Meeting, starting March 18. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HOME&AMP;GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   KITCHENS _ Kitchens are the big ticket when it comes to
remodeling, and there are tons of options to consider. You can
become dizzy looking at catalogs and displays. There's nothing like
seeing the whole package to help you define what you like and
dislike. A good sampling of the current trends in kitchen design
will be offered next weekend and all for a good cause. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN _ Lee muses on the joy of taking walks alone in a
garden.''Walking alone brings me unique value. Like gardening,
walking through woods transports me to simpler times, unfraught . .
. When I lose myself in the woods, I imagine a good life in a
natural, untouched place a thousand years ago _ or a thousand years
hence.'' (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Cutting the rabbets for your
bookcase, and more. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-KIDS _ There's no age limits posted when organizations
go looking for volunteers. And in many cases, youngsters prove they
can do the same sort of work handled by their elders. The benefits?
Volunteering is a way for children to enlarge their world and grow
spiritually. It's also a way to explore interests, learn leadership
skills and discover unexpected talents. We write about and
photograph five groups of kids and their volunteer efforts through
the Red Cross, school, scouts, church and the Atlanta Food Bank.
(Henry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS .
</P>
<P>
   GRAPETREE _ As if a Christian gangsta rap label doesn't sound
like enough of an oddity, how about the fact that there's one in
Round Rock. And that it's one of the few area record companies
making money. Profile of Graptree Records, run by and featuring
street thugs who've found God without giving up the rapping.
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman). 30. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
