<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BARTLETT-$ADV1     03-12 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BARTLETT-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A 'DINOSAUR' EMERGES AS EARLY FRONT RUNNER IN HISTORIC MEXICAN
ELECTION
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trim.
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With BARTLETT-BOX-$ADV14.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLO, Mexico _ Among the many books in the governor's mansion
in this state east of Mexico City, Manuel Bartlett Diaz kept a copy
of ``The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an amusing choice of reading for a man struggling to
overcome an image as one of Mexico's most endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett -- who wants to be Mexico's next president -- has a
reputation for being one of the country's crustiest ``dinosaurs,''
the nickname for the authoritarian faction that used to control the
Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The party, which celebrated its 70th year in power this month,
has dominated the Mexican presidency and nearly every other aspect
of political life here since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   However, the PRI has been losing ground in recent years, and in
July 2000 could face Mexico's most competitive presidential
election yet. Hoping to energize its grassroots supporters, it has
decided to establish a more democratic internal process to select
its nominee for the election. Ironically, Bartlett -- considered by
many to be the consummate anti-democrat -- is benefiting most from
more party democracy and emerging as a front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where rumors substitute for solid information,
Bartlett is haunted by unproved allegations that he masterminded
electoral fraud for the PRI a decade ago and has consorted with
drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   He is not the favorite of President Ernesto Zedillo, a PRI
reformist and one of the 'technocrats' or free-market proponents
now dominating the party. But Bartlett is a shrewd politician who
is popular in Puebla, the state he governed for six years until
last month, and surveys show he is a top choice among the party's
rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   That support is significant because later this year, for the
first time in the PRI's history, the rank-and-file will be allowed
a voice in selecting the party's presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a candidate for the presidency of the republic in a
totally new process,'' said Bartlett, beaming with confidence in a
recent interview with Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the PRI's candidate has always been hand-picked by
the sitting president of the republic in secret machinations known
as the ``dedazo,'' the ``big finger.'' But this May the party is
expected to devise a new system for holding primaries to select a
candidate either by direct votes or through delegates at a national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect is delicious to Bartlett, who exudes the enthusiasm
of a born-again democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``For six decades the decision as to who would be the
presidential candidate was made behind-the-scenes by people on
high,'' Bartlett said. ``This process was useful and worked for
many years. But now it doesn't work because the country has changed
and we have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, following a speech by Zedillo endorsing the concept
of rank-and-file voting, Bartlett wasted no time in kicking his
campaign into gear.
</P>
<P>
   He made political history here by becoming the first PRI hopeful
to start airing television commercials explicitly depicting himself
as the best choice for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   He is challenging potential rivals serving in the federal
government to give up their jobs and declare themselves candidates,
too, so the fight can begin.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett has set up campaign headquarters in Mexico City and
other cities, and is making rounds to shore up his support among
PRI-affiliated labor unions and other party associations.
</P>
<P>
   At a speech last month before the Revolutionary Confederation of
Workers and Farmers, a PRI-controlled union, Bartlett gave the
crowd what it wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bases resent the loss of vigor in our party, resent its
separation from popular concerns,'' he said to cheers and
backslapping. ``They demand that the party be rescued.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Bartlett tried to drum up support at a Mexico City
university recently students mocked him with signs calling him
``Manuel Barney,'' a play on the stuffed purple dinosaur toy.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts too find Bartlett's embrace of democracy surprising,
given his strong-man image.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he thought he'd get the 'dedazo,' he'd never be in favor of
democracy now,'' said Luis Miguel Rionda, a political scientist at
Mexico's University of Guanajuato.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Licona Ygaldi, director of Market Research, a polling
firm in Mexico City, said that Bartlett's chances at the nomination
are very good if hard-core PRI activists are allowed to vote
without interference by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The militants want Bartlett because he would protect them.
He's a true PRIista(CQ). He's totally different than the
technocrats,'' said Licona. ``His message is he's strong, firm,
capable of governing. And he's confronted the president by
criticizing his neo-liberal policies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He also inspires fear,'' Licona added. ``Some people think,
'He'll get rid of crime, but he might get rid of me, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Free-market changes pushed by Zedillo and other technocrats --
including the sale of state-owned industries and reduced tariffs on
imports -- have left some PRI members disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   Many blame the policies for deepening poverty and driving people
away from the PRI, which no longer controls the Congress nor all
state governorships.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's populist rhetoric is aimed at the disaffected, who
long to revive a paternalistic system that exchanges votes for the
PRI with special treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of Mexico has to make social needs a top
priority,'' said Bartlett. ``We can't maintain social peace in the
country if we don't make sure the country is employed and that
poverty doesn't get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett believes the PRI must attend to the poor, and he isn't
shy about claiming personal responsibility for providing basic
services like water and sewage systems to his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   He has softened his opposition to free trade, noting that during
his term as governor Puebla's giant Volkswagen plant expanded,
producing more automobiles for export and attracting more foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean that we don't think globalization has its
serious problems, not just for Mexico but for the world,'' Bartlett
said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, who inherited his last name from an English
grandfather, has a long history in public life in Mexico. Even
those who would never vote for him regard him as intelligent,
quick-witted and an able administrator.
</P>
<P>
   The fit 61-year-old bears a striking resemblance to CNN's
popular talk show host Larry King. He's held several powerful jobs,
including secretary of public education and secretary of the
interior.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the latter post that Bartlett, in charge of the
nation's elections, was widely denounced as the mastermind of
alleged fraud during the 1988 presidential race -- which put the
PRI's Carlos Salinas de Gortari into office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That claim is absurd,'' Bartlett said, arguing that several
investigations have absolved him.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett is equally upset by persistent allegations that have
cast him in an evil light in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   An informant told United States authorities that Bartlett was
present at a torture session of Enrique ``Kiki'' Camarena, a U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration agent who was murdered in Mexico in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Camarena case is another false statement that's used to
attack me politically,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was forced to hire a law firm in the United States to
represent him and has provided evidence showing that the
informant's story was fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. authorities requested that Bartlett testify before a grand
jury in the United States, but he declined to appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not submit to any grand jury or any justice system of
another country,'' he said, ``because I have not been (formally)
accused of anything. I am the victim, and it's the responsibility
of the United States government to clarify this. I've done my
part.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
