<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, March 12, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING (El Portal, Calif.) _ When the toughest question came,
Jens Sund couldn't answer. He caught his breath, placed his hand on
his friend's leg, signaling for him to respond. Does the family
believe his wife, daughter and their Argentinian friend were still
alive? ``They still have hope they will be found well and alive,''
answered the friend. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-VERDICT (San Francisco) _ An HIV-positive man who sued a
surgeon after being denied treatment for a debilitating shoulder
condition was awarded $166,000. In a 10-2 decision, the San
Francisco Superior Court jury found that Dr. Franklin Hoaglund, a
now retired orthopedic surgeon, committed malpractice when he
declined to perform shoulder-replacement surgery nearly two years
ago. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKOUT-DISCIPLINE (San Francisco) _ PG&AMP;E is moving to
discipline employees responsible for the Dec. 8 blackout that left
San Francisco and the Peninsula powerless for up to six hours.
Utility spokesman Len Anderson confirmed that the disciplinary
process had begun but he declined to specify how many workers were
affected or whether any had been fired. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOW-MILESTONE (Undated) _ With trillions of dollars at stake,
Wall Street pros and investors are trying to divine how high the
amazing Dow will fly. One raging bull of Wall Street _ Ralph
Acampora, director of technical research at Prudential Securities _
thinks the Dow will reach 11,500 by the third quarter. By EDWARD
IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-SBC (San Antonio) _ Telephone giant SBC Communications Inc.
will offer high-speed Internet access over its phone lines to AOL
customers in its Southwestern Bell, Pacific Bell and Nevada Bell
service areas using a technology called asynchronous digital
subscriber line, or DSL, company officials said. By SANFORD NOWLIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Memory hogs have to be tempted by
the falling prices for removable storage. But before buying,
consider the very different ways these devices operate. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ Where and how does one check to
make sure one has the latest drivers? By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HOTLIST (Undated) _ Radio on the Internet. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ONLINE (Undated) _ There's a site that tries to be all
things to all surfers. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ If some lawmakers get their way, the
federal government will turn over much of the enforcement of the
nation's workplace health and safety laws to private consultants.
By L.M. SIXEL
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SCOLDS (San Francisco) _ Perhaps you've heard of
commercial aviation's new no-guff policy. After too many cases of
passengers taking a swing at the flight attendant or exposing
themselves at 40,000 feet or trying to stuff moose antlers into the
overhead bins, the airlines are getting tough. Exactly how tough
was demonstrated to me when my wife and I flew from San Francisco
to Denver. We were briskly scolded all through the flight. By AL
MCKEE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CORRUPTOR (Undated) _ Kiss-kiss, bang-bang gets a
workout in ``The Corruptor,'' a convoluted shoot-'em-up in which
everyone fires piles of weapons but only the bad guys die. On the
other hand, everyone's a bad guy. The end sum is skillful but
standard filmmaking, slick, gimmicky and powered by numbing action.
By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-CLEOPATRA (Undated) _ The Discovery Channel doesn't
mess around when it has an exclusive. Discovery has Cleopatra _ at
least her old haunts _ and the network is going to show the goods
to 142 countries in 23 languages simultaneously. That's a loud
shout. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-WING (Undated) _ While it may be true that in space
no one can hear you scream, groaning should be a perfectly audible
way of saying the intergalactic alien-buster ``Wing Commander'' is
terrible. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-OCEAN (Undated) _ Adapted from Jacquelyn Mitchard's
novel about the miraculous reappearance of a boy who wandered away
from his brother and mother one hectic afternoon, ``The Deep End of
the Ocean'' is a vexing simplification of an extremely ornate
ethical and moral situation. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LOCK (Undated) _ I doubt that next March, the
creators of ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' will be
standing on the podium at Dorothy Chandler Pavilion. Flawed but
scrappy, confusing yet exhilarating, the Brit-made film is far from
a perfect movie. And it's not for anyone squeamish about violence.
By JANE GANAHL.
</P>
<P>
   CINERAMA (Dayton, Ohio) _ At first glance, and second, New Neon
Movies would hardly seem to be the site for the first screenings of
Cinerama in the United States in more than 30 years. Yet, yet here
is the revolutionary motion picture process in all its three
projector, curved screen and stereophonic glory. By MARK SOMMER.
(For release Sunday, March 14.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS-POLLUTION (San Francisco) _ The 6,000 cubic yards of
dirt shipped to the landfill and the 12,000 cubic yards that remain
at the the Giants' new ballpark in China Basin have been found to
contain lead at levels that could contaminate groundwater. By JANE
KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-ARKANSAS-COACH (Denver) _ A federal court ruling nullifying
NCAA rules that require a minimum score on the SAT for incoming
athletes was good news for Arkansas Razorbacks coach Nolan
Richarchson. ``My old heart started pumping,'' Richardson says, his
voice taking on an evangelical flavor. ``I'm walking around on
Cloud Nine, and I haven't played a game yet.'' By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Half the crowd across from SS
Peter and Paul's Church were reporters or cameramen interviewing
the other half of the crowd. Yet for one day we were living in the
1940s, not the culture of celebrity, and even those with press
cards joined in applause with DiMaggio's friends as the hearse
drove away from North Beach. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The case of Jermaine Henderson, a
college basketball star who was arrested at a pub and ended up at
the police station more banged up than when he left the bar, has
been a classic study in incompetence, venality, petty political
bickering and sheer, unadulterated stupidity. It's time for
somebody to do something sensible. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-NAZIS (San Francisco) _ Couch potatoes kind of like it
when a fitness advocate comes to an untimely end _ it gives them an
argument to use against those who preach at them to start jogging
and renounce hamburgers, smoking and beer. They aren't totally
wrong. These days, almost everyone knows of an athlete who never
smoked, ate a vegetarian diet, spent hours biking or running,
looked great and now is dying of cancer. By EVE PELL.
</P>
