<HEADER>
A7871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-RATES-$ADV0314-     03-12 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-RATES-$ADV0314-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROMISE OF LOWER CABLE BILLS PROVES ELUSIVE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories for use
Sunday, March 14 or thereafter
 &HT;    with COX-CABLE-BOX-$ADV0314 (moved earlier) and
COX-CABLE-DATA-$ADV0314
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Paul Edwards, a retired Marine and business
executive, has time these days to peruse things such as the fine
print on his monthly cable bill.
</P>
<P>
   It's not pleasant reading.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin, Texas, resident estimates that over the last two
years his cable rates have soared 21 percent and his channel-box
rental has increased 16 percent. What's more, he pays local fees
and franchise charges _ plus 8.25 percent sales tax on top of the
total.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gets my blood pressure up,'' says Edwards, who
complains every year to his cable provider, Time Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   Today, his bill is $49.52 a month. And he doesn't see it going
down.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of cable customers nationwide, Edwards feels the
pinch of telecommunications deregulation without the promised
benefits. Washington lawmakers and regulators had assumed cable
companies would face competition in local markets by now, naturally
forcing rates downward. But that hasn't happened. Instead, prices
have soared.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, federal government oversight of nearly all cable
pricing will expire March 31. That means cable companies will be
free to hike prices for the most popular level of service without
fear of government intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Federal Communications Commission has the power to
investigate consumer complaints and order cable companies to rebate
what it considers outrageous charges on the most popular services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of the business of cable-rate regulation at the end
of the month,'' says Morgan Broman, the FCC's Cable Services Bureau
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for Edwards' plea to control price hikes,
according to Consumers Union, a national advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Since passage of the Telecommunications Act in 1996, overall
cable rates have risen about 21 percent, or nearly four times the
rate of inflation, according to the group's February study. Average
rates on expanded basic service, the most popular category, have
gone from $23.07 a month in 1995 to $27.43 a month in 1998,
according to Paul Kagan Associates Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Under the March 31 change, basic service will continue to be
policed by local governments. Expanded basic service _ which
usually includes news, sports and entertainment channels-- will
unregulated. Premium service, such as pay-for-view shows, has never
been regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years are a good indication of what we're going
to see,'' says Gene Kimmelman, co-director of Consumer Union's
Washington office. ``The only way to hold prices down is to slap a
lid on them.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming months, advocates don't expect sudden price spikes.
Instead they anticipate cable operators will continue to raise
expanded and premium plans by as much as 5 percent a year. Basic
rates likely will remain stagnant at between $8 and $12 per month
because they remain regulated.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the FCC has policed basic and expanded rates by
investigating consumer complaints. Since 1993, for example, the FCC
has looked into thousands of complaints nationwide, and has ordered
rebates of as much as $100 million to consumers .
</P>
<P>
   Consumers would have paid between $3 billion and $5 billion more
in cable fees since 1992, if the federal government had not had
watchdog authority, according to some telecom analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Cable industry executives say they are forced to charge
consumers higher prices because they are offering more services and
channels. In addition, industry leaders such as Time Warner, Media
One and Cox Communications are investing billions of dollars in
two-way interactive cable networks to provide high-speed Internet
access and interactive digital television.
</P>
<P>
   In this advanced data services market, cable operators are
competing head-to-head with other telecom giants such as AT&AMP;T,
which bought Tele-Communications Inc. for its cable lines and its
interest in the (at)Home Network.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, for example, Time Warner has spent $50 million in the
last five years to upgrade its two-way interactive network. Later
this year, the company will roll out its Road Runner Internet and
digital television service.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carey, president of Time Warner's Austin, Texas, division,
says his company doesn't plan to jack up unregulated prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to appear irresponsible, or we will invite
unwanted regulation,'' Carey says. ``And we especially don't want
to irritate customers, or we will lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable lobbyists stress that their industry is much more
competitive today than five years ago. So consumers have choices if
they are not satisfied with their cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable companies know that if they don't deliver a strong
value, customers will sign on with one of their competitors,'' says
Scott Broyles, spokesman for the National Cable Television
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 13 million customers nationwide now have satellite
television service, for example. In 1998, though, two of every
three new subscribers chose satellite service, he says.
</P>
<P>
   An FCC analysis, however, shows that most cable markets
nationwide remain monopolies. What's more, in roughly 200 small
communities nationwide with competition, prices are roughly 10
percent lower than in other markets with no competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are urging the cable companies to act responsibly,'' says
Deborah Lathen, chief of the FCC's Cable Services Bureau. ``But we
can not regulate the industry further unless Congress gives us the
authority to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not likely to happen. On Capitol Hill, lawmakers have
been reluctant to jump back into the regulation of telecom sectors
that they are turning over to free markets. Instead, Sen. John
McCain (R-Az.), chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, intends
to unveil legislation this year aimed at easing burdens on cable
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to move to re-regulation unless we absolutely
have to,'' says Lauren Belvin, the committee's majority senior
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But for residents such as Bill Long, another Austin, Texas,
resident, that strategy is not likely to impact his cable bill.
</P>
<P>
   Long, a self-employed Internet consultant, has considered
cutting cable service. But his wife, Josie, uses educational
programming to school the couple's three teenagers at home. So the
Longs pay about $40 a month for cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at cutting our household expenses, this comes
up,'' Long says. ``It's frustrating. This is one bill that won't go
down.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
