<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-REED-0313-COX     03-12 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-REED-0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE REPORTS, REED ELSEVIER DECLINES TO SPECULATE ON NEW CEO
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A prime candidate has surfaced in the six-month search
for a new chief executive for Reed Elsevier, the European-based
parent company of Lexis-Nexis, a London newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Newcomb, the chairman and chief executive of U.S.
publishing giant Simon &AMP; Schuster, is reportedly in discussions
with the company to assume the position, according to the The
Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   The London office of Reed Elsevier declined to respond to
questions about the search for a chief executive, and said in a
statement only that the search was ``at an advanced stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the position was fueled by the company's
report Wednesday that net profits fell 5 percent last year to $918
million dollars, along with a warning that a flat performance can
be expected this year. The results are consistent with a forecast
published in December.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have not regarded the absence of a new chief executive
as fundamentally harming the media giant's performance to date, but
concern is expected to increase if the position isn't filled within
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The search has taken longer than expected because of the
difficulties of defining the job for the first time, the newspaper
said. The search began last August when the company decided to
discard its two-headed chief executive structure in favor of a
single CEO. Neither of the two chairmen, Herman Bruggink of
Dutch-based Elsevier or Nigel Stapleton of the British-based Reed
are candidates for the job.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview with journalists, Stapleton said he
recognized that there has been some ``disappointment'' in the
market that no announcement has been made today on the appointment
of a new chief executive for Reed Elsevier.
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton said the search process is now ``extremely focused''
but declined to say if a final short list has been drawn up or when
an announcement can be expected. ``We have a perfectly tenable
interim structure working very effectively,'' he said. ``We are not
in a situation faced by other companies where we've been left in a
void when a chief executive leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From a Reed Elsevier perspective we haven't raised any
expectations that there will be an announcement of a new CEO at
this stage,'' he said. ``The whole process is at an advanced stage
and we are expecting good results from the chief executive
search.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement issued with the profits report, the
co-chairmen said the conditions causing reduced profits are likely
to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our development program and the unfavorable economic situation
on some markets, does not suggest that profits will grow
significantly in 1999,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed-Elsevier is one of the biggest publishing groups in the
world, employing 27,000 people. Its main markets are in Europe and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have cited four key factors bearing on the company's
performance:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Competition in the legal division intensified in the second
half of the year, especially in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Advertising markets in Britain deteriorated in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reed Elsevier invested heavily in electronic products,
particularly those on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Profits also were hurt by the acquisition of Matthew Bender to
complement Lexis Nexis, an investment not expected to generate much
in the way of short term sales.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the trade publication Extel Examiner,
Bruggink said he expects a tough battle in 1999 between Lexis-Nexis
and Thomson Corp.'s Westlaw in the U.S. online legal publishing
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be equally strong pressure (in the U.S. legal
market) in 1999 as in 1998,'' he said. ``Competition will be
fierce.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
