<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRTH-SISTERS-NYTSF-M     03-12 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTH-SISTERS-NYTSF-MED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'BIRTH SISTERS' MAY HELP WOMEN DELIVER WITH LESS PAIN  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 BY SUZANNE LEIGH  
 c.1999 Medical Tribune News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When ``Shirley'' was 16, she delivered her son after a long,
savagely painful labor, concluding in a caesarean section. Haunted
by memories of a labor punctuated by an arsenal of surgical
devices, Shirley's anxiety manifested itself as post-traumatic
stress disorder. Thirteen years later Shirley is working as an
office manager for a Boston computer company and married. She is
also _ to her horror and delight _ pregnant with her second child.
But this time Shirley wants to feel in control of her own labor.
</P>
<P>
   Expectant mothers like Shirley are candidates for a program at
Boston Medical Center that recognizes that women who do not feel in
control of their labor are more prone to anxiety and a high level
of pain, and are also more likely to require intervention such as
forceps and C-section.
</P>
<P>
   More radically, perhaps, the program also recognizes that a
woman's husband or partner is not always the best source of support
during labor and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The program involves pairing an expectant mother with a ``birth
sister,'' a woman who provides advice and support during labor and
in the first few months after delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Birth sisters are more commonly known as doulas, a Greek word
sometimes translated as ``servant'' or ``slave.'' It's a name the
center prefers not to use.
</P>
<P>
   The program was started last fall thanks in part to a grant from
the March of Dimes, the voluntary health agency aimed at improving
the health of babies, which is based in White Plains, N.Y. So far,
the program has recruited 57 women to become birth sisters after
completing a 50-hour training course covering the basics in labor,
delivery, relaxation techniques and breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Walker is a nurse-midwife at the center whose job
includes referring women to the program. Birth sisters, she says,
are a godsend in an era when the realities of healthcare mean that
midwives can no longer provide ongoing care to women in labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a woman in labor is very anxious, her uterus stops
contracting and the birth becomes more painful. Having someone
there to assure her she is doing well and the pain will subside has
been shown to reduce the odds of C-section and forceps delivery as
well as decrease the need for oxytocin [a drug given to make the
uterus contract more forcefully] and epidural [anesthesia to block
pain],'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a less stressful, less painful birth experience is not
only advantageous to the new mother, according to Walker, it also
provides lasting benefits to the infant.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mothers are more likely to bond with their babies and
have less problems breast-feeding. Breast-fed babies receive
protection against anything from diarrhea to middle-ear
infections,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is not opposed to a woman's husband or partner being in
the delivery room but believes that a birth sister can provide
unique assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about providing empathetic support. Traditionally women
have always supported women during labor and delivery. There comes
a time during the procedure when the father takes a step back, and
this is usually when the birth sister jumps in and plays a primary
role in taking care of the mother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker hopes that HMOs will recognize the financial benefits of
birth sisters and cover their costs. The Boston Medical Center's
program costs about $400 per pregnancy and covers two pre-labor
consultations and about eight hours of post-partum care.
</P>
<P>
   Studies reinforce Walker's assertion that women whose labors are
assisted by a doula, or birth sister, are likely to have better
birth experiences. This is especially the case with younger,
socially disadvantaged women, where a number of studies have
demonstrated a significant drop in the incidence of C-section,
forceps delivery and use of oxytocin, painkillers and anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: THE STORY MAY END HERE, OR YOU MAY INCLUDE THE
FOLLOWING OPTIONAL MATERIAL)
</P>
<P>
   Older, better-educated women also reap the rewards of having
doula-assisted labors, but the differences may not be so striking.
</P>
<P>
   In a study published in the current issue of Obstetrics &AMP;
Gynecology, the effects of hospital-based doulas were evaluated
among 478 pregnant patients in a private hospital. The mean age of
the mothers was 29 and more than half were college graduates.
Approximately one-half of the women were assigned to a
doula-assisted program and the remainder received standard care
with their labor and deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Lead researcher Nancy P. Gordon from the Kaiser Permanente
Medical Center in Oakland, Calif., and colleagues found that 54
percent of the mothers who had had doula-assisted labors had
received an epidural. Among women who did not have a doula, the
rate was 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers asked the new mothers how they rated their
birth experience, 82 percent of those with doula-assisted labors
said it was good, compared with 67 percent with non-doula-assisted
labors. No significant differences were found between the two
groups' incidence of C-section, forceps delivery, use of oxytocin,
breast-feeding and post-partum depression.
</P>
<P>
   But less notable advantages should not mean that doulas should
be reserved for socially disadvantaged women, according to Dr. Alan
S. Cadesky, a family physician at the department of family medicine
at Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Cadesky is an advocate of doulas, as well as being the husband
of one. His youngest child was born with the two older siblings
present together with a doula who supported them during their
mother's labor.
</P>
<P>
   Cadesky said he recommends doulas in all cases. ``There are no
side-effects with having doulas present,'' he said, adding that
they bring ``a positive energy'' to the delivery room, which
facilitates labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doulas are not there to supplant the role of anyone else or to
lobby for medication. They are there to support the couple and that
can only be a good thing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
