A7900 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-PLANT-PA     03-12 0332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-PLANT-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        HOMEGROWN INVENTION GETS SMITHSONIAN SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 11 -- Plants may no longer have to pay the
ultimate price for their owners' vacations.
</P>
<P>
   A group of five Drexel University engineering students have
invented an automatic watering system designed to keep house plants
alive while their owners are away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible feeling to come back from vacation to find a
house full of dead plants,'' said Paula Bielski, 22, of Delaware
County. ``This invention is good for vacationers or people who are
just busy.''
</P>
<P>
   At a one-day exhibit yesterday at the Smithsonian American
History Museum's Lemelson Center, student inventors from around the
country showed off their work.
</P>
<P>
   Bielski and her colleagues, Duc Nguyen, Phillip Nguyen, Vadim
Pavolotsky and Ilya Rakhman, worked for six months to design and
build the system.
</P>
<P>
   Their invention senses the soil moisture levels in each plant
and decides when to add water. It can water up to five plants for
two weeks. The device has a six-and-a-half gallon refillable tank
and can be used in any home or office.
</P>
<P>
   Systems now on the market are mostly geared toward greenhouses,
not homes, Bielski said. Also, the systems currently available give
the same amount of water to all plants, even though different
plants have different moisture needs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The students want to market their product in the future. It cost
$500 for the students to make the system, but they hope to get the
price down, so customers would only have to pay $200, Bielski said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit was part of the National Collegiate Inventors and
Innovators Alliance's third annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   Other Pennsylvania student inventions included a machine that
simulated wear and tear on ankle joint replacement parts and an
electronic measuring and transmitting device for monitoring
hospital patients' vital signs, both from the University of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
