<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-OYSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE CULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has been just over a decade since the Blue Oyster
Cult _ the original thinking person's heavy metal band _ has
released an album of new material or played on a Boston area stage.
Has the band been hibernating?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, says singer-guitarist-songwriter Eric Bloom, who
shares the Cult spotlight with Don ``Buck Dharma'' Roeser. They've
been on the road _ playing state fairs, biker fests, and clubs _
and they just got back, Bloom says, from a three-week
midwest-northwest tour played to soldout clubs. Their abscence in
Boston, Bloom says, has had to do with no appropriate place to play
since the Channel shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Oyster Cult rectifies that situation next Thursday when
they play the Middle East Downstairs. And they finally have an
album out, ``Heaven Forbid,'' which Bloom says, ``has done well in
Europe.'' What it signifies, he adds, is ``that we're not just an
oldies band. On top of that, it's a really good record.'' On the
album, they collaborate with cyber-horror writer John Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one of Bloom's fond memories of the tour: ``We're playing
a show in California and I go out to leave after the show and
there's a couple of guys there, 17, 18-years-old with green and
orange hair _ and that's not your typical Blue Oyster Cult fan.
They go, `Hey, man, Blue Oyster Cult, you're so cool. We're so
proud of ourselves. We got thrown out for moshing.' And I said, `We
need more guys with green and oragne hair at our shows who are
thrilled to meet us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Point being, in this day and age, rock 'n' roll tends to be
age-specific. And the guys in Blue Oyster Cult _ keyboardist Allen
Lanier is the remaining co-founder, bassist Danny Miranda and
drummer Bobby Rondinelli the new guys _ tend to attract fans in
their own post-40s age group. Which is fine. But if, say, Metallica
fans are paying attention, they may want to come to the gig, too.
Metallica released the covers-only double-CD ``Garage, Inc.'' last
year, a tribute to their influences, and did a faithful version of
BOC's ``Astronony.'' Mike Watt, ex-of the Minutemen and fIREHOSE,
now on his own, has long covered BOC's ``The Red and the Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades ago, Blue Oyster Cult formed in Long Island
as Soft White Underbelly, an unlikely hybrid formed by five members
of frat and garage rock bands. During the early-mid 1970s, they
made their bones: With irony and wit, with moody guitar phrases and
blistering metal attacks, with turn-on-a-dime tempo changes, they
took heavy metal into another realm. They wrote melodic rockers,
about bikers (``Transmaniacon MC''), warfare (``ME 262''),
fetishism (``She's As Beautiful As A Foot'') about dominance and
submission (uh, ``Dominance &AMP; Submission'') and the star-making
machinery (``Stairway to the Stars'').
</P>
<P>
   Overdue commercial success came calling in 1976 with the
Byrds-like ``(Don't Fear) The Reaper.'' Then, BOC scored with FM
radio favorites such as ``Godzilla,'' ``Burnin' For You'' and
``Joan Crawford.'' Bloom and Roeser had contrasting writing styles.
``I like crunchy heavier stuff,'' says Bloom, ``and Buck writes
more melodic stuff. What you get is an interesting chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   In their heyday _ 1976 to 1981 _ they played arenas and carried
around three semi-trucks worth of equipment and a 27-member crew.
They played with KISS and Aerosmith; they co-headlined a ``Black
and Blue'' tour with Black Sabbath. ``We were incredibly lucky,''
says Bloom. ``It seemed like a normal progression at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Their star began to wane in the mid-1989s. ``Well, eventually,
gravity set it,'' says Bloom. A case could be made that when
writer-drummer Albert Bouchard left/was sacked (1981) and his
brother bassist Joe left (1985) the songwriting took a step back.
Bloom doesn't care for that notion.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Blue Oyster Cult lives, and this is a good thing.
They can draw from a catalog of songs that can produce an A-level
set. On Thursday, they'll play a couple from the new album and the
cream of the rest of the crop. It's pretty heavy cream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
