<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT A JOYSTICK, `COMMANDER' DOESN'T FLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WING COMMANDER 
Directed by: Chris Roberts 
Written by: Chris Roberts and Kevin Droney 
Starring: Freddie Prinze Jr., Matthew Lillard, Saffron Burrows,
Ginny Holder, Jurgen Prochnow, Tchecky Karyoall 
At: Copley Place, suburbs
<TEXT>
<P>
   Running time: 100 minutes &QL; 
Rated: PG-13 (mild violence) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Video games should not be made into feature-length films.
</P>
<P>
   Video games aren't about watching, they're about doing. Gamers,
you see, derive their pleasure from having their finger on the
trigger and picking off the baddies themselves. The joy is in the
joystick. But Hollywood doesn't understand this, even though the
failures of such dismal fare as ``Super Mario Bros.'' and ``Mortal
Combat'' should have made this abundantly clear to all future
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Such lessons apparently weren't absorbed by the makers of ``Wing
Commander,'' a tired trifle of a movie based on the popular
computer game of the same name. So cheesy it could be served on
crackers, ``Wing Commander'' takes place in a future where
Earthlings are at war with alien ``pilgrims,'' and decent actors
are in very short-supply. Freddie Prinze Jr. brings what's quickly
becoming his trademark blandness to his character, Chris Blair, a
hotshot good guy fighter pilot. Chris is supposed to be half-human,
half-pilgrim, and is therefore considered somewhat suspect by some
of his compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   While Chris is pretty enough to be a pin-up, his only trace
alien genes are some sort of grand navigational skills. At least
that's what he's told by his tough-guy superior Taggert (Tchecky
Karyo). So Chris is a handy guy to have around. Less necessary is
his best pal, the aptly named Maniac (Matthew Lillard), who likes
nothing more than executing risky manuevers in his spaceship and
endangering the lives everyone around him.
</P>
<P>
   There's the typical ragtag gang of hard-drinking, well-armed men
and women, all pretty indistinguishable expect for the
blonde-haired Rosie (Ginny Holder) who looks like model Alek Wek,
and flies a plane like Chuck Yaeger. Overseeing this lot is
Devereaux (Saffron Burrows), who for reasons never made clear
constantly refers to her crew as ``ladies.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the battle scenes are rarely more than mildly distracting.
It's mostly air combat with big explosions and such, and that's
gets old fast. ``Wing Commander'' is the kind of piffle where
sparks fly, fires flare, people run a lot and yell things like
``Brace for impact!'' and ``We've locked onto one of the
destroyers, sir!'' It's a movie filled with exclamation-point
dialogue, although there's really very little point to anything on
screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LEWIS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     03-12 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... missles fly.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If he fights properly, with good balance and a hard jab, he'll
win. He's one of the most dangerous men in the world if he doesn't
get off his mental pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if he does? Or what if hesitation and timidity are, by
nature, his true ``mental pattern,'' as his staunchest critics
believe?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't use a solid, authoritative jab then it won't
matter,'' Steward admitted. ``That's what gives this fight so much
mystique. I think he's ready to shine but even I don't know which
Lennox will show up.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a dangerous way to be going into the most important
fight of your life, especially when the guy waiting for you is most
assuredly 215 pounds of fire and ferocity. Yet Lewis has seemed
calm all week. He has never once trained in front of the public, as
Holyfield willingly has done, but other than that he has been
steadfast in his position that he is too big and too strong for
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking for this fight for a long time,'' Lewis
said. ``This is an opportunity to actually show the reason why all
the other boxers have been ducking me. Now I'm going to get the
opportunity to go out and try to prove all the people wrong. I know
this is a fight where I need to go out and assert myself. I realize
how important a fight it is for me. This kind of fight has been
eluding me for a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield knows I am a true threat to him. I'm the one who is
going to take away all the glory he's built up with all those other
big fights. People have asked why I think he's saying bad things
about me. Well, I don't believe he should have a good feeling about
me. We both fought Ray Mercer and Mercer is picking me. He should
know. He's a true warrior who looked at our fight as a war. I think
Evander will look at it the same way, maybe to his detriment.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so because there is no question that Lewis's right hand is
as dangerous as any tool in boxing. When it lands it does damage.
When it lands flush, it closes the show. Holyfield certainly
understands this yet continues to predict a third-round knockout,
saying ``sometimes a guy's best weapon can become his downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   What Holyfield is suggesting is that his superior hand speed
will allow him to counter Lewis's right, as McCall did the night he
knocked Lewis out, and his superior boxing ability, which is not in
dispute, will create such an opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox always said I was ducking him,'' Holyfield said
confidently this week. ``But this fight is real now. It's here and
he's got to face it. Now's his chance to prove he's the great man
he's supposed to be. He brought all this upon himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Those do not sound like the words of someone terribly fearful of
what Lewis has to offer and few would expect Holyfield would be
fearful knowing his nature. But to Lewis there is a lack of respect
in those words that he finds irksome, a respect he says he intends
to win by fighting the way he _ and few others _ believe he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize the magnitude of this but I won't have time to think
of 20,000 people in Madison Square Garden,'' Lewis said. ``When I
step in that 20-by-20-foot ring, I won't be looking out of it until
the end comes. I am going to go in that ring with one belt and come
out with three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield is a great warrior. He will bring out things
in me the public hasn't seen yet. This is the defining fight for
Lennox Lewis. People's problem with me is they haven't seen me
against someone they thought was a great boxer. Those fights seemed
to elude me until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every time I went to train for this fight I would look at
a film of Holyfield first, to get into the mind-set to fight. He's
got a big heart. He won't go in and be easy to knock out, but on
the night I know I'm going to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, Lewis will become the most powerful economic force
in boxing, an undisputed heavyweight champion. But he insists this
fight is not about the money he will make, even though it is
considerable. Rather it is about what he first fought for as a boy
seeking to win trophies to put in his sparsely furnished room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make a lot of money for this fight ($9 million to
Holyfield's $20 million) but I don't think about the money,'' Lewis
said. ``I fight for the glory. This is a stage for me. There's
nowhere to run, nowhere to hide, no one to depend on. It's
dangerous. That's the thing I like about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis will face danger like he has never known before in this
fight. He will risk everything he has won in boxing against the
most dangerous man he has ever faced. He will fight to unify the
heavyweight title but he will be fighting for much more than that,
much more than even Holyfield has on the line.
</P>
<P>
   He will, as he said, fight for glory and fight to clear his name
at last. That's an awful lot for one man to have to fight over but
he has been preparing for this moment for 21 years, preparing for
it since the first time he threw his hands at a kid who made fun of
him on a schoolyard in Kitchener.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he won't be that far from those days when he walks
down the aisle at Madison Square Garden and enters an arena full of
skeptics for he knows this night, at last, he will get to prove who
he is . . . for better or for worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
