<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE WOMEN'S TEAMS BEAT THE MEN EVERY TIME: GRADUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   P.J. O'Rourke and John Hughes wrote, ``After equality, wage
parity, liberation of body and soul, and the extension for the
ratification of the ERA, women still can't do the following: start
barbecue fires; hook up a stereo; shine shoes; anything on a roof;
decide where to hang a picture; investigate mysterious house noises
at night; kill and dispose of large insects or walk past a mirror
without stopping to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Women, girls, this is the time to throw O'Rourke back at the
men. It's March Madness. These are the three weeks when men
sacrifice marriage, mortgage, and metabolism the moment their alma
mater or their team in the office pool hits the TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   These are the weeks where guys are inmates in a primordal
asylum, speaking in gutteral tongues that, if done at the airport
x-ray machine, would have federal agents whisking you away in
handcuffs and straitjacket: ``Yes!!! Awww!!! Baby!!! Ohmigod!!!
(expletive deleted) Shoot you idiot!!! (Burp) Don't shoot, you
idiot!!! You blind ref!!! Great move!!! (expletive deleted)
Unbelievable!!! Incredible!!! What an upset!!! (Burp) Oh, nooo!!!
How stupid can you be!!! (expletive deleted) How could you choke on
that free throw??! Fire the coach!!! (Burp)
</P>
<P>
   Noel Coward said in 1930 that certain women should be struck
regularly like gongs. We don't believe that mess anymore, but in
1999 the only thing certain men would understand is a rhetorical
bong to the cheek. So, women, during the next three weeks, stride
smoothly into the room, right when beer and corn chips fly into the
air because Jamal the Helicopter Sikorsky has dunked for the upset
at the buzzer. Calmly block the TV as high fives and chest thumping
reach a thunder known only by Zeus and King Kong. Then say:
</P>
<P>
   ``After inequality in fame, millions of dollars to the colleges,
the liberation of body and soul, and the extension of
basket-weaving courses, men still can't do the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``Think.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after O'Rourke and Hughes's observations, women now
play as many college basketball games, practice just as long, and
are recruited almost as hard as men for scholarships. By and large,
they are still student athletes. In fact, with the women in mind,
it is criminal that the National Collegiate Basketball Association
even allows a men's Division 1 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 64 women's teams, 47 have graduation rates of 60 percent
and above. Of the 64 men's teams, only 15 have a rate of 60 percent
or more. Only eight women's teams have graduation rates under 50
percent, but 41 men's teams are under 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Graduation rates reflect how many scholarship athletes get their
degree in six years. The mass disregard for academics on men's
teams is evident among the top 16 seeded teams. The graduation rate
for the top 16 is 44 percent, one point over the national average.
But that is skewed by the handful of teams that actually graduate
players.
</P>
<P>
   Look what happens by removing just five of the 16 top seeds,
Duke (83 percent graduation rate), Stanford (100), St. John's (85),
North Carolina (77) and Michigan State (67). The graduation rate
for the other 11 teams plummets to 27 percent with African-American
graduation rates of 21 percent. The worst is Cincinnati, which
graduates no one.
</P>
<P>
   The top 16 women's seeds have a graduation rate of 60 percent.
That is skewed by a handful of teams that fail to graduate players.
Take out the five lowest teams and the average goes to 69 percent,
3 points above the national women's team average and 10 percentage
points above the national graduate rate for all women at Division 1
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Take out the five lowest teams in the top 16 for graduation
rates of African-American players and the rate soars from 55
percent to 65 percent, 22 percentage points above the national
graduation rate for all African-American women.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams once wrote that hysteria is a natural
phenomenon, the common denominator of the female nature. Well,
ahem, other than the Super Bowl, there is no greater example of how
men turn living rooms into an asylum (burp). Women, there is no
better time to slamdunk humility back into the male species.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the announcers faze you when they gush about 4.0
players. Don't let them sucker you with those tired,
saved-from-the-ghetto stories. Block the TV with the truth. We are
men screaming like idiots, cheering on dummies. Many of us proudly
wear the colors of schools that no longer even bother with the
pretense of basket weaving.
</P>
<P>
   O'Rourke can joke about women not shining shoes. Women have the
last laugh. In their increasing equality and liberation of body and
soul, they have not yet forgotten that a basketball team is a means
to an end.
</P>
<P>
   As for men, we must confront this sobering fact: We have had
decades of unequal advantage, billions of dollars of college and
pro inequity, and the extension of our privilege that keeps the
men's tournament on the networks while the women are consigned to
cable. Many of the men we cheer for during March Madness will be
lucky if all they can do, once their athletic eligibility is over,
is shine a shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Next Week: The Scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
