<HEADLINE>
THE DOW: THE SKY'S THE LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What can you say about a Dow Jones industrial average as it
approaches the 10,000 mark?
</P>
<P>
   That it reflects a nation full of relentlessly optimistic
people. Whether you measure consumer confidence or investor
sentiment, survey after survey turns up the same result: We are
upbeat and we expect the good times to continue. If confidence is
the fuel that powers stocks, then the current market is running on
a full tank.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow crossed the 9900 mark Thursday before falling back in
the afternoon. The market peaked at 9935.46 and closed for the day
at 9897.44. Thursday marked the first time the Dow passed 9800 and
9900.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the 10,000 barrier would represent a psychological
triumph. Big numbers _ Mark McGwire's 70 home runs, Titanic's 11
Oscars _ draw the attention of the public. On Wall Street, crossing
the 10,000 barrier could, in the short run, trigger a sell-off, say
analysts, as some investors use the event as an excuse to take
profits. But on Main Street, the number focuses talk on how good
things are _ and how long they might stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   Just how optimistic are we? When discount broker Quick &AMP; Reilly
did its quarterly poll of customers recently, it found that
investors were as bullish as they have ever been. Of those
interviewed, 62 percent categorized themselves as bulls; only 8
percent listed themselves as bears. In 1993, the bulls outnumbered
the bears by only a narrow margin, 31 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The participants in Fidelity Investment's 401(k) plans are also
feeling chipper these days. Fidelity Thursday said its own survey
of investor confidence showed a rise in optimism since last fall.
Of those surveyed in February, 35 percent said they were planning
to increase the amount they contribute to their retirement
accounts; 61 percent said they would maintain their investment
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps trying to keep expectations in check, Peter Smail,
Fidelity's head of retirement services, pointed out that investors
have enjoyed an unprecedented four straight years of returns of
more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors ``should keep in mind that stocks historically have
returned about 11 percent annually,'' he said. Smail didn't say
investors were driven by ``irrational exuberance,'' Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan's famous phrase, but others have suggested
expectations have gotten out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are also in a good mood. In February Americans were
more positive about their economic situation than at any time since
the Conference Board began its well-known survey in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   That confidence is translating into more spending. The
government Thursday reported that retail sales rose a robust 0.9
percent in February as consumers went shopping for cars, clothing,
and furniture. In response to those numbers, the nation's biggest
car makers Thursday said they were raising their sales forecasts
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Why is everyone so gosh-darn happy? It's the economy, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy has performed brilliantly,'' said Nancy Kimleman,
chief economist at Technical Data in Boston. Unemployment and
inflation are as low as they have been in 30 years. The federal
government is running a budget surplus. Technological progress,
especially the rise of the Internet, has given people a sense that
anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   The good news on the economy has made investors more bullish and
the strong performance of the stock market, in turn, helps the
economy by making consumers more willing to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The optimism feeds on itself and becomes self-reinforcing,''
said Mark Zandi, chief economist at Regional Financial Associates,
a Pennsylvania forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   But what goes up can come down. Virtually all market watchers
say investor sentiment could turn on a dime if some bad news rears
its ugly head. That scenario played itself out in the summer of
1997 when the Asian financial crisis first hit. The percentage of
bulls in Quick &AMP; Reilly's survey fell from 58 percent to 39 percent
in one quarter. Something similar happened last summer when the
Russian economy collapsed, touching off a decline in stock prices
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would take much to puncture sentiment,'' said
Ned Riley, chief investment officer at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   What could that something be? Weak earnings reports from
technology companies could do the trick, say analysts. Other
possibilities include more trouble overseas or a hike in interest
rates by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a Fed tightening could be a stake in the market's
heart,'' said Zandi.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, however, investors see only blue skies ahead.
As long as that is the case it's a good bet the bulls will continue
the assault on the 10,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Street Corp.'s latest proxy statement is expected to show,
among other things, how much it paid chief executive Marshall
Carter last year. Whatever the number is, shareholders are not
likely to complain much. State Street stock Thursday closed at a
record high of 88 1/4, up 3 13/16 for the day. During last
October's market turmoil the stock traded as low as 50. Over the
past three years, State Street's stock price has nearly quadrupled.
Numbers like that make multimillion-dollar paychecks a lot easier
to swallow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
