<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE COLORS OUTPOURING FOR JOLTIN' JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all respect due to a man of phenomenal ability and
achievement, isn't it apparent that much of the public mourning for
Joe DiMaggio is really keening for the bygone era of the white
athlete? I had my ear cocked to the radio on Tuesday and Wednesday,
and I couldn't help hearing racial code words pouring out of the
ether. Caller after caller decried today's greedy, money-grubbing
athlete, who immodestly brags about his or her accomplishments and
publicly taunts opponents, talks trash, etc. Inevitably, callers
and commentators alike contrasted today's unsportsmanlike behavior
with the quiet dignity of DiMaggio, who supposedly never squawked
about contracts (he did), or poor-mouthed his adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. But aren't we really talking about stereotypical
``white'' behavior, contrasted with stereotypical ``black''
behavior? Is it wrong for today's athletes, most of them black, to
want a bigger share of the white billionaire owners' revenues?
(Yes, if the fans' reaction to the recent NBA lockout is any
indicator.) And when fans complain about the extravagant behavior
of the Denver Broncos' touchdown salute, or Reggie Miller and Spike
Lee woofing at courtside, don't we hear the unspoken comment: White
players wouldn't act like this.
</P>
<P>
   Why have several writers already mangled DiMaggio's famous
response to columnist Jimmy Cannon, who asked why Joe hustled so
much? ``Because there's someone out there who's never seen me play
before,'' DiMaggio replied. (It's in Cannon's collected columns;
you can look it up.) But George Will and others have already
changed the quote to ``Because there's some child out there who's
never seen me play before,'' as if DiMaggio was selfessly hustling
for children, and not for himself. Why do we read of DiMaggio's
``fierce pride'' in insisting that he be introduced as ``the
greatest living ballplayer,'' when a similar gambit by, say, Bill
Russell, would have been deemed ``arrogant''?
</P>
<P>
   A necktied Joe DiMaggio hangs out with showgirls at Toots Shor's
and it's classy. A tattooed Dennis Rodman hangs out with Carmen
Electra in Las Vegas and it's vulgar. And what's this about Joe's
``matchless grace'' in ``patrolling'' center field? The year
DiMaggio retired, a black man named Willie Mays came on the scene
and defined defensive center-fielding for all time _ or at least
until Ken Griffey Jr. showed up. Most of DiMaggio's impressive
statistics, including his 1941 hitting streak, came before baseball
admitted black players into the league.
</P>
<P>
   I think what white sports fans really miss in the passing of a
DiMaggio or a Mickey Mantle is the presence of white athletes we
can admire. Mark McGwire? He can hit a home run, and then what? I'm
racking my brains to think of a white basketball player I find
remotely interesting. Football? Football still has a tenuous hold
on fan interest because a healthy percentage of the stars, like
John Elway and Brett Favre, are white.
</P>
<P>
   The world has changed in the three decades since I went to sleep
with Mantle's biography on my bedside table. Like millions of
suburban American children, my own son sleeps underneath a poster
of Michael Jordan. The post-DiMaggio world isn't a worse place. In
fact, it's probably a better place. But it is a different place, as
worthy of celebration as DiMaggio's own glory years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Because they don't take . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine had to buy some American Express gift
certificates for some charity hoo-ha. She was directed to the AmEx
office at 1 Court St., where she learned that . . . they don't take
American Express! Disbelieving, I retraced her steps the other day,
and asked if I could charge some gift certificates to my AmEx card.
I was politely informed that no, a personal or corporate AmEx card
would not do. (Reason: the AmEx card is for charging merchandise,
and the gift certificates would be considered cash advances. But
they would take cash, checks, or . . . Visa.
</P>
<P>
   I'm writing the ad copy right now: ``In Boston, when buying
American Express gift certificates, make sure you have your Visa
card . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
