<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV14-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PAINT OFF CERAMIC TILE SHOULD BE EASY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In a condo I bought, someone painted the wall tile in the
bathroom, yellow, of all things, over perfectly acceptable light
blue tiles. Now I am trying to remove the paint. Is there an easy
way to remove the paint, which is peeling badly? How about putting
new tile over the old? The old tile was installed in mud.
</P>
<P>
   DON YOVICSIN, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no easy way, but chemical paint remover will take
off the paint quite well; and for your purposes, try a less toxic
remover such as Cistristrip. When the stripper softens the paint,
you can scrape most of it off with a putty knife. Apply more
stripper and remove remaining paint by rubbing with fine steel
wool. Wear skin and eye protection when working with stripper, and
provide lots of ventilation. The paint will be difficult to remove
from grout, but you can scrape it off physically. But before you do
all this, take the paint off a few tiles and check for any sanding
marks. Tile should be power sanded before painting, and if you find
any sanding marks, then the tiles are beyond help. Since the paint
is peeling badly, chances are fair that no sanding was done.
</P>
<P>
   If stripping sounds like too much work, you can set new tiles on
the old, using thin-set mortar. The old finish must be power sanded
so the thin-set will stick. When you come to the top of the tile,
the doubled tiles will provide a half-inch shelf. Cover this with
half-inch-wide border tiles or cut regular tile to cover it.
</P>
<P>
   For fixtures such as towel racks, soap holders, and others, you
can butt the new tiles against them and fill the gap with grout
when you grout the rest of the tiles.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way you can remove tiles in a mud job without
tearing out the whole wall and starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Having written all this, it occurs to me that removing the paint
is easier, and if the tiles have not been sanded, the result can be
pretty good for a lot less work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a puzzle. I get animals down my fireplace flue, they
never come into the fireplace and they always leave. But what if
one goes down the furnace flue and gets killed by the fumes, then
blocks the flue? That could be a big hazard. What can I do about
it?
</P>
<P>
   ED BOOTH, Medford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You have a good point, but animals often stay in flues even
with the burner on, and somehow can back away from the gaseous
stream, or get out in time to continue dear old life. But you can
have peace of mind by having stainless steel chimney caps
installed, covering all flues. These caps, generally installed by
chimney sweeps, keep out animals and water. Just make sure the
critters are out when the caps go on. It's funny; there are
thousands of old and new uncapped chimneys, some with flue liners,
some not, that have never had any animals in them. I don't know
why, but those who do not have critters are just lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I.H. of Belmont, Mass. asked if old-fashioned wood storms
were still made and where to get them, the handyman suggested
salvage yards and other dealers in old house things. Such storms
are the type that hang on the outside casing from hooks at the top
of the casing.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what John Miley of Belmont (I hope I got the name right)
wrote: I feel compelled to share some information with you and the
reader from Belmont. Traditional storm screens and windows are
available from: Midwest Architectural Wood Products Ltd., 300
Trails Road, Eldridge, IA 52748, phone: 319-285-8000.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, John Miley, for taking the time to write with some
valuable information. That information is going into the handyman's
vast electronic file, even as we speak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The above was good news for I.H., and the handyman has good news
for ``Looking a Long Time'' in Dorchester, Mass., who asked if
there were any toilet seats available with enlarged openings. The
handyman didn't know, so asked, and here's what he found:
</P>
<P>
   Paul MacInnes, who heads up Standard of Lynn, specialists in
bathrooms and kitchens, wrote: ``Church is coming out later this
year with a seat they call the Jumbo, (no euphemistic approach with
this name). However, it has been designed with larger folks in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not only larger than standard, but has a
larger-than-standard opening. And, MacInnes said, it will fit on a
standard toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It will be introduced in April at the National Kitchen and Bath
Industry Show; after that it should be in plumbing supply shops.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Paul MacInnes. ``Looking a Long Time'' will thank you as
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
