<HEADLINE>
MAIER'S RUN SPOILED BY FELLOW AUSTRIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March Madness on the slopes: All over the world, from Sunday
River, Maine, to Sierra Nevada, Spain, the competitive ski season
is wrapping up this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alpine World Cup finale, the question is how much of the
winners' circle Austria will cede to the two great Norwegian
skiers, Lasse Kjus and Andre Kjetil Aamodt.
</P>
<P>
   In the hills of western Maine, meanwhile, a pitched battle
between east and west NCAA rivals intensified Thursday as the
action swung to cross-country freestyle at Black Mountain in
Rumford.
</P>
<P>
   In World Cup, Austria's Hermann ``The Herminator'' Maier, has
all but conceded his overall World Cup title to Kjus, who cllected
enough points (50) with a fourth place finish in Thursday's Super-G
to hang onto a 102-point lead over Austria's team leader and most
colorful racer, Maier.
</P>
<P>
   The race is not officially over, but with just two technical
races left _ giant slalom and slalom _ Maier has said he will not
race the slalom, and thus can win only 100 points if he wins the
giant slalom.
</P>
<P>
   Since Kjus is a much better technical skier, Maier had clearly
seen the writing on the wall when he said bitterly that he would
not race in the slalom.
</P>
<P>
   Since that would simply hand the overall title to Kjus without a
fight, great unhappiness settled into the camp of the all-world
Dream Team, and conferences were convened, one of them between
Maier and the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Maier had agreed to race in the slalom but
made it clear that his heart is no longer in this season. Even
though his team remains dominant in the standings nearly
everywhere, Maier's image of invincibility _ which even more than
the comparison with his friend Arnold Schwarzenager made ``The
Herminator'' title such a perfect fit _ has worn thin this year.
</P>
<P>
   What really took Maier out of the overall race, which he
captured last season, was some substandard (for Maier) ski racing.
Despite some stong racing this season, which he finished with four
straight Super-G wins and a shared gold medal with Kjus at the
Alpine Worlds in Vail, Maier skied a disappointing seventh
Thursday, and was victimized by his own teammates who had been
gunning for him as hard as rivals from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has been tough or me,'' Maier told reporters after
the race, adding ``I need time to regenerate my body.''
</P>
<P>
   Maier also complained of the soft snow, and made the mystifying
claim that a strong tailwind blowing down the course helped the
skiers who stood upright, whereas he almost always skis in a tuck.
</P>
<P>
   But another Austrian, Chris Mayer, who by virtue of his victory
over Maier Thursday all but gave the overall title away to the
Norwegian, was gleeful. His comments after the race give a glimpse
into the competitive heart of the Austrian team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could beat Hermann today because he is tired. Since
Christmas, I knew Hermann was not unbeatable in Super-G.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Maier is no washout, either. Though he slumped at the
end, he had a dominant year in Super-G, winning the last four races
and clinching the title in the discipline a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayer's jubilation at winning Thursday adds another insight
into the psyche behind Austria's juggernaut. Last month at Vail,
Maier was abruptly taken off the Super-G team the day before the
race because coaches thought that Hans Knaus was on a hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   Embittered but quiet about it, Mayer waited until Thursday to
unload his own negative glee: ``This is my revenge on the coaches
taking me out of the Super-G team for Vail.''
</P>
<P>
   So the irony of Thursday's result is that, despite a season of
dominance in almost every discipline and in both genders, the
overall title probably goes to two Norwegians _ Kjus who stands
with 1,409 points and Kjetil Aamodt with 1,317. Maier collected
1,307.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two Norwegians were rocking the world of college ski
racing Thursday. Twin brothers Rune and Frode Kollerud, who ski
cross-country for the University of Utah, finished 7 seconds apart
to take the top two spots in men's freestyle cross-country.
</P>
<P>
   The victory knocks Colorado from the slim lead it held after
placing first and third in Wednesday's GS and moves Dartmouth out
of second, which it held after the first day of competition.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, the University of Vermont's Ekaterina
Ivanova continued her winning ways in the 5K, beating Steffi Kindt
from Alaska-Anchorage by 13 seconds, and third place Britta Wieand
of Denver by 22 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanova, a star Nordic skier on the Russian national biathlon
team, has won her last 18 races.
</P>
<P>
   Action continues for both Alpine and Nordic skiers. The title
will be decided Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
