<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SYNC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACE OF HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 'N Sync, the quintet of camera-ready, harmonizing heartthrobs
from Florida, inspires the sort of time-honored and ear-shattering
passion in young girls that moves CDs by the millions, lands the
band's biography on bestseller lists, and sells out concerts in a
flash. Tickets went in less than an hour for 'N Sync's show Tuesday
night at the FleetCenter. The bill also includes BWitched and
Tatyana Ali.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with 22-year-old JC Chasez _ also known as Mr.
Sleepy and the Perfectionist _ in Greenville, N.C., the day after
'N Sync's first show headlining an arena.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the best thing about being in 'N Sync?
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, being with your best friends. Second of all,
reaching out to people.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the worst thing about being in 'N Sync?
</P>
<P>
   A. Probably the lack of sleep. It's just a crazy schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there anything that you always take on the road with you,
something you can't live without?
</P>
<P>
   A. I usually take a guitar or keyboard, some sort of instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's your most prized possession?
</P>
<P>
   A. Um, um, I would say my family.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What was your first big splurge after 'N Sync hit it big?
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, there wasn't one. The only thing I bought was a
keyboard, the one I take on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It didn't cross your mind to buy a Porsche?
</P>
<P>
   A. There's really no need for a Porsche, because I'm never home
to drive.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have a girlfriend?
</P>
<P>
   A. Not right now. I'm definitely talking to a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Sounds like you're conducting interviews. . .
</P>
<P>
   A. At this point, where we are now, you've got to get to know
people real well, you know, because you don't know what their
motives are before you date them. I'm just trying to check them
out.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Describe your dream girl.
</P>
<P>
   A. Somebody patient. I don't know. Somebody who's really
outgoing, but patient, who's going to accept me for all my faults.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What are your faults?
</P>
<P>
   A. They're gonna have to deal with me being on the road so much.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you were a Beatle, which one would you be?
</P>
<P>
   A. I would say McCartney or Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If you were a Backstreet Boy, which one would you be?
</P>
<P>
   A. You can stick me on any of them, I don`t care.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So the reports of bad blood between you and the Backstreet
Boys are a nasty rumor?
</P>
<P>
   A. They don't bother me none.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the wildest and craziest thing a fan has ever done?
</P>
<P>
   A. We have a few stories. My favorite is the one about the fan
who jumped onto the luggage belt at the airport and then tried to
get through security riding on the luggage racks.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the wildest and craziest thing you've ever done?
</P>
<P>
   A. I jumped off a two-story building just to get down. I started
down the drainpipe, and just dropped down. I hurt my ankle pretty
bad. For some reason my eye said I could make it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Now that you're famous, is security a drag?
</P>
<P>
   A. We like our security guys. We like everybody we hang out
with. You barely notice they're there.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You guys toured with Janet Jackson. Did you all pal around?
</P>
<P>
   A. We talked to her a few times. We both had busy schedules.
She's a really, really cool woman. A special person, period. She
makes you feel so comfortable, and gets everything done in a nice
way.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's on your CD player?
</P>
<P>
   A. I just pulled out my Lenny Kravitz CD. I think it's one of
the coolest records this year. If it's got a good vibe, regardless
of style, I like it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you do for fun?
</P>
<P>
   A. I sleep. That's my favorite thing to do. I catch a flick from
time to time, too. The ``Star Wars'' trilogy is my favorite of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you all as squeaky clean as you seem?
</P>
<P>
   A. I take a shower sometimes. I mean, people say we're good. But
I don't know what people think we are.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I think people see you as extremely wholesome, clean-living
fellows, who never do anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A. We just carry on like your next-door neighbor. We have our
good days and our bad days. But I wouldn't try to do something on
stage that my mom couldn't watch.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have any strategically placed tattoos?
</P>
<P>
   A. No tattoos. I'm terrified of needles.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Don't you ever feel like sneaking out of your hotel room in
disguise and carousing a bit?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, because I want to be asleep at night. If we want to go
out, we go out. If I'm with my parents at dinner, and they're
having wine, I might have some. But we don't drink stupidly. We're
very goal-oriented. You don't need stuff like that beating you up.
We want to keep it on the up and up.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Critics are pretty harsh on you. Are you more talented than
you're given credit for?
</P>
<P>
   A. Critics can say what they want. Some of what they write is
good and some is bad. I'm just happy the fans like us. The Beatles
were looked at as a crazy rocker phenomenon. People bash things
that are supposed to be a phenomeonon. So be it. Like I said, I'm
not worried about the critics.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will there be any surprises on the new record?
</P>
<P>
   A. We've only done a few songs for the new record. We'll do the
bulk of it in June. There will be more songs by us. All of us are
contributing to the writing. We had one song on the last record.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Whom do you most admire?
</P>
<P>
   A. I look up to my family. They've had to deal with a lot of
stuff, running a family with my sister and brother and dealing with
me. Musically, I look up to Sting and Seal, who are both melody-
and story-driven writers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What was your most embarrassing moment on stage?
</P>
<P>
   A. Oh, boy. I've had times when my fly's been down for one or
two songs before I noticed it. Thankfully it wasn't in front of
20,000 people. Just 5,000. We stay pretty cool now.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You all wear WWJD bracelets. When's the last time you asked
yourself, ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   A. Actually, it was Wednesday. The guys called at 10 p.m. and
asked me to go to a movie, and I had to decide if I should go out
and be tired the next day, or get some sleep. We wear the bracelets
as a reminder. You want to make good decisions every time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
