u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DEEP-BOS &LR;      03-12 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEEP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFEIFFER'S RAW NERVES PROPEL `DEEP END' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE DEEP END OF THE OCEAN 
Directed by: Ulu Grosbard 
Screenplay by: Stephen Schiff (novel: Jacquelyn Mitchard) 
Starring: Michelle Pfeiffer, Treat Williams, Whoopi Goldberg,
Jonathan Jackson, Ryan Merriman, John Kapelos 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (language and thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' is interesting for the very things
that make it a chancy commercial prospect. Although it smooths away
a lot of the rough edges in Jacquelyn Mitchard's novel about a
mother whose 3-year-old son is kidnapped, then, against the odds,
returned nine years later, it's more unruly in more ways than the
average studio film wants to know about. At its center is Michelle
Pfeiffer's jangly mom, torn with anguish and guilt after the boy is
spirited away from a crowded Chicago hotel lobby where she
momentarily left him in his older brother's care while she went to
check in.
</P>
<P>
   As she proved in ``A Thousand Clowns,'' Pfeiffer is willing to
play characters who do not immediately engage an audience's
sympathy. As Beth Cappadoro, juggling motherhood with a
photographer's career, Pfeiffer does not handle crisis well. Her
husband, played by Treat Williams, is the steadier of the two. He
perseveres, continuing to do the daily things that must be done,
while she takes to her bed, bereft and depressed, when she isn't
going over the case with Whoopi Goldberg's investigating detective,
Candy Bliss. It's a name she makes clear she realizes must be
accompanied by an explanation and a joke, and also a declaration of
her sexuality (gay).
</P>
<P>
   As if deliberately playing against her beauty, Pfeiffer makes
sure her eyes are the eyes of a woman who cries a lot. She's tense,
taut, an emotional tripwire whose pain is sometimes expressed by
verbally jeering her husband's steadiness, which she sometimes
interprets as a reproach. She's far from being a basket case, but
she's not easy to live with, either. Then this bifurcated film
stops and picks up nine years later. If not exactly cheery, Beth
has recovered somewhat and made her peace with her family. At least
her older son no longer has to torture his younger sister so their
parents will interrupt their fighting to see why the baby is
crying.
</P>
<P>
   While not quite brandished as a badge of integrity, discomfort
(in star and audience alike) does at least tip us off that this
film is willing to go a few places that conventional films aren't.
The thing that turns ``Deep End of the Ocean'' into more than just
another overextended TV movie is its willingness to play out the
likelihood that when the boy is reunited with his family nine years
later after turning up at the door and offering to mow the lawn,
the family isn't exchanging sadness for a happy ending. Rather,
it's only trading one set of problems for another set.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Ryan Merriman's 12-year-old misses the man he
regards as his father, who lives only a few blocks away and is
innocent of the kidnapping. The boy is not sure about taking up a
new life with his biological family, and Pfeiffer's Beth is forced
to ask herself what the best way might be to ensure his happiness.
Or, rather, what the best guess might be, since Stephen Schiff's
refreshingly intelligent screenplay recognizes the problematic
nature of the situation, respects it, and doesn't insist on
wrapping everything up conclusively. It leans toward resolution,
yet leaves things open-ended. While it often seems a merely neat
and efficient exercise in motivation-supplying, it's certainly a
healthy cut above most.
</P>
<P>
   The film is jagged in its pacing and sometimes flat in its tone,
and yet Ulu Grosbard reminds us why he's celebrated as an actor's
director. Pfeiffer's clenched, antiglamorous Beth is one of her
best characterizations. It's a thing of intensity and integrity,
almost all raw nerves, serious to the point of dourness. Never does
Pfeiffer trade on her looks or resort to histrionics. She just goes
with the emotion. Williams's husband is smoothed into near
blandness, but the young actors playing her sons are affecting.
Merriman, as the unwitting prodigal returned, persuades us he's
just trying to be a good kid and not make anyone feel worse. As the
guilt-ridden older brother, Jonathan Jackson impressively projects
sensitivity and idealism. ``Deep End of the Ocean'' is not without
its compromises, but it's still above Hollywood's average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
