<HEADLINE>
`CORRUPTOR' IS PREDICTABLE COP EXCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kiss-kiss bang-bang gets a workout in ``The Corruptor,'' a
dizzyingly convoluted shoot-'em-up in which everyone fires piles of
weapons but only the bad guys die.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, everyone's a bad guy even the good guys, who
rub elbows and other parts with a variety of corrupt forces
(gangsters, smugglers, prostitutes) before mowing them all down in
a hail of bullets. It's that sort of movie.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by James Foley (``At Close Range,'' ``The Chamber''),
``The Corruptor'' stars Chow Yun-Fat and Mark Wahlberg, which is to
say one of them keeps his clothes on and the other one doesn't.
Both wreak havoc on animate and inanimate objects, including the
requisite cars, trucks, scummy sub-basement lairs and, in the
film's forcibly noisy climax, one large ship.
</P>
<P>
   The excuse for all this destruction is Robert Pucci's
screenplay, which knits together one of the snarlier plots to
attach itself to an action film. Chow plays Nick Chen, a veteran
New York cop whose shady connections with a Chinese mob have helped
him rise through the ranks. Then Danny (Wahlberg), a clean young
idealist, is transferred to Nick's Chinatown precinct,
discombobulating both Nick and his web of criminal chums among them
Henry Lee (Ric Young) and Uncle Benny (Kim Chan), currently in the
middle of a turf war with Bobby Vu (Byron Mann).
</P>
<P>
   Bobby's the head thug of a violent gang called the Fukienese
Dragons, which might or might not be part of a slavery ring
involving illegal immigrants. Complicating matters are a bunch of
inexplicably dead prostitutes who keep turning up in Dumpsters.
</P>
<P>
   Will Danny stay clean? Will Henry corrupt him? Will Danny
disrobe for a nude scene with prostitutes? Will Nick and Danny
overcome their differences and forge mutual respect? Or will Nick
continue to say things like ``You don't change Chinatown, boy it
changes you!'' and ``You wanna be a Chinese, you gotta eat the
nasty stuff!''? (Danny, for the record, is the one who says ``I
don't care if you pick a raisin out of Sammy Davis' eye socket.''
Umm, OK.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese gangsters are the supposed crux of the movie, but
their internecine squabbles never make much sense all we know is
that Bobby hates Benny and Henry, who's using Nick to get back at
Bobby (or is it Benny?) while simultaneously using Danny to jerk
around Nick. For what it's worth, most of this makes more sense at
the end than it does when you're sloshing around in the middle of
it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the film features a few genuine plot twists
and one eye-popping, hair-raising six-minute car chase. The
bloodshed, while witless, incessant and absurd, is limited mainly
to gun battles choreographed to cartoonish excess.
</P>
<P>
   Chow, the broody Hong Kong action star who made his American
debut with the equally rat-a-tat ``Replacement Killers,'' does a
fine job of offing people while remaining fashionably groomed.
Wahlberg gives his green kid a good shot of ambiguity: In the tug
between right and wrong, he's ripped right down the middle. Juan
Ruiz-Anchia's black-and-blue photography looks appropriately
bruised, while his antsy camerawork may remind TV viewers of a few
prime-time cop shows.
</P>
<P>
   The end sum is skillful but standard filmmaking, slick, gimmicky
and powered by numbing action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
