<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK SIDE OF FAME HAUNTS SILVERCHAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surreal: That's how Silverchair singer-guitarist Daniel Johns
describes his past year. His band had become a kind of Australian,
teenage Pearl Jam, blasting its way around the globe. But the
contrast with his world at home, where Johns had not finished high
school, took an alarming toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from playing in front of thousands of people who said
they loved me, to coming home to see gangs waiting to beat me up
outside of school just because I was different,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Johns, who is 19, finished high school in 1997. By that time,
silverchair had released two hit albums, ``Frogstomp'' and ``Freak
Show.'' On Tuesday, the group issues a third disc, ``Neon
Ballroom,'' which reflects the many tensions in Johns's young life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to write songs about being a tortured artist. I
didn't want to glamorize depression. I just wanted to be honest and
open,'' says Johns, who admits to many anxiety problems leading up
to the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I locked myself in my house for three months and had family
and friends deliver food. I suffered from paranoia,'' he says. The
upshot is a turbulent, but arrestingly varied, album. ``Neon
Ballroom'' has some cathartic rock numbers, but also more pensive,
personal tunes such as ``Emotion Sickness,'' a strikingly mature,
6-minute song that opens the album and features an appearance by
David Helfgott, the pianist whose mental breakdown and comeback was
portrayed in the film, ``Shine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt a connection because he started young and was
Australian. We both have a lot of nervous energy. You can hear it
in his track,'' says Johns. ``But it was amazing working with him.
He's very affectionate and . . . needs to touch and kiss people all
the time. I'm not sure what it's all about, but it's not a sad
thing. He left everybody very high.''
</P>
<P>
   The collaborative song features some sweeping power chords on
guitar, countered by Helfgott's manic, but economic, piano inserts.
The lyrics describe the mental anguish of ``distorted eyes'' and
the appeal of antidepressant medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I wrote the song, I was trying to avoid being a
cliche of the rock singer on antidepressants,'' says Johns. ``But
later on the album, on the song `Paint Pastel Princess,' is when I
gave in to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns, whose bandmates include drummer Ben Gillies and bassist
Chris Joannou, says antidepressants have helped him cope with
crowds. Hence, his consent to another worldwide tour, which stops
at the Paradise March 23. ``I'm fine in front of crowds as long as
I'm not in among them,'' he says. ``Throughout all this, I've been
lucky to have a stable family life. That means so much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hey Jude: Former Bostonian Jude, a fast-talking wordsmith in the
Dylan tradition, has caught on with his new album, ``No One Is
Really Beautiful.'' It's done well nationally and been nominated
for a Boston Music Award for debut album of the year. Released on
Maverick Records (owned by Madonna), the disc is an acoustic-pop
gem. Sporting a wise-guy sensibility, Jude spits out lines like
``Charlie says no one is really beautiful, they're just mediocre
men of the hour'' and ``the words of the prophets are no longer
written on the subway walls.'' Cocky and sensitive at the same
time, Jude grew up in Jamaica Plain and Needham and is now living
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up reading a lot of poetry, a lot of anthologies,''
says Jude, who was more conversant as a youth with T. S. Eliot than
with Dylan or other folk poets. He moved to LA five years ago,
because he wanted to fight his way into the record biz and also
``sit up front at Laker games wearing Celtic green.'' Soon came the
Maverick deal and such smarty-pants tunes as ``Rick James,'' now an
alternative rock hit.
</P>
<P>
   Jude's current plans are to ``tour, tour, tour and play, play,
play'' with his five-piece band. But he also hopes to release an
indie record of piano ballads in the next year. ``Maverick lets me
put out stuff on small pressings. The label has been real cool. I
waited a long time and said no to a lot of other (labels). I wanted
to be able to sit with a record company president and have him like
what I do, which is what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dead-related news: It's looking less and less likely that the
Other Ones _ the band anchored by Grateful Dead alumni _ will tour
this summer. Part of the reason appears to be that Bob Weir wants
to stay home with his new baby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
