<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO CORRECT A BUNGLED ABUSE CASE AGAINST THE POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's hard to believe that so many people with so
much experience could screw up anything so badly for so long. But
this Jermaine Henderson case has been just one boneheaded blunder
after another.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a chance to get it right. That's possible only if
District Attorney Sol Greenberg finally starts using his head. As
distasteful as it might be, the DA needs to back off his refusal to
grant the Henderson kid immunity and get his testimony against the
two cops accused of beating him up while he was in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. I was one of the people urging the vigorous
prosecution of both Henderson and the cops. Ideally, that would
still be my preference. But the situation is hardly ideal. Instead,
it's a horror show.
</P>
<P>
   That means that Greenberg has to do with Jermaine Henderson what
the feds did with Sammy ``The Bull'' Gravano when they needed his
testimony for an honest prosecution of John Gotti. Gravano, a
ruthless hit man who'd single-handedly filled up cemeteries all
around New York, got immunity for his truthful testimony in the
Gotti case. Now Gotti is in the slammer, and murderous Sammy the
Bull is lolling in the sun somewhere, courtesy of the witness
protection program.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so these cops aren't John Gotti. But Henderson isn't Sammy
the Bull, either. Prosecutors are forced into these tough decisions
all the time. The good ones bite the bullet and make those
decisions with an eye toward what's best for the community.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Henderson might have done, and there are indications
that he did plenty, he represents only himself. The two cops in the
case represent this entire community and its essential sense of
fairness. They represent the system of which Greenberg is an
integral part.
</P>
<P>
   They're also the pivotal figures in a case that has come to
reflect horribly on the quality of law enforcement and basic
political decency in Albany. I mean, just look at the mistakes that
have been made here:
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number one came the night two off-duty cops busted
Henderson in a bar, claiming that the College of St. Rose
Basketball star had punched one of them and then resisted arrest.
If that's what he did, that blunder was Henderson's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number two was made by whatever supervising officer
permitted the two off-duty cops to take Henderson in for booking
that night. He apparently showed up at booking vastly more banged
up than when he'd been dragged off in the wagon, and he was
claiming that the cops had kicked him around in a parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   If that's what they did, then that blunder was the cops'.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number three was Greenberg's decision that his office
shouldn't prosecute the cops. Instead, he would get a judge to
appoint a special prosecutor for them while his office would take
care of Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   That was the key blunder. Why shouldn't the DA prosecute cops _
especially when the cops are white and the complainant is black?
After all, two out of three people busted in this town are
non-whites. Doesn't the minority community have a right to see that
the DA's office will treat white cops the same way it treats
non-white street criminals?
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that an essential ingredient in ensuring that the
population most intensely policed maintains at least some semblance
of faith in the system's even-handedness? Sure, the DA works with
the police every day. But DAs in other jurisdictions prosecute
police officers all the time in cases like this. They do it because
they need to demonstrate to the minority community that they're
fair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number four was Judge Tom Breslin appointing John
Dorfman as special prosecutor. It's widely believed that the
judge's brothers, Albany County Executive Mike Breslin and State
Sen. Neil Breslin, would like to see Dorfman run for DA when the
current term for Greenberg, who's pushing 80, expires. Since
Greenberg's office is jammed with would-be successors, this was a
prescription for disaster. From the start, Dorfman was doomed to
bitter, disastrous conflict with the DA and his deputies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number five was a series of complicated legal
maneuvers by both Dorfman and Greenberg in prosecuting the two
cases _ the assault charge against Henderson and the separate
assault case against the cops _ that led to the charges against
everybody being thrown out and then effectively reinstated against
the cops alone on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blunder number six was the city's decision to settle a civil
suit by Henderson before the criminal cases were resolved.
Henderson has $60,000 in his pocket. As he said the other day, he
has no incentive to testify in the criminal case against the cops _
not when he could face new criminal charges for minimizing his role
in the bar fight that started all this, which he apparently did in
his initial statement to the police and later as well.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue is how to resolve this mess. And Greenberg has
committed yet another blunder by denying Henderson immunity for
anything he might say in the cops' trial. That leaves Dorfman with
no complainant to put on the stand _ unless he wants the jury to
hear his star witness invoke the Fifth Amendment, which he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the cops is going on right now. Ultimately, the
case against the cops is vastly more important than the conduct of
any obnoxious, smart-ass college kid in a bar fight, even if he
lied about it later. The behavior of the cops relates directly to
the credibility of the Albany Police Department and the criminal
justice system in general.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council already has passed a resolution begging the
feds to come in and prosecute this as a civil rights violation _ as
though Albany, N.Y., in 1999 were Selma, Ala., in 1956. If that
happens, it'll be a monumental humiliation for this town, the state
capital. That's because the handling of this case from the start
has been a classic study in incompetence, venality, petty political
bickering and sheer, unadulterated stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for somebody, finally, to do something sensible. Grant
the kid immunity and get his butt on the stand. It's Albany's last
chance to get this right.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
