<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV14-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIME FOR MOVE TO MORE FIXED-INCOME HOLDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I enclose lists of my investments and the on-going
contributions to the accounts. I am now 57 1/2 years old, and I
estimate that in retirement I will receive about $21,500 a year
from two pension plans and $15,600 from Social Security. I would
like to bring my total income up to the $50,000 to $55,000 annual
level. How much income can I expect from my investments at ages 63
and 65? All my contributions to my current 401(k) plan are going
into Fidelity's Magellan. Although I am happy with the performance
of this fund, I am concerned about having too much of my money in
any single fund. Should I change, perhaps to Fidelity Low-Priced
Stock or Fidelity Growth and Income? Should I reallocate the money
in my inactive 401(k)? Finally, I am a little nervous about the
market and would like to move toward safer investments. What do you
suggest?
</P>
<P>
   D.C., West Boylston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I agree that you might do well to move toward a more
conservative portfolio. I calculate that you have only about 18
percent of the portfolio on the fixed-income side, a tally which
involved guessing that the balanced fund in the old 401(k) account
has a 50/50 breakdown between stock and bond holdings. Both because
of the market and the relatively short time period before you
retire, I would suggest something in the neighborhood of 33.33
percent of the portfolio in fixed-income issues, and modifying your
ongoing investment pattern so that by the time you retire the
portfolio balance will be about 50/50 stocks to bonds.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for this is that I calculate your portfolio should be
able to deliver just about what you want in retirement if you rely
on half the accumulation to deliver your income stream and left the
other half alone, to grow and provide you protection against the
effects of inflation in the later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how I calculate. If we presume average portfolio growth
of 8 percent for the next 66 months, until you reach age 63, with
your ongoing contributions you should have a $510,392 nest egg.
Half of that amount invested on the fixed-income side and yielding
6.5 percent would bring you $16,587 a year, which would combine
with your pensions and Social Security to give you $53,687 a year _
with no invasion of principal and half your savings left in growth
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   At age 65, the pool would amount to $664,605, using the same
assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   The stake in Magellan represents a little more than 49 percent
of the entire portfolio, which wouldn't be a problem if that
represented the so-called core holding of a diversified portfolio.
But when you combine it with your other investments, which also
concentrate on large-cap domestic issues, it does indeed represent
a problem. It would be less of a problem if you follow my advice
below about changes in the older 401(k) portfolio, but I agree it
would create a nicer balance if about $25,000 were moved to
Fidelity Low-Priced Stock, an excellent offering available through
your 401(k) although closed to most new investors. Diversifying
further by moving money to Fidelity Growth and Income probably
wouldn't hurt, but although it's also an excellent fund it probably
wouldn't help much either, given the fact that its portfolio
represents the same kind of large-cap blend Magellan has.
</P>
<P>
   Now, how do we reallocate ongoing contributions, both to reduce
risk and to move the portfolio toward a more appropriate
stock-to-bond balance?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly you don't want to stop buying your company's stock,
given the handsome 50 cents on the dollar your company is matching.
So the way to move to a more conservative portfolio is to change
the allocation of your other investments. You are putting $300 a
month into taxable accounts in Janus and Janus Mercury funds. I
suggest that you leave these holdings as they are but direct $500 a
month into Janus Balanced and the other $100 go into Janus Venture.
Then I would move all of the contributions to the current 401(k)
account to Fidelity Intermediate Bond, in another move designed to
reduce risk. The upshot of these moves is that you would be putting
a bit more than 60 percent of your ongoing contributions on the
fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   You could then achieve that target 33 percent current allocation
on the fixed-income side by moving the entire balance of the assets
in the inactive 401(k) account to the fixed-income side. I think I
would put the largest concentration, perhaps 75 percent, in the
Diversified Bond, with the rest in the Government Securities fund
offered on that 401(k) menu.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are retired and living on a monthly income of
$2,100. My wife is 66 and I am 67. We would like to do more travel
in the near future and are looking for additional funds from our
investments. We are planning to invest $40,000 in Vanguard's Total
Stock Market Index, $30,000 in its Wellesley Income, and $10,000 in
its U.S. Treasury Money Market. However, we hope to derive the bulk
of our supplemental income from my wife's traditional IRA, which
has a $105,000 balance. Which fixed-income investments would
produce a minimum of $500 per month for us?
</P>
<P>
   J.B., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since your minimum requirement represents an average return
of only 5.7 percent, you should be able to put together a
conservative portfolio that easily exceeds that $500 target.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to transfer the IRA to Vanguard, putting
$25,000 in Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund, $20,000 in its
Short-Term Corporate Bond fund, $40,000 in its GNMA fund, and
$20,000 in its Corporate High-Yield Bond fund. These funds are
listed in the order of their riskiness, and their current yields,
in the same order, are 4.69 percent, 5.94 percent, 6.79 percent,
and 8.31 percent. Such a portfolio would bring you $6,738.50 a year
at current rates, or a 6.42 portfolio average. Since all of these
but the money market fund will fluctuate in value from day to day,
you might decide to withdraw only $500 a month, letting any
additional income build up in the account, thus creating a buffer
so that even when the bond markets are jumpy, the chances are the
principal in the account would not be invaded over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm wrong and you feel that you'd be willing to shoulder a
bit more risk in return for a slightly higher yield, you could
simply put half the money in the GNMA fund and divide the remainder
between the Short-Term Corporate Bond and High-Yield Corporate Bond
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
