<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT YOUR AVERAGE JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the end, Joe DiMaggio confounded the press
with characteristic elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Half the crowd across from the SS Peter and Paul's Church were
reporters or cameramen interviewing the other half of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for one day we were living in the 1940s, not the culture of
celebrity, and even those with press cards joined in applause with
DiMaggio's friends as the hearse drove away from the North Beach
section of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the standing ovation, as the hearse started to move,
a few older people in the crowd said quietly, ``There he goes.''
</P>
<P>
   They knew him. They grew up with him. They proudly carried
pictures of him.
</P>
<P>
   Nino Cresci carried a picture of DiMaggio and his two
baseball-playing brothers, Vince and Dom, who was a star outfielder
for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother told me he was a strong little kid, who could run
and play ball. He wasn't a show-off,'' Cresci said of Joe. ``We
were so proud he went to the Yankees from San Francisco. All those
aspects of him, the way he crossed the plate, tipped his hat, they
meant so much.''
</P>
<P>
   These are people who lived through the Depression and war years
that transformed America, and they saw how their quiet friend
symbolized that transformation.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian-American kid from the neighborhood, the son of a
fisherman, became the nation's greatest sports hero, the very model
of a man, and married the most beautiful woman imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   There he goes.
</P>
<P>
   He's still here, though, even in the hearts of the young. No
wonder he was disturbed by that Paul Simon song.
</P>
<P>
   Two brothers in their 20s, Nelson and Larry Yee, stood across
from the church wearing Yankee caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and grandfather worked in his restaurant,'' Nelson
Yee said. ``My father remembers going out to pick up some fish and
meat with him and Marilyn Monroe.''
</P>
<P>
   Yee said DiMaggio was his hero and model as a ballplayer. I
asked him if he thought it would be possible to have a DiMaggio in
baseball today. He said it might be possible at the high school or
college level, but not in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought an assurance to the game, a style to the game, that
is not compatible with today,'' Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   As the cortege pulled away to touch all the DiMaggio bases in
San Francisco, a single seagull circled the steeples of the church,
set in an improbably blue sky. This was North Beach, though, and
soon everyone took shelter from the sun in the neighborhood's
restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
   At the New Pisa Restaurant, owner Dante Benedetti held court and
impromptu press briefings under a collection of pictures of his
friend Joe DiMaggio. He managed to come up with story after story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Williams came in one day and said, `The greatest hitter I
ever saw was Joe DiMaggio.''' Benedetti said. ``Williams said he
asked Joe what kind of pitch he likes to look for. Joe said,
`Anything in the strike zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the bar of the New Pisa, Roger Boschetti was showing friends
a photograph of himself with DiMaggio and a few other North Beach
ballplayers. It was taken in 1944 at Hickam Field in Hawaii, and
they were all in military uniforms just before playing a game
against a Navy team.
</P>
<P>
   How'd you like to be that Navy pitcher?
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fernandez and Melissa Metcalf were at the New Pisa
celebrating DiMaggio, even though they are thirtysomethings, far
too young to have seen him play. Metcalf, who works for the Giants'
catering department, said DiMaggio once signed a cast on her broken
leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a gentleman, a soft-spoken person, a man, a real
man,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she spoke of him in the present tense.
</P>
<P>
   I sat at Ed Moose's restaurant with Boston Globe political
writer Marty Nolan. ``During DiMaggio's hitting streak in 1941, you
could go into any diner in East Lockjaw, Montana, and people would
say, `How'd he do today?''' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   That was a time of dreadful prejudice against Italian-Americans,
and DiMaggio beat it. He even beat Red Sox fans' prejudice against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiMaggio was the only Yankee who was never booed at Fenway
Park,'' said Nolan, who went to every Red Sox-Yankees game he could
during the famous 1949 pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian kid from North Beach, a modest and elegant man,
became a hero to America as it grew to a maturity it doesn't have
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joltin' Joe has left and gone away. Our nation turns its
lonely eyes to you.''
</P>
<P>
   I never understood any of Paul Simon's lyrics until now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
