<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LOCK-BOS &LR;      03-12 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO BARRELS OF MADCAP COCKNEY LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LOCK, STOCK AND TWO SMOKING BARRELS 
Written and directed by: Guy Ritchie 
Starring: Jason Flemyng, Dexter Fletcher, Nick Moran, Jason
Statham, Steven Mackintosh, P.H. Moriarty, Lenny McLean, Vinnie
Jones, Sting 
Playing at: Nickelodeon; Harvard Square Cinema, Cambridge 
Running time: 106 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence, pervasive language, sexuality and drug
content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' is a Cockney crime farce
that hits the ground running and never stops. It tries a little too
hard to be hip, but it's pretty entertaining even if it doesn't
always achieve the heady lift it's after. Like so many gangster
capers from the British Isles, this one revels in the sheer
theatricality of its lowlifes. So do the lowlifes revel in their
own shtick. Half the time you feel they went into lawbreaking as an
entry into over-the-top show biz. The film is stolen, not by any of
its numerous leads, but by a pair of imposing athletes who play
hired muscle with such obvious enjoyment of their respective brands
of menace that it's hard not to share the fun you're convinced
they're having.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, big Lenny McLean, shaved head and all, died of
lung cancer shortly after the film was made. It's dedicated to the
former East End weightlifter and heavyweight bareknuckle boxing
champ. He plays a character whose way of dunking the heads of his
boss's debtors in water and not yanking them out until they're
almost drowned has earned him the nickname of Barry the Baptist.
You won't soon forget him, not so much because he's scary but
because he looks like a really nice bloke beneath all that beef.
Nor will you overlook footballer Vinny Jones as a scary-looking
enforcer named Big Chris whose specialty is digital removal _ he
takes off fingers until the debtor pays. He looks as tough and
unforgiving as the blade on a guillotine and takes his young son
along on collecting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The two enforcers work for a porn king and all-around sleaze
named Hatchet Harry (P.J. Moriarty), who's regarded as a target by
four young go-getters who ought to know better. ``Lock, Stock and
Two Smoking Barrels'' is a piece of whizbang clockwork set in
motion when Soap (Dexter Fletcher), Bacon (Jason Statham) and Tom
(Jason Flemyng) bankroll their pal Eddy (Nick Moran) and send him
in to run up their stake in a card game with Harry. But the game is
rigged. When he staggers out dazed, Nick is in hock for half a
million pounds and has only a week to raise it. Of course, Harry
has an ulterior motive. He wants to humiliate his old rival, Eddy's
dad (Sting in a nice turn), and he'll take the pub owned by the
latter in payment of Eddy's debt.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a lot of thieves stealing from thieves,
including a dimwit drug dealer, his lethal Jamaican supplier, and a
crooked fence. (Is there any other kind?). The two smoking barrels,
by the way, belong to an antique shotgun, which figures in a
burglary along the line. As it happens, greedy Harry also covets
the shotgun, which plants the seed for a full circle of mayhem,
which first-time director Guy Ritchie loses no time propelling
along. After a while the pace and complexity of the plot (Ritchie
directed his own screenplay _ good thing, since another director
might have had trouble untangling it) nudge characterization out of
the picture, diminishing our likelihood of involvement with the
four mates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't mean we can't enjoy them as the stakes and
danger escalate. Even they can see that they are less than criminal
masterminds, despite a history of successfully perpetrating a
string of petty scams. Increasingly, they rely on their youth,
improvisatory abilities and luck. Think of Damon Runyon on speed,
speaking with a thick Cockney accent, and you'll have the idea
here. After a while the convolutions become an end in themselves
and take over. But there's lots of hurtle, hustle, humor, and color
here. No British crime caper has ever been a wilder or more
high-velocity, high-energy ride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
