<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARKANSAS-COACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA RULING SENDS RAZORBACK COACH TO CLOUD NINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Nolan Richardson got the news from a newspaper
reporter. Which should not, under any circumstances, be mistaken
for Richardson getting the news from reading a newspaper. We need
to be clear on this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't read nothing,'' Richardson said. ``I don't read the
papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. Richardson doesn't read or listen to what outsiders might
say about him or the Arkansas Razorbacks' basketball program. He
just finds out about any slights _ real or imagined _ by osmosis.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it was early Tuesday morning, and a reporter from
Arkansas was asking about something nearer to Richardson's heart
than a first-round West Regional game against the Siena Saints. A
federal judge had made a ruling on Monday nullifying NCAA rules
that require a minimum score of 820 on the Scholastic Aptitude Test
for incoming athletes to be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 16, the judge decreed, violated civil rights laws
because they have ``an unjustified disparate impact against
African-Americans.'' Richardson has been saying the same thing _ in
saltier language _ for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My old heart started pumping,'' Richardson said, his voice
taking on an evangelical flavor. ``I looked up at the Man upstairs
and said, `Thank you, Lord. Somebody up there woke up.' I'm walking
around on Cloud Nine, and I haven't played a game yet. My guys
don't know me today. I'm just a hound dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy right now, I don't know what the hell to do. I'm
as happy as happy can be. Now, write about that: Nolan's happy.
He's not an (expletive) this week.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1994 NCAA Tournament, Richardson displayed a brand of
insufferability rarely witnessed on American soil. That was no
small feat, because the Razorbacks were on the way to winning the
national championship. By the time the Razorbacks cut down the
nets, Richardson had made the short list of coaches you'd least
like to run into without earplugs or an accessible exit.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 57, railed on and on about the injustice of it all,
with or without provocation. Even seemingly innocuous questions
about Arkansas players triggered bitter tirades about academic
standards designed to raise the bar for incoming freshmen.
Richardson was so relentless with his bully pulpit, he took away
from the attention that his players deserved for their performance
on the court.
</P>
<P>
   And what a team it was. The Razorbacks went 31-3 with their
``Forty Minutes of Hell'' mission. A team deeper than the musings
of Jack Handey wore down the opposition. Almost as much as
Richardson wore out anybody within earshot.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time in '94, I was angry personally,'' Richardson
said. ``I was angry, but I had a reason to be angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson won three national coach of the year awards in '94.
The Razorbacks made it to the championship game in '95. Richardson
was still angry, still bitter, and he wore it on his sleeve. He
complained about not getting respect for his coaching ability. He
complained that black coaches never got enough credit for their
intelligence. He complained that a black coach's success invariably
was attributed to motivational skills, or recruiting great talent.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Richardson doesn't read newspapers or the
inscriptions on national coaching awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's perception of Nolan Richardson had changed,
because I was going through a national championship,'' Richardson
said. ``That wasn't the thing that was affecting me. It was
affecting me because you were taking opportunities from youngsters,
which is my livelihood. And particularly black kids. That's wrong.
That's why I was adamant about 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I look back over it now, to think what has happened with
one judge's ruling, it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Proposition 16 guidelines, students scoring less than
820 (out of 1,600) on the SAT or 66 (out of 120) on the American
College Test could not compete as freshmen. The national average in
the SAT is 1,017. The judge seems to be making a crusade for
watered-down standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love standards,'' Richardson said. ``But you've got to make
the standards fair. Education is always going to be _ hopefully _
for the poor also. If you don't fix what's broke at the bottom and
you try to fix it at the top, you're going to destroy what's at the
bottom. It must be fixed at the bottom: K through 12. Not the
colleges. If you fix up here and they don't fix it down there, then
what have you got?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I call, `Free at last.' I have told the NCAA,
`Rule out freshman. That solves all problems.' If they don't pass
it, you've given them the opportunity. Money? But look at what
you're making.' No, nobody wants to do that. That's all you have to
do. When I was in school, freshmen couldn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was a freshman in an era before shot clocks and
three-point lines and widespread integration. He graduated from
college in 1963 _ three years before his alma mater, Texas Western
(now the University of Texas at El Paso) defeated an all-white
Kentucky team in the NCAA title game. He began his coaching school
at the high school ranks in El Paso, where a middle school since
has been named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old-fashioned coach, I guess,'' Richardson said.
``Those days are ending, because everybody's leaving. The young
days, they pat 'em on the back, kiss 'em on the butt and tell 'em
how great they are. I don't do a whole lot of that. Not until the
season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten years of dues-paying at the high school level led to a gig
at Western Texas Junior College. He used seasons of 29-9, 35-5 and
37-0 as a spring board to Tulsa, Okla., which led him to the big
time. The only losing season of Richardson's college coaching
career was his first one at Arkansas (12-16 in 1985-86). Four years
later, he had the Razorbacks in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   His career Division I winning percentage of .734 (455-165) is
the seventh-highest among active coaches. He shouldn't be defensive
about his credentials as a coach, yet he still looks over his
shoulder as if a posse could be on the way any minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that I'm at the end of a mediocre career,''
Richardson said. ``I call the old guys `the cowboys.' They're all
dying out. Used to be, you'd shake a guy's hand, and it meant
something. You shake a guy's hand today and see how much it means.
In the old days, they'd walk up and say, `You've got a four-year
deal,' shake your hand, and nobody worried. You'd go about your
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got to have a lawyer. We've got to have an agent.
We've got to have everything. Because let me tell you something:
They forget real soon. `I don't remember that. Did I say that?' All
they have to do with somebody is pull one of their chains, and
you're gone. Did you know that? You're out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Richardson smiled. He's so happy, he doesn't know what to
do with himself. ``Can I go to practice?'' he asked. Oh, that's
right: The Razorbacks have an NCAA Tournament game to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
