<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ORBISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORBISON SPECIAL CAPTURES HIS SOULFUL GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ROY ORBISON ANTHOLOGY 
PBS documentary produced by Barbara Orbison Productions 
When: Sunday, March 14, 9-10 p.m. 
On: PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's arguable, of course, but a very good case can be made that
Roy Orbison had the most perfect male voice in pop music. And, that
in the songs he sang and co-wrote _ ``Crying,'' ``It's Over,''
``Only the Lonely'' among them _ he conveyed the depths of emotion
that few pop songs get near. You might consider Orbison the polar
opposite of the young Elvis Presley. Elvis was cocky,
self-possessed; he swaggered. Orbison stood immobile, seemingly
stoic, singing soulful songs of heartbreaking vulnerability and
pathos. Mid-tempo rockers like ``Oh Pretty Woman'' were fun, but
the dramatic ballads are where Orbison's talents really shined.
</P>
<P>
   Orbison's work was done too soon. He died at age 52 from a
massive heart attack on Dec. 6, 1988, just days after two sold-out
Boston gigs at the defunct Channel. Earlier that year, he'd seen a
career renaissance via his role in the Traveling Wilburys with Bob
Dylan, Tom Petty, George Harrison, and Jeff Lynne. Orbison's
comeback solo album, a stellar work called ``Mystery Girl,'' was
just about to be released. When it was put out, it became the
biggest-selling album of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at 9 p.m., WGBH-Ch. 2 airs the ``Roy Orbison Anthology,''
an hourlong special that features Orbison performances from 1960 to
1988 and many interviews with artists who loved and have been
influenced by him. The show is well put together, a satisfying mix
of rare black-and-white clips from the early days and takes from
his latter period. If the musicians who discuss Orbison sound as if
they're gushing, well, maybe they are, but their feelings are
genuine, not just the usual celebrity/tribute yak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made emotion fashionable. . . . It was all right for men to
sing about very emotional things,'' says the Bee Gees' Robin Gibb.
</P>
<P>
   U2's Bono echoes that theme, praising Orbison's luminous
falsetto, and noting that it ``leaves you wide open as a man.''
Orbison was born with the voice, Bono says, ``but in the end
there's another voice that has to overpower that, to touch the
human spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Yoakam speaks of Orbison's voice as a ``fingerprint,''
and that voice opened the door for the journey. Elton John's
musical collaborator, Bernie Taupin, says, ``To me, it was the
voice of God.'' K. d. lang, who dueted with Orbison on a remake of
``Crying,'' found an ``extrapolation of goodness'' in his music.
</P>
<P>
   Orbison hit his first creative and commercial peak in the late
1950s and early 1960s, and then again in the mid-late 1980s. He
dressed in black, wore dark sunglasses, and had a magical aura, as
if he possessed secrets that he was about to share with an
audience. He barely seemed to open his mouth when he sang, but when
he did a majestic, operatic sound came out. He knew heartbreak and
solitude, fear and yearning. He knew how to scale mountains. He
knew how to bond with an audience that spanned generations. He was
the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The producer of the PBS documentary is Orbison's widow, Barbara,
who met the singer in 1968 at one of his shows in Germany. Barbara
Wellhoener was 17, he 32. Age gap aside, they clicked and were
married within six months. She became his manager in 1985 and
helped steer his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is the curator of his legacy, running Barbara Orbison
Productions. In addition to working on the ``Roy Orbison
Anthology'' for PBS, she's planning a boxed set, an ``authorized
bootleg'' four-CD collection, and two live discs, one from the
``Austin City Limits'' show and the other ``Live at the BBC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my role was given to me by Roy,'' she says, from her
Nashville home. ``To look after the bodies of work he's left
behind. He was specific that I could hire anybody I wanted to help
me. I have a really fine staff around me and I stay involved by
checking in. We run it as a business that has its own integrity and
sense of quality. We get together and ask what projects we want to
do and should we do it. `Would Roy want it?' It's all about Roy.''
</P>
<P>
   Orbison had no premonition of his death. ``It came out of the
clear blue,'' his widow says. ``There were no signs. He was pretty
invincible.'' He always liked keeping things in order and saw to it
to advise her on both musical and business matters in case of his
death. This process began, she says, when they were first married.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a really wise man,'' Barbara says. Roy Orbison knew how
capricious fate could be, how quickly tragedy could strike. His
first wife, Claudette, died in a 1966 motorcycle accident; two sons
died in a fire a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Was Orbison, the person, as lonely as Orbison the singer often
sounded?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess at times he must have known what it felt to be
alone,'' says Barbara. ``I don't know about lonely, because I never
saw him lonely. Or bored. He was his own best company in a way. He
always had something to do _ his workshop, reading, painting. Every
day he started basically like a kid. He was so polite and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was human and had human baggage to carry,'' adds Barbara.
``He had his dark side, but what was so wonderful about Roy was the
way he treated you. In those 20 years, from the first time he tried
to take me out _ and you know how guys can be really wonderful when
they want to take someone out _ to the last time he called me, nine
hours before he died, Roy treated me the same.'' She says she can
count the spats they had on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Orbison always sang his songs seriously. There wasn't a feeling
of wistful nostalgia. When he sang, Barbara says, he was always in
the moment. ``All of his songs,'' she says, ``he would have told
you, `I have to sing each song like it was the first time, and
that's good for me.' '' In his last interview, with the Globe a
week before his death, Orbison said that by having cowritten most
of the songs, he felt a deeper investment. ``The songs come from
deep within,'' he said, ``and then you treat them as an artist with
that much respect. I couldn't hardly cheat myself and not do the
best I could. . . . My voice is a gift; my talent is a gift; the
opportunity for the journey is a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Orbison says she doesn't feel cheated by her husband's
death and its cruel timing. She says she's grateful he completed
``Mystery Girl,'' that she and he talked at length hours before he
died. She says she feels Orbison, who was born again as a Christian
three years before his death, is in heaven: ``I'm at ease that Roy
is in the place he needs to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1339EST &QL; 
