<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7991 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-MILESTONE-HNS &LR;      03-12 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MILESTONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW BUOYS THE BULLS AS BEARS AWAIT JUDGMENT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With trillions of dollars at stake, Wall Street
pros and investors are trying to divine how high the resilient Dow
will fly.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Dow Jones industrial average has wobbled
like a drunkard. It fell below 8,000 in October but has bounced
back with a vengeance, edging toward the 10,000 mark on Thursday
and Friday before backing off.
</P>
<P>
   When will the index, which tracks the stocks of 30 blue-chip
companies, hit the 10,000 ... or 11,000 ... or 12,000?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling _ this market keeps powering ahead,'' said
Art Micheletti, chief investment strategist at Bailard, Biel &AMP;
Kaiser, an investment company in San Mateo, Calif. ``And the
momentum clearly favors the market going even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Acampora, a raging bull who is the director of technical
research at Prudential Securities, thinks the Dow will reach 11,500
by the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Barton Biggs, an investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, is less optimistic. He told CNBC Thursday that domestic
stocks are not poised ``for a new leg of this bull market.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether bearish or bullish, the analysts say many key economic
signs still look good. Productivity and employment are up.
Inflation is down. And the Federal Reserve hasn't jacked up
interest rates, which would cool the economy and hurt stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the best of all worlds,'' Bellero said. ``As long we
have strong economic growth with no inflation, financial assets
will grow to extraordinary levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of telecommunications, the Internet and other
wireless technologies should keep the economy surging well into the
next century, Bellero predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't begun to tap the surface yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellero and others preached caution, though. Like a rabid beast,
the market could turn on investors any day and bloody their
favorite stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very nervous about this market _ it keeps defying
gravity,'' Micheletti said. ``Even if you believe we're in a new
era of technology, there have got to be some limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears warn the boom market is at the brink of a long-term
correction or a catastrophic crash.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is rampant, they argue. Stocks on the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index are dangerously overvalued, trading at 30 times
earnings. Worse, the market is too narrow and concentrated, with
investors pouring too much money into too few good stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing extremes here,'' said Joe Turner, a partner at
Pring Turner Capital Corp. in San Ramon, Calif. ``We're advising
our clients to be a little defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a longtime Wall Street veteran, recalled the hoopla when
the Dow flirted with 1,000 in 1968. It was not until Nov. 14, 1972
that it actually closed above 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the temperamental Dow could easily drop to the low-
or mid-8,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can go from love to hatred of the market very quickly,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
