<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKW-OSULLIVAN-BOS &LR;      03-12 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKW-OSULLIVAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'SULLIVAN BACK IN FULL STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPOO, Finland _ In her preface to ``Under the Tuscan Sun,'' a
memoir detailing the restoration of an Italian farmhouse and its
small vineyard, Frances Mayes writes of learning how to bury the
old tendril of a grape vine in such a way that it shoots out new
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie O'Sullivan is here to bury her grape tendril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's all just a new beginning, starting out fresh,'' said
the left wing from Dorchester, Mass., back wearing No. 19 for the
US women's national ice hockey team in the Women's World
Championships. ``It's a new year. What happened in the past, I
can't change that. You've just got to look through the windshield
and not the rearview mirror in any of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Any of this. A simple phrase, shorthand for more shock, more
sadness than most 27-year-olds see in twice that many years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, O'Sullivan's father, John, died of lymph cancer; two
years later her mother, Ann, was claimed by brain cancer. The 11
O'Sullivan children _ including middle child Stephanie and younger
brother Chris, who plays for the Calgary Flames of the NHL _ banded
together under the eldest, Shaun, to stay in the family home on
Elmer Road. But the sad fact remained: Before she was 20 years old,
O'Sullivan had lost both parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go through phases sometimes when I was angry,'' she
recalled late in 1997, chatting one night during the 28-game tour
that would end in the selection of the 1998 Olympic team. ``The
healing process never ends. You can't bottle it all up; you can't
stop living.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan had no idea she would soon be reliving those words,
retracing those emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Having graduated from Providence College in 1995 as the school's
all-time scorer and assist leader, ahead of even Olympic captain
Cammi Granato, O'Sullivan was considered a lock to make the Olympic
team. After all, she had notched 10 goals and 11 assists in 22
games of the tour, and had considerable international experience as
a veteran of four national teams.
</P>
<P>
   But when the final Olympic roster was announced Dec. 20,
O'Sullivan's name wasn't on it. One of the last three cuts, along
with fellow veterans Erin Whitten and Kelly O'Leary of Auburn,
Mass., she was stunned and confused. And angry.
</P>
<P>
   She just got beat out, coach Ben Smith told reporters that
night. It wasn't an easy decision. ``Some of the younger players
are pushing their way to the forefront,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of declining to talk publicly about her
disappointment, O'Sullivan finally agreed to be interviewed by
Globe columnist Dan Shaughnessy on the eve of the Olympics.
O'Sullivan lashed out, saying her exclusion was a mystery that had
nothing to do with either her performance or her attitude and
declaring that Smith had put himself above the team and the country
in making his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can never be justified,'' she said before she left for an
extended vacation in Florida and the Caribbean, where she did not
watch the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Few denied O'Sullivan was entitled to her feelings _ she said
this week that trying to explain what it felt like to be cut from
the team is a lot like trying to explain what it felt like to lose
both parents as a teenager, how no one who hasn't been through
either experience can ever understand _ but some feared her
bluntness might destroy any chance of coming back to the national
team. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said Smith this week. ``It kind of goes with the
territory; teachers and coaches get blamed for a lot of things. We
were obviously trying to make decisions in the best interest of our
team. Some individuals are not always going to see that right away,
maybe ever. But she's had time, and she's reflected upon it. It's a
credit to her tenacity that she's still going hard at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's reaction didn't surprise Shaun O'Sullivan. ``Coach Smith
has been through the ranks, too,'' said Stephanie's oldest brother,
34, who played hockey at Northeastern. ``He appreciates people who
have guts, who want to play, instead of just fading off into the
sunset. It tells a lot about people, what they go through and what
they conquer along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Sullivan says she doesn't regret speaking out, but says: ``You
can't blame others. Maybe I wasn't that articulate. Maybe it did
come out negative. (But) after everything I've gone through,
negativity doesn't play a part. A lot of people read it and said,
`You don't get along with Coach Smith.' I love Coach Smith. He's a
great coach and he's always been good to me, but he has a job to
do. It had to be somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment she found out she was left off the Olympic team,
O'Sullivan said, she knew she would bury that grape tendril; it was
just a matter of how to go about it. Evaluating her life, she broke
things down like an outline for a book: What she could do to
improve on the ice, what she should work on off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the cancer unit at Children's Hospital was one step:
``It really puts life in perspective. I'm lucky to be happy and
healthy, and not a 5-year-old with my final days approaching me.
There are no limits. I can get better, I can do better, I can work
harder. I don't know if I knew I'd ever get the chance but I knew I
would work hard to get that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Actively heeding some advice from Smith was another step. Smith
had told her she needed to work on moving her feet, so O'Sullivan
practiced and scrimmaged four or five times a week with a men's
team of 18-to-20-year-olds, the Bay State Breakers, in Walpole. Not
only has it improved her footwork, she said she makes quicker
decisions at full speed on the ice. She said, ``I've got to be
skilled, crafty, smart'' to keep from getting flattened in the
men's games, where checking is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   So at this stage of the healing process, O'Sullivan is back
living the life of a national-team player, a life she first tasted
in 1994 and loves. ``It's great to be back with everybody,'' she
said. ``I just want to work hard, contribute, be a team player.''
As for the Olympic gold medal 11 of her teammates have, she added,
``I'm real happy for all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If, in turn, any of her teammates harbor any discomfort with
her, it has not been apparent. Said Granato, a teammate of
O'Sullivan since their days at Providence, ``You worry, have you
lost a friend? (But) to Stephanie's credit, she really did a great
job from the beginning to say hi to everybody, make contact. That
barrier came down. I'm happy for her.''
</P>
<P>
   And, added Granato with a big grin, ``When she gets in front of
the net she just hunts that puck down.'' In the three games played
so far, O'Sullivan has a goal and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   When she returns to Boston next week, O'Sullivan will resume her
other life: playing with the Breakers; conducting year-round
clinics and a summer hockey camp with Chris; working 20 hours a
week with the Police Athletic League, helping put together youth
sports programs to help keep city kids out of trouble. She will
unpack her bags back on the family home on Elmer Road, virtually
empty now with just brothers Shaun, Peter, and David (the youngest,
now a senior at Thayer Academy who hopes to play baseball in
college) living there now as siblings Michael, Mark, Tom, Ann,
Chris, Denise, and Julie have left for either college or careers.
She will think about someday becoming a Boston police officer. (``I
love the action,'' she said. ``You're always on the go, especially
in the city.'') She will do her laundry, which has been piling up
on this journey from Lake Placid to Toronto to Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   And she will look ahead to 2002 and the Olympic Games. ``That's
what I'm aiming for,'' she said. ``It's never left my mind. But
there's a lot of hockey to be played between now and then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
