<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-LEWIS-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      03-12 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL ON THE LINE FOR LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lennox Lewis has boxed for 21 years, ever since he
was steered into a gym in Kitchener, Ontario, at age 12 by one of
his teachers shortly after the teacher, for the third time, had to
pry Lewis off a schoolmate who unwisely made fun of Lewis's harsh
cockney accent.
</P>
<P>
   In all those years he won nearly every significant amateur
title, including an Olympic gold medal in 1988, two world
heavyweight championships, and 34 of his 35 fights since turning
professional in 1989. He has rendered 27 of his 35 opponents
unconscious and has not lost a match in nearly five years. So what
has he got to prove?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, everything.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all he has done, Lennox Lewis has never done enough to
convince the boxing public that he is who he says he is, which
happens to be ``the best fighter on the planet.'' Normally, two
heavyweight titles and an Olympic gold medal would be enough to
inflate one's resume significantly but there have always been
lingering doubts about the massive Brit, doubts about his chin,
doubts about his ability, and, most of all, doubts that the enigma
he seems to be is just a sullen mask hiding the fact that he is
little more than a product of careful matchmaking and a down time
in the heavyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   None of that may be true, but in 10 years as a professional
Lewis has never faced the kind of competition that could dispel
those doubts and too often he has looked unimpressive enough
against lesser opponents to make even his staunchest supporters
wonder about him. Not once in all those years has he been in what
promoters like to call a super fight. But he will be when he climbs
into the ring at Madison Square Garden with a heavy burden on his
broad shoulders as he tries to unify the heavyweight title for the
first time since 1992 at the expense of Evander Holyfield, the
aging conquerer of Mike Tyson, Riddick Bowe, George Foreman,
Michael Moorer, and Ray Mercer, among others.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult enough to try to win the heavyweight title at
Holyfield's expense for he is a warrior of legendary proportions
whether he is winning a fight or losing it. Yet Lewis must face not
only that but the sure knowledge that if he cannot win this one
fight all his other victories will be dismissed and he will slip to
the outer fringes of his sport, joining a long list of British
heavyweights found wanting when their moment came.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For years now Lewis has insisted all the top heavyweights have
ducked him out of fearful respect for his clubbing right hand. He
has apparently convinced himself this is true and, for a time, he
even included Holyfield on that list, an absurdity if judged by
Holyfield's track record of facing every top fighter of his day
that made Lewis's previous arguments about others seem equally
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night his moment will finally come. After a
lifetime of boxing, Lewis will find out what it means to be in a
fight. Even his trainer, the legendary Emanuel Steward, has made
clear for weeks now the significance of the voyage Lewis is about
to embark upon, stating that ``Lennox's whole career will be
defined by this one fight. He's going to have to live the rest of
his life on this performance.''
</P>
<P>
   That is an unfair burden for any man to carry into a boxing
ring, but Lewis must tote it because his resume is littered only
with heavyweight remnants such as Zeljko Mavrovic, Henry Akinwande,
Shannon Briggs (who nearly knocked him out in the first round last
year), Oliver McCall (who did so with one right hand to the chin in
1994), Tony Tucker, and a broken Razor Ruddock.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the best fighter Lewis has faced is countryman Frank
Bruno, who was a longstanding member of Britain's Horizontal
Heavyweights Club himself before he had Lewis in significant
trouble only to be knocked senseless by one powerful Lewis right
hand in the seventh round of their 1993 outdoor encounter in the
rain at Cardiff, Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lewis faces the possibility of joining that 100-year-old
list of burly British bombers who have come to the United States
seeking the heavyweight championship and left broken men. England
has grown used to this, yet each time it produces a new
heavyweight, Englishmen pray fervently that he is what Holyfield
has long been called: ``The Real Deal.'' If Lewis is not a first
cousin to Joe Bugner and Brian London and Tommy Farr and Terry
Daniels and so many of their predecessors, he will have his chance
to prove it on the biggest and most storied stage in boxing, in the
same building where Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier fought their
titanic struggle in 1971 for the same title Lewis and Holyfield
will battle for.
</P>
<P>
   There is a mystique to this fight that is different than
Ali-Frazier however and Lewis is most responsible for it because
despite a 4- to 5-inch height advantage and 30-odd pound weight
advantage, nobody knows what he will do when he gets in against
Holyfield, even a Holyfield who may well be used up himself after
too many years of heavyweight wars against men far bigger than he
is.
</P>
<P>
   Even Steward, Lewis's loyal aide de camp, admitted, ``We may not
know how much Holyfield has left but we know he'll bring all he
has. We know he'll come to fight. Lennox hasn't been in a situation
like this so until he is you can't say for sure how he'll react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to fight the fight of his life but it's
very frustrating for a trainer who's used to having a Thomas Hearns
or an Aaron Pryor, who you know is going to fight. Lennox is a
different kind of fighter. A strange kind of fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he fights up to his potential, he's too big and powerful
for this guy. I just hope he's not coming in there with his chess
board. I hate that crap. Too much thinking. You've got to be
instinctive in boxing. He can't hesitate and think, like a chess
player. Lennox has to let his missles fly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1343EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
