<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CARRIE-BOS &LR;      03-12 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CARRIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE REVENGE: SKIP THE `CARRIE' SEQUEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE RAGE _ CARRIE 2 
Directed by: Katt Shea 
Screenplay by: Rafael Moreu 
Starring: Emily Bergl, Jason London, Amy Irving, Dylan Bruno, J.
Smith-Cameron, Zachary Ty Bryan, Justin Urich, Elijah Craig, Rachel
Blanchard, Charlotte Ayanna, Mena Suvari, Steven Ford 
Playing at: Copley Place; suburbs 
Running time: 104 minutes 
Rated: R (strong graphic horror violence and gore, brief strong
sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an awful lot of red in the ``Carrie'' sequel, ``The Rage
_ Carrie 2.'' Red paint on a brush, red paint on the walls, red
dress on the heroine, red in the name of the production company,
Red Bank Films. When Emily Bergl, as the new Carrie, checks her
makeup (red again) in the mirror before heading off to dish out
some good old telekinetic teen payback, you find yourself checking
the press notes to see if maybe you didn't misread the new film's
title. Are we in fact watching ``The Rouge _ Carrie 2'' and not
``The Rage _ Carrie 2''?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the people behind this new piece of campy
inanity deserve to have red faces. Teen horror movies depend
largely on teens being stupid. Slasher movies require teens to go
for midnight walks where they know serial killers lurk. And
``Carrie 2'' requires its teens to get the new Carrie angry, even
though they know Sissy Spacek's Carrie reduced their school, to say
nothing of most of her classmates, to rubble. Actually, Bergl's
character isn't called Carrie. Her name is Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   She's Carrie's sister, but she's made of sturdier stuff than
Carrie. She's tougher and has better defenses. But she also has the
same telekinetic genes. The only one who knows it is Amy Irving,
who made her film debut as the only survivor in the original and
now returns as a worrywart guidance counselor trying to head off a
repeat performance. She doesn't like it when Rachel is called to
her office and the coffee cup on her desk starts to move. One is
tempted to add she's being punished belatedly for being among the
original Carrie's tormentors, as we're reminded when Rachel flashes
back to the first film's less than immortal tampons-in-the-shower
scene.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is a bunch of neanderthal jocks who turn dates
into rapes, then humiliate the girls by dumping them and letting
them know they're just pawns in an ongoing competitive game in
which the guys keep score in a well-thumbed notebook. There's one
exception to the football scuzzballs, Jason London's sensitive
receiver, who catches Rachel's attention by knowing what ``Romeo
and Juliet'' is actually about. Rachel is doubly wary because her
best friend just committed suicide after being used as a sex object
by one of the jocks.
</P>
<P>
   There's a strength in Bergl's Rachel that was lacking in
Spacek's Carrie. But that film, let's face it, was about Carrie's
revenge and this one is about Rachel's revenge, exacted at a
post-football-game party in the kind of glass house whose
inhabitants should know better than to throw stones, especially
psychic stones designed to hurt and humiliate Rachel, who had let
her guard down in the belief that the sensitive footballer could be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Bergl, making her film debut, is a strong presence. Like so many
girls stigmatized as weird in teen movies, she's bright-eyed, cute
as a button, and projects presence and authority, even when she's
mouthing stupid lines. Through sheer force of will, she
occasionally convinces us there's something going on inside Rachel.
I'm sure it won't be long before we'll have the pleasure of
watching her take on material that isn't so resolutely
self-defeating. ``The Rage _ Carrie 2'' isn't so much a sequel to
``Carrie'' as a labored attempt to simply do it all over again. It
remembers the blood, but not much else about the characterizations
that made the original what it was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
