<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-POLLS-$ADV14-COX     03-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POLLS-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS FRET AS GORE LAGS REPUBLICANS IN POLLS
 &HT;    700&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
for release Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, in his nearly unencumbered
dash to the 2000 Democratic presidential nomination, has some party
faithful worried about his weak showing in head-to-head polling
against leading Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll completed in recent weeks showed Gore
trailing Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in a hypothetical matchup by
18 points, and trailing Elizabeth Dole by eight points. Several
other recent polls show the same pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and his top advisers have dismissed the
polling results as meaningless _ a reasonable assessment given that
the first presidential voting is still nearly a year away.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gore prepares to make his first trips to New Hampshire
and Iowa as a candidate Monday, Democratic tongues are wagging.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``may not be the party's best choice,'' New York Democratic
Chair Judith Hope said last week on Northeast Public Radio. ``While
I have high regard for Vice President Gore, I think we do need to
be mindful that in the past (vice presidents running for president)
have not produced victories for the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll numbers also have given Bill Bradley, Gore's only
opponent for the nomination, an opportunity to present himself as
the candidate who can beat Bush, the GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have a nominee who can win,'' Bradley, a former
senator from New Jersey, said during a trip to Missouri last week.
``I think I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, widely regarded as a long shot for the nomination, has
the luxury of not having been matched up against Bush in a trial
heat. Gore, on the other hand, has been paired against Bush since
the first week of January.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll, published Friday by the Wall Street Journal and
NBC News, showed Bush leading Gore 52 percent to 34 percent. More
important, among independent voters, who are likely to tip the
electoral scale in next year's general election, Bush led Gore 49
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls are simply predictions of the future, in this case of an
election that's years away,'' Gore told CNN last week. ``And you
know the old saying that six months is a lifetime in politics. That
means there are four lifetimes between now and then.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the general chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, said Bush's strong showing against
Gore is due to ``the Eisenhower effect'' _ the fact that the Texas
governor has never had to ``call a ball or a strike on the federal
level.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore advisers compare the vice president's current standing
in the polls to former Vice President George Bush in 1988, noting
that Bush too trailed several Democratic contenders a year before
the primaries, but eventually won the nomination and the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the Pew analysis, Gore's favorability ratings
today are significantly below those of Vice President Bush at the
comparable point in the Reagan administration _ 58 percent compared
to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gore's poor polling performances are occurring in what
should be a favorable political environment: President Clinton has
a 64 percent approval rating and the Democratic Party has a better
national image than the Republicans, 58 to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's position ``may have more to do with his own image
problems,'' according to an analysis this month by the Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore is unburdened by the character questions that have
haunted Clinton, he also lacks the president's charisma and
personal touch. And there is some sentiment that he is an
environmental extremist.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists suggested the polling data could prod
Gore out of Clinton's shadow sooner than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice presidents are always in the shadow of a president,''
said Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster who is not part of the
Gore campaign. ``It takes some time for them to emerge in their own
image and strengthen it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Morris, a longtime political adviser to Clinton, said,
``Clinton is not going to be a plus for Gore, ... so Gore needs to
stop being vice president and be a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Staying the course can win the nomination, Morris added, but not
necessarily a general election.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew analysis found that in six open Republican contests
since 1960, the early poll front-runner has held on to win the
nomination five times, while in six open Democratic contests, the
early leader has won the nomination just once _ and in that
instance, former Vice President Walter Mondale led the Democratic
Party to one of the biggest landslide defeats in history in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``History tells us that one of these guys is not going to be the
nominee of their party,'' said Ed Goeas, a Republican pollster who
is working for a Bush rival, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
