<HEADER>
A8009 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TELLING-BOS &LR;      03-12 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TELLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TELLING YOU' NEVER FINDS ITS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TELLING YOU 
Directed by: Robert DeFranco 
Written by: Robert DeFranco and Marc Palmieri 
Starring: Peter Facinelli, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Dash Minok, Robert
DeFranco, Andy Berman, Richard Libertini, Matthew Lillardall 
Running time: 94 minutes 
Rated: R (adult language and sitautions) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Fazzulo and Dennis Nolan are the executive chefs at
Lombardo's, a tony Italian restaurant that is all the rage in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so that's not exactly true. Phil and Dennis are really the
guys flipping the dough and keeping the napkin holders full at
Lombardo's, the local pizza joint in their hometown. There would be
nothing wrong with this, except that both are recent college grads
who have somehow gotten sidetracked on their path to success and
glory. How these high school buddies wound up selling slices _ are
they victims of a bad economy or bad judgment? _ is never explained
in ``Telling You,'' a wobbly first feature by Robert DeFranco, who
also co-wrote the script with Marc Palmieri. Both are Sudbury
natives.
</P>
<P>
   This could have been a comic examination of dreams deferred,
sort of ``The Little Chill'' for 20-something college grads
discovering what their elders have told them all along _ adulthood
just isn't all it's cracked up to be. But the writers don't know
what story they want to tell, and in the end, they don't say a
whole lot about anything.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though the main characters _ Peter Facinelli's
pretty-boy slug, Phil, and Dash Mihok's hangdog Dennis _ can't
still make something of themselves. These aren't really wasted
lives, although they could get there; these guys just seem
derailed. It's certainly an embarrassment for both of them. If a
familiar face _ such as the Phil-obssessed Deb (Jennifer Love
Hewitt) _ enters the restaurant, they'll duck behind the counter to
avoid explaining how two hotshots wound up working in a pizza
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis seems particularly troubled by this; his young life
already seems a series of missed opportunities, beginning with his
reluctance to hook up with the girl of his dreams, Kristen (Gina
Philips). He fantasizes about what he could have done differently,
but hey, maybe a better idea would be finding a real j-o-b.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Phil and Dennis hang out with their knucklehead buddies,
John (Gary Wolf), Howard (Andy Berman), and Steve (writer-director
DeFranco), whose lives are also in limbo. They sit around playing
video games, drinking beer, and waxing stupid about whether
Superman would be more effective on the offensive or defensive end
in football. It's the kind of mindless guyspeak that has been
written with more flair and spark in films from ``Tin Men'' to
``Stand by Me'' to ``Clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also two uninteresting subplots about missing
restaurant funds and a vagrant (Richard Libertini) who may have
life lessons for Dennis wrapped in a windy story about his
seafaring days. DeFranco and Palmieri would have served their
actors better if they had stuck with Phil and Dennis's dilemma, not
that they make much hay with it. They fail to flesh out these
characters beyond caricatures so there's never a deeper
understanding or compassion for the dreary state in which they
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The movie almost finds its way in a scene when the guys run into
an obnoxious former classmate (Matthew Lillard), who's doing a lot
better than they are. The friends grow quiet, looking away from
their own lives, as much as from this drunken braggart. But the
screenwriters simply don't trust themselves enough to stick with
and develop what is clearly the most genuine moment in their film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-CLASSICS-BOS &LR;      03-12 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-CLASSICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT REVIVALS SEND A MESSAGE TO BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Serious American theater has made it back to Broadway
in a big way this year with three sizzling productions. That all of
them were written before 1949 shouldn't obscure the fact that they
have much to say about how we live our lives in 1999. Nor should
they obscure what has happened to Broadway in the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman,''
Tennessee Williams's ``Not About Nightingales,'' and Eugene
O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' (which begins previews March 29 and
opens April 8, but is already an enormous hit) recalls a golden age
of Broadway, but it isn't nostalgia that's driving the box office.
At least not in the sense that nostalgia is often used _ a yearning
for the safe and the comforting. These three plays are as safe as
shaving with a switchblade and as comforting as a nightmare. Brian
Dennehy's powerful performance in ``Salesman'' and Kevin Spacey's
superb stint in ``Iceman'' brought those two plays to Broadway, but
that's only part of the story. That ``Salesman'' and
``Nightingales'' are getting rousing ovations (and ``Iceman'' is
almost sure to follow) are a testament to something else.
</P>
<P>
   Accessibility has become as dirty a word as nostalgia in many
circles, but for all the existential sturm und drang of ``Iceman''
and the multilevel causes of Willy Loman's disintegration in
``Salesman,'' you don't have to be a weatherman to know which way
the authorial winds are blowing in these plays.
</P>
<P>
   In an essay in the March issue of Harper's, Miller raises
important issues about what has kept serious new drama off Broadway
_ the millions of dollars it takes to mount a play necessitates
that it prove itself somewhere else (London for ``Iceman'' and
``Nightingales,'' Chicago for ``Salesman''). He also mentions that
a play can't survive a negative review in The New York Times, the
high cost of advertising, and the stratospheric cost of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But the main subject of his essay is the primary reason serious
plays have such a difficult time making it to Broadway _ the
changing aesthetic that came to dominate American theater,
beginning in the 1950s and progressing from there, an aesthetic
that became as alienating to a mass audience as the ticket prices
to many theatergoers. Miller blames critics as much as if not more
than playwrights:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Realism' is now a put-down; `poetic' is praise.
`Experimental' is attractive; `traditional' is not. `Metaphorical'
is intriguing, though perhaps not so much as `lyrical,'
`non-linear,' `dreamlike,' and `surreal.' It is almost as if
`realism' can hardly be poetic, or as if the `poetic' is not, at
its best, more real then the merely `realistic' and, at its worst,
more conventional beneath its elusive, or unfathomable skin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightingales'' is basically a ``realistic'' play and
``Salesman'' is often interpreted as belonging in that tradition,
while ``The Iceman'' cometh from the more ``poetic'' Irish and
Irish-American genre. When considered together, however, what is
most impressive about them is, first, that there is no artificial
distinction between the real and the poetic. Perhaps more
important, that there is no real barrier to understanding the
plays. They are all good yarns. The artistry of the playwrights
makes them more than that, but they are basically understandable to
anyone without a degree in history, philosophy, or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller said in a 1996 Globe interview, ``Tennessee and I felt
that we wanted to embrace the big audience, we didn't want simply
to creep into the art audience. Tennessee's plays and mine,
different as they are, are addressed to anybody. You don't have to
know anything in particular. You don't have to juggle philosophic
concepts. They're not in any way arcane or difficult to grasp. They
can lead you somewhere that's intellectually interesting, but they
insist on meeting you on your terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Which shouldn't imply that either Miller or Williams were
dumbing down. ``Macbeth'' is not difficult to grasp, either. The
more one knows, the more one understands, certainly, which is true
of these three plays as well. ``Salesman'' _ appropriately at the
Eugene O'Neill Theatre _ is a perfect case in point. One of the
more amazing things about it is how much of the language has
entered the vernacular _ attention must be paid; riding on a smile
and a shoeshine; we're free and clear; I am not a dime a dozen! I
am Willy Loman! And 50 years later it has even more resonance in
terms of corporate mentality toward the disposability of the
individual. That the issue has grown over 50 years rather than
receded, and that it plays as well in communist China as in
America, are testaments to the play's universality as well as
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't what makes it a great play, though. The mediocre Hal
Holbrook version that played in Boston three years ago dealt with
those issues, but _ to go back to Miller's point _ eliminated all
the poetry. It never got beyond the purely political or purely
realistic. The Broadway production, imported from the Goodman
Theatre in Chicago, beautifully captures the play within Willy's
mind. A revolving stage keeps Willy's mind constantly veering from
the terrors of his current, disintegrating condition to the glories
and disappointments of the past.
</P>
<P>
   I was not as taken with Dennehy as most others have been.
(Elizabeth Franz all but steals the show as Mrs. Loman.) The
opening scene makes it seem as if it's going to be a towering Lee
J. Cobb-ish performance, but Dennehy and director Robert Falls use
the actor's bulk against him. Placing his fingers to his mouth and
cowering at confrontations show how scared Willy is at what's
happening to him, but it's an interpretation that invites some of
the analysis in The New York Times, reducing Willy to someone in
need of Prozac or in the early stages of Alzheimer's. If you come
away from ``Death of a Salesman'' with a biochemical rather than
sociopolitical or psychological analysis, something is wrong. On
the other hand, perhaps it's the particular genius of this play
that there is so much to talk about when it's over that one
shouldn't be surprised at bringing Willy's angst down to earth.
Miller lets you be as analytical as you want.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams, at 27, had not attained that level of
playwriting when ``Not About Nightingales'' was written in 1938.
Vanessa Redgrave unearthed the play, although she isn't in it.
``Nightingales,'' which deals with fascistic conditions in an
American prison, was not produced in Williams's lifetime. This is a
case in which a play was too accessible, not because it's instantly
graspable but because Williams hadn't yet found the balance between
realism and poetry that Miller mentions in Harper's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what we have here is definitely not a failure to
communicate. Trevor Nunn's direction for the combined Royal
National Theatre-Alley Theatre (of Houston)-Moving Theatre
production is spectacular, with prisoners marched through the
audience and Corin Redgrave (Vanessa's brother) as the charismatic
dictator of a warden serving to make the violence palpable.
Williams hadn't quite learned how to layer a play to make the
analogies with fascism more organic or to make the plight of the
prisoners more metaphysical. The second-half prison riot borders on
the laughable. Nevertheless, one can hear a great playwright's
voice begin to develop with a poetry that already lifts it above
agitprop thanks to the loving detail that Nunn, who's now head of
the National Theatre, and the Redgraves bring to ``Not About
Nightingales.''
</P>
<P>
   It often seems that the British hold all our playwrights in
higher regard than we do, although Williams and Miller seem to
enjoy a special place in their hearts. Perhaps it's because the
British theaters attract a wider audience that doesn't sneer at the
idea of accessibility. You'd think that a four-hour production of
``The Iceman Cometh'' would have people running out of theaters
instead of into them, but not the Almeida Theatre Company
production that's coming to New York. It's not fair to review the
production based on what I saw in London, but I can say that Spacey
lives up to all the hype. For that matter, so does O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright did not covet a mass audience the way Williams
and Miller did, and make no mistake about it, ``The Iceman Cometh''
is not ``Chicago Hope'' or even ``Shakespeare in Love.'' But even
though O'Neill contemplates the abyss more profoundly and
terrifyingly than Miller and Williams, a production as good as this
takes the audience along on the ride rather than leaving them at
the station.
</P>
<P>
   One can see the Mamet-Shepard aesthetic arising from ``The
Iceman Cometh'' as well as the Miller-Williams aesthetic and, in
fact, Williams and Miller would venture into more abstract waters
themselves. But one doesn't negate the other. The richness of these
productions shows that it's many of today's playwrights and critics
who have failed Broadway instead of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' continues at the Eugene O'Neill Theatre
and ``Not About Nightingales'' at Circle in the Square. ``The
Iceman Cometh'' begins previews at the Brooks Atkinson Theatre
March 29, opens April 8, and runs through June.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey Into Night''
continues at Hartford Stage through April 1; Williams's ``Sweet
Bird of Youth'' continues through March 21 at the Boston Center for
the Arts in a Delvena Theatre Company production; Williams's ``The
Glass Menagerie,'' directed by Joseph Chaikin, begins previews at
the Yale Repertory Theatre March 18, opens March 23, and runs
through April 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-SBC-HNS &LR;      03-12 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SBC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SBC, AOL FORM INTERNET ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SANFORD NOLAN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ SBC Communications Inc. and America Online Inc.,
the nation's largest on-line service, have formed an alliance to
offer high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   SBC will offer the high-speed access over its phone lines to AOL
customers in its Southwestern Bell, Pacific Bell and Nevada Bell
service areas using a technology called asynchronous digital
subscriber line, or DSL.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio-based SBC, which announced in January that it would
introduce DSL in most of its markets, plans to make the high-speed
service available to more than 8 million homes and 1.5 million
businesses by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a partner like AOL, we can get the message out about our
product more quickly to a mass market,'' Steve Dimmitt, the vice
president of consumer marketing at SBC, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   DSL allows customers to access the Internet over copper phone
lines dozens of times faster than standard computer modems.
</P>
<P>
   It also allows customers to simultaneously access the Internet
while talking on the phone or sending a fax.
</P>
<P>
   Dulles, Va.-based AOL, facing growing demand for high-speed
access from its 16 million subscribers, is cutting the deal so it
won't lose customers to other service providers that offer
high-speed Net access, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL in January reached a similar alliance with Bell Atlantic
Corp., which serves the Mid-Atlantic and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   The two alliances give AOL the ability to market high-speed
access in 21 states.
</P>
<P>
   AOL will charge customers an additional $20 a month for SBC's
high-speed service. It charges $21.95 per month for its main
on-line service.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers and businesses may buy high-speed Internet service
from SBC without subscribing to AOL, but the service costs $39 a
month and doesn't include the monthly fee they pay to an Internet
service provider. SBC offers Internet access to DSL customers for
an additional $10 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal could fuel consumer interest in SBC's DSL
service, while allowing to AOL to keep up with consumer demand for
faster speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really powerful alliance here,'' said Scott Wright,
a telecom analyst for Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York. ``I think this
is really going to jump-start DSL for SBC. The phone companies need
to play a little catch-up with cable modems.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies such as Time Warner and Tele-Communications Inc.
_ now owned by AT&AMP;T Corp. _ have aggressively deployed their own
high-speed Internet services using cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   So far, cable companies have a lead in the high-speed contest.
They have about 500,000 high-speed Internet customers across the
country, almost 10 times the number of subscribers to DSL services
provided telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies have charged more for DSL than cable
companies have for cable modem service, scaring some consumers
away, said Bruce Leichtman, an analyst with Yankee Group, a
Boston-based telecom research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is definitely more in line with cable modem
pricing,'' Leichtman said. ``They're not going to reach everybody
with this price, but it will be appealing to the high-end niche of
people that are on line.''
</P>
<P>
   Dimmitt declined to reveal specific terms of SBC's agreement
with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to say whether SBC would extend the deal to
cover Ameritech Corp.'s service area if SBC closes its $62 billion
acquisition of the Chicago- based Bell company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
