<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SCOLDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURBULENT SERVICE AT 40,000 FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AL McKEE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ He was a nervous traveler seeking reassurance
from the agent at the departure gate that the boarding pass he had
been given in the lobby would actually get him onto the plane.
</P>
<P>
   But the agent was having none of it. She snatched the boarding
pass from his hand and held it up as an example to the assembled
crowd. ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' she said while the man squirmed,
``if you have one of these boarding passes, you don't need to check
in at this gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Her subtext was clear: Don't waste my time.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't seen this maneuver since Mrs. Harrison, my third-grade
teacher, held up Charley Pickens' homework to show our class how
not to do long division. Poor Charley's ears were like red neon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you've heard of commercial aviation's new no-guff
policy.
</P>
<P>
   After too many cases of passengers taking a swing at the flight
attendant or exposing themselves at 40,000 feet or trying to stuff
moose antlers into the overhead bins, the airlines are getting
tough. Exactly how tough was demonstrated to me when my wife and I
flew from San Francisco to Denver. We were briskly scolded all
through the flight.
</P>
<P>
   As we stood in the aisles putting away our carry-on bags, a
flight attendant insisted everyone sit down so the airline could
get on with assigning spare seats to passengers it had overbooked.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, she was back with a threat: ``We're going to
come through and look under your seats and if any bags are sticking
out, they will be taken and checked.''
</P>
<P>
   While handing out headphones for the in-flight entertainment,
another attendant warned, ``If you don't take it now, you won't get
another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the captain turned off the seatbelt sign after takeoff
and an elderly woman got up to make her way down the aisle, a
clearly peeved stewardess announced to the cabin, ``We realize
people need to use the restrooms, but we have to get these carts to
the front. Please clear the aisles.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows there is no greater impediment to the efficient
conduct of business than the customer.
</P>
<P>
   But given the nature of commercial aviation and the fact that
its customers are held captive six miles in the air, surely a
measure of indulgence is not too much to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Had it been possible, I would have walked out on this trip to
Denver. Particularly so late in the flight when the crew was
serving drinks and my wife had the temerity to ask for two cans of
tomato juice. The stewardess smacked the second can onto her tray
as Mrs. Harrison might have smacked a pencil onto Charley Pickens'
desk _ he having forgotten to bring one for the test on long
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma'am, I haven't had anything to eat either,'' she sneered.
``I know it's hot. I know it's stuffy. You think you're dehydrated.
Sometimes I get nosebleeds!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not old enough to remember the glory days of aviation, when
traveling by air was a luxury experience. But I do recall a time
when each flight was attended by a cordial spirit of adventure,
when a passenger had room to stretch his legs and when cabin crews
could be counted on to perform with good humor, with competence and
with sufficient stoicism to suffer their nosebleeds in silence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
