<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8041 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-12 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 FILM'S SHORTCOMINGS FADE IN THE LIGHT OF McDONNELL'S GLOWING (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So here's the setup: Woman is happily married. Or so she thinks.
Husband, a grade-school principal and a real slice o' slime, is
having an affair. With their daughter's fifth-grade teacher, no
less. Whole town seems to be in on the secret except you know who.
Woman's life is shattered when she finds out. Husband leaves her,
and now it's time to pick up the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   It may be impossible to get an accurate count of how often this
plot line has been used in a film. A hundred? A thousand? A few too
many?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the score, add ``Replacing Dad'' (CBS 9 p.m. Sunday) to
the list. But not the A list.
</P>
<P>
   And if it should happen to squeeze its way onto the B list, give
all credit to the extraordinarily talented Mary McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell (``Dances With Wolves,'' ``Passion Fish'') carries
this CBS film to the extent that it almost could be billed a
one-woman show. Not that the rest of the cast is invisible.
Goodness, no. Tippi Hedren, in fact, is happy to show that some
women in their 60s can still wear tight sweaters _ and tighter
jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Hedren plays Dixie, the ebullient and aerobically healthy mother
of McDonnell's character, Linda Marsh. It falls to Dixie to lift
Linda's spirits after Linda's husband leaves her and their three
kids after 16 years of marriage. Hedren is, well, ebullient in the
role _ certainly not unconvincing as a mom living out the
beauty-queen dreams she once held for her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hedren's performance is a reliable and very
well-preserved Chevy, McDonnell's is a top-of-the-line Cadillac
with power to burn.
</P>
<P>
   The range of emotions she portrays is an entire curriculum of
Actors Studio seminars, and the truth in each emotion is as
unassailable as one of Honest Abe's oaths.
</P>
<P>
   From energy-sapping ennui to crushing heartbreak to tentative
exhilaration, McDonnell's face and voice perform a marvelous
expressionistic duet that takes the viewer's mind off the film's
shortcomings, one of which is a flat performance by William Russ as
Linda's sleazebag husband, George Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Another is an even flatter portrayal, by Jack Coleman, of the
``new man'' in Linda's life, a too-good-to-be-true physician. But
the biggest problem may be the rough edges on the performances of
the three children.
</P>
<P>
   It's not nice to criticize kids, but a script that builds a big
part of its story around them needs strong actors, and ``Replacing
Dad'' should have replaced the weak ones in its cast. Mary
McDonnell deserves the support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
