<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-1800(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURF BATTLES GET BLOOD BANK INDUSTRY BOILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED:to become affiliates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hometown folks were skeptical, but in the eyes of Carter Blood
Center executives, such an arrangement was worth talking about,
said former chief executive Bill Miller, who now operates a blood
center in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were interested mainly in an arrangement where we would
preserve our relationships and work in a coordinated way with
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it became clear that the Red Cross had something else in
mind, Miller said. Rigid management guidelines were surfacing in
the proposals. The upshot was that the Red Cross would essentially
call the shots from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was close to a hostile takeover attempt, Miller said, and he
felt misled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement turned out to be, at least on our terms,
offering dire circumstances,'' Miller said. ``The governance aspect
was so unpalatable that we just switched off. They wanted us to go
out of business and become part of the Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Miller contends, the Red Cross was applying
outside pressure by offering to provide some Carter clients with
blood more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because the Red Cross is laboring under a large debt,
the strategy was to go to a much larger market share, and once it's
achieved, to raise prices and enjoy wider margin,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox acknowledged that the Red Cross cut deals with some of
Carter's clients, but he said it did not want to take over the
entire blood service business. Blood pricing wasn't an issue, he
said, because the Red Cross matched the price of Carter products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our red-cell price was $75,'' he said. ``The Carter price,
when it was just Fort Worth, was $75. Dallas BloodCare's was $80.
So we didn't low-ball any prices. Our approach from the very start
was to add new donors but not to take them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox contends that some of Carter's customers initiated contact
with the Red Cross to explore deals. The Red Cross was not trying
to conquer Carter's operation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   What ensued was intensified battles for blood-supply bids that
helped trigger alliances among smaller North Texas nonprofits.
Carter Blood Center merged with Dallas BloodCare. The trade group
America's Blood Centers assisted them and other independents with
marketing approaches and other resources.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross opened a center last year in Farmers Branch with a
day of festivities that included a widely publicized appearance by
Dole. The Red Cross has secured some new business since then, but
it is paltry compared with Carter BloodCare's penetration in North
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter BloodCare facility in Bedford houses a
state-of-the-art laboratory in two buildings that it bought on 11
acres at Bedford Road and Texas 121. It will process as many as 1
million pints of blood each year, serving 200 health care
facilities in 22 North Texas counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, they are much stronger than individually,''
McPherson said of Carter Blood Center and Dallas BloodCare.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, a wake-up call hit the area blood industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Red Cross came in and started giving Carter a run for
its money, some customers said, `OK, what will it take to keep your
loyalty?' A new world emerged. A competitive world,'' McPherson
said.
</P>
<P>
   One example of the independents' new sophistication was beating
the Red Cross on a lucrative job of supplying blood to a chain of
Texas hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Red Cross' feeling was that the independents would
bid against each other,'' McPherson said. ``What happened was we
put together an umbrella organization and the Red Cross got shut
out. It showed what, collectively, the independents can do.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains is an industry chasm that, for the most part,
results from philosophical differences. One is having blood
agencies be more cooperative vs. having a free-for-all. Another is
local control vs. central authority in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board here is a community board and firmly believes it
should meet the community's interest,'' said Merlyn Sayers, Carter
BloodCare chief executive. ``It's community representation against
a blood program that is directed out of Washington, D.C. Basically,
our community decided that Washington, D.C., couldn't dictate our
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the battles, there's evidence that the industry
thermostat could be cooling, Miller said. Cox said the Red Cross
has a handful of successful affiliate ventures with regional blood
centers in Washington state and California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Cross hasn't made money on blood services. So to
continue to buy market share with losses at some point becomes
nonviable,'' Miller said. ``At some point, it's not in the Red
Cross' interest to provoke fights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller said it's difficult to get the taste of the Texas
battle out of his mouth. He wouldn't comment about Dole's role in
the area skirmishes, saying, ``She's a powerful lady, and I
wouldn't want to cross her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've dealt with Red Cross people who were professional and
thoughtful, but for some this was a jihad, a holy war,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Karen Brooks contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
