r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOD-1800(2TAKES)-TE     03-12 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOD-1800(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURF BATTLES GET BLOOD BANK INDUSTRY BOILING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since bottling its first drop of plasma 50 years ago, the blood
bank industry has cut an almost sanctified public profile. It's
disaster relief. Fuel for hospitals. Giver of life.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the line, America's most wholesome nonprofit
enterprises became infected with politics and competitive fever.
</P>
<P>
   The big players _ regional blood banks and the American Red
Cross _ started acting more like big businesses as battles sprung
up nationwide over control of the blood supply. Some unleashed
aggressive pricing strategies or predatory marketing tactics. The
motives? To retire debts and guard turf.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more bruising battlegrounds was North Texas, where the
former Carter Blood Center and others have gone head to head with
the Red Cross, the industry's heavyweight, over a massive volunteer
donor base.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts cite that the new Carter BloodCare facility in
Bedford, halfway between Dallas and Fort Worth, which serves more
than 22 Texas counties. That center symbolizes a triumph of
regional blood centers in the face of advances by the
expansion-minded Red Cross, which aims to beef up blood collections
and snare new supplier contracts, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Cross stormed in and clearly said to Carter, `Align
with us or you'll die,' '' said Jim McPherson, executive director
of America's Blood Centers, a Washington-based trade group for the
nation's independent blood services. ``Everybody became angry.
Rather than align themselves with the Red Cross, it only made
people dig in their heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Red Cross, which has been sharply criticized
across the nation for its aggressive maneuvering, acknowledge that
they have become more competitive. Still, they say, they have not
bullied anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they're talking about hardball, I don't know what exactly
we did,'' said Richard Cox, regional director of the Red Cross. ``I
wasn't involved in meetings where there were ultimatums. We felt
there was an opportunity to come in and recruit more people. That's
what we tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross controls 45 percent of the U.S. blood supply and
is driving for more market share, partly to retire a $300 million
debt incurred to improve its blood safety programs. The safety
revamp was spearheaded by former Red Cross President Elizabeth
Dole, but the federal government sued to speed up changes.
</P>
<P>
   As it has launched initiatives, the Red Cross has become a
lightning rod for much of the blood industry's infighting. Disputes
with the $2 billion-a-year charity have spilled into courts,
regulatory agencies and political arenas.
</P>
<P>
   In Memphis, Tenn., an ailing blood bank says the Red Cross stole
one of its biggest donor clients, FedEx. In California, the Red
Cross is clashing in court with a blood center over trade secrets.
And in Washington, the Justice Department has started an antitrust
investigation of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Other skirmishes involving the Red Cross are unfolding in
Indiana and Kansas, trade experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of the blood industry warfare, philanthropists
are re-evaluating how they should operate in a world where
competition is increasingly saturating nonprofits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the really big question of the day right now among
nonprofit groups,'' said Kate Conover, vice president of the
National Committee for Responsive Philanthropy. ``Many nonprofits
are finding themselves in a more competitive atmosphere. They're
wondering, `Should we stay nice and sweet or get more aggressive?'
''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, at least in the North Texas blood bank community,
was to be more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Cross burst on the scene three years ago with the
idea of serving what it considered an underserved market, it began
courting the main operators, Carter Blood Center and Dallas
BloodCare, with proposals to become affiliates. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
