<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS: WHAT'S ONLINE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask away: There are many sites on the World Wide Web where you
can ask an expert about a specific problem. These are usually
narrow _ you can talk to a computer expert about computers at one
site, but don't expect to get help for your love life there. Or,
you can get help restoring an antique car at another site, but that
same place will be useless if you are trying to help your daughter
with math homework. There simply aren't many places where you can
ask just about anything and expect to find someone who can help.
Now, there's a site that tries to be all things to all surfers _
Allexperts.com. As the name implies, Allexperts has assembled a
group of experts on a variety of topics. Here you can pose
questions ranging from how to install a hard drive to how to kiss
well. Ask questions related to relationships or entertainment;
current events or investing; religion or the arts; sports or the
law. Allexperts features a squadron of volunteers who purport to be
knowledgeable in specific fields. They're grouped by general topic,
and then by specifics. When you get to the area dealing with your
question, there's a brief statement by the volunteer for that topic
about his or her background and level of expertise. Click on the
name, and you can then send e-mail to the expert _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family ties: E-mail has done wonderful things for the American
family. Suddenly, people in the same family who haven't spoken to
each other in years are exchanging e-mail and getting closer. Given
that e-mail has been a boon, imagine what would happen if you put
the power of the Web into the collective hands of a family. At
www.MyFamily.com, you can set up your own, private family Web site
and use it to keep members of your clan updated. Post news
headlines on the main page that link to more detailed info, and
allow others to react to the news. You can have a joint calendar,
so you can tell at a glance who'll be where and when. There is a
secure chat area so you can gather and type messages at each other
in real time. You can set up free family e-mail, and even establish
an online photo album.
</P>
<P>
   _ Catch the wave: Five years ago, it's likely that most people
didn't know what the acronym IPO stands for. International Police
Organization? Idiot Pundit Operation? But with the huge amount of
interest in the stock market _ and particularly in Internet stocks
_ most folks now know that IPO stands for Initial Public Offering
... that first batch of shares available when a company goes
public. But how do you find out about upcoming IPOs? Try Alert-IPO
at www.ostman.com/alert-ipo/, where you can subscribe to a mailing
list that alerts you when IPOs are being planned. Or you can check
regularly at the site for various filings to the Securities and
Exchange Commission. You can sort your search by date, location,
industry, and even find out when IPO plans have changed or been
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ribbit: The last time we visited the Exploratorium, the San
Francisco science museum was offering an exhibit on the physics
behind baseball. Frankly, it probably was just an excuse for the
curators to catch a few choice Giants games. (See
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/09/11/online.html) Now, the
Exploratorium looks at a topic that's quite different _ frogs.
Begin with a history of frogs _ they pre-date the dinosaurs _ and a
look at their role in the environment. The site is filled with fun
frog facts, such as this one: ``Frogs' eyes have a surprising
auxiliary function: They help in swallowing. As a frog swallows its
prey, the eyes sink through openings in the skull and help force
the food down the throat. This is why frogs seem to blink as they
eat.'' Pay a visit to Rayne, La., which bills itself as the frog
capital of the world. And learn about the myths surrounding frogs
and toads _ can they really give you warts?
</P>
<P>
   _ Up and at 'em: Need a wakeup call? Schedule one from the Web!
Mr. Wakeup at www.mrwakeup.com/ is still in the testing stage, but
it's still incredibly useful. Fill out a basic form, and then tell
Mr. Wakeup when to call you, and at what phone number. Your phone
will ring at the appointed time, and you'll be prompted with
information you've typed into the Web site. You'll also have to
listen to a 15- to 20-second ad, which is why the service is free.
Eventually, Mr. Wakeup will offer information services, with news,
sports scores, even your horoscope via a phone call that you
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ahoy!: Cruises have a certain allure _ mysterious,
adventurous, romantic. But pick the wrong cruise, and you can add
words like ``nightmare'' and ``horrible.'' America Online has set
up an area called the Cruise Critic (use those keywords to get
there) that talks about specific cruises and provides information
about them. You can read the message boards to find out from former
passengers about various lines and ships, and you can read the very
useful tips for first-time cruise passengers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
