<HEADLINE>
BILL MAY PRIVATIZE SAFETY ENFORCEMENT 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If some lawmakers get their way, the federal government will
turn over much of the enforcement of the nation's workplace health
and safety laws to private consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is pending in Congress that would require the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration to certify
consultants who would, in turn, be hired by companies to inspect
their work sites. If the companies fix the problems they'd be
exempt from routine OSHA inspections and penalties for one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you mean OSHA deform,'' said Charles Jeffress with a
smile, when he was asked about the new OSHA ``reform'' legislation
known as the Safety Advancement for Employees, or SAFE, Act.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress, assistant secretary of OSHA, visited Houston recently
and, over lunch, discussed his concerns over what he views as a
relationship that would be a mite too close.
</P>
<P>
   If a consultant depends on a company for his livelihood, there
would be an incentive for the consultant to please the company by
providing a favorable report without rigorously inspecting the
workplace, he said. And employers may feel obligated to buy extra
services to curry favor.
</P>
<P>
   It creats a conflict of interest, which is not good public
policy, Jeffress said. There also may be a legal problem if the
government delegated its inspection authority to a private party,
he said, adding the Justice Department has concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shaw, secretary-treasurer of the Harris County AFL-CIO,
was even more blunt when asked about the legislation sponsored by
Sen. Michael Enzi, R-Wyo., a former safety manager with an oil well
servicing company,
</P>
<P>
   ``You're basically putting the fox in charge of guarding the
henhouse,'' the local union leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Worker safety would be compromised, Shaw said. Companies can't
be entrusted with ensuring the safety of workers without outside
inspectors and the threat of punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes, founder and director of the Families in Grief Hold
Together Project in Fairhope, Ala., said he is concerned about how
OSHA would monitor the consultants because the agency has trouble
enough monitoring its own employees.
</P>
<P>
   But something needs to be done to improve safety and health
practices and a consultation program may be part of the answer,
said Hayes, who became an OSHA watchdog when his son was killed in
an industrial accident. In OSHA's 29-year history, the agency has
never really enforced the law because it doesn't have enough
inspectors, and when they find a problem, they let the companies
negotiate the fine and penalty classification down, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayes doesn't like the idea of exempting employers from
penalties. Companies caught violating safety laws commonly promise
they won't do it again _ but they do, Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce favors Enzi's bill because it
believes the incentives are strong enough _ avoidance of routine
OSHA inspections and fines _ to hire a safety consultant. That
would improve the health and safety of workplaces, especially in
small and medium-sized companies that typically can't afford to
have an expert on staff, said Peter Eide, manager of labor law
policy for the chamber in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Eide said he's not worried the plan would make companies too
lax. OSHA would still be able to inspect a company if an employee
made a complaint or if there is a serious injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffress testified against the SAFE bill recently before the
Senate Subcommittee on Employment, Safety and Training. The bill is
a scaled-down version of a more comprehensive OSHA ``reform'' bill
introduced last year that never made it to the floor of the Senate.
It too was opposed by OSHA and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional insider predicted the SAFE Act won't have an
easy time of it. The Clinton administration has threatened a veto,
and it's unlikely there would be enough votes to override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., plans another piece of OSHA
legislation in the next two weeks that would extend OSHA's coverage
to state and local government work sites. The legislation also
would allow OSHA to fine federal government offices for workplace
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   When budgets are tight, the first thing government agencies put
off is maintenance, which increases safety hazards, Jeffress said.
And the hazards at government work sites are often similar to
hazards in the private sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time, Shaw said, adding that state and local
governments haven't paid much attention to fixing safety hazards
because they haven't had much of an incentive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
