<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVABLE STORAGE HAS NO STANDARD, YET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Having some form of large, removable storage on a
personal computer is becoming more and more crucial. Though it
remains an important part of any PC, the standard 1.44-megabyte
floppy drive no longer has the capacity for the kinds of things
that many people are doing with their systems these days.
</P>
<P>
   The plummeting price of hardware has made removable storage much
more affordable, in many different forms. However, there's not yet
a defining standard that is as ubiquitous as the floppy, so you'll
have to choose based on what's best for your needs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at three drives that illustrate two different
approaches to having megabytes to go:
</P>
<P>
   __ Zip 100 USB _ $150, Iomega Corp. The Zip drive is the closest
thing we have to a new standard as a ``super-floppy,'' but it's not
quite there. More and more new computers come with them, but
usually as an option. You just can't rely on everyone having a Zip
drive, as you can with a standard floppy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, if you wanted a portable Zip drive, you could move
from computer to computer, you had to rely on either the SCSI or
parallel-port models. The SCSI version required that a PC have a
SCSI card, which few do. (Not so for the Macintosh version _ all
Macs up until recently had SCSI connectors.) The parallel port,
which could be used on virtually every PC, was dog-slow. Copying
the contents of a nearly full, 100-MB Zip disk could take seemingly
forever.
</P>
<P>
   At long, long last, Iomega has introduced a USB-based version of
its 100-MB Zip. The company originally was not planning to move as
quickly as it did, but the popularity of Apple Computer's iMac _
which has no floppy disk but includes a USB port _ forced Iomega's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a good thing. While the USB version is not as fast as
the internal model sold in many Windows-based PCs, it is
significantly peppier than the parallel port. It took only a few
seconds to transfer a 10-MB file via the USB port, compared with
nearly 90 seconds with one of the original parallel-port Zips.
</P>
<P>
   The USB model comes in a translucent green case, and to me, the
plastic felt a little flimsy. Treat this baby with care.
</P>
<P>
   __ Zip 250 Parallel _ $200, Iomega Corp. When I first heard that
Iomega was finally going to sell a Zip with a greater capacity of
250 MB, and that it could also read the original 100-MB disks, I
was overjoyed. Then I learned the awful truth.
</P>
<P>
   There are only two configurations _ SCSI and parallel. Where's
the USB model?
</P>
<P>
   In my dreams. Or, at the very least, somewhere in Iomega's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   I tried out the parallel port version, and while it wasn't as
sluggish as the original Zip, it is certainly no speed demon. It
seems to be about 30 percent faster, but much slower than the USB
model. It took a full minute to copy a 10-MB file.
</P>
<P>
   At least the case on this one was quite sturdy, with a nice
curved design that will look snazzy on anyone's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Having 250 MB of space, though, is quite a plus, and it's
necessary for Iomega to compete with Sony and other manufacturers,
who have introduced 200-MB-plus removable disks. The greater
capacity should be particularly helpful to anyone who works with
large graphics or video files, and with the boom in scanners and
digital cameras among home users, that's more and more of us.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-MB disks cost a little more than the 100-MB disks:
$17-$18 in multipacks, compared with about $12-$13.
</P>
<P>
   __ Backpack CD-ReWriter _ $449, MicroSolutions. If your need for
removable space goes way beyond 100 or even 250 megabytes, you'd do
well to look at a writeable CD-ROM drive. There are both internal
and external models. The internals are cheaper and somewhat faster,
but the external models have been used on multiple PCs.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at MicroSolutions' new external drive. It can handle
both kinds of writeable CDs _ CD-R, which lets you write to the
disk just once; and CD-RW, which lets you write to it over and over
again, just like a hard or floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   Each type has its benefits and best uses. CD-R disks are cheap _
about $2 to $3 in bulk _ and are faster. CD-RW disks are more
expensive _ about $17 to $20 each _ and are a little slower in the
writing process.
</P>
<P>
   CD-R is great for making duplicates of existing disks, or
storing programs or data you don't expect to change. This also is
the medium you'd use to make audio CDs to be used in any compact
disc player.
</P>
<P>
   CD-RW can be used for backing up crucial data, just like a tape
or removeable floppy. Unfortunately, it can't be read in all CD
drives _ only those that support the Multi-Read standard.
</P>
<P>
   The Backpack CD-ReWriter can write to a drive in 4X speed (four
times the speed of the first CD-ROM drives), and reads at 6X
speeds. It takes about 20 minutes to fill up a 650-MB disk. On
older computers, though, you may not be able to achieve these
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with an older version of Adaptec's excellent Easy CD
Creator software, which makes creating a CD in either format a
snap. I'd highly recommend upgrading to the newest version, Easy CD
Creator Deluxe 3.5, which comes with some very useful components.
For example, it has CD Spin Doctor, which lets you turn your vinyl
LP collection into CDs, and a module for putting video on CD.
</P>
<P>
   Although I'm enthusiastic about the Backpack, parallel ports can
be finicky. For example, I had some problems getting a
Hewlett-Packard DeskJet 882C printer to co-exist on the parallel
port with this drive. I'd love to see MicroSolutions offer a USB
version of the Back CD-ReWriter.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman (at) chron.com, or call
713-220-2000, access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
