<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-CLEOPATRA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY GOES DOWN UNDER IN SEARCH OF CLEOPATRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Discovery Channel doesn't mess around when
it has an exclusive. In these days of the History Channel and PBS
stations and legions of other television outlets for cultural
information, when you have something hot, you have to shout about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery has Cleopatra _ at least her old haunts _ and the
network is going to show the goods to 142 countries in 23 languages
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   That's a loud shout.
</P>
<P>
   The event is called ``Watch with the World.'' What we'll all be
watching, at least those interested in the Ptolemaic period, is a
show called ``Cleopatra's Palace: In Search of a Legend'' (Sunday,
Discovery Channel, check local listings). This is an hour-long show
that ultimately seeks to make Franck Goddio, a very wealthy French
businessman-turned-underwater explorer, into the next Jacques
Cousteau.
</P>
<P>
   Given the nature of the discovery and the size of this event, he
may well deserve the mantle. In a world where the Fox network can
claim it is taking its cameras into Egyptian tombs unseen by human
eyes, you get the real deal here, where extraordinary work since
1996 went into the major discovery of Cleopatra's Royal Quarters in
the water just off the coast of modern-day Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   There's a real payoff in ``Cleopatra's Palace,'' a sense of
scholarly discovery and a significant contribution to history.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype, however, ``Cleopatra's Palace'' will not leave
you on the edge of your seat. This is partly due to television's
dumbing-down effect, the fact that the medium always promises
something shocking and revealing and revolutionary, and we end up
with a big nothing at the end. Maybe in this studied production _
Discovery had cameras at the scene and slowly chronicles the
tedious way these artifacts were unearthed from the sea floor _
robs it of charisma.
</P>
<P>
   What Goddio has found is real and important and, in a historical
context, very fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday night, Discovery will follow the underwater
adventures with even more about the Egyptian queen in ``The Real
Cleopatra.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
