r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     03-12 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MERCEDES-BENZ AMG E55 SEDAN IS ONE FAST MACHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend who took a ride with me in the new Mercedes-Benz AMG
E55 sedan summed up the experience this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the fanciest Mercedes I've seen, but I believe it's
the fastest car I've ever been in.''
</P>
<P>
   Well said.
</P>
<P>
   The E55, a special model re-engineered by Mercedes' German
performance partner, AMG, probably is the fastest
automatic-transmission sedan I have driven. And even under the
right conditions, the E55 probably would beat two rather speedy
sports cars _ the Dodge Viper and Chevrolet Corvette.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what prompted Mercedes to create this rocketship
version of its best-selling sedan line, the E-class, but my guess
is that Toyota's Lexus luxury division egged the German automaker
on.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lexus introduced the GS 400, billing it as ``the
fastest automatic sedan on the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over, GS 400; the E55 is about to blow right by you.
</P>
<P>
   With a published zero-to-60 mph acceleration time of 5.4 seconds
(and I believe that's a bit conservative), the E55 is ready to take
on all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Its 5.5-liter V-8 engine, with 349 horsepower and 391
foot-pounds of torque, is more powerful than the 'Vette's 5.7-liter
engine, with 345 horsepower and 350 foot-pounds of torque. The E55
seems to handle better than the 'Vette, thanks to its more-refined
suspension system and its active handling system, which includes
automatic slip control and an electronic stability program. The
Viper's crude suspension system is no match for either the 'Vette
or the E55, both of which would easily pass the muscular Viper at
the first series of curves.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this power could get you in trouble with the
traffic cops pretty quickly. But you don't have to speed to have
fun with the E55.
</P>
<P>
   Goosing the gas pedal when the traffic light turns green, and
accelerating just up to the speed limit was enough of a thrill for
me. By the time I was up to the speed limit and nearly to the next
block, the other traffic was still trying to clear the
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   From a dead stop, with the gas pedal to the metal, this vehicle
pins you to the back of your seat like the supersonic transport
Concorde roaring down the runway toward take-off. With the possible
exception of the Texas Giant roller coaster going down the first
big hill, there's no feeling quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   So, is all that power worth the price tag? The Mercedes E-class
is the middle tier of the automaker's lineup, generally ranging in
price from $43,000 to $55,000. But this special edition, the E55,
lists for $69,100, and with the $865 CD changer, $1,000 gas guzzler
tax and $595 transportation charge, our test car topped out at
$71,560.
</P>
<P>
   As one of my colleagues pointed out, you could buy a house for
that. Not a very fancy one, though, and certainly not one in a
neighborhood where everyone has a Mercedes, Lexus or BMW.
</P>
<P>
   If you can afford to pay for that kind if driving thrill, then
why not? People are paying more than that for the Viper and the
Plymouth Prowler, two very impractical cars. At least the E55 is
also a practical, comfortable and roomy family sedan. Who says a
nice family sedan has to be boring?
</P>
<P>
   The E55's AMG engine has sequential multipoint fuel-injection,
two spark plugs per cylinder with computer-phased firing, and a
magnesium two-stage resonance intake manifold. All of that
contributes to the engine's extra power.
</P>
<P>
   The transmission is a five-speed automatic with computer
controls that allow it to adapt itself to each driver's particular
style of driving.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic slip control helps get all of that power to the rear
wheels during start-up without breaking traction. The computerized
system senses drive-wheel slip and automatically brakes the
slipping wheel and reduces excess engine power until control is
regained. Of course, you can turn off the slip control for quicker
acceleration on smooth, dry surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   The computerized electronic stability program enhances the
vehicle's handling by comparing the driver's intended course, via
steering and braking input, to the vehicle's response, then brakes
individual front or rear wheels and decreases excess engine power
as needed to help correct over- or understeer.
</P>
<P>
   The E55 has four-wheel independent suspension with a
double-wishbone front arrangement and a five-arm multilink rear
setup with solid stabilizer bars. Sport-tuned AMG-Bilstein
gas-pressurized shock absorbers and progressive-rate coil springs
round out the package.
</P>
<P>
   Rack-and-pinion steering has speed-sensitive power assist, which
keeps the steering stiff at higher speeds for more precise handling
in turns.
</P>
<P>
   The four-wheel, power disc brakes have both an antilock system
and Mercedes' brake-assist feature, which, when sensing emergency
braking by the driver, applies maximum available power boost to
reduce overall stopping distance. The system is designed to
overcome the driver's tendency not to brake hard enough, soon
enough, Mercedes says in its explanation of the system.
</P>
<P>
   AMG has put its own styling cues on the E55, including a
sculpted front air dam, side skirts and a rear apron. There are
xenon high-intensity headlights with heated washers, projector-beam
fog lights and a power tilt/slide tinted-glass sun roof.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin is midsize and roomy enough for five adults. The trunk
is a roomy 15.3 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features include dual-zone automatic climate
control, one-touch express up/down power windows, remote control
power door locks, power mirrors, heated 10-way power front sport
seats, premium leather upholstery, black birds-eye maple interior
trim, an eight-speaker Bose premium sound system (AM/FM/weatherband
radio with concealed cassette player), automatic theft alarm, and
remote opening and closing of the windows and sun roof.
</P>
<P>
   The E55 is slapped with the gas-guzzler tax because of its EPA
fuel-economy ratings of 16 miles per gallon in the city and 23 mpg
on the highway. That's because of the government's ridiculous
policy that penalizes passenger cars but lets sport-utility
vehicles off the hook because they are classified as trucks. The
Dodge Durango SUV I drove last week doesn't have a gas-guzzler tax
with its 12 mpg in the city and 16 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The tank holds 21.1 gallons of fuel, and premium unleaded is
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Mercedes-Benz AMG E55 sedan
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Midsize, four-door, five-passenger, V-8 powered,
rear-drive sedan, a new model for 1999 with a high-performance
package by Mercedes' AMG performance partner.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: With its 349-horsepower, 24-valve V-8, this is the
fastest sedan on the market and one of the most powerful production
cars on the planet. It looks great, rides smoothly, handles like a
sports car, and has room for people and their luggage.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: It's a high-dollar vehicle, and there really isn't
anywhere in the United States to open the throttle and enjoy this
vehicle's thrilling power.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Lexus GS 400, Jaguar XJ8, BMW 750il.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 16 miles per gallon city, 23 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $69,100 plus $595 transportation and $1,000
gas-guzzler tax.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $71,560, including transportation and
gas-guzzler tax.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
