<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESISTANCE IS FUTILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: The new Pentium III has a serial number that
has to be entered before it works. When it is entered, your
processor can communicate with ``headquarters,'' and Intel and
others can see exactly what is on your computer. Soon, the computer
programmers will have control of everything that we do.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chicken Little
</P>
<P>
   DEAR LITTLE: We already do, Einstein. Look, if you think Intel
is masterminding some international master plan that will let them
find out you downloaded all those pictures of Melissa Joan Hart,
I've got news for you: Everybody already knew about it long before
the Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Things are getting blown way out of proportion. The chip ID is
intended to be an added layer of security for things like
e-commerce: You might steal my MasterCard number and my password,
but you're not using them to buy Viagra on the Web until you steal
my computer, too. Besides, anybody who knows me would know that I'd
never need Viagra. Stop laughing. It's true. Really.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of things have happened since the last time I wrote
about all the loons out there who think Intel has nothing better to
do than spy on them. First, Intel came up with a utility that
prevents anyone from obtaining your serial number. Second, some
hackers found a way around that. Big whoop. Like that's never
happened before.
</P>
<P>
   When you plug into the Internet, you might as well give up any
thoughts of privacy. Web sites have always been able to track you
and what you're doing, and any geek with a copy of ``Back Orifice''
and some free time can find his way inside your computer. How do
you think I found out about Melissa?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I want to get new equipment and move into the
21st century with everyone else, but how do I get rid of the old
stuff? Taking it for a ride to the dump just doesn't seem
environmentally friendly. Also, if I can actually find someone who
will take the computer off my hands, how do I purge the hard drive
so they can't reconstruct all those steamy letters I wrote when I
used to have a love life?
</P>
<P>
   _ Movin' On Up
</P>
<P>
   DEAR UP: Luckily, I never had that problem. With getting rid of
computers, I mean. No, really. Women send me steamy love letters
all the time. And underwear. I can prove it.
</P>
<P>
   My philosophy is to work a computer until it drops, because
you'll never get anybody to buy it. Sometimes, a computer gets
demoted to doing different things, like being a game machine or
someplace to experiment with Linux. Or I'll use parts out of the
old machine in the new one.
</P>
<P>
   The way technology doubles every three minutes doesn't help the
used-computer market. There will always be neophytes out there who
want the cheapest computer they can find, but when they can get a
new PC for under a thousand bucks or an iMac for not much more,
your 10-year-old doorstop isn't too attractive.
</P>
<P>
   If you do find a chump, though, don't worry too much about your
love letters. A simple file deletion or formatting the hard drive
is usually enough to stump most people. Anyway, I didn't find your
letters all that interesting. Well, certainly not as interesting as
mine. No, really. It's true.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay makes most men look like feeble Barney Fife.
Adoring women with lots of money can reach him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101. Fax: (817) 390-7257. His
real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
