<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     03-12 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`QUALITY' IS IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Sentinel'' built a loyal but exceptionally paltry
following after its 1996 debut, so it wasn't all that shocking when
UPN pulled the plug last season. Surprising was the number of
hearts the cancellation broke. Devoted fans deluged the network
with calls, letters, e-mails and general threats of mass hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   So, figuring ``The Sentinel'' had some life left, UPN scheduled
the drama as a midseason replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Most intriguing about this rare resurrection is this: When
viewers campaign to save endangered series, it's usually for shows
carrying the oft-used, but awfully nebulous label of ``Quality
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Relativity'' carried such a tag a few seasons back. ``Nothing
Sacred'' last year. ``Cupid'' this season.
</P>
<P>
   The rap on ``The Sentinel,'' about a police detective with
extraordinarily heightened senses, was that it didn't fall in the
``quality'' category and therefore wasn't worth saving, despite all
those viewers who thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Surfacing once again was the issue of ``Quality TV'' _ what it
is, what it isn't, who has the credentials to spot it, which
programs have the artistic elements to possess it. We've heard this
descriptive term tossed about quite freely by TV critics, media
pundits and other discerning couch voyeurs, figuring it quickly
constitutes both an aesthetic judgment ``and'' a generic style,
much the way film divides independents from big-budget studio
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Few who use the term can say exactly what it is, but they know
it when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' is quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nash Bridges'' is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier'' is quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' is not.
</P>
<P>
   From what I can come up with, the term ``Quality TV'' started
regularly appearing in the 1970s, but really caught on after ``Hill
Street Blues'' caught our attention around 1981. Three years later,
a lobbying group protesting the cancellation of the female
buddy-cop show ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey'' began.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers for Quality Television (VQT), a nonprofit group made up
of discerning couch voyeurs, would make the term an acceptable part
of TV description. VQT is now an influential organization
attracting the attention of the industry's top producers, writers,
stars and network executives. Attendance is high at annual VQT
conventions, where they hand out awards for, of course,
``quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's monthly newsletter, in which members fire off
comments on series in general and episodes in particular, is a
must-read by industry insiders who want _ need _ to be part of the
organization's ``endorsed'' list. (There is no ``unendorsed'' list
because VQT doesn't commit space to stuff it doesn't care for.)
</P>
<P>
   To its founder and newsletter editor, Dorothy Swanson, there
truly is a set of ``quality TV'' criteria. Essentially, these
include breaking rules (''The Simpsons''); having a quality
pedigree (''The Practice''); undergoing a noble struggle against
profit-mongering networks (''Sports Night''); having a large
ensemble cast (''ER''); and creating new genres by mixing old ones
(''NYPD Blue''). They also tend to be writer-based (''Frasier''),
self-conscious (''Ally McBeal''), controversial (''Nothing
Sacred'') and realistic (''Law &AMP; Order'').
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't talk down to the viewer,'' but ``challenges them,''
she notes. ``And it appeals to the intellect and touches the
emotion. It provokes thought, and good characterization is
explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Manipulative writing is frowned upon, Swanson insists, and if it
focuses on the funny bone, it should do so by ``engaging the
intellect, the way ``Frasier'' does while illuminating the human
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   She's asked about the current talked-about drama ``Providence.''
``They call it a hit,'' says Swanson, ``but it's manipulative. I
don't respect it.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is where the line blurs, because audiences have
responded well to that series. ``I'm sure it's entertaining,'' she
says. ``But you can't compare `Providence' to `The Practice.'''
</P>
<P>
   Being entertaining needn't be part of the criteria.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict on two recently canceled series: the long-running
``Melrose Place'' on Fox _ no. ``Cupid,'' the new series on ABC _ a
yes, barely. ``It was interesting and unique,'' Swanson says of
``Cupid.'' ``It's soft around some of the edges. But it takes
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the requirements can't possibly be absolutes, like, for
instance, controversy, which would make ``The Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer'' quality TV. Same for big casts, which would
include the departed ``Mercy Point.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who consider VQT elitist snobs. Swanson has
heard the criticism. ``To me,'' she says, ``it's like picking up a
good book to read. It has to engage my attention. It has to be
worth my time. I have to be compelled to read it.''
</P>
<P>
   She understands that not everyone has similar requirements.
``And that's fine,'' she says. ``That's why we don't debate shows
that are not quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Which merely brings us back to what is.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to accept the term ``Quality TV'' on programs
sanctioned by critics or nonprofit organizations, yet harder to
admit that what's known as escapist TV _ the ``Melrose Places'' of
the world _ is just as integral a part of the tube's diverse menu.
</P>
<P>
   At times people crave catharsis, and at any intellectual price.
For that moment in time, perhaps, what they truly see is their
``quality.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
