<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAZZLED-PARENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S PERFECT, BUT YOU GOTTA LOVE HER ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHERINE NEWTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember the first time I learned of Her. It was at a party
for a little girl, who was turning 1, or maybe 2. As the
distinguished invited guests squirmed and drooled in the laps of
their mothers, we watched the birthday girl's mom peel the colorful
wrappings off the gifts and then hold them up, one by one, for us
to ``oooooh'' over.
</P>
<P>
   A pink sweater. A little white bunny. A Tonka truck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no!'' a voice cried out from the crowd. ``That was for the
other party this weekend!'' The words hung on the air for a moment,
awkwardly, until someone said what everyone else had apparently
been thinking, which was this: ``Oh, I'm so relieved!''
</P>
<P>
   I was confused, but everyone else laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Because they knew that She, the mother who had made the mistake,
was none other than the Perfect Mom.
</P>
<P>
   You know her. She may have a different name in your
neighborhood, but she's there. And she's busy. She's creating the
Yellow Brick Road in her living room for her 4-year-old's birthday
party. She's stitching Teletubby costumes for Halloween after
designing her own pattern. On her bookshelf are 10 three-ring
binders filled with photographic memories of her children's lives,
one for each year and all decorated with colorful suns and flowers
and soccer balls cut lovingly with pinking shears.
</P>
<P>
   She's never settled for Pop Tarts for breakfast. She never lets
her kids watch the Power Puff Girls, and, worse, they don't seem to
care. She honestly doesn't understand what you mean when you say
you can't get your children to keep all their Legos and Power
Rangers in separate bins.
</P>
<P>
   She's wonderful. Completely admirable.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we hate her.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years that have passed since I first saw Her, I've
glimpsed her from time to time, although I think she tries to hide.
Perhaps to protect herself from the inevitable wrath of the flawed
Every Mom, she has become the master of disguise. Sometimes She's
the blonde in the khakis selling school carnival tickets in the
car-pool line. Sometimes She's the redhead, who I hear reads to
groups in the school library on Fridays. Sometimes She's the one in
tennis shoes, on Sunday afternoon, pushing her child on the swing
as my kids and I drive by, munching burgers and fries from little
bags.
</P>
<P>
   I know She's out there, so I shouldn't have been surprised two
weeks ago, late on a school night, when a group of moms and I were
stuffing PTA raffle tickets into take-home envelopes, and suddenly
there She was, wearing the face of a woman I'd met several times
before.
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling came gradually, as our mom-chat turned to the
topic of books. She had read the latest Oprah selection. She had
read ``Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood.'' As far as I could
tell, She had, in fact, read the New York Times bestseller list and
She even had interesting opinions on all the titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when,'' asked one mom brave enough to pose the question on
all of our minds, ``do you ever have time to read?''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, we should have understood the reply. She said
it simply. She went to bed ``by 8:30 every night.''
</P>
<P>
   All hands stopped stuffing, and we turned to her as one. She had
three children. She had a job teaching at a preschool. How could
this be? we wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could this be?'' my friend Beth asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said She, ``what is there to do after 8?''
</P>
<P>
   It made no sense. What was there to do? What about cleaning up
the kitchen? Taking care of the laundry? Running out for more milk?
Paying the bills?
</P>
<P>
   The questions came fast and furious, but She answered with
aplomb, giving us a glimpse into a family Shangri-La that we could
only hope to comprehend. She lived in a land where kids helped with
the dishes. Kids put away their clothes. Kids made their own
lunches. The very thought that this could be happening in our
neighborhood and that we were missing it filled us with wonder _
and shame. It was all so terrible.
</P>
<P>
   And then it got worse. It turns out that Her kids eat
home-cooked meals every night. She makes a veal spaghetti sauce
that takes three days to cook. She prepares all her dinners for the
week on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of something called ``democracy.'' It's when everyone
gets to vote. They vote on what they want for dinner at the
beginning of the week, and She even has a daughter who loves
chicken tetrazzini and would have it every day of the month, but
she only gets it about once a month or it wouldn't be ``fair.''
</P>
<P>
   It was all too much for Beth and me. We began shaking our heads
in unison. Our own horrible ineptitude lay exposed before us like a
gaping wound.
</P>
<P>
   Another mom was unusually quiet. Finally, she spoke. Quietly,
and staring straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask my kids every night, `What do you want to eat?' All they
say is macaroni and cheese or pasta or spaghetti ... like they're
three different things.''
</P>
<P>
   I turned to Beth to see if she was empathizing with the pasta
mom as much as I was, but she had an odd, dreamy look on her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder,'' she mused, ``if my Ragu would taste better if I
cooked it for three days?''
</P>
<P>
   We laughed, but the message was clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Perfect Mom had inspired us. She'd touched us with her
Martha magic.
</P>
<P>
   She'd given us hope that maybe we could do something, anything,
to make our lives a little more perfect.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, she'd inspired us, as she always does.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why, I guess, we love her.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
