<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLERBEE-SPEAKS-OUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLERBEE SPEAKS FROM THE HEART ABOUT ALCOHOLISM, CANCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the past quarter-century, Linda Ellerbee has won just
about every award for TV journalism. Her candid descriptions of her
struggles with breast cancer and alcoholism have made Ellerbee one
of America's most in-demand public speakers. There is no way she
can satisfy all the demands on her time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ellerbee, currently serving as producer, writer and host of
``Nick News'' on cable TV's Nickelodeon network, said it was easy
to agree to speak at next month's 10th annual ``Stars in Recovery''
banquet in Fort Worth, benefiting the Tarrant Council on Alcoholism
&AMP; Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The call came from Texas; I'm a Texan, and anytime an
invitation comes from Texas, that helps,'' Ellerbee said in a
recent phone interview. ``If other people want to say that's
showing favoritism, fine. It is.''
</P>
<P>
   As with any Ellerbee TV commentary, her address, dealing with
her alcohol problems, will be blunt and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I particularly think that the stigma of being a woman
alcoholic is terrible in this country,'' Ellerbee said. ``Guys who
are alcoholics are often shown as sort of funny, but women with
drinking problems are always perceived as sad, awful things. So
women alcoholics are so often reluctant to speak out, to admit
their problem and seek help. When (former first lady) Betty Ford
spoke out, admitted what she faced and that she was brave enough to
face it, that gave me the courage some years later to go into
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Ellerbee can't find humor in the most desperate
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I thought it was hilarious, wonderful, when `Murphy
Brown' _ you know, the sitcom _ had Murphy coming out of alcoholism
treatment,'' she said. ``I think there's a lot of truth in sitcoms,
though, unlike Dan Quayle, I do know the difference between sitcoms
and real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Many celebrities moan about having their private lives endlessly
dissected in public, but Ellerbee has no regrets about everyone
knowing of her alcoholism and breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a conscious choice to be open about these things,'' she
said. ``With the alcoholism, I had Betty Ford's example. With
breast cancer, I wanted some time to think how to discuss it, but
`USA Today' outed me. Fine. In both cases, I didn't feel like
public interest was an intrusion. Everybody gets moments in life
when they've dealt with something bad, when you stand in front of
the mirror and it's just you having to ask yourself, `How will I
handle it?' My decision both times was to use my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In both instances, Ellerbee said: ``I immediately began getting
messages, letters from so many women all over the country. They
would tell me their stories, how they had coped, and that gave me
strength. So you can certainly say the gifts I got back from others
far outweighed my loss of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Tarrant Council on Alcoholism &AMP; Drug Abuse are
glad that privacy was less important to Ellerbee than providing a
good public example. And those who attend, Ellerbee promises, will
hear honest words, not fluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think that I'm showing any courage in talking about
alcoholism,'' she said. ``I'm coming because somebody feels I might
know what I'm talking about. Alcoholism is a daily struggle to keep
sober, and it's a struggle for me. It's always a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I will talk about it, because silence is not my way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
