   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ECON (Frankfurt) _ The German stock market soars in the
wake of Oskar Lafontaine's resignation at finance minister.
Chancellor Schroeder takes over as head of his party and names Hans
Eichel, the outgoing premier of Hesse and a ``low-key economics
expert'' as the new finance minister. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-EICHL (Frankfurt) _ Sidebar on Hans Eichl, new German
finance minister. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Dateline to kum) _ More fighting and refugee flight in
the troubled Yugoslav province. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL (United Nations) _ Developments on the
proposed tribunal for Khmer Rouge; Cambodia's foreign minister
meets with the U.N. secretary-general. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-ECON (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ Ecuador's president
announces tax increases, freeze on some bank deposits and other
measures to fight the economic crisis. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HOPE (Hope, Ark.) _ President Clinton returns to Hope to
attend a ceremony dedicating his birthplace, just days after the
Arkansas legislature refused to approve a bill providing $500,000
for its renovation. He then goes on to Texarkana for a dinner
honoring a Texas congressman. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno
testifes before the Senate Judiciary Committee. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-ASSESS (Washington ) A news analysis on Republicans and
what they're up to: Hoping to bury their image as the impeachment
party with substantive criticism of Clinton on foreign policy and
modest but concrete steps on the domestic side. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-WAR-GAMES (Carmel, Calif.) _ Less than 48 hours before
Pentagon war games were scheduled to begin in Monterey, the
California Coastal Commission has decided that migrating gray
whales and military hovercrafts may not mix. By Bill Staggs.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
16 points, or 0.2 percent, at 9,880. The Nasdaq index was off 46
points, or 1.9 percent. Elsewhere, shares jumped more than 5
percent in Frankfurt because of the Lafontaine resignation.
London's market was down 0.7 percent, following Wall Street.
Brazilian stocks were off 1.7 percent, and Mexican stocks were
little changed. Overnight, prices were flat in Tokyo and up 1.3
percent in Hong Kong. On the American debt market, the long bond
was up 7/32 point, with the yield at 5.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ A separate on credit market developments. By
Robert Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-TALKS (Undated) _ Oil ministers from five oil-producing
countries, meeting in the Netherlands, agree to cut supply by more
than 2 million barrels a day, or about 2.7 percent of world demand.
The accord among the five _ Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela, Algeria
and Mexico _ causes oil prices to jump more than 7 percent on world
markets. It is the latest in a flurry of attempts by producing
nations to boost oil prices, which fell to 12-year lows in December
but which already had been rising recently. The Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries will meet again in less than two
weeks. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   OIL-INFLATION (Undated) _ Will the latest attempt to boost oil
prices hold, and what might that mean for inflation? Story takes
into account other items in the day's news: Caterpillar's earnings
warning, the disappointing Japanese GDP numbers and the fall in the
U.S. producer price index. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS-TRUST (New York) _ Folo on the Bankers Trust bookkeeping
fraud in illegally diverting $19.1 million in unclaimed checks and
other credits owed to customers to the bank's own books to enhance
its financial performance. Plus a look at the corporate culture of
Bankers Trust. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   CATERPILLAR-OUTLOOK (Chicago) _ Caterpillar, citing slowing
machine sales to the agriculture, mining and energy industries, as
well as the economic mess in Latin America, says it expects profit
in the current quarter to be 50 percent below analysts' estimates.
It also says it will cut an unspecified number of jobs, and it will
temporarily shut some plants in Latin America, Europe and the
United States. Its shares fall as much as 8 percent. By David
Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Despite a surge in government spending that
was meant to trigger a recovery, Japan's economy shrank in 1998s
final quarter for a record fifth consecutive quarter. Gross
domestic product declined 0.8 percent from the prior three months,
or at an annual rate of 3.2 percent. In the year as a whole, GDP
contracted 2.8 percent, the biggest drop since the government began
tracking the data in 1955. Meanwhile, the central bank's board
votes to keep monetary policy unchanged, and the government
approves 7.5 trillion yen, or $63 billion, of investments in 15 of
the nation's biggest banks. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NISSAN (Tokyo) _ The Japanese Government again signals
that it will not allow Nissan to collapse. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see also GERMANY-ECON and ECUADOR-ECON, listed under
INTERNATIONAL.
</P>
<P>
   RJR-NABISCO (Undated) _ Developments in the breakup of RJR
Nabisco and the sale of its international tobacco operations. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MOODYS (New York) _ Folo on reports that the Justice Department
has ended its civil inquiry into Moody's ratings practices without
taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-MAGAZINES (Toronto) _ Canada's House of Commons may vote
today to approve legislation that would ban Canadians from
advertising in ``split-run'' magazines, which are sold as the
Canadian editions of American magazines but have little Canadian
elements. Canada's last attempt to ban split-runs was struck down
by the WTO. The U.S. is threatening to impose trade sanctions and
Canada is threatening counter-sanctions. By Kalyani Vittala.
</P>
