<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKOUT-DISCIPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY DISCIPLINES WORKERS OVER POWER OUTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Pacific Gas and Electric Co. has disciplined
employees blamed for a Dec. 8 incident that left parts of the San
Francisco area without electricity for up to six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Len Anderson, a spokesman for the utility, confirmed Thursday
that the disciplinary process had begun. He declined to specify how
many workers were affected or whether any had been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from non-utility sources say that PG&AMP;E suspended 14
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have cited two causes for the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   One was the failure of a PG&AMP;E crew to remove grounding wires it
had installed for its own protection while hooking up a new
transformer at a substation in suburban San Mateo. The other is
that an operator failed to switch on protective relays that would
have limited any problem with the new equipment to the substation.
</P>
<P>
   The oversights caused the San Mateo substation to shut down and
shut down two other regional substations, affecting business,
public transportation, hospitals and traffic signals.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the blackout has been estimated at up to $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said 4,400 customers have submitted damage claims and
that 3,000 have been paid by the utility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
