<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-NAZIS-HNS &LR;      03-12 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-NAZIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORE THE HEALTH NAZIS; LIVE FOR THE MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EVE PELL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Couch potatoes kind of like it when a fitness
advocate comes to an untimely end _ it gives them an argument to
use against those who preach at them to start jogging and renounce
hamburgers, smoking and beer.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't totally wrong. These days, many of us know of an
athlete who never smoked, ate a vegetarian diet, spent hours biking
or running, looked great and now is dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees,'' said my long-time running partner,
Margaret Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   She contracted lung cancer a year ago and has been given only a
few months to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``A healthy lifestyle gives you better odds, but the universe is
random. You can't count on anything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret, 50, never smoked. Apart from an occasional splurge
with me at a burger joint, she is a vegetarian, has no family
history of cancer and no predisposing factors anyone has
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret and I met at 7 a.m. every weekday for 11 years to run
the trails of Mount Tamalpais in Marin County. Six years ago, she
married a professor, moved across to Berkeley and continued to
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   In all her too-short life, she has spent as much of her time
outdoors as she could, immune to the ethos of accumulating
possessions and measuring success in dollars. She loves children,
poetry and photography. She earned a living by designing a catalog
of new-age classes and seminars. She took trips to Greece. She
traveled to Bosnia to help children orphaned by war.
</P>
<P>
   The actor George Burns smoked cigars every day of his adult life
and lived to be 100 _ twice her age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life isn't fair,'' my stepfather always said. I never liked
that message, but I have come to understand it a little better.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the grasshoppers, besides having more fun, get more
rewards than the ants, who have diligently labored and stored up
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, I do not follow the advice of the health
Nazis. I exercise, yes, but that is because I take pleasure in
moving my body around.
</P>
<P>
   And, because I'm competitive and vain, I enjoy winning races and
looking slim. People who know that I run a lot assume that I
subsist on salads, vitamins and all-natural substances. They are
horrified when I ask for a hamburger or unwrap a Milky Way _ two of
life's more delectable foods.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, they disapprove of the estrogen-replacement
hormones that I have taken for years.
</P>
<P>
   One is supposed to get through menopause with green tea and
banish hot flashes with herbs, they say. Well, maybe tea and herbs
work for some women _ more power to them _ but, if Esterase and
Premarin do the trick, I think that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   The point, as I see it, is to live well. If living well also
helps to live longer, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret said she is glad that she indulged her love of nature
and beauty, that she followed her heart, that she pursued
adventures when they came her way. She wanted more of life,
especially more years with Frank, her beloved husband.
</P>
<P>
   But she has lived with passion for the moment _ admiring the
colors of a wildflower or jumping into a lake or camping out on a
summer night with a friend. That example, rather than one of
renouncing pleasure in the hope of longevity, makes the most sense
to me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1436EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
