<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, March 13,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-OPENRECORDS _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes says the
Olympic records should be open, and that the state attorney general
should evaluate the request to open them. But Barnes says that's
about all he can do. (Pruitt/Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS _ Three top Olympic officials will escape
expulsion. Only the member from Western Samoa faces expulsion,
bringing the total to six. (Turner, Atlanta Jourtnal-Constitution).
16-18.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PALM BEACH POST SMUGGLING SERIES
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Palm Beach Post has a three-day package for Saturday,
March 13, Sunday, March 14, and Monday, March 15, on the business
of smuggling aliens; why the U.S. Border Patrol, the INS and the
federal court system cope poorly with it in Florida; and why
Florida employers are able to hire hundreds of thousands of illegal
workers each year. Here are the budget lines for the first day in
the series. Stories will move on the Cox wire Friday evening.
Graphics and photos will be available Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   PURSUIT _ WEST PALM, BEACH, Fla. _ Smuggling immigrants into
Florida is a money-making enterprise. It's becoming a booming
business as more and more immigrants find that paying smugglers
equipped with fast boats and high-tech gear improves their chances
of reaching the United States. Sometimes it goes wrong, as when 40
Haitians drowned between the Bahamas and Palm Beach County last
weekend. The Border Patrol is charged with the responsibility of
putting the alien smuggler out of business. But the Miami sector
has less than 60 agents to patrol its four-state region. The agency
hasn't seen an increase in its workforce in 10 years. During that
period, the U.S. Border Patrol has experienced dramatic growth,
doubling the number of agents to a force of nearly 8,000.
Unfortunately for the Miami sector, almost all of the thousands of
agents hired during the past few years have been assigned to Texas,
California, New Mexico and Arizona. For example: The Miami Sector
has 52 agents assigned; Laredo (Texas) has 638; El Paso has 9,752;
Tucson has 1,022; and San Diego has 2,257. Miami's budget is $6.2
million; San Diego is $178 million. (Kane, Palm Beach Post) 60
inches.
</P>
<P>
   WITH Charts on budget and manpower numbers.
</P>
<P>
   DAY _ Border Patrol Agent Larry Belotti works the graveyard
shift. He says he's the often the only Border Patrol agent working
from Corpus Christi, Texas, to Vermont. One recent night, he
rounded up 26 Cubans who came ashore in Miami Beach. This
effectively shuts down the Border Patrol station because Belotti
will spend the rest of the night processing these refugees. 30
inches. (Kane, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-REED _ LONDON _ A look at what the future hold for
Anglo-Dutch publishing giant Reed Elsevier after it disappointed
the stock market Thursday by issuing a gloomy outlook statement and
admitting it had still not secured a new chief executive after
seven months' searching. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-AID _ ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The first shipment of the
$400 million in food aid the United States promised to Russia
months ago to help its most troubled states make it through an
anticipated long, harsh winter will be unloaded from port here on
Friday _ at least three months late. Why? Developing. (Holmes, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CORRECTION _ WASHINGTON _ A correction for story slugged
CLINTON-TROOPS-0310 that moved Tues., March 9. (Christie, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BRYOSTATIN _ WASHINGTON _ The presence of a group of
single-celled animals called bryozoans in underwater sand just off
Fort Pierce, Fla., didn't matter to anybody until concern about the
animals' future caused a federal judge last week to temporarily
halt Corps of Engineers work to renourish the beach. However, to
one of the world's largest drug companies and a group of
scientist-divers who scour the ocean floor for substances that
might be converted into useful medicines, the word bryozoans stirs
excitement. Bryostatin, a drug derived from relatives of Fort
Pierce's sandy creatures, is being tested on human volunteers as a
possible new class of cancer drug, one that seems to act on
particularly stubborn forms of the disease. Some drug industry
analysts say it may have a market worth $1 billion a year if it is
ultimately licensed. Environmentalists fighting the beach
renourishment project say it is typical of the treasures that could
be destroyed forever if such projects are not undertaken with great
care for the environment. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Vice President lunches in Palm
Beach at an event hosted by Gore 2000. Then he flies to Miami to
meet with Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas and U.S. Rep. Carrie Meek
to discuss investing in distressed areas. (Crowley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   LIBBYDOLE _ ATLANTA _ Soon-to-be presidential explorer Elizabeth
Dole speaks to Atlanta Women's Network on their 25 anniversary
dinner. Says she will launch exploratory committee next week.
(Sanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-TRAFFIC _ LAREDO _ Laredo and its sister cities along the
Texas-Mexico border are lobbying the Legislature for relief as
their roads become gridlocked as their own booming populations go
bumper-to-bumper with commercial traffic that has grown
dramatically since the North American Free Trade Agreement took
effect five years ago. But to get what they want, border counties
will have to convince lawmakers to either divert transportation
money from other parts of Texas or dip into a budget surplus that
state leaders have all but promised to use for tax cuts and
education. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOPOKER _ HAMMOND, La. _ Because video poker was voted out of
almost half of Louisiana's parishes two years ago, the machines are
set to be unplugged this summer. But not without a fight. Some
small towns who see the machines as their lifeblood are fighting to
have a new vote. One parish is trying to annex some other town to
get its machines. This likely will be an issue in the legislature,
and already there is a court battle brewing with a May trial date
on whether the vote was legal in the first place. Real issue here
is, once you've let gambling in, how do you ask it to leave?
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
