<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     03-12 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING LESSONS FROM TRAGEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My sister Jo and I were in a rather passionate debate recently
over the wisdom of sending a 14-year-old to boot camp for taking
alcohol to school.
</P>
<P>
   I said the punishment was too harsh. Jo said she got what she
deserved. I said she wouldn't feel that way if it were Jana or
Jasmine (her daughters).
</P>
<P>
   She was suddenly quiet. And I was left with the words of an old
blues song playing in my head: ``if the shoe was on the other
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Our conversation ended there; but last week, while following the
Jasper hate-crime trial with the rest of the country, it occurred
to me that this is the sort of debate that could have been going on
between the families of James Byrd Jr. and John William King. But
in the nine months since King was accused in the dragging death of
Byrd, the families have been trying on the other's shoes, feeling
the other's pain.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to King's ailing father, Ronald King, just hours after
his son was convicted:
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to save my boy's life,'' he was quoted as saying
in one news report. ``I can understand (the Byrds) not wanting to.
If I was in their shoes, I'm sure I'd feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   And this from Clara Taylor, one of James Byrd's six sisters,
after King was sentenced to die: ``I remember reading once that
empathy is feeling your pain in my heart. If everyone felt this
way, there would be no need for the death penalty or jail cells,
because there would be no crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a simple thought, but Taylor is right. Much of the
confusion, the horror we live with in this life could be avoided
simply by applying the golden rule: Do unto others as you would
have them do unto you.
</P>
<P>
   And so I was struck by the Byrds' capacity to empathize with
Ronald King, knowing full well that his son was partly responsible
for James Byrd's death. (Two other defendants are awaiting trial.)
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that the Byrds aren't angry. They are. As a
son, father and brother, James Byrd Jr. left many grief-stricken
and confused relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should have to suffer and die the way my brother died,
but we have chosen not to let that anger control us,'' Taylor said
recently. ``That's why King did what he did. We don't want our
brother's legacy to be one of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, the family plans to start programs to
encourage and advance racial healing and education. In addition,
they will launch a campaign to heighten awareness of the
consequences of racial hatred, reduce the number of racially
motivated attacks and provide support to other victims of hate
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who preach racial healing, this is a good way to
help work for it. Donations to the effort may be made to the James
Byrd Jr. Foundation for Racial Healing by calling (888) 656-6414 or
by writing to the group in care of the First National Bank, Box
700, Jasper, TX 75951.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a community effort,'' said Taylor, ``with
political, religious and community leaders working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Diggles, executive director of the Deep East Texas
Council of Governments, is among those working with Taylor's
family. He said that if all goes according to plan, the foundation
will kick off the programs no later than June, the first
anniversary of James Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said that every man, woman and child should know who her
brother was and what happened to him so that it doesn't happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   She's right. There is much to be learned from this tragedy, not
the least of which is taking the time to wear someone else's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
