<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST IN SPACE CLICHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While it may be true that in space no one can hear you scream,
groaning should be a perfectly audible way of saying the
intergalactic alien-buster ``Wing Commander'' stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between ``Starship Troopers'' and ``Top Gun'' sits
director Chris Roberts' feature, which has neither the ambition nor
the budget to take the highway to the danger zone. Instead, it
threatens to take your breath away with a level of blandness unseen
since that last late-night Sci-Fi channel binge.
</P>
<P>
   What a run-of-the-mill mediocre space flick lacks in characters,
plot, integrity, credibility, structure, intelligence, legitimately
diverting entertainment value, acting, substance or vision is
usually recouped in the technical scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' looks like it was put together by people who
couldn't agree on whether or not the year 2564 would be colored
with red bulbs and fluorescent cafeteria lights or costumed as if
Urban Oufitters had gone to Uranus. Though, it's hard to tell _
actually, the only thing dimmer than the movie is the lighting by
the otherwise inimitable and elegant Thierry Arbogast (``The Fifth
Element.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' is based on the popular series of eponymous
computer games, and it's a shame each ticket doesn't come with a
joystick or a keypad that allows you to control the actions of
space rookie Christopher Blair (Freddie Prinze Jr.) and Maniac
(Matthew Lillard), his hotdog co-pilot. You could make them hook-up
with the ladies sooner and more frequently than they do.
</P>
<P>
   You could create more inspired stunt-banter like the
double-entendre-laced babble between Blair and Devereux (Saffron
Burrows), his British wing commander.
</P>
<P>
   Were you to grow irritated watching Euro actors with
impenetrable accents _ apparently Prinze Jr. and Lillard are the
only Americans allowed in outer space, and even they sound foreign
_ you could pretend you're a lackey at any ad agency and overuse
that cool time-slicing special effect that freezes people and
objects in midair while the camera rotates around them. With the
press of a button you could make a subtitles request since the film
has a cast so deliberately international and grouchy you suspect
you've wandered into the United Nations before lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The aliens in question look like they've been designed by the
folks who created the goofy pests that irked the Power Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   And it's saying a lot about a movie's lethargic atmosphere when
even Lillard looks sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   This latest youthquake hellbent on giving kids their own
``Dangerous Liaisons'' and their umpteenth ``Pygmalion'' has now
provided them with another knock-off they didn't know they wanted:
their very own ``Battlestar Galactica.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1456EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-AID-0313-COX     03-12 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-AID-0313-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WINTER AID ARRIVES FROM U.S. -- IN TIME FOR SPRING
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ The first shipment of U.S. food aid
intended to help Russia through its long winter was unloaded Friday
at the port of St. Petersburg -- just in time for spring.
</P>
<P>
   After months of delays, the initial delivery of nearly $1
billion in food aid pledged by the United States landed as 48 cargo
containers full of crop seeds for Russian farmers were off-loaded
from a cargo ship.
</P>
<P>
   Better late than never, said Russian officials who insist the
aid still is badly needed. The American offer of food aid came
after the onset of Russia's economic crisis in August, followed by
its worst grain harvest in 40 years and predictions of an
exceptionally harsh winter.
</P>
<P>
   The months-long lag in delivery was the result of American
demands for assurances that the food assistance would not be
hijacked by corrupt Russian officials and criminal-infested
food-distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States in coming months will supply Russia with more
than 3 million tons of food supplies, mainly wheat and other
grains. Another 100,000 tons of food will be provided to the Red
Cross and other private relief organizations working in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   American and Russian officials presided over the unloading at a
ceremony at the icy St. Petersburg port, nearly six months after
the U.S. government first offered its food assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman billed
the aid as ``good news for the Russian people who might otherwise
face the possibility of food shortages this winter and it is good
news for America's farmers and ranchers, who are facing economic
hardships related to large supplies and low prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedious negotiations followed as U.S. officials sought
assurances that the aid would not be misused in Russia's
notoriously corrupt market system. American officials also had to
convince the Russian government that it should not be charged
customs duties on the aid being donated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the Russian government will sell the food
to regional wholesalers at prevailing market prices. Proceeds from
the sale must be deposited in Russia's state pension fund, which is
more than $1.5 billion in the red.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ambassador to Russia, James Collins, downplayed the
late arrival of the aid. He said it would offer important support
for Russia just as their stocks of grain and other supplies are
running low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of helping Russia through its winter; it's
helping it through the agricultural year,'' Collins told reporters
Friday. ``The real issue is to make sure that adequate supplies are
available until the next harvest starts and that's in the fall or
the late summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say it will be virtually impossible for the U.S.
government, and the European Union, which will deliver its own $500
million food-aid package, to monitor the aid once it reaches Russia
and is distributed to the provinces.
</P>
<P>
   A previous American food-aid program in 1992 was tainted by
reports of widespread corruption among Russian food-trading
companies and government officials who profited from the sale of
donated grain. U.S. officials later said that problems were never
documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am highly suspicious of this plan if the main purpose is to
get the food to the people who need it,'' said Peter Westin,
analyst with the Russian-European Center for Economic Policy in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But both U.S. and Russian officials said distribution of the aid
would be closely monitored by a joint committee and all Russian
records must be readily available to American observers.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The United States can halt the aid shipments at any time should
problems arise. But Collins said he was confident that the aid will
reach the markets and people who need it most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we've got a system in place that is pretty
straightforward and insures that this stuff goes where it is
intended. It is not rocket science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.S. deal, Russia will receive 1.7 million tons of
wheat and 30,000 tons of dried milk as outright aid and another 1.3
million tons of soybeans, corn, beef and poultry to be purchased by
Russia using a low-interest U.S. loan. American farmers will be
paid full market value for their goods, but Russia will only have
to pay back about one-quarter of the value under the terms of the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment unloaded Friday of 1,000 tons of seeds for green
peas is part of 15,000 tons of corn and vegetable seeds to be given
to Russia. The seeds will be sold to farmers in the northern
Caucuses region, on Russia's southern border, which suffered
droughts last summer. Russian agriculture officials warned Friday
that the country faces a shortfall of as much as 1.3 million tons
of grain seeds needed for spring sowing.
</P>
<P>
   Westin and others contend that distribution of food, not
supplies, is Russia's biggest problem. While food shortages have
been reported in isolated Russian towns above the Arctic Circle and
in distant Siberia, Russia exported more than 2 million tons of
wheat last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really looking at a small and sporadic food-shortage
problem. It's more a transportation problem,'' Westin said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
