<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8168 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOCK-HNS &LR;      03-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITON'S FIRST FILM PORTENDS IMMENSE PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE GANAHL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I doubt that next March, the creators of ``Lock, Stock and Two
Smoking Barrels'' will be standing on the podium at Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion. This film is to ``Shakespeare in Love'' what
Green Day is to the San Francisco Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Flawed but scrappy, confusing yet exhilarating, the British-made
``Lock, Stock'' is far from a perfect movie. And it's not for
anyone squeamish about violence. But it is, like Green Day, a
rockin' good time.
</P>
<P>
   With a fine ensemble cast peopled with half-wits and brutes
going by names like Hatchet Harry and Barry the Baptist, ``Lock,
Stock'' is a dark-hearted crime comedy set in London's East End _ a
place that can't be in too many tourist guides. The cast moves
about in gangs, double-crossing each other, stealing, breaking
legs. Male-bonding stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of characters to actually care about, ``Lock,
Stock'' works beautifully as an exercise in joyful anarchy, an
unsentimental roller-coaster ride that is both violent and funny.
Imagine ``A Hard Day's Night'' directed by Quentin Tarantino.
</P>
<P>
   Director Guy Ritchie, 30, will inevitably be compared to
Tarantino (for ``Reservoir Dogs'') or Danny Boyle (for ``Shallow
Grave'' and ``Trainspotting''), but those filmmakers are all about
the drama, with mere dollops of humor thrown in. ``Lock, Stock'' is
comfortable going for the belly laugh _ lots of them in fact. And
the violence, while always nerve-wrackingly possible, is more
implied than graphically depicted.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun of the film is trying to figure out who _ if
anyone _ will be left standing.
</P>
<P>
   The complex plot revolves around a quartet of young
ne'er-do-wells _ Eddy, Bacon, Tom and Soap, all played by virtual
unknown actors _ who plot to make some money by pooling their
resources and giving it to Eddy, who is a well-known card shark.
</P>
<P>
   He enters a high-stakes game with porn king/gangster Hatchet
Harry (P.H. Moriarty), and things go dreadfully wrong. Instead of
winning, Eddy winds up losing in a fixed game, and owing the
gangster nearly half a million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Harry's true goal is to take over the bar run
by Eddy's dad, J.D. (played smartly in a small role by Sting, whose
wife, Trudie Styler, was executive producer of the film). So now
Eddy's not just in danger of losing his life, his dad is ready to
take him to the woodshed.
</P>
<P>
   To get their money back, and avoid having their legs broken by
Harry's henchmen (one of whom is played with surprising alacrity by
English soccer star Vinnie Jones), there isn't much the foursome
wouldn't do. That includes breaking the law: beating a rival gang
to the punch on a heist of both money and plants from hydroponic
marijuana farmers.
</P>
<P>
   After a hail of bullets and high-fives all around, the gang
discovers they have inadvertently also made off with some antique
rifles highly coveted by Harry. It gets _ if you can imagine _ more
complicated from there.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie as both writer and director shows a dazzling talent for
creative camera work, clever plot twists and Cockney dialogue _
although some of that is nearly incomprehensible to Yankee ears (a
portion is even subtitled). Made for a mere $1.6 million, it's
refreshing to see a film that excites without special effects.
</P>
<P>
   But as exhilarating as it is, the galloping pace and cumbersome
number of players start to wear thin towards the end.
</P>
<P>
   The short-attention-span direction could be due to Ritchie's
previous experience as a director of music videos (this is his
first film). But give this kid another great script, a few bucks
and a smaller cast, and there's no telling what he can do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
