<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-LIGHTNING-$AD     03-12 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-LIGHTNING-$ADV15-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING SIMPLY ISN'T MY FORTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we enter the spring storm season, I find it reassuring to
know there are scientists dedicating at least part of their
professional lives to the study of lightning, which is the weather
phenomenon that most strikes fear in my otherwise fearless heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Well, fearless except for all the other stuff that scares the
pazooties off me.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have never been struck by lightning, I'm pleased to disclose,
despite what you may have heard about how that is what made me this
much off plumb. And yet I've always had a healthy respect for its
killer nature. In fact, when my children were small and were scared
by a storm in the night, I was perfectly willing to let them get
under the bed with me. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most people, certain fears are silly and inappropriate, such
as the fear of being bitten by a rhinoceros. (Well, unless you try
to steal his or her dinner.) But some things deserve to be feared,
and, as I say, I rank lightning high up on that list, even slightly
above Jerry Springer's TV show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So I was pleased to read recently about scientists from the U.S.
Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory who are
studying the electrodynamic processes of lightning. I have no idea
what they mean by electrodynamic processes, but it sounds exactly
like the sort of complicated matter that scientists should worry
about so you and I don't have to. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These researchers are reported to be examining measurements of
millions of lightning bolts recorded by a radio receiver aboard a
satellite known as FORTE. Those initials stand for Fast On-orbit
Recording of Transient Events, and despite what that sounds like it
has nothing to do with Monica Lewinsky or Linda Tripp. And I, for
one, am monstrously glad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This is an aside that I give you permission to skip: Did you
know Lewinsky said recently she was thinking about going to law
school? I bet some social scientist could get a lucrative
government grant to study the admissions policy of any school that
would let her in.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The radio receiver on the FORTE satellite is pretty high tech.
Radio signals associated with lightning last less than one
thousandth of a second, so, FORTE scientists say, the receiver can
make a recording and reset its trigger almost instantaneously. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I know lightning is a visible discharge of atmospheric
electricity, but I never thought about it flashing out radio
signals. It strikes me, however, that a radio signal lasting one
thousandth of a second would deliver as much of the Rush Limbaugh
show as I usually can enjoy at one sitting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the FORTE satellite was developed to detect
nuclear detonations and help slow the spread of nuclear weapons.
But Los Alamos physicist Abe Jacobson, who heads the FORTE team,
says lightning ``is of interest to Los Alamos' national security
missions because there is a parallel between the spectrum of
lightning emissions and the electromagnetic pulse created by a
nuclear weapon detonation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See? I'm not crazy to be scared of lightning. It apparently is
sort of like nature's own nuclear arsenal. Yikes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of its orbit, the FORTE satellite makes several passes a
day over South America, Africa and Southeast Asia. But how much
different can killer lightning be in those locations than it is in
the Midwest, where I live and do my best to avoid getting zapped by
bolts from the scary spring sky? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that lightning bolts are like the previously
mentioned Jerry Springer TV show. If you've seen one you've pretty
much seen 'em all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Monday, March 15, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
