<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-CO     03-12 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The voices of vouchers
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The readers write ...
</P>
<P>
   A recent column opposing school vouchers produced _ or provoked,
as the case may be _ an outpouring of e-mail. Here's a sampling
from here, there and yonder:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Every citizen has an investment in public education. Both my
children attended church schools and public schools at different
times in their life. Not all public schools are bad schools. My
disappointments were with the church schools, not the public
school.'' Sheila M. Hopkins, Ohio, sheila.m.hopkins(at)bge.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Education (in public schools) fails miserably. The current
liberal cure is to reduce class size. That ain't the problem. When
we were in school (in the 1950s) classes were larger than they are
now, but we had quality teachers who had, and gave, quality
education. Vouchers make competition. Competition improves
organizations, or they die.'' Thomas W. Moore, Houston,
tmoore(at)pyramid3.net.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vouchers have been a threat to public education for the
state of Michigan for many years now, thanks to Gov. John. M.
Engler, and continue to threaten the nation as a whole. This is a
'quiet issue' that would have devastating consequences to our
future, our children, should it sneak its way through the national
agenda.'' _ Kathleen Tabor, ktabor(at)mstv.org.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Government is not a restaurant where services are a la
carte. It is a system whereby what is best for the group as a whole
is, in theory at least, the choice that is made. Some, such as
public schools or drinking water, we may choose not to use. But
either way, government has decided that the majority of its
citizens benefit by having that service available.'' David Sattler,
falcon4(at)home.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We are opposed to school vouchers because it will destroy
the public schools. We are in favor of public schools for the
education of all our children.'' Mr. and Mrs. Byrd Harris, Corpus
Christi, Texas, whubler(at)trip.net.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Times, kids, schools and staff have changed, clearly not for
the better. What worked in the past doesn't necessarily work today.
I'm confident the Cleveland, Ohio, schools are not as strong today
as was the case 50 years ago when I attended. Clearly, change is
necessary in most parts of the country.'' Dean Webster,
dwebster01(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You may be right. But for a different reason. Once the
government got its hands on the private schools it would probably
try to teach the same crud it has forced on the public schools. So
I would urge all private and religious schools to be very careful
about taking any government money!'' Douglas B. Doty, Forest Hill,
Md., doty(at)magnus.net.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It's amazing to me that the people who crow the most about
traditional values and have the least patience for
multi-culturalism are so eager to carve society up into a buch of
splinter groups. I've read that the voucher movement got its start
after the Brown vs. Board of Education case that desegregated the
public schools. Though the voucher idea strains for credibility, it
has a bad pedigree.'' Daniel Rosen, sed(at)toad.net.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What has contributed the most to democracy in America from
its conception has been freedom of choice, not the public school
system. This is a phrase, freedom of choice, that liberals love to
use when it applies to issues they're concerned with, but not when
it comes to how parents choose to the educate their children.''
Catherine Matthews, Baltimore, Md., eastmatthews(at)juno.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It is my opinion, based on what I've observed in the public
schools I've worked in and subbed in, that allowing vouchers would
further delineate the 'haves' and the 'have nots.' While a voucher
of $1,500 a year, for example, might nicely ease the burden placed
upon a middle-class family whose child attends private school, this
may not be enough to make it possible for a lower-income child to
attend the same school. The additional $500 or more that the
lower-income parents might have to pay from their own pockets could
be an insurmountable cost.'' Kathy Fink, kdkgfink(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The address is jmurray(at)lcc.net for e-mail and P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915, for snail mail. I respond to all
correspondence and read most of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
