<HEADER>
A8245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATH-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      03-12 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATH-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATH EMERGES BLINKING INTO THE GLARE OF THE POP WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ When more than a hundred mathematicians from
around the world gathered at the Institute for Advanced Studies
here recently to discuss the work of the French-born mathematician
Andre Weil, no one even mentioned his one achievement that has
affected tens of thousands of people, most of whom have never heard
of him.
</P>
<P>
   Weil, who died in August 1998, was possibly one of the greatest
mathematicians of his age, making fundamental discoveries in number
theory, laying the basis for algebraic geometry and searching for
what he called a Rosetta stone that would establish the unity of
all branches of mathematics. But Weil was not interested in the
utility of his discoveries. ``If you asked Andre to justify
mathematics, he would say that was like trying to explain a
symphony to a deaf person,'' said Armand Borel, a Swiss
mathematician.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Weil's math has had one significant practical consequence.
It helped create the boom in sales of popular books about
mathematics since 1994. That was when a young British mathematician
named Andrew Wiles made headlines around the world by using an idea
developed by Weil and two Japanese mathematicians to solve the most
famous mathematical conundrum in history, Fermat's last theorem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular science books had been doing well for some time, but
after Wiles solved Fermat's theorem the focus swung to
mathematics,'' said George Gibson, president of Walker &AMP; Co., which
publishes the American edition of a best-selling book about Wiles'
work called ``Fermat's Enigma: The Quest to Solve the World's
Greatest Mathematical Problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are good stories in math no one has told,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Princeton University press followed up a 1994 book
about the mathematical idea known as ``e'' (the base for natural
logarithms) with a book about the imaginary number ``i'' (the
square root of minus 1), a book of ``adventures in applied
mathematics'' and another on the role of computers in math. Another
book, published this month by Paulo Ribenboim, includes an account
of the mathematical strategy Wiles used to prove the theorem,
written for the layman.
</P>
<P>
   And no less than three American writers are working on popular
books about the concept of zero.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in the February issue of the Notices of the
American Mathematical Society, the country's leading mathematics
journal, says ``the present time is a `golden age' for
popularizations of mathematics,'' noting that ``in the past couple
of years one finds that a large number of well-received popular
books on mathematics have appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   To encourage the new interest in mathematics, the society is
``establishing a public relations effort to help reporters find out
about stories in mathematics.''
</P>
<P>
   It includes a Web site called What's New in Mathematics at
www.ams.org/new-in-math/.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been very striking,'' said Ian Stewart, a British
mathematician at Warwick University who has written 10 popular math
books. ``I used to approach publishers. Now they come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Peter Tallack of Weidenfeld &AMP; Nicolson, a London
firm that has published several popular math works, such books give
readers ``the illusion they are mastering complicated ideas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
