<HEADLINE>
MADALYN MURRAY O'HAIR'S DIARIES ATTRACT FEW BIDDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ After only four modest bids, the diaries of
vanished atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair will soon be sold as part of
the ongoing liquidation of her estate.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Ingalls, the court-appointed trustee of the estate, has
asked a federal bankruptcy court for a hearing to approve the sale
of the diaries to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest bid to date is from Stanley Main in the amount of
$6,500 cash,'' wrote Ingalls, who said additional bids are still
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls said only four offers were received for O'Hair's diaries
that span more than four decades, with several lengthy gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of personally disappointed. I thought the diaries are
real interesting, and I thought they would have commanded a
price,'' Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   The other bids ranged from $3,000 by the University of Texas to
$5,000 bids by the American Atheists organization, which O'Hair
founded three decades ago, and by the Council for Secular Humanism.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls said that Main, of Austin, Texas, didn't indicate why he
is interested in buying the hand-written journals of O`Hair, who
once described herself as ``America's most-hated woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to look. He didn't indicate he was involved with any
organization. He made an offer. That's about all I can say,''
Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   Main did not return a telephone call Friday asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls said the hearing on the sale will probably be next
month.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeds will be applied against more than $260,000 in
creditors' claims filed against O'Hair's estate. The biggest
creditor is the Internal Revenue Service, seeking unpaid taxes and
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the diaries do not pull a higher bid, O'Hair's assets
total less than $20,000, Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, then 76, and her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin
Murray O'Hair disappeared from Austin in late 1995. They spent
approximately a month in San Antonio and then vanished, along with
$500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   Theories about their disappearance range from kidnapping and
murder to a self-imposed foreign exile with funds skimmed from
their atheist organizations. The FBI and several police agencies
are currently investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls said he is still hopeful that other offers will come.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
