<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-MASSAGE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HORSEWOMAN DELIVERS HEALING MASSAGES TO EQUINE CLIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TIM TESCONI   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETALUMA, Calif. _ The client is a big, horsey kind of gal
suffering trauma to her back and hips from a lifetime of
high-stepping.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to her relief is masseuse Dianne Magliulo whose hands and
fingers rub away years of tension as they squeeze and manipulate
tight, sore muscles during a 1 1/2-hour session.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just loves this,'' said Magliulo, running her hands over
knotted muscles along the broad back.
</P>
<P>
   The client, a 14-year-old thoroughbred named Impress, seems to
relish the massage, stretching, licking and lowering her head _ all
signs of equine contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's animated now,'' said Impress's trainer John Stanley of
Petaluma. ``She's more receptive to everything because she's
feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the $65 massage _ Impress's third in the last two months
_ has improved her disposition, stamina and physical condition.
She's acting more like a filly than an irritable old mare.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, a former cowboy and athletic coach who now trains and
boards horses on his Petaluma ranch, said Impress was an
award-winning jumper whose muscles and tendons had become stressed
and sore from years of hoof-pounding jumps in show arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Impress' ailments weren't something a veterinarian could treat,
said Stanley. But it was clear she needed something to make her
feel better so she would be more sociable with the other horses on
his ranch.
</P>
<P>
   He called Magliulo, a Penngrove horsewoman certified in equine
sports massage, a growing field in horse care.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more horse people, both lay and professionals, are
recognizing the benefits of deep tissue therapy,'' said Magliulo,
46.
</P>
<P>
   She became certified seven months ago after completing training
at Equinology, a school operated by Debranne Patillo of Windsor.
People from throughout the world come to the Sonoma County school
to learn equine massage therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Magliulo said horses get stiff, tight and sore just like people
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses are tremendous athletes. Approximately 60 percent a
horse's body is muscle and just like humans, a horse's muscles get
overstressed and overused,'' Magliulo said. She said massaging a
horse was as much intuition as physical touch, knowing when to
apply pressure and when to ease off.
</P>
<P>
   For an old cowboy like Stanley, it's just plain old horse sense
that muscles _ whether human or horse _ sometimes need a healing
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horse massage is widely used today. It's no longer fringe and
even when it was there were horse owners who were using it and
didn't make it known,'' said the longtime trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Magliulo, a horse enthusiast all of her life, didn't own her
first horse until seven years ago. She believes she has found her
life's calling as an equine masseuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love horses so much. This is a way for me to give
something back to horses who give so much to us without ever asking
anything in return,'' said Magliulo, who works part time in the
family real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   She admits she is more passionate about horses than real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I do is gain the horse's trust,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She starts with the muscles in the nose and ends more than an
hour later by firmly pulling the horse's tail.
</P>
<P>
   When her hands go over a muscle that is tight or sore Impress
stiffens and lifts a leg. Once the kink is worked out, the horse
relaxes again.
</P>
<P>
   Magliulo said the work was as therapeutic for her as it was for
the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``After massaging a horse I feel so pumped up. I feel I have
done something to make them feel better and that's a good
feeling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Tesconi writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
