LEGOLAND-PARK (Los Angeles) _ LEGOLAND, opening later this month in
Carlsbad, has 128 acres of interactive attractions, family rides,
shows and miniature streets and landmarks built out of _ what else?
_ LEGO blocks. (Runs with sidebar slugged LEGOLAND-HIGHLIGHTS). By
Nancy Hewitt. 
 
 
DIGITAL-LA (Los Angeles) _ Steve Zehngut, the former San Fernando
Valley boy turned Web game guru, sort of stumbled into business
creating Web-based games for big-name corporate clients. By David
Bloom. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN     03-12 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES FOR INTERNET GAMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Note use of italics in 2nd graf)  
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Staple-shooting copiers. Career-building
production assistants navigating a busy backlot with a cup of
coffee. A taco maker fending off roaches.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALS)This (END ITALS) is the future of Internet gaming?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe, in the twisted but affable inventions of Steve
Zehngut, a former San Fernando Valley boy turned Web game guru.
Zehngut sort of stumbled into business creating Web-based games
particularly for the sites of big corporate clients, such as
Toshiba and Bugle Boy clothing.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating with a radio, TV and film degree from
California State University, Northridge, Zehngut found he didn't
much like the people he worked with in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But the folks in multimedia were different.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would answer their own phones and talk your ear off,''
Zehngut said. And Zehngut had played a lot of games growing up,
beginning with the Atari 2600 and on every major platform since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all these games, shoeboxes of them,'' Zehngut said. ``I
definitely grew up on games.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining his gaming interests, film training and new-found Web
opportunities, Zehngut eventually started Zeek Interactive (at
www.zeek.com where you can try out all of his company's game
sites), moving it recently from Santa Monica to Seal Beach.
</P>
<P>
   His company is one of the few to use Macromedia's powerful but
complex Flash technology to create online games. Flash creates
files that are small enough to load quickly into a Web browser, but
involving enough to captivate a user for an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is to find the cinematic elements in 100 or 150k
(kilobyte-sized game files),'' Zehngut said. ``That's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Zeek's first big breaks came when Toshiba asked him to
create a game for its Web site devoted to a line of copiers. The
result was a wacky game where paper wads and staples fired by the
copiers fight off marauding co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of other work has followed, most recently with a deal
with the Fox Family Network to create game sites for 10 of the
cable channel's shows. He also helped create and co-publish a pair
of CD-ROMS with former employer ADout in Van Nuys that use games to
train people how to use major Mac and PC programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my parents and parents of friends said, `Why are
you wasting your time playing games?' '' Zehngut said. ``But it
turned out to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THEY'RE DRAWN THAT WAY: With Cartoon Network Online, we finally
have a Web site that does what it says it does: put cartoons on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The online spinoff of the cable channel devoted to animation has
started what it calls Webtoons, creating series of animated
adventures that will debut online. If there's enough response,
they'll migrate the characters to full-fledged TV shows, said Sam
Register, the site's vice president and creative director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use this as a laboratory, to test new characters,
new styles, new episodes,'' said Register. ``The Web is the
Nielsens (TV rating service) on steroids. Hopefully we'll see right
off the bat what people are buzzing about. And if something is
buzzing, maybe we'll make another Webtoon, or maybe we'll go right
to TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But Register said Webtoons will take advantage of the Net's
nonlinear nature to add features that can't be replicated on TV,
such as branching narratives that change the story line, depending
on where you click.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, it remains to be seen what will be the standard''
for Web-based cartooning, Register said. ``We are learning so much
about what's working interactively and what's not working. We're
just looking to see how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two sets of Webtoons are already up. One, from
Emmy-winning Gary Panter, is called ``Pink Donkey and the Fly,''
and follows the misadventures of an insect infatuated with, yes, a
pink donkey. The other, ``B. Happy,'' stars a less-than-gleeful
bluebird of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up soon will be a series of shorts based on the old
Hanna-Barbera Studios live-action children's show, ``The Banana
Splits,'' Register said. And expect lots more of the classic, but
visually simple Hanna-Barbera cartoons to start appearing on the
online site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about the H-B library is they made (the
original cartoons) cheap for TV, so many of the characters hardly
animate,'' Register said. ``It's like H-B was pre-purposed for the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of places doing animation on the Web in
substantial amounts already, Register acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Wired, for instance, started an animation section a few
months ago. And Shock Rave, the showcase site for developers using
Macromedia's Flash and Director software, also features some fun
stuff in its regularly changing galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing it, but the difference is the expertise in
making animation,'' Register said. ``They're technology people, not
animation people. And that's where you really see it. I have a
whole network of people who will tell me if it sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   To check out the site, go to www.cartoonnetwork.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THEY'VE GOT GAME: The techno-fanatics at Digital Home Entertainment
Magazine dreamed up a particularly fun little exercise recently:
designing the ultimate computer gaming system. The results,
detailed in their winter 1999 issue:
</P>
<P>
   _ An IBM Aptiva SE7 computer, a sleek black beauty housing a 450
Mhz Pentium II brain, a whopping 16.8 Gb hard drive, and an equally
eye-popping 128 Mb of memory. The machine, with a 56-kpbs modem,
respectable ATI Rage Pro Turbo graphics card and DVD-ROM player,
make the SE7 enough computer even for most gamers. But wait,
there's a lot more to this dream system:
</P>
<P>
   _ Creative Labs SoundBlaster Live! sound card, to take the
increasingly sophisticated audio from games and create
three-dimensional sound;
</P>
<P>
   _ Cambridge SoundWorks Desktop Theater 5.1 speaker system, to
reproduce that movielike sound;
</P>
<P>
   _ Intensor Sensory Gaming Chair, literally a chair that vibrates
with the explosions and impacts of your game. You'll be wrung out
from this after a few hours;
</P>
<P>
   _ Union Reality UR Gear Headset, to allow you to do
voice-activated control of games;
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft Sidewinder Freestyle Pro controller, a very cool
batwing that uses internal sensors to help steer, so you focus on
the shooting buttons and other actions;
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft Sidewinder Force Feedback Pro Joystick, to give you
the feel of a tire blowout in a racing game, or the recoil of a
weapon in that first-person action shooter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Panasonic CT36VG50 36-inch SVGA monitor/TV, a massive hybrid
TV and computer monitor that's also ready to accept HDTV signals if
you want to splurge on a decoder box;
</P>
<P>
   _ Monster 3D II Model X100 Video Accelerator Board, to push
polygons onto the monitor at eye-popping rates. For good measure,
the dream system uses two of these cards working in tandem;
</P>
<P>
   _ JAM!! videogame console connector, to allow you to hook up
PlayStation, Nintendo and Sega games to your dream system (works
with Macintoshes also).
</P>
<P>
   Total cost of this particular fantasy? A mere $7,090. Not too
bad, and the Monster video card even comes with a couple of games
to get you started. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
