<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ORANGE-SHORTAGE-A     03-12 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ORANGE-SHORTAGE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA ORANGE CROP DOWN MORE THAN 20 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW SAUER   
 The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ True to federal predictions issued in October,
Florida's orange crop is down more than 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the drop has brought a 10 percent increase in
prices. For Bill Ferrari, vice president of procurement for
Tropicana, the drop has yielded a challenging season.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Florida's orange crop is used in juices. To meet his
company's needs, Ferrari must arrange to buy about 25 percent of
this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari remembers well Oct. 9, when the U.S. Department of
Agriculture predicted this season's crop would drop 22 percent to
190 million 90-pound boxes, which is the standard of measure in the
citrus industry. The 1997-98 season produced 244 million 90-pound
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the USDA released updated figures that put the
orange crop at 192 million 90-pound boxes. That figure shows how
accurate the department has become with its predictions issued each
October.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari said when one of his procurement workers brought him the
number in October, he had trouble believing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She brought the number in on a piece of paper to look at,''
Ferrari said. ``I thought, `This is the early-mid-crop estimate.
Where's the rest of the crop?' She says, `No, no, this is the
number.' I stared at it and I literally waited until I got a second
confirmation before I sent ... e-mail out to the whole company. I
later apologized to her for not believing her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana, a unit of PepsiCo Inc., has adjusted accordingly,
increasing the fruit and juice it purchases from outside of its
traditional 250 suppliers and, like its competitor, Coca Cola
Co.-owned Minute Maid, raising prices 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The average supermarket price of orange juice, as of
mid-February, was $4.26 per gallon, the highest it has been in
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The crop shortage has been worse than any freeze. But such are
the vagaries of procuring fruit for one of the world's largest
juice makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we had the largest _ not percentage wise _ but the
largest absolute volume drop in boxes,'' Ferrari says. ``When
you're faced with that and you're as reliant on the Florida crop as
we are for your product, you can't go to an offshore source.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a challenge this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana, which is based in Bradenton, has a procurement
department of about 20 employees, including 14 field workers who
work directly with growers. Ferrari, 45, has held his procurement
job for about nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The field workers determine daily how many loads of fruit are
needed for Tropicana, which has major plants in Bradenton and Fort
Pierce. They also test and document crops, using a 3-year-old
database.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their jobs have changed over the years,'' Ferrari says. ``They
will already start sampling and testing next year's crop probably a
month after this one is over. We try to get an early start on being
able to predict what that next year's fruit crop will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   That helps Tropicana's plant managers know how to use stored
juice to maintain a consistent quality.
</P>
<P>
   The number of field workers has shrunk as the citrus industry
has moved south and consolidated. The company had nearly 30 such
jobs in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Three of today's workers replaced their retiring fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of field reps were born and raised in the areas they're
working with, so they know a lot of these growers,'' Ferrari says.
``They went to school with them and played with them as kids.
That's an important part of our area, the relationships built up
with the growers. It helps get through the difficult times.''
</P>
<P>
   When Anthony Rossi, Tropicana's founder, picked the Bradenton
and Fort Pierce plant sites, some in the citrus industry thought it
odd.
</P>
<P>
   But Rossi proved prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's citrus belt has moved south after devastating freezes,
putting Rossi's plants in the thick of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came down in '82, Orlando was kind of the center of the
industry. Our two plants were considered way south,'' Ferrari says.
``Now, our two plants, which are almost directly across from one
another, are right in the middle ... You couldn't have picked
better locations.''
</P>
<P>
   Some growers have been with Tropicana for more than 30 years.
Their citrus holdings range in size from five acres to 40,000
acres.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, with a boom in plantings, Tropicana bought
about 20 million boxes of fruit each year from about 700 growers.
While it now buys more than twice the number of boxes, its base of
growers has shrunk to about 250 with the consolidation of the
growing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana often buys all of a grower's crop.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts set a floor price and generally run from three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Tropicana will offer longer contracts to try to
encourage growers to plant. The stability of a 10- or 15-year
contract gives a grower better borrowing leverage with banks. It
can often take five years just to get any cash flow from a grove,
Ferrari says.
</P>
<P>
   Tropicana has encouraged growers to plant more valencia trees.
Valencias are the mainstay for Tropicana's Pure Premium,
not-from-concentrate juices. The late-ripening orange is prized for
adding color and flavor to Pure Premium throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   Valencias typically do not have the same crop yield as other
varieties of citrus and can create cash-flow problems for growers
because of their late development, but they generally garner a
price premium from juicers.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari is looking forward to the end of the season this summer.
He's hopeful that next year's crop will be larger.
</P>
<P>
   He's still reeling from this year's drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that number was just a shock,'' Ferrari says.
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Sauer writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
