A8327 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-HATE-NAT     03-12 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-HATE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BILL TO EXPAND FEDERAL HATE CRIMES LAW INTRODUCED BY
LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By C.J. Karamargin  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 12 -- James Byrd, Jr. was killed in Jasper,
Texas last June because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Matthew Shepard was killed in Laramie,
Wyoming because he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   And just last month, Billy Jack Gaither was killed on the banks
of a river where baptisms are performed in rural Alabama because
he, too, was a homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   The three high-profile murders were cited by a bipartisan group
of lawmakers and Vice President Al Gore Thursday as reason to
expand the federal laws covering hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the nation's outrage over the treatment of Rosa Parks
helped lead to the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, I
believe that revulsion over these incidents will galvanize the
public and lend support for hate crimes legislation,'' said Rep.
John Conyers, Jr. (D-MI).
</P>
<P>
   The Hate Crimes Prevention Act would extend the current federal
hate crimes law to cover sexual orientation, gender and disability.
The current law covers crimes motivated by racial, religious and
ethnic prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   Introduction of the act comes as the Senate Judiciary Committee
prepares to hold what are expected to be a series of emotional
hearings on hate crimes next month.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the hearings on Tuesday, Chairman Orin Hatch
(R-Utah) said he has ``become increasingly shocked and appalled by
the level of visciousness associated with a type of criminal
activity that is bigoted, ugly and downright un-American.''
</P>
<P>
   When the committee held hearings on a similar bill last July,
Hatch said that despite his belief the federal government has a
role to play in fighting hate crimes, there are disagreements about
what that role should be.
</P>
<P>
   That previous bill, as well as companion legislation in the
House, never got out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by 120 members of Congress, the act introduced
Thursday would make it easier for federal authorities to get
involved in hate crime cases by loosening what Gore called
``needless jursidictional requirements'' that now leaves state and
local officials with the primary responsibility to prosecute the
perpetrators of hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 10 states do not have hate crime laws and another 21
states do not mention sexual orientation as a category for
protection.
</P>
<P>
   This omission prompted Elizabeth Birch, executive director of
the Human Rights Campaign, a Washington-based gay and lesbian
lobbying group, to urge Congress to pass the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hate Crimes Prevention Act is a key component of the
effort to reduce hate crimes, and it sends the message that hate
motivated violence against minorities has no place in Amercia,''
she said. Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-MA), co-sponsor of the act in the
Senate with Sen. Arlen Specter ((R-PA), called the current law
inadequate and said ``the federal government has been forced to
fight hate crimes with one hane tied behind its back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bill does not undermine the role of states in
investigating and prosecuting hate crimes,'' Kennedy said. ``States
will continue to take the lead. But the full power of federal law
should also be available to investigate, prosecute and punish these
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the act, Kennedy said, ``will make the federal
government a full partner in the battle against hate crimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0209 </DOCNO>
