</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-WAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV DOCUMENTARY DEVOTED TO WAR EFFORTS OF WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Sunday, March 14 by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(``Tonight'' refers to Sunday, March 14)  
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Say you were an alien and knew virtually nothing
about World War II. If you learned about America's ``Good War''
only through the current films ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The
Thin Red Line,'' you'd think women had no role in the war.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be wrong. Tonight, cable TV's History Channel will show
America something Hollywood hasn't: the real and fascinating story
of women who served in World War II. ``Free a Man to Fight'' tells
the story of women who became mechanics, pilots and officers and
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being hailed as heroes as male GIs were, they were too
often chided and forgotten by their fellow citizens, and even their
families. A few have managed to produce books, but their stories
remain largely unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that we have to rewrite ourselves back into
history,'' says Josette Dermody Wingo, who wrote the memoir
``Mother Was a Gunner's Mate'' and came to know ``Free a Man''
director and producer Mindy Pomper through the film.
</P>
<P>
   Pomper was herself startled when she stumbled across the story.
``I went to the Burbank Aviation Museum to see some Tuskeegee
Airmen talking there,'' Pomper recalls. ``They had great stories,
but they said they were already working with George Lucas on a
movie,'' continues Pomper, ``so they were tied up. But then, at the
end of the evening, they said a thank you to the female air pilots
who participated in World War II. And I said, `What?!'''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, after conducting dozens of interviews and
running up her credit cards to help finance the film, Pomper
finished ``Free.'' Meanwhile, the multimillion-dollar studio films
``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The Thin Red Line'' are vying with
expensive ads for a combined 18 Academy Awards between them.
</P>
<P>
   These big studio movies tend to have one thing in common: They
have virtually no female roles of any substance. Mrs. Ryan, the
soldier's mother, is a faceless icon in ``Saving Private Ryan.''
Agents reportedly were so desperate to get their female clients
into ``Thin Red Line'' that they were fighting for the opportunity
to have actresses play the single female character who has more
than a minute of screen time: a nonspeaking role, seen only in a
few gauzy flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of war films that include women is largely due to
ignorance, say women who have studied and written about the
subject. ``Men truly don't know about these stories; it's not like
there's a cabal of men intentionally keeping these stories out of
Hollywood,'' says author Susan Isaacs.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs wrote ``Shining Through,'' a novel about a woman who
becomes a spy in World War II. Though Hollywood did make the book
into a movie, the female character (played by Melanie Griffith)
became more passive and more stereotypically ``feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   Tara McPherson, professor of critical studies at USC's School of
Cinema-Television, says she has an idea why women aren't being
included in these big war films. ``There is a kind of narrowness
among filmmakers, of not being able to imagine women outside of
traditional roles,'' McPherson says.
</P>
<P>
   She continues, ``I think the problem goes beyond these (war)
films: There seems an unwillingness on the part of studios to make
movies that aren't blockbusters. In general, that doesn't serve
women well.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-male casts of most war films would seem to further cut
down on the already small pool of strong female acting parts. ``I
noticed this year that the male nominees for the (Screen Actors
Guild) awards tended to be in bigger pictures, while the women were
in smaller films,'' says Rafe Greenlee, a SAG spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Award nominations tend to recognize work in ``arty'' films. But
big-budget, high-minded war films like ``Private Ryan'' can allow
actors the best of both worlds. That is, a healthy paycheck
!ital!and !off! critical acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Figures compiled by SAG show that for 1997 (the last full year
for which figures are available), there were 1,232 men hired for
lead roles vs. 736 women.
</P>
<P>
   The number of days worked by males vs. females in lead roles is
even more slanted: Men worked a total of about 35,000 days, nearly
double the 17,800 days worked by women.
</P>
<P>
   This reflects the fact that even when women do have ``lead''
roles, those roles are somewhat smaller and tend to be in
smaller-budgeted films with shorter shooting schedules.
</P>
<P>
   John Burman, who tracks stars' ``bankability'' for the Hollywood
Reporter's Star Power report, says women are catching up, to some
degree, but only at the very top. ``It's getting better at the
rarified air level, among stars who get the very top salaries,''
Burman said. He cited recent reports that Julia Roberts is getting
$20 million for her next movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jodie Foster or Julia Roberts wanted to do (a war-themed
picture), I think it could be done. But I think it would still be a
bit of an uphill battle, and it almost certainly wouldn't be a $70
million picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for Creative Artists Agency and the William
Morris Agency, two of the top talent agencies in Los Angeles,
declined to discuss the status of roles for women in film. Those in
the business who are willing to discuss the subject, though, tend
to agree with Burman that it's up to top female stars to seek out
strong roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put the most commercial names in a picture that we
can,'' said Pamela Pickering, head of Mutual Film International
(Mutual developed and co-produced ``Saving Private Ryan.'') She
added: ``God help me if I champion a strong woman's role, and the
movie doesn't end up doing any business. Then I'm out of a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said there are several ``compelling'' scripts about
female war correspondents making the rounds. For the most part,
though, scripts overwhelmingly seem to categorize females as ``the
subject of violence, as a bitch, as fluff-heads,'' Pickering said
bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   Pomper hopes her documentary ``Free a Man'' will open some eyes
in the real world _ and in Hollywood. ``You have to take into
account what the public wants. But it's kind of a chicken-and-egg
sort of thing,'' Pomper said. ``If you show good stories with
strong female roles, people will be interested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
