<SLUG> BC-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI FEARS MISSING WOMAN, TWO GIRLS ARE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PORTAL, Calif. _ When the toughest question came, Jens Sund
couldn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   Does the family believe his wife, daughter and their Argentinian
friend were still alive?
</P>
<P>
   The FBI believes Carole Sund, 42, her daughter, Julie, 15, and
Silvina Pelosso, 16, a friend from Cordoba, Argentina, were the
victims of a violent crime and probably are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Maddock, FBI special agent-in-charge, said his 50
investigators have all but eliminated a theory that the three were
involved in an accident while traveling in the rugged, twisting
mountain roads near Yosemite National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund amd the two girls vanished Feb. 15 from the Cedar
Lodge, a restaurant and motel in El Portal on the western edge of
the park.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a credit card wallet insert belonging to Carole Sund
was found on a street in nearby Modesto, about 80 miles west of the
park, the FBI continues to search dozens of abandoned gold mines,
gorges and hills using all-terrain vehicles and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one possibility left, Maddock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that we feel almost certain that the women were
the victims of a violent crime,'' Maddock said. ``We are now
focusing on one theory that we believe to be the most likely
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scenario includes a violent crime occurring at or near the
Cedar Lodge on the evening of Monday, Feb. 15, or during the early
morning hours of Tuesday, Feb. 16.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jens Sund left a meeting with the FBI looking worn
and drawn, saying he was devastated by what he was told.
</P>
<P>
   But it was news he had heard before, perhaps not willing to let
it sink in.
</P>
<P>
   Sund sparked a news media frenzy Wednesday by implying that
there had been a major development in the case. He apologized
Thursday and said he was reacting to the tremendous stress of it
all. He returned to his home in Eureka for a visit with his other
children, promising to return for a Sunday vigil.
</P>
<P>
   Maddock declined to say what investigators told the Sund and
Pelosso families that upset Jens Sund so much. But Maddock said
investigators were making ``substantial'' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not arrested anyone,'' Maddock said. ``No one has been
charged in connection with the missing persons. We have not
recovered the missing people. We have not found the car.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
