<SLUG> BC-TV-IGGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK WHEN POP WAS PUNK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
IGGY POP: BEHIND THE MUSIC 
When: Sunday at 9 p.m. Program repeats March 19 at 1 p.m. and March
20 at 2 a.m. 
On: VH-1 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Some people thought I was arrogant; some people thought I was
crazy; some people thought I was funny. All were correct,'' Iggy
Pop tells his interviewer during VH1's ``Iggy Pop: Behind the
Music.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 18, he'd been drunk, been in a car crash,
been in jail. By the time he was 21, in 1968 with his Ann Arbor,
Mich.-based rock band the Stooges, he became what might be called
an anti-rock star: a bare-chested, coiled spring of a singer who
corkscrewed across stages, goaded audiences, and exposed himself.
His autobiography was called ``I Need More.'' His theme song might
be ``Gimme Danger'': ``Gimme danger little stranger / And I'll feel
your disease''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of everything I've done onstage,'' Pop says in the
hourlong musical documentary. He saw what the Doors' Jim Morrison
did onstage and upped the ante. His early music, concocted as the
hippie dream was coming apart, was harsh and nasty, expressing rage
and futility. At the time, it went largely unheard. Says Pop: ``We
did really well with social deviants, high school dropouts, people
with lousy jobs, alcoholics, drug addicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the mid-'70s, punk rock exploded and Pop got a new
lease on life. He was the godfather of it all. ``We changed the
playing field of what was cutting edge,'' Pop says.
</P>
<P>
   Pop _ born James Osterberg, once called Iggy Stooge _ has led a
fascinating life, for what he's accomplished and endured (massive
amounts of drugs and self-abuse) and, simply, for surviving. If the
Rolling Stones' Keith Richards has topped everyone's Next Rocker to
Die list for a couple of decades, Iggy Pop _ the proud,
self-proclaimed ``world's forgotten boy'' of ``Search and Destroy''
_ has been right behind him.
</P>
<P>
   VH1 producers Jeff Gaspin, George Moll, and Gay Rosenthal have
put together a highly entertaining hour, with Pop serving as the
older-but-wiser tour guide to his own tattered life. The show draws
upon interviews with former Stooges, mentor-savior-collaborator
David Bowie, his discoverer Danny Fields, and others. The most
notable other would be Iggy's son, Eric Benson (he took his
mother's last name), who looks and sounds very much like his pop,
and went through many of the same highs and lows. (The two work
together now; Eric has helped protect his dad onstage and may
become his road manager.) Top-flight Rolling Stone writer David
Fricke provides critical context.
</P>
<P>
   But the title of the VH1 series is ``Behind the Music,'' and one
wishes that the producers had gotten behind the music. What was
Pop's motivation, besides the bottled-up anger and resentment of
his youth? Bowie jokes about their move to West Berlin _ they went
to the heroin capital of Europe to kick heroin addiction _ and Pop
says their work schedule was this: two-day binge, two-day recovery,
three days of music. Which is fair enough, but how does that
schedule accommodate the groundbreaking ``Lust for Life'' and ``The
Idiot'' albums that were recorded there? There's a larger issue
about the relationship between the drug-taking and the
music-making: How did so much vital music get made while these guys
were seriously messed up? What is the relationship between drugs
and creativity? What about the vicarious ride the audience gets
from the performer's tightrope walk? How about Pop's linkage of
hedonism and nihilism? What about Pop's transition from an angry
man to a more contemplative, philosophical one?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than explore these topics, ``Behind the Music'' skips
from one drug-phase-and-recovery to another
drug-phase-and-recovery. The bulk of the show dwells on the 1970s _
Pop's most fertile period _ but when it jumps into the '90s and his
relative commercial success, it's presented almost as a rushed
afterthought. Oh yes, he had a hit with ``Real Wild Child,'' got a
boost when ``Lust for Life'' was used in ``Trainspotting'' and Nike
picked ``Search and Destroy'' to peddle overpriced sneakers. Pop,
speaking on having his music used in ads: ``My policy is: Use 'em
for sausages, use 'em for cars. I do not care. They were not
commercially conceived.'' We learn that his relationship with his
wife, Suchi, which may have saved his life and career, is now over,
and Iggy Pop, at 51, is looking for love again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1658EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
