<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8359 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPIELBERG-BOS &LR;      03-12 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPIELBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW START DOESN'T DIMINISH SPIELBERG INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
INSIDE THE ACTORS STUDIO: STEVEN SPIELBERG 
Executive producer and host: James Lipton 
On: Bravo 
Date: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One learns a lot about Steven Spielberg, both the filmmaker and
the candid and likably engaging man, in Sunday's special
two-hour-plus edition of ``Inside the Actors Studio'' (on Bravo at
8). But be prepared. It takes a while for the show to get into gear
and for the understated Spielberg to wrest the event from the
interview series's dourly histrionic host James Lipton.
</P>
<P>
   The self-admiring host occupies nearly five fawning minutes
introducing the abashed-looking director, but it's worth enduring
this and his William Buckley-ish interrogation. ``Is it safe to say
your parents played a significant role in shaping the major
interests in your life?'' is a typically ornate query, delivered
with theatrical drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg himself is refreshingly unaffected. The interview
format is stiff, following its subject chronologically from
childhood through his major movies, but, because of Spielberg's
good humor, never stifling. Like his best movies, ``E.T.'' and
``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' Spielberg expresses a
childlike openness to experience and a gently percolating joie de
vivre.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he does say that his musical mother and technically
oriented father are perhaps the principal influences on his work.
He explains the parental roots, for instance, of the finale of
``Close Encounters'' in which a high-tech language of musical tones
and flashing electronics bridges our world to that of the innocent,
visiting aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg readily admits his near-phobic nature inherited from a
mother ``afraid of everything.'' He fears elevators, furniture with
feet, and, he says in regard to ``Jaws,'' not sharks so much as
water itself and what it conceals.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ambitious sweep of the interview, interesting
ideas and experiences are rarely developed completely. Some of his
success Spielberg attributes to creative looseness, a receptiveness
to the possibilities suggested by accidents on location, an
openness to improvisation. ``I always covet my second thoughts,''
he says tantalizingly, but the subject is accorded limited time.
</P>
<P>
   But even truncated musings like this are valuable for their own
sake and, often, for the way Spielberg unguardedly reveals himself.
He talks a little about his refusal to rehearse actors, believing
that ``fear produces extraordinary moments'' on film. He generously
praises collaborators and credits the late Francois Truffaut, the
great French director who appeared in ``Close Encounters,'' for
nudging him toward ``E.T.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg gets off his goofiest line when asked if E.T. was a
boy or girl: ``E.T. is a plant, a botanical garden,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The prolific, successful, and wealthy director never sounds
self-congratulatory. In the Q-and-A session with drama students
that concludes Lipton's interviews, Spielberg talks about his
image, but only because he's asked to. His disarming response is
worth repeating. ``I don't see myself the way you may, as a famous
person. If I see myself as you see me, I'll have to retire _ I'll
be imitating the person you think I am.''
</P>
<P>
   It has to be considered that Spielberg's benevolent ease, if not
his sharp memory and storytelling gift, has something to do with
Lipton's fulsome praise. In only one example, the host calls the
sometimes powerful but conventionally nostalgic ``Saving Private
Ryan'' a ``truly enduring 20th-century work of art.'' Lipton does
much the same thing with the actors he presents on other shows,
often resulting in cloying public love-ins. But while Spielberg
doesn't deflect the endless compliments, he pays scant attention,
concentrating on the frequently lively topics at hand.
</P>
<P>
   While no deeply critical probing takes place, Lipton manages to
mine intriguing information and wonderful anecdotes, and to reveal
interesting, unconscious connections among Spielberg's widely
varied movies. Whatever posterity says about Spielberg as a film
artist, he comes across as a generous, well-meaning man and an
earnestly dedicated, tremendously enthusiastic professional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
