<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITNEY-YOUTH-ART-$AD     03-12 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITNEY-YOUTH-ART-$ADV14-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINNER, DANCING AND, OH YES, ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SUSAN M. KIRSCHBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As members of New York's social establishment took
their seats at the annual winter gala for the Whitney Museum of
American Art, Andre Harrell was perplexed. Sitting beneath a giant
orb of white carnations, Harrell, a rap producer, gazed upon guests
like Ronald O. Perelman, John F. Kennedy Jr. and Martha Stewart,
and asked: ``What is this about? And what does this have to do with
hip-hop?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. Harrell, a guest of Russell Simmons of Def Jam
Records, had come to hear brief performances by Gloria Gaynor, the
disco queen, and Foxy Brown, a teen-age hip-hop sensation, at what
was billed as Brite Nite at the Whitney. ``It's probably timely in
the sense that hip-hop is becoming mainstream,'' Harrell said,
while Ms. Brown, in an olive micro-minidress that revealed the
tattoos on her upper chest, chatted nearby. ``I guess it's a way to
take an Upper East Side crowd and make it hip.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. In addition to a dinner committee composed of the
museum's chairman, Leonard Lauder, and other leaders of commerce
and the arts, Brite Nite, which raised almost $1.4 million, was
organized by a second committee, responsible for an after-dinner
dance. Its members, luminaries from fashion, hip-hop and the
downtown club world, were asked to send invitations to the $75
after-party to their friends, representing the museum's attempt to
get a younger and hipper crowd to support it.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell L. Anderson, the Whitney's director, made no apologies
for the unlikely after-dinner committee, which included Marcus
Schenkenberg, a former Calvin Klein model; Jade Jagger, a jewelry
designer and a daughter of Mick Jagger, and Jeffrey Jah, a promoter
for Life, a nightclub. ``I used to take dancing lessons in eighth
grade, at the Pierre,'' Anderson said. ``New York is changing. All
kinds of people are making their way into society.'' He declared
the sold-out dinner for 550 _ with tickets at $1,000 and up _ and
the packed dance to be the Whitney's most successful party.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the latest in a series of efforts by old-line New
York cultural institutions to embrace the realms of fashion and pop
culture with the express purpose of adding sex appeal to their
images. In fall 1997, the Whitney opened a show of Andy Warhol's
work with a gala featuring Duran Duran. The Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum has an underwriting deal with the fashion company Hugo Boss,
which has led to such promotions as one in which 100 Neiman Marcus
executives and buyers were asked to wear biker gear at the time of
the museum's ``Art of the Motorcycle'' exhibition last summer. An
exhibition catalog was awarded to the store executive with the best
biker outfit.
</P>
<P>
   And last December, the Guggenheim put on a lunch and a somewhat
airy discussion of style in art and fashion, attended by 30 fashion
designers, including Michael Kors and Diane Von Furstenberg. ``We
wanted to get the `in crowd' of society,'' said Gina Rogak, the
Guggenheim's director of special events, ``by bringing in a fashion
element and seating designers at every table.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hartley, the director of communications and sponsorship for
the Guggenheim, said bluntly: ``We are in the entertainment
business and competing against other forms of entertainment out
there. We have a Guggenheim brand that has certain equities and
properties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By doing these cross fertilizations, we get a crowd that
perhaps doesn't typically come to Guggenheim openings,'' he added.
``But if they are here for a party and happen to look at the art
and come back again, that's valuable to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some museum-goers question whether borrowing the patina of chic
has anything to do with art, and whether such extravagant parties
make a difference. ``It's becoming more about the people and less
about the art,'' said William Corbin, a restaurant marketing
consultant, who said he moved from the Upper East Side to Chelsea
expressly to be near the exploding gallery scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art seems conspicuously absent from the
trend; its main effort to attract young patrons is through its
Junior Associates group, whose activities are narrowly art-related.
``We get lots of young people coming to the openings for the art
without any further enhancement,'' said Mary Lou Strahlendorff, a
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But even an institution as traditional as the Museum of the City
of New York, where many of the patrons are from old-line families
with names like Astor and Pulitzer, has dipped into youth culture.
Last June, the museum held one of its most successful openings for
``Half Past Autumn: The Art of Gordon Parks,'' the African-American
photographer. The event was supported on the invitation by Sean
``Puffy'' Combs, the rap entrepreneur, and Spike Lee, the director,
both listed as members of the honorary committee. It drew more than
1,000 attendees, more than double the museum's average.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Dubin, the director of Sotheby's fashion department,
likes the diverse crowds that museums are embracing, even if things
are sometimes confusing. Ms. Dubin, a young woman recognizable by
her perfect chin-length bobbed hair and Empire-style dresses, was
on the cover of Town &AMP; Country magazine in January. She met a few
nights before Brite Nite to plan the after-dinner party with some
other committee members, among them Amy Sacco, the owner of Lot 61,
a hip lounge in Chelsea, and Avi Adler, a floral designer of the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   As the others discussed Twilo, a downtown dance club where the
well-known deejay Junior Vasquez presides over an all-night
Saturday party, Ms. Dubin, who rarely ventures below 50th Street,
looked blank. ``I've never heard of these places,'' she said. But
she was eager to welcome the new crowd sought by the Whitney. ``The
people going now are interesting,'' she continued. ``Fund-raisers
in the past have been stereotyped as ladies who lunch and spend
days attending meetings, which is less enticing for my generation,
who work and do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Four nights later, following the seated dinner, the Brite Nite
crowd descended from the fourth floor to the third, where Foxy
Brown belted out a song from her hit record ``Chyna Doll,'' and
Kennedy approached the stage just as she finished. He said he was a
big fan. ``I was in Korea two weeks ago and couldn't sleep,'' he
said. ``I turned on the television and saw Foxy doing `Hot Spot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brandywine, a bewigged drag queen, darted through the
pitch-black party space, as the Earl of Albemarle escorted Princess
Olga of Greece. Club kids, a few wearing wedge-heeled boots with
long dresses, gathered near the sound stage to boogie to the sounds
of Funkmaster Flash, the deejay.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Bushnell, the author of ``Sex in the City,'' surveyed
the room and said, ``If Edith Wharton were around today, instead of
the opera she'd be going to the Whitney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
