 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, March 14, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUBU-FASHION (New York) _ Fubu stands for ``For us, by us.'' The
company, which was founded in 1992, has prospered by promoting
itself as a black-owned fashion label by and for young urban men.
The founders, Daymond John, Carl Brown, Keith Perrin and J.
Alexander Martin, all from Hollis, N.Y., insist that ``For us, by
us'' is not a call to racial empowerment, but clearly race is part
of their appeal. Last year, the company says it sold a stunning
$350 million worth of goods, which catapults it beyond a niche
market into a league with labels like Donna Karan ($670 million)
and Tommy Hilfiger ($847 million.) By Leslie Kaufman. Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIGARETTE-LOUNGE (Undated) _ These days cigarette girls have
gone the way of Gibson girls. And not only is smoking outlawed now
in most New York restaurants, but so is the sale of individual
cigarettes. That is why cigarette girls aren't employed at Circa
Tabac, billed as the city's only ``cigarette lounge.'' But it
certainly has everything else a smoker could desire. There's a full
bar, an interesting selection of appetizers (in order to avoid
being classified as a restaurant, it does not serve entrees), an
international cigarette menu with more than 100 brands, and every
kind of antique cigarette accessory imaginable _ from holders,
cases and lighters to a roll-your-own maker from the 1920s. By Alex
Witchel. Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-YOUTH (New York) _ The Whitney museum sponsored a Brite
Nite event recently, which raised almost $1.4 million. Luminaries
from fashion, hip-hop and the downtown club world, were asked to
send invitations to the $75 after-dinner party to their friends, in
the museum's attempt to get a younger and hipper crowd to support
it. By Susan M. Kirschbaum. Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MODELS-FILMS (New York) _ Filmmakers have been down this road
many times, smitten by stars of the runways and cosmetics
advertisements and casting them for publicity value or in hopes
that their stunning beauty will rivet viewers. But experience
suggests a hard lesson. The model Angie Everhart has twice played a
hooker _ in ``Jade'' (1995) and ``Bordello of Blood'' (1996) _ but
neither performance hooked audiences. The appearance of Elle
Macpherson in ``If Lucy Fell'' in 1996 prompted some to suggest a
new name for the film, ``If Elle Could Act.'' By Jared Paul Stern.
Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIKH-NITEOUT (New York) _ Vikram Chatwal, 27, is one of those
people who uses the word ``slash'' suspiciously often when he
describes what he does for a living. ``I guess you could say I'm a
model slash hotelier slash actor slash screenwriter,'' the Sikh
impresario said on a recent March evening at the Staley-Wise
Gallery in SoHo, his white turban bobbing above the chain-smoking
crowd. Chatwal had stopped in for a show of photographs by Ellen
von Unwerth, who shot him for a Vogue fashion spread in 1997 _ that
explains the model part of his self-description. Chatwal comes
across as a 1999 poster boy of multicultural chic: a spiritually
conversant playboy with a penchant for rap music and friends
gathered from the worlds of banking, music and just plain money. By
Alex Kuczynski. Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ They are a colorful group, the
corydalises. Their small, trumpet-shaped flowers are tinted in
yellows, blues, reds, pinks, purples or whites. Their foliage
spectrum encompasses blue-greens sheathed with silver to warm
greens tipped with bronze. Until the last decade or so, they were
almost unknown in 20th-century American gardens. Now, with the fall
of the Soviet Union, there are a host of exciting new plants
becoming available, and there is renewed interest in old standbys
as well. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
