<P>
   CARMIKE _ ATLANTA _Carmike Cinemas Inc. (CKE) Chief Financial
Officer John O. Barwick resigned. In a press release Friday, the
company said Barwick also resigned from the positions of senior
vice president of finance and treasurer, after 22 years at the
company. The company said Barwick plans to focus on other business
activities. The company said it hasn't named a replacement.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola's stock has been on a tear over the
past few days. The stock is up almost 10 percent just this week.
(Inger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS _ ATLANTA _Stocks opened mostly higher this morning, with
the Dow again approaching 10,000, but weakness in technology issues
tempered some of the advance.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:45, the Dow was down 26.The blue chips came within 42
points of 10,000 before giving up some ground. Broaders market
indicators were mixed. The market had moved higher after the Labor
Department released the PPI, which dropped a seasonally adjusted
0.4 percent in February, indicating that inflation remains under
control. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-PAXTV - WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paxson Communications shares
rose as much as 21 percent on speculation that it may announce a
joint venture or an outright purchase by another media company.
Names mentioned include General Electric NBC's, Time Warner and
America Online. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING-GREEN _ SPRINFIELD, Ohio _ In a marriage of development
and conservation, local builders are starting to think green.
Environmentally friendly building techniques and materials are
improving every day. (Springfield News-Sun)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PRIVACY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As the Internet blooms, even the
most technophobic among us deals daily with logins, passwords and
the ever-present issue of privacy. But as network technology gets
away from the desktop and the keyboard, a whole new set of privacy
options arise. How will you protect your smart cards, digital
assistants and home networks? (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WOLF-Q&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Michael Wolff tried to get an
Internet business going way back in the early years of the World
Wide Web. It was 1996 and he was in new media.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about his adventures in dealing with venture
capitalists, media barons, old and new, and other Internet gold
seekers in a book, ``Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years
on the Internet.'' (Green, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
