<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINERAMA-2TAKES-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYTON MOVIE HOUSE CARRIES ON A CINEMATIC REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SOMMER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ New Neon Movies, a small art house nearly
swallowed up by a nearby sprawling, concrete parking garage located
above the Greyhound Bus station, sits across from a 24-hour White
Tower hamburger stand.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a highway overpass away from a gritty stretch of
downtown and its mix of coffee bars and X-rated book shops. At
first glance, and second, this would hardly seem to be the site for
the first screenings of Cinerama in the United States in more than
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Just as improbable is it's revival in this heart of Middle
America, home to Wright-Patterson Air Force Base and once, Orville
and Wilbur Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlikely as it is, nearly a half-century since Cinerama's
debut, John Harvey, a projectionist and theater equipment supplier,
and Larry Smith, the theater's co-owner, have done what some
thought would never happen: They have brought back the
revolutionary motion picture process in all its three-projector,
curved-screen and stereophonic glory.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with wide-screen movie formats taken for granted and IMAX
theaters housing screens eight stories tall, it's hard to grasp the
special excitement Cinerama once held. But at a recent matinee of
``This Is Cinerama'' it was possible to see what all the fuss was
about.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake about it: When ``This Is Cinerama'' opened on
Sept. 30, 1952, at the Broadway Theatre in New York, beginning what
would be a 122-week run, it was a hugely anticipated event.
</P>
<P>
   Promotional material touted Cinerama as ``a new technique for
seeing the world of reality as well as the world of make-believe
with new eyes.'' But it wasn't only the company saying that; many
front-line publications agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinerama is truly wonderful to behold. (It's) the movies
greatest innovation since sound,'' proclaimed Newsweek. ``Most
spectacular and thrilling,'' declared the New York Times' Bosley
Crowther in a rare front-page review. ``Cinerama is the most
exciting thing to hit New York since Penicillin,'' added Ed
Sullivan (yes, that Ed Sullivan) of the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when narrator Lowell Thomas looked into the camera and
boldly declared, ``Ladies and gentlemen, this is Cinerama!'' he was
at once heralding a new era in motion pictures and a sensory
experience that many film aficionados insist remains without
parallel to the present day.
</P>
<P>
   As the theater's red curtain pulls back, and still back some
more, Thomas' normal-size flickering, black-and-white image gives
way to an astonishing depth and field of vision, shot in
Technicolor, of Rockaways' Playland in New York that is nothing
short of breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   With a sonic blast, the audience is transported into the lead
car of the Atom Smasher Roller Coaster, feels the anticipation of
its slow rickety climb up the first slope, braces for the
impossible descent that looms ahead and holds on for dear life with
each sudden dip and drop and turn of the 90-second ride.
</P>
<P>
   The opening roller coaster scene in ``This Is Cinerama'' is just
one of many extraordinary sequences in the travelogue. Others
include panoramic aerial views of national parks to a rousing
``America the Beautiful''; a buffalo stampede; ``Aida'' being
performed inside the Italian opera house, La Scala; and a close-up
of the Vienna Boys Choir. But it's the one most remembered after
all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sort of prepared that we were going to get something
we were not quite ready for, and sure enough, it's true,'' Dayton
resident Tommy Bankston said during the film's intermission, a big
grin stamped across his face. ``You really did feel like you were
actually there. There's the whole anticipation of the roller
coaster descending, and it's just absolutely breathtaking, it
really is.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``This Is Cinerama,'' the theater also showed
coming attractions for ``The Wonderful World of the Brothers
Grimm,'' ``How the West Was Won,'' and as an added Cinerama treat,
a 1959 Renault commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Residents from Dayton, like Bankston, seemed to be in the
minority at the screening. Many among the 78 people in attendance
had come hundreds of miles for the opportunity to see Cinerama. For
some it was the first time; for others, it was their first time
since the Eisenhower or Kennedy administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Cletus Epple was among the latter. He drove from a town outside
Indianapolis to be there, and seemed pleased to have made the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it holds up very well,'' he said after the film. ``A
lot of movies and things from your youth don't hold up, but this
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Cinerama was developed by Fred Waller, a former head of
Paramount Picture's special effects department. A prodigious
inventor, Waller created water skis and the Waller Gunnery Trainer,
a modern flight simulator credited with saving thousands of lives
in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He was determined to create a motion picture experience that
would mimic how people actually see and hear. After years of trial
and error, he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Waller developed a camera to capture images on three strips of
film concurrently, and then have three projectors project the film
onto a 146-degree curved screen that emulated the range of a
person's peripheral vision. In this way, Cinerama was able to
provide a depth and field of vision unlike anything seen before.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``The foreground and background are both in focus, which creates
a kind of hyper reality,'' Smith explained. ``Because of the sharp
focus, and the curved screen, Cinerama breaks the third dimension,
and it actually feels like you're part of the action.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem Waller addressed but never completely
solved _ masking the vertical lines that appeared on the screen,
where the seams of the film strips met. For some viewers it would
be an annoying distraction that negated the Cinerama experience.
</P>
<P>
   Cinerama's stereophonic sound, which allowed sound to be heard
through seven channels rather than one, was developed by Waller's
associate, Hazard Reeves. He used seven microphones for filming,
which when played back through a sound reproducer, produced a
highly defined tracking of sound direction and movement. (Disney's
``Fantasia'' in 1940 had been recorded in stereo, but the sound
suffered for not having been magnetically recorded.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite Cinerama's initial success, and a rash of imitators that
followed, including KinoPanorama, in Russia, only seven
feature-length films were made, the first five of them travelogues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is Cinerama'' was the top-grossing movie to come out in
1952, with a box office take of $12.5 million in just four
theaters, but ticket sales for the subsequent releases were
disappointing with the exception of the last, 1962's ``How the West
was Won.''
</P>
<P>
   One of only two Cinerama pictures to boast Hollywood stars _ the
all-star cast included Henry Fonda, Gregory Peck and Jimmy Stewart
_ it was also the third most expensive film ever made by M-G-M.
</P>
<P>
   The movie studio, which had bought out Cinerama Prod. in the
late-1950s, then turned to simpler and less ambitious wide-screen
formats, including 70 millimeter film and Cinemascope, that could
be shot by a single camera and projected onto a wide but flat
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Cinerama, the process that opened the door for wide-screen
presentation and stereophonic sound, was in the end a victim of
high costs and technical difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the final curtain came down on Cinerama at the same
time a wave of Super Cinerama theaters, with wide, curved screens,
began opening across the country. The best known, the Cinerama Dome
in Los Angeles, never actually showed the three-projector process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Variety Cinemas contemplated two years ago putting a wall
down the middle of New Neon Movies to create two small auditoriums,
Smith, a minority owner and also the theater manager at the time
and a Cinerama buff, and his long-time friend Harvey, proposed the
unlikely notion of presenting films in Cinerama.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the larger screen _ it's two stories tall and 50
feet around the curve _ and the three projectors, they and a team
of 40 volunteers pulled 88 of the 300 seats, tore out a third of
the ceiling, built the booth and did all the wiring and carpentry.
They finished in five weeks, and began showing Cinerama in August
1996 on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance began earnestly but tailed off after several months.
Last year, the theater nearly closed, and employees say the movie
house is not yet out of the woods. There were only eight weekend
showings of Cinerama, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   With prospects for Cinerama's long-term revival uncertain, Smith
and Harvey have started the Cinerama Preservation Society, a
non-profit group dedicated to keeping Cinerama alive, with the goal
of establishing a museum in Dayton. They have been unable to get
Pacific Theaters, which owns the rights to ``This Is Cinerama,''
and the negatives to the other travelogues, and Warner Bros., which
has ownership of ``The Wonderful World of the Brothers Grimm,'' to
strike new prints or to show interest in bringing Cinerama back.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvey and Smith insist they will keep on trying to build
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (New Neon Movies is located at 130 E. Fifth St., Dayton, Ohio.
For more information, call 937-222-8452.)
</P>
</TEXT>
