<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIKH-NIGHTOUT-ART-ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH VIKRAM CHATWAL: THE TURBAN ALSO UNWINDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday March 14)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vikram Chatwal is one of those people who uses the
word ``slash'' suspiciously often when he describes what he does
for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say I'm a model slash hotelier slash actor
slash screenwriter,'' the 27-year-old Sikh impresario said on a
recent March evening at the Staley-Wise Gallery in SoHo, his white
turban bobbing above the chain-smoking crowd. Chatwal had stopped
in for a show of photographs by Ellen von Unwerth, who shot him for
a Vogue fashion spread in 1997 _ that explains the model part of
his self-description.
</P>
<P>
   Chatwal emigrated from India to Canada in 1984, and moved to New
York a decade ago. Because he is a Sikh, he usually wears a
pristine white turban. (Sometimes he takes it off when he dances,
he said.) Chatwal comes across as a 1999 poster boy of
multicultural chic: a spiritually conversant playboy with a
penchant for rap music and friends gathered from the worlds of
banking, music and just plain money.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of Pennsylvania, Chatwal
worked at Morgan Stanley. ``Then I left to pursue some more
cultural journeys,'' said Chatwal, who is becoming something of an
Indian Ian Schrager. He is already a part owner of Joe's Pub, the
downtown boite of the moment; in May, Hampshire Hotels, a chain run
by Chatwal's family, will open the Time, a hotel on West 49th
Street, where Chatwal will be the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an upscale boutique kind of hotel,'' he said,
his voice as soporific as warm buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   A gallery assistant flashed the lights as a signal to disperse.
Chatwal rounded up friends for dinner: Gotham Chopra, the son of
Deepak Chopra; Daniella Rich, the daughter of the social songwriter
Denise Rich; a globe-trotting English lawyer named Richard, and Sky
Nellor, a slim brunette who described herself as ``a deejay slash
television hostess slash model.''
</P>
<P>
   The group piled into Chatwal's white Mercedes 500S sedan, a car
more suitable for a Palm Beach housewife. Chatwal says he likes it
``because it's a moving living room.'' He turned on Big E. Smalls
(``Uh-uh/Money, I'm gonna front you/Uh-uh/Girl, I'm gonna flaunt
you'') and drove to Bamboo, a restaurant on West 14th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's an Arawak steak?'' Ms. Rich asked as she perused the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arawak are one of two indigenous Indian tribes in the
Caribbean,'' the lawyer replied, without moving his eyes from his
menu.
</P>
<P>
   As plates of steak and steamed mussels and jerk chicken, fried
plantains and crab cakes arrived, the conversation turned to
organized crime. Chopra and Chatwal are writing a screenplay
together, which Chatwal described as ``the Indian `Scarface.''' A
guest posed this question: Does crime pay?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Chatwal said, turning solemn. ``There is nothing you can
do to assuage your conscience when you commit sins. Crime is a
spiritual assault on the soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Chatwal said his movie was ``really about the pressures on
immigrant families to achieve the American dream.'' He started
talking about how difficult it was to be a, well, Sikh slash
American.
</P>
<P>
   Chatwal said he was not a religious Sikh. ``I'm more of a
cultural one. As a Sikh, you're not allowed to cut your hair,
drink, smoke or have premarital sex.'' Despite his parents'
expectations, he said he would not submit to an arranged marriage.
``I'll be marrying for love, like we all should be,'' he added.
Slash romantic?
</P>
</TEXT>
