<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INS-TACTICS-$ADV14-HN     03-12 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-TACTICS-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS TAKES DIFFERENT TACK AGAINST UNDOCUMENTED WORKERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(for release Sunday March 14) By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) In Washington state's Yakima Valley, undocumented
workers in the fruit packing sheds thought they knew what to expect
from the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   The INS would show up, people fearing deportation would bolt for
the doors and the INS would sometimes make 50 to 60 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   But the landscape in Yakima changed dramatically last month when
the INS took a different tack.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of scattershot raids at various fruit-packing sites, the
INS reviewed the payrolls at 13 different packing companies and
then instructed the companies en masse to fire those workers whose
documents were false.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 600 workers were fired. Several hundred more who already
had been laid off during a seasonal downturn will apparently not be
allowed to return to work. And Yakima is in an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way that the social service agencies are going to
be able to support 700 families for any period of time,'' said
Rosanne Fischer-Pineda , director of the Yakima Interfaith Council.
``There's got to be some kind of political solution to this.''
</P>
<P>
   But this type of enforcement strategy is a political solution,
of sorts, for the INS. The embattled agency concedes that it cannot
realistically catch all of the estimated 5 million people living
illegally in the United States and it cannot afford to deport
everyone it can catch.
</P>
<P>
   INS resources have swelled dramatically in recent years, but
with few exceptions the money and staff have gone to U.S.-Mexico
border districts. Budgets for special agents in the interior _ the
people who handle work-site enforcement and investigate document
fraud _ have not grown accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and INS officials agreed the agency needed a more
comprehensive approach to interior enforcement. Joe Greene,
district director for the INS Denver region, led a committee which
in January recommended several ways to respond to changes in the
pattern of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Greene wants the INS to stop using the number of deportations as
a measure of the agency's success. Critics like Rep. Lamar Smith,
R-Texas and chairman of the House Subcommittee on Immigration,
thinks that sends a message of encouragement to anyone who does not
immediately get caught at the border.
</P>
<P>
   Greene countered that while deportations will be one of many
tools the agency uses to deter illegal immigration, the agency has
conceded that removing large numbers of immigrants does not prevent
them from returning _ often in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most telling points in Greene's analysis was spelled
out in numbers. The INS apprehended 13,897 illegal immigrants at
work sites throughout the United States in 1988, which works out to
45.5 apprehensions per INS investigator per year.
</P>
<P>
   At that rate, it would take take almost 35,000 investigator
``work years'' to apprehend the illegal residents who entered the
country in the last four years alone.
</P>
<P>
   The approach used most recently in Yakima was developed by an
immigration officer from Phoenix who was assigned temporary duty in
Reno, Nev., five years ago. Tony Esposito said that by following up
on old leads he found in office files, his small staff found 450
unauthorized workers on the payrolls of five casino industry
businesses. They pursued more business payrolls and the list grew
to as many as 800 illegal workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said what do we do now? We can't arrest them,'' Esposito
recalled. ``And transportation is even a bigger problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Esposito put together a training seminar for affected
businesses, teaching them how to spot fraud in workers' documents.
The agents then presented employers with lists of illegal
employees, and asked that they confront and dismiss them. If the
employees are not fired, the employer would be subject to INS
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the genesis for new a INS strategy _ target large groups
of illegal employees within a specific industry, and target those
workers through firings. With the development of sophisticated
computer databases, the INS is now also providing software to
employers to allow them to access immigration, Social Security and
even drivers license information to help verify immigrant
employment documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sanctions become heavily worked in an industry, it becomes
a place that's not friendly to the unauthorized alien,'' Esposito
said. ``If we do this throughout the country, we're going to be
working real smart _ with fewer resources and a smaller force.''
</P>
<P>
   Esposito says deportations are still an important psychological
tool. But trying to go out and arrest people every day means having
to arrange corresponding transportation, bed space, food and
manpower, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has prosecuted thousands of employers for willfully
hiring undocumented workers over the past decade, but the agency is
now also aiming for the cooperation of employers they say are being
victimized by employees who present sophisticated, easily obtained
fraudulent documentation of eligibility to work.
</P>
<P>
   Esposito said the efforts to train employers to spot fake
documents have been pretty successful, but a participant in one of
the recent training seminars for employers in Yakima disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, he's dreaming,'' said Michael Gempler,
executive director of the Washington Growers league. ``At the
seminar they showed slides of documents that were false _ and
nobody in the room could tell they were false.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The one good thing is they haven't grabbed the people and
shipped them out of the country,'' said the Rev. Patrick C. Carroll
of Yakima's St. Joseph Catholic Church. ``They got into too much
trouble the last time because they shipped out mothers with tiny
children.''
</P>
<P>
   But his parishioners are very upset, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of the women I ran into (who had been fired), single
mothers with children, said they have no other means of support,''
Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the tough side of it,'' said Bill Strassberger, a
spokesman for the western regional office of the INS. ``We've heard
that somewhere in the order of 500 to 600 people have been
terminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how many people will not reapply and say ... it's time to
go home? There's no way for us to count those numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
