<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGARETTE-LOUNGE-ART-     03-12 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTE-LOUNGE-ART-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEALING A SMOKE, IN GOOD COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In third grade, I wanted to be one of two things when
I grew up: either a counterman at my favorite delicatessen,
Feitlin's, in Passaic, N.J. _ free hot dogs and fries _ or a
cigarette girl. No occupation seemed more glamorous: sexy outfits,
lots of lipstick, and the men about town were always happy to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   These days, of course, cigarette girls have gone the way of
Gibson girls. And not only is smoking outlawed now in most New York
restaurants, but so is the sale of individual cigarettes. That is
why cigarette girls aren't employed at Circa Tabac, billed as the
city's only ``cigarette lounge,'' open since December at 32 Watts
St. But it certainly has everything else a smoker could desire.
There's a full bar, an interesting selection of appetizers (in
order to avoid being classified as a restaurant, it does not serve
entrees), an international cigarette menu with more than 100
brands, and every kind of antique cigarette accessory imaginable _
from holders, cases and lighters to a roll-your-own maker from the
1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Circa Tabac's owners, Lee Ringelheim and Brian Michels, have
devoted themselves to a simple, if currently verboten, concept: to
directly cater to the discerning smoker.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you, Lord. I asked my friend Nan to join me for a few
stolen hours of Puff Mommy sin. She is a devoted smoker who rails
at the smoking police, which include her husband and college-age
daughter. In my house there are my stepsons and my husband, a
long-reformed three-pack-a-day man who seems convinced he'll start
again if he even smells smoke. Most days, my neighbors find me
inhaling in the service stairway.
</P>
<P>
   Circa Tabac is certainly an improvement. It has a distinctly
different feel from the burly, wood-paneled dens for cigar lovers
around town; while not exclusively feminine, it does have a certain
``Casablanca'' elegance. A smallish space that seats 75, it is
filled with Art Deco touches, including a mirror behind the bar
etched with a woman in evening dress with a cigarette holder
protruding from the silhouette.
</P>
<P>
   The windows are covered in lacy curtains that repeat the
palm-frond motif of the carpets. There are powerful air purifiers
on the ceilings and others strategically placed around the room _
two to remove smoke, two to remove odor. They change the room's air
every six minutes, the owners say. The place smells better than
most restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was early, 6 p.m. (the lounge opens daily at 5 p.m.
and goes till 2 a.m. Sundays through Wednesdays and to 4 a.m. on
weekends), the room was almost half full with a young, chic,
racially mixed clientele, which looked like the lounge's staff:
dressed in black and decoratively tattooed.
</P>
<P>
   Plates of spinach won tons and filet mignon en croissant passed
quickly to a table of 16 that filled the back wall, while
painstakingly poured cosmopolitans and martinis crept by more
slowly. As far as we were concerned, though, dinner could wait.
Framing the bar is a dizzying variety of cigarette packages, and
upon being seated at a tiny circular table in oversize velvet
chairs, we were handed a cigarette menu.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. We could choose from Britain, Canada, Indonesia, Turkey,
France, Colombia, Egypt, Malaysia, Spain, Japan, China, Greece,
Germany, the Netherlands, Uruguay, Austria, Ireland, Switzerland,
India or, naturally, the United States. There were also
tobacco-free herbal cigarettes. Please.
</P>
<P>
   After serious consideration, Nan and I ordered two packs _
Cleopatra Lites from Egypt and Al Capone Sweets, Cognac-dipped
cigarillos from Germany. Cleopatra came in a gold striped paper
box, Al Capone in a navy plastic box adorned with the slogan ``no
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Which did not apply to us. Emboldened by Circa Tabac's Candyland
atmosphere, we gave full vent to our disgust of the punitive world
outside. ``On my way over here I passed a Y,'' Nan said, ``and
there was a big sign out front: `The YMCA thanks you for not
smoking within 15 feet of the YMCA entrance.''' We shook our heads,
then bemoaned the new Jackson Pollock stamp, which pictures him in
his famous crouch but erases the cigarette from his mouth. I also
told Nan I had just read that in the next James Bond movie, for the
first time, 007 will not smoke. ``That's censorship!'' she cried.
``Ian Fleming created a character who smoked and drank martinis.''
</P>
<P>
   We were soothed by the arrival of our drinks _ bourbon all
around _ and opened the Cleopatra pack first, reveling in the
freshness of the new-tobacco smell. The cigarettes were just as
good to smoke, with a mild, pleasant taste. The best part, though,
was not what we were smoking but how we were smoking. I leaned all
the way back in my plush chair and stretched my arm along its side,
taking up as much space as I possibly could.
</P>
<P>
   I've become so accustomed to affecting an apologetic cringe when
I smoke in company, twisting one arm out of its socket to try to
aim the smoke in an opposite direction. Even if people insist they
don't mind, someone will invariably make a show of opening a window
or pushing a chair from the table, and I find myself puffing faster
and faster and slumping lower and lower and end up just as glad as
they are when I'm finished. But here, there was no rush, no
schoolmarmish sighs and glares. If I knew how to blow smoke rings,
I would have.
</P>
<P>
   Nan lighted another. ``Why aren't these places all over town?''
she asked longingly. We called Ringelheim over to ask him, but he
said he and Michels were more interested in pursuing South Beach
than midtown. What a shame. At the next table, a waitress opened a
humidor to display some cigars to a man smoking cigarettes. He
considered a while, then shook his head. The four twentysomething
women at another table got up to leave and were quickly replaced by
four more, yet the room stayed at about half capacity. ``People
must hear `cigarette lounge' and think it will smell like a
clogged-up opium den,'' Nan said. ``They probably want to avoid
it.''
</P>
<P>
   I smiled. ``Let them,'' I said, while lighting up an Al Capone.
Even though the Cognac dip tasted sweet, this was a macho smoke,
thick and rolled with dark leaves. A busboy came by and replaced
the dirty ashtray with a clean one _ the fourth time he did so in
less than an hour. Nan looked around. ``It's not the slightest bit
smoky in here,'' she said triumphantly.
</P>
<P>
   Our waitress brought the bill and stayed to chat. We learned
that the BBC recently shot a documentary here on the history of
smoking and that, unsurprisingly, the space was popular for private
parties. It would surely be ideal for a cocktail party. She
laughed. ``Actually, we had a baby shower here a few weeks ago,''
she said. ``They all smoked.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Upon leaving, Nan and I split custody of the cigarettes; she
loved Cleopatra, so I settled for Capone. The following week, when
we got together again, this time for dinner with our husbands, I
rejoiced to see that she had brought along the remainder. We were
at a restaurant with a smoking section, and she and I each lighted
a Cleopatra. Almost instinctively, I leaned back in my chair and
exhaled luxuriantly. My husband took this as a cue to wave his hand
in front of his face. ``Can't you blow it in the other direction?''
he asked plaintively.
</P>
<P>
   Nan's husband, delighted with his anti-smoking company, started
waving his hand, too. She dutifully turned in her seat, bent her
arm back, twisted her neck and blew the smoke sideways. I shifted
my legs so my body faced away from the table and blew the smoke
down, while craning my head back to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Nan hunched over to whisper. ``Next time,'' she said,
``we'll go smoking without them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' I said, ``we'll go to the chiropractor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
