<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (for release Sunday, March 14) 
 
APATHY, LENGTHY DEBATE MAY KILL OVERHAUL OF TEXAS CONSTITUTION &HT;     
By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As chairmen of the state Legislature's
budget-writing committees, Sen. Bill Ratliff and Rep. Rob Junell
usually have enough muscle to remove obstacles to their legislative
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But so far they haven't been able to budge the public apathy
that threatens to smother their proposed overhaul of the
123-year-old Texas Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Senate State Affairs Committee held a public
hearing on the effort, and only six witnesses showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists _ hundreds of whom have signed up to battle each other
over electric utility deregulation, insurance, vouchers, abortion
and numerous other divisive issues _ are mostly ignoring the
Ratliff-Junell proposal. And average Texas residents are nowhere to
be found.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, the Senate's presiding officer, has
received only two letters on the issue, said spokesman Ray
Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, believes that many Texans, tired of
being asked to vote on a long list of constitutional amendments
after each legislative session, would welcome the opportunity to
vote on a shorter, modern document.
</P>
<P>
   But he admits that his and the San Angelo Democrat's proposal,
filed separately in the Senate and the House as SJR1 and HJR1,
hasn't stirred up the public or created any sense of urgency among
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can this Legislature tackle a matter of the gravity of the
constitution in the absence of a crisis?'' Ratliff asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're accused of not being able to do that. I'd like to think
that we have enough members in the Legislature who can look
seriously at something as important as this and be able to do it
proactively rather than be driven by a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   But other lawmakers say it is unrealistic to expect the
Legislature to rewrite the entire state constitution in one
session, particularly when Perry, House Speaker Pete Laney and Gov.
George W. Bush are all cool toward the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem are controversial features in the
Ratliff-Junell proposal _ including a Cabinet and more powers for
the governor, term limits for legislators and changes in the
judiciary _ that could each generate extensive debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we have enough time,'' said state Rep. Joe
Driver, R-Garland, chairman of a special committee that Laney
appointed to consider the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Although constitutional revision is the only issue that Driver's
nine-member committee will address, the panel waited until March 1,
seven weeks into the 20-week session, to have its first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Driver predicted that the House would do little more than
``clean up'' the present constitution by removing some obsolete
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan is to kick something out (of committee) that makes
nonsubstantive or minimal changes,'' he said. ``The present
constitution has worked well for a long time. So I'm not rushing to
make major changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff and Junell argue that the constitution, initially
adopted in 1876, has been able to work at all in modern times
because it has been amended more than 370 times, a tiring process
for both legislators and voters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
