<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-TAYLOR13-COX     03-12 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-TAYLOR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Falling' about a marriage doomed from the start
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is no more finely calibrated human
hell than a bad marriage. Half of us have been in them, and we've
all seen them. Let's face it, even some of the marriages that seem
to be good aren't. Nobody knows what goes on inside a marriage
except the two people in it, and sometimes not even then.
</P>
<P>
   Journalist John Taylor (``Storming the Magic Kingdom,'' ``Circus
of Ambition'') has written a book about his marriage's failure, and
you know it won't be an ennobling saga about rising from the ashes
when he compares people without a prenuptial to criminals who don't
think about prison when they commit their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marriage wasn't hellish, it was simply dispiriting,'' he
writes. ``My wife and I didn't hate each other, we simply got on
each other's nerves.'' Actually, as the book proceeds, it's obvious
that they did dislike each other but were either too well-mannered
or too indifferent to bring out the long knives.
</P>
<P>
   Since Taylor's marriage is his book, to review the latter is to
review the former. So let's go right to What Went Wrong: The
marriage was doomed because neither party had a sense of humor.
There, I've said it. More important than intellectual stimulation,
and damn near as important as sexual compatibility, husbands and
wives had better be able to make each other laugh, because, baby,
it's cold outside.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing _ you'd better never think that it'll
get easy, because it never does. Marriage is hard work; it's
supposed to be hard work, otherwise, every marriage would succeed.
(Personal disclosure: I've been married to my only wife for 13
years, and I've always regarded the entire transaction as a
glorified 12-step program: one day at a time.)
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and his wife separated after 11 1/2 years. He started
having affairs shortly after their daughter was born. What's worse
is that, as Taylor tells it, the marriage was never good.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing here about the good times, the great sex, the
shared interests, the laughter, all those things that can logically
lead you to the delusion that you can spend the rest of your life
with someone.
</P>
<P>
   No, this was one of those three-yard-and-a-cloud-of-dust
relationships, a slow, grinding slog down the field only to find
that the goalposts have receded just when you thought you were in
field-goal range.
</P>
<P>
   The gray, ominous air of an impending icestorm permeates
``Falling.'' ``Our marriage was a mechanism so encrusted with small
disappointments and petty grudges that its parts no longer
closed.'' Rage grows, and it doesn't take much to set it off.
Taylor takes a baseball bat to a car whose alarm won't shut off; at
another point, he assaults a cabdriver who refuses to take him to
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough when one marital partner is a brooder and an
injustice collector, but when there are two of them, it's not a
question of whether things will explode, just when.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it, a successful marriage involves some harsh
choices, as well as a little luck _ not a combination frequently
encountered when the hormones are pounding like jungle drums. There
are more ways to fail in a marriage than to succeed. (My favorite
strategy was told to me by my aunt, who was married for 54 years:
``You both have to agree to always put the other person first.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Falling'' is more clinical than voyeuristic, probably because
Taylor and his wife have a teen-age daughter. Even the feverish
gropings that are early-stage affairs tend, in Taylor's telling, to
devolve into accusations and unhappiness. If his affairs ended up
as miserably as his marriage, why was Taylor bothering?
</P>
<P>
   It's a sad, mildly corrosive book, and Taylor asks a lot of
questions (``Are we all opaque to ourselves? . . . Were we weaker
people than our parents? . . . Did we have less self-control, a
diminished sense of duty?'') without answering them.
</P>
<P>
   There is one nice touch of irony: Taylor gets roped into paying
lifetime maintenance to his ex-wife _ she has an early case of
Parkinson's _ obligating him for an immense sum of money. I rather
like the idea of his writing a conspicuously public book about
their mutual failure in order to get money he'll need to pay
alimony.
</P>
<P>
   There's a tinge of malice to it _ maybe some of this confused,
unconsciously poignant and very dark book rubbed off on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falling: The Story of One Marriage,'' by John Taylor. Random
House; 225 pages; $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
