<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nonfiction top 100 won't get same reation
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Coming: 100 top nonfiction books (Do you
care?)
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to repeat the publicity storm that greeted last spring's
list of the 100 greatest novels of the century, the Modern Library
will be issuing its list of the 100 greatest nonfiction books of
the century at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: there will be no remotely similar reaction. For one
thing, readers don't have anywhere near the emotional connection to
nonfiction that that they do to fiction; for another, the list of
nonfiction books will probably be largely confined to the postwar
era, because, other than occasional bright spots such as Hendrik
Van Loon, H.L. Mencken, H.G. Wells, Douglas Southall Freeman and
John Hersey, nonfiction as such didn't really flower until the
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   In other news, Modern Library is expanding its publications by
inaugurating several new series. The Harlem Renaissance series will
debut this spring, and Modern Library War, edited by Caleb Carr
will begin reissuing books. Later this year will come Modern
Library Exploration, edited by Jon Krakauer, and Modern Library
Hollywood, edited by Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   New wrinkles . . .
</P>
<P>
   Please welcome Vivisphere Publishing, an on-demand publishing
operation that will keep its list of titles digitally stored. Among
the previously out-of-print titles offered are books by Erskine
Caldwell, Mel Arrighi and Terry Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   On-demand publishing boasts that it can print just one copy,
when ordered by a bookstore or any of the online suppliers. The
upside is that, in the very near future, it's possible that many
books will never go out of print. The downside is that, unless the
major publishers get behind this concept with their backlists, all
that on-demand publishers will be able to get are the rights to
books few people want.
</P>
<P>
   Zora . . .
</P>
<P>
   Go Gator and Muddy the Water (Norton, $13.95) is a wonderful
collection of writing by Zora Neale Hurston from the time she spent
working for the Federal Writers' Project during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Hurston's modest stipend enabled her to travel around Florida
and record local folklore and storytelling. There's much humor
here, as field hands gather and try to top each other with
picturesque insults. The Works Projects Administration, the
umbrella organization that the FWP was under, published some of
Hurston's work _ but not much _ in its Florida Guide, but the
enterprising work of editor Pamela Bordelon in the WPA archives
restores more of the work of one of America's better writers to
print.
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard days, lots of work, no money, too much silence. Nobody's
fault. You chose it.''_ Bill Barich
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
