<HEADER>
A8477 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV14-     03-12 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORYDALIS STANDBYS GREET THEIR DISTANT COUSINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 14)  
(mk) 
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are a colorful group, the corydalises. Their small,
trumpet-shaped flowers are tinted in yellows, blues, reds, pinks,
purples or whites. Their foliage spectrum encompasses blue-greens
sheathed with silver to warm greens tipped with bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Many glow in dark corners, and others shine in full sun. Until
the last decade or so, they were almost unknown in 20th-century
American gardens. Now, with the fall of the Soviet Union, there are
a host of exciting new plants becoming available, and there is
renewed interest in old standbys as well.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those standbys enrich my central New Jersey borders. The
first to bloom, usually by late March, is Corydalis solida. Like
most other members of the genus, it does not have a popular name,
so I simply call it pink corydalis. But ``various shades of
lavender-pink corydalis'' would be more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Classified as a perennial, pink corydalis is usually offered by
bulb catalogs because of its tuberous nature. Its refined,
blue-green foliage glistens in the bareness of early spring shade
gardens. The abundant flowers, reaching no more than six inches,
are equally attractive.
</P>
<P>
   As with all corydalis plants, they cluster on short spikes,
technically called racemes.
</P>
<P>
   My plants were a gift from a garden dating back to the turn of
the century. It was around then that pink corydalis disappeared
from horticultural favor. This was no mean feat, because like most
corydalis plants, it is a prolific self-seeder. Perhaps it was a
victim of European sentiment, which deemed it rather plebeian
because it is so widespread throughout the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness American gardeners are no longer in thrall to
European horticultural dictates. With its good looks and carefree
nature, pink corydalis, common though it may be, is wonderful in
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Fernleaf corydalis (C. cheilanthifolia) is an equally handsome,
low-maintenance flower. As long as it has excellent drainage, it is
a superb front-of-the-border or rock garden plant, provided it has
shade or only morning sun. Its soft yellow flowers appear about a
week or two after those of pink corydalis. Similar in height, the
two form a charming pastel combination.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike pink corydalis, which goes dormant in summer, the
fernlike foliage sprays forth joyously, often all year long, from a
central rosette. In fall, bronze shades tip the warm green tones.
In winter, frost often sparkles on the lacy, finely textured
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Fernleaf also differs from pink corydalis in that it is a
relative newcomer. In 1933, as reported in Bailey's Standard
Cyclopedia of Horticulture, fernleaf corydalis was not only rare in
the garden but also ``probably unknown in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't totally true. Henry Francis du Pont, the plant
collector who created Winterthur, had managed to obtain fernleaf
corydalis from central China despite the Japanese invasion of
Manchuria in 1931. He placed it in one of his rocky slopes and then
moved on to other projects.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, when du Pont decided to develop his slope as the Quarry
Garden, he found fernleaf corydalis splashed throughout its nooks
and crannies. Since it had demonstrated such amazing ease of care,
he made it part of the site's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   C.lutea is ubiquitous in England, its golden yellow flowers and
rich blue-green foliage found in locations ranging from sunny
sidewalk cracks to woodland glens. As recently as 1986, Donald
Wyman was writing in his Gardening Encyclopedia that it should be
grown more widely in United States borders.
</P>
<P>
   American gardeners may have hesitated to do so because they may
have heard that yellow corydalis, a perennial that grows to six to
eight inches, is suited only to alkaline limestone soils. That
doesn't hold true in my acidic dirt. From May through light October
frosts, this gem of a workhorse blooms away in dark settings. In
full sun, it flowers from mid-April to mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   While botanists distinguish between C. lutea and C. ochroleuca,
I find they are very similar in appearance, except that C.
ochroleuca bears creamy white flowers, is not as prolific a
self-seeder and must have shade. Nestled in a dark, slightly moist,
protected corner on my property, it flowered from mid-April through
the first week of December last year.
</P>
<P>
   As attractive as these corydalises are, even more enticing ones
are entering the horticultural pipeline. They were discovered by
plant explorers in the Soviet Union during the Cold War and are
only now being seen in the West, largely through the efforts of a
Latvian horticulturist, Janis Ruksans.
</P>
<P>
   From Magadan in far eastern Siberia, there is C. magadanica, a
white-flowered dwarf with silver-tinged foliage. Vladivostok is the
home of C. turczaninowii Kedrovaya Padj, with bright blue flowers
and light green, finely divided leaves.
</P>
<P>
   A profusion of C. solida cultivars have emerged. Blushing Girl,
with soft, creamy pink flowers, was found in Riga. The milky white
flowers of Snowstorm were discovered in a Latvian river valley. The
Penza strain was gathered in central Russia and features flowers
ranging from pure white to muddy blue.
</P>
<P>
   Though long obscure in this century, colorful, easy-care
corydalis flowers could easily become garden staples in the next.
</P>
<P>
   Sources
</P>
<P>
   Old-fashioned C. solida tubers are available from Brent and
Becky's Bulbs, 7463 Heath Trail, Gloucester, Va. 23061; (877)
661-2852; free catalog, and from McClure &AMP; Zimmerman, P.O. Box 368,
Friesland, Wis. 53935; (800) 883-6998; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Fernleaf, C. lutea and C. ochroleuca are offered by a new
mail-order company: Willow Pond Nursery, P.O. Box 192, Hewlett,
N.Y. 11557; (516) 374-2522; catalog, $2; www.willowpondnursery.com.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are feeling adventurous, you may want to get a
catalog from Janis Ruksans, Bulb Nursery, P.K. 441, LV-1010 Riga,
Latvia; the cost is $5 in cash (no checks or money orders).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
