<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINTAGE-AIRPLANE-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINTAGE AIRPLANE HAS PLENTY OF WORK, THANKS TO NAFTA 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
(for release Sunday, March 14) By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas _ In the new era of air cargo along the border,
Charles ``Chuck'' Stewart flies to Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, picks up a load of car parts and drops them off five hours
later in Guadalajara, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The next flight might be up the Rio Grande to load auto
components in Laredo, then down south to a factory in Saltillo,
Mexico. Or up to Evansville, Ind., with wire harnesses for washing
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 49, and his cargo company are riding a growing demand
on the border for air freight delivery of auto and electronic
component parts created by NAFTA and other U.S.-Mexico trade
treaties. The parts are shuttled overnight to northern U.S.
assembly lines after they are manufactured at hundreds of plants
known as ``maquiladoras'' south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fly anything, anywhere, anytime,'' is the catchy slogan of
International Air Services, the company Stewart formed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But notice Stewart doesn't advertise getting there at jet speed.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the workhorses of this family-owned McAllen air
freight service are three World War II-vintage Douglas DC-3s _
silver-bodied, propeller-driven airplanes that are perhaps the most
recognizable, efficient and durable of any American-built aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the jet age, when newer aircraft can whisk their cargo
at 450 mph, the DC-3 can still compete. Although it plows along at
a tame 175 mph, the aging transport can cheaply deliver up to three
tons of bulky parts to a destination 1,200 miles away or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DC-3 still provides a critical service, and I don't see it
ending anytime soon because no one has built an airplane that can
replace it,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing about the DC-3 is that it can go so far. It
carries 800 gallons of fuel _ which is seven hours of flying time
plus reserve. It can go nonstop for 1,200 miles. That's a long way
to carry cargo. It would take a truck days to go that far.''
</P>
<P>
   And NAFTA has given new life to these veteran aircraft, which
for decades were hangared in airfields along the border and flown
deep into Mexico by contraband smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and 1980s, scores of DC-3s, Curtiss C-46s, Lockheed
Lodestars, Fairchild ``Flying Boxcars,'' and other surplus military
transports were crammed full of Sony color TVs, VCRs, radios,
pantyhose, Bic pens, jogging shoes and other consumer items, and
flown to clandestine landing strips all over Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The smuggled goods stocked the shelves of Mexico's huge black
market _ known as the ``fayuca'' trade _ which developed because of
past trade restrictions that slapped hefty customs duties on most
imported items. And while the contraband pilots were not breaking
U.S. law by exporting the merchandise, Mexican officials who caught
them often seized the aircraft, confiscated the untaxed merchandise
and sometimes even threw the pilots in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``As NAFTA came into effect, it became a situation where it was
no longer as profitable to move the stuff clandestinely into
Mexico,'' said Stewart, who acknowledged flying for the fayuca
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Stewart and his pilots are not concerned about operating
cargo airplanes that in most cases are older than the pilots who
fly them _ planes that were first laid out on drafting boards in
1934. Because of strict FAA regulations, every component of a DC-3
except the airframe _ from radios to propellers, tires and engines
_ must be replaced or rebuilt after so many hours of operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very docile, a very smooth-flying airplane. It almost
flies itself,'' said Kyle Battle, a 30-year-old Plano, Texas,
native who often co-pilots a DC-3 for International Air. ``It's
amazing, but there are quite a few still flying.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Stewart's pilots is John Emerson, a former Navy
combat pilot who logged 175 missions over Vietnam and 300 carrier
landings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done all types of flying. I've flown fast, flown high,
shot at people, dropped bombs, taught people to fly, but I've
always wanted to fly `The Doug.' It's the ultimate transport,''
said Emerson, 58, who began flying DC-3s last month after moving to
McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   For Emerson, Stewart and other pilots, the allure of the DC-3 is
not only the plane's rugged utility _ Stewart last year flew one
which had logged 104,000 flight hours _ but the opportunity to fly
a bona fide hunk of aviation lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This airplane has a colorful and very diverse history,''
Stewart said. ``It has done everything you can imagine. There's a
version built with skis on it that has done research work in the
Arctic and Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been in virtually every theater of operation in the
world, pressed into any kind of service you can think of. This
airplane is built like a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufactured in huge numbers by Douglas Aircraft Co., the DC-3
was built after American Airlines asked the company to widen its
already popular DC-2 so sleeping berths could be installed. The
company reluctantly agreed, and international aviation experts say
the resulting airliner is one of the world's best.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, a military version of the DC-3, called the
C-47 Skytrain, was produced with reinforced floors and double cargo
doors.
</P>
<P>
   The C-47 ``made such an important contribution to the U.S. war
effort that General Eisenhower considered them to be one of the
four most significant weapons of World War II,'' according to
``Jane's Encyclopedia of Aviation.''
</P>
<P>
   They even fought as heavily armed gunships in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Douglas built 10,654 such aircraft between 1935 and
1947, Russian allies produced another 2,000 and Japan built 485
with plans obtained before the war, according to ``Jane's.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the thousands manufactured, finding a DC-3 today is
not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's air freight operation has three. Two were purchased
last year in Michigan and Canada where they were hauling freight or
passengers to the Northwest Territories. The third DC-3 was found
in an aircraft graveyard in the Arizona desert and refitted.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a Vietnam veteran who came to McAllen in 1982 from
Michigan to fly air charters, decided to stay in the Rio Grande
Valley ``because I liked the climate, I liked the people and I
thought there was opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty obvious with NAFTA that McAllen's airport needed
an operation that was going to specialize in cargo,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
