</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EELS-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (for release Sunday, March 14) 
THEY'RE ROUNDING UP EELS IN TEXAS 
 
By TERRY KLIEWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONAVILLE, Texas _ Out here on the fertile prairie west of
Houston, the coming summer holds the promise of something beyond
its usual bounty of tall corn, fat watermelons and sleek cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Signs are that 1999 will be a banner year for eels, too.
</P>
<P>
   You heard right, pardner: eels, those slimy, snakey fish chiefly
known for lurking in coral reefs and providing skins for belts and
wallets.
</P>
<P>
   It so happens that the freshwater variety, which do their
lurking in rivers and ponds, are eminently edible and much in
demand in certain markets. To serve those markets, a fast-growing
Chinese company called Longshan Group is out to make Waller County
the eel capital of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Eels may not seem like a natural fit for a county where most of
the water is found in stock tanks or irrigation ditches and marine
life generally means crawfish, turtles and frogs. But Longshan,
whose eel ranch is about halfway between Brookshire and Hempstead,
has been raising blue eels at the location since 1997 for sale to
Asian restaurants and supermarkets from Houston to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Doing business in this country as Longshan USA, the company
recently acquired an indoor aquarium facility near Katy where tiny
inch-long baby eels are being nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, by month's end Longshan expects to fire up the
ovens at its new processing plant in Hempstead, where filleted eel
will be steamed or broiled, packaged and shipped across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Longshan is finishing what amounts to its start-up
phase, during which it acquired a production site, dug and filled
ponds, and raised and marketed its initial _ herds? crops? schools?
_ of eel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term is `harvests,' '' explains Christina Lynn Koo,
Longshan's chief financial officer. When the 6-inch fingerlings get
to 1{ to 2 pounds, or about 18 inches long, ``we harvest them by
seining the ponds. We've already had a number of harvests.''
</P>
<P>
   A baby eel reaches market size in a year to 18 months, during
which it spends its time idling in the muddy water and grazing on
the gelatinous glop of fish meal and potato starch that's dumped at
water's edge each day.
</P>
<P>
   The budding eels' only worry comes from above, says General
Manager Jim Meader. ``The herons and cormorants manage to get a
bunch of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Left alone and fed regularly, these eels would grow to 10 pounds
or more, but by then they would be up to 3 feet long, too awkward
to net and handle, and far too tough for customers' tastes.
</P>
<P>
   The seining and culling, which assigns market-size eels to
holding tanks and sends the rest back to the ponds, is a
never-ending chore. Each of the 40 eel ponds on the Longshan site
is seined twice monthly.
</P>
<P>
   The task involves first stretching a 20-by-400-foot net along
two sides of the 2-acre pond. Then, with the help of workers in the
water and tractors on the levees, the net is guided slowly across
to the opposite corner, where the now-compressed net is filled with
a roiling, writhing mass of eels.
</P>
<P>
   The workers then move the eels into tank-trailers, using
hand-held basket nets, and trundle them over to the sorting table
and holding tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The eels are a handful. Or rather, they're not: Smooth and
slippery as, well, eels, they easily squirm out of all but the
firmest handholds. On the plus side, their catfishlike skins are
tough and durable, and they have no teeth or spiny fins to watch
out for.
</P>
<P>
   Eels sorted for shipment are put in plastic bags with ice,
boxed, then trucked away, usually to Houston's Bush
Intercontinental Airport, in a cold-induced stupor. Eels survive
unusually well in very little water, and there's no fresher product
than one that's still alive when it arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process _ ``very labor intensive,'' Koo admits _ was
imported from China, where eel-raising is a huge industry. The
pilot project here has been modeled after its Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That even included the construction of the ponds,'' says Koo.
``A man from China was brought in to supervise the earth-moving,
and he relied on his mental picture of the ponds back home to
determine the size and banking. The `blueprint' for everything was
in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Meader says the ``old country'' approach resulted in a few
problems, such as misaligned levees, but there's nothing that can't
be fixed as the operation matures.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described jack-of-all-trades who until recently managed
an area fish farm, Meader, 50, already is plotting improvements for
the Longshan operation. Right away, he wants to automate the
tedious seining and sorting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes way too long,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there's no arguing with success, and so far the
Monaville eel ranch has been that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to reinvent the wheel for a lot of our business side,
but things are coming together,'' says Koo. ``Our sales are up.
We're expanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Koo came into the eel business by way of her father, Carlos Koo,
a California businessman who became lead investor in Longshan's new
stateside project through friends with the company in China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese wanted a foothold in the U.S. market because they
were concerned about possible over-reliance on Japanese buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Father tapped 26-year-old daughter, who has a master's degree in
economics from the University of California at Davis to oversee the
project. With no previous agricultural experience, she concedes she
felt a little overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it seemed like an adventure, and my dad needed someone he
could trust. So here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   She first scouted possible sites in California and Arizona, but
either land costs were too high or water supplies too iffy to make
the grade. On a hunch, she moved her search to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't end up right here by design, but just by luck _ good
luck,'' says Lynn Koo. ``But this is rice-farming territory and
there's lots of water. It figured we ought to look here.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting started at the 255-acre site involved more than
pond-digging. Wells had to be drilled, pipe laid, pumps installed,
permits and licenses secured, feed supplies arranged _ the list
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of eels to the ponds was almost an
afterthought. ``We weren't even sure they'd grow here. In China
they grow in river water,'' says Koo.
</P>
<P>
   But grow they did. The first 500,000 fingerlings, air-shipped
from China, were put in the water here in the spring of 1997. By
the end of 1998, Longshan had sold its first 15,000 pounds of fresh
eel.
</P>
<P>
   Production capacity at the site here is about 50,000 pounds a
year, Koo says.
</P>
<P>
   The operation doesn't include eel-breeding. Meader says eel
reproduction is somewhat mysterious and takes place only in the
wild, which is why captured baby eels must be imported regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Meader guesses the facility now has about 120,000 pounds of eel
in the water, ranging in size from a few ounces to as much as three
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   If 15,000 pounds of eel sales _ or even the targeted 50,000 _
doesn't sound like a lot, Meader reminds that the eel market isn't
quite the same as that for catfish or beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish sells for maybe 75 cents a pound,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The price for live freshwater eel: $5 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big money,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECUADOR-ECONOMY-$ADV1     03-12 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-ECONOMY-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (for release Sunday March 14) 
 
ECUADOR'S SINKING ECONOMY COMPARED TO THE TITANIC 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Once again, things seem to be getting crazy in
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after mass demonstrations led to the ouster of a
flamboyant president who called himself ``El Loco,'' or ``the Crazy
One,'' protesters returned to the streets last week to decry their
current president's failure to stanch an economic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, inflation jumped so fast that supermarkets hired
emergency help to keep up with price changes. Long lines formed at
instant-cash machines after banks were ordered to shut until next
Monday to stop a panicked run on deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Police and army troops used tear gas to break up riots and
looting during a two-day national strike. Following wild rumors
that President Jamil Mahuad was preparing to resign, the government
declared a 60-day state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad survived last week's strike. But he acknowledged that
this impoverished South American nation of 12 million people is on
the brink of disaster. At one point, he compared Ecuador's sinking
economy to the Titanic. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In a nationally televised speech Thursday night, Mahuad tried
to stop the hemorrhaging by proposing steep budget cuts and tax
increases. Many fear the austerity measures will provoke more
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador's worst economic crisis in decades was brought on by
natural and man-made disasters.
</P>
<P>
   A brief border war with Peru in 1995 led to a surge in military
spending that, analysts say, the country could not afford. Soon
afterward, prices for oil, one of Ecuador's main exports, began to
plunge. Last year, Ecuador's oil income dropped to nearly one-half
of 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 El Nino weather pattern caused $2.6 billion in flood
damage along the nation's Pacific coast. Washed-out roads and
bridges prevented exporters from getting their products to ports,
leading to a wave of defaults on bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   Bad loans _ plus the January currency crisis in Brazil, which
sparked capital flight throughout Latin America _ led to the
failure of a handful of Ecuador's leading banks. An &UR;  &LR; effort to bail
them out sparked inflation and weakened the sucre, which has lost
half of its value in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our money isn't worth anything,'' lamented Francisco Lara, a
truck driver. His monthly wage of about 2.2 million sucres is now
worth less than $200.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of confronting the looming fiscal deficit, analysts say,
Ecuador's political class has been entangled in scandals and
infighting.
</P>
<P>
   The past two presidents _ Abdala Bucaram, who was widely called
``El Loco,'' and Fabian Alarcon, who served as Bucaram's
replacement until new elections were held last year _ were
sidetracked by corruption charges and left office in disgrace. Even
before Mahuad was sworn in last August, Ecuador's economic
situation was viewed as critical.
</P>
<P>
   Mahuad, a Harvard graduate and a successful two-term mayor of
Quito, initially won wide support by signing a treaty to end the
long-running border dispute with Peru and by waging a war on
government corruption.
</P>
<P>
   To address the economic crisis, he eliminated subsidies on
cooking gas and raised gasoline prices. Further austerity measures
were blocked by legislators in the 121-member Congress, where
Mahuad's political party lacks a majority of seats.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been months of gridlock, according to analysts.
In his speech Thursday, Mahuad called on Congress to do the right
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I govern if I'm not given the indispensable tools to
do so?`` Mahuad asked in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say that some of Ecuador's problems are Mahuad's own
doing, however. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In a country with one of the lowest rates of tax collection in
Latin America, Mahuad eliminated the income tax, a move viewed as
favoring the rich. He replaced it with a 1 percent fee on all bank
transactions, a regressive measure that affects far more people
than an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   And against the advice of experts, Mahuad engineered the bailout
of the loosely regulated financial sector.
</P>
<P>
   The government loaned more than $1 billion to several banks, a
cash infusion that required the nation's central bank to print more
sucres. That drove up inflation and pushed down the value of the
currency. The sucre, which traded at 6,400 to the dollar in
November, reached a record of 18,000 to the dollar early this month
before stabilizing at 12,800. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Diego Cornejo, assistant editor of the Quito newspaper Hoy,
said that Mahuad felt obligated to go forward with the bailout,
because he had received huge campaign contributions from bankers.
Still, eight banks have closed down or have been taken over by the
state in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its troubles, Ecuador _ due to its small size _ has
received just a fraction of the attention showered on other
financially strapped Latin American nations such as Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Some people complain that after Nicaragua and Honduras were
waylaid by Hurricane Mitch last fall, governments and banks
canceled parts of their foreign debt. By contrast, there was no
debt relief for Ecuador after the El Nino flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of debt relief is extremely sensitive. In a nation
where 60 percent of the population is classified as poor, 40
percent of the annual budget is swallowed by payments and interest
on the $15 billion foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   In just seven months, support for Mahuad has dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers are baffled by what they call Mahuad's detached
style. Until Mahuad's Thursday night speech, he had all but
disappeared from public view.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged Congress to approve within 30 days an increase in
the sales tax from 10 percent to 15 percent as well as a tax on
luxury vehicles and a law to imprison tax evaders. He restricted
the amount of money that can be withdrawn from checking and savings
accounts to stem capital flight and proposed steep spending cuts
and banking reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Even the U.S. State Department jumped into the fray, calling on
Ecuador's Congress and the Mahuad administration to ``work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   An impasse could stall negotiations for a long-term accord with
the International Monetary Fund that would give Ecuador access to a
desperately needed $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's strike, demonstrators burned paper-mache
effigies of Mahuad and called for him to step down. But cooler
heads noted that the removal of former President Bucaram _ who was
fired by Congress for ``mental incapacity'' in February 1997 _ made
little difference in the fate of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to sacrifice just so the rich get richer.
That's why they are in the streets,'' said Leonardo Carpio, an oil
worker. ``The idea isn't to oust Mahuad,'' Carpio said. ``The
country can't keep going from coup to coup.''
</P>
<P>
   John Otis is a free-lance journalist based in Bogota, Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
