</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF SIMULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Golf courses come in all shapes and sizes. So do golf-simulation
programs for the computer. We'll look at two today, ranging from
the ridiculous (3-D Ultra MiniGolf Deluxe) to the somewhat more
sublime (Tiger Woods 99).
</P>
<P>
   3-D Ultra MiniGolf Deluxe (Windows; about $20-$25) from Dynamix
is the sequel title to the 3-D Ultra MiniGolf. That program had 18
holes of miniature golf, some of them pretty strange.
</P>
<P>
   The standard putt-it-through-the-windmill ones were there, but
so were some other unconventional offerings. One of them, for
instance, was underwater, where an octopus' tentacles were one of
the hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The Deluxe version builds on that theme. Its first 18 holes are
from the original game, but it has added nine more. The new version
also can be played over a local-area network, modem or the
Internet. Internet play is free and supports up to four players.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics are good, and the themes of the holes are generally
well conceived. Hitting up the wrong ramp of the sawmill hole, for
instance, sends sawdust flying back from the mill accompanied by
the sound of the blade ripping into lumber. It costs a penalty
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   On another hole, the ball must be putted up a ramp so that it
goes into the screen of a drive-in movie while a monster is in
view.
</P>
<P>
   The animated characters found throughout the holes have
``intelligence coding,'' said a Dynamix spokeswoman. That means the
spider that hides in the ruins on one hole and the shark that
inhabits another can react to the ball in a more realistic fashion
rather than just wondering aimlessly on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   There are two methods for controlling the putter. Players can
either use the mouse to aim and move the putter, or use the
EasyPutt meter where a power bar gauges the shot based on how long
the mouse button is held down.
</P>
<P>
   Registered buyers of the first version can get a discount from
the publisher for buying the new version.
</P>
<P>
   A playable download demo version is available at www.sierra.com.
It's more than 40 megabytes, so downloading may take time.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods 99 from EA Sports (Windows, PlayStation; about
$35-$40) is this year's version of last year's PGA Tour Golf 98.
Putting a Tiger in the CD-ROM tank is EA's marketing answer to
Links 99, which features a picture of Arnold Palmer on the box
front.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to compare Woods with Links. It's even best not
to, because I expect EA Sports and Access Software, Links' parent
company, had two different markets in mind. Links 99 seems geared
for the Arnie-era golfer who wants pure, super-realistic golf play.
</P>
<P>
   Woods 99, on the other hand, moves along quickly. And while the
game emulates golf, it has many helpful features to make play easy
_ and ways to turn off those features to increase the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Woods 99 offers solid graphics _ although not quite as sharp as
Links _ with quick screen changes between shots. It's possible,
playing against one computer opponent, to move through an entire
18-hold round in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The game supports high-resolution graphics (up to 1600X1200),
but be advised that the higher settings will require a fast system
and a 3-D video card with a chunk of on-board memory to move things
along, and even that can produce choppy graphics if the computer
chemistry isn't right.
</P>
<P>
   There are a wide range of golfers from which to choose, Woods
being only one of several PGA pros on the disk, as well as three
courses: Pebble Beach, TPC at Summerlin, and TPC at Sawgrass. You
can set the game play of the pros from poor to extraordinary _ a
handy feature for allowing users to get the feel of playing and
still remain competitive with the pros.
</P>
<P>
   My 11-stroke lead on Woods looked impressive on the scorecard as
we went back to the clubhouse. I just hoped no one saw me playing
from the red tees, and with Woods set to play only his ``good''
game.
</P>
<P>
   Another big handicap-reducer: The swing meter has a red and
green button on it. Pressing either button before a shot or a putt
automatically lines up the shot and adjusts for wind speed and lie.
Use the green button for a safe shot, the red button for an
aggressive one.
</P>
<P>
   Those items help introduce users to the game, and they allow new
players to play their friends who have become seasoned on the
course without hacking around the course and crisscrossing the
green trying to hit the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Putting without this feature is a good deal harder than it
should be. More than once during the game, the on-screen player
blocked the view of the cup, making it impossible to line up the
putt. The view can be changed, but lining up a putt looking at it
from an off-angle isn't much more of a help.
</P>
<P>
   Players who are experienced at golf sims may prefer the
traditional gameplay offered by Links 99. Those who want more input
before making a purchase can download a playable demo of Tiger
Woods 99 (http://www.gamespot.com/sports/tigerwoo/demos.html), but
take note that it's a 9-megabyte-plus file and takes some time.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Camera Uses
</P>
<P>
   The Kodak DVC323 digital video camera is a small color camera
designed to sit on top of a monitor and show other people on the
Internet what you look like. It has other uses beyond video
conferencing, however.
</P>
<P>
   It came out last year, and the only way to hook it up to a
computer was through a Universal Serial Bus. Not many home users
had one of those on their machines, but with computer prices
dropping, and new ones replacing old ones in the home, USBs are
more common. (It's a small, flat opening in the back of the
computer about the width of a thumb.)
</P>
<P>
   USB connections are now all the rage, in fact. No wonder. Plug a
device in. That's it. The computer knows it's there. Moreover, if
you've forgotten to connect the device, simply plug it in without
rebooting the computer. It will still be found.
</P>
<P>
   The DVC323 is an upgraded version of the DVD300. It supports 30
frames a second (provided the computer has a fast processor) and
has a resolution of about 350-by-290 pixels in video mode. In full
resolution mode for picture snapping, it has a 640-by-480
resolution. That's good, and can be used to make printed shots as
long as the finished product is kept to a small format. For users
who want to turn out pictures to enlarge and pass around, the
resolution falls short.
</P>
<P>
   The camera has a large depth of field, so focusing won't be a
problem. And it can be focused on objects as close as half-foot by
a knob on the top of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   The USB feature gives the camera its power. So if you have a
laptop computer with a USB port, the camera becomes portable for
outdoor pictures away from the wall plug. A 10-foot cord gives it
additional movement.
</P>
<P>
   It has the ability to white-balance almost any lighting
automatically from incandescent to fluorescent. PictureWorks Live
software was included with the unit I tested.
</P>
<P>
   Exposures may be set automatically by the camera, or adjusted
manually by the user using software.
</P>
<P>
   The camera's price varies from store to store. The cheapest
price was found from a mail-order company on the Web: about $140.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer
columns are on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
