<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S ECONOMY SHRANK 2.8 PERCENT IN 1998, GOVERNMENT REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Despite a surge in public spending that was meant to
help touch off a recovery, the Japanese economy was still shrinking
in the fourth quarter of last year, the government reported Friday.
The decline, at an annual rate of 3.2 percent, was a surprisingly
sharp drop that extended the economic contraction to a record five
straight quarters.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998 as a whole, the economy contracted by 2.8 percent, the
first annual decline in a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   The results show that Japan, the world's second-largest economy,
remained slumped in its worst recession since the end of World War
II. Some economists said that Friday's announcement tended to dash
hopes that Japan might be beginning to recover from its long
downturn. Others noted that the figures, which track the
September-to-December period, are a lagging indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is the last thing Tokyo needs these days as it
tries to raise confidence at home and abroad and entice investors
back to the financial markets and shoppers back to stores. These
kinds of gloomy announcements, particularly after officials have
been making hopeful comments, tend to erode public sentiment and
undermine the credibility of Japanese officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a very, very serious decline,'' said Jeffrey D. Young,
economist at Nikko Salomon Smith Barney in Tokyo. ``It's huge for a
big economy.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last eight years, the economy here has done little more
than seesaw up and down, eking out little overall gain. In recent
years, U.S. officials and other governments have called on Japan to
do its part to revive growth throughout ailing Asia. Now, the
dismal results may intensify calls that the government try
different methods to battle the recession, given that the vast
amounts of money poured into economic revival have so far shown few
results.
</P>
<P>
   The government has released some encouraging data in recent
weeks, and this has raised hopes for an economic lift. But the
situation is highly fluid. Company bankruptcies have plummeted 40
percent from last year's levels, but unemployment is hovering at
record highs. Companies are beginning to sell off some of their
stockpiles, but price deflation is spreading. Orders for new homes
are up, but the houses have not yet been built.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the worst figures in Friday's data reflected the
weakness in home building, which fell in the fourth quarter by 7
percent over the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment was that consumer spending, which
makes up some 60 percent of the economy, fell by one-tenth of 1
percent for the quarter, compared with the July-to-September
period. Businesses also cut investment by 5.7 percent over the
previous quarter, an annualized fall of 21 percent that was the
third-largest drop on record.
</P>
<P>
   The government is under enormous pressure to deliver some
positive results. Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi has vowed to achieve
five-tenths of 1 percent growth for the year that begins on April
1, and Friday, Hiromu Nonaka, the chief Cabinet secretary, echoed
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be easy for Obuchi to hold onto his job
unless he can ensure that the bad numbers are not repeated,'' said
Robert Alan Feldman, an economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Investors have begun to favor Japan's stock market once again in
recent weeks. The government has made significant progress in
cleaning up the nation's financial system, nationalizing two large
banks last fall and toughening the rules that govern the way banks
treat several hundred billion dollars in bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the government marked a milestone by reaching final
plans to pour $63 billion of taxpayers' money into recapitalizing
the banks. Government officials also declared _ to a skeptical
investment community _ that the banks are almost finished with
writing off their unrecoverable loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this step, we are now about to finish the most difficult
part of our job of tackling the bad-loan problem,'' Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Friday at a news conference. ``I
think this will restore the financial industry to health.''
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have also been heartened by dramatic steps taken
by the Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, which last week
drove down the overnight interest rate effectively to zero. Some of
the investors had expected the Bank of Japan to take more steps at
its policy meeting Friday, either to further lower other short-term
interest rates or to signal a shift toward increasing the money
supply through quantitative targets.
</P>
<P>
   But its board members made no change in policy Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taichi Sakaiya, head of the Economic Planning Agency, had
recently suggested that there was a ``quickening'' in the economy
and that the bottom might come soon. He said in an interview this
week that October was probably the worst moment in the recession.
Friday he reiterated his view that the decline might soon stop, but
he avoided any specific talk of the recession's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many signs these days of the economy's slide being
halted,'' Sakaiya said.
</P>
<P>
   Private economists acknowledge that it is difficult to pinpoint
the bottom of an economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, it can be said that when we are near a turning
point, it is very difficult to judge _ whether the economy is still
going down, leveling off, or picking up; this is a difficult
judgment for any economy,'' said Makoto Nomura, chief economist at
Sumitomo Life Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   He added, half-jokingly, ``So when it's difficult, that usually
means it's near the turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakaiya also underscored the importance of economic
restructuring, which has been a slow and tedious process in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   If done properly, restructuring Japan Inc. will make companies
more efficient, but it will also increase unemployment and bring
about even more pain in the economy. Some economists say that with
companies stepping up their reorganization plans, the economy could
fall even further this year, putting pressure on the government to
turn to steeper tax cuts, even higher public spending and finally
move to sharply expand the money supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
