<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS &LR;      03-12 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TAKES ON GORE IN BUSH'S BACK YARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley said Friday he is a
bolder leader than Vice President Al Gore, his almost certain rival
for the Democratic presidential nomination next year, and portrayed
himself as more in touch with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   During a fund-raising trip to Austin, the former New Jersey
senator also challenged a potential Republican candidate in the
2000 campaign, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, to sign hate crimes
legislation in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bradley trails Gore in the polls, he said he was the
better candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the real questions is who's best to lead the country
at this time in our history, given our circumstance and what our
future could be. And I think I'm the better person to do that,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who served in the Senate from 1978 to 1996, said he has
spent time traveling the nation and learning about people, while
Gore, the former congressman and senator, has spent much of his
time in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is the only announced candidate against Gore for the
Democratic nomination. He came to Bush's back yard to raise money,
adding about $100,000 to his presidential campaign fund at a
Thursday night event.
</P>
<P>
   Bush this week formed an exploratory committee as a prelude to
deciding on his own campaign for president.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley attended a luncheon hosted by supporters of a bill aimed
at hate crimes _ those committed against people because of their
sexual orientation, race, gender or religious affiliation. He later
told reporters that Bush should support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think leaders have to step up, and no leader should be
silent on this,'' Bradley said. ``If I get the Democratic
nomination and the governor of Texas gets the Republican nomination
and he does not support passage of this bill, I will make this an
issue in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not said whether he would support a hate crimes bill,
saying he views all violent crime as acts of hate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would provide help to small counties prosecuting
murders, make Texas' hate crimes definition conform to one upheld
by the U.S. Supreme Court, and assign a prosecutor to coordinate
hate crimes in the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's been silent or not. I only know that if
it passes, he's (Bush) got to support it,'' Bradley said. ``He has
to support passage.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates or those considering running in the Republican
primary include Elizabeth Dole, a former Cabinet secretary and head
of the American Red Cross; Arizona Sen. John McCain; former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander; conservative commentator Pat
Buchanan; publisher Steve Forbes; and conservative leader Gary
Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that if Bush does run and wins the GOP nomination,
Democrats should not write off Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Texas is no different than any other state in the
union when it comes to a presidential race. People are saying who
do I trust with my life, who do I trust with my job, and who has a
set of values that are similar to mine?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
