(Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A powerful and dangerous storm system churning slowly east from
Texas will bring an assorted arsenal of heavy weather to parts of
the Gulf states and lower Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow swath of moderate to heavy snow will fall across the
middle Mississippi and lower Ohio Valleys as a conveyor of moist,
cold air on the northern flank of the low-pressure system wraps
westward around the low.
</P>
<P>
   More than a foot of snow is possible from eastern Oklahoma
across northeast Arkansas and into the lower Ohio Valley by
Saturday night. Accumulations may be limited on the southern edge
of the snowy swath where snow changes to sleet or rain.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, moderate to locally heavy rains, some with
thunder, will deluge the Tennessee Valley and areas just south of
the lower Ohio Valley. Farther south, a line of potent
thunderstorms, some with drenching rain and damaging winds, will
develop along and ahead of a cold front moving east from eastern
Texas. Behind the front, brisk winds from the northwest will whip
across west Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rain will return to the Pacific Northwest as a cold
front approaches from the Pacific. Farther east, sunny, mild
weather will embrace much of the Great Basin and Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds associated with low pressure that has been stalled for
the past few days off the New England Coast will slowly recede
northward, with only a few residual snow showers and flurries in
the mountains of northern New England. Gusty winds from the
northwest will continue over parts of eastern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Makings of a Storm
</P>
<P>
   A burst of rain doused San Nicholas Island in Southern
California on Thursday as a compact but potent Pacific disturbance
arrived. Such an active disturbance in the southern branch of the
jet stream is a key ingredient for making a large storm in the East
because its southern path allows it to garner moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico. The next ingredient for a large storm in the East
is a timely merging with a disturbance from the northern branch of
the jet stream, which allows the high-altitude part of the system
to intensify, which, in turn, causes the surface storm to rapidly
deepen.
</P>
</TEXT>
