<HEADLINE>
REST ASSURED, ARIZONA WOULD DIVE INTO A WATER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Every so often I wonder: Is the day creeping up on us,
living as we do in the hottest desert in North America, when we
will turn on our faucets and all that comes out are a few pitiful
drops?
</P>
<P>
   That question arose after reading a story in last Sunday's
paper, warning that a worldwide water shortage is fast approaching.
The story was pegged to steps being taken by Canada, which holds a
fifth of the world's supply of fresh water, to ban bulk sales to
America and other nations.
</P>
<P>
   A similar prediction was made in a recent book called ``Tapped
Out,'' by ex-Illinois Sen. Paul Simon. He says a ``water crisis of
catastrophic proportions will explode on us'' early in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   A few things to think about:
</P>
<P>
   - Nine thousand children die every day due to thirst or polluted
water.
</P>
<P>
   - Global demand for water is doubling every 21 years. By 2025,
nearly 3 billion people in 52 countries _ roughly a third of the
world's projected population _ are expected to suffer from chronic
water shortages, even without a serious drought.
</P>
<P>
   - A predicted water shortage in China, the world's most populous
nation, could have severe repercussions. Unable to grow enough
food, China would likely import massive amounts of grain, sending
up prices and starving poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
   - The next century's wars will be over water, a 1998 World Bank
report predicted.
</P>
<P>
   - Expecting 15 million more people in the next 20 years,
California water officials last year predicted a ``serious water
shortage'' without much stronger conservation efforts and new
storage projects.
</P>
<P>
   The last two points bring to mind one of Arizona's oddest and
boldest moves.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five years ago, Gov. Benjamin B. Moeur dispatched the
Arizona National Guard to the Colorado River during the
construction of Parker Dam in an effort to stop California from
impinging on our state's water rights. It marked the last time in
American history that one state took up arms against another.
</P>
<P>
   Moeur, a man with a flair for the dramatic, sent a 100-man
militia unit and trucks with mounted machine guns to the
construction site, and work was halted. He contended that the dam
was illegal because it hadn't been authorized by Congress. The U.S.
Supreme Court ruled in Arizona's favor, but Congress soon passed a
bill approving the dam and enabling California to drink heavily
from the river.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive as his show of force may have been, Moeur was properly
mindful of the state's future. He could see that Southern
California would outgrow its annual entitlement of 4.4 million
acre-feet and thus might ``borrow'' what it needed from Arizona's
2.8 million allotment. That's just what happened; California has
taken up to 5.2 million acre-feet. Moeur feared that Arizona might
have trouble getting its full share when it was needed.
</P>
<P>
   That fear has not been extinguished. Along with its swelling
population, California has been gaining political clout that could
be used to increase its Colorado River entitlement. Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt recently heightened that concern when he
commented on the pressing needs of California and Nevada, implying
that Arizona might have to help out.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows when Arizona will need its full share, but 30 years
from now would be a fair guess, said Rita Pearson, director of the
state Department of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
   If Southern California can't meet its demands then, and can't
get more water short of towing icebergs from the Arctic, a
political power play to cut into this state's allotment doesn't
seem far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's drought, too much growth here, a covetous
California or all three, Arizona's water future is not guaranteed.
Fighting a water war may sound like a crackpot notion, but that's
probably what people said in 1934, too.
</P>
<P>
   How much provocation would it take for Arizona to send troops
again to the Colorado River to defend its supply?
</P>
<P>
   Pearson had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given this state's tenacious attitude toward water,'' she
said, ``not much.''
</P>
<P>
   I can see our military convoy heading for Hoover Dam. Don't get
greedy, California. Your water thieves won't see tomorrow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
