<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS WORK TO SAVE U.S. CONSTITUTION, OTHER FAMOUS DOCUMENTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The original copy of the U.S. Constitution has
survived more than 200 years. On Wednesday government engineers and
scientists will unveil the model of a set of new protective cases
they hope will preserve it and other famous documents for at least
another 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1951 the U.S. Constitution, Bill of Rights and Declaration
of Independence have been displayed at the National Archives in
sealed, bronze-framed cases. The three documents, called ``the
Charters,'' are among Washington's most popular tourist
attractions, bringing more than 1.2 million visitors a year through
building's rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, scientists discovered that the glass in the
documents' display cases was starting to deteriorate. The changes
weren't visible to the eye, but they were detected by a special,
NASA-built camera.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cooper, an Archives spokeswoman, said the documents
themselves currently aren't in any danger but that if the problem
is ignored, they could eventually deteriorate as well.
</P>
<P>
   When the four old cases were built, air was pumped out and they
were filled with helium and some water vapor to keep the parchment
documents from becoming brittle. A sheet of glass touches the
parchment, holding it in place, which experts now say could harm
it.
</P>
<P>
   In the six new cases that will be constructed of titanium and
aluminum, the documents will be held in place with clear polyester
clips rather than glass. The cases themselves will have panes of
two layers of glass separated by a layer of plastic, and they will
be filled with argon, an inert gas, and water vapor.
</P>
<P>
   The new cases, unlike the current ones, will allow for easy
removal of the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said this will give the Archives more flexibility to make
changes in the cases if any problems develop or if there are
further advances in technology that would allow the documents to be
preserved in an even better way.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists and engineers who have designed the new
enclosures expect them to last much longer than the current cases,
perhaps indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   As the restoration proceeds, the Archives rotunda will be
refurbished to accommodate the two extra cases, which will display
the two middle pages of the Constitution. Currently, the cases show
only the first and last pages of the Constitution, which was
written in 1787, as well as the 1776 Declaration of Independence
and the Bill of Rights, which was ratified in 1791.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the Archives' public exhibits will be closed shortly
after July 4, 2001, and won't reopen until 2003. The building will
still be open to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Charters aren't the only American treasures under
renovation. The Washington Monument is currently wrapped in
scaffolding. The inside of the 555-foot monument, where tourists
can ride almost to the top to see panoramic views of the city,
reopened last month after being closed for five months.
</P>
<P>
   In December the Star-Spangled Banner was removed from its
display area in the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of
American History. But in mid-to-late April it will return, and the
public will be able to view the restoration of the 184-year-old
flag as it proceeds over the next three years in the museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1823EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
