<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN14-COX     03-12 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catching up with my old friend Rufus
 &HT;    EMBARGOED for Sunday, March 14
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My friend Rufus and I ate cheeseburgers and
home fries and washed them down with lots of iced tea at Big T in
Kilgore the other day. We caught up on each other's lives while
inhaling the grease-and-cigarette ambience of one of our favorite
eateries, a venerable place favored by oilfield workers and those
with discerning palates in search of a cholesterol-laden meal.
</P>
<P>
   The place is always full at lunch. I haven't eaten here in
probably eight or nine years, but the waitress looked familiar. A
collection of hard hats with stickers on them adorned the wall near
us. Total tab for both of us, including tip: $8.71. It's that kind
of place.
</P>
<P>
   O Rufus Lovett, no period after the ``O'' because it doesn't
stand for anything (at least that's his story) teaches photography
at Kilgore College. He's been there more than two decades. Now he's
gaining a reputation as one of the state's finest documentary
photographers. Truth be known, he's the main reason I quit taking
pictures for a living and got into editing newspapers. It didn't
take long to figure out I was nowhere in his league when it comes
to technical skill, creativity and, more importantly, an innate
ability to establish a rapport with anybody, from a resident of
Houston's Fourth Ward to a poor butcher in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   I first met Rufus when I took a job as college photographer,
yearbook adviser and part-time teacher at KC in a misguided attempt
to wean myself from the addiction of putting out newspapers. I
lasted a year before fleeing academia for the raw comfort of
running a country newspaper out in West Texas, until I got a
reprieve and returned to the Pine Curtain. At the time, Rufus drove
a 1965 (I think) Cadillac, and he sported an earring and an
attitude. The earring and Cadillac are gone, but the attitude is
still there.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean that in a bad way. Rufus just has a way about him.
He can talk to governors and poor folks living out in the middle of
nowhere and put both at ease. It's a talent that has stood him well
as he travels Texas and Asia, photographing in large format,
black-and-white prints, sending forth his version of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Once I invited him to the annual gala event at Stephen F.
Austin. He immediately buttonholed Bo Pilgrim and pretended like
they were long-lost friends, though the closest Rufus had ever been
to Bo was seeing his likeness on those 18-wheelers hauling frozen
chicken down the road. It was entertaining to watch, if a bit edgy
since he was there on my nickel. To be fair, he has a story or two
to tell on me, but you'll have to ask him.
</P>
<P>
   You've likely seen some of his photographs if you read Texas
Monthly. He shoots for them regularly, including a multipage piece
in December on Weeping Mary, a small black community just west of
Alto, behind the Indian Mounds. Rufus has been traveling out there
for about five years, documenting an insular place that now treats
him like a prodigal son. I made a few trips out there with him,
including a memorable family reunion in the middle of summer where
we feasted on barbecued hog and all the trimmings, the only white
folks in sight.
</P>
<P>
   He's spent years documenting the Rangerettes, spring break at
South Padre Island, yard art, and the land of his wife's family _
Hong Kong and mainland China. His work hangs in museums across the
state. It hangs throughout my house, too, nine photographs from
China, Weeping Mary and Kilgore. I get a discount rate.
</P>
<P>
   But as I dropped in on him last week, what struck me most is
that he is still first a teacher who still loves his work. He
carefully looked at test prints made by students, brought out from
the darkroom in trays, still dripping wet. He told them how to make
the prints better. Student work hangs about his office, and he
points out pieces he particularly likes. I've hired a gaggle of
students from Kilgore College over the years, some of whom still
work for me.
</P>
<P>
   I've about given up taking photos, but it's still my first love,
a close first over writing. Rufus has made a life for himself doing
what he's best at, and that's a precious gift, for which I envy him
at times.
</P>
<P>
   (An exhibit of O Rufus Lovett's photographs is on display
through early April at the Longview Museum of Fine Arts. Call
903-753-8103 for more information.)
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
