<SLUG> BC-STATES-STEEL-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        STEEL UNION PRESIDENT URGES CLINTON NOT TO VETO QUOTA BILL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By C.J. Karamargin  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 12 - The leader of the nation's largest union
of steel workers urged President Clinton Friday to ignore one of
his senior advisors and embrace legislation that would impose tough
limits on the amount of foreign steel allowed into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of America,
asked Clinton to ``override'' White House Chief of Staff John
Podesta and ``stand up for steel.'' Becker asked the President not
to veto a bill introduced this week by Rep. Pete Visclosky,
(D-In.), and Rep. Ralph Regula, (R-Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   Podesta, in a March 10 letter to the House Ways and Means
Committee, criticized the bill as not being in the economic
interests of the nation and said he would advise Clinton to veto
it.
</P>
<P>
   The committee on Wednesday sent the bill to the full House for
consideration but urged members of Congress to reject it. A floor
debate is likely next week.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, in his own letter, told Clinton that contrary to
Podesta's assertion that progress has been made in curbing steel
imports, steel-producing countries ``show no intention of playing
by the rules'' and, as a result, the American steel industry is
reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 10,000 steelworkers have already been laid off and tens
of thousands more on the edge,'' Becker wrote. ``Steelworkers in
Ohio, Indiana, Pennsylvania, Illinois, Alabama and in every state
where there are steel facilities have felt the effect of these
imports either through layoffs or reduced hours of work...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President,'' Becker continued, ``how much more must we
bleed?''
</P>
<P>
   The Visclosky-Regula bill would require that the volume of steel
imported into the United States during any month does not exceed
the average of volume of steel products imported during the
36-month period preceding July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It would also require a monitoring system to be established and
for steel importers to obtain a special certificate before their
products could enter the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, a 15-term Republican from Texas who is
chairman of the powerful Ways and Means Committee, said he shares
the concerns of the Clinton Administration about the bill's
potential ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dangers of drifting toward protectionist policies are very
real,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Visclosky's office, the bill now has 204
co-sponsors, inlcuding 160 Democrats and 44 Republicans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
