<SLUG> BC-OZ-BONDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS HOUSE APPROVES NEW FINANCE TERMS FOR OZ PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Kansas House gave final approval Thursday to a
bill expanding the public bond financing for the Wonderful World of
Oz theme park and resort, a proposed project in western Johnson
County.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 105-17 with only one Johnson County member _ Rep.
Bob Tomlinson, a Roeland Park Republican _ voting no.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, House Bill 2166, moves to the Senate for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passing of this legislation, combined with the Salomon
Smith Barney highly confident opinion with respect to the park's
feasibility and financing, gives us every reason to believe this
Disney-quality theme park and resort will be built,'' Skip Palmer,
president of the Oz Entertainment Co., said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give Oz developers a 1 percent sales tax increase
on the 9,065-acre Sunflower Army Ammunition Plant land, bringing
the total sales tax authority to 8.375 percent. The money would be
used to pay off $250 million in bonds, or about 40 percent of the
entire project cost.
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax would apply only to purchases made inside the
theme park or anywhere within the development area, which would
include most but not all of the 12-square-mile site.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would extend the life of those bonds from 20 to
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds must be authorized by the Kansas Development Finance
Authority, a state agency, before they can be issued. The Johnson
County Commission has endorsed the Oz bill.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment added Thursday would require Oz to submit a
detailed development plan. If that was substantially altered,
project officials would have to renew their request for bonding
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Other amendments require Oz to buy insurance guaranteeing the
cleanup of pollution on the plant site and assuring the flow of
property tax dollars to the De Soto School District if Oz officials
receive a property tax abatement.
</P>
<P>
   Oz officials want to built a $771 million theme park and resort
on 3,500 acres. In exchange for ownership of most of the 9,065
acres, Oz officials have pledged part of the $250 million in bond
revenue to clean up the pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson said he still was uneasy about the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt the figures added up reasonably,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
