<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS AND THAT FROM COURTSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Marketplace musings for a March Madness
weekend:
</P>
<P>
   - Given the opportunity, my first official act as a television
station boss would be to fire any weather person acting gleeful at
the prospect of snow, sleet or freezing rain.
</P>
<P>
   - Studies tagging Kansas and Missouri as states with inordinate
numbers of psychopathic, sociopathic and just plain stupid drivers
only confirm what any driver arriving here from someplace else
learns very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   - Do Kansans ever notice that at the first sign of fiscal
uncertainty in Topeka, it's the taxpayers rather than state
government who are always the first choice to make any necessary
sacrifices?
</P>
<P>
   - Is it my imagination, or is e-mail spam easy to spot because
the intro almost always uses all capital letters?
</P>
<P>
   - You're getting old if you can remember when the Sports
Illustrated swimsuit offering was only a section of the regular
magazine featuring a modest collection of rather tastefully done
cheesecake photos.
</P>
<P>
   - In case you hadn't noticed, the Olympics had been giving
purity and nobility a bad name long before the recently revealed
corruption came to light.
</P>
<P>
   - Does anyone find it remarkable that Washington is the only
place in America where sleaze mogul Larry Flynt is treated with
respect and deference?
</P>
<P>
   - It's amazing that so many people who'd never dream of being
rude enough not to sign a regular letter will send e-mails without
the courtesy of identifying themselves by signing it at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   - Those who find themselves being inexorably drawn to World War
II literature and films might want to consider making a serious
acquaintanceship with the works of Ernie Pyle.
</P>
<P>
   - Intel proved itself a lot smarter than Microsoft when it opted
to settle peacefully with the trust-busters, but its capitulation
can only encourage more depredations by politically motivated
antitrusters.
</P>
<P>
   - Wake me when the NBA season is over.
</P>
<P>
   - Perhaps it's time to switch the defining labels, what with
conservatives pushing for radical change in areas such as education
and Social Security while liberals battle tenaciously to preserve
the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   - Whatever happened to F. Ross Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   - It's not an encouraging sign for the movie theater industry
when major players perceive the marketing need to combine film fare
with food fare.
</P>
<P>
   - Is the 45-point spread in the Duke-Florida A&AMP;M game the widest
in NCAA basketball history?
</P>
<P>
   - The U.S.-European dispute over banana trade qualifies as one
of the most benighted geopolitical feuds in the history of global
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   - Nothing against the two candidates in the race, but imagining
city auditor Mark Funkhouser as mayor of Kansas City is certainly
an interesting thing to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   - Why haven't liberals been more eager to prod the Kansas Senate
to go along with efforts to eliminate the state sales tax on
grocery purchases?
</P>
<P>
   - If you're a fan of the movie, ``The Quiet Man,'' watch for it
soon at your local TV tube.
</P>
<P>
   - If you like Pat Buchanan and Lamar Alexander, you would have
loved Harold Stassen.
</P>
<P>
   - When oil prices rise in response to OPEC threats to curb oil
production, it's a triumph of hope over experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
