<HEADER>
A8551 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILICORP-MOVE-KAN &LR;      03-12 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILICORP-MOVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILICORP UNIT TO MOVE HIGH-PAYING JOBS TO DOWNTOWN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY, MARK P. COUCH and LYNN HORSLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ UtiliCorp United Inc. plans to make downtown
Kansas City the home of a major subsidiary, bringing 415
extraordinarily high-paying jobs and instantly making the area a
national hub for energy trading.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila Energy, the subsidiary, has 285 employees in its Omaha,
Neb., headquarters and 130 in Raytown, Mo. This summer those
workers will begin moving into three floors of Town Pavilion. When
the transfer is completed by 2001, the company expects to have 560
employees downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank (UtiliCorp) for their commitment to the urban
core,'' said an elated Kansas City Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, who has
made economic development the cornerstone of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City and the state of Missouri offered about $16 million
worth of economic incentives to attract Aquila. Boosters said it
was a wise investment that would provide an economic shot in the
arm for downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the number of jobs, the average salary of Aquila
employees is expected to be nearly $170,000, more than eight times
the city's per capita income in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The total payroll is expected to reach $95 million.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown retailers and restaurants have struggled despite some
rejuvenation in the area. Aquila's well-paid work force is seen as
cornerstone in bringing back the area.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Treasurer Bob Holden said it was relatively unusual for
a company with such a high payroll to relocate to the downtown
section of an American city. Much of downtown Kansas City's recent
job growth has been lower-paying back-office and clerical workers.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Green, UtiliCorp's president and chief operating officer,
said the decision to bring Aquila to Kansas City was based on
business considerations, principally the need to consolidate
Aquila's growing operations in one place.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of bringing Aquila to Kansas City, just a few
blocks from UtiliCorp's headquarters, also was noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thrill for us today to announce this move,'' Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   For downtown and the Kansas City area, the economic boost looks
promising, especially with an average salary of $170,000. Officials
emphasized that some employees would make much less and others much
more than that figure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Kansas City's per capita income was $19,776. The area's
per capita income was $26,676 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Manager Bob Collins was delighted with the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big deal,'' he said. ``This is exactly the kind of
company you want in downtown. It brings in a national headquarters
and good jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate agents already are salivating at the
high-salary workers that Aquila is bringing to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are my kind of people,'' said Carole Colson, Realty
Executives Professional Group. ``They are not your first-time
homebuyers. We can put them in $300,000 or $400,000 homes today,
unless they have too much debt on their BMWs.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Omaha got the bad news while Cleaver and others
were savoring the deal. Aquila was founded in Omaha 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to lose a good company like that,'' said Vicki
Krecek, spokeswoman for the Omaha Chamber of Commerce. ``On the
other hand, we have a hugely, massively strong economy with
companies begging for highly qualified workers like those at
Aquila.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Omaha Mayor Hal Daub said the city was sorry to
see Aquila go, but he noted that Omaha still was home to about
1,000 other UtiliCorp employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that there are obvious efficiencies being near
the corporate parent,'' spokeswoman Joy Schulz said. ``It was a
decision solely made by the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Aquila is a trader of energy _ mainly gas and electricity. It
handles so much of the commodity that its dealings in one day would
heat and power San Francisco for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila, the second-largest energy trader in the United States,
has aggressive plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our hope we will make (Kansas City) an international hub
for the marketing of energy,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp had been thinking about a move for Aquila for about
two years. But the deal heated up over the last 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations were conducted in considerable secrecy. The
proposed move had the code name Eagle's Nest.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Zimmer, president of Zimmer Cos., said Aquila would rent
about 70,000 square feet on the 31st, 33rd and 34th floors of Town
Pavilion. The company also has an option on the 32nd floor, now
occupied by the Shook Hardy &AMP; Bacon law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila signed a 10-year lease on the space, which had been
vacant about three years. The company also has an option to renew
when its lease expires. The deal is expected to bring occupancy of
the largest downtown office building to about 94 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer represented Aquila in negotiations with the building's
leasing agent, Copaken, White &AMP; Blitt.
</P>
<P>
   Aquila will receive about $16 million in state and local
subsidies to upgrade its office space, including improvements in
communications and computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   About half the incentive package comes from a partial rebate of
earnings and other city taxes that will be generated by the
operation over 20 years. The other half comes from an assortment of
state bonds and tax credits, said Mark Bunnell, president of
Economic Development Corp. of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Council on Thursday passed a resolution
approving the deal to move Aquila.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Aggie Stackhaus was the lone dissenter. She said
she thought the proposal should have gone to a committee for
further review and discussion, rather than to the council floor for
a quick vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the rush?'' Stackhaus asked.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Ken Bacchus said the announcement showed how Kansas
City's aggressive economic development policy and incentives to
businesses were more favorable than those in some neighboring
states.
</P>
<P>
   City and economic agency officials ``go out and catch the
biggest fish that are in the ocean and the most positive fish,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
