r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-POLLUTION-     03-12 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' DIRT STRIKES OUT WITH LANDFILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shouts of ``Get the lead out!'' at San Francisco
Giants baseball games are usually directed at a catcher with bad
knees or some other player chugging around the bases at Candlestick
Park.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, it was directed at team officials in charge of
building the Giants' new ballpark in China Basin.
</P>
<P>
   A representative of Waste Management Inc. told the Giants its
lead-contaminated dirt from the Pacific Bell Park construction site
was unwelcome in its Altamont landfill and must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Toxic Substances Control had signed off
on shipping the dirt to the Altamont landfill Feb. 26, but based
its approval on the wrong environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 6,000 cubic yards of dirt shipped to the
landfill and the 12,000 cubic yards that remain at the ballpark
site have been found under tough state disposal guidelines to
contain lead at levels that could contaminate groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Toxic Substances Control confirmed ... that
the material is hazardous,'' said Douglas Sobey, senior vice
president for the western area of Waste Management. ``We don't
believe that it should be in the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to remove it as soon as possible, and send it to
Kettleman,'' a hazardous-waste landfill operated by Waste
Management in Kettleman City, Calif., Sobey said.
</P>
<P>
   Sobey wouldn't say if the company intends to bill the Giants for
costs that would run in the hundreds of thousands of dollars for
hauling the dirt to Kettleman City.
</P>
<P>
   At a San Francisco Board of Supervisors' Public Health and
Environment Committee hearing Thursday, Robert Stephens, deputy
director of the toxics department's science, pollution prevention
and technology program, said his staff examined further test
results submitted by the Giants this week.
</P>
<P>
   The tests, he said, confirmed that the lead levels of the soil
aren't low enough to be classified as nonhazardous for the purpose
of burial in a landfill such as Altamont.
</P>
<P>
   In order for the Giants to dump it at Altamont, permission would
have to be received from county and state solid waste and regional
water-quality control boards, Stephens said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bair, Giants vice president and general counsel, told the
committee members that the Giants are awaiting direction from the
state and landfill operator on how to handle the dirt dug up from
the Pac Bell site. He assured the members that it would not affect
the opening of the new ballpark in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion over the notorious dirt pile stems from a series of
letters that the Giants organization received from the state, Bair
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Toxic Substances Control on Feb. 26
approved the Giants' request to reclassify its waste as
nonhazardous.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Giants were told that they would have to comply
with a new law requiring permission from state and local agencies
to dispose of the newly reclassified dirt because it contains lead
above 350 parts per million. That level is the legal threshold
which determines whether it is too contaminated to put in a
regular, municipal landfill.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the information, the Giants didn't seek
permission themselves, Bair said Wednesday, but supplied the letter
and test samples to the Altamont landfill. The Altamont landfill
agreed to accept the waste, Bair said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 2, the state Toxics Department sent the Giants a second
letter, this time revoking the reclassification as nonhazardous and
citing the test result that showed that the dirt could pose a
threat to groundwater if buried in a landfill unequipped to accept
it.
</P>
<P>
   That letter immediately triggered a halt in the parade of about
350 trucks that had hauled uncovered dirt to the Altamont Landfill
between March 1 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County officials at Thursday's hearing were furious with
the Giants and their lead-contaminated dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most common word in Alameda County is `outrage,''' said
Chris Gray, an aide to Alameda County Supervisor Scott Haggerty.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that upsets Alameda is, once the Giants saw
the lead was over 350 parts per million, instead of taking it to a
(hazardous waste) landfill, which is the safest thing, they took it
to a closer, cheaper landfill,'' Gray said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
