<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUAL-HARASSMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE DETECTIVES AGREE TO $250,000 SETTLEMENT IN HARASSMENT
LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAWNEE, Kan. _ Shawnee on Thursday announced that it had
reached a settlement with three male police detectives who had sued
the city, accusing a male supervisor of sexually harassing them.
</P>
<P>
   By settling the lawsuit, the city avoided a series of three
trials scheduled over the next month in U.S. District Court in
Kansas City, Kan. The first was to start next week.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives, and their lawyer, will split a $250,000 payment
from the city's liability insurer. The insurance company also will
pay the city's legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives' lawyer, Harold Youngentob of Topeka, Kan., said
the trials would have attracted national attention because they
would have been among the first since the U.S. Supreme Court last
year ruled that on-the-job torment can be illegal sexual harassment
even when the offender and victim are the same sex.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, filed in January 1998, the detectives alleged
that Lt. Walter McDaniel subjected them to unwelcome homosexual
advances, unwanted touching and requests for sexual favors while he
was their supervisor in the investigations unit in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives also contended that Police Chief Tom Hayselden
did not handle the complaint fairly after he was told about
McDaniel's conduct. They contended that the city did not have an
adequate anti-harassment policy.
</P>
<P>
   The city maintained that there was no basis for the lawsuit.
Sexual-harassment policies were in place and no inappropriate
conduct continued once officials were notified, city attorney
Marvin Rainey said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides said they were relieved that the case would
not go to trial. More than 15 city employees had received subpoenas
to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will take a lot of stress off people in the
department,'' said plaintiff Delbert Nicholas, who retired last
year as a sergeant. ``It put a lot of people in a very
uncomfortable position because they couldn't show their support.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas said it was difficult for him and the other plaintiffs,
Detectives Tom Carney and John Wells, to come forward with their
allegations because no one had heard about a similar situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me. I didn't even tell my wife,'' Nicholas said.
``I felt angry, embarrassed and humiliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Capt. Charles Clark investigated complaints about
McDaniel in 1996. In a deposition, McDaniel said he would unzip his
pants, grab his crotch and show a lewd photograph of a boy as a way
to break the ice with co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Clark concluded that the acts were sexual harassment, and gave
the report to Hayselden, who said in a deposition that he
considered the acts horseplay. Hayselden did transfer McDaniel from
investigations supervisor to training supervisor, but he was not
suspended, as the captain recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement announced Thursday did not address the future
employment or supervisory roles of anyone involved in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made any changes and we will certainly look at our
organization,'' City Manager Gary Montague said Thursday. ``But we
are not ready to make any statements about our personnel at this
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Shawnee hired the law firm Shook, Hardy and
Bacon to provide sexual-harassment training seminars to all city
employees, at a cost of $3,250. City officials also reviewed and
made minor changes in the city's sexual-harassment policy because
of the lawsuit, Montague said. One change allows employees to file
a complaint to officials other than their direct supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they now understand this type of conduct is not
appropriate and that it is not a joke,'' said Youngentob, the
detectives' attorney. ``And hopefully, my clients won't suffer any
retaliation for coming forward _ it took them a lot of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney said he and Wells still feared retaliation and didn't
know whether the settlement would improve the atmosphere at the
police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be a safe haven in the workplace, but when you go
deal with criminals, you're on alert status and it raises the
adrenaline level,'' Carney said. ``You come back to the station to
recharge, but I haven't been able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells' wife, Terri Wells, said it's been the same for her
husband, whom she married after he complained about McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day he's come home from work, he has talked about it,''
she said. ``Even on a Cancun honeymoon, it didn't leave him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayselden, the police chief, said he felt ``relieved it's over
with and that we don't have to go to trial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
