<HEADLINE>
DOG SNIFFS OUT MARIJUANA HIDDEN IN TRUCK FILLED WITH PEPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ Turns out red chili peppers weren't the
hottest item inside the big rig authorities stopped in southern
Missouri earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   That honor would go to the 3 tons of marijuana hidden among
boxes of red peppers. Even the peppers' pungent smell couldn't fool
the drug-sniffing dog brought in by police.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Missouri Highway Patrol announced what might be
the largest seizure of marijuana in the state's history, more than
6,500 pounds taken from a tractor-trailer near Springfield. The
marijuana has a street value of about $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Highway Patrol Lt. Chris Ricks said officials at a
state weigh station along Interstate 44 in Strafford became
suspicious of a tractorload Wednesday evening and called in Highway
Patrol officers, who brought a drug-sniffing dog along.
</P>
<P>
   ``During routine questioning about the load, the driver wasn't
able to tell the weigh station officials exactly what his load
contained,'' Ricks said. ``He also said he wasn't exactly sure
where he was taking the load. On top of that, his paperwork wasn't
in order. Normally, a truckdriver has this type of information in
order. When he doesn't, it's a good sign that further inspection
might be needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have arrested Abbas Amir Shambayaty, 28, an Iranian
national, and charged him with one count of possession with intent
to distribute marijuana. He was ordered held without bond pending a
hearing March 22. He faces up to 10 years to life in prison without
parole and $4 million in fines if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks said: ``A lot of times, smugglers think the smell of red
peppers or onions will throw off police. And if you or I stepped
into the back of that trailer, the smell would probably be
overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the dog, he hit on the marijuana immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the driver had picked the load up somewhere in Texas
and was en route to the Chicago area, Ricks said. Once there, the
driver was supposed to make a phone call for instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks said the driver has been turned over to the U.S. State
Department because he's a foreign national. Next, the patrol will
investigate the source of the drugs and their destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driver usually isn't the person we want the most anyway,''
he said. ``He's usually just some poor guy who's made a very bad
decision on how to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Ricks added that a check of records indicated this was the
biggest marijuana seizure in Missouri's history.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest marked the second time in a month that authorities
have seized a huge load of marijuana at the Interstate 44 station
near Strafford. About 5,700 pounds was found in a truck there two
weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
