<HEADER>
A8555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOPAC13-COX     03-12 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPAC13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS rulings on charitable groups linked to Gingrich cause
confusion
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two charitable organizations worked closely with
Newt Gingrich in the 1990s to help spread his political philosophy
to wide audiences through new technology.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS ruled that one group violated the prohibition against
taking part in partisan political work. The IRS revoked its
tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   The other was cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Now, tax specialists and others who have watched Gingrich's
ethics battles fear the IRS has made a muddle of the situation and
blurred the line between charity and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why they would rule differently,'' said
Frances Hill, a tax expert at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS investigation of the links between Gingrich, GOPAC (the
political group he once led) and the charities grew out of the
House ethics committee's probe of the college course Gingrich
taught at Kennesaw State and Reinhardt College in Waleska, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   That probe resulted in a $300,000 penalty and Gingrich's
admission that he violated ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   James Cole, special counsel who led the ethics investigation,
concluded in late 1996 that both the Abraham Lincoln Opportunity
Foundation and the Progress and Freedom Foundation violated their
tax status.
</P>
<P>
   Charitable groups do not pay federal taxes and their donors may
take tax deductions for their contributions. In return, the
charities may not engage in partisan political activity.
</P>
<P>
   In the Progress and Freedom Foundation case, the IRS ruled that
the charity was aiding in the dissemination of educational, not
political, material. It was a ``close case,'' the IRS said, given
the links between the foundation and GOPAC. The foundation served
as a funding source for Gingrich's Renewing American Civilization
course, principally because GOPAC did not have sufficient
resources. But the foundation was within its rights and ``did not
serve the private interests of Mr. Gingrich, GOPAC and Republican
entities,'' the IRS said.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the Lincoln Foundation, which funded earlier
broadcasts of Gingrich's ideas about government, the IRS ruled that
it was ``part of GOPAC's effort to train Republican political
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   GOPAC and the foundation shared office space and employees. Some
GOPAC employees told prospective donors they could give to GOPAC or
to the foundation, where the donations would be tax-deductible.
</P>
<P>
   This conduct, and other financial ties, showed that ``ALOF was
operated for the private benefit of GOPAC and other Republican
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   William J. Lehrfeld, the foundation's attorney in its appeal of
the IRS ruling, wrote in court documents that the IRS could not
treat the two foundations differently.
</P>
<P>
   Cole also concluded that the charities had behaved similarly and
should be treated the same way, although he differed with Lehrfeld
about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And Hill said the disparate rulings only confuse the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Ruskin, director of the reform-minded Congressional
Accountability Project, called the rulings ``inexplicable.'' He is
calling for a Treasury Department inspector general's investigation
to determine how the IRS cleared the Progress and Freedom
Foundation, even after it acknowledged that it did not have all the
information it needed.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling was made public last month by the foundation. It
provoked worry among some tax lawyers and politicians that the IRS
had made it easier for politicians to use charitable groups to fund
some activities.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the ruling raises the possibility that candidates
could run many aspects of their campaigns through charities,
offering tax deductions and the promise of privacy to contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Foundation ruling, made public in Lehrfeld's March 5
filing in U.S. Tax Court, seems to cut the other way, reinforcing
the ban on mingling charitable and partisan aims, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty, said San Francisco attorney Greg Colvin, ``is
that it's as if we're being given a picture in which half the
painting appears and other half doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``clearly, there is more room than many of us
thought for politicians to make use of (charitable organizations)
... as long as they maintain certain a amount of distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
