A8556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-WING13-COX     03-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WING13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review of `Wing Commander'
 &HT;    By Hank Stuever
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I saw ``Wing Commander'' the other night, a
movie based on a video computer game, a tradition going all the way
back to ``Tron.'' I saw it with one of those ``special advance
screening'' stadium-theater crowds made up mostly of people who
call radio stations to win free tickets. As spaceships exploded in
astral ripples and yet another batch of athletic-looking Post-Xers
(led by Freddie Prinze Jr. _ astral dimples!) battled yet another
batch of neon-green-eyed, angry-kitty-cat-looking aliens, exactly
five things occurred to me:
</P>
<P>
   1) Freddie Prinze Jr. : A few light years ago, when I was a
reporter out West, I learned that the teen-age son of a famous but
tragically dead '70s TV-sitcom comedian was living a quiet life
with his mother in Albuquerque, N.M. It took some doing, but the
shy, handsome son agreed to meet me for an interview in the
cafeteria of La Cueva High School, from which he was about to
graduate. We talked about the father he never knew (he was 10
months old when Freddie Sr. shot himself) and what he planned to do
with his life. He didn't know yet, but he assured me that show
business was out, since show business was basically one big
cautionary tale. He didn't strike me as a teen idol then. Maybe he
didn't know either. Or maybe he was acting.
</P>
<P>
   2) They have to race the aliens back to Earth to warn everyone
to be ready for a surprise attack. Also, they need Freddie because
he's the descendant of an oppressed, extinct race of people who
knew about shortcut interstellar navigation. I know it's nitpicky,
but I absolutely insist in these kinds of movies that I be able to
follow it, to get a fix on the center of what matters here, and
hold on. Otherwise my mind drifts. (Which is very different from
saying the plot was complicated.)
</P>
<P>
   3) Computers: What do you think? I still believe that, just
because computers can do the heavy lifting in filmmaking these
days, it does not always mean that they should. Even if the
computers are from Austin, Texas. (No, especially if the computers
are from Austin, Texas.) I mean, there are some nice touches, but
secretly I wish for a season of adventure movies in which no mouses
were double-clicked.
</P>
<P>
   4) Litigants: What if the franchise holders of ``Star Wars,''
``Alien'' and ``Star Trek'' filed some sort of class-action
infringement suit against the next movie that manages to
shamelessly rip off (another view: pay homage to) all three? Could
a legal precedent actually encourage someone to make an original
space fantasy? I ask because I'm looking around at this sci-fi
crowd and wondering if they aren't just bored out of their
corduroys by now. (Alas, I already found a flaw in my plan: ``Wing
Commander'' is paid for by Twentieth Century Fox, which bankrolled
two of the three originals mentioned above. So what's going on is
self-plagiarizing, in a way.)
</P>
<P>
   5) Script: Toward the end, Freddie shouts to his love interest
and wing commander (Saffron Burrows), ``Hey, don't you die on me.''
These particular kinds of dude-isms have to go a long way in a
movie like this, and naturally can't quite do it. Computers do the
work in ``Wing Commander,'' and everything else gets left in the
smithereens. I'm sure it's a delightful computer game. I'm sure
that it's loud, and I'm sure I'd explode soonest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
