<HEADER>
A8559 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-INFORMER-ART-2TAK     03-12 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-INFORMER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACKETEERING CASE SPURS FBI TO REASSESS ITS USE OF INFORMERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It began in 1995 as a simple racketeering indictment
whose defendants included two reputed mob leaders long infamous in
Irish-dominated South Boston: James ``Whitey'' Bulger and Stephen
``The Rifleman'' Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   By now, however, the case has become what many call one of the
most embarrassing messes for the FBI in years. And it has called
into question one of the oldest practices in law enforcement and
one of the most troublesome: the use of confidential informers to
fight organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   The imbroglio, little-publicized outside the Boston area,
centers on accusations that for decades, FBI agents protected
Bulger and Flemmi while they committed assorted crimes because the
two also provided information about their Italian mobster rivals
that helped decimate La Cosa Nostra in New England. Defense lawyers
are essentially arguing that the government may not prosecute
crimes it effectively authorized informers to commit.
</P>
<P>
   Revelations of the FBI's practices, in pre-trial testimony in
the racketeering case, have prompted sweeping internal
investigations of the bureau and a months-long policy review by the
U &UR; . &LR; S &UR; . &LR;  Justice Department. That review is expected to end in new
rules that would require agents to share more about the
relationships with informers that have long been their most closely
guarded secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would require the FBI and other agencies to
notify federal prosecutors whenever an informer commits an
unauthorized crime and whenever someone who is about to be indicted
is an informer.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department team has also begun to consider whether to
require the FBI and other agencies to consult with federal
prosecutors before making the sensitive decision of whether to sign
up a criminal kingpin in the first place, said Jonathan D.
Schwartz, an associate deputy attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Any week now, a federal judge is expected to issue a ruling on
whether the government owes Flemmi immunity, which could affect
other informer-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Other cases have raised similar questions about the slippery
agent-informer relationship, but for pure suspense, for local Irish
and Italian underworld color, and for depth of disclosure of the
murkier inner workings of the FBI, this one seems to have them all
beat.
</P>
<P>
   The most commanding figure in the case, Bulger, is the
black-sheep brother of the current president of the University of
Massachusetts; he is also a convicted bank robber, a former inmate
at Alcatraz and, according to prosecutors, the sometime head of the
closest thing to an Irish mob in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   His associate, Flemmi, whose professional criminal resume is
similar, is in jail awaiting trial on the racketeering charges, but
Bulger has been on the lam with nose-thumbing success for four
years. He is a fit, 70-ish fugitive who, lament the authorities who
have picked up his trail and lost it, passes easily as a harmless
retiree and has been cruising blithely through the Sun Belt with
his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has offered a $250,000 reward for help catching him, and
he has been featured on programs like ``America's Most Wanted'' and
``Unsolved Mysteries.'' John J. Connolly Jr., a retired FBI
supervisor who worked closely with him, figures Bulger will likely
stay uncaught: ``He was a down-range thinker,'' Connolly said.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is not going quietly either. His disclosure in 1997 that
he had long been an informer _ to his own lawyer's surprise _ and
his argument that he had been authorized by the government to
commit his crimes &UR; ,  &LR;  opened the door to the metamorphosis of his
case into a virtual indictment of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-trial motions in his case took up most of 1998, and it has
been through that pre-trial testimony that a picture has emerged of
the kind of behind-the-scenes dealing the FBI &UR;  &LR; sometimes does.
</P>
<P>
   It all began back in the 1960s and 1970s, when federal
authorities saw the Mafia as a central threat to national security,
and Boston was caught in gangland warfare that killed dozens. The
word came down to Boston FBI &UR;  &LR;  agents that the No. 1 priority was
to close down the New England branch of La Cosa Nostra, and with
that directive came a new tool: the Top Echelon Informant program,
a special effort to recruit informers highly placed inside crime
groups, and thus, by definition, criminals themselves.
</P>
<P>
   To get at the Mafia, FBI agents here decided to try to enlist
the aid of Flemmi, who had useful ties to the Mafia but was not a
member. Somewhat later, they also turned to Bulger, who was then
considered a criminal leader in Irish-dominated South Boston and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, according to the picture painted in court, were
mostly their own little gang, the kind of territorial bosses who
would demand protection money, or ``rent,'' from bookmakers,
loan &UR;  &LR; sharks and other petty criminals, and who were also involved
in illegal gambling enterprises and loan &UR; - &LR; sharking themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If that were all they did, it might seem understandable that the
FBI let them keep doing it to glean information about the Mafia.
Certainly, some of the information was spectacular, including a tip
that helped lead to the first tape-recording the authorities ever
obtained of a Mafia induction ceremony, replete with finger-cutting
and the oath, ``I enter alive into this organization, and I will
have to get out dead.''
</P>
<P>
   And in general, the men helped the FBI trounce the Boston-area
Italian Mafia, putting away dozens of members.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also emerged in court that the two may have been
involved in crimes as serious as murder. In an event that casts the
agent-informer relationship in perhaps the worst light, the two men
were suspected in the killing of an Oklahoma City jai alai owner.
After FBI agents told them that another informer had fingered them
for that death, that informer was killed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger and Flemmi also became the targets of investigations by
the Drug Enforcement Agency and the Massachusetts State Police. But
it appears, according to testimony and court documents, that they
were repeatedly tipped off or protected by their FBI allies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
