<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDREN'S-HOME-HNS &LR;      03-12 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN'S-HOME </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-CONTROVERSIAL CHILDREN'S HOME WILL BE REVIVED 
 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVAN MOORE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) More than a decade after its doors were closed to
troubled children, the once-controversial Lester Roloff Home for
Boys and Girls is soon to be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   The facility in Corpus Christi, Texas, became notorious in the
late 1970s when its late founder refused to seek state licensing.
Roloff, a fundamentalist and leader of the People's Baptist Church
in Corpus Christi who believed the state had no right to license
his homes, even went to jail during litigation with the Texas
Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question would seem to be whether Roloff would feel
vindicated or disturbed at the revival of his Rebekah Home for
Girls and Lighthouse for Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The homes, still operated by Roloff's church, are soon to be
approved by the Texas Association of Christian Child Care Agencies
Inc., a private organization created as part of Gov. George W.
Bush's ``faith-based'' legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The private group inspects and approves church-operated homes
for &UR;  &LR; children with behavioral or drug problems, although the
association itself answers to the Texas Department of Protective
and Regulatory Services.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had no comment this week about the application for the
Roloff home, and a spokeswoman said only that faith-based
facilities can provide ``meaningful alternatives'' for problem
juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Roloff once operated one of the largest church homes in the
nation, with 200 girls housed in Rebekah and 50 boys in the
Lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   He came under fire when complaints surfaced, including claims of
severe whippings and the withholding of food by the staff. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; His real problems mounted, however, when then-Attorney General
Jim Mattox insisted that the homes apply for a state license and be
inspected by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Roloff continued to rail bitterly against the state until his
death in a private plane crash near Houston in 1982. The youth
homes were closed in 1985 and moved to Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley Cameron, Roloff's former second-in-command, succeeded him
as head of the church and continued to run five homes for adults
between the ages of 18 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron refused to speak to the Houston Chronicle, referring all
questions to the Christian child care agencies, which confirmed
that Cameron was the first to apply for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they'll receive approval,'' said the Rev. David
Blaser, a Dallas minister and head of the child care group. ``We're
just barely off the ground, but we've made inspections. I was a
great supporter of Lester Roloff and Brother Cameron when they ran
the homes before.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaser said Cameron currently has two boys housed at the home
and plans to return the operation to its former capacity of 250.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the largest in the nation,'' said Blaser. ``It was
when Lester Roloff had it. He was a very dedicated man, and I
thought he did a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   Roloff's greatest opposition came from former Assistant Attorney
General John Odam, who was in charge of the Roloff case. Odam is
now an attorney practicing in Houston and a member of the Texas
Youth Commission board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no question in my mind that those type of homes
provide a good service when they're properly run.'' Odam said.
``And the question really wasn't Roloff's operation of the homes as
much as it was his absolute refusal to get a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some complaints about severe whippings in one home,
but that could have been straightened out,'' he said. ``It was just
that Lester believed he was not subject to the state. He used to
get on the radio and pray for me personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought I did the devil's handiwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Blaser nor Odam are sure whether Roloff would approve of
the new application process.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand it's an option that wasn't available to him, and
it means the homes can operate,'' said Blaser. ``On the other, our
group is subject to the state and maybe he would regard it as
licensing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
