<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8563 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-INFORMER-ART-2NDT     03-12 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-INFORMER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: FBI allies.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trial testimony and related interviews have verged repeatedly on
the cinematic. There was a moment, as recounted by Connolly in an
interview, when Bulger was recruited to inform on his enemies and
said: ``They want to play checkers; we'll play chess.''
</P>
<P>
   There were homey, boozy dinners shared chummily by FBI agents
and criminal informers, as described in testimony by both sides.
And there has been jaw-dropping courtroom drama as criminal after
criminal has been revealed to be an informer too, like some zany
comedy in which one actor after another pulls off a lifelike rubber
mask.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the remark that lies at the crux of Flemmi's
argument that the government owes him immunity.
</P>
<P>
   At one of those cozy dinners, Flemmi has testified, an FBI
supervisor, John Morris, told him and Bulger, ``You can do whatever
you want, just don't clip anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor says he does not recall making the remark. But it
encapsulates the sense that emerges from the case of the FBI's
willingness to resort to questionable means to achieve its end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does anyone in their right mind really believe Jimmy Bulger
and Steve Flemmi survived the most powerful law-enforcement agency
on earth unless we fully intended them to survive us?'' asked
Connolly, who believes that the government owes both Flemmi and
Bulger immunity.
</P>
<P>
   In another pivotal comment, Morris has said that he once asked
Connolly what the two men wanted in exchange for their information,
and Connolly replied, ``a head start.'' In other words, warning in
time to run if an indictment against them was about to come down.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, until the FBI guard changed and the two men's
usefulness declined, they seem to have gotten, and gotten away
with, much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   So the awkward question arises of who, exactly, was running
whom?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always weighing how bad are the bad guys versus how
good is the information they're providing,'' said Robert M. Bloom,
a professor of law and specialist in federal procedure at Boston
College Law School who has been following the Boston case. ``That's
the dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   But the picture here gets even worse for the FBI. Morris, who
has immunity, has admitted to acts of outright corruption: taking
several thousand dollars and cases of the wine he was so fond of
that the criminals nicknamed him ``Vino.''
</P>
<P>
   So, then, another question arises: Is all this really about a
couple of rogue agents who got too friendly with a couple of
criminals?
</P>
<P>
   No, said Kenneth Fishman, Flemmi's lawyer. If it were just that,
he argued, the Justice Department would not be talking about
changing its whole system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an aberration,'' Fishman said. ``It's an inherent
part of law enforcement that the courts have found to be
acceptable. You can make these deals with the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishman is arguing that the government must live up to its deal
with an informer like Flemmi _ a deal that he describes as
effective immunity for the racketeering crimes of which he stands
accused.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis O'Callaghan, former assistant special agent in charge of
the Boston FBI office, said that dealing with criminals was
naturally a significant part of the bureau's job. ``You don't go to
the local church pastor for information,'' he said. ``We use
criminals. Do we think at certain times they do certain things they
don't tell us about? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   But agents are already obligated to follow up leads on
unauthorized crimes by criminal informers, he said. He decried
Morris' corruption, but said of Connolly, ``You hate to see people
who are out there trying to get the job done whose reputations are
destroyed simply because they handled those people.''
</P>
<P>
   To Flemmi's arguments that he is owed immunity, the government
is arguing back strenuously, through its team of federal
prosecutors, that no such deal was ever made and that Flemmi was a
criminal who happened to find it advantageous to inform on his
enemies but received no legal promise of protection from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   A government brief filed recently accuses Flemmi of ``trying to
rationalize a life of heinous crime and duplicitous treachery into
the actions of some super federal undercover agent imbued with the
license to commit crime purportedly in the service of his
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney in Boston, Donald K. Stern, emphasized the
importance of informers for fighting everything from hate groups to
drug dealers. ``We're not suggesting everything here worked the way
it should have,'' he said, ``but we'll strongly defend the ability
of law enforcement to develop and nurture informants _ within
carefully constructed guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Connolly says Flemmi and Bulger ``were no angels,'' he
disagrees with the government's position on whether it owes them
immunity. He says his superiors did in fact make a deal with the
two informers, at least concerning gambling and loan &UR; - &LR; sharking.
And a deal is a deal.
</P>
<P>
   He did say, however, that ``It was always understood they could
not commit violent acts.'' Brought up on the same South Boston
territory as Bulger, it was Connolly who helped Bulger turn
informer, and he does not regret it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a business decision, pure and simple,'' said Connolly,
who retired a highly commended agent. ``We were going to use a gang
of two to get rid of a gang of 42.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if you were a victim of Flemmi and Bulger, a victim of
criminals given virtual carte blanche by the government?
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the matter is, what if you're one of the Mafia's
victims?'' Connolly countered. ``The 42 people we put away were
probably responsible for 200 murders over 30 years, maybe more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the name of the game,'' he said. ``It all depends on what
your investigative priorities are. A decision was made by the
Department of Justice and FBI to go after the Mafia, and that's
what I did. My only crime is doing my job and doing it too well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
