<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ASSESS-650&AMP;ADD-N     03-12 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ASSESS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: 3 NATIONS' DAY OF DELIVERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NATO, NATO-POLAND-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., born a Hungarian,
long since naturalized as an American, could scarcely contain his
joy as he flew west Friday morning for the ceremony here marking
the accession of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a thousand years of desperate craving to be part of the
West, today it's official _ we're in, we get the imprimatur of
NATO,'' the silver-haired Lantos, 71, said.
</P>
<P>
   He offered a history lesson by way of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pagan Hungarian king, St. Stephen, embraced Western
civilization in 1001 by accepting a crown from Rome,'' Lantos said.
``But it has taken a millennium to complete the process. In the
interim, we missed the Renaissance because we were occupied by the
Turks. We spent centuries as an appendage of Vienna, clinging to
the West through the hyphen that connected us, humiliatingly, to
Austria. We stumbled through the 20th century, cut off from the
mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling of deliverance from an implacably cruel fate
suffused the little auditorium at the Harry S. Truman Library where
the ceremony took place.
</P>
<P>
   It took place here, of course, because it was President Truman,
with his secretary of state, Dean Acheson, who called NATO into
existence to meet the Soviet threat after World War II. Truman was
unpopular then; now he is revered, and modern administrations
identify themselves with his achievements and his matter-of-fact,
middle-American style.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 52 years ago Friday, on March 12, 1947, Truman delivered
a special message to Congress, enunciating the Truman Doctrine and
seeking legislative support for American aid to Greece and Turkey.
It was, he said, ``a fateful hour,'' in which ``the free peoples of
the world look to us for support in maintaining their freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains true, but delivering the support has become harder,
quite aside from the enlargement of NATO. There is no agreement
among its members as to what action to take in Kosovo. There is no
agreement on what the criteria should be for action in future
crises in Europe or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, support for possible U.S. military action
in Europe, absent Russian aggression, is shaky. The House of
Representatives voted only narrowly on Thursday, 219-191, to
support President Clinton's plan to send troops to Kosovo. Former
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger told a House committee on
Wednesday that the whole idea made him ``extremely uneasy,'' and
Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., said Friday that if a Kosovo operation
was bungled, ``NATO could turn out to be a collateral casualty.''
</P>
<P>
   Other developments also threaten Atlantic equilibrium as the
50th anniversary celebration of the NATO pact in Washington next
month approaches. A seriocomic little trade war has broken out over
bananas. The presence of tens of thousands of U.S. troops in
Europe, a decade after the end of the Cold War, reassures European
political leaders but sometimes infuriates the European public.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will no doubt try to ease such concerns in April, as
well as the worries of the Russians that NATO expansion is aimed at
them. But he chose not to avail himself of Friday's event to get a
head start. Truman stood at Acheson's side as the secretary of
state signed the original NATO treaty, but for whatever reason,
Clinton did not accompany Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
Missouri to stand beside her as she signed enlargement documents.
</P>
<P>
   The signing marked the achievement of a major foreign-policy
goal of the Clinton administration, as State Department briefers
were eager to proclaim. It put an exclamation mark to the end of
the Cold War, as Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek of Poland
suggested. It validated the deeds of those who revolted against
Soviet domination in the Budapest uprising of 1956, the Prague
spring of 1968 and the Solidarity movement that was born at Gdansk,
Poland, in 1981.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But for the Central Europeans, it did much more.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three nations that joined NATO Friday has struggled
for centuries to find and preserve its national identity. To them,
membership in the alliance symbolizes success at long last in that
endeavor, not just military protection from the United States.
Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek spoke for them all when he said last
month in the Polish Parliament that belonging to NATO would enable
Poland ``to overcome the geopolitical curse laid on us since the
17th century.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that there have been no connections across the
Atlantic in the past. Casimir Pulaski, whose homeland, Poland, had
been partitioned in 1772, fought on the side of the colonists in
the American Revolution. Lajos Kossuth, a Hungarian nationalist,
was acclaimed in the United States in the 19th century. Eduard
Benes and Jan Masaryk, Czech democrats, were widely admired here.
Indeed, as Jan Kavan, the Czech foreign minister, noted Friday,
Czechoslovakia was founded after World War I on treaties for which
Woodrow Wilson was primarily responsible.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the Poles fought furiously against the
Nazis, in their own army until it was crushed, then in brigades and
divisions attached to British or American commands in Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But for centuries, as Western Europe flourished and the United
States grew to maturity, Central Europe was unable to throw off the
yoke of misery for good.
</P>
<P>
   The Poles, whose king, Jan Sobieski, had ridden at the head of
Christian armies that beat back the Muslims at the gates of Vienna
in 1683, found their lands split up among the Russians, the
Prussians and the Hapsburg Empire. Risings in 1830 and 1863 and
1905 came to nothing. And when independence was finally restored in
1918, it lasted only two decades, ending in joint German-Russian
occupation in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign rule was a way of life for the Czechs. Even their
greatest leader, Charles IV, who built Prague's unforgettable
bridge, was a Luxembourger whose native language was French. Things
got worse in 1620; defeated at White Mountain, the Czechs fell
under the sway of the Hapsburgs for 300 years.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Hungarians, they were ruled by foreigners for 600
years, almost without interruption _ Frenchmen and Poles, Turks and
Bavarians, Luxembourgers and Russians. They have suffered at the
hands of dictators of the left and dictators of the right, with
only fleeting moments of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Janos Martonyi, the Hungarian foreign minister, made the point
about 1956, 1968 and 1981. But he also put Friday's events into the
larger context. For a long time, he said, his country had dreamed
of belonging to what he termed ``the community of Western
democracies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary has come home,'' he said. ``We are back in the
family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
