<HEADLINE>
TOP SCORER SCHMIDGALL LEADS US INTO SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPOO, Finland _ Wiped out from a bout with the flu last
weekend, Jenny Schmidgall might have been forgiven for not playing
her best hockey the past few days. But thanks, rather than
forgiveness, has been in order: The 20-year-old center has been
playing her best hockey, leading all scorers in the Women's World
Championships as the top-seeded United States heads into its
semifinal game Saturday against No. 3 Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really coming on center stage now, and it's great to see
because she's such a gifted player,'' said US coach Ben Smith after
Schmidgall figured in the first five of Team USA's six goals in its
win over China Thursday night. ``She loves the game so much, with
so much passion.''
</P>
<P>
   The survivor of the US-Finland matchup will meet the winner of
Saturday afternoon's Canada-Sweden game in Sunday's final.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidgall, who made her national team debut with the 1998
gold-medal Olympic squad, scored 11 points (4 goals, 7 assists) in
the three preliminary-round games. The rest of the scoring leaders
list reads like an all-star roster: Canada's Jayna Hefford is
second with 9 points, while Cammi Granato (US), Karyn Bye (US), and
Hayley Wickenheiser (Canada) each have 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun,'' said Schmidgall, a freshman whose 66 points
(32 goals, 34 assists) for the University of Minnesota, just a
half-hour from her hometown of Edina, put her fourth in the nation
in collegiate scoring. ``I just came out here ready to play, trying
to play the best hockey I can and if it goes in, it goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   The US likely will need her to produce to find its way to the
gold-medal game. Finland barely lost to Canada Thursday night, 1-0,
and has maintained _ or even improved _ its bronze-medal Olympic
form despite the loss of Riikka Nieminen, who is second only to
Granato all time in scoring at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a formidable foe,'' said Smith. ``They like to play a
kind of transition game where they let you attack and like to
counter off that if you make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a tough power play, especially effective when
defenseman Kirsi Hanninen gets into the slot, and the US will face
by far its toughest opponent so far in the tournament. In the
preliminaries, Team USA outscored Russia, Sweden, and China, 27-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we scrimmaged so hard today,'' said Smith.
``They've got a bit of an advantage because they've had a serious
game and we haven't. We wanted to get ourselves in that frame of
mind, because it will be a much different pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Erin Whitten will be in goal for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the crowd. The just-opened Lansiauto Tapiola Arena
was rocking with 4,601 partisan fans for Finland's game against
Canada, and it's likely to be no different when their hometown
heroines meet the Olympic champions.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Schmidgall. ``It just pumps me up,'' she said.
``Sometimes it pumps me up more when they're cheering against you,
because you kind of want to put it back in their face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1927EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
