<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPRECIATE-MENUHIN-BO     03-12 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-MENUHIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENUHIN BEGAN AS PRODIGY, BECAME EDUCATOR, HUMANITARIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yehudi Menuhin died Friday of heart failure in Berlin; the
violinist, conductor, educator, and humanitarian had been
prominently before the public for 75 of his 82 years. Mr. Menuhin,
who lived in Switzerland and England, was in the German capital to
conduct a concert by the Warsaw Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Menuhin may have been the most astonishing of all
instrumental prodigies. Born in New York April 22, 1916, of
Russian-Jewish parents, Mr. Menuhin started studying the violin at
the age of 4 and made his debut playing the Mendelssohn Concerto
with the San Francisco Symphony at 7. His teachers included Sigmund
Anker, Louis Persinger, Adolf Busch, and Georges Enesco. In later
life, he himself became a leading force in musical education,
particularly in Great Britain, where he created the Yehudi Menuhin
School for talented young musicians in 1963 and later served as
president of the Trinity College of Music.
</P>
<P>
   In his youth, Mr. Menuhin, famously photographed in short pants,
played in a state of grace that moved all who heard him, including
the greatest musicians of the era, like conductor Wilhelm
Furtwaengler and composer Edward Elgar. In 1932, when Elgar was 75,
he conducted the 16-year-old violinist in a recording of his Violin
Concerto that has seldom since been absent from the catalog. Bartok
composed his Sonata for Solo Violin for Mr. Menuhin, and Walton his
Sonata for Violin and Piano.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Mr. Menuhin intermittently faced violinistic and
emotional difficulties, including depression, which he wrote
candidly about in successive editions of his autobiography,
``Unfinished Journey,'' first published in 1977. His second
marriage in 1948, to dancer Diana Gould, helped to restore his
balance, along with his discovery of Indian religion and the
practice of yoga.
</P>
<P>
   His most frequent recital partner until her death in 1981 was
his pianist sister Hepzibah, with whom he toured the world for
decades. He appeared repeatedly in all the musical capitals of the
world and played eight engagements with the Boston Symphony
Orchestra between 1934 and his last appearance at Tanglewood in the
Beethoven Concerto in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Even before his bow arm became shaky and his intonation
unreliable, Mr. Menuhin had embarked on a notable career as a
conductor and organizer of concerts, orchestras, and music
festivals, and he was an active recording artist throughout most of
his life, amassing one of the largest discographies of any
classical artist. His recordings of many of the standard concerti,
particularly those of Mozart, for which he wrote his own cadenzas,
and Beethoven, remain points of reference. Among his best-selling
discs were crossover albums with sitarist Ravi Shankar and jazz
violinist Stephane Grappelli that were made because of Mr.
Menuhin's artistic convictions and not for commercial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Menuhin did not shirk controversy. During World War II, he
had played hundreds of concerts for American and Allied troops,
sometimes in dangerous situations, but after the war he became the
first Jewish musician to appear with Furtwaengler and the Berlin
Philharmonic, an act for which he was fiercely criticized, and
which he fiercely defended. Mr. Menuhin wrote, ``Music creates
order out of chaos; for rhythm imposes unanimity upon the
divergent, melody imposes continuity upon the disjointed, and
harmony imposes compatibility upon the incongruous.'' Mr. Menuhin
was laden with official honors throughout his life because of his
musical citizenship. He was an eloquent speaker and writer on
musical and humanitarian matters and the relationship between them.
His essays were collected in the book ``Theme and Variations'' in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   Conductor and retired Boston Symphony violinist Harry Ellis
Dickson first heard Mr. Menuhin in Berlin in 1932. ``Mothers of
people like me used to use him as an example. In 1932, I heard him
play three concertos with the Berlin Philharmonic in one night, and
it was overwhelming. Later he began to analyze himself, and he did
not play as well; I remember one time with the Boston Symphony he
spent the intermission standing on his head. It was sad to hear him
struggle with the violin, because he had really been a magnificent
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based violinist Peter Zazofsky said Friday, ``Mr. Menuhin
was one of the most important musicians of the century, and never
satisfied with just playing the violin. As a musician, he felt he
was a spokesman for humanity in the largest sense. There was an
aura of expansiveness and humanity about him that came through in
his playing, even when he was not at his best. The audience never
noticed, because they saw him in short pants again, and when they
heard him, they were listening to memories of their own youth.''
</P>
<P>
   Violinist Daniel Stepner also fondly remembered Mr. Menuhin's
influence. ``Mr. Menuhin was one of the three most influential
violinists in my growing up, the other two being David Oistrakh and
Henryk Szeryng. Mr. Menuhin represented the Apollonian ideal, a
very high-minded and idealistic approach to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to me to discover that he was an American,''
said the Boston-based musician. ``I played for him once, and he was
very unassuming, but also encouraging; he had all sorts of ideas
and represented a whole world of violinism that I had had little
contact with besides recordings. He was very close to Nadia
Boulanger, who was a teacher of mine; with her he shared a high
idealism about music-making and about teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   This writer heard Mr. Menuhin play only on troubled occasions in
the late '60s and early '70s, but even then there were glimpses of
the qualities one cherished in his great recordings. When Mr.
Menuhin was at his best, his playing represented a unique
configuration of insight, sweetness, nobility, and fire.
</P>
<P>
   I well remember a rebuke from former Boston Symphony
concertmaster Joseph Silverstein. Once in complimenting Silverstein
on the awesome standard of consistency he maintained throughout a
long and busy career, I asked him how he had done it, mentioning
the erratic standard of Mr. Menuhin's playing. ``Well, let's put it
this way,'' Silverstein said, ``I never had the problem of playing
as well as Yehudi Menuhin did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Menuhin is survived by his wife and four children: sons
Gerard and Jeremy (a pianist), from his marriage to Gould; and a
son, Krov, and a daughter, Zamira, from his first marriage, to Nola
Nicholas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
