<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-UNC-URI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH CAROLINA-CHARLOTTE UPSETS RHODE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Lamar Odom sat on the Rhode Island bench and stared
blankly out at the court as North Carolina-Charlotte was putting
the finally touches on its 16-5 overtime run and 81-70 victory in
the first round of the NCAA Midwest Regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was I thinking?'' asked Odom afterward. ``I was thinking
how close we came. How we had the game nearly won. How we let it
get away.''
</P>
<P>
   That they did.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island played a solid first half. The Atlantic 10 champion
shut down 3-point threat Diego Guevara (he make a shot in the
opening 20 minutes) and forced the 49ers into taking bad shots
(34.4 percent from the floor and 25 percent from beyond the 3-point
arc). The Rams also survived an eight-minute span when Odom sat on
the bench following three early fouls. If it was a boxing match,
Rhody was one punch away from putting it away.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Rhode Island, North Carolina-Charlotte has
fared well this season when on the ropes. Seven prior times they
trailed at halftime and won. They knew trailing, 36-31, at
intermission was not a herculean deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we didn't play our best,'' said UNCC coach Bobby
Lutz. ``In fact, it's the worst we've played in a while. But you've
got to give Rhode Island credit. They did some nice things
defensively. I'm extremely pleased to survive an overtime game.''
</P>
<P>
   The box score will show Odom finished with a team-high 16
points, taking just 12 shots in 37 minutes. Teammates Antonio
Reynolds-Dean and Luther Clay had 12 each and Tavorris Bell 11.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina-Charlotte's Galen Young, who fouled out with five
minutes remaining, had a game-high 17 points and Kelvin Price 15.
Marlon Thomas threw in 13 and Guevara had 11, all in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   What the box score will not show is how Young did a masterful
job guarding Odom one-on-one and so did Thomas, who inherited the
job when Young fouled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be out there real bad, but I have confidence in my
teammates,'' said Young. ``They came through once again. That's one
thing I can credit to our team, when somebody goes down, we're all
there to pick each other up. Marlon did a terrific job. I knew he
could do it because he and I go at it all the time in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he pulled out all the stops. ``I'm a senior and
every game can be my last game so I played it as such,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who is quicker than Young, stripped Odom of the ball
late in regulation. In fact, Odom didn't score after Young left the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Even after North Carolina-Charlotte caught Rhode Island near the
end of regulation, the Rams had a chance to put it away.
</P>
<P>
   URI led, 63-60, with 2:33 to play when Reynolds-Dean hit a
3-pointer that would have given URI a 6-point bulge. Instead, it
was disallowed because he was called for traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't travel. It was a crucial call. It ended our season,''
said Reynolds-Dean, who also saw his career conclude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had the game won but it got away from us,'' said
URI coach Jim Harrick. ``From our standpoint, we had enough shots
to win the game. We just didn't make them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the extra session, North Carolina-Charlotte went on a 12-0
run, helped along by five missed URI shots and two turnovers. It
was a quick death for the Rams (20-13), who return to Kingston,
R.I., wondering if Odom will return for another season, while the
49ers advance to play Oklahoma in Sunday's second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 50-50 whether I return or turn pro,'' admitted Odom after
the game. ``If I return, it will be because I love my teammates.
It's a decision I'll have to make, but I don't have to make it
right away.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Jerry DeGregorio has been a mentor to Odom and
guided him to Rhode Island. A year ago, Odom asked DeGregorio if he
was ready for the NBA. DeGregorio told him he wasn't prepared
physically or emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   What does DeGregorio say now? ``He can't make a wrong choice.
Whatever he does is a right choice.'' Translation: Odom is ready
for the NBA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
