<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-BC-OHIOST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE FACES FAMILIAR FACES ON BC TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Ohio State women's basketball coach Beth
Burns has a pretty good idea what's in store for her team when it
faces Boston College in the first round of the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's Eagles guard Alissa Murphy of San Diego, whom
Burns tried to recruit when the latter was a coach at San Diego
State.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's freshman guard Brianne Stepherson, whom Burns heard
about through Scoonie Penn, a current Buckeye transfer from BC and
former neighbor of Stepherson's.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's coach Cathy Inglese, who used to work alongside
Jim O'Brien, the men's basketball coach at Ohio State who used to
be at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the irony of it all,'' Burns said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   About Murphy, Burns said, ``I know she's great, so she doesn't
have to show me (tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   About Stepherson, Burns said she told Penn: ``Just don't tell me
she's got your game, because we're in deep trouble if that's the
case.''
</P>
<P>
   And she said O'Brien, ``who has been nothing but complimentary
about Cathy,'' gave her great advice. ``I think he said, `Don't
screw it up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State (17-11, 9-7 in the Big Ten) last went to the NCAA
Tournament in 1996, when it got knocked out in the second round by
eventual champion Tennessee. The Buckeyes, seeded ninth, were
ranked as high as 19th in the Associated Press national poll, and
finished tied with Wisconsin for fourth in the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have been hearing about being on the bubble for
their whole careers, and boy, we were on the bubble; we were the
last bracket announced,'' Burns said. ``But we felt we should be
here. We're excited not just to play a good Boston College team,
but in an environment that is probably unequal to anywhere in the
country in the history of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the winner of Saturday's game has the unenviable task
of facing the winner of the later game between Appalachian State
and heavily favored Tennessee, which is seeking its fourth straight
national title.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles come into their first-ever NCAA Tournament looking
much like they did all season _ banged up and bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Senior cocaptain Paula Bacso, who was hobbled most of the season
with a stress fracture in her right foot, was starting to practice
more last week when she developed a stress fracture in her left
foot. Freshman forward Becky Gottstein just started practicing
after suffering a sprained ankle against Seton Hall two weeks ago.
Senior center Whitney Steele has suffered from back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese said she keeps hearing that her players ``are just glad
to be here,'' but she doesn't want them to assume they should just
go through the motions tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is, `Don't just be happy to be here,' '' she said.
``We want to have fun being here, but realize that we're here to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as the Eagles made their way to the University of
Tennessee for practice Friday, it's understandable if they were
overwhelmed. They drove past a billboard in downtown Knoxville
congratulating coach Pat Summitt on her 25 years at Tennessee,
drove across a road on campus renamed for the coach, and went into
the gym and saw six NCAA championship banners hanging from the
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking onto the court, the whole feeling, the whole
atmosphere,'' said Stepherson, shaking her head. Not to mention the
25,000 seats painted in the Lady Vols' color. ``There was a whole
lot of orange out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
