<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-CINC-MASON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI HAS LITTLE TROUBLE WITH GEORGE MASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jason Miskiri talked the talk before Friday's matchup
with Cincinnati. The George Mason guard said he saw nothing special
about the Bearcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just another team that wears Cincinnati on their
jerseys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, after the Bearcats administered an across-the-board 72-48
thrashing of George Mason, Miskiri had a somewhat different view.
He may have talked the talk, but he _ and his teammates _ walked
the plank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little more than that,'' he conceded. ``They have
the whole package.''
</P>
<P>
   They had too much, way too much, for starry-eyed George Mason,
making its second NCAA appearance and first in 10 years. Team star
George Evans, who was all-Everything in the Colonial Athletic
Association, had that deer-in-the-headlights look all game. He
posted a big doughnut (0 for 6) in 25 frustrating minutes as
Cincinnati swarmed him in the post and ran different guys at him
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a good defensive game,'' Evans said. ``Not just on
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati dominated inside, built a 41-17 lead at the break,
and cruised into a Sunday matchup with without breaking much of a
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big load off of us,'' said guard Melvin Levett,
referring to the 3-14 seeding matchup and Cincinnati's status as
the heavy favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Added Pete Mickeal, who led Cincinnati with 18 points, ``We
jumped on them. We didn't come out soft. We played good defense and
they didn't get any confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The peril of being a prohibitive favorite was nothing new to
Cincinnati. If it needed a reminder, it merely had to look at the
previous night's game between North Carolina and Weber State. The
Bearcats also struggled last year in the opener against Northern
Arizona and coach Bob Huggins gave his team a little pep talk
Thursday night to bring it all back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit home for me, I know that,'' Levett said of Huggins's
talk. ``Guys were ready to play. We didn't have that situation that
we had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   It took 10 minutes for Cincinnati to flex its many muscles.
Leading, 15-11, the Bearcats went on a game-breaking 26-6 run over
the final 8:13 of the first half. Mickeal had 8 points in the run
and Kenyon Martin (10 points, 6 rebounds) added 4. That accounted
for the 41-17 halftime score and the second half became a
made-for-television enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Bearcats were simply overpowering inside _ the halftime
rebounding advantage was 37-17 _ and of their 14 first-half
baskets, 10 were dunks or layups. George Mason, meanwhile, was 5
for 31 in the half, going more than six minutes without a hoop. The
Patriots also were 4 for 10 from the line in the half. Nothing
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, you're nervous before the game,'' said
George Mason coach Jim Larranaga. ``We got more nervous as the game
went on . . . They put tremendous pressure on you. Everything is
contested. Even if you're open, you have a sense of someone
attacking you. And you rush. We found ourselves doing that early.
We haven't been in this situation before and we didn't know how to
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins's season-long concern has been Cincinnati's shooting.
``We can beat anybody when we make open shots,'' he said. ``We've
got really good shooters on some days. But we defend well enough
and we rebound well enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati shot only 40.3 percent Friday and missed most of its
outside shots. It didn't matter. When the other guy shoots 16
percent from the field in the first half, everything is relative.
The Bearcats simply relied on their old staples _ defense and
rebounding _ until they could get their layups and dunks. George
Mason got nothing, all day, at least not when it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended with Cincinnati adopting its business-as-usual
approach and the George Mason fans standing for the final two
minutes, applauding a team that came a long way in a short time.
The team that got them here is the one the coach, the fans, and the
players will remember. The one that came unglued Friday is one that
is best left forgotten.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
