u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PAYNE-$ADV15-BOS &LR;      03-12 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PAYNE-$ADV15-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PAYNE' LACKS PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, March 15)   By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
PAYNE 
Starring: John Larroquette, JoBeth Williams, Rick Batalla, Julie
Benz 
On: CBS 
Time: Premieres Monday at 9:30. Another episode airs Wednesday at
8:30, then the series moves to a regular Wednesday at 8 timeslot. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there any pleasure in ``Payne''? Let's just say the new CBS
sitcom is pretty painless, as in toothless and declawed and
watered-down. A remake of ``Fawlty Towers,'' the 12-episode BBC
series that was replayed here on PBS, ``Payne'' wants to be as
brilliantly farcical as the original, with John Larroquette trying
his own sly version of John Cleese's bold rudeness. But the show,
which premieres Monday night at 9:30 p.m., plays out more like a
mildly sexualized adaptation of classic soft-hearted American
sitcoms like ``Newhart'' (the one set in Vermont) and even
``Petticoat Junction'' (the one set in, alas, Hooterville). Despite
it's fast pace and able cast, ``Payne'' is just another familiar
network comedy about the quirky characters at a country inn _ this
time, though, with a bit of randy repartee.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-to-late 1970s England of ``Fawlty Towers,'' there was
some glee to be had in unmasking the hostility behind the polite
hotelier veneer. The show had an outrageous energy, fueled by class
tension, the battle of the sexes, and Cleese's unapologetic
contempt and fits as Basil Fawlty. In 1999 America, on the other
hand, we are nothing if not unmasked. There are so many nasty
characters on TV right now, including Ted Danson's ``Becker,''
which ``Payne'' replaces, that the duplicity of a sour inn owner
isn't particularly novel or juicy. And comically nasty characters
on American TV are required to have a lovable quality, one that can
dull the fun as it sands down the abrasiveness. No matter how gruff
and fake Larroquette is in ``Payne,'' his lanky charm generally
wins out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne'' isn't helped by the writers, whose dusty plot devices
reach back to the sneaky-spouse gags of the ``I Love Lucy'' era.
The setup of the premiere is so old and predictable you may wonder
how the writers even kept themselves interested enough to finish
the script. Basically, Larroquette's Royal Payne gives his wife,
Constance, an anniversary gift pin that he secretly lifted from the
inn's lost and found. But then the pin's owner shows up. Yikes! The
only show I can imagine adding freshness to such a hack storyline
is ``Frasier,'' which still manages to stretch from subtle comedy
of manners to farce effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual material in ``Payne'' is also curiously dated.
Constance wants to make love with Royal, but as she pulls him into
bed she doesn't know the bellhop is hiding in the room. The scene
crosses the line from bedroom-farce staple to bedroom-farce cliche,
and it offers only a tinge of fascination when you realize that the
show's creators have the Paynes sleeping in twin beds. ``Payne''
may be trying to offer a more adult alternative to the sort of
singles sexuality that fill shows like ``Just Shoot Me'' with sassy
attitude. But twin beds? What's that about?
</P>
<P>
   There are four main characters running the Whispering Pines inn
in Northern California: Royal Payne; his wife, Constance; a
goody-goody chambermaid; and a very thick bellhop. As the couple,
Larroquette and JoBeth Williams have a good sense of timing and
chemistry. Larroquette, with his snowy-slopes head of white hair,
is an especially compelling TV presence, as viewers of ``Night
Court,'' ``The John Larroquette Show,'' and ``The Practice'' will
remember. He deserves a fresher vehicle that doesn't require him to
be the henpecked husband calling out, ``Yes, my delicate flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Another episode of ``Payne'' airs Wednesday at 8:30 p.m. Next
week, the series moves to its regular timeslot of Wednesday at 8
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
