<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GAZA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAZA YOUTHS DIRECT IRE AT PALESTINIAN POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAFAH, Gaza _ With black smoke billowing from burning tires for
the third day in this Palestinian town, 27-year-old Mahmud
struggled Friday to explain what has brought him and hundreds of
residents into the streets in clashes with Palestinian police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are unfair and people can't take it,'' said Mahmud, a
tailor and veteran of years of street protests against Israeli
occupiers.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the anger is directed at their own:
Palestinian authorities who took control of this southern Gaza city
as part of the Israeli-Palestinian peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmud took part in the stone-throwing attacks this week that
injured scores of Palestinian police, who responded with tear gas
and live ammunition. Friday, he waited to see whether the flaming
tires would spark a demonstration that he could join.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when the Israelis were here I used to throw stones at
them because we wanted them out . . . they're out and now we want
to live freely, and if anything blocks this, we will stand against
it,'' said Mahmud, who refused to give his last name.
</P>
<P>
   Above his head was one of hundreds of black-and-white posters
plastered overnight on cinderblock walls throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shook the land under the feet of the Israeli Zionists and
we will make it a hell against the traitors,'' said the posters.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the protesters were demonstrating against the ruling
Palestinian Authority, viewed as heavy-handed and corrupt. Against
the Palestinian police, which fatally shot two teenage protesters
Wednesday. Against the special Palestinian security court, which
sparked the riots when it sentenced a former Islamic activist to
death.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations, which tapered off Friday into a relatively
quiet march, have raised fears the situation could intensify into
civil war. With the peace process with Israel frozen and the local
economy desperate because of corruption, mismanagement and Israeli
restrictions, frustration against the Palestinian Authority is on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian police tried to calm the situation Friday by staying
out of sight. But when a Palestinian Cabinet minister, Abu Ali
Shaheen, came to speak to the relatives of the two boys killed, he
was shouted at and told to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not between any organization and the
Palestinian Authority, but between the people and the Palestinian
Authority,'' said Ghazi Hamad, editor of an Islamist weekly
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people mistrust the Authority, they mistrust the judicial
system and what erupted in Rafah is not just a reaction to the
death sentence, but a reaction to the violations they see all the
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting started after a local man, Raed al-Attar, was
sentenced to death for killing a Palestinian police officer who was
trying to arrest Attar and two other former Islamic activists.
Attar was a member of a different security force and he allegedly
was planning an attack against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But to many people in Rafah, Attar is seen as a Palestinian
nationalist unjustly sentenced to death by a court that is already
under heavy criticism from human rights groups for lack of due
process and hasty trials that end with death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration in Rafah was sparked by the court verdict, but
the fervor appears to have been fueled by a general frustration
with the way things have turned out since Palestinian Authority
took over in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of the two teenaged boys on the first day only
inflamed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better during the Israeli occupation,'' claimed
55-year-old Shaban Mugari, whose son was out demonstrating this
week. ``Because then if you were killed, it was your enemy doing
the killing, but now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how Palestinian President Yasser Arafat will deal
with this problem. Political groups, including the Islamic Hamas
and Arafat's Fatah organization, have pleaded for Arafat to review
Attar's death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Arafat has shown himself responsive to pressure
from the street, but in this case it might be more difficult for
him to solve things. While many in Rafah are clamoring for the case
against Attar to be reopened, the family of the police officer he
allegedly murdered wants revenge. Meanwhile, the families of the
two boys killed in the rioting this week also want revenge on the
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of their relatives have been staging a sort of sit-in.
Plunked on blue plastic chairs pulled out on a side street, they
say they will wait there until they have justice. In this case,
justice means punishing the people who shot the boys, but one man
said Arafat needed to take steps to address some of the more
fundamental complaints as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat is doing his best to establish an independent state,
but without justice and democracy it won't work,'' said a
50-year-old relative of Hamis Salameh, one of the slain
17-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has achieved a lot since 1994 and all his achievements are
being destroyed by bloodsuckers,'' said the man, who would not give
his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
