<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola stock jumps 10 percent
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Big Red appears to be on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co. stock jumped 10.4 percent over the last two days
on heavy volume.
</P>
<P>
   The stock closed Friday at $69.43 3/4, up $3.06 1/4 for the day
and $6.56 1/4 from Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing new in the near-term fundamentals,'' analyst
Jennifer Solomon of Salomon Smith Barney said Friday. ``I think
people are realizing that it's Coke. ... It's still an excellent
business model and has a great management.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, analyst Skip Carpenter of Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette Securities raised his rating to ``buy'' from ``market
perform,'' citing the company's ``unrivaled'' global reach.
Carpenter expects Coca-Cola's stock to reach $79 within 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-December, Solomon upgraded the stock to ``buy,''
predicting that it would hit $73 in about six months to a year. On
Feb. 23, she reiterated her position.
</P>
<P>
   Since hitting a 52-week high of $88.93 3/4 July 15, the company
has seen its stock fall to as low as $53.62 1/2. Investors have
been concerned about its exposure overseas, where a number of
economies have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Coca-Cola's Chairman and Chief Executive M. Douglas
Ivester delivered several speeches to business groups stressing the
company's long-term strategy of staying the course in turbulent
markets so it can capitalize when the good times return.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has more than 1.5 million shareholders who own the
stock directly or through their brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
