</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dow continues surge toward 10,000
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Dow Jones industrial average resumes its10K run
Monday after twice coming within a whisper of a landmark close
above 10,000, only to drop back both times.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow came within 41 points of 10,000 on Friday, or 23 points
closer than on Thursday. But the effort fizzled immediately and
never seriously threatened again.
</P>
<P>
   A gain by each of the Dow's 30 blue chip stocks would have been
enough to push the index over the top after Thursday's
record-setting close at 9,897.44.
</P>
<P>
   But two Dow stocks were responsible for postponing that
achievement: Caterpillar, the manufacturer of earth-moving
equipment, which fell $6.18 3/4 to $44.68 3/4 after warning of
lower than expected first quarter sales, and computer giant IBM,
which fell $4.87 1/2 to $178 on general market concern about
technology profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of lackluster earnings releases, particularly from
the technology sector, has sparked the current selloff,
particularly given the market's recent worries over a possible PC
sales slowdown,'' said Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst David Kim.
</P>
<P>
   A disappointing third quarter sales report by Oracle Corp. put a
damper on the market in general.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-loaded Nasdaq composite index posted the biggest
decline on Friday _ 1.3 percent _ followed by a 0.7 percent decline
in the Russell 2000 index of smaller stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The blue chip indexes _ the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 _ posted
declines of about 0.2 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street analysts scoff at the attention that 100-point
and 1,000-point advances receive as being mostly a psychological
phenomenon. But others say such attention can have an impact in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of enthusiasm for Dow 10,000 and it almost seems
like it's built-in now,'' Peter Cardillo, director of research at
Westfalia Investments, told Dow Jones News Service.
</P>
<P>
   He looks for the Dow to reach that milestone by the end of next
week, which is the next ``triple witching'' session for the stock
market. That once-a-quarter event is when stock options, stock
index options and stock futures expire on the same day, and
typically add to the market's volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
