<HEADER>
A8599 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-NEON-ART-2     03-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-NEON-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGE NEON: HI, AGAIN: THAT CONGENIAL COMPACT GROWS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Chrysler Corp. broke the rules when it brought out
the first-generation Neon in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   While American and Japanese auto makers offered homely
econoboxes, the Neon had a style that was funky and unpretentious.
While the Big Three were struggling to attract 18-to-25-year-olds
to their showrooms, the Neon quickly developed a youthful
following.
</P>
<P>
   While some competitors had small, anemic engines producing less
than 100 horsepower, the Neon was available with as much as 150.
The peppy, responsive Neon was also relatively fun to drive, and
there was even a weekend racing model _ the Dodge Neon R/T with a
special race package. Owners could participate in
Chrysler-sponsored competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Neon was designed to earn a profit, in contrast
to most small cars, which are often loss leaders aimed at drawing
customers into showrooms _ and helping to improve corporate economy
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually identical Neons were sold through both Dodge and
Plymouth dealers, an industry first. The move saved money that
otherwise would have been spent to differentiate similar models
with slightly different trim, and it eliminated huge marketing
costs by advertising a single Neon instead of two distinct cars.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising also took a fresh and memorable approach. Who
could forget the simple ad campaign in which the Neon was presented
like a friendly pet, its grinning face filling the television
screen with only a single word _ ``Hi'' _ underneath?
</P>
<P>
   The Neon has suffered a sales slump lately along with the entire
small-car segment, which still accounts for nearly a third of all
United States car sales. At times, Chrysler has offered hefty sales
incentives to move Neons, and production has been occasionally cut
back because of bloated inventories. Still, the Neon has been an
unqualified success; Chrysler has sold 1.5 million in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The second-generation Neon is now arriving in Dodge and Plymouth
showrooms. Developed by Chrysler before its merger with
Daimler-Benz, the 2000 Neon retains many of its original features,
including style, value and a fun-to-drive character. But like its
prospective owners, it has grown up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Neon rides on the same basic chassis as the previous
model, though the wheelbase is an inch longer, the car's overall
length is 2.6 inches longer and the roof is slightly higher. The
most significant structural change is the addition of steel frames
around the door windows. Along with some other beefing up, this
makes the body more rigid.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon wears new skin over its old skeleton, though its
distinctive face, with headlamps resembling a toddler's wide-eyed
gaze and a grille like a child's grin, has not changed much.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Neon looks a little less cute and a little more
grown up, to appeal to the Generation X consumers who are settling
down and the Baby Boomers whose nests are emptying _ the two groups
most likely to buy the car. From the rear, the Neon resembles its
much larger sibling, the handsome Dodge Intrepid.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon also retains Chrysler's cab-forward design, which
plants the wheels out near the corners of the car for increased
interior room. In fact, the 2000 Neon has grown a bit inside, and
trunk space has expanded to 13.1 cubic feet from 11.8.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrics and materials are significantly upgraded and more
sophisticated. A new instrument panel features circular white-faced
gauges under a wide brow. Features like power switches have been
repositioned on the door for easier access. There are storage
compartments for coins, cellular phones, sunglasses, compact disks
and tissues, as well as large map pockets in the front doors.
</P>
<P>
   The locking glove box has holders for pens and a tire gauge.
Four cup holders can hold large cups, mugs or juice boxes. The
front seating position is higher than its predecessor for improved
visibility, though it still felt as if it were designed for
youthful bodies. My middle-age frame found the front seats still
uncomfortable, lacking back support on long drives. The back of the
rear seat is split and either part, or both, folds for increased
cargo capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The original Neon was the first small car to have standard
driver and passenger air bags and to offer anti-lock brakes as an
option. The new Neon has adjustable head restraints including ones
in the rear seat. But like all other Chrysler-developed models, the
Neon does not have side air bags; some competitors, including the
Chevrolet Prizm, do offer them.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon does have more standard equipment than its predecessor.
Standard now are an AM/FM radio with a cassette player and six
speakers; a rear defroster; floor mats; a battery saver that shuts
off the dome light if it is left on, and gradual theater-style
dimming for the interior lights. The door handles are now
body-colored.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A number of options are grouped in packages for easy ordering.
For instance, one $1,760 package adds air-conditioning, keyless
entry, a tilt steering wheel, power windows and power door locks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its sophisticated appearance, the Neon's youthful,
fun-to-drive character remains intact. This has has long been among
the sportiest of the small economy cars, and its chassis is better
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon continues to be powered by a 2-liter, 4-cylinder engine
with a fairly modern single-overhead-cam design. Rated at 132
horsepower, this engine is at the high end of the class and is one
of the Neon's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the Neon was available with a 150-horsepower,
dual-overhead-cam engine. To the chagrin of enthusiasts, that
potent but noisy power plant has been eliminated. DaimlerChrysler
says a higher-performance Neon is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon comes with a standard five-speed manual transmission,
my preference, or a three-speed automatic. Unlike most other small
cars, the Neon doesn't have a four-speed automatic, which in theory
would provide better mileage and smoother performance. But even the
tested Dodge Neon with the three-speed provided plenty of zip from
a dead stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Neon's brakes have been redesigned for shorter stopping.
Front disks and rear drums are standard, but four-wheel disk brakes
with an anti-lock system and traction control are available as a
single $595 option _ one that is worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   Despite attempts to quiet the noise _ the latest of which
includes triple seals on the full-frame doors and extra
sound-deadening material, the Neon remains noisy, especially
compared with, say, a Toyota Corolla. (The Saturn suffers similarly
from a high noise level.) But hey, that's where those six speakers
on the audio system come in handy. Just crank it up and drown out
the noise.
</P>
<P>
   The first Neon initially suffered from many quality problems,
with several recalls in its early months on the market. With the
2000-model test car, I encountered only a single glitch, though a
significant one. On occasion, I would shift the automatic
transmission into reverse to back out of a parking spot, and it
would behave as if it were in neutral. Throwing it into park and
trying the process again resolved the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reduce costs, DaimlerChrysler not only dropped
the dual-cam engine, it eliminated the two-door model entirely.
(The coupe's share of Neon sales had recently fallen to 18 percent,
from 25 two years ago.) Only two trim levels are now offered: a
basic version and a fancier model called LX by Plymouth and ES by
Dodge.
</P>
<P>
   Despite various cost-cutting measures like these, the Neon's
price has gone up. When it was introduced in 1994, the base price
of the entry-level model was under $10,000. The base price of the
2000 Neon, albeit with more standard equipment, is $13,390 when
destination charges are added. Options quickly push the price to
$15,000 and beyond _ into the realm of considerably larger cars
like the Nissan Altima and DaimlerChrysler's own Plymouth Breeze.
</P>
<P>
   While the original Neon stood out for its perky character and
sporty performance, the new version faces much tougher competition.
In particular, Ford promises a real battle this fall when it brings
its new Focus, which replaces the Escort, to North America.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus is designed to raise the bar in the small car class
for bold styling, interior roominess, responsive driving dynamics
and engines that rival the power of Neons. Already voted European
Car of the Year by a panel of auto writers, the Focus will be
available in three body styles _ a coupe, sedan and wagon _ with a
choice of five trim levels and two engines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, the 2000 Neon owns the neighborhood. But a prodigy, the
Focus, will soon be the new kid on the block. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: That cute baby is now a good-looking adolescent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
