<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV14-NY     03-12 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARK SIDE OF PROSPERITY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ The surging prosperity over the past three
years has lifted a lot of boats, and has left the water rather
choppy for many others.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki and James Stogdill are in the latter group. They own a
television and appliance store on Franklin Avenue here, in a mixed
commercial and residential area. And their troubles are the
troubles of many small retailers, who find themselves at the wrong
end of an American boom that has spread its benefits unevenly.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for small retailers is labor. The shining
characteristic of the 1990s expansion, in contrast to those of the
1970s and 1980s, is that wages have risen faster than inflation for
most workers. The raises for people at the low end, earning $6 to
$9 an hour, have been particularly strong. These are workers that
the Stogdills hire, and the rising labor cost, while a happy
circumstance for the workers, is squeezing the Stogdills.
</P>
<P>
   They can't raise prices to offset higher payroll costs _ too
much competition. Inflation is all but dead in the late 1990s, for
small retailers and for everyone else. Big companies, however, have
aces up their sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   They can deflect higher labor costs by moving operations to
lower-wage cities, for example, or by automating. Such tactics are
not really an option at Stogdill's TV and Appliances, the family
business founded by James Stogdill's father in 1957 and profitable
ever since, although less so lately because of the wage pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Selling TVs, VCRs, audio equipment, refrigerators, washing
machines, dishwashers and other appliances off the floor is
labor-intensive. So are the repairs done in a back shop and the
service calls to customers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I belong to a small-business organization,'' Mrs. Stogdill
said, ``and at meetings, when I bring up my problems, the whole
room chimes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising wages are one face of the problem. The other is a
shortage of workers. During slack times, lower-wage workers count
on small companies like Stogdill's for jobs. But the unemployment
rate in Des Moines today is less than 3 percent. Available workers
are hard to find, and larger companies, offering better pay and
better benefits, are drawing down Stogdill's normal pool of
potential hires.
</P>
<P>
   After much searching, the Stogdills recently filled vacancies
for a bookkeeper and a clerk, the bookkeeper at $11 an hour and the
clerk at $8. The previous occupants had earned $8.50 and $6.50,
respectively. ``I had used an employment agency to try to fill the
clerk job,'' Mrs. Stogdill said. ``I had never used an agency
before, and that's an extra expense right there. Luckily, through a
friend, I got someone for $8 an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stogdills normally run their operation with 21 people,
including themselves. They have managed to keep their labor cost at
a steady $35,000 a month, despite wage increases averaging 10
percent a year since 1996. That is a sharp departure from the
cost-of-living raises that had been standard practice at
Stogdill's, and still are for the higher earners on the staff. But
holding labor costs steady at $35,000 entails a sacrifice: the
staff has dwindled to 17 people, and that creates another problem.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen people are not enough hands to build up revenue, Mrs.
Stogdill said. Times are good and people are spending, and that
requires a bigger staff to exploit the opportunity. She and her
husband would like, for example, to hire another repair person.
Repair work, which now accounts for only 20 percent of the
company's revenue, generates the highest profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't raise prices on the product side, so we are going to
have to do it on the service end,'' Mrs. Stogdill said. ``Even now,
we are implementing job pricing, which is a flat rate rather than
an hourly rate for a service job. It's like car dealers who for
years have charged flat prices to change brakes, although an
experienced mechanic can do it in 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stogdills are offering $10 an hour for that additional
repair person, a wage that is no longer high enough to land one
quickly. ``I could attract someone for $15 an hour,'' Mrs. Stogdill
said, ``but only by stealing from a competitor, and I don't want to
get to that point. We would get into a free-for-all that would hurt
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience at Stogdill's is reflected in the surveys of the
National Federation of Independent Business, which has 600,000
members, including Stogdill's. One-quarter are retailers, and most
of the members have fewer than 40 employees. Like Stogdill's, a
significant percentage report that their profits are under pressure
and that they are having trouble filling jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Such strains skew the economic expansion, accentuating its
uneven nature. These are prosperous days. Wages are rising and
unemployment is falling. That is certainly good. But in the absence
of almost any inflation, boom has come to mean squeeze for
Stogdill's, and for tens of thousands of companies like it in
America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
