<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, STUDIES AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting Evolution On Fast-Forward &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The corporate chief who has created more shareholder value ($300
billion plus) than anyone not currently accused of monopolistic
practices acknowledged in a New York appearance last week that he
is a ``Neanderthal'' when it comes to computers.
</P>
<P>
   But that executive, John F. Welch Jr. of General Electric, is
determined that each of his company's businesses will leap from the
Stone Age to the 21st century when it comes to making the best use
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the Internet's growth, seen in the surge of on-line
retail sales at the end of last year, caught him by surprise, Welch
acknowledged to an audience at the 92d Street ``Y.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the company's many units, he credited only NBC with making
good use of the new medium: MSNBC, the cable channel, is owned by
NBC and Microsoft; Microsoft's chairman, William H. Gates, is one
of Welch's golfing buddies.
</P>
<P>
   GE is seeking ways to use its own Internet interests as currency
to buy or invest in other Internet businesses. Instead of dipping
into its $4.3 billion cash hoard to make acquisitions, Welch said,
``we have to have seven more dot-coms, so we can trade our paper
with somebody else's paper.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allen R. Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Living for the Weekend &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bucking the trend toward longer and longer retail hours, Aisle
3, a new off-price retailer, cut the ribbon Friday on three stores
that will be open just _ you guessed it _ three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that career-oriented adults don't have time to shop
except on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays, and that it will be
easier to recruit employees for a 28-hour week than for longer
hours spread over more working days.
</P>
<P>
   Aisle 3, a division of the Filene's Basement Corp., sells
housewares and men's and women's clothing. The first
60,000-square-foot stores are in Spring Valley, N.Y., and Totowa
and Union, N.J., all near New York City, with a store in Towson,
Md., outside Baltimore, to come at month's end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Hershey Jr. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8603 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-MARKETS-ABROAD     03-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MARKETS-ABROAD-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EURO'S FICKLE FINGERS FOIL MANY A PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, with the arrival of the new single European currency
and forecasts that the American economy would slow down in 1999,
European stock markets seemed as though they would be a pretty good
choice for American investors.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not been the case so far this year. Although
Europe's major markets other than Germany have done nearly as well
as the United States for local investors, the returns for Americans
in those markets are smaller or even negative.
</P>
<P>
   This disappointing performance is the fault of the new currency,
the euro. Most forecasters, especially those in Europe, predicted
that the euro would rise smartly against the dollar and other
currencies after its debut. Instead, it has slumped since its first
week of trading. This decline erodes the year's gains on European
stocks when they are translated into dollars.
</P>
<P>
   For American investors, the euro's performance is a stark
reminder that currency moves can still play a major role in the
value of an international portfolio, despite assurances that the
new euro, by combining 11 currencies, would make investing in
Europe less complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currency can really make a difference,'' lamented Joe Rooney,
global strategist for Lehman Brothers Securities in London and one
of many analysts who had expected the euro to rise in value. ``What
really caught us was the euro,'' he said. ``We thought the good
local stock returns would have been re-enforced'' by a rally in the
new currency.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the CAC index of 40 stocks is up 5.9 percent in euro
terms. But after accounting for the 7 percent fall in the value of
the euro against the dollar, that gain reverses to a 1 percent
decline. The 3.8 percent increase in Italy's Milan index of 30
stocks becomes a 3 percent decline in dollars. Ireland's overall
index is up 8.2 percent in euros but only 1.1 percent in dollars.
Only in Finland, where the main stock index has soared 14.8
percent, is the dollar return _ 7.3 percent _ a match for Wall
Street's performance.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has even undermined a remarkable turnaround in the
German stock market. The DAX index of 30 stocks shot up 5.1 percent
Friday on news of the resignation of Oskar Lafontaine, the German
finance minister, who had alienated business leaders in part by
calling for tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   That surge left the DAX up half a percentage point for the year
in euros, back in the plus column after a sharp selloff from its
January high. But American investors are still in the red in
Germany, by 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of the dollar has also hurt Americans investing
elsewhere, although that rebound was better anticipated. The dollar
is now up 4.5 percent against the yen this year and has cut sharply
into one of the better recent performances of the Japanese stock
market. The Nikkei index of 225 stocks is up 11.9 percent in yen
but 7.1 percent in dollars. (Given Japan's recent track record,
American investors are probably not complaining.)
</P>
<P>
   Rooney thinks the euro will rebound later this year, wiping out
the currency losses and then amplifying gains that investors
receive from the stock market. By the end of the year, Rooney is
forecasting a 10 percent increase from current levels, to $1.20.
</P>
<P>
   That would make a big difference for American investors. With
the euro worth $1.20, the 1 percent decline in the French stock
market in dollars so far this year would be transformed, for
example, into an attractive 8.9 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   But will Rooney prove to be correct? The euro rallied last week,
rising three-quarters of a percent, to $1.0905. But its biggest
daily gain _ an almost 1 percent jump on Thursday, when the German
Finance Minister resigned _ evaporated on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Karen E. Parker, the currency strategist at Chase Securities,
who predicted a fall in the new euro, still does not think it will
rally this year, although Lafontaine's resignation may stem its
near-term decline. She thinks an interest-rate cut to spur sluggish
European growth is more likely, a move that would weaken the euro.
</P>
<P>
   And she is betting that the relatively stronger American economy
will keep investors more interested in holding dollars than euros,
leaving the new currency at about the same weakish level in 12
months that it is now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
