<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO (Independence, Mo.) _ Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic Friday became the first former members of the old Soviet
bloc to join NATO, expanding the Western military alliance to 19
members. At a ceremony in the hometown of the late U.S. President
Harry Truman, the foreign ministers of the three new members signed
formal documents of accession and gave them to U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who told the ministers: ``You are truly
allies, you are truly home.'' By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADES-SHORTAGE (Chicago) _ Faced with a shortage of
tradesworkers to meet the voracious demand for new construction in
the United States, desperate builders and eager unions have kicked
off aggressive campaigns to court new workers, attracting women and
members of racial minorities to the traditional bastion of white
men, a world where a coveted union card was handed from father to
son. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
