u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS13-     03-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-EXPULSIONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Action against IOC members falls short of expulsion
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Insisting that his corruption investigation was not a
``whitewash,'' the head of an International Olympic Committee panel
said Friday severe public rebukes are recommended for many members.
</P>
<P>
   IOC Vice President Dick Pound said the penalties fall short of
expulsion, however, for all the members still under investigation
save one, Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   IOC investigators recommended severe censure for the two
highest-profile members implicated in the corruption scandal, Kim
Un-yong, an executive board member from South Korea and Phil Coles,
a longtime IOC member from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A third leading member, Vitaly Smirnov of Russia, was
recommended for a ``very serious'' warning in a report from a
six-man inquiry that examined the conduct of 17 IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a whitewash at all,'' Pound said of the report. ``It
is a very serious rebuke to the members that is being made public
throughout the world. I think that is very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Less-severe warnings also were proposed for Louis
Guirandou-N'Diaye of the Ivory Coast, Willi Kaltschmitt of
Guatemala, Shagdarjav Magvan of Mongolia, Anani Matthia of Togo,
Austin Sealy of Barbados and Mohamed Zerguini of Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations must be acted upon by the IOC's executive
board before final action by a special general assembly in
Lausanne, Switzerland, next week.
</P>
<P>
   Nine IOC members already have resigned or been expelled in the
corruption scandal surrounding Salt Lake City's winning bid for the
2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation dealt with 14 members in its first
phase and reconvened to consider another 16 members implicated last
month in a Utah ethics board report. Six of those cases, involving
unidentified members, were considered insignificant and dropped
without any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were probably as tough on IOC members as any outside body
would be,'' said Pound, responding to criticism that the IOC was
not capable of investigating its own members.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation alleged that Kim used his Olympic position to
help land lucrative jobs in telecommunications and music for his
two children _ daughter Kim Hae-jung, a concert pianist, and son
Kim Jung-hoon, a satellite television executive also known as John
Kim.
</P>
<P>
   While the panel issued a recommendation on Kim, however, his
case remained open. The report said allegations still to be
completely investigated could lead to a recommendation for
expulsion ``if what's alleged turns out to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, who resigned Friday from the Australian Olympic
Committee, was cited for accepting some $60,000 in travel to ski
resorts and the Super Bowl from Salt Lake bidders. Coles has
repeatedly denied wrongdoing but conceded he had been ``careless''
in handling the lavish perks.
</P>
<P>
   The Pound report determined that Coles ``did not exercise his
best judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Smirnov was cited by the Salt Lake report for involvement in a
scholarship at the University of Utah for the daughter of the head
of a leading Russian recording company. Kim Jae-hung signed her
first major recording contract with the company Melodiya.
</P>
<P>
   Wallwork came under investigation after it was revealed his
wife, Julia, had borrowed $30,000 from Tom Welch, the former head
of Salt Lake's Olympic efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also recommended the IOC set up an ethics
committee, including outside members, and establish a code of
conduct; create a reform commission including outside experts to
study structural changes of the IOC; and adopt a new Olympic
bidding and site-selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
