u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-OPENRECORDS13-COX     03-12 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OPENRECORDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gov. Barnes: Olympic records should be publicly released
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt and Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes said Friday he will ask the state
attorney general to determine whether documents related to
Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Centennial Olympics should be publicly
released.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, who helped craft Georgia's open records law and pushed
legislation this year to strengthen it, said he would release the
documents if they were in state custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made my position pretty clear from the beginning. I
believe the documents are subject to open inspection,'' Barnes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's comments followed a request from The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution seeking his support, as well as that of Mayor
Bill Campbell, in efforts to gain access to the Georgia Amateur
Athletics Foundation's records. Nick Gold, a spokesman for
Campbell, said the mayor ``absolutely'' supports opening the
records to public inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he will reiterate his position in asking Attorney
General Thurbert Baker for a legal opinion. He said he expects
Baker to be sympathetic. ``He's been generally very sensitive to
Open Records also,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAAF, a nonprofit organization created by Billy Payne in
1987 to direct Atlanta's bid for the 1996 Summer Olympics,
maintains the documents are the property of a group of private
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, however, said the fact that the foundation started off
as a private entity isn't enough to shield the records. ``The
intent of the law was clear. If there is a private group that
performs public functions, then that private group is subject to
the Open Records-Open Meetings acts,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's officers were not all private citizens. Andrew
Young pledged his support to the bid effort and was chairman of the
foundation while he was mayor of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   And the foundation's bid pledged the use of city and state
facilities, government services and construction of a
state-financed Olympic Village at a public university.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GAAF will gladly work with the attorney general's office
and the governor's office on this matter,'' said Lee Echols,
foundation spokesman. ``However, we have made it clear that we
believe the Georgia Open Records Act does not apply to the private
records of GAAF.''
</P>
<P>
   GAAF lawyers did not return calls Friday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's bid effort has come under scrutiny during
investigations into a million-dollar vote-buying scheme surrounding
Salt Lake City's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``GAAF is currently creating an archive of the documents that
are in question,'' Echols said. ``And these are documents to which
the public will have access once they are properly archived.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he has no reason to believe improprieties
occurred. ``I know all these folks, they're honorable folks,''
Barnes said. ``I don't have any knowledge there was anything
substantially done wrong. But that's not the issue here. The issue
here is whether the public has a right to information to make a
decision on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
