A8615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LIGTENBERG13-COX     03-12 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LIGTENBERG13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ligtenberg may be lost for season
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ In another stunner that could effect
the Braves for the rest of the season, Kerry Ligtenberg was found
Friday to have a partial tear of the medial collateral ligament in
his right elbow that could require season-ending surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg, who recorded 30 saves as a rookie last season, has
been shut down for the next three-to-four weeks, when his condition
will be re-evaluated. If the ligament has shown improvement, he
could rejoin the club as early as mid-April. If it has not
improved, he would require ``Tommy John'' ligament transplant
surgery that would end his season before it ever begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real happy it happened the way it has,'' said
Ligtenberg, who finished sixth in the National League Rolaids
reliever standings after replacing Mark Wohlers as the Braves
closer last season. ``I've never been injured before so it's kind
of a shocker.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz alerted the club's scouting
staff to Ligtenberg's injuryFriday morning, so that the team would
have it's ``antennas up'' for a possible trade for a closer. But
the GM estimated such a deal would come later in camp and singled
out Rudy Seanez, rookie Kevin McGlinchy and foremost John Rocker as
possible successors to Ligtenberg's closer role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a substantial blow,'' Schuerholz said. ``You can't
minimize that, but there are a lot of people in our organization
who have felt strongly about Rocker's ability to handle a job like
that, if the opportunity ever came. Well, it's come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who already lost first baseman Andres Galarraga this
spring, suspected Ligtenberg had a problem Wednesday, after he
allowed five runs in the ninth inning to the Astros. He told
trainers something caused a burning sensation in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like in my head I could loosen up my forearm a little
bit but that just wasn't the case,'' Ligtenberg said. ``It was only
after the inning was over and I'd stopped throwing that basically,
my forearm was in a knot. And that's when I knew something was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg underwent an MRI Thursday and was examined by team
orthopedist Joe Chandler again Friday morning before the diagnosis
was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
