</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-ITALY-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT NATO EVENT, ITALIAN PRIME MINISTER CALLS FOR JUSTICE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: MARINE-AVIATOR-MAPS) 
(rk) 
 By   ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, in Poland to mark the
expansion of NATO, warned Friday that Italy may someday want to
make some other changes to the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we demand that justice be done,'' D'Alema said. If not, he
said, Italy might have to reconsider some aspects of a 1951 NATO
agreement. D'Alema, like the rest of Italy, was outraged by the
acquittal of the U.S. pilot who flew into a ski lift cable in
Northern Italy last year, killing 20 people. Under NATO rules, the
United States had jurisdiction over the case.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating at the NATO gathering what he had told President
Clinton and the Italian Parliament, D'Alema said that he expected
the United States to find those who were responsible for the
disaster. If not, the prime minister said that Italy might have to
reconsider how jurisdiction is awarded in the future.
</P>
<P>
   There is no indication that D'Alema, a former Communist who has
consistently defended the presence of U.S. troops at NATO bases in
Italy, has any intention of altering Italy's commitment to the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But since the verdict came out at Camp Lejeune, he has
repeatedly said that if no culprit is ever found, then Italy may
try to reopen negotiation of the 1951 multilateral treaty that
allows governments to claim jurisdiction over cases in which their
soldiers are accused of a crime while serving overseas. But he has
been careful to say he does not want to scrap that provision,
merely adapt it.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Italy has also availed itself of that agreement,
most notably in 1988, when an Italian stunt plane crashed at an air
show at Ramstein, a U.S. air base in Germany, killing 70 people.
The squadron commander and pilots were tried in Italy, and
acquitted in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is evident that while the principles of jurisdiction as
they are formulated in those accords remain firm,'' D'Alema told
the Italian Parliament on Wednesday, ``it is possible, first, that
in practice, the accord will be applied only in exceptional cases.
And second, when the jurisdiction is carried out by the country
that claims it, then there should be guarantees for the country in
which the alleged crimes took place, including the possibility of
filing a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most experts say it is unlikely that the 16 NATO countries that
signed the agreement in London in 1951 would all agree to alter it,
and that may not be D'Alema's real goal. His comments are mostly
aimed at appeasing domestic public opinion, which remains
infuriated by the acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   They are also part of a campaign to pressure the United States
to keep investigating the accident. And they are also intended as a
warning to the U.S. military to take seriously its pledge to
cooperate fully with Italy in improving safety at U.S. bases here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Thursday, D'Alema turned over to Italian prosecutors two
bilateral agreements that had previously been classified. Both deal
with the rules governing the presence of U.S. forces and the use of
installations.
</P>
<P>
   One is a 1954 accord, and the other a 1995 memorandum of
understanding, that says, among other things, ``planning and
execution of all training and operational activity will be in
respect of civil and military regulations of the host nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents were requested by military prosecutors in Padua,
who are investigating whether to bring charges against Col. Orfeo
Durignon, the Italian commander of the Aviano base, for failing to
ensure that proper procedure was followed there.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that Durignon will be given a court
martial in Italy. Civil prosecutors in Trento had already decided
against bringing him to trial on involuntary homicide charges.
</P>
<P>
   The chief military prosecutor in Padua, Maurizio Block, said
Friday that the Italian military was unlikely to put Durignon on
trial. ``All the documents and testimony we have seen so far in our
investigation suggest that his authority at the base was empty,''
Block said. ``He had some formal responsibility, but in reality, he
did not have the power to say no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
