<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVEST DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wide Yield Premiums For Less-Risky Bradys &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's natural enough that Latin American government bonds trade
at prices that translate into double-digit yields these days: With
turmoil in Brazil's finances and lingering worries that it will
spread, Latin bonds summon up ``risky'' in many a mind the way Tito
Puente does salsa. Investors demand high yields to compensate for
high currency and credit risk.
</P>
<P>
   It's less obvious why yields should now be so high on
collateralized Brady bonds. Though issued by Latin American
governments, these bonds are denominated in dollars, and repayment
of all or part of the principal (though not interest) is
effectively guaranteed by the United States Treasury. Yet the yield
spreads between these Bradys and comparable Treasuries are now
temptingly wide.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gray, head of emerging-markets debt research at Rogge
Global Partners of London, points to one example of a Brady,
Mexican par bonds due in 2019, which were trading last week at
around 77 cents per dollar of face value, giving them a yield of
8.6 percent. That is more than 3 percentage points more than
Treasuries of the same maturity, which finished the week yielding
5.4 percent. Some similar Brazilian par bonds due in 2024 traded at
about 57 cents on the dollar, yielding 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For yield-hungry investors, though, a caveat: Not all Bradys are
collateralized, and those that are may be only partly covered. On
those Brazilian pars, for instance, 28 cents on the dollar is
guaranteed, reckons Umran Demimirors of the Templeton Emerging Debt
fund. And the big denominations of Bradys, usually $250,000 or
more, put them beyond the reach of many individual investors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (International Herald Tribune) &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Opts Out Of New S&AMP;P Rankings &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You might expect mutual fund managers to jump at the prospect of
inclusion in Standard &AMP; Poor's new select list of top funds. S&AMP;P, a
unit of McGraw-Hill, wants to grab some of the market for fund
ratings and data now dominated by Lipper Inc. and Morningstar Inc.
by publishing regular lists of the top 10 percent or so of funds in
more than 15 style categories.
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for any Fidelity Investments funds in the lists
anytime soon, even though the Fidelity family has been performing
well lately. Fidelity objects to an S&AMP;P requirement that it
disclose its portfolio holdings quarterly, instead of twice a year
as the Securities and Exchange Commission requires.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P starts by using three-year performance results, accounting
for risk, to find roughly the top one-third of funds. Then it
reviews holdings and conducts interviews with portfolio managers to
assess each fund's clarity and consistency of philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot get that from performance data,'' said Philip
Edwards, a managing director in S&AMP;P Ratings Services' Managed Funds
unit. ``You only get that from talking'' to fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   The first list, of the 24 best large-cap growth funds, includes
big names like Janus Growth and Income and Putnam Investors, and
smaller funds like Accessor Growth Portfolio, Alleghany Chicago
Trust Growth and Income and Papp America Abroad. A small-cap growth
list is due in April, and mid-cap growth in May.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the S&AMP;P ratings are available free on the World Wide
Web, at www.standardandpoors.com/onfunds. Eventually, S&AMP;P hopes to
make money from subscriptions and reprint fees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Oppel Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among Stock Funds, Small is Beautiful &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While bigger has certainly been better lately when it comes to
stocks, that's apparently not true of mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Research Corp. of Boston studied the past decade
and found that the smallest domestic stock funds _ meaning those
with the fewest total assets, not those that invest in the smallest
stocks _ were the funds that most often outperformed the average
for their categories.
</P>
<P>
   For example, funds in the bottom fourt, ranked by total assets,
beat their category averages for the quarter seven times out of
eight, the study found, and had annual returns one percentage point
higher than the average. (The study's author concedes that these
figures are inflated a bit because poorly performing small funds
tend to shut down and disappear from the statistics.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest quarter of funds beat their category averages just
48 percent of the time, even though many, by dint of how much money
they attracted, were investors' favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larger funds that had enjoyed periods of outperformance saw
their returns revert to the mean as assets continued to balloon,''
Financial Research reported. ``Clearly, the investment flexibility
or `nimbleness' enjoyed by smaller funds provides a significant
performance advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
</TEXT>
