<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Downsizing Moves Up the Ladder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lowest jobless rate since the Nixon administration isn't
translating into job security in American executive suites.
Corporate cost-cutters are increasingly aiming at the
well-compensated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an outplacement firm
based in Chicago, managers who lost their jobs to downsizing in the
final quarter of 1998 had a median salary of of $92,000, up 18
percent from $78,000 in the third quarter and the highest since the
firm started keeping track in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The high pay that made them targets also made it harder for them
to find new jobs: the median search time rose to 3 months, from 2.6
months.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate survey, covering the overall work force, just 2
percent of job holders expect to be dismissed because of downsizing
or other reasons this year, according to Lee Hecht Harrison, an
outplacement firm in Woodcliff Lake, N.J. ``While there is every
indication that companies will continue to downsize,'' said
Bernadette Kenny, chief operating officer, ``most people feel it
isn't going to happen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Hershey Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving in North Carolina &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having succeeded in business, particularly in high technology,
entrepreneurs have been teaming up to form ``giving circles,''
supporting local charities by pooling dollars and expertise. Such
groups are already operating in Seattle and Silicon Valley, but a
new one is starting in the Research Triangle of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Warner, who sold his software company, the Atwork Corp.
of Chapel Hill, for $240 million in 1995, and Fred Hutchison, a
lawyer for local entrepreneurs, are forming a new givers' group,
not yet named. ``With entrepreneurs, what we are getting is not
just dollars but tremendous brainpower, and that has the likelihood
of changing the face of our communities,'' said Shannon St. John,
executive director of the Triangle Community Foundation, which
through its Catalyst Project is helping to organize the group.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
