<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECONDHAND, BUT ROSIER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NICOLE S. URDANG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I live in a secondhand house, wear secondhand clothes and eat
with a secondhand fork off a secondhand table. I drive a secondhand
car, read secondhand books and mix my children's milkshakes in a
secondhand blender. Everywhere I look, I see what once were someone
else's dressers, lamps, art, baskets and dishes. Even my husband is
secondhand.
</P>
<P>
   Buying most of our possessions at garage sales and thrift shops
has had a profound impact on my family's financial Weltanschauung.
By living on so much less at home, we now have far greater
resources for things like movies and dining out. We also have more
money for charitable donations, wonderful vacations and summer
camps.
</P>
<P>
   Without the need to fret about $75 jeans and $300 blazers ($3
and $6, respectively, and in perfect condition at my local thrift
shop), I've had the luxury of working only part time, and my
husband has been able to pursue a management career with a
nonprofit organization instead of practicing law. Yet we've been
able to maintain a comfortable, middle-class life style.
</P>
<P>
   I have my mother to thank for instilling these pecuniary skills
and values in me. She finds enlightenment and treasures by sorting
through other people's discarded artifacts. Once, her remarkable
skills brought her a 14-karat gold panther-link bracelet _ for only
25 cents at a tag sale.
</P>
<P>
   Mom wasn't able, though, to teach me the value of keeping quiet
about my own shopping victories. She still shudders every time I
crow about some bargain I picked up at a yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why tell anyone?'' she'll ask. ``Then, when you do buy
something new, they'll think you only spent a dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I've tried to refrain from telling my friends how little
I paid for something they admire, but the temptation to revel _ my
own form of reverse snobbism _ is too hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Like my mother, I've never understood the fascination with
newness. I've always believed that if I buy something for a scant
percent of what it cost originally, not only am I recycling but I
am also changing the psychic equation that makes us enjoy something
in proportion to what we pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   If a new jacket sets me back $300, I surely want to get $300 of
use and pleasure from it; if I pay only $3 for the same _ albeit
slightly used _ jacket, the joy-to-dollar ratio will be much
greater. And if I decide I don't like the jacket, at least I know
my mistake is inexpensive; I can simply give the item away with few
misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   I'm grateful that my children don't care if their Gap clothes
come from the Gap store or from the sale at the church down the
street _ or, for that matter, whether they bear the Gap brand at
all.
</P>
<P>
   By now, they're indoctrinated; they rarely think of doing what
most people would call normal shopping. And they understand the
value of a dollar, not to mention a mother whose schedule allows
her to be home to ask them how their day was.
</P>
<P>
   I'm aware that many people may cringe at the very thought of
using certain personal items that are secondhand. But I like to
remind these folks that if they have ever spent a night in a hotel,
they have slept on secondhand sheets and have dried themselves with
secondhand bath towels. And if they have ever been to a restaurant,
they have surely eaten with forks and spoons that have touched the
lips of countless other people.
</P>
<P>
   So let's face it: There is no genius or superiority in buying
retail. I must acknowledge, however, that I've been enticed lately
by those dollar-discount and odd-lot stores, discovering the joys
of almost-out-of-date spices, candy and juice _ not to mention
remaindered books, candles and children's toys.
</P>
<P>
   Secondhand or cut-rate does not mean inferior. A secondhand pair
of jeans never needs to be prefaded, and secondhand furniture is
imperfect enough to allow you to neglect it.
</P>
<P>
   And secondhand husbands are especially good at making pancakes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nicole S. Urdang is a psychotherapist and homeopathic educator
practicing in Buffalo. Submit your account of struggling or
succeeding in financial life to My Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New
York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036, or e-mail to
mymoney(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
