<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-ECON-580&AMP;ADD-     03-12 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ECON-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN MARKETS SOAR FOLLOWING DEPARTURE OF FINANCE MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also GERMANY-EICHL) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ One day after the abrupt resignation of
Germany's most powerful left-wing political boss, German financial
markets soared in euphoria Friday while Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder struggled to keep his five-month-old government from
melting down.
</P>
<P>
   The German stock market surged 5.4 percent in a torrent of
trading as investors concluded that the departure of Oskar
Lafontaine, the finance minister, meant that Schroeder would be
forced to dilute or even abandon plans to raise taxes on business,
shut down nuclear plants and increase regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders jubilantly announced that a new era was at hand
and that Schroeder's entire agenda was suddenly up for grabs. The
stock prices for insurance companies and electric utilities, which
would have been threatened with enormous tax increases, jumped more
than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the happiest day of my professional life,'' said Hans
Schreiber, chief executive of the insurance company Mannheimer AG
and head of Germany's federation of insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly calm, Schroeder moved quickly to fill the gap left
after Lafontaine, who was both his ally and rival, abruptly quit
both his post as finance minister and his chairmanship of
Schroeder's Social Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   To replace the bombastic Lafontaine at the powerful Finance
Ministry, Schroeder named Hans Eichel, a relatively colorless
Social Democrat who is the lame-duck prime minister of the state of
Hesse, where Social Democrats were trounced in local elections
several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder then put himself in charge of the Social Democratic
Party, a move that gives him control of both the government and the
powerful machinery of the political party. Until Friday, the
comparatively pragmatic chancellor had been locked in an uneasy
dependence on Lafontaine's organizational strength in the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the sense of chaos and shock was pervasive in both the
Social Democratic Party and its coalition partner, the
environmental Green Party. And political experts said it was far
from clear that Schroeder could repair the damage to his party.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine himself remained silent, staying behind the shuttered
windows of his house in the city of Saarbruecken near the French
border. An outspoken and ideologically passionate left-wing
traditionalist who had enraged central bankers with blustery
demands for lower interest rates, Lafontaine handed in a
one-sentence resignation on Thursday and has offered no hint about
his motive for resigning.
</P>
<P>
   Uwe-Karsten Heye, Schroeder's spokesman, said the chancellor had
been unable to reach Lafontaine on the telephone. Chancery
officials said Schroeder was as surprised and mystified as anybody
by Lafontaine's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an event that is hard to come to terms with,'' said Otto
Schily, the interior minister and a longtime friend of
Lafontaine's. ``It would be valuable to know what led him to this
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt Friday that Schroeder would amend some of his
biggest projects. His tax reform plan, drawn up by Lafontaine,
would have added billions of marks in extra taxes on corporations
while giving a slew of new breaks to lower- and middle-income
families.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has drawn enormous criticism from industry as well as
from Germany's most respected independent economists. In their
view, the plan did little to reduce Germany's overall tax burden,
which consumes about half the country's entire economic output.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Corporate executives were furious at the prospect of huge new
burdens without much offsetting relief. Insurance companies would
be particularly hard-hit, because of a provision that would have
required them to pay taxes on vast sums of reserves that had been
shielded from tax liability under current law. Electric utilities
would have been forced to pay heavy taxes on money set aside for
shutting down nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, insurance and electric utility stocks were the
biggest winners in an extraordinary day. Shares of Allianz, the
giant Munich-based insurance carrier, went up 15 percent. Munich
Re, the big re-insurance conglomerate, jumped more than 10 percent.
Conglomerates with big electric utilities like RWE and Viag AG rose
nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't get carried away, but the euphoria is to a large
extent justified,'' said Holger Fahrinkrug, an economist at Warburg
Dillion Read in Frankfurt. ``A major barrier to corporate profits
has left today.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger question was whether Schroeder and his ``red
green'' political coalition would be able to regain its balance or
even survive in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, a self-styled pragmatist who is a master at
projecting charisma on television, remains personally popular. But
the nature of power in Germany requires control of the major
political parties, and it was the much more left-wing Lafontaine
who could muster discipline on that level.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from a struggling coal-mining area near the French
border, Lafontaine had long been Schroeder's rival in seeking the
Social Democratic nomination for chancellor. But he played a
crucial role in organizing Schroeder's support among unions and
party traditionalists, and he had ambitions of becoming tantamount
to a vice chancellor in the new government.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine's departure gives Schroeder much more free rein. But
political experts said Schroeder faced brutal problems ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schroeder may have been the winner, but this was no victory,''
said Werner Patzelt, a political scientist at Dresden University of
Technology. ``I believe Schroeder is in a more difficult position
now than before. Schroeder has been the darling of the mass media,
and Lafontaine has been the darling of the Social Democratic Party.
But in Germany, politics is based on political parties.''
</P>
<P>
   An equally serious problem lies with the chancellor's coalition
partners in the Green Party. Even before Friday, the Greens had
capitulated on all their top priorities, from much higher fuel
taxes to much more rapid closing of nuclear plants, in order to be
part of a governing coalition. But rank-and-file members had
already become depressed and disillusioned, and many political
experts wondered Friday whether the Greens would be willing to
concede even more to industrial interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
