<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-PRIVACY13-COX     03-12 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-PRIVACY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet security isn't a dream
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Think somebody's watching you?
</P>
<P>
   You're not just being paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, despite its cryptic user names, anonymous e-mail
accounts and extensive use of passwords, is still very much a
wide-open prairie in which everything you do _ from Web browsing to
buying _ is subject to somebody else's prying eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When you are on the Web, you are vulnerable. If somebody sets
their mind to it, they can steal your credit card information,
usurp your identity or just monitor your frequent visits to
furby-fetish.com.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the technology that keeps snoops out of
your business and keeps your private information private is
improving, and within a few years, an infrastructure and set of
tools will be in place that will make it much harder to break into
a person's virtual life.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp.'s recent inclusion of security ID features on its
Pentium III and some Pentium II processors generated protests from
groups concerned about privacy. Intel says the feature is meant to
make electronic commerce more secure, but privacy advocates say the
chip allows Intel to monitor people's Internet use and habits _ a
violation of their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The protests show that privacy and security are big concerns to
both users and to companies as use of the Internet becomes more
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Thompson, an independent security analyst working in
Austin, says security that protects privacy and transactions is
better than a lot of people think. And it keeps getting better.
Thompson, who's advised IBM Corp. and Intel on security, says he's
optimistic that security enhancements will become invisible parts
of communication and transaction software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're pretty close,'' Thompson said. ``A lot of
security concerns are being addressed (by software makers) and
biometrics and voice recognition are going to revolutionize
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Biometric readers _ which would identify a user through
fingerprints, a retina scan or a facial scan _ would be many times
more secure than a password or PIN-code based transaction system.
</P>
<P>
   And voice-recognition passwords, which would identify a user by
the unique characteristics of their voice pattern, would also
tighten up security and could be simply implemented through a
microphone and the right software.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said these methods of identification will speed along
Internet commerce, allowing transactions of up to billions of
dollars at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Other privacy concerns _ unsolicited e-mail and unwanted
snooping of a user's information _ may also become things of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Software that filters unwanted e-mail is becoming increasingly
sophisticated as is security on basic Web browsing and online
buying.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, using a credit card on the Internet on a secured,
encrypted connection is one of the safest things you can do on the
Net. Giving a credit card number on the Net, Internet experts such
as Thompson say, is safer than giving up your credit card for
billing at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   If this all sounds a little too bright and trouble-free, it may
be. As home networking _ hooking up multiple computers through a
single high-speed Internet connection in the home _ grows, home
users will have to use some of the same security measures used by
large companies such as Dell Computer Corp. today.
</P>
<P>
   Firewalls, which allow information to come into a local network,
but block access from the outside, will have to be implemented if
home users want to keep their data private. But users will have
greater options about what content comes through their network
connection and what information they want to make available.
</P>
<P>
   As more of our daily lives _ the things we buy and the
information we use _ originate online, it'll be more important than
ever to guard our information vigilantly as the tools to do it
become available.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
