<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS FLORIDA UTILITY CAN'T BACK OUT OF MAINE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in New York has ruled that a Florida utility
can't renege on its $845 million deal to purchase Central Maine
Power Co.'s generating facilities, a decision that is expected to
lower the electric bills of Central Maine's customers by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   FPLEnergy Inc., a subsidiary of FPL Group Inc., which is both
Florida's largest utility and an investor in independent power
projects in other states, attempted to cancel the Central Maine
Power contract 10 months after it was signed in January 1998,
citing changes in federal regulatory policies for connecting new
power plants to the electric grid in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, US District Court Judge John Martin Jr.
rejected FPL's argument. His decision is expected to put Maine back
on track to launch statewide electricity deregulation next March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed in the court's ruling,'' said Michael
Yackira, president of FPL Energy. ``However, we accept the court's
decision and we will proceed accordingly.'' The acquisition is
scheduled to be completed April 7.
</P>
<P>
   FPL's lead attorney in the case was David Boies, the key lawyer
for the Justice Department in its ongoing antitrust case against
Microsoft Corp. Boies argued that revised regulatory rules for
connecting new electric generation facilities to the electric grid
in New England might be very costly and were unforeseen when the
Florida utility won a competitive bid.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, after two hours of oral arguments, ruled that the
contract FPL signed contained no guarantees on transmission
policies, and that FPL participated in the bidding with the full
knowledge that utility rules were changing.
</P>
<P>
   David T. Flanagan, president of Central Maine Power, called the
decision ``a victory for Maine consumers.'' Central Maine Power is
the state's largest electric utility with 530,000 customers in
central and southern Maine. The utility's case was strongly
supported with friend-of-the-court briefs from the Maine Public
Utilities Commission and the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities around New England, including New England Electric
System and BEC Energy Inc., the parent company of Boston Edison,
have sold their nonnuclear electric generating assets at
higher-than-expected prices. But the $845 million FPL offered for
Central Maine's four power plants and 27 hydroelectric stations was
well above the $550 million bid some industry observers expected.
</P>
<P>
   FPL was anxious to gain a foothold in New England as part of its
expansion plans to own and operate independent power plants. The
Florida utility's pursuit of Central Maine Power's generation
facilities followed an unsuccessful bid to acquire New England
Electric System's extensive fossil fuel and hydroelectric
facilities. FPL lost out to PG&AMP;E Corp., which bid $1.6 billion for
New England Electric's plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8632 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-     03-12 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET THE X-FACTOR TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is supposed to be nothing more than the Duke Invitational,
is it not?
</P>
<P>
   It's Duke this, and Duke that. Mike Krzyzewski's Blue Devils are
being compared to the greatest teams of recent times, and it's a
given that they will be in the Final Four. They are heading for a
coronation in St. Petersburg, Fla., while everyone else is simply
praying to get into the Final Four, where, God-willing, they will
have the honor of losing to Duke. The word ``invincible'' is even
being tossed around.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is good, real, real, real good. But it is not invincible,
and we've got a team right here in our torn-up town to prove it.
Duke is (itals)32 and 1(unitals), and the 1 was administered by the
University of Cincinnati Bearcats back on Nov. 28 in the finals of
the Great Alaska Shootout. Those would be the same Bearcats who
will be playing Temple in the second round of the tournament Sunday
at the Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game tells everyone else that we are capable of beating
anyone,'' argues Cincinnati senior Melvin Levett, who had 11 points
during his team's perfunctory dispatch of terrified George Mason
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Huggins also believes his team can beat anyone _ if.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat anyone if we make shots,'' explains the
controversial Cincinnati mentor. ``If we can make open shots, we
can beat anybody. We have good shooters on certain days.''
</P>
<P>
   There are even days when Cincinnati can win without making a
single outside shot, and this was one of them. The Colonial
Athletic Association champs were helpless against the combination
of Cincinnati's inside and transition prowess. The Bearcats had 25
field goals, and 17 of them came on layups or dunks.
</P>
<P>
   But George Mason was seeded 14th for a reason. One of these days
the Bearcats will have to demonstrate some outside shooting
proficiency against a very good team. Huggins would not like to bet
his weekly paycheck on that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, his reaction to a postgame inquiry as to
``what was wrong,'' when, over 10 minutes into the game, his
third-seeded squad was only ahead, 15-11. ``Sometimes that is our
game,'' he shrugged. ``Sometimes we have a hard time scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   This team adheres to the basics of what we have come to know as
a typical Huggins aggregation. Cincinnati is loaded with aggressive
athletes. There is no seeming end to the size, quickness, leaping
ability, and just plain on-court meanness of a team that knows
there are many folks out there who don't like them, and which
embraces the role of National Villain.
</P>
<P>
   To be blunt, Coach Hug ain't no Huggy Bear. He routinely
recruits kids who make people nervous. He works the Juco trail as
well as anyone, and there are still people around who are blatantly
hostile to those kids. He'll take a shaky transfer or two. He
seldom has a player graduate, and so he is viewed as the
anti-Christ by another set of breast-beaters. In case he hasn't
done anything else to aggravate people, he has now taken to wearing
black on black. Oh, and let's not forget that quasi-Fonz hairdo.
Just another reason to hate Coach Hug.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. He can, as Dicky V would say, flat-out coach.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his 10th year at Cincinnati, Bob Huggins is 246-80.
Overall, he is 415-153, and, at age 45, is on target to win
700-plus if he so chooses. He also wins with an identifiable style.
Year-in and year-out, no team routinely plays any harder in general
or is more ferocious on defense. He almost always has a fleet of
guys from 6 feet 5 inches to 6-9 who snack on glass while making
the other guys routinely enjoy the taste of leather.
</P>
<P>
   Once Cincinnati made a few mental adjustments, George Mason
simply had no chance in this game. The Patriots shot an execrable 5
for 31 in the first half, leading to a 41-17 state of affairs.
George Mason center George Evans, the CAA Player of the Year, went
for the ultra-bagel. He was 0 for 6 from the floor. ``We can really
guard the post,'' declares Huggins.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rebounding . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Their major strength is rebounding,'' said George Mason coach
Jim Larranaga, ``and they were able to flex their muscles against
us. They had 37 rebounds in the first half, and that's as many as
our opponents usually get in a game. We could not keep them off the
boards, and they knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cincinnati was good enough to beat Duke (77-75, on a
buzzer-beating hook-and-ladder long pass play leading to a Levett
dunk), why is it only a No. 3 seed? Is that your question?
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple answer. The Bearcats lost some games they had
no business losing. A February three-game losing streak tarnished
their image, but they were still in the running for a No. 1 seed
until they lost to North Carolina-Charlotte in the semifinals of
the Conference USA tournament. Let the record show that in their
five losses, Cincinnati shot a combined 40 percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   So we are back in the intellectual clutches of Coach Huggins,
who says no one needs an advanced course in Hoopology in order to
figure out the '98-99 Bearcats. ``We (itals)can(unitals) beat
anyone,'' he reminds us. ``In the 10 years I've been at Cincinnati,
this is one of the better half-court defensive teams I've had.
We've had better pressing teams, but not many as good in the
halfcourt. I know we're going to defend, and I know we're going to
rebound. What I don't know is if we're going to make shots.''
</P>
<P>
   They shot 57 percent at UNLV, and won by 13. They shot 58
percent at Louisville and beat them by 26. On that long ago night
in Anchorage, they shot 57 percent from the floor and the Duke Blue
Devils came tumbling down. Seeds be damned. This is the scariest
X-factor team in the entire tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
