<HEADLINE>
VINATIERI GETS $2 MILLION, 3-YEAR DEAL FROM PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In what has been a rather grim offseason,
the Patriots finally got some good news Friday when kicker Adam
Vinatieri, a restricted free agent, said he would return to the
team, agreeing to a three-year contract worth more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest goal was to remain with the Patriots,'' said
Vinatieri. ``When I hired my agent (Neil Cornrich) I told him that
was my first preference and Neil acted accordingly. I'm glad things
worked out. There might have been other opportunities to earn more
elsewhere, but I'm happy with my deal and happy to remain here.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri had been wooed by the Cleveland Browns, who made a
verbal offer of $2.5 million over three years. The New York Jets
also expressed interest but didn't make an offer, and the Browns
never raised their initial offer.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri said he wasn't bothered by the Patriots bringing in
veteran kicker Norm Johnson for a visit Thursday. ``I understood
the reasons they brought Norm in,'' he said. ``Obviously, they had
to have a backup plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri had a career-high 127 points last season, hitting 31
of 39 field goals for a 79 percent success rate. For his career,
Vinatieri is 83 for 103 (80.1 percent). He was voted AFC special
teams player of the week twice and special teams player of the
month in October.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri's one shortcoming, however, is kicking off. He had
only six touchbacks last season and will be pressed by new punter
Lee Johnson, signed as a free agent, for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to (new special teams coach) Brad Seely and I told him
I'd be in agreement with whatever is best for the team,'' said
Vinatieri. ``Lee and I will compete for it in training camp. Brad
didn't rule out the possibility of using both of us. I'd love to be
the kickoff guy again.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri said lengthening his kickoffs is his major goal in the
offseason. He plans to look at tapes he made with his former
kicking coach, Doug Blevins, who is now kicking coach with the
Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri said he's looking forward to working with Seely, who,
like Vinatieri, went to South Dakota State. ``I admire Brad
tremendously,'' said Vinatieri. ``(Former Patriots special teams
coach) Dante (Scarnecchia) spoke highly of him even last year. He's
definitely one of the best in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri said he will miss punter Tom Tupa, one of his best
friends, who departed for the Jets. ``He's a great friend and he
did an unbelievable job here,'' said Vinatieri. ``But I think Lee
will fill those shoes nicely. He's an experienced punter who should
add a lot to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
