<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SADLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADLER MAY FIT IN AT SECOND FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Could lightning strike twice for Donnie
Sadler? Don't bet against him being the Red Sox starter at second
base for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Sadler, 23, has performed so well this spring that
he has pulled away from the competition, which includes Jeff Frye
and Lou Merloni. And don't forget Jose Offerman, the much talked
about free agent signee who started 152 games for Kansas City, all
at second base, and had his finest year in the majors last season.
</P>
<P>
   But all things being equal, Sadler would seem to have as good a
chance as anyone. Frye, who missed all of last season with a knee
injury, has a pulled rib muscle and has missed all nine exhibition
games this spring. Merloni suffered a knee injury last June and
must prove he is ready. Offerman's role remains the great unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to play second?'' Williams said before Friday
night's game against the Phillies. ``Where does Sadler fit in with
us? I really can't say. We'll figure this out between now and the
end of spring training. But I'd love to see him out there. I really
would.''
</P>
<P>
   One area in which Sadler is way ahead of the pack is speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hitter can go out and learn to hit home runs,'' said
Williams. ``But you can't teach speed. Either you have it or not.
Sadler is invaluable because he can do so many things. He can run.
He has arm strength. He has a shortstop's arm. But there is no
substitute for speed. So far, we've exposed him to three different
positions. Second, third, and short. He's shown us that he's a
gamer with good skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler has been on the Red Sox horizon since 1996, his third
year in pro ball. He is a natural shortstop but with Nomar
Garciaparra around, there is no future at that position in Boston.
In 1996, Sadler was asked to play 28 games in center field at
Double A Trenton, where he hit .267. The following year at
Pawtucket, he took a step back, hitting just .212. He struck out
121 times in 121 games and seemingly lost his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But the confidence was restored in 1998. With Frye out of the
picture, the Sox signed free agent Mark Lemke just before the end
of spring training. But Lemke wasn't ready when the season opened,
so the Sox broke camp with Sadler as their starting second baseman.
After six games, however, he was sent to Pawtucket, where he still
hit only .221. Even so, his strikeouts were down and he was playing
with more confidence. In May, Lemke suffered a concussion and
Sadler was recalled. He played in 61 games, gaining valuable
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turned out, I got to play quite a bit last year,'' said
Sadler. ``I was surprised that (Williams) was still putting me in
there during the stretch in the wild-card race. Jimy showed a great
deal of confidence in me. The experience I got there helped me out
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``By being there, I was able to get an idea of what being in the
big leagues was all about. Coming into last year, I knew it was a
place that I wanted to be but I didn't have any experience. To be
out there with Mo, Valentin, Nomar was fun. So was playing against
guys like Ripken, Belle, Thomas, and the Alomars. It helped me a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he is confident Sadler, who hit .226 with Boston,
will come around at the plate. Sadler agrees that it's only a
matter of time and hard work. There are no short cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, I need to be more consistent at the plate and
put the ball on the ground and utilize my speed,'' said Sadler. ``I
have to get on base and score some runs ahead of the other guys.
Once I perfect that, I could project to be in the big leagues for
10 or 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, including Sadler, is expecting miracles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got here quick, but I still don't feel that they pushed
me,'' he said, ``But I don't feel I was ever overmatched. The bad
year I had at Pawtucket was my fault. I was trying to do too much.
I went out there pressing instead of trying to play my game. I was
thinking if I hit .300 or tried to do this or that by the All-Star
break, I had a chance to be called up to the big leagues. It didn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second or short, it doesn't matter. I'm starting to get
comfortable, but I'm still learning the position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
