<HEADLINE>
NEW GERMAN FINANCE MINISTER KNOWN AS CONCILIATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: With GERMANY-ECON) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Germany's former finance minister, Oskar
Lafontaine, was a blustery, bumptious political boss who managed to
provoke outrage among bankers and business leaders almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   The man chosen Friday to replace him, Hans Eichel, is almost a
complete opposite. Eichel, 57, is a low-key seeker of consensus who
has spent eight years leading a Social Democrat government in a
state that includes Frankfurt, the biggest banking and financial
center in Germany. Eichel is prime minister of Hesse. But he is now
a lame-duck, after his party was defeated by the center-right
Christian Democratic Union in state elections several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was apparently attracted to
Eichel's experience in financial issues and his experience in
working with conservative bankers, who wield great power in Hesse.
Though far less known and far less charismatic than Lafontaine,
Eichel has won praise for his quiet ability to get things done _
valuable qualities in the wake of Lafontaine, a man that the
British tabloid The Sun has denounced as ``the most dangerous man
in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichel was born in the town of Kassel, 90 miles northeast of
Frankfurt. He joined the Social Democratic party at age 23, while
he was studying philosophy and history. He campaigned against
nuclear proliferation and for environmental causes, and became
mayor of Kassel in 1975 at age 33.
</P>
<P>
   His politics have moderated since then. Eichel was considered a
business ally during the years he governed Hesse state, which has
the highest per-capita gross domestic product in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel lost the post in February when Christian Democrats won a
state election by capitalizing on concerns over the federal
government's plans to grant some foreigners double citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Although his position on Lafontaine's tax reform is unknown,
Eichel in practice promoted only minor changes in taxation.
</P>
<P>
   As finance minister, Eichel is unlikely to pose any policy
challenges to Schroeder or to pressure the European Central Bank to
lower interest rates, as his predecessor did. As the governor of
Hesse, he already has a working relationship with Wim Duisenberg,
the president of the European Central Bank, who was one of the
first to congratulate Schroeder on the choice of Eichel as finance
minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
