<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REBELS BACK PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Kosovo Liberation Army leaders decided
Friday to accept a European-sponsored peace plan and directed the
leader of the ethnic Albanian delegation to sign the accord ahead
of peace talks that are planned to resume on Monday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in a village deep in rebel-controlled mountains in
central Kosovo, the guerrilla commanders and leaders of the
political directorate gathered to discuss the plan, which would
give ethnic Albanians self-rule and deploy NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the head of the delegation, Hashim Thaci,
confirmed that he had received approval to sign the pact, a source
close to the delegation said. Other members of the team have
expressed support for the plan. But it had not been clear how the
rebels would act.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci is expected to sign the pact over the weekend. The
delegation is scheduled to fly from Pristina to Paris on Saturday,
although Serbian arrest warrants issued last week for three
delegation members, including Thaci, could pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci, 31, a former commander, slipped back into Kosovo three
days ago to be present at the meeting. Western mediators have been
pushing the rebels to accept the accord. But despite promises to do
so, they kept delaying the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the rebels said Thaci had a difficult time
convincing some hard-line commanders, who would have to accept
disarmament and forgo their aim of full independence.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia said he
firmly opposed foreign troops in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
