<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MENUHIN-3TAKES-N     03-12 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MENUHIN-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEHUDI MENUHIN, VIOLINIST AND CONDUCTOR, DIES AT 82 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds. Discography appears at end of obituary. Ysaye and Furtwangler
require an umlaut over the a. An abridged version of this obituary
also is being filed.) (DW) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yehudi Menuhin, the legendary violinist who came to prominence
in his childhood as a virtuoso in velvet knee-pants and later
became a respected conductor, organizer of festivals and schools
and an idealistic supporter of hundreds of charities, died Friday
at Martin Luther Hospital in Berlin. He was 82 and lived in London.
</P>
<P>
   When Menuhin was at his best, his playing had a grandeur and
personal intensity that made his sound instantly recognizable, both
in the concert hall and on disk. He recorded prolifically,
beginning in 1928 when he was 12 and even after he stopped playing
the violin publicly, in the early 1990s, he continued to perform
and make recordings as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Though an American by birth, Menuhin lived in Europe for most of
his life. He described himself as an internationalist, and in the
1950s, he contended that peace would be achieved only under a
single benign world government. After he accepted honorary Swiss
citizenship in 1970, tendered because of his services in founding
the Gstaad Festival, the State Department threatened to revoke his
American citizenship, but later relented. In 1985, Menuhin became a
British subject. He had been given an honorary knighthood by
Britain 19 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and visions of a utopian future often seemed to be as
much on Menuhin's mind as music-making. A devotee of yoga and
health food, he regularly warned against the dangers of white rice,
white bread, refined sugar and red meat, and advocated
vegetarianism. He spoke about the dangers of pollution long before
ecology was a chic topic of discussion. He championed inventions of
all sorts, including electric cars. He put forward his own notions
of city planning, including a vision of New York City with all
traffic moving underground.
</P>
<P>
   Musically too, his interests ranged widely. He performed and
recorded most of the standard classical repertory, and he gave the
premiere performances of Bartok's Unaccompanied Sonata, Bloch's
Suites 1 and 2, Walton's Violin Sonata and pieces by Georges
Enesco, Vaughan Williams, Lennox Berkeley and Paul Ben-Haim.
</P>
<P>
   He also recorded jazz albums with Stephane Grappelli, and, as an
early and eloquent Western advocate of Eastern music, he made a
series of ``East Meets West'' recordings with Indian musicians,
including Ravi Shankar, the sitarist, and Ali Akbar Khan, the sarod
virtuoso.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in his career, personal and technical crises
forced Menuhin to stop playing. But as a child violinist in the
1920s Menuhin stunned listeners with his pure tone, virtuosic
technique and interpretive insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem ridiculous to say that he showed a mature
conception of Beethoven's concerto, but that is the fact,'' Olin
Downes wrote in The New York Times in November 1927, when Menuhin,
at age 11, made his first New York appearance as an orchestral
soloist, at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   By then, young Menuhin was famous. In 1924, when he was 8, he
played Beriot's ``Scene de Ballet'' with the San Francisco Symphony
Orchestra. The next year, he was the subject of a silent-screen
newsreel that showed him alternately playing the violin and riding
on a swing.
</P>
<P>
   Yehudi Menuhin was born in New York on April 22, 1916. His
parents, Moshe and Marutha, were Russian-Jewish immigrants who had
met in Palestine in 1909, and married in New York in 1914. They
named their son Yehudi, which means ``Jew,'' after a landlord
showing them an apartment told them that a benefit of living in the
building was that there were no Jews in residence there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, the Menuhins moved to San Francisco, where Moshe
Menuhin, after a brief and unsuccessful attempt to run a farm near
Oakland, Calif., supported his family by teaching Hebrew. Menuhin
asked for a violin when he was 3, and was taken to Sigmund Anker, a
teacher who specialized in very young players. Four years later he
became a student of Louis Persinger, a renowned teacher and chamber
player.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's parents were wary of the prodigy syndrome, in which
musicians who were hailed as geniuses during childhood proved
unable to sustain the originality of their early performances into
adulthood. They limited their son's public appearances, and they
insisted that he and his two younger sisters _ Hephzibah and
Yaltah, both pianists _ undertake a rigorous course of home study.
Their father taught them math, history and Hebrew; their mother was
their French, German, Italian and Spanish tutor.
</P>
<P>
   During the Menuhins' visit to Europe in 1927, Menuhin played for
the great Belgian violinist Eugene Ysaye, who was astonished to
discover the extent to which Menuhin's technique was intuitive.
Although he could play difficult works like Lalo's ``Symphonie
Espagnole,'' he had bypassed the traditional technical exercises
and studies. When Ysaye asked him to play a three-octave arpeggio,
Menuhin didn't understand the request.
</P>
<P>
   On the same trip, Menuhin played for the violinist and composer
Georges Enescu, with whom he studied informally, both in Paris and
at Enescu's home in Romania. Menuhin also studied with Adolph
Busch.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin made debuts in Berlin in 1928 and London in 1929, and
soon began making recordings as well. His 1932 recording of the
Elgar Violin Concerto, with the composer conducting, remains a
classic. The same year, he made the first of many recordings with
his sister Hephzibah.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played almost automatically, as if we were one person,'' he
told The New York Times soon after her death in 1981. After several
years in Europe, the Menuhins moved back to California in 1934 and
had a family compound built in Los Gatos. Two years later, at age
19 and with more than a decade of concert experience behind him,
Menuhin experienced his first crisis of confidence. Canceling all
his concerts and withdrawing to his home in Los Gatos, the young
virtuoso came to terms with the fact that his early training had
been deficient.
</P>
<P>
   But technique may not have been his only problem. Robert
Magidoff, in ``Yehudi Menuhin: The Story of the Man and the
Musician,'' a biography written with Menuhin's cooperation and
published in 1955, said Menuhin's problems were psychological, and
could be traced to the overprotectiveness of his parents,
particularly his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Palmer, in a 1991 biography and television documentary,
``Menuhin: A Family Portrait,'' made a similar point, using
interviews with Menuhin's sister, Yaltah, and his children, to make
his case. They maintained that when Menuhin married Nola Ruby
Nichols in 1938, Marutha Menuhin wrote letters to her
daughter-in-law instructing her on everything from what to feed
Menuhin to when to abstain from sex.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's first marriage produced a daughter, Zamira, and a son,
Krov, and ended in divorce nine years later. In 1947, Menuhin
married Diana Gould, a dancer who had worked with George
Balanchine. They had two children, Jeremy, who became a concert
pianist and often performed with his father on the podium, and
Gerard. His wife and children survive him, along with a sister,
Yaltah, and four grandhildren.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By then, Menuhin had come through a second crisis, caused by the
tensions in his marriage and by the devastation he saw in Europe
during World War II, when he gave more than 500 concerts for U.S.
and Allied troops, often in combat zones. After the war, he
performed in displaced persons camps (sometimes with the composer
Benjamin Britten as his accompanist) and visited concentration
camps soon after their liberation. He continued touring in Europe
until 1948, but when he returned to the United States, critics
began to note that his playing had lost some of its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin soon found himself embroiled in political problems as
well. Jewish groups denounced him for performing with Wilhelm
Furtwangler and the Berlin Philharmonic soon after the war, because
Furtwangler had remained in Germany and prospered during the war.
When a Jewish relief organization in Berlin boycotted one of his
concerts, soon after his appearance with Furtwangler, Menuhin
called a meeting to argue that Furtwangler had never joined the
Nazi party and had helped Jewish musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to bind the wounds,'' he said, adding that ``love,
and not hate, will heal the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He supported Furtwangler again in 1949, when the Chicago
Symphony Orchestra was considering hiring Furtwangler as its music
director. A group of illustrious musicians _ among them, Isaac
Stern, Nathan Milstein, Arthur Rubinstein, Vladimir Horowitz and
Lily Pons _ said that in that case they would never play there
again.
</P>
<P>
   Furtwangler eventually withdrew his candidacy, but Menuhin's
support of him drew fire from Jewish communities all over the
world, including Israel, where there was a bomb threat at one of
his concerts in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   He played countless benefits for Israel and its charities during
its early years and after the 1967 war with the Arabs, even though
his father had become a strident anti-Zionist in the 1930s and
refused to attend his son's concerts in support of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, just as he played benefit concerts for Israeli
organizations, he also played concerts to benefit Arab refugees. He
found himself under attack in 1975, when Leonard Bernstein and 100
musicians and dancers asked him to join a boycott of cultural
activities connected with the U.N. Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization, which had refused to admit Israel as a
member. Menuhin, who at the time was president of the
organization's International Music Council, responded that he
considered boycotts cowardly, and that he agreed with UNESCO's
criticism of Israel's archeological digs in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's personal life and musical career took new turns in the
1950s. On a trip to New Zealand, in 1951, he became fascinated by a
book on yoga he found in a doctor's waiting room, and began a daily
regimen that included 15 or 20 minutes of standing on his head.
When he visited India in 1952, he was introduced to B.K.S. Iyengar,
who became his guru. He also persuaded executives at Angel Records,
EMI's classical label, to make recordings with Indian musicians
like Shankar and Khan.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin began his association with a string of festivals around
this time. He founded the Gstaad Festival in Switzerland, in 1956,
and he was appointed music director of the Bath Festival in
England, two years later. At Gstaad, he established a chamber
orchestra, where he made his first recordings as a conductor, among
them a notable set of Bach's ``Brandenburg'' Concertos and a
traversal of the Schubert symphonies.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin actually made his conducting debut more than a decade
earlier, with the Dallas Symphony in 1942; but it was at Gstaad and
Bath that he began his conducting career in earnest. At Bath he
conducted opera for the first time, and it was in a dispute about
opera _ the board considered it too costly, Menuhin considered it
essential _ that Menuhin resigned in 1968. He took over the Windsor
Festival the following year.
</P>
<P>
   He also increasingly became interested in musical pedagogy. In
1963, he established the Yehudi Menuhin School for music students
beginning at 6, at Stoke d'Abernon, in England. Two of his books _
``The Violin: Six Lessons With Yehudi Menuhin'' (1971), and ``The
Compleat Violinist'' (1986) _ were meant for student violinists. He
was appointed president of Trinity College of Music in London in
1971, and in 1977 he founded the Menuhin Academy at Gstaad.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin started several musical outreach programs, including
Live Music Now, which began offering concerts in hospitals and
prisons in 1974 and was sponsoring more than 2,000 events a year by
the mid-1990s, and Mus-E, which was started in 1994 to bring music
educational concerts to primary schools in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the organizations that he started or was actively
involved with, he lent his name, as a sponsor, patron or board
member, to hundreds of cultural and charitable organizations. A
list of his involvements, compiled in the late 1980s, ran to six
single-spaced pages. Included among the predictable _ festivals,
music schools, associations devoted to specific composers _ were
organizations as varied as the African Music and Drama Trust,
Friends of Animals and the Good Gardeners' Association, all in
England; the North Africa Ashram in Tangier, and the Catgut
Acoustical Society and the Grenville Clark Institute for World Law,
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s, Menuhin was conducting regularly, and by the
1980s he had led most of the world's great orchestras and had
recorded with many of them. In 1985 he undertook his first American
tour solely as a conductor, with the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra.
But except for a sabbatical in 1976, when he was 60, he continued
to tour and make recordings as a violinist. Although critics noted
his technical flaws in these years, they also found a
communicativeness and devotion in his playing.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, he stopped playing the violin in public and
concentrated on conducting. Although he concentrated mostly on the
standard orchestral repertory, he could surprise listeners with his
adventurousness. As part of his 80th-birthday celebration in 1996,
for example, he conducted the Orchestra of St. Luke's at the
Lincoln Center Festival in a program of 14 new works composed in
his honor. The composers were a strikingly diverse group, among
them Lukas Foss, Karel Husa, Philip Glass, Steve Reich, Somei
Satoh, David Del Tredici, Guya Kancheli and John Tavener.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his books on violin playing, Menuhin published two
volumes of memoirs, ``Theme and Variations'' (1972) and
``Unfinished Journey'' (1977). Another volume, ``The Music of
Man,'' which he co-wrote with Curtis W. Davis (1979) was based on a
television series in which Menuhin visited 27 countries and
examined music from ancient times to punk rock.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his British Knighthood, he was made a commander of the
Legion of Honor and of the Ordre des Arts and Lettres, by France, a
knight commander of the Order of Merit, by Germany and a knight
commander of the Royal Order of the Phoenix, by Greece. He also
received the Order of Leopold and the Ordre de la Couronne, from
Belgium, the Kennedy Center Honors, from the United States, and the
Handel Medallion, New York City's cultural award.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed. Yehudi Menuhin kept up his enthusiasms, his
aura of innocence and his often complicated visionary way of
engaging the world to such an extent that, as Donal Henahan wrote
in a profile of Menuhin for The New York Times, ``One still seems
to discern, under the mask of the graying adult, the child wonder
who made his New York recital debut at age 10 ... and to whom
Einstein himself, a fiddler of famously modest talent, once said:
`Today you have again proved to me that there is a God in
heaven.'''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL DISCOGRAPHY FOLLOWS. STORY ENDS HERE.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   SELECTED DISCOGRAPHY
</P>
