<SLUG> BC-CATERPILLAR-OUTLOOK-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CATERPILLAR PREDICTS 1st-QUARTER PROFITS BELOW EXPECTATIONS  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. _ Citing a sales slowdown in Latin America and
stiff competition in North America, Caterpillar Inc., the world's
largest maker of construction and earth-moving equipment, on Friday
warned that its first-quarter profits would be far below
expectations. The news caused the company's stock to tumble 12.2
percent, pulling down the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   The warning was just the latest in a series of blows to
Caterpillar, which has been suffering through a gradual decline in
sales and profits over the last year, largely because of the global
economic crisis that began in Asia in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Caterpillar fell $6.1875, or 12.2 percent, on the New
York Stock Exchange on Friday, to $44.6875. The stock was the
biggest decline among the 30 stocks in the industrial average,
which finished the day with a decline of 21.09 points, or 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release issued Friday morning, the company said it
expected earnings per share to decline by as much as 50 percent
from the same quarter a year ago, well below the estimates of Wall
Street analysts. Business is expected to strengthen in the second
half of the year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts are projecting an earnings-per-share decline of
10 to 15 percent in 1999, and Caterpillar officials say they are
comfortable with those estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar said it would temporarily idle plants here and
abroad in the coming months and cut back on administrative costs
and on research and development. Reductions in the work force are
also being considered.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's North American business is suffering from
stiff competition and pricing pressure, most of its problems are
related to recessionary forces in Asia and Latin America. And that
has many analysts worried that the same forces could spread to the
United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We knew that Asia was quite depressed, and now Latin America
is sinking like a stone and Europe is flattish,'' Robert McCarthy,
an analyst at ABN Amro in Chicago, said. ``This means they are very
vulnerable to any slowdown in North America.''
</P>
<P>
   While sales of construction and earth-moving equipment remain
strong in the United States, sales of agricultural and mining
equipment are slumping because of weakness in those sectors. Sales
of engines and solar turbines are also depressed, Caterpillar said,
which could force temporary plant shutdowns in Europe and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Latin America accounted for about 9 percent of
Caterpillar's sales. The company said its sales in Brazil were
particularly bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said before that Brazil and Latin America were going to be
in recession, and that's definitely the case,'' said Marsha
Hausser, a spokeswoman for Caterpillar. ``But we're anticipating
that the second half is going to be better than the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, analysts say, is that Caterpillar and other
companies have introduced a broad mix of new agricultural tractors,
but the agricultural sector _ even in the United States _ is in a
slump because of plummeting commodity prices. Those tractors are
being aggressively priced, and as a result profit margins are
shrinking throughout the industry, particularly at companies like
Case Corp., which is based in Racine, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   For Caterpillar, one of the companies that make up the Dow Jones
industrial average, the economy in the United States has been
strong enough to offset some losses in other markets. But the
construction industry here has not been strong enough to bring
healthy profits to a global company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said Friday's announcement was not very
surprising, but it did force some of them to trim back their
expectations for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This pretty well cements the fact that this will be the second
down year for Caterpillar, even though North America remains
strong,'' McCarthy of ABN Amro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
