<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIRAMAX-OSCARS-LADN     03-12 1535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRAMAX-OSCARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIO LEADS INDEPENDENTS' GOLDEN GRAB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Sunday, March 14 by NYTimes News Service) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Next Sunday, if the Hollywood soothsayers are
correct, Miramax Films may well lose another big battle to Steven
Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   But 20-year-old Miramax, a onetime low-budget art-house upstart
turned Hollywood juggernaut, gradually seems to be winning the war
for the hearts and minds of Oscar voters.
</P>
<P>
   With a total of 23 nominations this year, including best-picture
nods for ``Life Is Beautiful'' and ``Shakespeare in Love,''
Disney-owned Miramax is leading the Oscar field for the second time
in the last three years. In 1996, the company scored 20
nominations, winning for best picture (``The English Patient''),
best director and in several other major categories.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Spielberg's World War II
epic, remains the odds-on favorite to cart home the best-picture
prize this year, Miramax co-chairman and brothers Harvey and Bob
Weinstein have waged an expensive, aggressive bicoastal ad campaign
to boost their films' chances, particularly those of ``Shakespeare
in Love,'' whose 13 nominations are the most for any film this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The current campaign echoes 1994, when Miramax's ``The Piano''
was duking it out for best picture with another Spielberg project,
``Schindler's List,'' the eventual winner.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, independent film companies, with Miramax
at the forefront, have steadily been gaining ground on the major
studios as the unofficial arbiters of Oscar taste. That trend seems
likely to continue, whatever happens March 21 at the Dorothy
Chandler Pavilion, where the 71st annual Academy Awards will be
held.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rice, president of marketing for October Films, which
received two nominations this year for the feature film ``Hilary
and Jackie'' and one for the documentary ``The Last Days,'' says
the Weinsteins' Oscar success has helped other independents make
inroads in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they're big, I think their heart and soul,
certainly with the Miramax label, will always be independent,''
Rice says. ``It doesn't hurt to have a well-capitalized company
that can provide you with a marketing war chest, like they have
now, to raise the consciousness of the public and of the academy
members to the kinds of pictures that they make and the kinds of
pictures that we make.''
</P>
<P>
   What this success bodes for the future of independent film is a
more complex question. A central issue is whether Miramax, whose
high-end movies such as ``Shakespeare in Love'' now cost tens of
millions of dollars, still can be called an ``independent'' film
company in any meaningful sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess independent conveys a certain sort of edginess and a
certain subversiveness and a certain challenge to mainstream cinema
or mainstream ideas, a certain toughness, or a film that takes
risks,'' says critic Peter Biskind, author of ``Easy Riders and
Raging Bulls,'' a study of Hollywood filmmaking in the 1960s and
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these are all cliches, but taken altogether, I think
that, for me, to some extent, is what I expect from an independent.
And I don't think you can say anything like that about `Shakespeare
in Love.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hoberman, chief film critic of the Village Voice, says he
``doesn't really regard'' Miramax as an independent company, as he
did when it was distributing such movies as ``The Crying Game''
(1992) and Errol Morris' controversial documentary ``The Thin Blue
Line'' (1988), which resulted in a Texas Death Row inmate being set
free.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gill, president of Miramax L.A., says he agrees that
``Shakespeare in Love'' is not a cutting-edge film. But he points
out that Miramax continues to release many films every year made
for $3 million or less that deal with controversial subjects, in
languages and styles as far removed from the mainstream Hollywood
vernacular as Farsi.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Life Is Beautiful,'' which stars director Roberto
Benigni as a father attempting to shield his son from the horrors
of a Nazi death camp, Gill says, ``If you know a (riskier) film
last year, I'd like to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you, we are in no way shaping Oscar's tastes,''
Gill says. ``We are making more of the kind of movies that Oscar
voters like, so if you want to use the baseball analogy, we're up
to bat more often.''
</P>
<P>
   Piers Handling, director of the Toronto International Film
Festival Group, believes that both ``Life Is Beautiful'' and
``Shakespeare'' were ``more adventurous than your standard studio
(fare) in terms of the subject matter'' and ``the risks they
took.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miramax is a very interesting company because it still has a
very broad mandate, and I still think that Harvey (Weinstein) is
trying to fight the good fight in terms of an art cinema, an
art-house cinema,'' Handling says. ``But he's involved now with
films that are grossing $100 million a year, which takes the energy
of that company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at `Good Will Hunting,' which is far less
experimental than some of Gus's (director Gus Van Sant's) early
work,'' Handling continues. ``At the same token, you look at
`Jackie Brown,' which is a pretty adventuresome commercial film,
which didn't quite succeed, and I really have great respect for
(Miramax) financing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, Miramax has had a number of breakout
movies, including ``sex, lies, and videotape'' (1989), ``The Crying
Game'' (1992), ``The Piano'' (1993) and ``Pulp Fiction'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until 1996, when ``The English Patient'' won the
Oscar for best picture and only one of the other four nominees
(``Jerry Maguire'') was distributed by a major studio (TriStar),
that newspapers and entertainment publications proclaimed the
``Year of the Independents.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Miramax's Harvey Weinstein demurred that the
success of the independents was only ``the luck of the draw,'' and
that the studios might well be back on top in 1997 _ as they were,
to an extent, with James Cameron's ``Titanic'' blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ``year of the independents'' tag was questionable to
begin with, given that many independents are now owned by major
studios, such as Fine Line (Time Warner).
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that in that `year of the independent,' the four
nominated films were so disparate that they reflected nothing,
other than corporate bylaws,'' says Mark Urman, co-president of
Lions Gate Films Releasing in New York, whose ``Gods and Monsters''
and ``Affliction'' received a combined five nominations this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hollywood observers say that the major studios no longer
particularly care about winning Oscars the way they did 30 or 40
years ago. Miramax and smaller independents, some say, have been
able to fill a void created when the majors stopped making as many
prestige pictures and turned their attention more to adolescent and
action fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The broad overview is, the studios are largely out of the
Oscar game,'' says one veteran industry observer who requested
anonymity. ``They're in it to oversee those special films that come
along once in a while, a la `Titanic' or `Braveheart,' that are
tied to a major filmmaking talent that they're in business with.
That's why they're in that business at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Vogel, a veteran New York media analyst, believes the
majors ``do care, sure, on a studio level'' about winning Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you'd have to say that, in the greater scheme of things,
it means less and less from an investor standpoint, because these
companies are so huge,'' Vogel says. ``Look, Time Warner gets over
40 percent (of its revenues) from cable. So it's more important
what happens with AT&AMP;T and Time Warner cable than what happens if
one film wins a second award on Oscar (night). It really doesn't
have that much of an impact on the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   What exactly makes a film ``independent'' has become
increasingly hard to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Gilmore, director of programming for the Sundance
Festival, says that expensive movies with fairly big-name casts,
such as ``Shakespeare in Love,'' represent one end of an
independent spectrum that has been and will continue to be highly
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not simply a question of the amount of money involved in
a picture, or it's not simply a question of where that money comes
from, but it's really a complex of issues, and it's very hard to
define,'' Gilmore says.
</P>
<P>
   Lions Gate's Urman says that a number of so-called ``small
films'' _ ``and not just via Miramax'' _ have begun to go far at
Oscar time. That, he believes, will create more opportunities for
independents next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly you have a very large population exposed to a film in
which the female lead has a penis (`The Crying Game'), or exposed
to a film in which an Australian pianist experiences some sort of
redemption (`Shine') and on and on and on,'' Urman says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, whenever a film does 10 times what a successful
independent film should do, it increases the possibilities for all
of the films. And it creates, as we all must be concerned with, an
audience that is more receptive to trying it again.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
