u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MENUHIN-SHORTVER     03-12 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MENUHIN-SHORTVERSION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEHUDI MENUHIN, VIOLINIST AND CONDUCTOR, DIES AT 82 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: An umlaut is required over the a in Ysaye and Furtwangler. An
unabridged version of this obituary also is being sent.) (ART ADV:
A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yehudi Menuhin, the legendary violinist who came to prominence
in his childhood as a virtuoso in velvet knee-pants and later
became a respected conductor, an organizer of festivals and schools
and an idealistic supporter of hundreds of charities and causes,
died Friday at Martin Luther Hospital in Berlin. He was 82 and
lived in London.
</P>
<P>
   When Menuhin was at his best, his playing had a grandeur and
intensity that made his sound instantly recognizable, both in the
concert hall and on disk. He recorded prolifically, beginning in
1928 when he was 12, and even after he stopped playing the violin
publicly, in the early 1990s, he continued to perform and make
recordings as a conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Though an American by birth, Menuhin lived in Europe for most of
his life. He described himself as an internationalist, and in the
1950s he contended that peace would be achieved only under a single
benign world government. After he accepted honorary Swiss
citizenship in 1970, tendered because of his services in founding
the Gstaad Festival, the State Department threatened to revoke his
American citizenship, but later relented. In 1985, Menuhin became a
British subject. He had been given an honorary knighthood by
Britain 19 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and visions of a utopian future often seemed to be as
much on Mr. Menuhin's mind as music-making. A devotee of yoga and
health food, he warned against the dangers of white rice, white
bread, refined sugar and red meat, and advocated vegetarianism. He
spoke about the dangers of pollution long before ecology was a chic
topic. He put forward his own notions of city planning, including a
vision of New York City in which all traffic moved underground.
</P>
<P>
   Musically too, his interests ranged widely. He performed and
recorded most of the standard classical repertory, including the
major contemporary works, and he gave the premiere performances of
Bartok's Unaccompanied Sonata, Bloch's Suites 1 and 2, Walton's
Violin Sonata and pieces by Georges Enesco, Vaughan Williams,
Lennox Berkeley and Paul Ben-Haim.
</P>
<P>
   He also recorded jazz albums with Stephane Grappelli and as an
early and eloquent advocate of Eastern music, he made a series of
``East Meets West'' recordings with Indian musicians, including
Ravi Shankar, the sitarist.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in his career, personal and technical crises
forced Menuhin to stop playing. But as a child violinist in the
1920s _ a time when Fritz Kreisler, Mischa Elman and Jascha Heifetz
were the instrument's reigning elite _ Menuhin stunned listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may seem ridiculous to say that he showed a mature
conception of Beethoven's concerto, but that is the fact,'' Olin
Downes wrote in The New York Times in November 1927, when Menuhin,
at age 11, made his first New York appearance as an orchestral
soloist, at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Yehudi Menuhin was born in New York on April 22, 1916. His
parents, Moshe and Marutha, were Russian-Jewish immigrants who had
met in Palestine in 1909, and married in New York in 1914. They
named their son Yehudi, which means ``Jew,'' after a landlord
showing them an apartment told them that a benefit of living in the
building was that there were no Jews in residence there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, the Menuhins moved to San Francisco, where Moshe
Menuhin, after an unsuccessful attempt at running a farm near
Oakland, supported his family by teaching Hebrew. Menuhin asked for
a violin when he was 3, and was taken to Sigmund Anker, a teacher
who specialized in very young players. Menuhin's parents insisted
that he and his two younger sisters _ Hephzibah and Yaltah, both
pianists _ undertake a rigorous course of home study. Their father
taught them math, history and Hebrew; their mother was their
French, German, Italian and Spanish tutor.
</P>
<P>
   During the Menuhins' visit to Europe in 1927, Menuhin played for
the great Belgian violinist Eugene Ysaye, who was astonished to
discover the extent to which Menuhin's technique was intuitive.
Although he could play difficult works like Lalo's ``Symphonie
Espagnole,'' when Ysaye asked him to play a three-octave arpeggio,
Menuhin didn't understand the request.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin made debuts in Berlin in 1928 and London in 1929, and
soon began making recordings. His 1932 recording of the Elgar
Violin Concerto, with the composer conducting, remains a classic.
That same year, he made the first of many recordings with his
sister Hephzibah.
</P>
<P>
   After several years in Europe, the Menuhins moved back to
California in 1934, and had a family compound built in Los Gatos.
Two years later, at age 19, Menuhin experienced his first crisis of
confidence. Canceling all his concerts, the young virtuoso came to
terms with the fact that his early training had been deficient.
</P>
<P>
   But technique may not have been his only problem. Robert
Magidoff, in ``Yehudi Menuhin: The Story of the Man and the
Musician,'' a biography written with Menuhin's cooperation and
published in 1955, said Menuhin's problems were psychological and
could be traced to the overprotectiveness of his parents,
particularly his mother. Tony Palmer, in a 1991 biography and
television documentary, ``Menuhin: A Family Portrait,'' made a
similar point, using interviews with Menuhin's sister, Yaltah, and
his children, to make his case. They maintained that when Menuhin
married Nola Ruby Nichols Marutha Menuhin wrote letters to her
daughter-in-law instructing her on everything from what to feed
Menuhin to when to abstain from sex.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's first marriage produced a daughter, Zamira, and a son,
Krov, and ended in divorce nine years later. In 1947, Menuhin
married Diana Gould, a dancer. They had two children, Jeremy, who
became a concert pianist and often performed with his father, and
Gerard. His wife and children survive him, along with a sister,
Yaltah, and four grandhildren.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he performed in displaced persons camps and
visited concentration camps soon after their liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish groups denounced him for performing with Wilhelm
Furtwangler and the Berlin Philharmonic soon after the war, because
Furtwangler had remained in Germany and prospered during the war.
He supported Furtwangler again in 1949, when the Chicago Symphony
Orchestra was considering hiring Furtwangler as its music director.
</P>
<P>
   Furtwangler withdrew his candidacy, but Menuhin's support of him
drew fire from Jewish communities, including Israel, where there
was a bomb threat at one of his concerts in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   He played countless benefits for Israel and its charities and he
also played concerts to benefit Arab refugees. As the years passed.
Yehudi Menuhin kept up his enthusiasms, his aura of innocence and
his visionary way of engaging the world to such an extent that, as
Donal Henahan wrote in a profile of Menuhin for The New York Times,
``One still seems to discern, under the mask of the graying adult,
the child wonder who made his New York recital debut at age 10 ...
and to whom Einstein himself, a fiddler of famously modest talent,
once said: `Today you have again proved to me that there is a God
in heaven.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
