<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAR FROM PERFECT' CLINTON GOES HOME TO A PLACE CALLED HOPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPE, Ark. _ On a chill, wet late-winter afternoon, President
Clinton told adoring home folks Friday that he was ``far from
perfect'' but determined to complete the complex personal journey
he began in this small town 52 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the newly restored house where he lived from
birth to age 4, Clinton told an audience of several hundred that he
learned in Hope, a county seat about 30 miles northeast of the
Texas border, the lesson of taking the good with the bad.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that some years ago he was seeking to comfort
a great uncle, whose wife had Alzheimer's disease. ``This is really
hard,'' Clinton recalled telling the relative, who replied: ``Yeah,
it is. But I signed on for the whole load _ and most of it's been
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I learned _ to sign on for the whole load,''
Clinton said, without mentioning the personal and political trials
that have marked his more than six years in the White House.
``Though far from perfect, I have tried to do just that for my
family and my friends, for our beloved state and nation. If I had
not learned that lesson here ... we wouldn't be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came as he dedicated, and toured for the
first time in more than 40 years, his childhood home. It has been
refurbished by a private foundation and was opened to the public
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton clearly relished the nostalgic interlude and
full-throated praise from supporters after a year of scandal that
led to his impeachment by the House and acquittal in the Senate.
The impeachment resulted from his attempts to cover up a sexual
affair with White House intern, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The visit also came during what increasingly appears to be a new
rough patch in his marriage to Hillary Rodham Clinton. The first
lady, who had skipped her husband's trip earlier in the week to
Central America, did not accompany him on the sentimental journey
to Hope. The first lady's staff said she remained at the White
House with back trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Arkansas, Clinton's staff announced he would
not, as previously planned, stay overnight Saturday in Little Rock
at the home of his mother-in-law, Dorothy Rodham. Clinton instead
will return to Washington after two Democratic fund-raising events
in the state capital. Aides said Clinton decided to return to
Washington because he is tired after his four-day international
trip.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides have refused to respond directly to reports of
trouble in the White House family quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In their public comments, Hope residents were dismissive of
scandal talk about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for Bill, regardless,'' said Carlene Feild Barron, who now
lives in Nacogdoches, Texas, but maintains her house behind the
Clinton childhood home. She remembers the president as a precocious
toddler who by age 3 or 4 was pointing out words in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded in kind, telling the crowd: ``Thank you for
being there for me through this whole wonderful ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope residents have come to treasure Clinton's references to his
boyhood hometown and the president closed his speech with a line he
used in the 1992 campaign, a line the crowd clearly wanted to hear:
``I still believe in a place called Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But even among the faithful there was private acknowledgment of
longstanding reports of Clinton's womanizing during his political
career in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew he had a problem,'' said a longtime political
activist who has known Clinton since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke about nothing quite so heavy. He referred jokingly
to breaking his leg at Miss Mary Perkins' kindergarten, ``in the
first of many major mistakes I was to make in my life, jumping rope
in my cowboy boots.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a covered podium, Clinton reminisced about the white
clapboard house with freshly painted green trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this house, I learned to walk and talk,'' Clinton said. ``I
learned to pray. I learned to read. I learned to count from the
playing cards my grandparents tacked up on the kitchen windows.
Though I was only 4 when I left this place, it still holds very,
very vivid memories for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Clinton on his tour of the house were a number of
family members, including his young nephew, Tyler, whom the
president raced up the waxed wooden stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story house, built 82 years ago in the American
foursquare style, has been outfitted with period furnishings,
although none are pieces that were in the home in 1946-50 when
Clinton lived there.
</P>
<P>
   On a living-room table, a young Clinton beamed out from a
photograph in front of a Christmas tree. Nearby an Emerson
phonograph was open, with a Decca 78 rpm disc of ``Star Dust'' by
Guy Lombardo and his Royal Canadians on the turntable.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke first to several hundred people who had awaited
his arrival in a drenching rain at Hope's airport. It was an open
event as opposed to the invitation-only ceremony at the boyhood
home. He flew from Washington on a small Air Force passenger jet,
as there is no airport within 100 miles that could accommodate his
747s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter where you came from in life,'' Clinton told
the crowd, ``it matters what you do with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proclaimed the day the coldest March 12 in Hope in a
hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I made a lot of money for the hospitals in the
area,'' Clinton joked in his remarks at the house. ``There will be
people being treated for flu for three or four week after this.''
</P>
<P>
   More soberly, Clinton noted: ``Rain makes this thing more
poignant for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's father died in an auto wreck in Missouri three months
before he was born. Over the next few years, Clinton's mother was
often in Louisiana for nursing studies.
</P>
<P>
   Later Friday, Clinton spoke at two fund-raising events in the
border city of Texarkana for Rep. Max Sandlin, D-Texas, which were
expected to net more than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The second Sandlin event was at the home of Truman Arnold, a
wealthy Democratic contributor who has been questioned by a
Whitewater grand jury about arranging for about $90,000 in payments
to Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry concerned whether the payments, from Arnold and
other wealthy Democrats with Texas ties, were an attempt to buy
silence about the Clintons from the former deputy attorney general.
After Hubbell resigned from the Justice Department, he was
convicted on charges of doctoring fee records at the Rose Law Firm
in Little Rock, where he was a partner with Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
