<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers regains a whiff of success
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ In a sublime piece of timing, the
Braves threw Mark Wohlers into the fire Friday. His response was
almost perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Relieving Tom Glavine in the third inning with one out, the
bases loaded and Los Angeles' Gary Sheffield at the plate, Wohlers
struck out one of the game's best fastball hitters before ending
the inning on a soft line-out to center by Dave Hansen. Less than
hour after the club learned of Kerry Ligtenberg's elbow injury,
Wohlers recorded his first strikeout in three spring outings,
allowed no runs for the second straight appearance and looked
suspiciously like his former self.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty darn close. I really am,'' Wohlers said afterwards. ``I
don't want to jinx myself or get too far ahead, but I think today
was a pretty good step. To be as erratic as I was last year and to
come in with one of the premiere hitters in the game, even though
it's spring training, my frame of mind isn't spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers set up Sheffield with a first-pitch slider which was
taken for a strike, before coming back with three consecutive
fastballs, Sheffield whiffing on the last two. Having opened camp
by handling his deposed closer with kid gloves, manager Bobby Cox
no longer speaks cautiously about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's back-to-back,'' Cox said. ``He keeps going, man, that's
really bright news after getting bad news today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a lot to prove,'' Wohlers said. ``I knew I would
get to this point. I didn't know if it would be April or May or
July or when. I'm surprised I'm throwing the ball as well as I am
and feel as good as I do on the mound and carry myself as well. But
we still got three or four weeks down here. A lot can happen
between then and now.''
</P>
<P>
   SICK LIST
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux will attempt to pitch again today against Kansas
City after being sent home early with stomach flu he believes he
picked up from his children. He is expected to follow John Smoltz
against the Royals in Baseball City. ... Right fielder Brian Jordan
rebounded strongly after tweaking his right ankle Thursday, feeling
frisky enough after therapy to even trying to beat out a bunt
against the Dodgers. (He failed.) ... The infected cut on Glavine's
left thumb improved enough to allow him to start against Los
Angeles, though the left-hander insisted it had little to do with
his inconsistency (three hits and two walks in 2 1/3 innings). ``It
felt good, actually,'' he said. ``It bothered me a little on my
change-up but outside that, no. It was just I kind of lost my
location a little bit. Not that it was great before that.''
</P>
<P>
   SKORPUT DIES
</P>
<P>
   Pete Skorput, who for more than 30 years ran the Braves old
spring training complex in West Palm Beach, died Wednesday night
after a long bout with cancer. A former minor-league pitcher who
was hired by the Braves while Municipal Stadium was still under
construction in the early 1960s, Skorput passed away at his
residence in West Stockbridge, Mass., at 80. ``Things don't work
unless you have a nuts-and-bolts guy. He's the original,'' said
Cox, who first met Skorput in 1967. ``He kept everything working.''
</P>
<P>
   TURNER FIELD OPEN HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will hold an open house at Turner Field this morning,
where fans can stake out seating for 1999 season ticket sales.
Ticket plans, which start at $462, are available on half- and
full-season basis and full-season options are available in most
areas of the park. The open house runs from 9 a.m. to noon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
