<SLUG> BC-BKC-JIRSA-REACT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jirsa remains mum on firing
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If anyone is wondering how Ron Jirsa really feels
about his recent firing as Georgia's basketball coach or the
ill-fated season that led to it, they'll have to keep on wondering
because Jirsa is still not talking.
</P>
<P>
   One day after Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley announced
Jirsa would not be retained after just two years as the Bulldogs'
coach, Jirsa was not talking to the media Friday. When contacted
Friday afternoon, Jirsa's wife Laura said that her husband ``has
nothing to say'' to the media, referring them instead to a
statement released through Georgia's sports information office.
</P>
<P>
   Other than to thank the players and say his firing was a
surprise, little was revealed in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit that I was surprised to be dismissed
(Thursday),'' the statement read, ``but that's the nature of the
coaching business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jirsa's biggest regret is ``that I will be unable to complete
this recruiting class and coach the young men who have already
committed to the university.'' He also said that he intended to
remain in coaching.
</P>
<P>
   That Jirsa had nothing to say was only fitting because his team
certainly made no statements the final few weeks of the season. The
Bulldogs lost 11 of their last 14 games, including four straight to
end the season.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's weaknesses were glaring. The Bulldogs got virtually no
offensive or defensive production out of the center position and
were often reduced to a jump-shooting conglomerate. If their bombs
weren't hitting their targets, they were dead. Georgia was
out-rebounded in 10 of its last 11 games by an average of 7.8 a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as good as Jumaine Jones is, the 6-foot-7 sophomore
forward could not create on his own. Opponents simply put their
best defender on Jones and controlled the rest of the team with a
mixture of zones and man-to-man defense.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley, who never claimed to be a basketball expert, aptly
summed up Georgia's struggles this way: ``Who knows what one good
Larry Brown would have meant to this team. It's obvious to
everybody we didn't have enough muscle on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   A review of the season
</P>
<P>
   _ Best win: The Bulldogs defeated College of Charleston 84-63 on
Nov. 16, one of just two defeats the Cougars suffered this season.
Georgia also beat Texas on the road in November. Both teams are
made the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   _ Worst loss: The 70-66 overtime loss at South Carolina in the
regular-season finale was devastating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turning point: An overtime loss at Georgia Tech on Dec. 13 in
which the Bulldogs blew a 15-point lead in the game's final 10
minutes to lose 84-79.
</P>
<P>
   _ Key players: Jumaine Jones led the SEC in scoring with an 18.8
average and the Bulldogs in rebounding with 9.4, but at times was
more a distraction than he was an asset. Freshman guard D.A. Layne
(12.9 ppg) emerged as a potential star.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outlook: Regardless of who is hired as coach, he'll be
rebuilding from the loss of five seniors and likely Jones to the
NBA. Unless the Bulldogs can sign an athletic big man who can make
an immediate impact, they'll continue to struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
