<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-BRADLEY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big games are a family tradition for Szczerbiaks
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Wally Szczerbiak scored 43 points Friday. In any
other family, this would seem a big deal. In the Szczerbiak
household, it meant only that young Wally came within 23 of
bettering Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Szczerbiak holds the scoring record for Spanish
professional basketball _ 65 points for Real Madrid against a team
from Lugo. His son can cite the pertinent numbers: ``He was 25 of
27 from the field, 15 of 17 from the line. It's an unbelievable
record; it'll probably never be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   Not unless Wally Szczerbiak spurns the NBA to play in the
Catalans.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the NCAA Tournament a rumor, a big scorer from the
smallish Mid-American Conference who'd played but once, not well,
on national TV. Today Wally Szczerbiak (pronounced ZER-bee-ack)
stands as the author of the most stunning NCAA performance since
Bill Walton went 21-for-22. Szczerbiak scored 73 percent of his
team's points. He had 12 rebounds, two assists. He blocked Greg
Clark's shot at the buzzer. Szczerbiak's little team, Miami (Ohio),
toppled big-time Washington 59-58.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for people to get to see this,'' said Mike
Ensminger, Miami's sixth man. ``Before today, everybody undoubtedly
had mixed opinions. They'd say, `Oh, you play in the MAC.' ``But
for the next two days CBS will show the clips.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the off-the-ball work, the curling around screens, the
textbook shooting form. Of the 25-foot trey with four minutes
remaining, the flashing drive with 1:10 left. Of the game-saving
block. Here, America, is wall-to-wall Wally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity to play on the big stage,'' Szczerbiak
said. ``This is where you separate the men from the boys. The boys
went home, and the men are playing ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports Illustrated had ventured to Oxford, a bucolic burg 45
minutes north of Cincinnati, to tell the tale of this transplanted
Long Islander, but before Friday the evidence regarding Szczerbiak
was uncorroborated. In a way that helped. Washington appeared to
have no idea who he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of times down, I was as open as I've been all
year,'' Szczerbiak said. ``Whenever I drove, there weren't two or
three guys to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies refused to double-team Szczerbiak, a decision can
stand alongside the rollout of New Coke. He had 21 of Miami's 29
first-half points, 22 of 30 thereafter. ``This won't sound right,''
said Charlie Coles, the RedHawks' coach, ``but this was a team
effort.'' He was correct. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Szczerbiak watched from Row 1 of the Miami section,
literally leading cheers, even coaching a bit. ``Wally looked over;
I sort of told him to follow through on his shot.'' Walt Szczerbiak
knows a bit about watershed games: In addition to the 65 in Spain,
he had 31 points and 21 rebounds for George Washington in Madison
Square Garden against a UMass sophomore named Julius Erving. (Who
had, Szczerbiak cheerfully noted, 35 and 17 himself.)
</P>
<P>
   Said Walt Szczerbiak: ``This is what Wally does. He just steps
up. He's the type of player that it's killing him he missed his
last shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wally Szczerbiak: ``My dad tends to think a little
pessimistically. But he's right. I was mad. It was one of the best
looks I had all day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
