<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oklahoma State not intimated by Auburn
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Thursday's glorified blue-and-orange scrimmage is
over. Having flicked away Winthrop like so much lint, Auburn begins
this NCAA Tournament in earnest today as an 11 1/2-point favorite
over Oklahoma State in the second round of the South Region. That
spread startled Cowboys' coach Eddie Sutton and bemused Adrian
Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the (underdog) role,'' said Peterson, the senior guard
who scored 21 points in a 69-61 first-round win over Syracuse. ``It
let's you go out and play loose. You've got nothing to lose.
Auburn, they're the team that's got everything to lose. The No. 1
seed is expected to advance to the Sweet 16.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked hard all season and the hard work paid off for us
to receive a No. 1 seed,'' said Auburn's Scott Pohlman, the
sophomore guard from Roswell who had 14 points in the 81-40 blowout
of Winthrop. ``Seeds don't matter when you get this far in the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly are deserving of the No. 1 seed,'' said Sutton,
who admitted that he was ``a little surprised when I picked up the
newspaper (Friday) morning and saw'' the point spread.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for an experienced team like Oklahoma State, in its
second straight NCAA and seventh in nine years under Sutton, the
only coach to take four different schools (Creighton, Arkansas,
Kentucky and Oklahoma State) to the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess us being here last year, we know the ropes now,'' said
the Cowboys' Joe Adkins, whose only basket of the Syracuse game
gave Oklahoma State the lead for good, 60-57. ``Auburn has not been
here (since 1988), so I guess you can give us an edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet teammate Brian Montonati warns, ``Just because they haven't
been here, they're not going to show up dead.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sutton feels, ``They're the type of ballclub that could end
up in St. Pete.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Final Four. So Sutton must combat Auburn's superior
depth, athleticism and size with his typically tight defense and a
slower-paced, half-court offense orchestrated by junior point guard
Doug Gottlieb. The nation's assists leader (8.6 per game), Gottlieb
had 11 versus Syracuse but didn't attempt a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Sutton himself. ``I think we have a great advantage
because coach Sutton (29-19 in NCAA play) has been here so many
times,'' said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' said Sutton. ``Cliff Ellis is a
great coach. I don't know why Pete would say that, but I appreciate
the compliment. I'm one of the dinosaurs left in college
coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   TITANIC TRIUMPH
</P>
<P>
   ``This was important for the city of Detroit,'' Detroit's
Jermaine Jackson said of the Titans' thrilling 56-53 upset of UCLA
Thursday. ``It showed that we can play with any team in the
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Including No. 4 seed Ohio State tonight. But then, 12th-seeded
Detroit (25-5) beat two-time Big Ten champ Michigan State the
previous three seasons and upset St. John's in last year's NCAA's
before claiming the greatest win in school history Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would see us as small but mighty,'' said senior forward
Bacari Alexander. ``It's like the elephant and the mouse scenario.
The elephant comes right at you. It's real big. But the little
mouse comes at you, you run away. That's what Detroit's about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So am I Cinderella?'' wondered Detroit coach Perry Watson
after ousting the most fabled name in NCAA annals. Now Ohio State
(24-8) must solve a Detroit defense that's No. 2 nationally
(allowing 54.7 points a game).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
