<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGAWOMEN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McDonald, UGA put ambitions to the test
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Quite often it's the little things that get
freshmen in trouble as they learn to adjust to the college game.
For Georgia center Tawana McDonald, it may be as innocuous as
raising her hands short of vertical while playing defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, she's getting one or two fouls a game for doing
that,'' Georgia coach Andy Landers said. ``She doesn't get her
hands all the way up. It's due to inexperience, a lack of defensive
intensity and some bad habits that aren't glaringly bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But they have been tough enough to break thus far for McDonald,
who has fouled out of eight games and has gotten in early foul
trouble in some of Georgia's most important contests. It's what she
has been able to do when she does play that has Landers salivating
about the postseason prospects for the Lady Bulldogs, who play
Liberty today in their NCAA Tournament opener.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Landers had to be convinced of McDonald's potential
before she put on a Georgia uniform. He has favorably compared the
6-foot-4 Parade All-American from Flint, Mich., to former Georgia
greats Katrina McClain, Janet Harris and Tracy Henderson, post
players who took the Lady Dogs to Final Fours and national
championship games.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has the same ambitions with an underclass-dominated
squad that reached the NCAA first round last year but was missing
consistent post play. McDonald, who sat out the first seven games
of the season after suffering a sprained knee, has been trying to
catch up ever since. She leads the team with 46 blocked shots, but
often that has been her undoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone out there at times being anxious and wanting to go
after people,'' McDonald said. ``I'm learning that I don't have to
block every shot. There aren't many people who can shoot over me,
so I might as well try not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half against Tennessee in the SEC Tournament finals
two weeks ago, she demonstrated her ``presence,'' as Landers calls
it. She scored nine points, getting most of them on impressive
drives to the basket from the top of the key, and grabbed seven
rebounds as Georgia led the Lady Vols.
</P>
<P>
   But after halftime she was whistled for two quick fouls and
eventually fouled out. Without her, Georgia's guards were stranded,
and Tennessee rolled to a 16-point win. For the season, McDonald
averages 8.8 points and a team-high 6.8 rebounds, but raising her
21.8 minutes-per-game average could be a critical factor for the
Lady Dogs in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a big key to our success,'' point guard Kelly Miller
said. ``It's really important to our team that she's able to stay
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, a high school teammate of Georgia reserve forward
Deana Nolan, brushes off the lofty comparisons. ``I really don't
think about it that much, I'm just trying to continue to do what I
need to get better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Landers thinks she's well on her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just keeps getting better and better,'' he said. ``She's a
great person with a great work ethic. Tawana McDonald's gonna be a
great player.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
