<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's Garr in welterweight title bout
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The only Atlanta boxer in a title fight tonight is
not predicting a round. Just a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they think this is going to be an easy fight _ I'm sure
that's what they think,'' said Stone Mountain, Ga., welterweight
Sam Garr, who fights for the welterweight title tonight against WBA
champion James Page on the undercard of the Evander
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis at Madison Square Garden. ``But this is my
time to shine. When I go in there, I'm leaving with that belt.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder the 29-year-old Garr isn't dizzy from the
altitude. He has never been in a fight of this magnitude, despite
an impressive 25-2 record and 23 knockouts in seven years of
boxing. Only two years ago, he was spending most of his time
supporting his wife and son in landscaping jobs. Boxing was a
secondary occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd work 60 hours a week, then go to the gym at night,'' said
Garr, a native of Quincy, Ill., and Atlanta resident since 1991.
``When I was working, I really couldn't get into the shape I am
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Garr said he had no problems making the 147-pound limit, even
though he generally has fought in the mid-150s. But even superb
conditioning doesn't make it any less surprising that Garr is here.
Last September, in a club show at the Roxy, he was stopped by
little-known Stephan Johnson in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   But Garr recently signed a four-year deal with promoter Don
King, and magically, a title shot developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a powerful man,'' said Garr, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   He has fought once since the loss to Johnson, stopping James
Mullins in the second round.``I just took it as a way to grow,''
Garr said of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Page, who possesses good power, won a title elimination after
the belt was stripped from Ike Quartey.Other bouts:
</P>
<P>
   The other featured undercard bouts have heavyweight contender
John Ruiz (33-3) meeting Mario Cawley (21-1) and IBF junior
middleweight champion Fernando Vargas (15-0) meeting Howard Clarke
(26-10-2). Heavyweight Nate Jones (7-0), a 1996 Olympic teammate of
Vargas and Wells, also is on the card.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
