<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield's showdown with Lewis is personal
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man's entire career seemingly has been like one
big double take. So the fact that Evander Holyfield should once
again do something unexpectedly extraordinary is not itself
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the surprises don't usually come long before the
opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   When Holyfield steps into the boxing ring at Madison Square
Garden tonight, he will try to wrest the WBC title from Lennox
Lewis and fuse it with his WBA and IBF belts, unifying the
championship for the first time in over six years. Strangely, that
all has become a subplot.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to call his shot or ridicule his opponent, Holyfield
has continuously vowed to knock out Lewis in the third round and
minimize the talents of a heavyweight who is three years younger,
towers over him by three inches and has won 34 of 35 fights. The
reaction has been one collective ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be embarrassed,'' Holyfield said when asked if
he was concerned about the possibility of his vision not being
realized. ``But how can you be embarrassed by saying something you
know you can do. I don't feel any pressure. I know I'm capable of
taking this guy out in the first round. It's not like I even use
all the (weapons) I have when I fight. Sometimes I take the easy
way out. The whole thing is, I know how this man fights. I know
he's easy to hit. I know that if I hit him with the right
combinations, he's not gonna wanna take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been speculation that Holyfield is either, 1)
trying to pump pay-per-view sales, or, 2) shake Lewis' confidence,
he is not one to play mind games. When he says something, it's
because that is what he feels. As to why Holyfield maintains some
animosity against Lewis, it has far has less to do with Lewis's
crack about Holyfield being a Christian hypocrite than his Lewis'
previous charges that Holyfield was ducking him.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mike) Tyson always had that respect for opponents,''
Holyfield said. ``Lennox always wants to cheap-shot somebody. He
wants to make it more personal than it is. My whole thing is, it's
time to pay the piper. He'll pay the price.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis doesn't suffer, as Holyfield has forecast, the
British-born heavyweight will win over a number of critics who have
slammed him for not previously facing the division's strongest
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight is everything for him,'' said Emanuel Steward,
Lewis' trainer. ``His whole career will be defined on one night. If
he doesn't win and win aggressively, he'll never be considered a
great fighter or even a good fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis acknowledges he is perceived as a fighter who rarely
displays much heart or enthusiasm, but said, ``This particular
fight, Evander will bring out certain things in me the public
hasn't seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield will try to get in close to Lewis, who has a 6
1/2-inch reach advantage, and counter his shots quickly with
combinations to the body and uppercuts. Lewis will try to keep
Holyfield on the outside with a punishing jab that he seldom has
showed, and attempt to physically dominate Holyfield inside by
grabbing his arms and behind the neck when the two are in clinches.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who Holyfield believes has the advantage?
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy, his power is his weakness,'' Holyfield said. ``He
leaves his hands out there (after the punch) so you can smash him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson couldn't stand pain so he had to fight back. Your chance
of knocking him out was greater. Lennox is another one of those
guys who just can't stand to get hit. He's going to come out
swinging, and by him being bigger than Tyson, that just makes him a
bigger target.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
