<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS-TECH-ADVANCE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Texas Tech tightens defense for NCAA voyage 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In quiet moments, the tormenting demons resurface for Texas Tech
guard Rene Hanebutt. She'll be walking to class or resting in bed
when visions of leprechauns dance in her head.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly leprechauns. More like Notre Dame basketball
players, firing in long-range jumpers over the top of Tech's
matchup zone defense. Or scoring at will inside, when Hanebutt and
friends scramble to stop the onslaught from outside.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 51 weeks since Notre Dame put the brakes on Tech's
1998 NCAA Tournament run with a shocking, 74-59 upset in Lubbock.
As the Red Raiders (28-3) prepare for today's opening-round game of
the 1999 tournament against Stephen F. Austin (17-11) at Lubbock
Municipal Coliseum, they are determined to use last year's
surprising second-round exit as fuel toward the program's sixth
trip to the Sweet 16 since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have nightmares about that game,'' said Hanebutt, a
senior from Bowie. ``That was one of the most disturbing losses of
my career. It's definitely been in the back of our minds all year
that, once we get to the NCAAs, we won't let something like that
happen to us again.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players echoed similar vows. In fact, the Notre Dame loss
hit such a nerve with Tech coach Marsha Sharp that she used it as
the springboard to overhauling her defensive philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Fighting Irish hit 50 percent from the field
in that contest, Sharp switched her team's primary defensive
alignment from zone to man-to-man. Tech, the No. 2 seed in the NCAA
Midwest Region, has limited opponents to 40.1 percent shooting this
season, with an increase of two turnovers per game by its foes.
</P>
<P>
   The change, Sharp said, ``makes me feel safer'' in matchups
against teams with top-notch perimeter shooters. In the estimation
of rival Big 12 coaches, it also makes Tech a more versatile and
more dangerous team than at this time last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, they're better,'' said Iowa State coach Bill
Fennelly, whose team fell to Tech, 73-59, last week in the final of
the Big 12 tournament in Kansas City, Mo. ``It takes a lot of
courage for them to make a change like that to try and get to the
next level. But it's worked out well and it's been a great step for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska coach Paul Sanderford said: ``I think it's one of the
best stories this season, from a national standpoint. Texas Tech
had a great team last year. But Marsha was disappointed in what
they did in the NCAAs. So she vowed that this team was going to be
better on defense and be able to play more than a zone. Believe me,
they've done it. We couldn't do anything against them.''
</P>
<P>
   During a 77-59 loss to Tech in the semifinals of the Big 12
tournament, Nebraska's top scorers, guards Nicole Kubik and Brooke
Schwartz, combined to shoot 25 percent from the field. In the first
half of a regular-season meeting on Jan. 20, Tech limited Iowa
State's starters to a combined 1 of 23 from the floor while
amassing a 28-9 lead en route to a 71-47 rout.
</P>
<P>
   Such numbers, Sharp said, are encouraging. But even more
encouraging might be the resolve of the Lady Raiders to capitalize
on lessons learned against Notre Dame. Of the nine members of
Tech's regular player rotation, eight suited up in last year's loss
to the Fighting Irish. All are eager to begin making amends for
that debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still in the back of our minds and it's been there all
year,'' point guard Melinda Schmucker said. ``It's not going to go
away until we do something about it. The lesson we learned is to
take one game at a time and not take anyone lightly. Because of
that game, we realize how critical every possession in each game
is. Last year, we weren't ready to go out and play that type of
game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
