<SLUG> BC-CAR-B.LABONTE-ATLANTA-POLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPE STICKS B. LABONTE TO POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ Bobby Labonte used a fresh qualifying engine, and
mass quantities of tape, to get inside Mike Skinner's head at the
Atlanta Motor Speedway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The grille on his Pontiac Grand Prix taped tight to cut down on
wind resistance, Labonte toured the 1.54-mile quadoval in 28.437
seconds and 194.957 mph to win the pole position for tomorrow's
NASCAR Cracker Barrel 500.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, whose 1998 early-season nose-dived after he crashed in
the rain-delayed event here last March, was taking notes as Labonte
exited the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that thing taped way, way off,'' said Skinner, who
subsequently secured the No. 2 qualifying position with a hot lap
at 194.226 mph. ``It was pretty intimidating when he ran that lap.
It probably made me drive a little harder, and our car got really
loose in turns 1 and 2. We just couldn't get the balance good
enough to tape it up solid. I know that if you tape it up close to
solid, you get a lot more straightaway speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte had enough horsepower to become the first two-time
pole-winner of the 1999 Winston Cup season. Labonte also qualified
first last week at the Las Vegas Motor Speedway en route to a
fifth-place finish on Sunday. But this is AMS, where Labonte has
won three of the past five races. The native Texan captured last
spring's Primestar 500 after starting 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things on this race car I don't know about,'' said
Labonte, driver of the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac owned by
Joe Gibbs. ``But I'm confident enough when I get into the car I
don't have to worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that this place here takes a lot of power. For down
here, \Rengine builder\S Mark Cronquist and all the guys in the
motor room, they had a qualifying motor that was really stout.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs' in-house engine program has allowed Labonte to qualify in
the top 10 for the first four events of 1999. Jeremy Mayfield, who
qualified fifth yesterday in the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus, is the
only other driver to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Labonte is the man here,'' said Skinner, the series
points leader and driver of the No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet Monte
Carlo. ``But Atlanta is not a bad racetrack for me. When we got
hurt here, it was a freak thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The top 25 drivers secured starting spots in what will be a
43-car field. Rookie Tony Stewart _ Labonte's teammate _ qualified
the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac third at 194.192 mph. He was followed
by Dale Jarrett, Mayfield, Geoffrey Bodine, rookie Buckshot Jones,
reigning Cup champion Jeff Gordon, Joe Nemechek and John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   Among those failing to make the first-day cut were seven-time
Cup champion Dale Earnhardt (30th) and Las Vegas 400 winner Jeff
Burton (33rd). They are among 22 drivers who will have the option
of either standing on their speeds or requalifying today.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
