<HEADLINE>
THE MOVIES THAT MADE MIRAMAX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Sunday, March 14 by NYTimes News Service) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a snapshot of eight key Miramax films that have led the
company to prominence. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; S &LR; candal'' &QL; 
Plot elements: Rehashing of the Profumo affair that toppled the
conservative government in Britain in the early '60s. &QL; 
Sex: Orgy scene was edited from U.S. version to avoid X rating. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; My Left Foot &LR; '' &UR; (1989) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Story of Irish poet Christy Brown, who overcame his
physical disability (cerebral palsy only allowed him to control his
left foot). &QL; 
Notable achievement: Picked up five Oscar nominations, winning two
_ Daniel Day-Lewis for best actor and Brenda Fricker for best
supporting actress.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; sex, lies &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; videotape &LR; '' &UR; (1989) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Voyeurism, infidelity, techno-eroticism. &QL; 
Violence: Mostly psychological. &QL; 
Sex: More theoretical than its title implies, despite a strong
erotic current. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Title became a catch-phrase that even surfaced
during the recent Clinton scandal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; The Crying Game &LR; '' &UR; (1992) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Gender- and identity-swapping; contemporary
political terrorism; homosexuality/bisexuality; loyalty and honor. &QL; 
Violence: Lethal shootout between IRA and British Army; climactic
catfight pitting Jaye Davidson against Miranda Richardson. &QL; 
Sex: Off screen, although there's a candid shot of Davidson's
genitalia. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Had people talking about the secret of
Davidson's gender. Picked up six Oscar nominations, winning one for
best original screenplay.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; The Piano &LR; '' &UR; (1993) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Sexually charged story of a mute woman who moves
with her daughter to the wilds of New Zealand to marry. Has erotic
liaison with Englishman gone native. &QL; 
Violence: Some graphic scenes, including mutilation. &QL; 
Sex: Holly Hunter and Harvey Keitel leave little to the
imagination. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Received eight Oscar nominations, winning
three _ Holly Hunter, best actress; Anna Paquin, best supporting
actress; Jane Campion, best original screenplay. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; Pulp Fiction &LR; '' &UR; (1994) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Life imitating pop culture; sadomasochism;
homosexual rape; drug overdosing; honor among bad guys. &QL; 
Violence: Graphic and disturbing. &QL; 
Sex: Sweaty and perverse, though more implied than depicted. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Revived careers of John Travolta and Bruce
Willis; made Samuel L. Jackson a star. Got seven Oscar nominations,
with Quentin Tarantino winning for best original screenplay. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; The English Patient &LR; '' &UR; (1996) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Star-crossed lovers; European colonial malaise;
World War II, though as exotic backdrop. &QL; 
Violence: Minimal and off-camera, for the most part, though nasty
things happen to Willem Dafoe. &QL; 
Sex: Glamorous, soft-lit eroticism. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Received 11 Oscar nominations, winning nine,
including best picture. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`` &UR; Shakespeare  &LR; i &UR; n Love &LR; '' &UR; (1998) &LR;  &QL; 
Plot elements: Star-crossed lovers; gender reversal; life imitates
theater; romance turns hack writer into artist. &QL; 
Violence: One big brawl, played as comedy; one off-screen murder. &QL; 
Sex: Sensual, but mostly from the waist up. &QL; 
Notable achievement: Picked up 13 Oscar nominations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
