<HEADER>
A8674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUILDING-GREEN13-COX     03-12 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUILDING-GREEN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors' office offers environmentally friendly design, but at a
price
 &HT;    By Lawrene Trump
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Ohio _ In a marriage of development and
conservation, local builders are starting to think green.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentally friendly building techniques and materials are
improving every day. They still cost more than traditional
practices, but the difference is shrinking and some customers are
starting to demand them, builders said.
</P>
<P>
   At the owner's request, the Rocking Horse Center, a new doctors'
office across from South High School, includes some recycled
materials, extra insulation and geothermal heat, said its designer,
Springfield architect Stephen L. Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   The carpet is made from recycled carpet fibers; the vinyl
wallpaper used no heavy metals in its processing, and the restroom
stall doors and enclosures are made from recycled milk jugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 11 years I've been in business, this is the first client
who said this is a priority,'' Sharp said. ``It's not something
people think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp designed the building, but his colleague, architect Ken
Shook, did the leg work to find the materials and make them work.
</P>
<P>
   Shook found the restroom stalls _ Hiney-Hiders, the Santana
Company cheerfully dubbed them _ in Scranton, Penn.
</P>
<P>
   In Columbus he found Semco, a window manufacturer that uses some
recycled wood inside its window frames. Homasote, Inc., which
produces message boards from post-consumer recycled paper, is based
in West Trenton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The recycled plastic stalls cost 30 percent to 40 percent more
than new plastic ones, but the premium seemed worth it to Rocking
Horse founder Dr. Jim Duffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to be aware of how we use our nonrenewable
resources,'' Duffee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to provide an example for businesses in Springfield
and Ohio. We're putting up a building as energy-efficient as we can
make it in an area that traditionally has a high density of
hazardous environmental exposure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Old, multiunit rental houses, such as those replaced by the
Rocking Horse Center and still surrounding it, often have peeling
lead paint and crumbling asbestos, Duffee said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical offices will attempt a paperless system; records
transferred there will be scanned into the computer, then shredded
and recycled. Some other Ohio doctor's offices use the method,
Duffee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any doubt this is the way of the future,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,500-square-foot building is the largest commercial
building in the area to use geothermal heat.
</P>
<P>
   Danco Enterprises, the Springfield company installing the
building's geothermal heating system, has installed nearly 500
geothermal systems in homes all over southwest Ohio, owner Dan
Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's company had a booth at the recent home show at the
Upper Valley Mall, and public interest seems to be growing, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that turns people off is the price. It's about
$5,000 more than anything else, but the operating cost is so low in
three or four years that difference is paid back'' through utility
bill savings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About $30,000 of the Rocking Horse building's $1 million cost
was for the heating system.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen wells, each 300 feet deep, hold hoses that allow the
heating system's water to go down, up, down, up and back to the
furnace, where, warmed to the earth's year-round temperature of 55
degrees, its heat is electrically boosted to run a hot-air blower
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the next four years you'll see some major changes''
in building choices, Lehman said. ``Fuel prices are cyclical, and
they will go back up. That's why I got in the business in '76.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago Danco dropped everything else and went only to
geothermal installations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've converted some all-gas customers to all-electric and
actually cut their utility bill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until alternatives to burning fossil fuels cost the same as
conventional systems, homeowners won't choose them, said David
Bohardt of the 1,000-member Homebuilders Association of Dayton and
the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to sell the value of what's inside the walls of the
house. It's not at all from a builder's unwillingness to build
houses with these features,'' Bohardt said. ``It's that, if a buyer
has to choose between a hot tub or increasing the insulation,
they'll end up soaking in the tub.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty to 30 percent of new homes have more than the minimum
recommended insulation, he said, but many are putting in
super-efficient gas furnaces.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Sherry, president of the 80-member Clark County Builders
Association, said some local developers are pioneering green
practices.
</P>
<P>
   A superinsulated masonry home built by Springfield developer
Randy MacGillivray is one of two in the country being reviewed by
the Research Institute of the National Association of Homebuilders,
Sherry said.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Hibner, program manager at Dayton Power and Light's Energy
Resource Center, said about 20 percent of the 2,000 calls each
month to the company's 1-800-WAYTOGO energy hot line are from
homeowners concerned about energy efficiency in their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest is growing. Not at a tremendous rate, but it's
growing steadily,'' Hibner said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
