<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      03-12 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: REPUBLICANS IN CONGRESS HOPE CORE ISSUES CAN BRIDGE A
DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (wg) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As they seek their way after the impeachment trial,
congressional Republicans have gone on the offensive against
President Clinton on national security and foreign policy, while
taking stands on Social Security and education that they hope will
give them some claim to these popular domestic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   This balancing act is reflected in the issues that Speaker
Dennis Hastert has identified as the four ``pillars'' of Republican
policy in the 106th Congress: Social Security, tax relief,
education and national defense. In two of these areas, Republicans
admit they are playing defense; Democrats have long had the
public's trust on education and Social Security. So the Republican
aim is to look interested and responsible enough in these issues to
shield from attack.
</P>
<P>
   Tax cutting and national security, by contrast, are still issues
on which Republicans hold a slight edge, an advantage they hope to
rebuild into the potent political force of a decade ago when they
were twin tenets of Reaganism. But the Republican leadership's
decision to wall off Social Security funds from budget pressures
has limited its ability to propose large tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   So congressional Republicans have turned a laserlike focus to
national security as a way to distinguish themselves from Clinton.
The Senate has passed a military pay hike bill. The House Thursday
debated _ and narrowly supported _ the president's policy toward
Kosovo. Both chambers plan to consider measures next week to
promote a national missile defense. Republicans are calling for
large increases in military spending. And on several fronts they
are investigating the administration's response to suspicions that
China stole nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly stand for a far, far different foreign policy
than the one that is now going from embarrassment to near
humiliation in places like Kosovo and our China policy,'' Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., said this week on Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Reagan presided over the end of the Cold War. Public
interest in foreign policy has waned since the collapse of the
Soviet Union. And the foreign policy consensus of the last
half-century has been unraveling. Still, national security is an
arena that appeals to congressional Republicans for several
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For one, they sense that it is an area of vulnerability for a
president who has repeatedly bested them on domestic issues but has
had trouble articulating a compelling vision of a post-Cold War
foreign policy. ``There's a very strong sense in Congress that the
administration has conducted an episodic foreign policy that
careens from area to area,'' said Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   National security is also an area that resonates with the
Republicans' conservative base without alienating moderates and
swing voters the way social issues do. ``Missile defense is a great
issue with our base, but also a decent issue with the public and a
very good fund-raising issue as well,'' said one Republican
strategist, saying that the old Reagan dream of a defense shield
can still pull in direct mail contributions for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Republicans see national security as an area that
can give them the unity of purpose they lack right now on domestic
issues. ``It's really seen as one of the core beliefs,'' Lazio
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the question is whether Republicans can really gain traction
on national security.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating their push, Clinton responded by trying to co-opt
the issue the same way he did with Republican initiatives to
balance the budget and overhaul welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the Pentagon and trying to head off the
Republican Congress, Clinton this year proposed the first real
increase in military spending since the Persian Gulf War. He also
proposed a 4.4 percent across-the-board increase in pay for the
military in December along with other raises and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans one-upped him by approving a 4.8 percent
across-the-board increase and other benefits in the first bill they
considered after the impeachment trial _ a bill so expensive that
no one quite knows how Congress will be able to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Republicans are nowhere near as united on foreign
policy and national security issues as they might wish. The last
Congress brought a tug and pull between Republican
internationalists and populists over issues like trade and funding
for the IMF and for the United Nations. And Thursday's debate on
whether to authorize U.S. troops in Kosovo, far from showing
Republican unity, instead displayed a deep Republican divide over
America's role in the world.
</P>
<P>
   While Hastert supported the president's proposal to send troops
to Kosovo as part of a NATO force until a peace settlement is
reached, his majority leader and whip did not.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who had invoked the memory of the
nations' war dead during Clinton's impeachment trial, made a strong
appeal to the party to recognize the importance of the U.S. role in
NATO. ``We have had more years of continuous peace in Europe since
the days of the Roman Empire,'' he said. ``NATO is not only worth
it. It works, and the United States of America is the leader of
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is a moral obligation on those people who have
the resources to intercede when people are being wantonly,
atrociously killed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., said ``there is genocide
all over the world.'' He asked, ``Are we going to send troops
everywhere where genocide is committed? No.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans, he said, ``should be the job of the Europeans. It
is their job now that the Cold War is over. The United States of
America shouldered its share of the burden for stability in the
whole world in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments like that left Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority
leader, accusing the Republicans on Friday of being more
isolationist than internationalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking for politically attractive issues,'' he said.
``A more isolationist, `defend America first,' fortress America
stand, to many of their constituents is a politically popular place
to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
