<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-B     03-12 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS LONG AS HE KEEPS HIS HEAD, LEWIS HAS LITTLE CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gary Bell has had his bell rung by both men so when
he chimes in with an opinion on the outcome of Saturday night's
heavyweight title unification fight between Evander Holyfield and
Lennox Lewis, it is a learned one.
</P>
<P>
   Bell knows Holyfield and Lewis because he's been hit by them
both, which is the best way to understand what they will be about
when they square off at Madison Square Garden to settle the issue
of who is the real heavyweight champion of the world. Bell has
prepared Lewis for fights with Tommy Morrison and Ray Mercer and in
recent years he has sparred regularly with Holyfield, although he
did not work with him for this fight because his height did not
approximate Lewis's 6 feet 5 inches. Still, Bell knows what each
man will carry with him into the Garden and he says the choice is
clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield,'' Bell said. ``Keep your eye on his left hook.
That's what will do it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is a big man, but you can walk through his left hand.
I'm not going to lie to you. His right hand is a hammer but his
left hand is nothing. So I believe Holyfield will be able to get
inside Lewis's jab and when he does his hand speed will decide the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Lewis will come out and try to jump on Evander the
way he did (Andrew) Golota (whom he KOd in one round), but Evander
doesn't throw one punch at a time like Golota. He throws four,
five, six punches at a time and they can overwhelm you. I don't
think he can do it in three rounds, like he said. I think six
rounds myself. By a left hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has nearly as many supporters as Holyfield with many of
the predictions of doom for Holyfield centering on a belief that he
is finally at the end of his fistic rope. This had been said after
he lost to Michael Moorer and before he defeated Mike Tyson and if
it is said often enough about a 36-year-old fighter it eventually
will come true. But it shouldn't on this night unless Holyfield
gets so wrapped up in his talk of a third-round knockout that he
forgets who he has always been _ a professional.
</P>
<P>
   A professional prize fighter adjusts to situations and
opponents. He does not get angry when he is called a hypocrite, as
Lewis has called Holyfield repeatedly by challenging his religious
beliefs with the reality of the five children Holyfield has
fathered out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   A professional prize fighter ignores the personal differences
and does not go for knockouts that are not there. He does not
become involved in the hype of a big fight. If Holyfield can
maintain that professionalism he will win, unless his legs suddenly
to stone and his arms to dead weight because he has faster hands,
more skill, and a stronger will. But if he tries to turn the fight
into a brawl, he could lose because Lewis brings with him a right
hand like the hammer of Thor.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has 27 knockouts among his 34 wins and most of them have
been the result of that clubbing right. It lands not with an
exquisite snap but a dull thud. It does not explode on a man, it
dents him and sends him to the floor the way a piledriver sends a
steel rod into the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Such a weapon is dangerous and Holyfield has to understand that
or he will find out the hard way. In the past, Holyfield has been
able to get inside even his biggest opponents, such as Riddick Bowe
and George Foreman, and throw hooks and uppercuts in close, two
punches Lewis doesn't particularly like to see coming. It is likely
he will be able to get inside against Lewis as well because his jab
is not formidable despite trainer Emanuel Steward's insistence that
it will be Saturday night. If Holyfield gets inside, he will be
able to negate the power of Lewis's long right, which has to be
thrown at a distance to be most effective, and slowly carry the
day.
</P>
<P>
   But what Holyfield must avoid is rushing headlong into one of
those right hands or being kept at long range, where Lewis can paw
him with his jab and slam him with the right behind it. At a
distance, Lewis has the advantage, as Steward has been telling him
for 11 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is very determined to be aggressive but not reckless,''
Steward said. ``One of my concerns is that he'll go out and be
overly aggressive. He has to press the fight but be alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox knows what this fight means to his career. If he loses,
he'll be just a kid with dreadlocks who came over here and through
vacations (vacant titles) won two (World Boxing Council) titles.
He's going to have to live the rest of his life on this
performance. Lennox has to win this fight or he's nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do that he has to get his feet under him and stay balanced
to fire a hard jab. Not a pawing jab like he throws sometimes but a
hard jab. If he does, Holyfield will have to make great alterations
in his style to get inside.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis can do that, Holyfield will have a hard time hitting
him and a harder time avoiding the right hand that has turned so
many nights to Lewis's advantage. That may be why Holyfield has
made such a point of predicting a third-round knockout _ to lure
Lewis into the kind of attack he can counter.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has clearly been irked by Holyfield's dismissive
prediction but some believe it is just part of a psychological
battle designed to get Lewis to come out throwing his most potent
weapon in order to make a point. If Lewis does that, Holyfield
believes he is fast enough to counter it and land first, as Shannon
Briggs did in the first round of his fight with Lewis when Briggs
stunned Lewis with a counter punch that had him in trouble until
Lewis regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes three rounds, it can't be nothing but a slugfest,''
Steward said. ``Emotions are running pretty high. This could turn
into Hagler-Hearns. I think that's what Evander wants. He wants to
come out like Hagler.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, he may end up like Hearns _ unconscious _ because
that is not his fight. Holyfield has spoken often about his
knowledge in the ring and how it has led to many victories. That is
what he must focus on Saturday night because the one clear edge he
has is that he is more skilled and more willful than Lewis. He must
turn the fight into a test of skills and wills because he can win
on both counts. What he cannot win is a test of raw power, which is
the fight Steward hopes it will become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would you pick if you had Sandy Koufax pitching to Ed
Kranepool?'' said Don Turner, Holyfield's wise, old trainer. ``I've
got the better fighter. This isn't about the trainers. The fight is
decided by the fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is, the best fighter needs to remember who he is. He is a
wise guerilla warrior who wins the battle by winning many small
skirmishes first. If Holyfield is content to do that, he will wear
down Lewis, who has always shown signs of fading in the second half
of his fights, and stop him late.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Holyfield could get hit and suddenly turn into an old
man victimized on a dark street corner, which is what happened to
his longtime stablemate and old friend, Pernell Whitaker, several
weeks ago against Felix Trinidad. But what people seem to forget is
that Lewis keeps talking about how he will finally have the stage
to make the world see his greatness that has been long hidden.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters speak as if Lewis is 23 and Holyfield Methusela
as they discuss how Steward has been working the rough edges off
his fighter. What needs to be remembered is that Lewis is 33, not
23. If he still has rough edges after five years and nine fights
with Steward, they are not going to be polished off. They are
permanent flaws. If Lewis was a great heavyweight, would we not
have seen a hint of it by now?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is we have not and we will not. If he wins by knockout
Saturday night, we will not see the greatness of Lennox Lewis
finally shining through. We will have witnessed the greatness of
Evander Holyfield finally fade away.
</P>
<P>
   But don't bet on that. Not on this night anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
