<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-POLAND-SCENE-640     03-12 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-POLAND-SCENE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROUD BUT PENSIVE MOMENT IN WARSAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NATO, NATO-ASSESS) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ In what will hardly be the last adaptation the
Polish military will have to make, an honor guard performed an
unusual flag-raising ceremony after dark here Friday night to mark
the moment that Poland became a member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In a simple affair by the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in
Pilsudski Square, timed to the official ceremony in Independence,
Mo., the red-and-white Polish flag went up alongside NATO's
blue-and-gold, marking the end to a generation of ideological
division.
</P>
<P>
   As fireworks exploded over the vast square, Boleslaw
Siematkowski began to cry. Now 75, he was a captain in the Polish
Home Army that fought alongside the Allies in World War II, then
saw his family deported to Siberia by the victorious Soviet army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we stand a chance as a nation,'' he said. ``We stand a
chance not to be taken into captivity, to be imprisoned or
threatened, so we can live in human dignity in a free country that
has earned its freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Siematkowski gestured to the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, where
many of Poland's battles for sovereignty are chiseled on plaques.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, when Polish soldiers imposed martial law on the
Solidarity trade union and much of Polish society, passers-by would
sometimes spit when they passed the tomb.
</P>
<P>
   But since the end of the Communist regime, the list of battles
on the tomb has been expanded, to include the struggles against
Moscow, the battles of the Polish Home Army and even the uprising
of the Warsaw ghetto in October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of us fought for freedom and our pilots flew for
Britain, and then at Yalta they just gave away this land to
Stalin,'' Siematkowski said. ``It was a betrayal of Poland.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he have confidence in NATO now? ``It means a lot,'' he
said. ``It means our security.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall Polish captain, with a red beret sitting jauntily, said
he felt that Poland's new alliance ``is generally positive.'' Asked
if he was ambivalent about it, he laughed and said: ``No, not
ambivalent. What's happened has happened, and I suppose it's better
like this. Any time you get a strong ally, it helps. But after all,
it's only the first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wieslaw Prokop, bearing his own Polish flag, said he was
disappointed that only a few hundred people had come to the
freezing square, still marked by the morning's snow. ``This should
be celebrated more,'' he said. ``I suppose it's the weather. But
anyone who thinks about Poland's future is happy today.''
</P>
<P>
   A medium-sized country like Poland, ``stuck between Russia and
Germany,'' he said, ``cannot afford to stay on its own, to stay
neutral.'' At last, he said, ``we are with the West, with the
Americans, whom we can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Piotr, 22, an engineering student, said he had come to the
square ``because this is a historic event.'' No one really fears
the Russians now, he said, but NATO is an ``important psychological
guarantee, and it helps us forget the awful period under Russia.''
Anyway, he said, ``the Polish army could do with some help.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an important theme in the Polish press Friday, with the
daily Zycie, or Life, running a long and depressing analysis of the
poor discipline and drunkenness in the heavily conscript Polish
army.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wait to be proud of their army,'' said Tomasz
Wroblewski, who edited the paper's special NATO section. ``They're
tired of being ashamed of our soldiers, of seeing them drunk and
not well equipped.''
</P>
<P>
   For most Poles, Wroblewski said, NATO membership is an important
symbol ``of security and prestige.'' He described some journalists
as walking around the newsroom Friday with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few think war is feasible,'' he said. ``But this helps this
complex of ours: We feel like we are in the West and feel we are no
worse than Austrians or Germans, but we are considered Easterners.
And now we are on the other side.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gazeta Wyborcza, Poland's most successful and influential
newspaper, had a typically wry headline: ``If Today Is Friday, Then
We're in NATO.'' But the paper also ran a front-page article that
it had solicited from President Clinton, in which he, or his speech
writers, praised Polish aid to the American Revolution and Polish
courage through the centuries, saying that now ``we are not only
friends but allies.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper also ran an article by Zbigniew Brzezinski, the
Polish-born national security adviser to President Carter, in which
he suggested that the current round of NATO enlargement might be
the last for a long while. All three new members have urged NATO to
keep expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Marek Ostrowski of the weekly Polityka said some Poles still
mistrusted any security guarantee, misunderstanding how the world
had changed since 1939, when British and French guarantees of
Polish sovereignty proved hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly there is satisfaction that we have definitely changed
camps,'' he said. ``We were forced to be part of the Soviet camp
against our will. Then we were sort of liberated, but in this gray
zone not belonging to anyone, and now we are somehow raised to this
Western camp under American protection. That is the mood. We
remember that it was you Americans who pulled Europe out of the
mire in 1944, not anyone else, so we want NATO to remain strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations in Hungary and the Czech Republic were also
low-key. NATO members' flags were raised outside the Hungarian
defense ministry.
</P>
<P>
   In Prague there was a small rally Friday, and President Vaclav
Havel, who had pushed the Czechs into NATO, said in a statement,
``Never have we been part of such a broad, solid and binding
security alliance which at the same time respects in its essence
the sovereignty and will of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Havel is to be host at a celebratory ball in Prague Castle on
Saturday night, but the only official ceremonies Friday were local
ones in the North Bohemian town of Liberec. That is the home of the
Czech unit that specializes in defense against chemical weapons. It
is the only unit of the Czech army thus far that is fully
integrated into NATO's rapid reaction forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
