<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMIKE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carmike CFO steps down
 &HT;    By Christopher Seward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Carmike Cinemas Inc. announced Friday that Chief
Financial Officer John O. Barwick, who has been with the company
for 22 years, is resigning.
</P>
<P>
   Barwick said he plans to focus on other business activities. The
company has not named a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is difficult to leave something that I have been a
part of for so long, it is time to take a new direction,'' Barwick
said. He also resigned as treasurer and senior vice president of
finance.
</P>
<P>
   Carmike's stock closed down 50 cents Friday at $16. The stock is
down 21 percent year to date and well off its 52-week high of
$33.18 3/4, set in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company is one of the nation's largest movie theater
operators, with 2,752 screens at 488 locations in 36 states. But it
has been hurt by lower attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Carmike said it expects to suffer in the first
quarter of 1999, but the second quarter should get a boost from the
release of ``Star Wars, Episode I Phantom Menace,'' which is the
latest in the ``Star Wars'' series.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter ended Dec. 31, the company reported a
loss of $43.6 million, or $3.87 per share, after restructuring
charges totaling $73 million.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber analyst Christopher Dixon says Barwick's departure
should not have a major impact on the company's direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmike certainly has a very strong management team going
forward,'' Dixon said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's basic strategy is to serve ``secondary markets,''
or cities of 75,000 to 200,000 population. Its multiplex theaters
consist of 15 or 16 screens vs. the giant theaters of as many as 30
screens rising in larger cities.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
