<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-TEMPLE-KENT-     03-12 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-TEMPLE-KENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADLEY OVERCOMES INJURY TO LEAD DEFEAT OF KENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Temple coach John Chaney wasn't going to play Quincy
Wadley, the junior guard who hasn't been able to touch a basketball
with his left hand for the last two weeks without feeling
breath-stealing pain, the result of a deep bruise he sustained
against the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   What changed Chaney's mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept beating my ear to death,'' Chaney said after Temple's
61-54 win over Kent State University, the kind of smallish team
Chaney said he dreads playing.
</P>
<P>
   When Chaney finally relented and inserted Wadley into the game
90 seconds into the second half, Temple led by only 4, 31-27.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Owls guard Rasheed Brokenborough had given up on seeing
Wadley on the floor. ``Nobody knew he would play,'' Brokenborough
said. ``Coach wouldn't let him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quincy went over to our trainer, asked him to tell the coach
that he was all right to play. Then he went to Coach and said,
`Coach, this is our last game of the year if we lose. If I get
hurt, I'll have all summer to heal.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it make a difference he was in the game? We were up by 4
when he came in. The next time I looked up at the clock, we were up
by 15.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wadley hitting his first shot, a 3-pointer, and flummoxing
Kent with his harassing defense, the Owls pulled away with a 17-2
run in which the Golden Flashes scored just one basket in a
five-minute stretch. ``He was everywhere, man,'' Chaney said of
Wadley. ``He was like one of them (Kent guards). A little
leprechaun.
</P>
<P>
   Wadley said the pain was tolerable. ``It feels all right,'' he
said, ``except when there's contact. But I just had to suck it up
and play through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   During Temple's run, Kent turned the ball over three times and
had a shot blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a big impact in our zone,'' said Brokenborough, who
matched fellow guard Pepe Sanchez for a game-high 15 points, while
grabbing seven rebounds in 39 minutes, one fewer than Sanchez
played in a turnover-free wire-to-wire performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the back of our zone, and could react to their
guards quicker than our big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent State coach Gary Waters, whose Mid-American Conference
champions lost in their first-ever tournament visit, said that
Wadley's play ended the hopes of the 11th-seeded Golden Flashes
meeting in-state rival Cincinnati in a second-round game Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put pressure on us at the right time in their zone, and I
thought it took us out of the things we needed to do,'' Waters
said. ``They do such a good job of helping down inside that it's
really hard to score in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent trailed by only 4 at the half, 31-27, as guard Andrew
Mitchell hit all three of his 3-point attempts, including one at
the buzzer. But Nate Meers, the team's most dependable long-range
scorer, couldn't shake a shooting slump (1 for 15 from behind the
arc in three games) until he made three shots in the last 2:27. And
freshman Trevor Huffman, the team's top scorer off the bench, had a
sprained ankle and was scoreless in his seven minutes of action.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the third time in the last five years, the Owls will be
facing the Bearcats. In each of their previous two meetings, they
were bounced from the tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Brokenborough is the only Owls player still on the roster from
the last time Cincinnati eliminated them, in Orlando, and he wasn't
eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was Prop 48, man,'' Brokenborough said. ``I could have gone
to the game. There was a school raffle to go there, and I won it,
but Coach didn't want me to go. He didn't want anybody to say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokenborough said he didn't think Chaney would use history as a
motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't ever use anything as a motivator,'' Brokenborough
said. ``He tells us what we've got to do. He knows our defense is
going to keep us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Brokenborough said, this Cincinnati team doesn't have
the shooters that its predecessors did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what you say,'' Chaney said when asked about the
Bearcats. ``But they'll find a way to shoot over us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadley said his hand hurt most when he dived on the floor after
a loose ball. He also accused a Kent player of trying to hurt him
deliberately. He wouldn't name the player, but he threw a nasty
elbow at Kent forward Geoffrey Vaughn that led to some serious face
time before referees intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to,'' he said. ``I had to protect myself. I'm not out to
hurt anyone intentionally, but when somebody is trying to hurt me,
he's telling me, `I'm going to do such-and-such to your hand,' I've
got to do something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even have the basketball. There was no reason for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for at least another game, the basketball still belongs to
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tough guys,'' Chaney said of Cincinnati. ``They play
tough, with a confidence bordering on arrogance. But our chances of
winning that game are a lot better than winning against Kent State,
playing against the little guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
