<HEADLINE>
CALHOUN FIGHTING STOMACH VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ First, a coaching update: University of Connecticut
coach Jim Calhoun is expected to be on the sideline Saturday when
the top-seeded, third-ranked Huskies (29-2) face ninth-seeded,
25th-ranked New Mexico (25-8) in the second round of the NCAA
Tournament West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, who sat out UConn's first-round victory over Texas-San
Antonio Thursday night because of a stomach virus, attended the
team's morning practice but returned to his hotel afterward without
speaking to the media.
</P>
<P>
   In a taped interview conducted at McNichols Arena after the
practice, Calhoun said aside from being fatigued from medication,
he felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Saturday's contest, he said, ``I just need to get
more rest, and I will probably get another shot (Friday night) but
I 100 percent plan to be there when we face a very good New Mexico
basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   As for New Mexico, Lobos coach Dave Bliss said Friday he saw
UConn's victory over St. John's in the Big East tournament
championship game, and added the Huskies' efforts in the first two
minutes made him sick to his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known at that time we would face them in the NCAA
Tournament I would have thrown up right there,'' said Bliss, whose
team defeated Missouri, 61-59, in the first round. Friday he
rendered unyielding praise for the tem that stands in the way of
the Lobos' first trip to the Sweet 16 since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a difficult task for us,'' said Bliss. ``Connecticut
is arguably one of the best teams in the nation,'' said Bliss.
``They have high-profile players and are on a mission to accomplish
that which a lot of good teams try and accomplish at this time of
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut is without question the most formidable opponent New
Mexico has faced. The Lobos lost to Western Athletic Conference
opponent Utah three times and also suffered setbacks to Washington,
Texas-El Paso, and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they feature two of the best players in the nation in
center Kenny Thomas (18.5 points per game, 9.9 rebounds) and guard
Lamont Long (16.9, 6.5). The latter hit a pull-up jump shot with
6.1 seconds left to lift the Lobos past Missouri. The former, a
potential NBA lottery pick, is very difficult to defend one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of similarities of certain people in the Big
East,'' said UConn associate coach Dave Leitao. ``He can take you
outside and face-you up like (Notre Dame forward) Troy Murphy does.
He has a post game that's extremely effective like (Miami forward)
Tim James does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presents a real prowess, because if it was one thing, if he
were a back-to-the-basket guy, we could prepare for that. But if we
stop that he has an answer. He's going to face-you up and take you
outside, so we really have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Leitao said UConn's interior players Kevin Freeman and Jake
Voskuhl will be key against Thomas. The latter had four of UConn's
10 blocks against UTSA. ``Interior defense has been their
specialty, especially Jake,'' he said. ``They take it as a
challenge, whether it's a Thomas or a James or a Murphy, they zero
in on how best to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten Huskies played against Texas-San Antonio, eight 17 minutes
or more. UConn's depth and fast-break attack wore down the pesky
Roadrunners, particularly in the second half, and it will try to do
the same against New Mexico, which relies heavily on its starting
lineup (four of its five starters average at least 33 minutes a
game).
</P>
<P>
   ``We know their backcourt can definitely shoot the ball,'' said
UConn guard Khalid El-Amin. ``We just figure if we get our press
going early and get the ball out of their hands _ and get the
forwards bringing up the ball and keep it out of their guards'
hands _ that will work into our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-seed Arkansas (23-10) will meet No. 5 seed Iowa (19-9) in
the other second-round game in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas will try to wear down Iowa with its athleticism and
3-point shooting. Iowa is riding an emotional wave as it tries to
extend the career of coach Tom Davis, whose contract is not being
renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has repeatedly said he hasn't had time to think about his
final game with the Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope it lasts, but you know it could end any time,'' Davis
said Friday. ``You know the end is near and you just don't know how
and when.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, which beat Alabama-Birmingham, 77-64, Thursday, also likes
to run and press. But the Hawkeyes will probably try to slow the
tempo down a little after the Razorbacks' 94-80 win over a Siena
team that tried to run with Arkansas in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be in a street fight with (Arkansas coach)
Nolan Richardson,'' said Iowa forward Jess Settles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
