<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOPE-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISTFUL CLINTON DEDICATES BOYHOOD HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark.)  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPE, Ark. _ President Clinton took a sentimental journey to one
of his boyhood homes here Friday, but a driving rain and a chilly
wind dampened the turnout and cast a dispirited pall over the
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain makes this day more poignant for me,'' the president
said as he stood under a tent in front of the modest white
clapboard house where he lived until he was 4. He did not explain
that remark, but his comments were filled with references to family
and old friends that seemed melancholy and reflected a sense of
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember throwing a pocketknife into the ground on that
backyard I shared with my friend Vince Foster,'' Clinton said,
invoking the name of the boyhood friend who later, as Clinton's
White House counsel, committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching the old telephone when it rang, always
hoping that it was Mother calling from New Orleans,'' Clinton said.
After he was born, his mother left him here for two years with her
parents while she went to train as a nurse-anesthetist in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to take special meaning from a conversation he
recalled having with his late Uncle Buddy, who was having a hard
time coping when his wife developed Alzheimer's disease. It is
hard, the uncle had said, ``but I signed on for the whole load, and
most of it's been pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rain soaked the crowd of a couple of hundred of Clinton's
most stalwart supporters, and bounced off several empty folding
metal chairs, Clinton added: ``In this town, from my family and
friends, that's what I learned _ to sign on for the whole load.
Though far from perfect, I have tried to do just that for my family
and my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here alone _ Mrs. Clinton stayed in Washington _ to
dedicate his home, called the ``Clinton birthplace'' although he
was actually born in a hospital. The dedication was to be held last
fall, but Clinton's impeachment hearings in the House interfered
with the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton was sending a message about loyalty in the aftermath
of his impeachment and his admission that he lied about having an
affair with a White House intern, a few of those who have known him
a long time responded.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Thompson, 49, an optometrist who has known Clinton since
high school, said in an interview: ``In my life, my family and my
friends _ a lot of them have disappointed me. But when you're
family and friends, we try to stick together so we can get over it.
And I feel like I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of his oldest confidants, Thomas F. McLarty III, a
boyhood chum who served as his first chief of staff in the White
House, said: ``You feel a sense of disappointment, but growing up
you're taught to support your friends in good times and bad. I
think he's paid a heavy price personally, certainly with his
family, but I think he's accepted full responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But many people declined to comment after the brief ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Since his 1992 campaign for president, Clinton has mythologized
Hope in the Lincoln tradition of humble origins, and he has used
this tiny town in southwest Arkansas as a personal touchstone. He
stood Friday before a banner proclaiming ``I still believe in a
place called Hope'' and listened to a chorus of children sing a
hymn to him with that refrain.
</P>
<P>
   The house has been restored and was opened to the public on June
1, 1997. It was stocked with '50s-era furnishings and a few old
photos of Clinton. The only item that Clinton actually owned that
is on display is a book called ``The Kitten's Surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the timing of the dedication Friday, Beckie Moore, executive
director of the Clinton Birthplace Foundation Inc., said: ``This
was the first time he was able to arrive in Hope for a happy
occasion. He's returned to Hope four times _ three times for a
funeral and once when one of his relatives was very sick.''
</P>
<P>
   He had also scheduled four fund-raising events in the area, two
Friday night and two on Saturday night in Little Rock.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The foundation, begun in 1993, had a goal of raising $1.5
million for the restoration but has raised about $900,000. The
Arkansas Legislature earlier this week rejected a bill allocating
$500,000 for the project, apparently because of an unrelated
budgetary argument.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the contributions to the foundation, which is
tax-exempt, have come from unusual sources. These include Nina Wang
of Hong Kong, reputed to be Asia's richest woman with an estimated
worth of $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wang reportedly gave $50,000 for the Clinton birthplace at
the behest of Mark Middleton, a former White House special
assistant who lost his access to the White House in 1995 after
allegations that he had improperly used the White House restaurant
to entertain business clients. Middleton was part of a network in
Little Rock that aggressively solicited Asian business for Arkansas
when Clinton was governor and became embroiled in the controversy
over campaign donations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After his sentimental journey through Hope, and a stop by his
mother's gravesite on his way out of town, Clinton was headed over
the Arkansas border into the Texas half of Texarkana. There, he
planned to help Rep. Max Sandlin, a second-term Democrat, raise
more than half a million dollars at a $100-a-person reception and a
$1,000-a-person dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The host of the dinner was Truman Arnold, the Texas oil magnate
and former finance chairman of the Democratic National Committee.
Arnold left the committee after suggesting it publish a brochure
outlining how much access financial contributors would receive to
the White House in exchange for donations of certain amounts.
Clinton planned to spend Friday night at Arnold's home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
