<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACKER HAS NCAA DYNASTY OF HIS OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Packer's first Final Four championship game also was John
Wooden's last. As it happened, that March day in 1975 turned out to
be a particularly meaningful one for both men.
</P>
<P>
   In defeating Kentucky, the Wizard of Westwood won his final NCAA
title as coach at UCLA. The game marked the end of college
basketball's greatest dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Packer began his own amazing streak that day, however; this year
he will call his 25th consecutive NCAA men's basketball
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden's finale, Packer said, ``was special in the history of
college basketball.'' But, he added, many other championships in
the last quarter-century have stood out as he has watched from his
seat at center court.
</P>
<P>
   Villanova coach ``Rollie Massimino's upset win over Georgetown
\Rin 1985\S,'' Packer said, was equally special. North Carolina
State coach ``Jimmy Valvano's win \Rover Houston in 1983\S,'' was
another.
</P>
<P>
   One game sticks out for an entirely different reason. That was
the Indiana-North Carolina final in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember walking into the arena in Philadelphia,'' Packer
recalled, ``and someone telling me that President Reagan had been
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Which just goes to show that if you hang around the gym as long
as Packer has, you can put even a simple game like basketball into
a context of historic importance.
</P>
<P>
   Packer's context dates to his days on the court when he was a
star guard at Wake Forest. He played in the 1962 Final Four, where
Wake Forest fell in the semifinals to an Ohio State squad led by
John Havlicek and Jerry Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Not many basketball fans watching CBS' tip-to-buzzer coverage
this weekend and next will remember Packer the player, but they'll
surely recognize Billy the broadcaster. Having worked the
tournament, both for NBC and CBS, with announcers such as Curt
Gowdy, Dick Enberg, Gary Bender, Brent Musburger and, now, Jim
Nantz, Packer is an institution, even if he doesn't see himself
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think they are the game, that they're the story,''
he observed. ``I get a kick out of that. When I'm not broadcasting
the NCAA Tournament anymore, there still will be a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Packer said he has never been comfortable being the star of the
show. He recalled the time he spent on air with Enberg and former
Marquette coach Al McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point where we were bigger than the game,'' he
said. ``I would rather it be like three good referees, where some
fan says, `Man, that was a great game.' Then the other guy asks,
`Who were the refs?' And his response is, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Packer hardly shrinks from stating his views, however, and that
has always gotten him his fair share of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have opinions,'' he stated. ``It's because of my
position. And I do feel I'm knowledgeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Packer is confident enough, or maybe just honest enough, to
admit that he doesn't have the game plan on every one of the 64
teams entering the annual madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not smart enough to really sit down and watch tapes of a
hundreddifferent teams,'' he said. ``You do your research on the
games you're assigned to.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament has changed plenty over the years, evolving into
college sports' biggest event, one that has earned the moniker
March Madness. Asked to name the most significant changes to the
tournament in the past 25 years, Packer cites the expansion of the
field to 64 teams and the balancing of tournament brackets.
</P>
<P>
   A more subtle, but no less significant factor, he added, was the
increased racial integration of teams in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, ``A major talent pool \RAfrican-American
players\S had been prevented from participating,'' Packer said.
``We're not talking about a hundred years ago, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Packer hasn't been around for quite a century, but he is old
enough and experienced enough to have been involved in the
desegregation of college basketball in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Such personal experience is a big piece of the Packer package,
and is reflected in his philosophy of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say what you see,'' he said, ``and have as much research and
background available that you can tie things together.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get older,'' he adds, ``you do get a little bit of
perspective.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
