<SLUG> BC-BKC-EAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN LOSS BASICALLY POINTLESS
</HEADLINE>
 REGION-WISCONSIN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ And here's a partial score from the East
Regional: Southwest Missouri State 43, Wisconsin 32.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, wait a minute. Hold it. That's a ``final'' score.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, fifth-seeded Wisconsin scored the fewest points in half
a century of NCAA Tournament play. The 43-32 victory in an East
Region first-round contest puts the 12th-seeded Bears (21-10) into
Sunday's second round against Tennessee, a 62-52 winner over
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers shot 25.5 percent from the field, making 12 field
goals in 47 attempts. Their 32 points was the fewest since Oregon
State's 55-30 loss to Oklahoma State in the 1949 national
semifinals. Wisconsin's total was the lowest in NCAA Tournament
history for a first or second-round game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very embarrassed,'' Wisconsin coach Dick Bennett said.
``Our February has been like this; we've seen this before. I hoped
and prayed it wouldn't happen on a day like this. Now we've got to
live with this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the fewest points by a Badgers' team since 1948. A new
fight song could be in the works: Off Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Mason, the Badgers' leading scorer, had 11 points on
4-of-12 shooting; the Badgers' perimeter players were a combined
5-for-27. Mason was badgered most of the game by Southwest Missouri
State's Ken Stringer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my defense was OK on him,'' said Stringer, prone on
the locker room floor with an ice bag on his lower back to treat a
bruise. ``I didn't play up to my full potential. I just wanted to
make him work for his shots. I guess I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State won despite scoring a season-low. The
Bears shot 39.4 percent, but that was good enough when the
opposition couldn't hit water if it fell out of the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an offensive player, but when you start coaching, you
emphasize what you didn't do well as a player,'' Southwest Missouri
State coach Steve Alford said. ``We followed our defensive game
plan to an absolute T.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears took control late in the first half. Back-to-back
3-pointers by Ryan Bettenhausen and Allen Phillips helped provide a
21-12 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Badgers scored a season-low 12 first-half points, but in a
two-minute period of the second half, Wisconsin scored seven points
on three possessions to pull to within 28-22 with 12:34 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But for the rest of the game, the Badgers missed 13 of their
final 17 shots. And two of their field goals came in the final
minute after the Bears' defense had gone into hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really embarrassed,'' Wisconsin center Charlie Wills
said, noting the Bears' 35-18 rebounding edge. ``We got beat to
loose balls and it didn't feel like we were aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for defense, embarrassment for the losing coach and
humor for the winning coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we would have focused more on the defensive end,''
Alford said.
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding. Kind of like someone who tries to pass off the
final as a halftime score. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
