<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO TECHNOLOGY: VARIABLE TRANSMISSION WINS NEW DISCIPLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (bl)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ While driving the Honda Civic HX coupe, one
immediately senses that something is missing. Step hard on the
accelerator when a stoplight turns green, or press the pedal to the
floor to pass on a freeway, and there is no jerk as the
transmission shifts gears. Nor does the sound of the engine rise
just before a shift, along with its speed, and then fall off. The
tachometer's needle holds steady.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the car feels as though its transmission is not shifting
at all.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the Civic HX has a continuously variable
transmission, or CVT, the only one currently available on a
production model in the United States. It will certainly not be the
last.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Ford Motor Co. and ZF Friedrichshafen AG, the German
company that is Europe's largest supplier of transmissions,
announced a joint venture that is expected to eventually produce a
million CVTs a year at a Ford transmission plant in Batavia, Ohio.
The transmissions will show up in cars from Ford and from other
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of CVTs is simple. Aside from their smoothness, they
allow an engine to operate at optimal efficiency nearly all the
time, improving economy and saving wear and tear. They offer the
convenience of an automatic transmission with the better mileage of
a manual shift. Indeed, the Civic HX has been the only car without
a stick shift to earn a place on the Environmental Protection
Agency's list of the 10 mileage leaders, achieving a rating of 34
miles a gallon in the city and 38 on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer gets improved fuel economy because the vehicle
spends more time in areas of good efficiency,'' said Gordon Willis,
Ford's chief engineer for automatic transmissions. Although
gasoline prices are now around their all-time lows, Willis
acknowledges that fuel economy will matter again someday. And
global giants like Ford are already building plenty of cars for
countries where fuel economy is indeed important because gasoline
is very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and ZF expect the new CVT they will produce in Ohio to
raise fuel economy by 10 to 15 percent. In addition to better
mileage, the customer has the benefit of feeling and hearing no
gear changes. ``Every transmission causes you to feel the gear
change to some degree, and customers say they would rather not feel
those events,'' Willis said. ``They worry about those events if
they feel they are not always shifting exactly the same _ if it
shifts different today than it did yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, while a driver perceives that a CVT-equipped car is not
shifting at all, it is actually shifting much of the time, though
not in the specific increments of a traditional transmission.
Shifts on a car with an automatic transmission are based on
specific ratios between the speed of the engine and the speed of
the vehicle. First gear is one ratio, and second, third and fourth
gears are others; there are no possible settings between the gears.
As a result, the engine is sometimes operating extremely
efficiently, and sometimes quite inefficiently.
</P>
<P>
   But a CVT shifts continuously as the engine speed and vehicle
speed change, allowing an infinite number of possible gear ratios.
ZF executives say this should result in less strain on the engine
and longer life for other vehicle components.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's CVT works like the gearing on the two sprocket rings of
a 10-speed bicycle. Computerized sensors constantly adjust the
diameters of pulleys _ the drive pulley from the engine and the
driven pulley that sends power to the wheels _ at each end of a
steel drive belt, pushing the belt closer or farther away from the
center of each pulley. Every possible position of the belt on the
two pulleys represents a gear ratio. On acceleration, for instance,
the drive pulley will have a narrow diameter for more torque, like
a low gear. At cruising speed, the drive pulley widens and acts
like a high gear.
</P>
<P>
   CVTs are not new. The earliest automobiles operated on a similar
principle, and a Dutch car, the DAF, had a CVT in the years after
World War II, using sturdy drive belts developed by Van Doorne's
Transmissie of the Netherlands for such a purpose. In the United
States, Subaru offered a CVT on its Justy subcompact in the early
1990s. And they are used in foreign markets on several Nissan
models, including the diesel Micra sold in Europe; on the Microcar
of France, and on other vehicles. Snowmobiles have always used CVTs
to transfer power from their high-revving, low-torque engines.
</P>
<P>
   But while CVTs have been mainly used in small cars with small
engines, that seems likely to change. The University of Michigan's
Delphi studies on future automotive trends suggest rapid growth for
CVTs in the next 5 to 10 years because of increased pressure on
automakers to raise fuel economy, in part because they are selling
so many low-mileage vehicles, which lowers their corporate
fuel-economy averages.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford and ZF joint venture is a big step toward the
proliferation of CVTs. The first transmission from that venture
will make its debut on a 2002 model; company officials said that
would not be a Ford product, though Ford will not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Technical issues are the focus of much attention. Improved
materials, larger belts and better control systems should help make
CVTs practical with larger engines. ZF has introduced a CVT aimed
at engines of up to 3 liters. And Nissan is working on what it
calls a toroidal CVT, which does not use belts. That CVT has been
tested with a 300-horsepower engine.
</P>
<P>
   Low volume and limited availability of parts have make CVTs
expensive to produce, though Willis of Ford predicts that they
could ultimately prove cheaper than traditional automatic
transmissions as production increases, because they contain fewer
parts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
