<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8706 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV14-B     03-12 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV14-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOTS AND WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 14, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nowhere are the intimate relations between economics and the
real world more clearly glimpsed than in measurement _ beginning
with the measurement of prices. Prices are no simple matter, as
Andrew Court found out when in 1938 he tried to get a handle on the
changing cost of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Court worked for the Automobile Manufactuers Association. The
Depression was grinding on. A clamor had arisen to force General
Motors to drop its prices whenever sales lagged, in order to keep
production and employment constant. To reformers there seemed to be
plenty of room to cut. Offical indexes showed that prices had risen
45 percent between 1925 and 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Court knew that quality was changing. This was the heyday of
marketing wizard Alfred Sloan, after all. Not only was GM offering
``a price for every pocketbook'' (a strategically differentiated
line,) but new features were being added to all cars every year:
safety glass, automatic transmissions, more powerful and reliable
engines and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Court knew, too, that the Bureau of Labor Statisics made some
attempt to compare the underlying characteristics of farm tractors
and trucks in order to get a better idea of what was quality change
and what was ``pure'' price change. But when it came to cars, they
didn't even try; they simply reported the average list prices of
the brand name.
</P>
<P>
   So he devised a method he called ``hedonic'' pricing, a terrible
name for characteristics-based indexes. He zeroed in on particular
attributes of cars _ their speed, safety, window area, seat width,
and so on _ in order to get a standardized measure of the pleasure
that they yielded their users. Then he divided the price per
vehicle by its ``hedonic content.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, he found that prices for something like a
``standard auto'' actually had decreased by 55 percent in those ten
years. (On the same basis, computation prices today fall as much in
a single year, even though the price of the computer itself stays
more or less the same.) It was industrial work, but enough to blunt
the initiative against GM. (For a full account, see Ernest
Berndt's, ``The Practice of Econometrics: Classic and
Contemporary,'' from which this brief account is drawn.
</P>
<P>
   And there the matter rested until 1960, when a 30-year-old
immigrant economist named Zvi Griliches (pronounced GRI-lick-es)
picked it up.
</P>
<P>
   Griliches was interested in hybrid corn _ not unreasonably,
coonsidering that the ``green revolution'' had begun to increase
yields dramatically. His 1957 dissertation, subtitled ``An
exploration of the economics of technical change,'' had traced the
rate of adoption of new varieties of corn in various states. By
addressing the econonomic units side-by-side, there emerged a
yardstick for gauging ``what spills over to whom'' (as economist
Ariel Pakes puts it) _ and therefore a means of calculating rates
of return to investments in research and development.
</P>
<P>
   But in order to get out of the figures on seed prices, crop
yield and cash prices as much information as were in them, it was
necessary to address the same problems for hybrid corn _ as well as
arable land, fertilizer, and farm implements _ as Andrew Court had
tinkered with for cars. Indeed, productivity measurement of every
sort depended upon reliable price indexes.
</P>
<P>
   And so a fully-trained first-rate economic mind went to work for
the first time on hedonic pricing _ as it happened, in the context
of the automotive industry itself. Griliches had signed on to the
Stigler Commission, which was then investigating government price
indexes for the US Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Using modern statistical methods, Griliches built the simple
techniques of adjusting for quality change into a powerful tool for
interrogating the economy about almost anything under the sun: real
estate prices, wages and how education, environmental amenities,
new products, and so on, affect them. Strictly speaking, he did not
invent a whole new branch of research on price and quality,
measurement don Robery Lipsey of Queens College says, but ``he was
certainly was the crucial entrepreneur.''
</P>
<P>
   So if these topics interest you _ if you like to think about
productivity and hear others talk about it _ there was no better
place on earth for you last Saturday than a hotel meeting room in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the cream of the world's measurement community gathered
there, ostensibly to commemorate Griliches' 20 years as director of
the National Bureau of Economic research program on Productivity
and Technical Change.
</P>
<P>
   In fact they were saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Griliches was just 11 years old when Germans occupying Lithuania
herded his family into the Kaunas ghetto. In 1944, he and his
father were sent to Dachau. He survived; his father didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Orphaned, Griliches made his way to Israel, via Cyprus, in 1947.
By night he taught himself English and math; by day he worked on a
series of kibbutzim. In 1951 he won a scholarship to the University
of California at Berkeley _ in agricultural economics, because it
was deemed essential.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954 he had moved to the hotbed of high-tech methods that was
the University of Chicago in those days. His adviser: the great
agricultural economist Theodore Schultz, who in 1979 was awarded
the Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   It was during 15 years at the University of Chicago that
Griliches developed his distinctive style of trying to do
measurement ``right,'' or at least better than it was being done at
the time. He collaborated extensively; alongside his friend Dale
Jorgeson, he picked a fight with theorists of growth over
measurement that resonates to the present day. He married; Diane
Asseo Griliches provided, he says, ``the warmth, the stable home
base and the emotional support'' that enabled the work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he joined Jorgenson, Kenneth Arrow, and Martin
Feldstein in the rescue mission that eventually returned the
embattled economics department of Harvard University to a place
near the top of the heap. His first student was the young Robert
Barro (only the second-best conservative economist he taught, says
Griliches; at Chicago he had given a grade of C to the
undergraduate Robert Lucas _ a future Nobelist). He worked closely
as well with young radicals like Stephen Marglin, Samuel Bowles,
and Herbert Gintes.
</P>
<P>
   With Gary Chamberlin, he showed how the idea of human capital
could be used to assess the effect of schooling on the labor force.
Then a trio of remarkable students _ Mark Schankerman, Manuel
Trajjtenberg, and Pakes _ returned him to the topic of technical
change, just in time for the beginning of the productivity slowdown
of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   By 1980, Feldstein had taken charge of the National Bureau of
Economic Research; he was intent on turning it into the nation's
premier (virtual) laboratory of applied economics. He asked
Griliches to tackle the productivity slowdown. Couldn't be done,
said Griliches, who narrowed the topic and took the job anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The result was an explosion of exciting new work on the
economics of the high-tech age. The work on spillovers and
characteristic-based models found a whole new generation of
students eager to devise new models and apply policy issues. Do
patent suits distort research incentives? Can patent citations and
firms' market value be used as a measure of the value of the stock
of knowledge? Do network effects drive the rate of diffusion of new
drugs? These were some of the topics Griliches' students brought to
their meeting last week.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, because of shifts in the direction that took place
during the 1980s, an interest in technical change was returned to
economics' center ring. Griliches abundance of deep, sustained,
high-quality work on the topic made him an odds-on favorite in the
betting for a Nobel Prize sometime in in the next few years _
perhaps with his colleague Jorgenson, or Columbia University
theorist Kelvin Lancaster.
</P>
<P>
   There is just one problem. Last summer Griliches took a
persistent itch to his doctor _ and discovered he had pancreatic
cancer. As MIT's Frank Fischer said, presiding over a poignant
dinner last week, ``What Dachau couldn't accomplish, the cancer
may.''
</P>
<P>
   So his students took no chances. They rallied and presented him
with a survey of the field in his 67th year. Stanford's Tim
Bresnahancq, the government's chief economist in its case against
Microsoft, said, ``So, Zvi, what do you think now of this field
that you made?'' Schankerman put aside his otherwise technical
paper to say, ``You have given us roots _ and wings.'' Some years
ago, the historian Jurg Niehans noted that ``Histories of economic
doctrines often convey the notion that the past was an age of
giants, shaking the world with their deeds, and the present is an
age of pygmies engaged in agitated babble.'' Nothing, of course,
could be farther from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century has been the golden age of economics _
Griliches is a prime example of why. From one perspective, anyway,
it almost doesn't matter what happens now. Economics has few other
communities as deeply rooted as this one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
