<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trump Superspeedway planned for New York area
 &HT;    By Al Levine and Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Real estate developer Donald Trump and Bill France,
chairman and chief executive officer of the International Speedway
Corporation, revealed plans Friday to build a superspeedway in the
New York area, with an exact site to be chosen by summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big day for either New York, New Jersey or
Connecticut,'' Trump said. ``We are looking at five sites and we'll
probably have another five. A final decision on one will be made in
the next couple of months. In eight to 12 weeks, we'll have a
pretty good idea where it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump Superspeedway would have a minimum of 75,000 seats, at
least a one-mile track and a road course on about 750 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Bruton Smith, who owns Atlanta Motor Speedway and tracks in
Charlotte, Texas, California, Las Vegas and Bristol, Tenn., offered
a whimsical reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought maybe in 15 years I would want to build a speedway
around Manhattan,'' Smith said. ``That way you'd already have eight
million people in the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith once tried to buy $60 million of land on Long Island to
build a speedway but ran into environmental problems. A plan to
build a track in New Jersey was undone by asbestos. ``The first bid
for moving the asbestos was $5 million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's all for stock car racing moving closer to the world's
biggest market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be great for NASCAR,'' Smith said. ``I'm for anything
that pushes our sport on up the ladder. I think you've got two
great partners there. If anybody can get it done, I think they can.
They'll face numerous environmental and bureaucratic problems in
that part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   B. JONES REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Buckshot Jones of Tucker qualified for his first Winston
Cup race in last week's Las Vegas 400, but setup problems left him
with a 29th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones came to Atlanta Motor Speedway on Friday armed with a
Pontiac built by Richard Childress Racing.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start in the first practice _ Jones was
eighth-slowest in the morning session _ he rebounded in the second.
He had the 18th-fastest average speed in the second practice, and
then turned in the seventh-best qualifying speed, 192.654 mph.
He'll start inside the fourth row in Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just seemed to flow,'' Jones said. ``I think it's
the new chassis, but it's the guys on the crew, too. (Crew chief
Tony) Barclay has a really good setup for here. It feels awesome to
come home and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   BAIRD WINS ARCA EVENT
</P>
<P>
   Bill Baird of Sturgis, Ky., pushed his No. 52 Chevrolet in front
of Darrell Lanigan's No. 29 Ford on a one-lap shootout to win the
EasyCare 300, his first ARCA series victory. The last-lap finish
was set up when leader Mike Swaim Jr. hit the wall coming out of
turn four with seven laps to go, bringing out a caution. Swaim was
unhurt but was transported to Atlanta Medical Center for a
precautionary examination. Baird was the ARCA rookie of the year in
1998, fourth in points, but without a victory.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RUN FOR THE ROSES
</P>
<P>
   The red flying horse on Jeremy Mayfield's No. 12 Ford Taurus
will be replaced by a thoroughbred for the California 500 May 2 at
Fontana, Calif., in honor of the 125th Kentucky Derby. The Derby
will be run the day before at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of commemorative cars,'' Mayfield said,
``everything from an Elvis car to a Batman car. But nothing is
cooler than me, being from Kentucky, being in a Kentucky Derby
car.'' The announcement was made concurrently by Mayfield's team,
Churchill Downs and Action Performance, which manufactures model
cars. Think this has anything to do with selling more souvenirs?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
