<SLUG> BC-AIR-FARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE AIRLINES' FARE INCREASES MAY BE SHORT-LIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five of the country's major airlines raised their fares Thursday
and Friday, though the increase could be short-lived if three other
carriers do not match them.
</P>
<P>
   News of the fare increase sent some airline stocks soaring
Friday on a day when they normally might have fallen because of a
jump in the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines rose $3.50 to close at $64; the UAL Corp., the
parent of United Airlines, rose $2.0625 to close at $67.0625; and
the AMR Corp., which owns American Airlines, closed at $58 a share,
up $2.
</P>
<P>
   United began the price increase on Thursday evening, according
to Susan Donofrio, an airline analyst with BT Alex Brown in New
York. The carrier raised fares 1 percent for unrestricted tickets
designed for business travelers and 3 percent on advance-purchase
tickets favored by vacationers. United was then matched by Delta
and America West Airlines, followed by Continental Airlines and
American.
</P>
<P>
   For the increase to hold, Northwest Airlines, Trans World
Airlines and US Airways would also have to go along. Jon Austin, a
spokesman for Northwest, which is the country's fourth-largest
airline and has undermined many attempted fare increases in the
last year, declined to comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If it holds, the fare hike would be the second this year. In
early February, the airlines raised fares 2 percent for business
travelers and 4 percent for leisure tickets. Up until then, the
industry had not raised prices in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines have seen their revenues slide so far this
year after four straight years of record profits. But a fare
increase may be hard to maintain because many carriers are planning
to expand their fleets, raising fears of overcapacity.
</P>
<P>
   Fares between the United States and Europe have already fallen
steeply because many carriers have redeployed their planes from
Asia to transatlantic routes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
