A8709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOODYS-NYT &LR;      03-12 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOODYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION OF MOODY'S IS ENDED BY JUSTICE DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Justice Department has ended an investigation without
finding anti-competitive practices at Moody's Investors Services
Inc., the credit rating agency that is a subsidiary of the Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The government's investigation of Moody's, part of a
wide-ranging investigation into charges of anti-competitive
practices in the bond-rating services industry, began early in
1996. It was conducted by the Justice Department's antitrust
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust investigation of the industry is still
ongoing,'' said Jennifer Rose, a Justice Department spokeswoman.
``But the Moody's part of that investigation is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Becton, a managing director and spokesman for Moody's,
said the company received a letter from Justice on Feb. 1 saying
that the investigation had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter is straightforward and to the point,'' Becton said.
``It simply said the investigation into the firm's bond-rating
practices has ended. It was a wide-ranging inquiry and we provided
them with hundreds of thousands of pages of documents, mostly in
1996. We are pleased that the Department of Justice has completed
this civil inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its inquiry, the Justice Department examined whether
Moody's used the threat of unsolicited ratings as leverage on
issuers to hire the agency to assess their credit-worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   Most bond ratings are issued with the consent of the entity
selling the bonds. The company, state or city issuing the debt pays
a fee to the credit-rating company, which then publishes a rating,
often in the form of a letter grade, for the investing public.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rating agencies have been issuing unsolicited opinions on
the credit-worthiness of borrowers for decades. Indeed, it was not
until the late 1960s that agencies, beginning with the Standard &AMP;
Poor's Corp., a unit of the McGraw-Hill Cos., and then Moody's,
began to charge issuers for their services.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began after a lawsuit was filed in November
1995 against Moody's by the Jefferson County School District, the
largest in Colorado. The suit contended that Moody's hurt the
marketability of the district's bonds by issuing a negative, and
unsolicited, report on a 1993 bond sale after the district refused
to hire Moody's.
</P>
<P>
   A motion by Moody's to dismiss the lawsuit was granted by a
Federal District judge in Colorado on April 8, 1997. That decision
is under appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Justice Department's investigation into Moody's
was reported Friday by The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
