<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, BACK IN HOPE, RECALLS HUMBLE BEGINNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPE, Ark. _ President Clinton returned to his birthplace Friday
for the dedication of his childhood home, still believing in Hope,
and hoping that Hope still believes in him.
</P>
<P>
   In the nostalgic visit, Clinton recalled his humble beginnings
in this small town that shaped his vision as president, saying at
one point, ``In many ways, I know that all I am or ever will be
came from here.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stood in driving rain on a makeshift stage just outside
the house where he lived the first four years of his life, he
recalled his childhood friend, Vincent Foster, a former White House
aide who committed suicide in 1993 and was part of an independent
counsel's investigation of Clinton's Whitewater land deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Foster was with him when he broke his leg, ``in the
first of many major mistakes I was to make in my life, jumping rope
in my cowboy boots.''
</P>
<P>
   For the president, whose signature phrase at the 1992 Democratic
convention was ``I still believe in a place called Hope,'' Friday's
visit demonstrated the strength he still draws from the state.
Several hundred people turned out in a cold, driving rain to greet
him at the Hope airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said people here stuck with me through rain or
shine,'' he said. ``Now I know it's literally true.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arkansas is also a reminder of some troubling associations
from his past, long before his relationship with former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky became public, eventually leading to his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One of his Whitewater partners, Susan McDougal, is on trial in
Little Rock. A few weeks ago, nursing home operator Juanita
Broaddrick stepped forward to allege that Clinton sexually
assaulted her more than 20 years ago when he was state attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, who frequently accompanies her husband
when he returns home, remained at the White House Friday, further
fueling speculation about strains in their marriage amid Lewinsky's
book tour and Broaddrick's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady Friday held the latest in series of meetings with
top New York Democrats about the prospects of a run in 2000 to
replace retiring Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan. She met with
Sheldon Silver, the speaker of the New York state assembly, and
Judith Hope, the state Democratic Party chair.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's press secretary, would not comment
directly on the meetings, but said the first lady's deliberations
about a Senate campaign are ``going to take some time. There is no
sense of a timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry played down Mrs. Clinton's absence from her husband's side
in Hope. She said the first lady had ``never been scheduled'' to
attend the dedication because she had expected to just be returning
from a tiring trip to Central America. Because of the recurrence of
a back injury, Berry said, Mrs. Clinton at the last minute canceled
her plans to take that trip.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, the Clintons' schedules will take them in
separate paths. The first lady will resume a busy schedule next
week with several public events in Washington, and the following
week she will travel to Tunisia, Egypt and Morocco with daughter
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the president cut short his own scheduled three-day trip
to Arkansas and Texas, where he was to stay through Sunday. White
House aides said Clinton was tired after his trip to Central
America, and wanted to return to Washington to rest up before a
busy schedule next week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dedicating his childhood home, Clinton attended a
fund-raiser for Representative Max Sandlin of Texas and Saturday
will travel to Little Rock to raise money for the Democratic
National Committee and attend a reception in honor of retired US
Senator Dale Bumpers, who spoke in defense of Clinton at the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hadn't seen his childhood house, at 117 South Hervey
St., since 1990. After living in this house, and two years at
another house in Hope, he moved with his family to Hot Springs,
Ark. Friday, he dedicated a garden at the home in honor of his
mother, Virginia Kelley, who died in 1994. Clinton's father died
three months before he was born.
</P>
<P>
   The house has been restored to its appearance in 1946, the year
Clinton was born, and a neighboring house was converted to a
visitor center. Renovations on the 2 1/2-story began in 1995 in an
effort to restore it to its likeness during Clinton's childhood.
The only original item in the house is a little golden book, titled
``The Kitten's Surprise,'' given to Clinton by a childhood friend,
Susan Cook, that sits on the top of a chest in what was Clinton's
second-floor room.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Arkansas Legislature refused to provide $500,000
to make improvements to the boyhood home, which is now a museum.
Many of the lawmakers who opposed the funding said it had nothing
to do with Clinton, but with the source of the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sort of a speed bump for us. It's not going to slow
us down,'' said Beckie Moore, executive director of the Clinton
Birthplace Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Jo Hays, a Hope resident and member of the Birthplace
Foundation Board, said that despite Clinton's problems, ``We're
proud of the president. We think that he has been a very good
president for us, economically speaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
