<SLUG> BC-LEGAL-MERGER-CANCEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FIRMS CANCEL PROPOSED MERGER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prominent New York law firms of White &AMP; Case and
Brown &AMP; Wood called off their proposed merger Friday after at least
four months of talks, saying the move was ``impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   Top partners at the two firms refused to give details of why
they had abandoned their plans for a merger that would have created
the nation's fourth-largest law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The firms issued a brief statement that said that they were
ending their talks after concluding that ``issues such as the
significant differences in capital structure of the two firms make
the merger impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers at the two firms, who would speak only on the
condition they not be named, said they were surprised by the
announcement because the talks had seemed to be moving forward.
Both firms had been studying each other's list of clients,
financial statements and other matters crucial to joining their
practices, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   For partners at White &AMP; Case, which is already the nation's
seventh-largest law firm, a merger with the smaller Brown &AMP; Wood
would have strengthened its Wall Street practice. Brown &AMP; Wood's
major clients include Merrill Lynch, Lehman Brothers and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. A merger would have given Brown &AMP; Wood a wide
global presence. White &AMP; Case has more than two dozen offices in
Europe, Asia, Latin America, the Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, one sticking point between the firms had been
their differences in profitability. According to The American
Lawyer magazine, the average profit earned by each partner at White
&AMP; Case in 1997, the most recent year available, was $625,000, while
it was $535,000 for partners at Brown &AMP; Wood.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, in what was widely viewed as an attempt to get
past that issue, Brown &AMP; Wood announced its 1998 revenue and other
information that most law firms try to keep private. The firm said
it had realized its highest revenue ever, which had pushed the
average profit for each partner up to about $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   White &AMP; Case has 848 lawyers, according to a recent survey by
The National Law Journal, while Brown &AMP; Wood has 366 lawyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
