<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Green likes Cup challenge in Busch races
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From where he sits _ on the outside pole for today's
Yellow Freight 300 at Atlanta Motor Speedway _ Jeff Green doesn't
care how many Winston Cup drivers crowd Busch series races.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a sore point lately with some Busch drivers as they've
watched a number of their own fail to qualify for events while Cup
drivers make the field.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's final round of qualifying, nine Winston Cup
drivers were in the race (four among the first 10 starters) and 19
Busch teams packed up and went home. Among those failing to
qualify: six drivers ranking in the top 20 in points, including
Chuck Bown (10th) and Jeff Purvis (12th).
</P>
<P>
   Dave Blaney, whose average start in three races is 23rd, has the
pole after qualifying at 186.755 mph. Green was just 0.017 of a
second slower but he's not crazy about his No. 32 Chevrolet just
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're as good as we need to be to win this
race,'' Green said. ``I think we've got a top-five car. It's not
good enough yet. We're out of practice (time) so we're going to
have to guess a little bit. But I've got some awful good guessers
in my corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is ninth in points, despite failing to qualify at
Rockingham. And that experience hasn't moved him to join in the
anti-Cup sentiment in the Busch garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to go home,'' he said. ``But you've got to have
your act together when you come in the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes the Cup drivers have a right to be in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Cup guys, they put their pants on just like I do and I
can beat them every week if we have the right opportunity,'' Green
said. ``When we do beat those guys, it makes you know that you've
done your job that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do make us better, they make us work harder. There are
Busch guys that are just racing four or five races a year and they
sent some people home today. People don't look at that as those
people doing anything wrong. So you can't say the Cup guys are
doing anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's brother, Mark, starts sixth in the No. 50 Chevy. He'd
like to see to a Busch version of last week's Cup race at Las Vegas
when the Burton brothers, Jeff and Ward, battled the last four
laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``David and myself once ran first and second at Myrtle Beach
coming to the checkered flag,'' Jeff said. ``Not as close a race as
it was with the Burtons, that was pretty special. I thought it'd be
awesome to do that. Hopefully, it's coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
