<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCARPOLE13-COX     03-12 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARPOLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bobby Labonte puts Pontiac on AMS pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A driver of a Pontiac hasn't won NASCAR's Winston Cup
points title since Rusty Wallace held off Dale Earnhardt in the
final race of 1989 for his only championship.
</P>
<P>
   While Sunday's Cracker Barrel Old Country Store 500 at Atlanta
Motor Speedway is only the fourth event of this year's 34-race
schedule, Pontiac appears to be making a major push toward gaining
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Pontiac charge is Bobby Labonte, who won his second
consecutive pole by covering the 1.54-mile oval of AMS in 28.437
seconds, an average speed of 194.957 mph. It was the second-fastest
qualifying mark at the track since it was reconfigured before the
`97 season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we thought we were headed (in the right) direction
all year long (in the Pontiac),'' Labonte said. ``Then they came
out with the new spoiler and air-dam rule and I think that helped
us. ... We're awfully excited. The Pontiacs aren't hurting for
anything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac put four drivers among the top 10 qualifiers for
Sunday's race. Mike Skinner was second in a Chevrolet at 194.226
mph, but rookie Tony Stewart, who pairs with Labonte on Joe Gibbs'
team, was third-fastest at 194.192.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bobby running so well, it's easier for me to come here
and have a comfortable setup,'' Stewart said. ``I try not to bother
Bobby unless I have to, but it's great to be able to share
information with him. It makes both of us better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford drivers Dale Jarrett and Jeremy Mayfield round out the top
five qualifiers, but rookie Buckshot Jones and John Andretti also
made the top 10 in Pontiacs. Chevy also has four cars in the top
10, including two-time defending Cup champion Jeff Gordon, who will
start eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Pontiac drivers led only 7 percent of nearly 10,000
laps and collected only two victories on the circuit. This year,
Pontiac has led 17.3 percent of the first 860 laps, including 71
laps led by Ward Burton in last week's Las Vegas 400.
</P>
<P>
   In the three races since the reconfiguration at AMS, the winner
hasn't started in the top 10. Labonte won in November 1997 after
starting 21st, then followed that with another victory in March
after starting 14th. Gordon started 21st in November's
rain-shortened event, but won a 25-lap shootout over Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
