<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carter's size, quickness provide Falcons more flexibility at
safety
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons went into the offseason looking to get a
little faster and a little younger in the secondary. They
accomplished both Friday, when unrestricted free-agent safety Marty
Carter signed a five-year contract worth about $15million.
</P>
<P>
   Carter led the Bears in tackles three of the past four seasons
after playing four seasons for Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   At 29, Carter is four years younger than last season's strong
safety, William White, will be later this month. In the 6-foot-1,
214-pound Carter, the Falcons get more flexibility than they had in
White. Where White left the field in passing situations last
season, Carter will be an every-down player because of his speed.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who got a $2.6million signing bonus that leaves the
Falcons $1million or less under the salary cap, couldn't be
happier.
</P>
<P>
   A native of LaGrange, he lives in Marietta in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost didn't get any sleep last night because I thought I
would wake up and find out this was a dream,'' said Carter, who had
18 tackles in the Bears' 20-13 loss in Atlanta last Nov. 22. ``It
means a lot to have the chance to play in the ultimate game with
what is basically your home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother (who lives in LaGrange) would come to Chicago for
games in the winter, and it would be so cold she would end up
watching them on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter could move to a linebacker spot in passing situations now
that linebacker Cornelius Bennett is no longer with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played both safety spots; lined up at linebacker,'' he
said. ``Just let me make plays. I'll play wherever they want me
to.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons hired Giants assistant director of media relations
Aaron Salkin, who was in New York when coach Dan Reeves was there,
to replace director of media relations Charlie Taylor, who resigned
two weeks ago. ... Linebackers Jessie Tuggle and Ben Talley,
natives of Griffin, will be honored in their hometown with a parade
at 4 p.m. today. Tuggle also will be honored before a 1 p.m. Harlem
Globetrotters game at Alexander Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
