<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MILKEN-AR     03-12 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MILKEN-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTORING THE JUNK BOND KING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14)  
 (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ There, on one stage at a conference, sat
some of the best economic minds in the nation _ Gary Becker, Nobel
laureate; Merton H. Miller, Nobel laureate; Douglass North, Nobel
laureate; Myron S. Scholes, Nobel laureate, and Michael R. Milken,
fallen financier.
</P>
<P>
   Having the dethroned junk bond king rub shoulders with Nobel
laureates was not all that incongruous. As a brochure from the
conference notes, The Wall Street Journal once described Milken as
``arguably the most important financial thinker of the century.''
Besides, it was Milken's party, and he could crow if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   The Milken Institute Global Conference, which ended on Friday,
is part of the resurrection of Milken. Since leaving prison in
1993, he has enlisted his personal fortune and wide network of
contacts in an effort to become an influential force in medical
research, education and economics.
</P>
<P>
   His Association for the Cure of Cancer of the Prostate, formed
after the disease was diagnosed in Milken, has given away $65
million, much of it from Milken himself, becoming the leading
private sponsor of prostate cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   His Milken Family Foundation, run with his brother, Lowell,
makes awards of $25,000 each to about 150 teachers annually, part
of an effort to improve education.
</P>
<P>
   And Milken, 52, barred from securities trading for life, is
rebuilding a business empire in education. His Knowledge Universe
has quietly acquired companies in businesses ranging from day care
centers to computer training, with combined revenues of $1.2
billion last year. One unit, a corporate consulting firm called
Nextera Enterprises, has filed to go public.
</P>
<P>
   The economic conference was sponsored by the Milken Institute,
his small research center. In addition to the Nobel laureates,
speakers included Gov. Gray Davis of California, Mayor Richard H.
Riordan of Los Angeles and former Rep. Lee H. Hamilton of Indiana.
Reggie Jackson, the former baseball star whom Milken enlisted to
spread cancer awareness among minorities, sat by Milken's side at
the opening dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was only a coincidence that the conference was at the
Beverly Hilton Hotel, site in the 1980s of several of Milken's
extravagant junk bond conferences, known as Predators' Balls. In a
coincidence of timing, however, the conference took place the week
when the largest and most celebrated deal Milken financed, the 1989
buyout that created RJR Nabisco, was undone by RJR's decision to
break itself apart.
</P>
<P>
   Those at the conference, at least, seemed to care little about
his past. Supporters said Milken was active in philanthropy long
before he went to jail and is spending too much time and money for
it to be a charade. Besides, they ask, what's wrong with trying to
improve one's image by doing good?
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, you don't hold it against someone for
the rest of their lives,'' said North, a professor at Washington
University in St. Louis. ``My view is he's doing generally
constructive things now, and they are worth supporting. He's using
his money more intelligently than a lot of rich people do.''
</P>
<P>
   Milken declined to be interviewed. But in a brief conversation
he discouraged any interpretation of his motives, saying of the
conference, ``It is what it is,'' and adding, ``It takes time for
people to not be emotional about things.''
</P>
<P>
   Milken served two years of a 10-year sentence for violating
securities laws, and after leaving prison in 1992 was diagnosed
with cancer and given 12 to 18 months to live. The cancer, though,
is now in remission, and Milken is vigorous. But his sense of
having limited time has made him as driven and obsessive as he was
in his days at Drexel Burnham. He has staff meetings at 6:30 a.m.
and calls aides late at night when ideas occur to him, which is all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But the cancer has also made Milken stop to smell the roses,
literally. Besides conventional treatment, he has turned to
alternatives like meditation and aroma therapy, having flowers
planted around his house and smelling them to bolster his immune
system. He has gone to a low-fat, high-soy diet and even been
co-author of a cookbook, from which proceeds go to cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer foundation is given credit by scientists for
accelerating research and changing the way it is done. But
Knowledge Universe, while growing rapidly, still must prove it can
change education, as opposed to merely changing the ownership of
companies already in the business.
</P>
<P>
   The Milken Institute and its Global Conference are the least
significant of Milken's activities in terms of time and money. Even
some institute officials acknowledge that so far it has had little
impact on public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1991, the Milken Institute became a haven for young
PhDs to do scholarly but obscure research. In 1997, Donald H.
Straszheim, then chief economist at Merrill Lynch, was brought in
as president, expanding the staff and shifting toward work of
interest to businessmen and politicians rather than academics.
</P>
<P>
   This second annual Global Conference is part of that effort.
Peter Passell, formerly a business reporter for The New York Times,
is revamping the institute's magazine, with a new, sprightlier
version being sent free to 10,000 influentials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the institute's young researchers were dismissed or
quit, complaining that serious scholarly work was less valued than
was preparing slides for the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has always been very unhappy with the institute, and it
has never accomplished what he wants,'' a former researcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Another said: ``I think he wants basically nothing more than a
venue from which to address the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are still in flux, and the institute is still searching
for a firm footing. ``Changing a culture is not easy,'' Straszheim
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides appearing with the Nobel laureates, Milken delivered one
of his trademark speeches to the 1,000 people in the audience, an
hourlong ramble that meandered from the return on investment of the
Louisiana Purchase to the ethnic mix in Los Angeles, but along the
way he emphasized his perennial themes _ the need for capital
sources other than banks, the necessity for medical research and
the importance of education and human ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money has long ceased to be a major determinant in the
creation of value,'' he said. Though for Milken, who once made $550
million in a year, money helps in moving him back into the
limelight. But the value of his legacy, which he cares deeply
about, will be based on more than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
