<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-TEXASTECH-SFA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas Tech women have something to prove
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ There has been one thing that has driven the Texas Tech
Lady Raiders to a 28-3 record and the Big 12 women's title. There
has been one thing that has driven senior Angie Braziel to earn Big
12 Player-of-the-Year honors. There has been one thing that has
driven coach Marsha Sharp to earn conference Coach-of-the-Year
honors.
</P>
<P>
   There has been one thing on the Lady Raiders' minds every time
they hit the weight room, take shot after shot duringpractice and
when they tip off at the start of games this season _ revenge.
</P>
<P>
   They were the top seed last year at home when they were stunned
by Notre Dame in an embarrassing 74-59 loss. Their loyal fans
watched in shock as the Lady Raiders failed to advance beyond the
second round for the second consecutive season. This was a team
used to winning, staring every day at the 1993 National Champion
banner earned by their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw them (after the loss), I knew it was
something that affected them a great deal,'' Sharp said. ``From
that very moment, in the weight room, the things they did on their
own in the spring and summer, was more impressive than any group
I'd ever coached. They spent more time getting ready for this year
than any group we've ever had here. It carried over to our workouts
early and everything we did as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have gone over that game hundreds of time in their
minds, eagerly awaiting the day when they again could step onto the
court in another first-round NCAA Tournament game. The opportunity
comes tonight when the second-seeded Lady Raiders host No. 15 seed
Stephen F. Austin at 8 p.m. at the Lubbock Municipal Coliseum.
Tenth-seeded North Carolina State and No. 7 seed Mississippi State
play at 5:30 p.m. in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Lady Raiders (28-3) are the easy favorite against
the Ladyjacks, who got an automatic bid by winning the Southland
Conference tournament, they won't be thinking about their possible
second-round matchup. That is what was to blame for last year's
upset, Braziel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking about our next game too much,'' the 6-foot-2
post said. ``We would have played Louisiana Tech, and we were
focusing on them rather than Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Making its 12th consecutive NCAA Tournament appearance, SFA is
anything but the typical 15th seed. The Ladyjacks, who dealt with
the suicide of former star player Katrina Price, bring an
uncharacteristically mediocre 17-11 record into this year's
Tournament. However, they have won 10 of their last 12 games and
have gained strength and unity through tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a group that has gone through adversity like
they have, you become stronger,'' said Sharp, whose team is making
its 10th consecutive tournament appearance. ``And they are an
unbelievable 15th seed. I was surprised that they were that low.
They are extremely scary to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As is Tech to SFA. After all, the Lady Raiders are perfect at
home this year and hold a nine-game winning streak. Braziel leads
them in scoring with a 20.6 average, and senior guard Rene Hanebutt
is averaging 15.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest concern about Tech is that they are such a
complete basketball team,'' SFA coach Royce Chadwick said.
``They've got the best post player (Braziel) in the country and one
of the best shooters (Hanebutt). (Forward Keitha) Dickerson is one
of the best defensive players. They don't have any weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Raiders also will be better equipped to handle the
intensity. Last year, they were a No. 1 seed; this year, they're
No. 2. That top billing made for weighty pressure, Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than overlooking (Notre Dame) last year, we probably were
a little overwhelmed,'' Sharp said. ``(It was) the first time we'd
ever been a No. 1 seed, first time the regional had ever been held
in Lubbock. I can tell you that I've never felt as much pressure in
my life to stay in a tournament as I did last year, trying to be
here at home for our fans in the regional level. It really crushed
us.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of pressure, the same kind they've put on
themselves every day since that crushing loss to end last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though they won 28 basketball games, this season
won't be successful for them unless they go erase that memory from
the NCAA Tournament,'' Sharp said. ``After we won (the Big 12
tournament) Saturday night, we sat in the dressing room for a
moment as a group and talked about it. And the commitment I could
see on their faces was special to me because I think they finally
got to a point where they felt like they could go vindicate
themselves a little bit. In their minds, the success of their
season rests on the ability to get this done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
