 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Davis' involuntary departure, Arkansas weigh heavy on Iowa
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ He says he isn't dwelling on the finality of it all. There
is another team to scout, another game plan to fine-tune, another
40 minutes to scheme and matchups to fret about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really thought much beyond that,'' Tom Davis said
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The eyes say something different. You see that in the faces of
his players, too, as an era of Iowa basketball ends and ends badly,
no matter how much the man at the center of one of the season's
stranger stories tries to put on a civil face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about it, and coach doesn't really want us to
think about it,'' Hawkeyes guard Kent McCausland said. ``But every
time we go out there, we give a little more, because we know there
will be a change after this year.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the strange reality since last April, when the
school announced Davis' contract would not be renewed. His 13th
season as Hawkeyes head coach would be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can fathom why.
</P>
<P>
   Those years, after all, have produced 11 trips to the
postseason, nine of those to the NCAAs. They have resulted in a
268-139 record, part of a 542-289 mark in a 28-year head coaching
career that has included stops at Lafayette, Boston College and
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Davis' teams never lost a first-round NCAA game.
That modest but still remarkable trend continued with Thursday's
elimination of Alabama-Birmingham, setting up this afternoon's
second-round meeting with Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   If seeds hold, the No. 4 Razorbacks will put an end to the run.
And try as the Hawkeyes might to make the farewell party an upbeat
affair, the sadness in the eyes and the hesitation in the voices
tell a different story, one not short on irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' senior forward Jess Settles said, '' but the way
it's turned out, everybody in Iowa loves coach Davis now.''
</P>
<P>
   A 19-9 season has helped rekindle those affections. So has the
fact that Davis, a rumpled 60-year-old with an elfin smile, has
done his best to take the high road throughout.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to keep the parting as amicable as possible. He
continued to honor the commitment even when athletic director Bob
Bowlsby explained the move in an interview with a national
magazine, citing differences over scheduling, recruiting and the
character of some players as reasons for the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with the pulpit clearly his, Davis continues to keep
his own counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been dealing with this all season,'' he said. ``When
it's over, maybe there will be a time to look back and reflect on
things a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not now.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before play began in this half of the West Regional,
Davis and Nolan Richardson ran into each other in a McNichols
Sports Arena hallway. The Arkansas coach had a broad smile and a
warm handshake for a man he called a fellow ``cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson is 57. Even with a 1994 national championship in his
pocket, he wonders when his time will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches like Tom, myself, John Thompson, John Chaney _ to me,
those are the cowboys,'' Richardson said. ``Our days are numbered.
But are they numbered as bad as the ones coming behind them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm the age I am at. I'm glad I don't have to look
over my shoulder at some little young AD who's come to fire me.
Some of them are hired to fire you.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis wasn't exactly fired. He simply was told he no longer was
needed after 13 mostly successful years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of those years has become a hot topic of discussion
back home. Davis' supporters cite the NCAA bids and just two losing
seasons. They also point to the fact that ``Dr. Tom'' has run a
program that for the most part has steered clear of negative
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Critics view all this in a different light. They say the program
has been in a holding pattern since Davis' first season, when the
Hawkeyes won 30 games and came within a game of the Final Four.
They also note Iowa hasn't advanced beyond the NCAA second round
since 1988, and that Davis' teams never won a Big Ten championship.
</P>
<P>
   Davis takes pride in being a teacher and coach who can get the
most out of the available talent. This year's team earned another
NCAA bid despite losing its potentially best shooter, Kyle
Galloway, to a back injury and forward Sam Oakey to a broken wrist.
Each had been counted on to contribute to a club picked to finish
in the lower half of the Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   Even shorter on talent than expected, Iowa nevertheless
prospered. The Hawkeyes ended Kansas' 62-game home winning streak
with a 65-61 victory Dec. 8 in Lawrence. Despite losing eight of
its last 13, Iowa earned a No. 5 seed in this West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how much this means to him,'' junior guard Ryan
Luehrsmann said. ``We want to keep it going as long as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating a deeper, more athletic Arkansas team to earn a trip to
Phoenix may be a tall order. Either way, Davis will take them one
at a time at least one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing what I've done for 13 years in terms of trying to
develop the program, a clean program that is respected around the
country for playing by the rules with good guys _ stuff like
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, stuff like that isn't enough anymore.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Tom Davis has another game to worry about, another 40
minutes to plot and ponder. The time to think of other things will
come soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
