<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore announces $25 million to fight citrus canker
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dropping by for lunch, dinner and a
reception, Vice President Al Gore collected $600,000 for his
presidential campaign Friday during a 12-hour stay in South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took in $150,000 at the Four Seasons Resort where the lunch
crowd paid $1,000 each to dine with the leading candidate for the
Democratic nomination. Then he traveled to the Sheraton Bal Harbor
Hotel near Miami Beach, where he attended a reception with 200
contributors who gave him $250 each. He then moved on to dinner
there where 400 people paid $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   While $600,000 may seem like a lot of money, it's just a small
chunk of the $20 million that candidates are expected to need to
win their party nominations next year. Gore is the Democratic
front-runner, with former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, his only
announced opponent, a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech in Palm Beach was a grab-bag of political goodies
for everyone. He said the country needs better schools, a robust
economy, better health care, protection of Social Security, equal
pay for equal work, more progress in civil rights, stronger
families, a health-care bill of rights and an unshakable commitment
to fight crime.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd laughed after Gore said that on his way to Palm Beach
he read a 19th century description of the island that said it was a
patch of South Seas excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things don't change,'' Gore said. ``It also said you
could buy land here for $1 an acre. Some things do change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can expect to see a lot more of him in Florida,''
said Palm Beach County Commissioner Burt Aaronson, a staunch
supporter. ``We have to do everything we can to get him elected, or
Democrats could be in trouble for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
