<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8729 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHENS13-COX     03-12 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHENS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fine cabinetry, hidden storage blend tour kitchens with rest of
house
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mahogany islands that look more like fine furniture
than kitchen bars.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet doors and drawers that conceal not just pots and pans
but refrigerators and freezers.
</P>
<P>
   Arched alcoves that double as corner pantries while making them
more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   So what's happened to the kitchen as we know it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to see some really clean lines to the design of
kitchens, spaces that are less complicated in some ways but with
more attention being paid to the details and materials,'' said
designer Shirley McFarlane of Kitchensmith of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a kitchen that blends more than ever with adjacent
areas as it continues to evolve into a multipurpose room and, in
many cases, a status symbol. As eating out and taking out become as
common as drive-throughs and Tater Tots, cooking is only one of
several kitchen functions _ a gathering spot for entertaining
guests, an office for managing households, an unloading zone for
kids' books and toys.
</P>
<P>
   A taste of those trends can be seen March 20 during the second
annual Junior League of Atlanta Tour of Kitchens. The seven
featured kitchens, located in the Buckhead-Vinings area, will serve
up a smorgasbord of ideas for homeowners, whether they're building
or remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be amazed at the people who came through last year who
were getting ready to start a renovation,'' said Suzy Smith,
chairman of the tour, which benefits teen pregnancy prevention
efforts. (The first event raised more than $25,000, for
scholarships aimed at developing teen leadership skills.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's kitchens include new construction and renovations,
designs for family lifestyles as well as for casual entertaining.
All but one are traditional, and most are high-end examples of
what's possible with deep pockets, though one by do-it-yourself
giant Home Depot's Expo Design Center is bound to inspire visitors
who might leave house tours feeling discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot who came last year were the do-it-yourselfers who left
with plenty of ideas, just not the $75,000 or $100,000 budgets to
do kitchens like these,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Several features are evident in this year's lineup:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Layouts that blend the kitchen with family room. Great rooms
are nothing new, but the flow between kitchen and den has led to
some major changes in the look of kitchens. Open kitchens mean
fewer walls, so efforts are being made to hide refrigerators and
other large appliances by integrating them with cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   A look behind what appear to be the doors of tall storage
cabinets in a kitchen on Nancy Creek Road reveals a freezer; a peek
in several of its drawers shows refrigerated compartments.
``Everything is pretty much tucked away,'' said McFarlane about her
integrated design for the corner kitchen, which is open to the
breakfast room, family room and rear staircase.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, designers are mixing surfaces and cabinet
heights to give the kitchen a more interesting look. In some tour
kitchens, granite-top islands stand beside ceramic-tile
countertops. White cabinets and stainless steel appliances are
integrated with natural wood islands. Wall cabinets hang at varying
heights and counters are higher not only to meet the needs of an
aging population but for the sheer convenience of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cabinets designed to resemble furniture. One of the most
dramatic changes has been the emphasis on cabinetry styling. As
with appliances, cabinets are designed so they don't stand out but
instead look as if they could be used in any room in the house.
</P>
<P>
   In Bruce Patterson's new Wieuca Road home, Rutt of Atlanta
created a streamlined kitchen that at first glance appears
contemporary for Atlantans' traditional tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing about this kitchen is the interior designer
(Bill Cook of Vermillion Designs) wanted the dramatic impact with
the yin and the yang of black and white,'' said Jere Bowden, owner
of Rutt. ``But the thing that softens the look is that the cabinets
are all wood instead of laminates, and the floors are small-plank
oak, which extend to other rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Nancy Creek kitchen, the centerpiece is an
irregular-shaped granite-top island made of mahogany, with end
pieces inspired by carved stair pickets and containing display
shelves. Hidden behind the island's fine finish, intricate moldings
and brass hardware are state-of-the-art appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the mahogany gave us the opportunity to make the piece
look more like furniture and the overall environment warmer,''
McFarlane said. ``We're seeing more people going to more
furniture-quality products in their kitchens, not just pine, oak or
maple, but nicer finishes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Walker and Mary Jane Candler remodeled their Arden Road
kitchen and family room, they sought to blend the rooms. Walker, an
architect, designed a kitchen floor in a basketwork pattern
containing oak and St. Joe brick pavers. The bricks complement
those in the existing breakfast room floor, and the wood picks up
the mahogany cabinets and heart pine ceiling beams from Savannah.
Columns flanking a large prep and eating island are faux finished
to resemble heart pine. An oak armoire serves as a handy depository
for book bags as the Candlers' three children enter the back door,
and in a nearby corner is a small workstation for storing recipes
and keeping track of schedules.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Architectural details not sacrificed. The heavy crown
moldings, architectural columns _ even arches _ common in many of
today's new homes aren't being ignored when it comes to kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Candler designed his kitchen to mimic a Palladian style pool
house in his back yard. ``I was trying to relate the two houses,''
he said, so he incorporated archways between the kitchen and
breakfast room.
</P>
<P>
   Archways, instead of doors, also are used to separate kitchens
from storage areas, such as corner pantries and wine rooms, so that
they're readily accessible to the cook.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the columns on the tour aren't just accents; they're
storage units chock full of food.
</P>
<P>
   In Patterson's kitchen, Rutt incorporated black columns flanking
the cooktop that slide out to reveal hidden spice racks. Another
pair, beside the sink, holds cleaning supplies. The secret units
help give the owner clean, open space for impromptu dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a place where I could entertain comfortably, where I
could cook and still be with my friends,'' said Patterson, a real
estate developer.
</P>
<P>
   Angular walls, which open the kitchen on one end to the entry
hall and on the other to the breakfast room, contain a wine storage
unit and a wet bar, convenient for large parties throughout the
house or intimate get-togethers in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden chose a warm white for the walls and cabinets that is not
sterile and sleek but clean and classic. The result is a timeless
combination that even the most traditional tastes will find
inviting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the difference,'' she said, ``between being trendy and
having style.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Junior League of Atlanta Tour of Kitchens
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: 10 a.m.-4 p.m. March 20
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: Seven kitchens in the Buckhead-Vinings area
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: $20, available at Junior League offices, 3154
Northside Parkway and other locations. Call 770-350-0916. (A
limited number of tickets will be available for $25 during the
event.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Designers: Rutt of Atlanta, Kitchensmith, Design Galleria,
Brookwood Kitchens and Expo Designer Center
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Special events: How-to seminars and cooking demonstrations
will be presented at each house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 770-350-0916
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
