<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-KIDS13-COX     03-12 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-KIDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children find they make a difference in their world, and ours,
by pitching in as volunteers
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazing things can happen when children become
volunteers. Just ask Judy Avison.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta (Ga.) woman and her 8-year-old daughter, Hannah,
decided to do something for children in foster care after watching
a television program last year that showed such youngsters using
plastic garbage bags to hold their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Avison and Hannah came up with the idea to collect suitcases to
replace the garbage bags and enlisted the help of Hannah's Brownie
troop to carry out the project.
</P>
<P>
   In less than four months, the Brownies collected 800 suitcases,
which they turned over to the Fulton County Department of Family
and Children Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls have learned that they can start something from
scratch and it can turn into something huge,'' says Avison.
``They've discovered that they can really make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Such projects are one way to enlarge the world of children and
help them grow spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are naturally empathetic and want to reach out,''
says Mimi Doe, author of ``10 Principles for Spiritual Parenting''
(HarperPerennial, 1998, $13). ``When kids ask what they might give
instead of what they might get, it's a beautiful way to bring to
light the principle that all life is connected. It can make magic
out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Doe, who lives in Concord, Mass., encourages her two daughters
to express their passions by giving to others. Her oldest child,
Whitney, 11, loves animals, and so collects sheets to take to local
animal shelters for bedding. And her other daughter, Elizabeth, 8,
loves to play the flute, and so regularly performs at a nearby
nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried that my daughter would be upset when people
started to die,'' says Doe. ``But her concern is brightening up the
moment right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield Hebrew Academy's Betty Minsk thinks volunteerism
supplies a way of connecting the school's students with the
spiritual values of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The performance of mitzvahs _ good deeds _ is basic to
Judaism,'' says Minsk, director of special education projects at
the Sandy Springs (Ga.) school. ``We teach that good deeds should
be performed all the time, at home and at school, as a way of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   To put these ideals into action, Minsk, in partnership with
classroom teacher Sylvia Miller, organized a community day of
service last week for the 550 students at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The event was overwhelmingly successful,'' says Minsk. ``We
felt it made a tremendous impact on both the children and the
agencies, and the parents who came along were elated.''
</P>
<P>
   Doe understands the impact volunteerism has on youngsters and
youngsters have on volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are amazingly powerful,'' she says. ``Our children
can change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of volunteer projects involving youngsters take place
each year across metro Atlanta. Everyone benefits. Here's a
sampling below, including ways children can become involved.
</P>
<P>
   American Red Cross
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHAT: High school Red Cross volunteers teach first aid and
disaster preparedness to Gwinnett County fourth- and fifth-graders.
The instruction takes place at Collins Hill High School in Suwanee
as part of the Red Cross Elementary Leadership Development
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REACTION: ``It's very rewarding,'' says Paul Bruckman, 17, a
junior at Parkview High School in Lilburn, who has been
volunteering with the Red Cross since he was a sixth-grader. ``I
have so much fun with the kids, and I see the result,'' says the
Lawrenceville resident. ``A lot of times they will come up to me in
a store and say, `You taught me first aid.' It's great to think you
might have helped a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GETTING INVOLVED: The Red Cross has volunteer opportunities
for children as young as 9. Many schools have Red Cross clubs that
take oncommunity service projects, and there are also leadership
development conferences and youth councils and boards that sponsor
service projects. For additional information, call Sharon Burton at
404-575-3111.Girl Scouts
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHAT: After learning that children in foster care usually
transport their belongings in plastic garbage bags, eight
second-graders from Brownie Girl Scout Troop 7313 in Alpharetta and
Roswell (Ga.) decided to do something about it. With help from
troop co-leader Judy Avison and the approval of the Fulton County
Department of Family and Children Services, the Brownies began a
campaign, Suitcases for Kids, to collect suitcases for kids in
foster care. To date, they have collected 800 slightly used
suitcases, duffel bags and backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REACTION: ``It makes me feel good and it makes someone else
happy,'' says Megan Sweeney, 8, of Alpharetta. ``I thought it was a
very good project,'' says Hannah Avison, 8, of Alpharetta, who says
she wants to become president of the United States when she grows
up. ``Because of it, I got an interview on TV and talked in front
of our church and a whole bunch of other places.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TO HELP: To donate a suitcase or learn more about the project,
call Judy Avison at 770-664-9182.
</P>
<P>
   Hands On Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHAT: High school and middle school students serve as Saturday
morning tutors and mentors to children at East Lake Elementary
School in Atlanta, teaching them reading skills. Many tutors are
graduates of East Lake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHY: Forty-five percent of Georgia students are not reading at
an acceptable level when they reach the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REACTION: Nicole Riley, 13, an East Lake graduate, has been on
both the giving and receiving end of the Hands On Atlanta program.
Currently a seventh-grader at Glen Haven Elementary School in
Decatur, she now volunteers as an East Lake tutor. ``I help the
students with their reading and draw with them,'' says Riley. ``I
especially like helping the little children. I have learned from
it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TO HELP: Hands On Atlanta offers numerous volunteer
opportunities for children, families and adults. For additional
information, call Youth Service Coordinator Ken Hansberry at
404-872-2252, Ext. 52.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Community Food Bank
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHAT: Every week special education students from Turner Middle
School in Atlanta help to sort food.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHY: To help feed the hungry and teach the students work
skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REACTION: ``We pack food to give to people that don't have
food and let them know that we care about them,'' says Turner
Middle School student Crystal Foster, 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TRAINING: The food bank shows its volunteers videos about
hunger that explain why the need for volunteer help is so great.
``The kids not only have fun, but learn how they are affecting
lives,'' says warehouse manager Kevin Dorsey. Dorsey frequently
brings in his own five kids, 6 to 14, to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TO HELP: Children 8 to 18 are welcome, but need to be
chaperoned by an adult. For additional information, call
404-892-FEED (3333), Ext. 230.Greenfield Hebrew Academy
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHAT: This Sandy Springs-based Jewish day school involved its
entire 550-member student body, from pre-kindergartners to
eighth-graders, in 28 service projects _ Community Concern Day _
throughout Atlanta last week. Projects ranged from cleanups and
tree plantings to activities with senior citizens and homeless
children.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WHY: To honor the sacred Jewish injunction to perform mitzvahs
_ good deeds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REACTION: ``It was really positive and really fun,'' says
eighth-grader Carla Bloomberg, 14, of Dunwoody (Ga.). She helped
wash windows, prepare food, clean toys, do laundry and sort books
for children at the Genesis Shelter, a facility for homeless
newborns and their families. ``They were just little things,''
Carla says. ``But they sure had an impact. You felt so good about
yourself afterwards, and the people at the shelter said we were a
big help.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TO LEARN MORE: For additional information about the program or
school, call Betty Minsk at 404-843-9900, Ext. 334.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Henry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
