<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILOXI-RESORT14-COX     03-12 1897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILOXI-RESORT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi's casinos have paid off with prosperity _ for a
price
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 14.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ As big as an ocean liner and bathed in a ghostly
blue light, the pirate ship sits a few hundred feet offshore.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't move. It doesn't have to. This ship's quarry comes to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gamblers come to Treasure Bay from all over, from all walks of
life: denim-clad locals and fur-wrapped visitors, twentysomethings
and octogenarians, blacks, whites, Hispanics and Asians, all eager
to unload their doubloons within the hulking vessel.
</P>
<P>
   A few hunker over lush felt tables manned by sharply dressed
pirates' minions, whose hands blur in a hypnotic flurry of
card-fanning, dice dispensing and chip-scooping. Many more belly up
to endless rows of slot machines, which pulsate and ping with
electronic lights and bells and have seductive names such as
``Sizzling 7'' and ``Filthy Rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the fortunate ``win'' back a few coins. And then
proceed to fork over even more cash in the hope of getting
``lucky'' again.
</P>
<P>
   That human instinct is at the heart of this once-depressed Gulf
Coast city's multibillion dollar gaming industry, which has
accounted for more than 12,000 new jobs. Since gambling was
legalized here in 1992, nine mammoth casino-resort properties have
opened, and more are on the way. In six years, the number
ofvisitors has leapt from 1.5 million to 19 million per year. And
this crowded field is about to be joined by an even bigger player.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably already seen the commercial. Over pastoral
images of children swinging, seagulls gliding and shrimp boats
listing in a placid harbor, a plummy, faux-Scarlett O'Hara voice
(supplied by Elizabeth Taylor) drawls, ``And then, one day, it
happened. You looked up and there it was! Just like a storybook,
written large across the sky. . . . And after that, nothing was
ever the same. 'Course, we still like the smell of the magnolias.''
</P>
<P>
   What has ``happened'' is Beau Rivage, Biloxi's newest and
arguably grandest casino-resort, which opens Tuesday. The ad
epitomizes the balancing-act marketing plan behind this $650
million, 32-story behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Built by Las Vegas-based Mirage Resorts Inc., Beau Rivage aims
to be a posh, five-star retreat with a Deep South flavor. It
outsizes the competition in nearly every way, with nearly 1,800
hotel rooms _ compared to 1,088 at the second-largest Imperial
Palace _ plus 12 restaurants, a 30-slip marina, a full-service spa
and a 1,550-seat theater that will offer ongoing performances by
the avant-garde circus troupe Cirque du Soleil. Yet, for all its
look-at-me largeness, Beau Rivage is less garish than neighboring
casino-resorts. The muted color scheme is heavy on pastel yellows.
Taylor's favorite trees, magnolias, even shade the lobby. And the
casino itself is a forest of floral prints and fringe.
</P>
<P>
   All the better to attract the target customer: affluent women
from out of state. Barry Shier, 43, chief executive officer of Beau
Rivage Resort, says states such as Georgia, Florida and Texas boast
``a level of affluence'' higher than Mississippi's.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic studies show that the typical visitor to the Gulf
Coast is female, over 45 and college-educated. It remains to be
seen whether Biloxi's working-class male visitors will take to Beau
Rivage and its nicotine-distressed murals, sushi bar and
aromatherapy chambers.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the jackpot
</P>
<P>
   Deep within the bowels of Treasure Bay, Wonverlette Miller is on
a roll. The 29-year-old nurse's assistant from Hilton Head, S.C.,
has just scored a ``double jackpot'' on her slot machine, which is
spewing a slew of quarters into her waiting hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no skill to it,'' she tells an amazed onlooker. ``You
just sit down and play.''
</P>
<P>
   He does, feeding an adjoining machine with a roll of quarters.
Within four minutes, he's down to one quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you do?'' asks Miller, aghast. ``You must have done
something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Winners and losers. It has become Biloxi's story.
</P>
<P>
   Such dizzying growth in so short a time has made some in the
city of 53,000 giddy with newfound prosperity. Others feel that
their simple way of life has been lost to the pirates forever.
</P>
<P>
   The late 1980s and early '90s were dire times in Biloxi. The
city, with its 26 miles of man-made beaches and picturesque
antebellum homes, had been for decades a popular getaway spot for
New Orleans' upper crust. But when Louisiana's oil industry hit the
skids in the late 1970s, money grew scarce and the vacationers
stayed away. The hotels started to fall into disrepair. Other
travelers bypassed Biloxi for beach towns in Alabama and the
Florida Panhandle. The city began to have trouble paying its bills.
``We couldn't even afford to buy tires for the police cars,'' says
Vincent Kreel, Biloxi's public affairs manager.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s, several states in the Midwest and South hit
the jackpot with limited legalized gambling. In 1990, the
Mississippi Legislature cleared the way for the counties along the
Mississippi River and the Gulf Coast to offer dockside gambling.
The idea was to keep things small, with a historic riverboat feel,
so as not to insult the conservative Christian sensibilities of
many residents. Early on, one gaming official took pains to point
out in the Mississippi Business Journal that the combined square
footage of the dozens of casino boats then docked in Mississippi
was only as large as two Las Vegas casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought the industry would last maybe three or four
years,'' Shier says. But when gamblers began descending on the area
in droves, the casinos permanently dropped anchor. The riverboats
were replaced by immobile gaming barges and seamlessly fused with
land-based hotel and restaurant facilities. And gaming revenue
became an inextricable part of Biloxi's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rising rents, robberies
</P>
<P>
   Ask any number of Biloxi's merchants and they'll invariably say
the casinos have been good for business. Then, almost immediately,
they'll start talking about the downside.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody mentions the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Used to be, you could shoot a cannon down Beach Boulevard and
not hit anybody,'' says one restaurant owner, referring to Biloxi's
oceanfront thoroughfare. Others believe that crime in the area is
on the rise, pointing to a recent upturn in bank robberies.
Escalating rents and the loss of qualified employees to the casinos
are also concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of these problems is relative. Take the traffic.
True, Beach Boulevard and U.S. 110, which connects the coastal
highway to U.S. 10 inland, can get moderately conjested. But it
isn't exactly Atlanta's Spaghetti Junction during afternoon rush
hour.
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to combat traffic congestion by building a
3.5-mile loop around downtown and another connector in West Biloxi,
says David Nichols, Biloxi's chief administrative officer. As for
crime, he acknowledges that bank robberies are on the rise, but the
overall crime rate has fallen, he says, thanks to a burgeoning
police force funded by gaming tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody has a solution for skyrocketing rents, which are
pricing some mom-and-pop operations out of high-profile beachfront
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz and Bobbie Winnett pay $3,000 a month rent for their small
beachfront boutique, Bobbie's Bikinis, up from around $800 a month
in the early '90s. Their business has improved slightly every year,
thanks to an influx of young women employed by the casinos as
cocktail waitresses. But if the rent continues to rise, the
Winnetts may have to move inland.
</P>
<P>
   Small pawnshops, which can be seen as barnacles on the boat that
is gambling, are thriving. Mark Millette, owner of Beach Pawn &AMP;
Gun, set up shop six years ago and has seen his business grow 10 to
15 percent annually. Thanks to his largely local customer base,
Millette is well-stocked with hocked jewelry, guns and stereos. ``I
just saw all the people coming to the area,'' he says. ``And I
thought, `Hey, whether you have a pawnshop or a Ruby Tuesday's,
things are going to be good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He's not just talking. There's a new, double-decker Ruby
Tuesday's just down the block. The wait for a table on Saturday
nights: an hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   `A laissez-faire view'
</P>
<P>
   Scott Carter has the kind of energetic, up-with-people
personality common to young Southern ministers. He says
``wonderful'' a lot when preaching to the Leggett Memorial United
Methodist Church. ``Isn't it a wonderful day?'' he says to his
congregation of a year. ``It's wonderful to have y'all here.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the first Sunday in Lent, he's sermonizing passionately
about the need to ``examine ourselves'' in order to guard against
``unhealthy appetites.'' He never mentions gambling directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes talk about it, but I never rail against it,''
Carter, 37, says later. He understands that many who attend
services at the small beachfront church have, in his words, ``a
laissez-faire view'' of the local gaming industry. Some have even
found jobs in the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   His own feelings are unequivocal. ``I'm personally opposed to
it,'' Carter says. ``There's no question that it's rejuvenated the
coast, but I guess I see the underside of it.'' He ministers to the
homeless at a shelter in downtown Biloxi and says he sees plenty of
``personal destruction and despair'' caused by addictive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Others in Mississippi's religious community are even more vocal
in their opposition to the casinos. Last year, legislative aide
Elizabeth Stoner, with the support of religious groups, tried to
force a statewide vote on gambling. A judge rejected the initiative
because it did not address what effect a ``no'' vote would have on
the state's economy. Gaming taxes now account for 10 percent of
Mississippi's annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   And, to Carter, that's the rub. ``Many of my fellow pastors
oppose gambling, but now that it's here, they don't want to see it
taken away,'' he says. ``Our economy is tied to it. And that's a
big concern.''
</P>
<P>
   A bonanza in quarters
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Boomtown Casino, which looks from the outside like a
slice of Walt Disney World's Main Street, George Bowling dispenses
advice on how to win at the slots. ``It doesn't matter which
machine you play,'' he says. ``They're all the same. The only thing
that matters is that you stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 51-year-old retired infantryman from Columbus, Ga., knows
what he's talking about. He's popped down to the casino for a few
minutes while his wife dresses for dinner, and he's already $100
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Another gambler, a reporter hopeful of understanding the lure,
if not getting on a roll of his own, wasn't faring as well. One
roll of quarters was gobbled up by a slot machine called Treasure
Wheel.
</P>
<P>
   He tried again.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the machine's spinning reels stopped on a bar. So
did the second. Then the final reel landed on a super-fancy
Treasure Wheel bar. The machine began to flash and ping. Quarters
spilled out at a breathtaking rate.
</P>
<P>
   He cashed out, admiring his winnings _ $14 _ and walked out of
the casino.
</P>
<P>
   As pirate spoils go, it wasn't much. But it felt like a million
bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
