<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walk in woods leads to other time and place
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ As winter strains to hold back spring, the
woods offer the most satisfying solitary walks.
</P>
<P>
   Every season is a fine one for appreciating and learning from
nature's gardening; spring, with its rich burst of wild plants _
trillium, lady's slipper, rattlesnake plantain, azalea and all the
rest _ dazzles, delights. And autumn sets souls on fire with colors
so hot and brilliant, radiating from dogwoods, maples, sourwood,
sassafras, red oak.
</P>
<P>
   But now, when neither spectacular bloom nor awesome leaf color
grabs a walker's attention, the woods' essence takes center stage,
simple, profoundly beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   I have enjoyed countless woods walks with friends, lovers,
darlings. Assorted family members. Strangers. I even found pleasure
in trekking the woods with GI buds in Germany when I was a boy
soldier bivouacking.
</P>
<P>
   Walking alone brings me unique value, however.
</P>
<P>
   Like gardening, walking through woods transports me to simpler
times, unfraught. But because they predate any garden I've built,
the woods around the cabin feel more timeless than my planted
spaces. When I lose myself in the woods, I imagine a good life in a
natural, untouched place a thousand years ago _ or a thousand years
hence.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the only way to be truly alone is to walk alone.
Married, with children, they sleep with someone, wake up with
someone, take care of someone or go to work with someone _ then
start the cycle again. I believe many commuters shun company
because that is their only alone-opportunity. Even then, though,
they turn on car radios.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing this, I feel the desire from time to time to test my
tolerance for true aloneness. The timing was perfect the other day,
as I had done as much fall and winter planting as I intended. And I
was holding off on pruning for a little while. Not preoccupied, I
could occupy myself totally with the walk.
</P>
<P>
   The cloudless, blue-sky day was brisk, lit by sharp-edged
sunshine. The deeper I walked into the crunchy, crackly woods, amid
the white pines, hemlocks, Virginia pines _ all the workmanlike
trees that in spring become mere background for the showy azalea
and laurel _ the more striking the light became. It streaked
through the pine needles, bouncing here and there.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, the light hit mosses; in another, ground cedar. At
one point, I saw several bright spots about 10 yards away. So
bright, it had to be remarkably early blooms of some low-growing
perennial. A closer look showed it to be some kind of devil-weed,
perfectly lit. Throughout, pine branches with knots on the ends lay
like so many clubs.
</P>
<P>
   A good wind swooshed through branches as it swayed trees,
knocking them against one another. From time to time, I heard a
loud crack as another limb knocked too hard. The woods, populated
with tall skinny trees straining to reach the light, are punctuated
with others broken in half during blow-downs. Birds flitted through
all.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how long I was in there, but when I came out of the
woods, back into the angular day, I brought a few mosses for the
garden, a mental note on where to gather ferns, a question about
whether to transplant some ground cedar for ground cover. And, most
important, I brought back some time well spent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
