<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-UNNIFICATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS, HOLYFIELD AIM TO UNIFY HEAVYWEIGHT TITLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once Don King's sideshow shenanigans are stripped from
Saturday's heavyweight title unification fight, the key issues
aren't too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis is considered the harder puncher, and finally gets
an opportunity to carve his niche in boxing history. But even with
a 34-1 record, he hasn't been tested against a proven warrior like
Evander Holyfield. Does Lewis have the heart?
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is quicker, but talented big men like Lewis have given
him trouble. He will try to muscle inside to negate Lewis' 7-inch
reach advantage. But at 36, does Holyfield have the strength to
survive?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's finally time for me to make my mark,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   To which Holyfield said: ``Lennox Lewis is just a bump in the
road I have to get past. He doesn't stand a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is a slight favorite in the 12-rounder at sold-out
Madison Square Garden in New York. The fight can be seen locally on
cable TV pay-per-view and is scheduled to begin about 10:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The World Boxing Association and International Boxing Federation
recognize Holyfield (36-3) as heavyweight champion. Lewis, a
33-year-old from England, holds the World Boxing Council belt.
Holyfield is making $20 million for the fight, compared with $10
million for Lewis. The victor will be the first undisputed
heavyweight champion since Riddick Bowe in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Lewis have never fought, but their careers have
been intertwined to an extent. Bowe defeated Holyfield in 12 rounds
to unite the title, but his WBC crown was taken away because he
refused to fight Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Bowe defeated Holyfield twice in three bouts. That could be
relevant, because Bowe stood 6-foot-5 and weighed 235 to 246 pounds
in those fights.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, also 6-5, weighed in at 246 pounds. The 6-2 1/2 Holyfield
weighed 215 pounds, identical to his weight when he knocked out
Mike Tyson in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad thing,'' Holyfield said of the size mismatch.
``I fight tall and short, and it's been a proven fact that I have
won in both cases. I don't compare (Lewis) to Bowe. Bowe happened
to be the most talented big guy I ever fought.''
</P>
<P>
   But Emanuel Steward, a boxing legend who once trained Holyfield
and trains Lewis, said Lewis' size will pose problems for
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was involved with Evander and had any decision-making
authority, he would not be fighting Lennox Lewis,'' Steward said.
``Traditionally, Evander has a problem with taller guys. Whenever
he has to punch up, his rhythm is off. And Lennox is not just tall,
he's strong. There's a difference between being tall and being
big.''
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Holyfield has secured his place in boxing lore with
triumphs against Larry Holmes, George Foreman and Tyson. If he
beats Lewis, he will join Muhammad Ali as the only three-time
undisputed heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis probably has more motivation. He sought a major fight for
years without success, and a chance like this might not come again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Lennox Lewis' whole career,'' Steward said. ``After
this, there is no one else.''
</P>
<P>
   King is promoting the fight, and his hyperbolic stamp is
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a gracious opponent, Holyfield has been predicting a
third-round knockout, although power punching is not his game. Why
three rounds? Because God told him.
</P>
<P>
   The British-born Lewis has publicly called Holyfield a
hypocrite, because Holyfield speaks often about religion but has
fathered five illegitimate children.
</P>
<P>
   If this smacks of professional wrestling, that isn't unusual for
a King product.
</P>
<P>
   Doing his part, King said the satellite transmission of the
fight will temporarily end hostilities in Bosnia. He also said he
has undergone a religious conversion after Holyfield's victories
against Tyson, during which he stood in Tyson's corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've touched the garment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other championship bouts Saturday, highly touted Fernando
Vargas (15-0) of Oxnard, Calif., defends his IBF junior
middleweight title against Howard Clarke (26-10-2) from England.
WBA welterweight champ James Page (23-3) puts his title on the
title on the line against Sam Garr (25-2) of Stone Mountain, Ga. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
