A8737 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-REEVES-COLUMN-HOL     03-12 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-REEVES-COLUMN-HOLYFIELD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUNDER IN THIRD: HOLYFIELD READY TO POUND LEWIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield, the man with the shaved head and
the shortened ears, is going to hit Lennox Lewis so hard tonight at
Madison Square Garden, the big man's dreadlocks are going to
straighten out on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Thunder is coming, Holyfield says, in the third round. I'm not
sure Lewis, even as big as he is, lasts that long.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield may be 36, he may be on his last legs and he may even
be the hypocrite Lewis says he is, but he's a proven warrior, and
that's something Lewis is definitely not.
</P>
<P>
   When the two best heavyweights on the planet meet tonight in a
title unification bout that has captured the imagination of boxing
fans like no fight since the first Holyfield-Mike Tyson battle, it
will be about carving out a place in history.
</P>
<P>
   On the line for Holyfield: A chance to stamp himself as one of
the premier heavyweights of all time. A loss at this stage of his
career would label him good, but not great, pending a rematch if he
wants it.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis, it's a chance to prove that he's real and not just a
myth of boxing politics and public relations smoke. If he goes
down, don't hold your breath on a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden, attempting to recapture its romantic past
as a mecca for boxing, has been sold out for weeks and prime seats,
originally sold at $1,500, are being scalped for $10,000 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   This, for a fight Holyfield says won't go more than three.
</P>
<P>
   As long as it's a furious three, as many fight experts are
predicting it could be, no one will complain.
</P>
<P>
   There is a glint in Holyfield's eyes that does not bode well for
Lewis, despite a massive difference in size. The 6-foot-5 Lewis
weighed in at a strong-looking 246 Thursday to Holyfield's chiseled
215 rock-hard pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let that fool you. Boxing's historical canvas is littered
with the bodies of hulks who brought size, a big punch and a
veritable cornucopia of glass jaws. Can you say Gerry Cooney?
Buster Douglas? Jess Willard?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also carries the burden of a long line of Brits who have
come to the Colonies to box the ears of the upstart Colonials, only
to leave humbled and bloodied. Henry Cooper, Frank Bruno, Brian
London ... why should we believe that Lewis, who likens his style
to ``a chess game in the ring'' is any different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope he's not coming in here with his chess board,''
said Lewis trainer Emanuel Steward, who admits even he's not sure
``which Lennox will show up.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis tries to ``castle'' Holyfield tonight, I predict a
checkmate, on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis is an enigma,'' Lewis said, as if he was talking
about his next door neighbor. ``They don't know much about Lennox
Lewis yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And why would we? At 33, he is the WBC heavyweight champ more by
accident than design. He plucked the title out of the dumpster,
where it was tossed by Riddick Bowe, who wanted nothing to do with
Lewis, and won it again when Oliver McCall had a crying fit.
</P>
<P>
   The same man who clubbed Andrew Golota into submission in the
first round, but panicked, turned his back and cowered in the first
against Shannon Briggs. He carries the reputation of being too soft
where Holyfield is strongest _ in the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name the best fighter Lewis has beaten, Steward could
not come up with an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, to get what he wants _ respect _ Lewis must destroy
Holyfield. Better men have tried and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, once thought to be no more than a blownup cruiser
weight, has earned his respect the hard way. He has battered eight
former champions, including Larry Holmes, Bowe and George Foreman,
and twice took on the devil himself _ Mike Tyson _ and won for all
that is right and good in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe he's not exactly Sir Galahad, after all. More of a
philandering Lancelot, to hear Lewis tell it. Lewis has called
Holyfield a ``hypocrite'' because the WBA and IBF champ talks often
of his Christian beliefs despite having fathered five illegitimate
children, including a pair born last year to women not named Mrs.
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has been made about what I said, calling him a
hypocrite, but it's time to think about the fight,'' Lewis told
reporters this week. ``He knows what I feel and he's expressed what
he feels. Now I'm going to get the opportunity to go out and try to
prove all the people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' ``hypocrite'' comments may explain why Holyfield has gone
out of character to predict a third-round knockout. He sounds like
he means it.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has made a career out of beating bigger men. He's a
proven fighter, a warrior who understands that his place in the
sport's history is within reach and another big man is in his way.
</P>
<P>
   Time to duck. Thunder is coming. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817)
390-7972 \Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
