<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLANKS'S WORKOUT IS HOT, HIS STORY UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Blanks is hot.
</P>
<P>
   His Tae-Bo workout video has grossed $75 million since last
August. Time magazine devoted a full page to him this week,
trumpeting his story as that of a man who has risen from poverty in
Erie, Pa., to the fast lane in Hollywood as the personal trainer to
the stars. No less than Oprah Winfrey, Paula Abdul, and Wayne
Gretzky have become part of the spin.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Blanks, from zero to hero, a wonderful story. A self-made
man, living the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   But when Patricia Pierce of Hingham, Mass. hears the name of
Billy Blanks, she starts to sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is promoting a lie,'' says Pierce, a freelance writer and
art consultant who ``discovered'' Blanks more than 15 years ago and
became his trainer and manager. Pierce maintains that Blanks left
the Boston area more than 10 years ago, owing her an explanation
and several others money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought Billy here in 1981,'' says Pierce. ``I saw him in a
(karate) tournament in Minneapolis, thought he was a great talent,
and became his manager. For four years I paid for his dojo (workout
studio), apartment, car, health insurance, fixed his teeth, paid
his debts and all his expenses to train and go to major
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never took a dime from him and I paid all of his bills. It
was an American Dream for him; it became a nightmare for everyone
else. And his claim that he is self-made is a lie, as are many
other things in his public relations campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanks claims he is a seven-time world karate champion. ``He won
it twice,'' says Pierce, ``and never until I became his trainer. He
says on his web site infomercial that he won the Golden Gloves
light heavyweight championship (in Massachusetts) in 1984 and was
the Tri-State champion of champions. That's a lie. He tried boxing
and in his only fight, he got knocked out. He had a glass jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Romalo, who has run the Golden Gloves in Eastern
Massachusetts since 1969, said he has never heard of Blanks. ``I've
been here for 30 years. I looked back through all of our records
listing every champion. Blanks is not there. As far as we are
concerned, he never won the title and certainly was not a champion
of champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Vose, owner of the Vose Art Gallery on Newbury Street in
Boston, also has unkind things to say about Blanks. ``He owes me
money,'' says Vose, who trained with Blanks when he had a studio in
Quincy, just over the line from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loaned him $60,000, and I had to sue him to get the money
back. I had to settle for $30,000, so as far as I am concerned, he
owes me $30,000 plus interest for the last 10 years. Now that he is
making all of that money, it would be nice if he paid me back.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce says she is not looking for money, but she feels the
public is owed the truth. ``This is why I am speaking out,'' she
says. ``I just want him to tell the truth. He says he's 43; he's
45. He says he's been working on this technique (Tae-Bo, a fitness
program combining aerobics and karate movements) for 35 years. That
would have made him 8 years old at the time. This all started as
Kaerobics, which I was working on in 1983 and 1984. It was a
combination of karate and aerobics. He (Blanks) says Tae-Bo is
truth; then he should start stop telling lies. He stole the
Kaerobics concept from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to do all of this b.s. Why doesn't he simply
tell the truth? He never won the Golden Gloves. He was not the
seven-time world karate champion. He did have a lot of help from me
and other people back here who befriended him. He is not a
self-made man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disheartened to know that Billy feels it is necessary to
deceive the public. The Time story implies he is a holy man or
preacher. Holy men do not mislead people to attain money, power,
and fame. It is time for him to tell the truth. Anything less is
dishonorable and discredits the black belt he wears.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the lawsuit involving Patriots Drew Bledsoe and Max Lane and
their stage-diving incident goes the distance, coach Pete Carroll
might have to change his plans for practice this spring. Bledsoe
and Lane have been sued by Tameeka Messier, who was injured two
years ago at the Paradise nightclub in Boston. Messier claims she
was injured when Lane and Bledsoe landed on her while stage-diving
at a concert. The trial is scheduled to start in three weeks. The
judge has asked both sides to try to reach a settlement. But it
looks as though the case will go to a jury trial. Nearly 60
depositions have been taken to date, and if all those people are
called as witnesses, the trial could last more than a month.
Messier claims that first Lane, then Bledsoe landed on her. The
players deny it. Bledsoe claims he dived 5 or 6 feet to the right
of Lane. Lane has no insurance. The depositions make it clear that
Messier's attorneys also are going after Bledsoe, who would be
worth more than Lane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There could be more bad news for Red Sox team physician Arthur
Pappas. Former Sox pitcher Butch Henry lashed out at Pappas this
week, saying he misdiagnosed Henry's knee injury last season. Now
comes word from two people close to Tim Naehring that the former
Sox infielder is considering a lawsuit against Pappas and the team.
Naehring injured his throwing elbow two years ago and never was
able to play again. Naehring now has a front office job with the
Cincinnati Reds. Word has it that although Naehring likes Pappas,
he was told by other doctors that the surgery performed by Pappas
was flawed and that Naehring could have continued to play if the
operation had been done better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sox coaching staff was more than impressed with Ramon
Martinez's first workout. According to a team source, Martinez
threw the ball 86 to 87 miles per hour, which is outstanding this
soon after rotator cuff surgery. If he continues to throw with no
setbacks, the Sox expect him to be able to reach 93 miles per hour
_ and be ready for game action _ in three months . . . One of the
most prolific scorers in college hockey history will be in action
Saturday when Harvard hosts Cornell (2 p.m.) in the women's ECAC
quarterfinals. A.J. Mlezcko became the first woman to collect 100
points in a season, finishing with 102, including 31 goals. Tony
Hrkas, who played for North Dakota, has the men's record with 116
points. But it took Hrkas 46 games, including playoffs, to reach
that number. Mlezcko has her total in just 29 games . . . The Red
Sox expect to have 1.75 million tickets sold before Opening Day,
which would be a record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
