A8747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-MARINE-AVIA     03-12 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-MARINE-AVIATOR-MAPS-ART-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON STILL HASN'T UPDATED MAP OF JET-CABLE CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also MARINE-AVIATOR-ITALY) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   MATTHEW L. WALD      
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than a year after a Marine Corps jet hit an
alpine gondola cableway that was not on the crew's map, the
Pentagon has not updated its maps. While the Defense Department
says it can operate safely with the old maps, a lawyer for victims'
families said that changes in the maps would complicate the
government's legal defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The omission of the Mt. Cermis cableway on the map was a major
point for defense lawyers in the court martial of the pilot, Capt.
Richard J. Ashby, who won an acquittal a week ago, arguing that the
lack of a warning meant the case was an accident waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Any move by the Pentagon to update the maps by including the
cableway and dozens of other obstructions would help the families
of the 20 victims in bringing claims against the Defense
Department, according to an American lawyer for the families of
five Belgian victims.
</P>
<P>
   Two legal experts on international legal claims, while saying
they could not predict whether such a case will be successful,
agreed that changing the map now could help convince a judge or
jury that the original map contributed to the accident, but they
pointed out that failing to change it to bolster a legal position,
could also anger a judge or jury.
</P>
<P>
   Suits against the U.S. government can be brought only for
actions in this country, and any change in the map could be taken
as an admission that the originals, drafted here, were flawed, said
the lawyer for the families, C. Torrence Armstrong of McLean, Va.
Armstrong made a claim to the Department of Defense seeking damages
for the deaths of the Belgian victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speculate that there was a desire not to correct
anything for fear it might look bad,'' said Armstrong in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Pentagon, Col. Richard M. Bridges, said
the map ``fully complied and complies with military service
requirements for this product.'' It is meant to be used with a
second publication that now specifies planes must maintain a
2,000-foot minimum altitude above ground level, far higher than
man-made obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   The restriction was in place before the accident, but the Marine
crew, rotating through Italy on temporary Bosnia duty, was not
aware of it. In addition, Italian air traffic controllers now brief
pilots, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges and other defense officials stressed that a tower must
rise 200 feet to be included on the map, and the towers at
Cavalese, where the deaths occurred, were far lower. The cables
were higher, however, because the ground drops away beneath them as
it crosses a valley.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham D. Sofaer, a former federal prosecutor, U.S. district
judge and legal adviser to the State Department, and an Air Force
veteran, said a court might find the map to be ``a source of
negligence.'' By not changing it, he said, ``what they're trying to
do is avoid providing evidence of having made a mistake to begin
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridges said that Adm. Joseph W. Prueher, appointed this week to
conduct a review of changes made since the accident, could make a
recommendation about the map.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the chief Pentagon spokesman, referred obliquely
to Armstrong's claim on March 4, the day of the acquittal, when he
was asked at a briefing whether the maps had been fixed. ``There is
a separate, as I understand it, a separate litigation involving the
mapping agency, the National Imaging and Mapping Agency,'' he said,
adding that he was not aware any change had been made to the map
and could not discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's claim was rejected by the Pentagon on March 2, two
days before Ashby's acquittal. Defense Department lawyers told him
to file in Italian courts, and that any award would be paid under
the Status of Forces Agreement, which was ratified in 1951 to
govern NATO forces. Armstrong, who along with lawyers for other
families has complained that the process would take eight years,
has six months to appeal the denial to a U.S. District Court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials say they want to avoid a precedent that would
destroy the status of forces agreement, which is used for scores of
less spectacular damage claims every year. Asked if the desire to
preserve the agreement figured in the decision not to change the
map, Bridges replied only that the agreement ``is the exclusive
remedy for claims taking place in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Beck, the civilian lawyer for the navigator on the
flight, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, whose court-martial is scheduled
for next week at Camp Lejeune, said the omission on the map was
central to the accident. ``Had they known it was there, they
wouldn't have even flown down the valley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Italian Ministry of Defense, in Rome, officials said they
had sent another 10 copies of their maps to their American
counterparts after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   One official, who asked not to be identified by name, said that
Italian law called for foreign pilots to be using Italian maps. But
Defense Department policy is to use American maps, and the crews
permanently based in Aviano continue to fly across Italy using the
American maps that lack markings for the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how a correction to the map now would play in a federal
trial is not clear, but a law professor said that such a change
could be used to prove that an action taken in the United States
contributed to the accident. Andreas F. Lowenfeld, a professor of
law at New York University who specializes in international law and
in aviation, said that a measure taken after an event that could
have made the event less likely cannot be admitted as evidence to
prove negligence.
</P>
<P>
   But the existence of such measures, like a correction to a map,
can be introduced as evidence when offered to prove ``ownership,
control or feasibility of precautionary measures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear whether this would affect the litigation,'' he
said. ``Even if it does, you don't invite future accidents by
trying to cover your rear end on a prior one; that's a terrible
idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby's plane, an EA-6B Prowler on a training mission, hit two
cables at a point where they were about 360 feet off the ground.
The cable line has since been rebuilt, with $20 million
appropriated by Congress, and follows the terrain much more
closely.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Maj. Daniel J. Daugherty, cross-examining
Ashby, asked why the crew had not noticed a church at which they
were were supposed to execute a turn, and asked why he thought the
map-makers showed the church, if not for navigation purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they mark them, sir,'' Ashby responded. ``I'd
rather have them mark the cableway than the church.''
</P>
<P>
   A Marine colonel who held eight days of hearings last year on
whether there was enough evidence for a court-martial reported in
June that on the map used in the flight ``aerial obstructions
appear rare on Italian soil yet, in Austria, just north of the
Italian border, obstructions are marked with great frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   The colonel, Ronald L. Rodgers, concluded that the map makers in
a Pentagon agency outside Washington had gone to a less detailed
Italian map to copy down instructions.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force had a copy of the more detailed Italian map in an
office at the Aviano base, but did not use it, Rodgers reported.
</P>
<P>
   At the Italian embassy in Washington Friday, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe
Bernardis, a military attache , said that the map alone had not
caused the accident; that, he said, would have been prevented if
the crew had been aware of the Italian restriction of 2,000 feet,
or even if they had stuck to what they believed their restriction
was, 1,000 feet. But asked if putting the Mt. Cermis cableway and
other low-level obstacles on the maps would aid safety, he said
``it helps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
