<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-TRAFFIC13-COX     03-12 1541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-TRAFFIC13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas border cities lobby for relief from truck traffic
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ In this booming border city, free trade has a
sound. It's the hiss of air brakes and the deep rumble of diesel
engines and the clank of trailers hitched to tractors, readying
another load to take across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the sounds of money. Trucking has become Laredo's
bread and butter, its largest industry, its biggest employer and
the main reason Laredo is the busiest port on the U.S.-Mexico
border. The trucks are also its biggest headache, tearing up roads,
lining up for miles on Interstate 35, and clogging the narrow
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo Mayor Betty Flores calls her city, where up to 6,000
trucks each day cross the bridge from Mexico, a ``chokepoint
instead of a checkpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Laredo and other cities along the Texas-Mexico border are
lobbying the Legislature for relief as their roads become
gridlocked. Their own booming populations are going
bumper-to-bumper with commercial traffic that has surged since the
North American Free Trade Agreement took effect five years ago.
Their argument is simple: We're bearing the brunt of the trade
boom, so we need extra money to keep the traffic and the goods
flowing.
</P>
<P>
   But to get what they want, border counties will have to persuade
lawmakers to either divert transportation money from other parts of
Texas or dip into a budget surplus that state leaders have all but
promised to use for education and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Their challenge is to convince cities like Austin, Dallas, and
Houston _ which have their own traffic to deal with _ that it's in
their interest to help the border. Border leaders, who have united
and hired lobbyists to work for the entire region, hope to convince
lawmakers from other parts of the state that spending money on the
border will benefit them as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your border,'' Flores said. ``It's in my city, but
it's your border and you have to help me take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It promises to be a tough sell in a state that ranks 45th in per
capita highway spending. The Texas Department of Transportation
estimates it has about 40 percent of the money it needs for road
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The border's request for nearly a billion dollars in new highway
money has drawn skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If money is diverted down to the border, there are other areas
of Texas that are going to suffer, I would think,'' said Al
Luedecke, director of planning and programming for the
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, others say the problem is more complicated than
simply building more roads. The quality of Mexican highways, the
hours that trade-related businesses keep, and the increased
vigilance of federal agents hunting for drugs and illegal
immigrants all contribute to the border bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, the trucks leave their mark everywhere. In the smell
of exhaust that hangs over downtown. In the grooves their tires
wear into the blacktop. In the stretch of concrete on I-35 at the
international bridge where lanes had to be closed last summer when
idling trucks literally sank into the sun-softened asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're constantly trying to keep (the roads) in shape. It's a
never-ending battle,'' said Jorge Pineda, assistant general manager
of Celadon Trucking Services, a company that logs more than 100
border crossings every day.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo is home to 400 trucking companies and 55 million square
feet of warehouse space _ enough to cover all of downtown Austin.
The city is constantly repairing streets, and the police department
deploys officers to warn motorists away from the line of trucks
that stretches for miles on I-35 as truckers wait to clear Mexican
customs in the evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who has been mayor for a year, said the congestion is
killing downtown business. People are dying too. Every so often, a
motorist comes over a rise and smashes into the back end of a truck
stopped on I-35.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same on the Mexican side, with trucks stacking up by 10
a.m. waiting to clear U.S. inspections before rumbling down one of
Laredo's designated truck routes, mostly two-lane blacktops where
traffic stacks up at stoplights and railroad crossings. A third
bridge opened upriver to relieve the problem handles mostly
commercial traffic, but many truckers don't like the longer drive
to the bridge or the alarmingly narrow road on the Mexican side.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, said City Manager Florencio Pena III, ``caught us
off guard completely. We just didn't expect this much traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Other border cities have similar complaints. In the Rio Grande
Valley, big trucks rumble down farm-to-market roads from some
bridges to reach U.S. 83, the area's clogged main artery. Upriver
in Roma, a town in Starr County, a spacious new port facility is
underused because trucks have to cut through an alley to reach the
main highway, Reba said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could handle a lot more traffic, but the road is not
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Pass is building a new international bridge and wants the
narrow highway to San Antonio widened. El Paso, the second-busiest
port on the Texas border, wants a loop around the city. ``When 20
percent of NAFTA traffic comes through your community, believe me,
that creates a problem,'' said Sen. Eliot Shapleigh.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the congestion is the requirement that loads
going over the river use a drayage company, or short-hauler. Such
companies are necessary because the United States and Mexico don't
allow trucks from the other country to drive beyond the border
zone. That means three trucks are needed to get one load delivered
_ one on each side of the border, and one to cross the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   A provision of NAFTA that would allow truckers from both
countries to drive freely within the United States and Mexico was
scrapped indefinitely in 1995 over concerns about the safety of
Mexican trucks.
</P>
<P>
   There's been talk of keeping customs open 24 hours to ease
congestion. But Maria Reba, director of South Texas operations for
U.S. Customs, said the results were disappointing a few years back
when they tried opening at 7 a.m. instead of 8. The customs
brokers, warehouses, importers, and freight forwarders who help
move each truck, she said, were unwilling to change their hours to
match customs.
</P>
<P>
   Border leaders like Alan Johnson, a member of the Texas Turnpike
Commission from Harlingen, say the border has not historically
received its fair share of highway dollars. ``That's basically
because we've never had any political clout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luedecke, the state Transportation Department official, said new
construction projects are given priority based on a complicated
formula including the cost, existing traffic, and other factors.
Border areas in years past didn't have the traffic volume to put
their projects ahead of more populous areas, but that has changed
since NAFTA, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His agency says it is doing everything it can to address the
border's problems. The department had $440 million worth of
projects completed or under construction on the border at the end
of August, up from $300 million at the same time in 1994. The
department's total construction budget is $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has pitched in as well, setting aside $140 million a
year for five years to pay for highway improvements in border zones
and ``NAFTA corridors'' around the country. The state
Transportation Department has submitted 32 projects _ about half of
them on the border _ to compete for the money. Many border road
projects are in the pipeline, transportation officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, for example, a fourth international bridge, scheduled
to open upriver from Laredo early next year, will have direct
access to Interstate 35, and all commercial traffic will be
diverted from downtown to the two outlying bridges, Luedecke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will change the whole character of Laredo, I think,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Infrastructure Coalition's wish list includes almost
$1 billion more for road and highway projects. Earlier this month,
the Senate Committee on Border Affairs, pared that number to $623
million, with the bulk for new construction.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's proposal would also earmark $9 million to create
one-stop border inspection stations that would house the various
state and federal agencies that are responsible for checking
everything from truck brakes to insurance documents to pesticide
residue on Mexican vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Rene Oliveira (D-Brownsville) has proposed a
third option: up to $1 billion in highway bonds for the border. The
bonds would require statewide voter approval. Texas Comptroller
Carole Keeton Rylander has proposed issuing $700 million in bonds
to help speed construction on the border and other parts of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the House Appropriations Committee, Rep. Pete
Gallego (D-Alpine), said he and other border lawmakers have
convinced many of their colleagues there is a problem at the
border, ``but now we have to convince people to give up a little of
their share of the money to help someone else. That's a little
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
