<HEADER>
A8752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT &LR;      03-12 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT WROTE THE BOOK THAT IS JARVIS' MANUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind.)  (mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The first basketball book St. John's coach Mike
Jarvis bought was Bobby Knight's ``Let's Play Defense.'' At $1.50,
Jarvis says, it was the best basketball investment he has made,
still informing his strategy more than 30 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The first basketball clinic Jarvis paid to attend was one
conducted by Knight in 1967. Over the years, Knight, the bombastic
heartland hero, has been kind to Jarvis, the urbane philosopher,
calling him once to congratulate him on a victory and praising him
Friday for the job he has done at St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   But the two coaches have not faced each other in a game. Their
teams will finally square off Saturday, when Jarvis' third-seeded
Red Storm plays Knight's sixth-seeded Indiana Hoosiers here in the
second round of the NCAA tournament's south regional.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis and the Red Storm will face an Indiana team coming off
its best performance of the season, a 108-88 first-round drubbing
of George Washington that was a clinic in using a big lineup to
dominate the inside game and pound a smaller, quicker team into
submission.
</P>
<P>
   Starting three big men _ and Luke Recker, a 6-foot-6-inch
forward, at guard _on Thursday night, Indiana shot 65.5 percent
from the field and attempted only three 3-pointers. Not that St.
John's seemed terribly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they'll play big against us so we can run on them,''
the Red Storm's Ron Artest said. ``I don't think their
ball-handling was that great either.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana did have 20 turnovers, but Artest's insouciance was
indicative of the Red Storm players' broader lack of awe for a
program as storied as their own. St. John's is in fifth place on
the NCAA career victory list; the Hoosiers are 10th. But St. John's
players are too young to remember Isiah Thomas wearing red, and not
one of them has seen the movie ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   While Knight and his players spoke of the toughness and love of
the game that New York's playgrounds foster in St. John's players,
the Red Storm's perception of Indiana centers on an image of
country boys, old-fashioned play and ``Bobby Knight and a lot of
hollering,'' according to Bootsy Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis' impression of the Hoosiers is a little more analytical.
He watched Indiana's beating of his former team, the Colonials, and
then viewed six or seven tapes of earlier Indiana losses. What he
saw against George Washington was a nearly flawless game:
fundamentally sound, with such pinpoint passes that there was
little need to do anything but go inside for layups.
</P>
<P>
   The 108 points were the most by an Indiana team in tournament
history. The redshirt freshman forward Kirk Haston, who cracked a
bone in his left hand against Iowa on Feb. 27, scored 27 points on
9-of-11 shooting from the field and 9-of-10 shooting from the line.
Recker scored 20 on 7-of-11 shooting from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Knight did manage to find something wrong with the game: George
Washington scored 57 second-half points. ``We cannot play that kind
of defense and expect to win against St. John's,'' Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   If Indiana can approach that level of play again Saturday, a big
question in an erratic 23-8 season, St. John's (26-8) would face
multiple problems. Tyrone Grant said Friday that he still had pain
in his infected right hand and that he had less control of his shot
than usual, meaning that St. John's only true inside presence is
hampered.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's also prefers an uptempo pace to the slower halfcourt
game it is likely to get from Indiana, and if the officials call a
lot of fouls in what is expected to be a physical game, St. John's
has less quality depth than Indiana. The players' response to
questions about those potential roadblocks was essentially a big
shrug. They said that almost all of their opponents had greater
size and better depth, and St. John's had somehow won 26 games and
reached the top 10. Jarvis, though, was more cautious and more
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they played, I haven't seen too many teams play better
this year,'' Jarvis said. ``The things they do best have nothing to
do with size. They have to do with fundamentals. You're playing
against a system. They screen as well as anybody playing the game.
They do the little things that most coaches strive a lifetime to
get their kids to do. Like box out, pass, cut, screen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
