<HEADER>
A8754 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV14-NYT     03-12 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 14) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Was That Take On the RJR Cycle? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another turn in the history of RJR Nabisco changes participants
into revisionists, rehearsing what might have been. J. Tylee
Wilson, the former R.J. Reynolds chief executive who merged the
tobacco company with Nabisco in 1985, still thinks that building a
broad-based consumer products company makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson, now 68 and retired, is not about to second-guess the
intention of RJR Nabisco Holdings, it announced last week, to split
up the businesses and sell foreign tobacco operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't the faintest idea how it would work out for
shareholders, but they had to do something and this looks like a
reasonable solution,'' he said, citing the company's debts.
</P>
<P>
   He found some satisfaction from Japan Tobacco's willingness to
pay $8 billion for the international tobacco operations, saying,
``I set that business up in 1976.''
</P>
<P>
   RJR itself has come full circle, back to the way it was in the
1960s, Wilson said. But if tobacco companies have always been
besieged by competitors and regulators, today's climate is the
worst ever, he said, concluding, ``I certainly would never go into
the business today.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Atkins, a lawyer who advised the RJR Nabisco board on
buyout offers, said that RJR might have split up sooner if Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts had not bought it. In the 1990s, other companies
have sold off operations to focus on core businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demerger of RJR Nabisco is a late arrival in a fairly
well-established trend,'' he said. ``It might well have occurred
earlier but for the constraint of dealing with its liabilities,
including tobacco litigation and debt.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnaby J. Feder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Journalist's Juicy Reward &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the rare journalist who figures so large in a company's
business that his compensation becomes public as part of routine
financial disclosures. Add to the short list James J. Cramer _
hedge fund manager, columnist and part owner of TheStreet.Com, the
popular online financial news service.
</P>
<P>
   According to the prospectus issued last month, when the company
announced plans for going public, Cramer will get a salary of
$250,000 this year, with 10 percent annual increases through the
end of the agreement in 2002. But if the stock does well, his
salary will be the least of his rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer is TheStreet.Com's biggest stockholder; as of last month,
he owned about 2.7 million shares. (A $15 million investment in
February made The New York Times Co. the service's third-biggest
owner.) His new employment agreement gives Cramer an option to buy
an additional 333,333 shares at $3 a share. Given the roughly $11 a
share that the Times Co. paid for its position, that option would
be worth about $2.67 million. He can buy 25 percent of those shares
each year, starting in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What does TheStreet.Com get for its money? Cramer writes a
half-dozen or more columns for the service daily. Despite the poor
performance last year of his hedge fund, Cramer-Berkowitz &AMP; Co.,
Cramer's regular appearances on CNBC and his columns for other
publications help make him a one-man marketing department.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Cramer's journalist colleagues have nonetheless been
complaining about the founder's compensation _ but grousing is
common to newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   With TheStreet.com in a quiet period before its public offering,
Cramer said his lawyers had told him not to comment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warburg's Big Wager &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A collective gasp was heard on Wall Street last week. Who,
traders and bankers asked, could really be worth $70 million? To
Warburg Dillon Read, the investment banking business of UBS AG of
Switzerland, which was struggling to bolster its presence in the
United States, the answer was Benjamin Lorello, a Salomon Smith
Barney health care banker.
</P>
<P>
   Lorello left for Warburg after being offered more than $50
million in salary and bonuses over three years and about $25
million in deferred stock benefits.
</P>
<P>
   That huge price tag may say less about Lorello than the desire
of his new employer to crack the global health care industry. The
Europeans have largely failed in recent attempts to expand in
America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Deutsche Bank retreated from Wall Street, only a few
years after paying hefty hiring incentives. ``If it's $50 million
in salary, regardless of performance, it's a high-risk strategy,''
said Steven Eisman, an analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts question Warburg's timing, noting that
the health care business in general could use a resuscitator:
nursing homes and hospitals are comatose.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lorello nor his new employer would comment.
</P>
<P>
   LAURA M. HOLSON
</P>
</TEXT>
