<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHAT'S WITH HOLYFIELD'S PREDICTION? 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the bell rings, Evander Holyfield, shorter by 3
inches and outweighed by 31 pounds, is expected to try to move
inside in order to smother Lennox Lewis' longer reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get inside,'' Lewis has been saying, ``and he's
got to be allowed to do something there. I don't think he's going
to get inside, or be allowed to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk about Holyfield's fighting inside, the more
compelling issue is _ what's inside his head? What's behind his
blurting out that he would emerge as the undisputed world
heavyweight champion Saturday night at Madison Square Garden by
knocking out Lewis in the third round?
</P>
<P>
   Such a brassy prediction has never been Holyfield's style.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not predicting; this is what's going to be true,'' he
said. ``I knew I was going to knock him out in the third round.
What would the people like _ a surprise or foretell it? This time
I'm not going to surprise, I'm going to let you know ahead of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering the almost gentle humility displayed by the WBA
and IBF champion in the past, it's not as simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that Holyfield is now so completely confident
of his ability, he can boldly call the round. He even acknowledged
that confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more confident than I've ever been,'' he said of his
unprecedented prediction. ``I've been in this game 28 years. I know
what I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Holyfield overconfident? Although he is still fighting
for his rightful ranking in heavyweight history, he is talking
about how ``I'm one of them already, whether anybody knows it or
not.'' As if he deserves to be put up there on the same pedestal
with, say, Joe Louis, Rocky Marciano, Muhammad Ali, Jack Dempsey
and Jack Johnson. But a loss to Lewis would put that pedestal out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation for Holyfield's prediction is that, after a
sluggish but successful 12 rounds against Vaughn Bean in his
previous title defense, he was trying to bolster his own confidence
while also branding the third round into the WBC champion's brain.
And he already has Lewis not only thinking about the third round,
but also denying that he'll be knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will definitely still be there in the third round,'' the
Englishman said.
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield is either overconfident or needs more confidence,
he would appear to be vulnerable, especially against Lewis, who is
so much taller, heavier and, possibly, stronger. Holyfield has a
history of not being able to stop larger opponents, such as Riddick
Bowe (to whom he lost twice) and George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the 36-year-old Holyfield can fulfill his prediction or
the 33-year-old Lewis can land a big punch, this scheduled 12-round
unification bout should develop into the survival of the toughest.
And over his 36-3 record with 29 knockouts, Holyfield has been one
of the toughest. Mike Tyson would testify to that.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' toughness is subject for debate. Despite his 34-1 record
with 27 knockouts, he has never had the look of a gladiator. But
his trainer, Emanuel Steward, remembered Lewis hanging tough in
earning a 10-round decision over Ray Mercer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox was bleeding from around the eyes, the nose and the
mouth,'' Steward recalled. ``Against Andrew Golota, a street-tough
guy, he stopped him in one. Against Razor Ruddock, he just
overpowered him. Any time he's been in a tough fight, he's never
faltered. He's tougher than people give him credit for.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward expected Saturday night's early rounds to be wild, maybe
even a heavyweight version of the eight marvelous middleweight
minutes before Marvelous Marvin Hagler flattened Thomas Hearns in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   If Saturday night's pay-per-view showdown on TVKO for the
undisputed heavyweight title were to last only eight marvelous
minutes, it would end in the third round, too. That doesn't
necessarily mean that Holyfield's prediction will be fulfilled.
There's no reason Lewis couldn't generate a third-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander's chin is definitely questionable,'' Lewis said. ``He
hasn't been hit by a heavyweight as big as myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But if this brawl develops into a survival of the toughest, the
pick here has to be Evander Holyfield, the proven toughest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
