<HEADLINE>
IOWA'S TWISTED PLOTS PROVIDE MOTIVATION
</HEADLINE>
 DAVIS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Welcome to ``As the Bracket Unfolds,'' featuring the
soap opera stars of the 1999 NCAA men's basketball tournament, the
Iowa Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes (19-9) are seeded only fifth in the West Region
heading into Saturday's second-round matchup against fourth-seeded
Arkansas (23-10). But they clearly lead the 64-team field in
poignant story lines. In no particular order, the Hawkeyes feature:
</P>
<P>
   A lame-duck coach, Tom Davis, who seeks to prove that school
officials erred in April by announcing that his contract would not
be renewed and that 1998-99 would mark Davis' 13th and final season
at a school where he has compiled a record of 268-139 with nine
NCAA Tournament appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-year senior Jess Settles, the starting power forward and
spiritual leader who returned in November after a two-year hiatus
because of a back injury. NCAA officials granted him an unexpected
extra season of eligibility as a medical hardship case.
</P>
<P>
   Three unexpected losses from the roster in the past calendar
year.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the Hawkeyes are attempting to reach the
Sweet 16 for the first time since 1988, Davis' second season at
Iowa. Their motivation, Settles said, is at an all-time high
because of Davis' lame-duck status and the unexpected personnel
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough year on our program,'' said Settles, who
openly wept when introduced before a Feb. 23 game against
Northwestern that marked his final game at Carver-Hawkeye Arena.
``I'm glad how these guys have fought for coach Davis. ... There
are so many factors why we want to keep it going, but coach Davis
is the biggest one. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many story lines about why we want to win, it
makes your job pretty easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the angles, Davis' last dance is the most visible. Davis,
60, was hounded by detractors after a disappointing 1996-97 season
ended with a first-round loss to Georgia in the National Invitation
Tournament. But he emerged as a sympathetic figure after athletic
director Bob Bowlsby announced this would be Davis' final season.
</P>
<P>
   During Davis' final home game, chants of ``Fire Bowlsby'' echoed
through the student section. Knowing the next game could be his
last, Davis said, has made this NCAA Tournament run more emotional
than the eight that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the end is near, but you don't know how or when,''
Davis said. ``The emotion ... is deep. But I try to I take it day
to day, minute to minute.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling when the bandwagon will run out of steam. It
could happen against Arkansas. It might keep rolling until the
Final Four. When it does, Davis will become a former Iowa coach, a
prospect he declines to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been begging the question all year on that,'' Davis said.
``There's time to think about the future later. I try not to think
of it now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
