<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blue Devils not rattled; Vols survive
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Florida A&AMP;M's 15 minutes of fame actually lasted less
than four minutes in Friday's NCAA Tournament opener against
top-ranked Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the only team in the tournament with a losing
record, the Rattlers only trailed the favored Blue Devils 17-13
early in the first half. But Duke promptly answered with a 23-0
spurt that overwhelmed the Rattlers and sent them reeling to a
99-58 loss in the East Regional at the Charlotte Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Florida A&AMP;M (12-19), which opened the season with 10 consecutive
losses, won the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference tournament and
earning a first-round match against Duke (33-1), the ACC power
favored to win the national title. But the school's first-ever
tournament appearance ended with a thud as it trailed 59-20 at
halftime en route to its second-worst loss of the season.Duke
advances to Sunday's second-round game against the winner of the
College of Charleston/Tulsa first-round game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wally Szczerbiak scored 43 of his team's 59 points as Miami of
Ohio edged Washington in the Midwest Regional in New Orleans.
Szczerbiak scored 11 more points than the entire Wisconsin team as
the Badgers were eliminated by Southwest Missouri State 43-32.
Wisconsin's total was the lowest in the tournament since the
inception of the shot clock in 1986 and the lowest in a first- or
second-round game in tournament history.
</P>
<P>
   _ After winning the national title two years ago and advancing
to the regional semifinals last season, Arizona had another
first-round collapse in a 61-60 loss to Oklahoma. It was the fourth
time this decade the Wildcats lost in the opening-round to a team
seeded 12th or lower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Despite shooting only 33 percent from the field, Tennessee won
its first tournament game in 16 years and gave the SEC its fourth
straight tournament victory with a 62-52 win over Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
