</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLYNN-CATHOLICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BOSTON MAYOR WILL HEAD CONSERVATIVE ORGANIZATION OF
CATHOLICS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Va.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond Flynn, former mayor of Boston and later ambassador to
the Vatican, said Friday that he would become head of a national
Roman Catholic political organization that was founded as a branch
of the conservative Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, a 59-year-old Democrat, described his appointment, to the
national presidency of the nonpartisan Catholic Alliance, as part
of a change that began when the group became independent of the
Christian Coalition two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they want a leadership that is more in tune, more
focused on Catholic social teaching,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said that under his leadership, which takes effect next
Wednesday, the organization would encourage political participation
and provide a voice for Catholics, especially ``blue-collar,
working-class'' Catholics. ``Our focus will be on solidarity with
the poor, the needy and the immigrants,'' he said, adding that the
organization would also continue to oppose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Alliance's mission statement outlines ``four
pillars,'' or principles, the first of which calls for legally
protecting human life, ``from conception to natural death.''
</P>
<P>
   The other principles call for upholding the primary importance
of the family (and opposing legal recognition of same-sex
marriage); for recognizing that ``authentic freedom is bounded by
truth and personal responsibility,'' and for ``solidarity'' with
the poor (and opposition to ``the substitution of dehumanizing
government bureaucracy for real charity'').
</P>
<P>
   The organization, whose annual budget is about $1.2 million,
maintains a national office in Oakton, Va., near Washington, and a
smaller office on Capitol Hill. Flynn said it had about 125,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition created the Catholic Alliance in October
1995 with a mass-mailing appeal for members that coincided with
Pope John Paul II's pastoral visit to New York. At the time, Ralph
Reed, who was then the coalition's executive director, said that
anyone joining the new organization automatically would become a
member of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the publicity surrounding its start, the Catholic
Alliance has been a low-profile group, both before and after it
became independent in 1997. That year Keith Fournier became its
president, after having been head of the American Center for Law
and Justice, a conservative religious-liberty law firm founded by
Pat Robertson, who created the Christian Coalition. Fournier
recently stepped down as the Catholic Alliance's president.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lynch, a New York lawyer who became the organization's
chairman about a month ago, said that it recently had added new
board members and that its goal would be ``to inform and encourage
Catholics to participate in local, state and national affairs.''
Lynch said it would not endorse political candidates but would
create an Internet site where candidates' positions could be
compared with Catholic teaching on social issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
