A8766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SOUTH-INDY-HNS &LR;      03-12 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SOUTH-INDY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
No first-round fodder, Detroit tries to take next step
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ Enough already. For the Titans of Detroit and the
Midwestern Collegiate Conference, it's time to dissolve whatever
notion remains that their basketball team is a mid-level group from
a mid-level league.
</P>
<P>
   One win, even one like the 12th-seeded Titans' 56-53 stunner of
elitist UCLA, the No. 5 seed, in the South Regional's first round,
won't entirely wipe off the perception. Another win, like an upset
of No. 4-seeded Ohio State in the second round today at the RCA
Dome would certainly help, but the Titans and coach Perry Watson
are secure with their image.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors Jermaine Jackson and Bacari Alexander are two Detroit
recruits whom Watson, well-versed from his days in that city's high
school coaching ranks, has injected into this fast-rising program.
But the canny Watson realizes there is a danger with back-to-back
NCAA tournament appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bosses might tend to take it for granted, that it's an
every-year thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans (25-5) can't yet be considered NCAA regulars. They
have played in five Tournaments, but last year was their first in
19 seasons. The UCLA win was their third in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Watson if he accepts his team's role as one of this
Tournament's Cinderella teams and he parries the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm Cinderella?'' he says before noticing a friend in the
back of the room. ``Hey, Fran! They're making me Cinderella!''
</P>
<P>
   Fran Fraschilla coached last season at St. John's, eliminated by
the Titans in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deal in false hype,'' Watson continues. ``I deal in
city kids. I ask my guys to be the best player you can be and the
best team you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson dealt with city kids for 13 years at Detroit's
Southwestern High School. Three of his former players at
Southwestern _ Jalen Rose, who was in the stands cheering on the
Titans against UCLA, Voshon Lenard and Howard Eisley _ currently
play in the NBA. Watson recruits also helped fuel Michigan's NCAA
run with the Fab Five when he assisted Steve Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   While Michigan State and Michigan have appeared on recent Titans
schedules, Detroit is playing Ohio State for the first time since
1962 and the third time ever. But the Titans relish the chance to
take on a Big Ten power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to play anyone anywhere,'' Watson said. ``We
have tremendous respect for anyone that plays the game, but we
don't fear anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the MCC Player of the Year, played for a Detroit
suburban school and was recruited by Michigan State after he had
committed to Watson. He stuck with the Titans. Alexander had played
for Southwestern, Watson's former school. Yet Alexander seems to
understand the perception Detroit battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Detroit like the elephant and the mouse,'' he
said. ``Everybody sees the Michigans or the Michigan States like
the elephant. When the mouse comes at you, you tend to get startled
and run away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fans who have followed us for 20, 30, 40 years,''
Alexander said of the reception generated by the UCLA win. ``This
is a special time for them as well as us. This will be something I
will hopefully be able to tell my children _ that I was a part of a
team that beat UCLA in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Alexander doesn't think there isn't much more ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is a beautiful sport,'' he reasons. ``You can mix
all kinds of concepts and socio-economic backgrounds and get it
done in a team concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might get `B' players,'' he said, ``but we get `A' wins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
