<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's ugly, but Tennessee defeats Hens
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The late Jim Valvano once said that the NCAA
Basketball Tournament is about one thing and one thing only:
Survive and advance. And that's about all Tennessee did to
distinguish itself Friday when the Volunteers defeated Delware
62-52 in the first round of the East Regional at the Charlotte
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tennessee's Brandon Wharton (5 for 18 from the field),
summed up the afternoon best when asked about a moment in the
second half when the lights on the court got temporarily brighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they were trying to show us the way to the basket,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (21-8), the No. 4 seed, beat the 13th-seeded America
East champion (25-6) despite shooting 32.8 percent (20 of 61) from
the floor with 19 turnovers, and committing plenty of mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the SEC's Eastern Division champion is one of 32 teams
still alive and will meet Southwest Missouri State on Sunday for a
trip to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jerry Green's team won its first NCAA Tournament game
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still here and we know we can play a lot better,'' said
Green, who has the Volunteers in the tournament for the second
consecutive year. ``And I think our guys feel good about that. Now
we'll just get ready to play the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Delaware wasn't exactly ripping down the nets, either. In the
first half, the two teams combined to shoot 26.3 percent from the
floor (15 of 57) with 20 turnovers. The Volunteers needed a 11-0
run in the final three minutes to lead 25-22 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime we just said `we can't shoot any worse so let's
keep playing defense,''' said Wharton, who finished with 16 points.
``If we just kept playing defense, we knew we'd have a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Tennessee's superior size and athletic
ability began to take their toll. With the score tied at 25, the
Volunteers went on a 11-2 run to take a 36-27 lead with 15:24 left.
The Blue Hens climbed to within 36-35 with 11:20 remaining, but
Tennesee scored seven straight to take a 43-35 lead with 9:08 left.
The Vols were in control after that.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware, which was eliminated by Purdue in the first round last
year, shot 29.8 percent (18 of 57). The Blue Hens hit only two of
15 shots (13.3 percent) from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had our chances,'' Delaware coach Mike Brey said.
``But Tennessee did what they had to do to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
