</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-BOX-KING13 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet Delray's Don King
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some call him a convicted murderer, a swindler, the
King of Babble-On. But Don King is still here, still tireless and
tactless and shameless, 25 years after orchestrating Zaire's Rumble
in the Jungle between Muhammad Ali and George Foreman, eight months
after acquittal on insurance fraud charges that meant to send him
back to prison for 45 years, even as the U.S. Congress weighs a
bill targeting his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government went after John Gotti and got him, went after
Al Capone and got him,'' says Randy Gordon, the former New York
State Athletic Commissioner. ``They did an extensive investigation
on King, two trials worth, and came up with nothing. He has come
up, if not clean, then not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   So here he is on the Madison Square Garden theater stage, the
conductor in black tuxedo and diamond pendants, promoting tonight's
``unmitigated, unadulterated, undisputed heavyweight championship
of the world'' between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   King spent 45 rambling minutes Wednesday calling himself
agrarian and statesman for ``putting the seeds in the ground'' for
Kings' Crowning Glory _ a fight that will unify three titles and,
says King, cause a cease fire in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will not shoot each other on March 13. They will watch
Holyfield and Lewis on March 13.''
</P>
<P>
   As will many, for $49.95 a pop, in his adopted home state.
</P>
<P>
   Floridian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Florida,'' says King, 67. ``It is paradise, it is the
Garden of Eden. I think it is something that we say in the
vernacular of the ghetto, SKD ... something kinda different. I am
domiciled there, and I will continue to be domiciled there.''
</P>
<P>
   King's main offices are in Deerfield Beach, his crown logo
visible from I-95. ``He is not an absentee owner,'' says Howie
Evans, King's public relations director. ``He's usually the first
one in the building, the last one to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   A marker outside is dedicated to Henrietta, his wife of 43
years, for decorating the former warehouse, but the first grinning
face seen is Don's on a portrait behind the main desk. The
predominant artistic pieces are animal sculptures, allegorical to
the owner's career: majestic birds proudly spreading their wings,
cowboys and Indians hanging onto bucking horses.
</P>
<P>
   Kingvision Pay Per View is in this $2.1 million complex, and
there's International Operations, and Accounting, and a video
production room with tapes strewn across desks. A large white room
serves as an infomercial studio, an employees' workout room has a
Jacuzzi and lockers, and an unfinished ring sits in the warehouse's
corner. ``We may have small shows,'' Evans says.
</P>
<P>
   One guesses the shows upstairs are more combative, when King's
profile reflects in framed certificates and hanging photos of the
owner with Tip O'Neill and Jimmy Carter and Bob Dole and Bill
Clinton. One conference room is behind brown doors fronting the
executive suites, the offices of King and in-house lawyers, handy
considering his involvement in more than 100 lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   King moved his headquarters from Manhattan to Fort Lauderdale's
Oakland Park Road from 1993-1997. The Deerfield building is closer
to his home in Foxe Chase off Germantown Road in Delray Beach,
purchased early this decade and a place where he entertains the
chairmen of boxing's sanctioning bodies over the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   King's primary dwelling is a sprawling 400-acre estate in
Windsor, Ohio, with its indoor pool shaped like a boxing glove. But
his daughter Debbie lives in Boca Raton, his stepson Carl resides
in Boynton Beach. King has frequented the businesses of Delray
Beach's Linton Road for seven years: the Circuit City, the
Albertson's, the TCBY (now Brendy's), the Blockbuster Video. ``He
was a real nice guy,'' says Marco Conde, 16, who worked at TCBY and
now is at Circuit City. ``With a big wad of money, a rubberband
around it. He always let me keep the change.''
</P>
<P>
   He has noshed on bagels in Poppie's deli, with people like Boca
Raton police officer and community activist Wayne Barton, who says
King ``did more talking than eating; soon as he sits down, you are
in a classroom lecture.'' Barton attended King's 67th birthday
party at Renzo's Italian restaurant. ``He calls me to make chicken
soup,'' says owner Renzo Sciortino, whom King calls ``Fratello''
for brother. King comes in for trippa (cow stomach) with potatoes
and peas, and linguini al dente, and zuppa di clams. ``He mingles
with everybody, he talks to everybody if he has to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Community activists revere King, which is why there's a Don King
Plaza in Newark, N.J., and a Don King community center in South
Central Los Angeles, and an honorary doctorate for him at Shaw
University in Raleigh, N.C., where there soon may be a Don King
Wellness Center. He has been honored by the NAACP, the Rainbow/PUSH
coalition, the Council for Negro Women, the Southern Leadership
Conference, and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to have him in the community,'' Deerfield fire
chief Gary Lother says, especially after King spent $326,000 to
replace a fire engine that was rear-ended on I-95. In 1997, King
added this area to his holiday Turkey Tour, his staff working with
the Delray Community Action Center, and holding a press conference
at Tom's Place restaurant. Evans says King has spent close to $1
million on various South Florida projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a part of the community, with its problems, its
joys and its sorrows, and everything it involves,'' King says.
``And to do that, you have to be involved. You must be as John
Dunne was many years ago, when he said no man is an island ... when
the death bell tolls, does it not toll for me, for whom the bell
tolls. If any man dies it diminishes me, because I am involved with
mankind. I'm involved with Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did public relations that some people do with all the
things he's doing, you'd see a whole different picture,'' says Shaw
University alum and Stuart attorney Willie Gary, with whom King is
working on a scholarship foundation in Stuart. ``He doesn't look
for the limelight when he's giving, he just does it. He gives and
gives and gives and gives.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 27, he will give the area a third fight card in four
months, this one at Miccosukee Indian Gaming. He already has made
an impact through another gift, a $100,000 donation to former
Florida State Athletic Commissioner Mike Scionti's non-profit
foundation for needy boxers. Gov. Jeb Bush removed Sciont on
Wednesday. An investigation found him guilty of, among other
things, giving King back his promotional license while he was under
indictment, which is against Florida law, and endorsing a change in
state law to allow exclusive promotional contracts, which helped
King in his court battle with boxer Julio Cesar Chavez. King denies
his gift was coercion.
</P>
<P>
   He has always denied, especially after Jack Newfield's 1995
book, Only in America: The Life and Crimes of Don King, detailed
with considerable documentation how he intimidated his way to
prominence: getting what he wants through payoffs, death threats,
mob ties, the race card, and deceptive and restrictive contract
practices, and leaving broke, bewildered fighters in his wake.
Evans _ a former Amsterdam (N.Y.) News reporter _ calls Newfield's
book a ``vendetta,'' though King has not accepted the author's
challenge to sue. The boxing industry's consensus is that most of
the book is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere, Don lost his way,'' says Mike Marley, King's former
spokesman and a boxing journalist. ``At one time, he was a man on a
mission, a businessman who might have had a little bit of a noble
motive. The only blacks in boxing were in the ring, and he came in
the hard way. He excelled. His record speaks for itself.
Unfortunately so do a lot of his abuses of people. He used to say,
`It's for the needy not the greedy.' Over the years, he may have
reversed that phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Marley has seen ``slivers of decency,'' noting King gave Ali
sidekick Drew ``Bundini'' Brown a ``fitting burial,'' and helped
brain-damaged fighter Gerald McClellan financially, though some in
McClellan's family said King didn't fulfill his obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept all criticism,'' King said. ``I'm to blame for the
Johnstown Flood. I'm to blame for the second World War. I'm to
blame for the Lindbergh killing. I'm to blame for everything that
ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The book spawned a movie by HBO Pictures, which shows the
numbers runner beating Sam Garrett to death in 1966 over $600
(King's murder conviction was reduced to manslaughter and he served
less than four years). King calls the film a $9 million commercial.
On the Holyfield-Lewis fight he's again working with HBO, nine
years after bolting for Showtime with Tyson. ``Being on a promotion
with Don is like dating your ex-wife, carefully, and you hope
there's a second date,'' says HBO's Seth Abraham, who lauds King's
work on what is the fastest heavyweight sellout at MSG.
</P>
<P>
   King forgave HBO. He can even forgive lawsuits _ attorney Jim
Beasley recalls being told at a party, ``You're one SOB of a
lawyer, and I like you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has seen King's nasty and playful sides _ Gordon said
King once told heavyweight Greg Page, ``Don't you ever try to
think, I do the thinking. If you ever try to do the thinking again,
I will ruin you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was working as a USA Network broadcaster when King came
into a Las Vegas casino screaming, ``You're killing me, Randy
Gordon! You're killing me!'' Gordon protested he hadn't spoken
about King. ``That's what I mean,'' King bellowed. ``You're talking
about Bob Arum, you're talking about everyone in the world but
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite is happening in Washington D.C., where
Senators John McCain (R-Az) and Richard Bryan (D-Nev) introduced
the Muhammad Ali Boxing Reform Act, soon to be argued in the House.
The bill forces ratings organizations to establish consistent
criteria, limits option contracts with promoters to one year,
prohibits conflicts of interest between promoters and managers, and
forces promoters to disclose complete copies of their contracts to
state commissions.
</P>
<P>
   It strives to save boxing from itself, falling just short of
appointing a federal commission, and many in the fight business _
from trainers Angelo Dundee, Kevin Rooney, Gil Clancy and Emanuel
Steward to former King executives like Scott Woodworth and Sterling
McPherson _ are crying out for salvation. ``Promoters serve a role
in the industry,'' says McCain spokesman Paul Seeney. ``What we are
trying to cut back on are the monopolistic, or egregious, or
anti-competitive business practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-room deals and double contracts _ one signed, the other
blank. The inconsistency of rankings from one alphabet organization
to another _ ratings often influenced by promoters. A promoter's
domination of an entire division for years, by forcing a challenger
to give him future promotional options, should he beat the
champion. The insertion of puppet managers who serve the promoter,
rather than rightly serving their client, the fighter.
</P>
<P>
   King's practices. The practices so constricting they force even
the fighters who sue him, from Larry Holmes to Felix Trinidad, to
return to him. McCain won't say that the bill is aimed at King,
even if many in the Senate Commerce hearing did. King has called it
an anti-King bill. ``As Don tells the federal government, I don't
make the rules, I just play by the rules,'' Woodworth says. ``That
doesn't mean the rules are good.''
</P>
<P>
   King shied from the government this time. ``We invited every
major figure, and we never got a response from King,'' Seeney says.
Allan Grossman, Florida's assistant attorney general, says King was
accommodating when he met with him in Deerfield Beach on behalf of
the National Association of Attorneys General's Boxing Task Force _
which created a Boxers' Bill of Rights and may make recommendations
for amendments to the Ali Act. King couldn't attend the Task
Force's three-day hearing, however, and a spokesman for New York
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer says Spitzer is ``looking forward''
to receiving King's written testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, his appearance in Canastota, N.Y., was testimony to his
impact when he was inducted into the International Boxing Hall of
Fame. ``It is difficult for a fan to walk down boxing's memory lane
with so many world championship fights without seeing the DKP on
programs, posters, fight tickets,'' says Ed Brophy, the Hall's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's in Manhattan for this championship, quoting Kipling,
and Shakespeare, and Paul Revere, and FDR, sliding from phone to
phone on the press table to talk to radio show hosts for nearly two
hours. Sweating, rumpled, asking for water, then grabbing another
phone to tell the world how ``we couldn't paint a seat in if we
were an artist,'' greeting Mexico with ``muy grande, fantastico.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why critics _ even McPherson and Woodworth who have sued
him on behalf of fighters and whom he now calls Judases _ respect
him as a promoter. His ability to block out any noise but his own,
something McPherson tries to do now to make his teacher ``proud''
of him. ``Don paid me a very handsome salary, and what we did for
him was give up our lives,'' Woodworth says.
</P>
<P>
   King's life has become Ali's tactic in that Rumble 25 years ago,
the rope-a-dope. His critics have punched, and punched, and perhaps
someday they'll punch themselves out. For this King, what a
crowning glory that would be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
