<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-INFLATION-660&AMP;ADD     03-12 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-INFLATION-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PRICE SURGE DOES NOT MEAN INFLATION SURGE, ECONOMISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also OIL-TALKS) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The oil price surge this year, which got another boost Friday
with a new agreement on cutting production, is beginning to sting
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline pump prices began to creep up this month. Colder
weather in the Northeast could add to the heating oil pinch. Higher
prices for airplane fuel may make tickets more expensive quickly.
The indirect ripple effects in products, like plastics, that use
oil, will take longer to bite, but will come.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the oil price increase, economists are not
predicting a new surge in inflation across the board. Rather, they
are merely saying that the decline in inflation, which limited last
year's increase in the Consumer Price Index to 1.6 percent, will be
over if the oil price rises stick.
</P>
<P>
   This means, economists said Friday, that the rate of inflation
overall, which includes energy and food prices, is likely to move
up toward the rate for what economists call core inflation. That
rate, which excludes energy and food, is considered by some to be a
better measure of the long-term rate of price increases. Last year,
the CPI's core rate rose 2.3 percent. But, the economists agree,
there is no upward spiral on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should notice but not worry,'' said Gail Fosler,
the chief economist at the Conference Board. ``There is really
nothing in the global environment or the United States environment
that suggests that this is going to spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it remains to be seen whether consumers will get unnerved
when they see reports that prices are moving up rather than holding
steady or declining. Investors might also get disturbed and push
the price of bonds down and interest rates higher. But there was no
sign of this kind of concern in the bond market Friday, as interest
rates on Treasury securities fell and the government's
inflation-indexed bonds were virtually unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The changing outlook for inflation was reflected pointedly in
two separate news events Friday. First, the Labor Department
reported that prices paid to producers fell four-tenths of 1
percent in February. Without energy and food, producer prices were
unchanged. Throughout the report there were signs that the prices
of many goods were still falling.
</P>
<P>
   Oil ministers meeting at The Hague, Netherlands, also announced
that they had the outline of an agreement to cut oil production by
2 million barrels a day. That report pushed up the price of oil for
delivery in April to $14.49 a barrel, its highest since October.
The anticipation of some kind of new reduction in production has
been pushing up the price of oil steadily since mid-February when
it was $11.37 a barrel, just above a 13-year low.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons that economists are not predicting
another general price spiral. One is that the global economic
growth is still sluggish at best. Even if Asia, which triggered a
worldwide financial crisis in 1997 with a series of currency
devaluations, is recovering, Latin America is in decline and Europe
seems to be standing still or slipping.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan Bank is forecasting about 1.5 percent growth
globally this year. Even if stronger than expected U.S. growth
pulls that up to 2 percent, that will be significantly below the
pace of recent years, said James Glassman, Chase's senior U.S.
economist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main driver for all this good inflation news is that we
are not growing at our potential globally,'' he said. The way to
change his mind about the outlook for inflation, he said, was to
have oil prices rising because global demand was picking up.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is that other commodity prices, from cotton to
copper, are at or near their recent lows. The Commodity Research
Bureau/Bridge index of 17 commodities, which fell Friday, is just
five points above its 24-year low, hit at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until there is significant upward pressure on all commodities,
we are not going to have any worrisome price impact,'' said Ms.
Fosler of the Conference Board.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition, while oil prices have shot up 20 percent this year,
they have risen from very low levels and are just back to where
they were last summer or fall, when they were already low. The same
is true for gasoline prices, which were at their lowest level,
after adjustment for inflation, since at least the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the question of whether the production cuts will
hold or have a significant impact. Oil producers are notorious for
cheating, even after agreeing to pump less oil. After the last
major effort to cut production began in March 1998, the price of
oil dropped 36 percent to its low of $10.72 a barrel in December.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is not a new inflation spiral in sight, the
overall inflation rate will rise if the oil price increase holds.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rothman, senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch,
estimates that the price of oil could move up to $17 a barrel soon.
And he said it could possibly move near $20 a barrel by the end of
the year if there was a sustained reduction in production that made
a meaningful dent in the current overload of oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Latta, principal U.S. economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI
in Lexington, Mass., ran an end-of-the-year oil price of $18 a
barrel through her computer model and found the following: The DRI
forecast of a 1.8 percent rise in the CPI, year-over-year, in 1999
inches up to 2.1 percent. And if the oil price held there, the CPI
would increase 2.8 percent in 2000 and 2.6 percent in 2001, before
slipping back to 2.4 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   This is above the 1.6 percent increase for 1998. But the number
is less startling when compared with the 2.3 percent increase in
the CPI in 1997 and the 3 percent rise in 1996. In addition, the
forecasts are close to the increase in the core CPI, without the
volatile elements of food and energy, which rose 2.3 percent in
1998, 2.4 percent in 1997 and 2.7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   All this leads Ms. Latta to agree with the other economists on
the recent rise in oil prices: ``It is not going to have much of an
impact on inflation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
