<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RJR-NABISCO-NYT &LR;      03-12 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RJR-NABISCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICAHN NAMES HIS OWN BOARD IN FIGHT FOR CONTROL OF RJR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving forward with his bid to gain control of RJR Nabisco, Carl
C. Icahn Friday named a nine-member board of directors that
includes Icahn himself and several officials of companies he owns.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn announced Thursday that he would challenge RJR's
management over which part of the company to spin off.
</P>
<P>
   RJR's chairman and chief executive, Steven F. Goldstone,
announced plans on Tuesday to sell the company's international
tobacco division and set up its domestic tobacco operations as a
separate, publicly traded entity. That would take RJR out of the
cigarette business, and leave it with an 80.6 percent stake in
Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   But Icahn wants the company to spin off the food business and
leave the domestic tobacco division inside the holding company. He
has argued that doing so would increase shareholder value more than
Goldstone's plan, although Goldstone says a food spinoff cannot be
done.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for RJR said the company had no comment on the
proposed board, which includes two people Icahn persuaded to serve
on an alternate board when he sought to take over the company in
1996. Shareholders will vote on which board should run the company
at its annual meeting in Winston-Salem, N.C., on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   The notes accompanying Icahn's filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission say that the board will run ``on a platform
that advocates the prompt spinoff of Nabisco to stockholders.''
Icahn said Thursday that he hoped to keep the proxy fight focused
on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Icahn, the proposed board includes four executives or
directors of companies he owns. They are Russell D. Glass, the
president of Icahn Associates; Martin Hirsch, a vice president of
American Real Estate Partners LP, a partnership controlled by
Icahn; Robert J. Mitchell, the vice president of Icahn &AMP; Co., and
Jack G. Wasserman, a lawyer who is a director of several Icahn
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman was named to the alternate board filed by Icahn in
1996, as was Seymour C. Fliegel, an educational consultant and
senior fellow at the Center for Educational Innovation in
Manhattan, who is also on the list this time.
</P>
<P>
   The other proposed directors are Jerome M. Becker, 63, a lawyer;
Harold First, 62, a self-employed financial consultant, and Felix
Pardo, 61, chairman of Dyckerhoff Inc., Glen Falls, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
