<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAWEST13-COX     03-12 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAWEST13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators get crash course on Weber State
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Don't blame the Florida Gators for not knowing much
about Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe them, either, when they say they weren't expecting
to play third-seeded North Carolina in tonight's second-round West
Regional game of the NCAA Tournament in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   That went awry, of course, when 14th-seeded Weber State knocked
off the big-name Tar Heels late Thursday night to send North
Carolina, which was making its 25th consecutive NCAA appearance, to
its first first-round loss since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say the Wildcats got the Gators' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our coaches are big on watching film,'' Florida freshman guard
Teddy Dupay said. ``We'll probably be looking at film right up to
the time we go out to play.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Gators will be x's-and-o's prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become very, very educated on Weber State overnight,''
Florida coach Billy Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoops eductated, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the Gators
</P>
<P>
   (GT)please begin ital(GT) really
</P>
<P>
   (GT)please end ital(GT) know Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, probably, do you.
</P>
<P>
   A quiz is therefore in order. Answers are provided below.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Where is Weber State located?
</P>
<P>
   A) Flagstaff, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   B) Ogden, Utah
</P>
<P>
   C) Cheney, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   D) Aurora, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What is the correct pronunciation of the name of the school?
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Which former NBA coach, who won a title with the Washington
Bullets and is fourth on the league's all-time victory list (six
ahead of the Heat's Pat Riley at the moment), coached at Weber
State for six years beginning with the 1962-63 season?
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What's so big about the Big Sky Conference in which Weber
State plays?
</P>
<P>
   Q.: When was the last time Weber State played in the NCAA
Tournament?
</P>
<P>
   Q.: How did the university get its name?
</P>
<P>
   (GT)center bullet(GT)
</P>
<P>
   1. Weber State is located in Ogden, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   2. The name of the school is spoken with a long first E, which
makes the pronunciation sould like Weeeber State.
</P>
<P>
   3. Dick Motta.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Big Sky houses teams from seven states stretching from
the U.S.-Canada border to the U.S.-Mexico border and from the
Pacific Ocean to the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   5. The Wildcats beat Michigan State in the 1995 first round
before losing to Georgetwon in their next game.
</P>
<P>
   6. Legend has it that the area around Ogden, Utah, was a
fur-trapping territory in the 1820s and a man named John Weber
explored the river and valley now bearing his _ you ready? _
mispronounced name. As the name of the river was passed on over
subsequent years, it was frequently called the Weaver River by
trappers who had never seen the name in print. The subsquent result
was a translation to Weber, rhymes with Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   (GT)center bullet(GT)
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida locker room Saturday afternoon, most of the
Gators insisted they knew how to pronounce the name of their
upcoming opponent even before having it drilled into their heads
during those aforementioned film sessions. And all of them knew
Utah was Weber State's home, though they were mostly off on the
Ogden part of the location.
</P>
<P>
   Not, on the other hand and side of the country, that a lot of
the Weber State players knew Gainesville was Florida's specific
home.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is that a team such as Weber State becomes
something of a password for NCAA Tournament anonymity, and grows in
fan appeal after pulling off an upset of, say, a North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is always asking me where Weber State is,'' said
Wildcats junior guard Eddie Gill, who, by the way, didn't know,
either, when he was a Colorado prep star. ``Maybe they won't ask so
much now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill _ he's The Thrill _ played 40 minutes agaist North
Carolina, and scored 16 points in support of Harold Arceneaux _
he's The Show _ who rocked the Tar Heels for 36 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats also feature center Andy ``Big Bus'' Jensen, so
named because he catches a 5 a.m. ride to campus on such
transportation most days.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kind of storylines that develop when a Weber State
takes an unlikely step through the tournament bracket. There is a
momentum gathered in the process that won't, for example, manifest
itself for a 13th-seeded Oklahoma in the wake of its Friday victory
over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Oklahoma is too easily identifiable.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a Detroit or a Southwest Missouri State or a Creighton
or a Gonzaga. Or a Weber State, which gave KeyArena, in Jensen's
words, the feel ``of playing a home game'' while the Wildcats were
beating North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's Florida's turn to be big, bad wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why coaches in Donovan's position are so effusive with
their praise for a Cinderella opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really good, regardless of whether they've gotten
enough exposure'' he said. ``I think our guys respect them for what
they've done. You don't just show up, walk out there and beat North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   He and the Gators do know that much about Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
