u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL-725     03-12 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA REJECTS TRIBUNAL FOR KHMER ROUGE KILLINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of wavering, Cambodia Friday officially
rejected U.N. recommendations to convene a tribunal to try
surviving senior Khmer Rouge leaders, seeming to kill any chance of
an international court.
</P>
<P>
   Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's foreign minister, flew to New York and
informed U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan that Cambodia would hold
a trial of Khmer Rouge leaders in its own courts. He said he would
ask for international assistance to insure that the proceedings
would be ``fair and transparent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that what we are doing now is in conformity with
the convention on prevention and punishment of genocide,'' Hong
said in a later interview, pointing to the convention's article
that allows for a ``competent tribunal'' to be convened in the
country where the crimes occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have asked for international jurists to help us to ensure
it meets international standards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The minister also announced that his government has rejected the
recommendation that a truth commission be convened to try lesser
figures in the Khmer Rouge movement.
</P>
<P>
   The official rejection was announced days before the secretary
general was scheduled to make public the recommendation of a panel
of experts that the United Nations convene a tribunal to try a
dozen or more senior Khmer Rouge leaders outside of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of coordinated steps, the Cambodian government first
captured Ta Mok, the last fugitive senior Khmer Rouge figure,
announced that he would be tried in a military court in Phnom Penh,
and then dispatched the foreign minister to the United Nations to
head off the building movement for an tribunal before the release
of the U.N. report.
</P>
<P>
   With this strong rejection by Prime Minister Hun Sen's
government, the Security Council is unlikely to approve a separate
international tribunal, according to diplomats. China already has
said it will oppose a tribunal if the Cambodians oppose it. France
has given Cambodians assurances it will assist in a Cambodian
military trial to ensure that it meets international standards,
according to diplomats close to the Cambodian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambodian trial would cover the period from 1975 to 1979
when the Khmer Rouge governed Cambodia, taking the lives of 2
million Cambodians.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his government's stance with the secretary
general, Hor Nam Hong said the Cambodian courts would not restrict
themselves to the trial of Ta Mok alone. The court has the
authority to ``to try the whole Khmer Rouge organization and other
Khmer Rouge leaders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally do not believe Ta Mok will accept full
responsibility for the genocide and that he will reveal other names
of people to be tried,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After their meeting, the secretary general's spokesman said
Annan still had concerns about Cambodia's judicial system and its
ability to meet the minimal standards of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a show trial that brings neither truth nor
justice,'' said Stephen Heder, a professor and Cambodian scholar at
the School of Oriental and African Studies. ``At the end of the day
all the questions will be unanswered and all the suspicions left in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cambodian foreign minister disagreed and said the Cambodian
courts planned to use the evidence amassed with the support of the
United States by the Cambodian Documentation Center in its quest
for a ``transparent and fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind his country's determination to hold the Khmer Rouge trial
in Cambodian courts, Hor Nam Hong said, is the lingering anger over
the international community's refusal to punish the Khmer Rouge
when they were overthrown by the Vietnamese in 1979 and throughout
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the peace negotiations that led to the 1991 Paris
Peace Accords,'' said Hor Nam Hong, who was a principal negotiator
for the Hun Sen government. ``The international community forced us
to accept the Khmer Rouge as equal partners and forbid the use of
the word `genocide' in any peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Khmer Rouge refused to comply with the 1992 U.N.
peacekeeping effort created by the 1991 accords, and it was only
with the capture of Ta Mok last week that the government put an end
to what remained of the Khmer Rouge movement. Pol Pot, the top
Khmer Rouge leader, died last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nuon Chea, his second-in-command, surrendered in December with a
fellow Khmer Rouge leader, Khieu Samphan, to the Cambodian
government. All told, at least 10,000 Khmer Rouge soldiers and
officials have defected to the government since the Paris accords
of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to these defections, Hor Nam Hong said he told the
secretary general that the Cambodian government ``has achieved what
the United Nations peacekeeping plan and the Paris Peace Accords
failed to achieve'' and should be respected for accomplishing this
``national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general then reminded the Cambodian foreign
minister that Hun Sen requested help in 1997 to establish an
international tribunal and suggested that ``it would be good for
the image of Cambodia to cooperate with that recommendation,''
according to Hor Nam Hong.
</P>
<P>
   But the foreign minister said he demurred and underlined his
government's concern that a trial of all the senior Khmer Rouge
leaders by an international tribunal would upset the newly won
``reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. panel of experts recommended an international tribunal
precisely because the situation in Cambodia still was volatile and
the courts too inadequate to handle such a complex case. In his
1997 letter requesting the aid of the United Nations in setting up
a tribunal, Hun Sen said his country did not have the ``resources
or the expertise'' to conduct a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Hor Nam Hong said Friday that with the help of international
jurists, Cambodia could try the Khmer Rouge in the country where
``we were all their victims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has pushed for an international
tribunal for the Khmer Rouge and supplied critical financial
support for the gathering of evidence against them. David Scheffer,
the U.S. ambassador for War Crimes, met with Hor Nam Hong Friday
afternoon but failed to persuade the Cambodian to approve of an
international tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him we were grateful for the United States help,'' Hor
Nam Hong said, ``but we had to respond to the interests of the
Cambodian people and there is nothing else we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
