<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-PIONEER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS FORESEE BIDDING WAR OVER IOWA SEED CORN COMPANY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Switzerland)   By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pioneer Hi-Bred International, the world's largest producer of
seed corn, and DuPont Co. announced Friday that they were
discussing a possible combination, raising the prospect of a
bidding war in the agriculture industry.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the discussions was seen by some analysts as
an indication that Pioneer is eager for a deal _ either with DuPont
or with another company. Neither Pioneer nor DuPont would say
anything more than that they were talking.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the disclosure of the talks could prompt rival
bids for Pioneer from several of the world's largest producers of
agricultural products _ notably the Swiss giant Novartis _ if there
was not another bid already on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement about DuPont and Pioneer came out of left
field,'' said Robert F. Goldberg, an executive vice president of
the research firm New Vernon Associates. ``What could be happening
is that there is another company making overtures at Pioneer, and
DuPont wants to bail out its shareholders as a white knight.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Pioneer, which had reached a 52-week low on March 3,
soared 40 percent, or $9.8125, Friday to close at $34.3125.
DuPont's stock dropped 37.5 cents to close at $57.75.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Friday that several components of the disclosure
were puzzling. Several pondered why Pioneer and DuPont appeared to
be in such a rush to make a deal, and why the two companies would
want to increase their already close association.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, based in Wilmington, Del., owns 20 percent of Pioneer,
which is based in Des Moines, Iowa. The two companies are also
partners in a joint crop biotechnology venture, Optimum Quality
Grains. They reached an agreement in 1997 that DuPont would not
increase its position in Pioneer for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year agreement can, of course, be altered. But then there
is the matter of how a deal may be done. DuPont has stated that it
does not want to dilute its stock or hurt earnings in making any
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   If DuPont acquires Pioneer, a company roughly one-twelfth its
size, the company will have to overcome several obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, DuPont announced that it would establish a tracking
stock to allow investors to bet on the performance of one part of
the company. DuPont had intended to use the tracking stock to make
acquisitions, primarily in pharmaceuticals and in agribusinesses.
</P>
<P>
   Its interest in pharmaceuticals and agribusiness has also led
DuPont to discuss a possible merger with Monsanto, a large
biotechnology and seed company and the parent of the drug maker
G.D. Searle, executives who have been briefed on the negotiations
have said.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont had known about the negotiations with Pioneer when it
announced its plans for a tracking stock, analysts said. Yet the
stock will not be established until later this year, well after any
deal with Pioneer should be solidified.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, DuPont may have little choice but to pay cash for
Pioneer. Since DuPont owns a 20 percent stake in Pioneer, it will
face a huge tax bill should it pursue a cash deal.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont may face other hurdles. The founder of Pioneer, Henry
Agard Wallace, left the family fortune to his two children, Jean
Wallace Douglas and Robert B. Wallace. The two siblings own some 14
percent of Pioneer's stock, a stake that was valued at $1.15
billion after Friday's close. Analysts believed the Wallaces were
unlikely to accept a cash proposal for fear of the heavy tax bill
that would go with it.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone messages for Mrs. Douglas and Wallace were not
returned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Pioneer came to DuPont with these discussions,'' said
John McMillin, a food industry analyst with Prudential Securities.
``That's the only way to explain the rush of it. It will be
interesting now which companies are going to be able to take a
bid.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont disclosed the talks on the same day it announced steps to
bolster earnings. It will reduce capital spending 13 percent this
year, to $2 billion, and it plans to overhaul its polyester unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
