<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-FOLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TREASURY AIDE HAD LINK TO BANKRUPT ACCOUNTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert E. Foley, the former deputy treasurer accused of
embezzling $2.4 million from the state, had a close business
relationship with a Wayland accountant who declared bankruptcy
after being ordered to return $350,000 he allegedly stole from a
Newton Centre widow.
</P>
<P>
   Foley and the accountant, Louis J. Pellegrine Jr., operated an
accounting business called Foley &AMP; Pellegrine out of Foley's Natick
offices _ where Foley ran several other business ventures _ for
about four years beginning in the spring of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was sued by BayBank in 1991 after Pellegrine refused to
repay a $65,000 loan that Foley had guaranteed. Foley was also
named as a defendant in the widow's suit against Pellegrine.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1990, the widow, Louise A. Andrews, sued Pellegrine,
alleging he had stolen money she gave him to invest after her
husband Thomas died in January 1986. Court records show Foley was
dismissed as a codefendant in Andrews's suit by stating that ``at
the time of service of the Summons upon him,'' he had none of
Pellegrine's assets under his control.
</P>
<P>
   According to Middlesex Superior Court files, Pellegrine, who had
done the couple's tax returns since 1976, promised the widow that
he could make her 15 percent a year if she gave him $350,000 and
agreed not to touch it for three years.
</P>
<P>
   By 1989, Andrews wanted to withdraw $1,500 a month for living
expenses. Pellegrine allegedly refused to pay or return the money,
saying, ``I don't have the money. You can sue me if you want, but I
will just go bankrupt,'' according to court filings by Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews implored him to return the money. ``I believed you and
trusted you completely, Louie,'' the widow wrote him in February
1990. ``I have to have my money now to live on and to pay my bills.
I can't stand this anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Pellegrine's employees, Harlan Dunn, said in an affidavit
in the case he saw ``numerous accounting irregularities'' at
Pellegrine's business. Dunn said Pellegrine told him he invested
the widow's money ``in an extremely high-risk Israeli real estate
venture.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1990, Superior Court Judge Thomas E. Connolly
ordered Pellegrine to repay the widow $362,000 plus $186,767 in
interest. Pellegrine filed for bankruptcy about a month later.
</P>
<P>
   However, Andrews's attorney, Peter B. McGlynn, successfully
petitioned to block Pellegrine from having his debt to Andrews
dissolved as part of the bankruptcy. Last July, after Pellegrine
had returned only a few thousand dollars, Andrews re-sued
Pellegrine in Middlesex Superior Court to get back more than
$700,000, including interest.
</P>
<P>
   Pellegrine two years ago sold his Wayland house at far below its
assessed value to Richard D. Smith Jr., who was the leasing agent
and part owner of the building on Route 30 where Foley had his
office. Pellegrine, who court records show has a $600,000 Florida
home in his wife Margaret's name, is renting back the Cottage Road
home from Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews has an attachment on the Wayland house, and Friday,
Andrews's attorney, Robert S. Sinsheimer, went to court in an
attempt to void the sale to Smith as a way to get at least some of
her money back. The judge is reviewing the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Pellegrine and Foley could not be reached for comment. Foley's
lawyer, Gary Meyers, who represented Foley in both lawsuits
involving his ties to Pellegrine, said he recalled no details about
their business relationship. Pellegrine's attorney, Lawrence J.
Casey, did not return a call.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Pellegrine told the Globe he had run into financial
difficulties and could not repay Andrews because his investment in
the Ashland Market Basket Plaza that Foley developed in 1989-1991
had ``gone bad.'' The size and nature of Pellegrine's purported
investment in the mall could not be determined Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Through her attorney, Andrews said Pellegrine had told her one
reason he could not pay her back was because Foley owed him
$200,000 that Foley had taken out of their accounting business.
</P>
<P>
   Records at Worcester Superior Court show Foley personally
guaranteed two loans totaling $65,000 that BayBank made Pellegrine
in 1989. After Pellegrine defaulted on the payments, BayBank, now
BankBoston, sued both men in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1992, BayBank won a $58,339 judgment against Foley.
Court papers indicate Foley paid off some or all of the judgment
against him by selling an Ashland condominium that had been
attached by the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
