<SLUG> BC-ONEILL-FBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI PROBED LATE SPEAKER O'NEILL FOR ALMOST TWO YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With an effort that spanned 20 months and a dozen
states and used electronically wired informants, the FBI conducted
an exhaustive political-corruption probe of the late House Speaker
Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. from 1979 to 1981 and concluded he had done
no wrong, newly released records show.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the previously unreported FBI investigation were
released by the bureau to the Globe Friday under the US Freedom of
Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption probe was conducted under the tightest secrecy at
a time when the House speaker was playing a major role in national
affairs as an ally of President Jimmy Carter and, later, a foe of
President Ronald Reagan. Records were kept in a ``Special File
Room'' at FBI headquarters under the code names ``Phoenix Bird''
and ``Quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and his chief of staff, Hamilton Jordan, and James A.
Baker III, Reagan's chief of staff, all said in interviews over the
last year that they did not recall knowing of the FBI
investigation, harboring any doubts about O'Neill's honesty, or
talking to the speaker about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher O'Neill, son of the the late speaker, said his
father was aware of the FBI probe while it was being conducted, and
it was ``a quite uncomfortable experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was quite relieved when it was over, though he did
not have any doubts he would be vindicated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Rowan, a former aide to the speaker whose affairs were
also scrutinized by the FBI during the probe, said he had not known
of the bureau's extensive effort but was pleased with its ultimate
conclusion. ``It's always nice when you haven't done anything,''
Rowan said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agents, prompted by the testimony of a ``reliable
confidential source,'' pursued allegations that O'Neill had used
his political clout to win some $3 million in federal loans and
loan guarantees for projects in which he and his associates had
financial interests. For a time, the FBI suspected that O'Neill had
received $65,000 in kickbacks for his help.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation reached its peak in February 1981, when the
FBI conducted some 25 interviews in a burst of activity, only to
conclude that ``all interviews conducted met with negative results
regarding allegations concerning Congressman O'Neill and the misuse
of his office,'' according to the FBI records.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to take the case to a grand jury were called off, and on
March 30, 1981, the Justice Department attorney supervising the
probe concluded that ``there seems no present basis for continuing
the FBI special (investigation) on Speaker O'Neill predicated on
presently known facts.'' The bureau closed its investigation on
April 6.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the investigation were four government loans or
loan guarantees worth almost $3 million that were given to a
Jamaica Plain psychiatric hospital, a Middleton restaurant, and an
Attleboro nursing home in which O'Neill or Rowan had an interest.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the federal loan guarantees _ made in 1972 to the
Glenside Hospital in Jamaica Plain and in 1971 to the Bristol
Nursing Home in Attleboro _ were the subject of news reports by The
New York Times, the Boston Herald, WBZ-TV, and the Globe in 1977
and 1978. The US Small Business Administration launched its own
probe of the nursing home loan in 1978. But it was not until the
confidential source got the FBI's attention in August 1979 that the
bureau began to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Source . . . advises . . . O'Neill has received payoffs for
his assistance in obtaining these loans,'' the FBI investigators
wrote. In an August 1979 memo, the FBI's Washington field office
requested permission from FBI headquarters to outfit its source
with a transmitter and recording device and to record conversations
with O'Neill and associates.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI informant recorded three hours of conversations with
individuals whose names have been redacted in the files released by
the bureau. From those conversations, the bureau suspected that one
or more of O'Neill's associates was involved in some unspecified
``illegal acts'' on behalf of the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In ``highly sensitive'' reports to the FBI director's office,
the field agents theorized that O'Neill and his fellow investors in
the Jamaica Plain hospital had misled federal officials about the
ultimate use and beneficiaries of the funds when they applied for a
$1.1 million loan guarantee from the US Department of Housing and
Urban Development and a $1.6 million lease guarantee from the Small
Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agents kept the director's office informed, there
was no indication that any White House officials were consulted on
the probe.
</P>
<P>
   The agents suspected that O'Neill then used his influence to get
the federal guarantees, boosting the value of the hospital's assets
at a time when he and his fellow investors were ready to sell the
property. The sale went through, and O'Neill acknowledged on his
congressional financial disclosure forms that he made $108,000 on
the deal. The FBI, however, initially valued O'Neill's interest at
$43,000 and suspected that the other $65,000 was a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of two years, the FBI concluded that the Glenside
probe had ``ended with negative results.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bristol Nursing Home in Attleboro and the Country Squire Inn
in Middleton each received Small Business Administration loans or
loan guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   SBA investigators had concluded that the application for the
nursing home had contained ``false statements as to the
ownership,'' and complained to the FBI that O'Neill's lawyers had
challenged and forced changes in their final report. But they also
told the FBI they ``had no information that O'Neill limited or
applied pressure to inhibit the results of the investigation.'' An
IRS agent audited the nursing home's returns and examined O'Neill's
income tax return to verify that he had reported income from the
nursing home, and no wrongdoing was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill did not have an interest in the Country Squire Inn, but
Rowan did. The FBI investigation of O'Neill spun off a separate,
Boston-based arson probe in 1981 after the restaurant burned down.
</P>
<P>
   Like most raw FBI files, the ``Phoenix Bird'' records included
unsubstantiated charges _ in this case rumors of organized crime
connections that sent FBI investigators to work in Louisiana,
Florida, and Nevada _ and moments of low comedy, as in the report
of one woman the agents sought to interview, who told the FBI she
was taking a bath and didn't want to talk to them, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
