<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROFESSOR IN NANJING TAKES UP JEWISH STUDIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: China , Israel, Utah, Ill., Mass.)   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a time when advances in communication and an
increase in political freedom have eroded international boundaries,
scholars have an ever-greater opportunity for closer attention to
religions and places that might once have seemed vastly distant.
</P>
<P>
   So, should it be surprising that a Center for Judaic Studies has
sprung up in a university in central China? Or that Brigham Young
University, owned by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints, has begun publishing a series of bilingual (English and
Arabic) editions of classic Islamic philosophical texts?
</P>
<P>
   The center in China is the work of Xu Xin, a professor at
Nanjing University, in the city of that name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I tasted it, I really fell in love with Jewish history,''
Xu said in an interview in New York this week, where he had spent a
few days visiting Yeshiva University, and before he was to go
lecture at Park East Synagogue about the history of Jews in China
in the 19th and early 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   How Xu discovered Jewish history makes an interesting story in
itself, especially considering that nearly all of China's Jews
emigrated before the 1949 Communist revolution, about the time he
was born.
</P>
<P>
   Xu began teaching English-language literature in Nanjing in the
late 1970s, focusing on the work of post-World War II writers.
``Post-war writers were not known in China, so it was our job to
introduce them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His curriculum included Saul Bellow, Bernard Malamud, Isaac
Bashevis Singer. That they were Jewish tickled Xu's intellectual
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to do research to get the background to their
stories,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His interest picked up a decade ago, when he spent two years
teaching at Chicago State University. An American family took him
to synagogue services and to a bar mitzvah, Xu said. He read widely
on Jewish subjects and, before returning to China, visited Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, with help from grants, Xu has edited a one-volume
Chinese edition of an encyclopedia of Judaism, arranged an exhibit
on the Holocaust in Nanjing and returned to Israel to study Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   As a visiting scholar at Harvard University's Center of Jewish
Studies in 1996, Xu was interviewed by the Harvard University
Gazette, which said his academic writing ``includes an essay
comparing the figure of the schlemiel in Jewish literature with the
Chinese figure of the wise fool.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Xu lectured in Israel and was the subject of a profile
in The Jerusalem Post's magazine, which said his interest in
Israeli writers had led him to translate some short stories from
Hebrew into Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Xu's visit to Yeshiva came through a program in international
relations with which Rabbi Arthur Schneier, Park East Synagogue's
spiritual leader, is associated. The rabbi has visited China
several times, going last year to Shanghai, which sheltered
thousands of European Jews in World War II, to donate a Torah
scroll to its historic synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Schneier said that he had met an academic expert in Judaism in
Shanghai but believed that Xu had created something unique in
Nanjing. ``There's no other university in all of China that has a
Jewish studies department,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Xu said he had found considerable interest among his students in
learning Jewish history. He seemed to want to get the word out in
the West about how Jews had fared in China. ``I believe the Jewish
experience in China gives a good reputation to the Chinese, because
we never persecuted them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Brigham Young project, the books the university is
publishing in its Islamic Translation Series, are meant to help
foster a greater understanding of the Muslim world, said Daniel C.
Peterson, an associate professor of Islamic studies who is also
director of the university's Center for the Preservation of Ancient
Religious Texts.
</P>
<P>
   That the work is being sponsored by a Mormon institution,
Peterson said, is ``a little bit of a striking conjunction, I
suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   The first book in the series to be published is ``The
Incoherence of the Philosophers,'' an important work by the
11th-century Persian theologian and mystic Abu Hamid al-Ghazali.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, Peterson said, the book discusses the question of
whether human reason can supplant divine revelation. He has used
the work in philosophical discussions among his own students. ``The
issues he's talking about are still live issues,'' Peterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
