<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-H     03-12 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lewis knows his time is now
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ The bold prediction, a deviation from the normal manner
in which Evander Holyfield approaches an upcoming fight, had
floored Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis responded the way a proper English gentleman should.
Without bravado, Lewis simply called Holyfield's third-round
knockout prediction ``preposterous'' and then questioned Friday
whether the three-time heavyweight champion had gone 'round the
bend.
</P>
<P>
   There was too much at stake for Lewis to go berserk and perhaps
lose focus on the eve of their heavyweight title unification bout
at a sold-out Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the World Boxing Council heavyweight champion, is trying
to become the first resident of Great Britain to hold the unified
title since Ruby Rob Fitzsimmons in 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Quite important, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   It is critical, too, that he could upset the plans of Holyfield
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But this fight, more than any of the previous 35 Lewis has waged
(losing only once), is most important because it could validate his
place among the great heavyweight champions past and present.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my time,'' Lewis said. ``There's a reason for
everything and the reasons that I wasn't able to put my stamp on
things before, whether it was politics or whatever, now it has
finally come time to make my mark and create history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a defining fight for Lennox Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   But as his trainer, Emanuel Steward, has said, ``If Lennox loses
this fight, he'll just be another guy from England with
dreadlocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (36-3, 25 knockouts), the World Boxing
Association/International Boxing Federation champion, will earn $20
million for facing Lewis (34-1, 27 KOs), who will receive $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   While Holyfield-Lewis is the main event, two other world title
bouts are on the pay-per-view card, which gets under way at 7:30
p.m. CST. The main event is expected to start at approximately 10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Newly crowned IBF junior-middleweight champion Fernando Vargas
(15-0, 15 KOs) of Oxnard, Calif., defends against Howard Clarke
(26-10-2, 8 KOs) of West Ham, England, in the top bout on the
undercard.
</P>
<P>
   And James Page (23-3, 18 KOs) of Pittsburg, Calif., puts his WBA
welterweight championship on the line against Sam Garr (25-2, 23
KOs) of Stone Mountain, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a title unification bout in the heavyweight
division since 1987 when Mike Tyson beat Tony Tucker, then the
crown jewel of the now-defunct Houston Boxing Association, to add
the IBF title to the WBA and WBC championships he already owned.
</P>
<P>
   And there hasn't been a fight in Madison Square Garden to
generate the interest and excitement of Holyfield-Lewis since
Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier fought the first time 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot riding on the fight for Lewis, but there is
tremendous pressure on Holyfield, too.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Holyfield also wants to solidify his place in history
beyond joining Ali as the only three-time world heavyweight
titlists.
</P>
<P>
   There have been hints that should he win, Holyfield wouldn't
wait around for another fight with Mike Tyson, potentially the
biggest money-maker available to him. Nor would he be satisfied to
bide his time taking on a succession of pretenders.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, rumor has it that if he fulfills his dream of once more
owning the undisputed championship, Holyfield would fight two or
three more times and then retire to his spacious home outside
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That is of little consequence to Lewis. Although he often has
fought in the United States over the last seven years, there always
has been questions about his courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it amusing in one sense, and I find it offensive in
another sense,'' he said. ``How dare anybody question my heart. I
have never shown anybody I don't have heart. You have to have heart
in the first place to step into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander Holyfield does not have the monopoly on heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Beating Holyfield, said Lewis, would erase the stigma forever.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's prediction, Lewis has said, is an indication of the
``soft'' fight expected of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting enough respect. That just pushes me to win,''
Lewis said. ``I'm ready. I don't like waiting around. I want to get
in the ring. I will go into the ring with one belt, but I'm coming
out with three.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
