</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-LOSSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY LOSSES WON'T TOP $20 MILLION, MASS. TELLS FINANCIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly's office estimates
that losses from the state treasury scandal will likely not exceed
$20 million.
</P>
<P>
   One investigator gave the forecast quietly to jittery Wall
Street investment bankers Tuesday while they were considering
buying $250 million in state bonds. Several firms involved in the
otherwise routine sale wanted to know just how bad the scheme
involving the treasury's Unpaid Check Fund might get before closing
on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators allege that nearly $9 million has been stolen from
the fund, which holds unclaimed state payments. Four men, including
two treasury workers, have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has said he expects his investigation to turn up more
losses. The estimated $20 million figure is based on the
investigation so far, according to Brian Heffron, a spokesman for
the attorney general. The actual amount stolen from the treasury
could be much higher, but prosecutors believe some money could be
recovered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has already recovered $6.5 million allegedly stolen
from the account. Another $2.4 million is missing and may be gone
for good, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The office was asked: `Do we believe that the loss to the
state will exceed $20 million?' And we have said, based on what we
know at this point. . .it would be remote,'' Heffron said. ``But
again, it's based on what we've been able to review so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche, which is
responsible for reconciling the state's books, grew nervous late
last week that poor accounting and the alleged thefts could affect
the accuracy of their figures, which investors consult when buying
state debt.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banking firms involved in the sale also voiced
concern to Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, who sought an answer from
Reilly's office. She got one Tuesday, and the deal closed that
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a discrepancy of up to $20 million (in the state
coffers) that's considered to be a material omission of fact on the
official statement,'' O'Brien said. ``So we've actually had to work
with the attorney general's office to reassure them that there will
not be more than $20 million missing because that will have an
impact on how we sell our bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The word back from Reilly in a March 9 letter was short,
although bound up in legal language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the actual knowledge acquired by the office of the
Attorney General in its review to date of matters related to the
operation of the office of the treasurer, we believe the likelihood
of loss by the Commonwealth in excess of $20 million is remote,''
the letter, addressed to Deloitte &AMP; Touche, said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Unpaid Check Fund, John F. Trischitta, was
arrested last month for his part in the alleged theft of $6.5
million from the fund along with outsider, Martin Robbins, who is
accused of forging documents to siphon the money into an escrow
account at BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   A bank employee notified the attorney general when Robbins later
tried to withdraw those funds, an act that launched the
investigation. That $6.5 million has since been returned to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta's boss, deputy treasurer Robert E. Foley and another
outsider, Thomas Ciliberto, were arrested shortly after, charged
with bilking $2.4 million from the same account.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say they don't know if those funds will ever be
returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
