<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Bako-Astros-HNS &LR;      03-12 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Bako-Astros-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Bako fighting hard but losing the battle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ One mark of a good team is the scarcity of
position battles during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the Astros don't have many. But one they do
have has been a knock-down, drag-out.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner there's Mitch Meluskey, who has the inside track
to the second catcher's spot on the roster, along with Tony
Eusebio. Across the ring stands Paul Bako, whose only hope is to
match Meluskey blow for blow _ and then some.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as being like a heavyweight championship fight,''
Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``You don't usually
beat the current champ unless you knock him out. Bako has to
clearly distance himself from Mitch to win that job at the start of
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey, who doubled and scored twice in Friday's loss to the
Marlins, is hitting .571 with two RBIs in five games. Bako struck
his biggest blow with a grand slam Friday and is hitting .455 with
six RBIs in five games.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the Astros traded veteran catcher Brad Ausmus
was to create playing time for Meluskey. So it stands to reason the
25-year-old switch-hitter would be given every chance to prove the
Astros made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey's up-side potential offers the promise of more offense
than Ausmus. But Meluskey's spring performance will be evaluated
mostly on his work behind the plate, not beside it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitch just needs to reinforce our confidence that he can
handle the defensive part of the job,'' Hunsicker said. ``Unless he
does something during the spring to convince us he's not ready, he
has the advantage to start the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bako starts the season in the minors, Hunsicker has said
he wouldn't hesitate to recall him if Meluskey got off to a slow
start. Nevertheless, it appears Bako will open the season as an
insurance policy at Class AAA New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it sounds like,'' Bako said. ``But that's not how
I'm looking at it. I'm approaching things as if the job is as much
mine as it is anyone else's. All I can do is keep going out there
and busting my butt. I'm sure they can make a pretty fair
evaluation of me, and I think I can help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the minors would be nothing new. Although he didn't
make the club out of spring training, Bako ultimately became the
Tigers' every-day catcher and hit .272 in his first season in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   The confidence he gained from starting 83 of 139 games in
Detroit after his recall seems to have carried over into the spring
and is serving as momentum in Bako's quest to upset Meluskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything to lose the job,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   And he may not be able to do enough to win it.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Bako's best chance of making the opening-day
roster is if Hunsicker goes against his general philosophy and
keeps three catchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless the third catcher can play another position, you
generally shortchange yourself by carrying three catchers,''
Hunsicker said. ``The third one would have to be a better offensive
candidate then some of the other candidates you'd be considering
(for the final spot on the bench).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible _ because of Mitch's offense _ that you could
make a case for that. I wouldn't rule it out, but with the
commitment we have to the people already in place, there's just no
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three catchers has much experience at another
position.
</P>
<P>
   And unless he makes a trade for an extra outfielder, Hunsicker
is committed to giving the final spot on the bench to one of the
outfield hopefuls already in camp. Glen Barker has the inside
track; Ryan Thompson and Alex Diaz also are candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bako, he'll have to keep working for that knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just keep plugging away,'' he said. ``In baseball, you
never know what can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
