<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-OBIT-MENUHIN-SFC     03-12 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-OBIT-MENUHIN-SFCHRON-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC GENIUS YEHUDI MENUHIN DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB GRAHAM  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Violinist Yehudi Menuhin, one of the noblest musicians of the
century and one of its great humanists as well, died yesterday FRI
MAR 12  &LR; in Berlin. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   He was embraced as a son of San Francisco but as a citizen of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Death came ``totally unexpectedly,'' said a family spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He died at the Martin Luther Hospital in Berlin, where he had
been taken earlier in the week suffering from what turned out to be
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin was to have conducted the Warsaw Symphony Orchestra in
Berlin on Tuesday but took ill. His London office said the cause of
death was heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin's enormous international acclaim had its beginning when
he was a child prodigy in San Francisco. He became beloved as a
man, though in some eyes an eccentric one.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York on April 22, 1916, he said he always considered
San Francisco ``home.'' His family moved here when he was 2 years
old. His first violin lessons were in San Francisco _ he began
studies with Sigmund Anker before the age of 4 _ and the assurance
of his professional debut here at the age of 7 seems astonishing to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Paris, Berlin and London soon followed, and there came
a time when there probably was not a Western cq &LR; classical music
lover anywhere in the world who did not know his name.
</P>
<P>
   He added classical Indian music to his repertory as well. And a
little jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Those who could not hear him in person treasured his recordings.
He was the most widely recorded artist of his day _ and the highest
paid _ and his recording of the Elgar Violin Concerto made in 1932
has been available ever since.
</P>
<P>
   When he could no longer play the violin to his satisfaction, he
switched to conducting.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin practiced yoga as well as the violin. He was
health-conscious and an early advocate of organic farming and
alternative medicine. He liked conducting for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   His Ukrainian-Jewish parents, immigrants from Palestine, settled
in the Western Addition district of San Francisco, then a
predominately Jewish section.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, he created controversy when he was the first
Jewish artist to play with the Berlin Philharmonic, under conductor
Wilhelm Furtwaengler, after World War II. He refused to condemn an
entire people for the atrocities of the war.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, he gave hundreds of concerts for American and
Allied troops. After the war, though it was many years afterward,
he played a concert in the fire-bombed city of Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   Menuhin became an advocate of peace and human rights. He
supported dissidents in China and the Soviet Union. He was the
recipient of the 1960 Nehru Peace Prize for International
Understanding.
</P>
<P>
   He was associated with UNESCO, the cultural-scientific arm of
the United Nations, but felt  &LR; freely to &LR; criticized the U.N. when he
felt it was not living up to its obligations. The United Nations,
he once said drily, continues to have ``great potential.''
</P>
<P>
   He was devoted to education, supporting schools for the urban
underprivileged as well as the musically gifted.
</P>
<P>
   He sincerely believed music could change people's lives _ ``if
they're willing to listen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a belief he shared with Beethoven. Another trait he
shared with that fellow musical genius was deafness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
