A8805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT &LR;      03-12 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PEACE EQUATIONS IN KOSOVO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, March 13:
</P>
<P>
   When negotiations on Kosovo resume in France on Monday, Slobodan
Milosevic, the Serbian leader, may find himself isolated in his
opposition to peace. The House of Representatives voted on Thursday
to support sending U.S. peacekeeping troops to enforce a settlement
in Kosovo, removing any doubt about American participation.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the commanders of the ethnic Albanian guerrillas wisely
agreed to accept the peace plan proposed by Washington, its
European allies and Russia. The ethnic Albanians are expected to
sign the deal this weekend. If they do, Milosevic's refusal to
allow international peacekeepers into Kosovo will be the only
remaining obstacle. It is crucial that the countries supervising
the peace talks remain united, and that NATO sustain its resolve to
use force, if necessary, to get Milosevic to sign a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians initially were expected to embrace the
agreement, which may prevent the death of thousands of civilians.
But they left France with the promise only that they would sign
after two weeks of conferring in Kosovo. They now are apparently
prepared to do so, thus allowing NATO to unite on the threat of
force against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. diplomat, has returned empty-handed
from yet another visit to Belgrade, this time trying to persuade
Milosevic to allow 28,000 NATO peacekeeping troops into Kosovo,
4,000 of them American. Few expected Holbrooke to succeed, as
Milosevic senses that NATO countries are unenthusiastic about using
airstrikes. He expects he can divide the West and win concessions _
among them the assurance that he cannot be prosecuted by the war
crimes tribunal. The nations supervising the talks should not let
him dictate the terms of settlement for a conflict he began by
persecuting Kosovo's people.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration feared that the congressional debate
on Kosovo could undermine the peace talks. But Congress had every
right to debate this important issue, and the speeches for the most
part proved thoughtful and serious. The vote was close, but
admirably bipartisan, as 44 Republicans supported the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The House seemed swayed by the need to stop the killings,
prevent the bloodshed from spreading throughout the Balkans and
strengthen NATO as it stands up to Milosevic. Those arguments
should remind the Western nations running the talks of the many
good reasons to remain united in pursuit of peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2220EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-DRUGWAR-NYT &LR;      03-12 0318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DRUGWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DRUG WAR BACKFIRES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, March 13:
</P>
<P>
   Almost 70 years after the failure of Prohibition, the
much-trumpeted ``war on drugs,'' begun more than a decade ago, has
hugely misfired. ``We have a failed social policy and it has to be
re-evaluated,'' says Barry R. McCaffrey, the four-star general in
charge of national drug control policy.
</P>
<P>
   The boomerang effect of the failed policy was richly detailed in
recent articles by Timothy Egan of The New York Times. School
systems deteriorate while tax dollars build new prisons. Municipal
police forces have grown so militarized that drug warrants are
served in armored personnel carriers. Young mothers are imprisoned
for years for simple drug possession. Young black males in
California are now five times as likely to go to prison as to a
state university.
</P>
<P>
   The drug war was created in reaction to a wave of urban violence
triggered by crack cocaine that ignited fears that crack addiction
might spread widely. Surveys now show, however, that the use of
crack, by about 600,000 people annually, has not changed in 10
years. Nor has the general level of illegal drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The best hope for controlling illicit drugs lies in treatment.
Unfortunately, as new prisons have gone up, treatment programs
within them have declined. In their obsession to control drug use
by making war on it, federal and state legislators have turned the
world's greatest democracy into its largest prison system, where
young adults are warehoused and the opportunity to treat them is
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   As McCaffrey says, ``we can't incarcerate our way out of this
problem.'' But we can, he argues, focus punishment on drug dealers,
not drug users, while beginning to treat the hundreds of thousands
of people in prison with drug problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     03-12 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hurdling walls old hat to Maryland's Francis
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ This time, when the first-round music stopped
and there was no reason for the Cinderellas from tiny Valparaiso to
waltz on at the Big Dance, coach Homer Drew still left the floor
with a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a quick and decisive 82-60 loss to Maryland that had
none of the drama or joy of last year's stunning victory over
Mississippi in which son Bryce, the Rockets rookie, beat the buzzer
with the shot that would win an ESPY Award, there was reason for a
basketball coach to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to Steve Francis and shook his hand,'' Drew said.
``I just wanted to tell him that it won't be long before they're
calling him Sir Francis at the next level in the NBA. I don't think
there are any walls he can't climb.''
</P>
<P>
   There never have been walls that could hold Francis back.
</P>
<P>
   Not the solid walls of a cramped elementary school gym in Takoma
Park, Md., that were barely a foot beyond the baseline of the court
where a young kid tagged along with his older brothers and was
often sent headfirst into the cinder blocks after a driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   Not the just-as-hard walls of family tragedy, injury,
bureaucracy and his own academic indifference that kept blocking
Francis' path to the spotlight of the game. Maryland is his sixth
campus in six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of times over the years when it looked as
if Francis would never make it out of those dark shadows. Yet here
he is, finally in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Francis played just one season of high school basketball as a
5-3, third-string sophomore. He transferred to another school the
following year, sat out to become eligible as a senior, then
promptly broke his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hardest blow was still to come when his mother died of
cancer in 1995 at age 39. Francis left school, withdrew inside
himself, retreated from life and from friends. But he never gave up
on the game and his hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom taught me to be a man and not to run away from my
problems,'' he said. ``For a while, I thought maybe it wasn't meant
for me to go to college and play ball. But I just continued along
the way on my journey.''
</P>
<P>
   A long and unusual one. The little guard sprouted up a foot in
two years, but the only ball he was playing was at a gym in the
basement of a firehouse. He would play against the firefighters,
who were often called away in the middle of a game when an alarm
would ring.
</P>
<P>
   He became one of those playground figures whose reputation
spreads by word of mouth. People who had never even laid eyes on
him would talk about the amazing things he'd done on a basketball
court. Like the time he notched a quadruple double in a junior
college game. Or the time he scored 42 points in a half of a game.
Or the time he used his 43-inch vertical leap in a pickup game to
gather in an alley-oop pass and slam home a dunk over the head of
6-10 NBA star Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   Before he pulled on a Maryland uniform for the first time last
fall, he had been named to the All-Atlantic Coast Conference first
team by several writers. Traveling from a military academy in
Connecticut to junior colleges at San Jacinto and Allegany (Md.),
Francis had become an urban legend.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Terps lost 6-10 senior center Obinna Ekezie with a
torn Achilles' tendon on Feb. 9, Francis wouldn't let them stop,
and they entered the Tournament ranked No. 5 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The hype has been so great, you half expect a trail of sparks to
follow him up and down the court. Yet his game is more fine silk
than glittery sequins. He led Maryland to the win over Valpo with
just 15 points and seven assists while getting all of his teammates
involved in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the next game will be mine to shoot,'' Francis said. ``I
do whatever it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Always has. Once in a rec league playoff game at Takoma Park,
Francis got the winning basket when he defended an inbounds pass,
asked a gullible opponent to ``check'' the ball and then converted
the gift turnover. In a summer league game, he fed a pass for the
winning hoop to a teammate whom he had set up in a hiding place
behind one of the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he can take over a game by running, jumping, leaping,
dunking, filling up the hoop. But he doesn't feel the need to do it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the package with Steve,'' said Terps coach
Gary Williams. ``He keeps us very unselfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Terrapins head into today's second round against upset
winner Creighton trying to get past the Sweet 16 for the first time
in a generation and maybe even to the Final Four for the first time
ever. Without Ekezie, it's a big obstacle for Steve Francis.
</P>
<P>
   But after all he's been through, what's one more wall?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
