<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOME MAJOR OIL PRODUCERS AGREE TO CUT PRODUCTION
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of major oil producers, hoping to capitalize on
their modest success in stabilizing world oil prices, announced
they had agreed to reduce production by another 2 million barrels a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predicted that if the cuts were carried out as
promised by April 1, and if nascent signs of an economic recovery
in Asia were realized, a steady recovery of crude oil prices could
be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   DOW FALLS AFTER NEARING 10,000
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average paused in its climb toward
10,000 as technology stocks suffered. The Dow came within 42 points
of 10,000 before giving up ground and closing at 9,876.35, down
21.09. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 3.09 points,
to 1,294.59. The Nasdaq composite index fell 30.72, to 2,381.53.
</P>
<P>
   ICAHN PROPOSES RJR NABISCO BOARD
</P>
<P>
   Carl Icahn, moving forward with his bid to gain control of RJR
Nabisco, named a nine-member board of directors that includes
several officials of companies he owns.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN PLEDGES SUPPORT FOR NISSAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government sent the clearest signal to date that
Japan would not allow automaker Nissan Motor to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE AIRLINES ARE INCREASING FARES
</P>
<P>
   Five of the country's major airlines raised their fares late
this week, though the price increase could be short-lived if three
other carriers do not match them. News of the attempted fare rise
sent some airline stocks soaring on a day when they normally would
have fallen because of a jump in the price of oil.
</P>
<P>
   STRIKE ROILS ECUADOR'S ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices more than doubled in Ecuador, and some bank accounts
were frozen after a two-day strike that paralyzed commerce.
</P>
<P>
   RESIGNATION HELPS GERMAN MARKET
</P>
<P>
   The German stock market soared one day after the abrupt
resignation of Oskar Lafontaine, the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   CATERPILLAR SAYS ITS PROFITS WILL LAG
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar, the maker of construction and earthmoving
equipment, warned that its first-quarter profits would be far below
expectations. It cited a sales slowdown in Latin America and stiff
competition in North America. The news caused the company's stock
to tumble 12.2 percent. Caterpillar has been suffering through a
gradual decline in sales and profits over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY CONTRACTS IN JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese economy was still shrinking in the fourth quarter
of last year, the government reported, despite a surge in public
spending that was meant to help start a recovery. The decline, at
an annual rate of 3.2 percent, was a surprisingly sharp drop that
extended the economic contraction to a record five consecutive
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PLAN FOR RUSSIAN DEBT
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston, the largest holder of Russia's
defaulted Treasury bills, rejected the current terms of debt talks
accepted by some major banks and issued its own plan, according to
a document sent to investors.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE GROUP FAULTS SUBSIDIES
</P>
<P>
   The World Trade Organization ruled that subsidies in Brazil and
Canada unfairly helped aerospace companies such as Empresa
Brasileira de Aeronautica and Bombardier.
</P>
<P>
   REORGANIZATION OF MICROSOFT SET
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it would soon announce a reorganization, creating
four groups based on customer service instead of the current three
based on technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
