r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIAMI-OHIO-WASHIN     03-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-OHIO-WASHINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI OF OHIO'S WALLY WORLD ECLIPSES WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Considering the distance the Washington Huskies
traveled for this, someone should have at least informed them of
the change in plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies might have thought they were in the Superdome for a
first-round NCAA Tournament game in the Midwest Region yesterday.
Actually, they were rounded up to serve as featured foils in the
Wally Szczerbiak Show.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with seconds remaining _ and despite a 43-point bombardment
from the Miami of Ohio forward _ there was still a chance. There
was a loose ball and a last, desperate shot, which was ... blocked
by Szczerbiak.
</P>
<P>
   The play preserved a 59-58 victory for the RedHawks (23-7) and
produced a deadpan response from Miami coach Charlie Coles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I thought it was a very exciting basketball game,'' he
said, ``despite the score.''
</P>
<P>
   It also produced a memorable duel between two players of proud
lineage _ Szczerbiak, whose father, Walt, played professionally in
the ABA and Europe, and Washington's Donald Watts, son of former
Seattle SuperSonics guard Don ``Slick'' Watts.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Watts performed admirably, scoring 28 points and keeping
Washington (17-12) in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It paled in comparison, however. Szczerbiak finished the day
with 43 points, 12 rebounds, two assists, three blocks and a steal.
He hit five 3-point shots and played all but 49 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies put three different defenders on him and used three
defenses, but nothing worked for long on Szczerbiak, who said the
dislocated knee he suffered two weeks ago is feeling fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he always plays like this,'' said RedHawks guard Damon
Frierson, who had 12 points and two steals. ``Toward the end of a
close game like this, you just feed him the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   At one crucial juncture, Szczerbiak came up with a rebound, a
steal, an assist and a 3-pointer in a span of 15 seconds. But when
he missed a short jump shot with 25 seconds left, the Huskies had a
chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   Washington brought the ball upcourt, but as Watts was moving in
for a shot in the key with 10 seconds left, Miami's Anthony Taylor
knocked the ball out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing scramble, Washington's Greg Clark (brother of
Detroit first baseman Tony Clark), came up with the ball. But as he
rose to shoot, Szczerbiak rose with him.
</P>
<P>
   For his final act of the day, he blocked the shot, recovered the
ball, and clung to it while the last two seconds ran off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had set a screen and I was getting ready to help on
Watts, when we knocked the ball loose,'' Szczerbiak said. ``I just
went up with Clark, and got a piece of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't stop that guy alone _ we all did. Maybe the
scoring total doesn't look like it, but this was a team effort. A
big part of this win was the job we did on Todd MacCulloch, and
that was mostly John Estrick and Mike Ensminger _ they stood in
there and banged heads with a 280-pounder.''
</P>
<P>
   The RedHawks' defensive plan had been to stop MacCulloch, the
Huskies' 7-foot center who came in averaging 19 points. He scored
11 yesterday, but only two came in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Coles, ``now we have to play Utah. We got two
guys who took 45 shots today and scored 55 of our points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means I have a day and a half to teach the other three
guys how to shoot.'' \Ntagtop:Whit Canning, (817) 390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
