<HEADER>
A8816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-Rockets-Cavaliers     03-12 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-Rockets-Cavaliers-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets' Barkley nears elite company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Rockets guard Michael Dickerson lowers himself into a shooter's
crouch, hands open wide with his arms extended like Oliver Twist
pleading for just one more.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson is performing a basketball pantomime, waiting for a
pass from the low post as if Charles Barkley across the locker room
was waiting for just the right time to bounce the ball across the
carpet to Dickerson at an imaginary 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets the ball inside, I'm always like this,''
Dickerson said, readying himself like a gunslinger. ``When other
guys get it, I'm (hands on hips and standing straight) `OK, OK.' I
know when he (Barkley) gets the ball inside, when I'm open, he will
pass it. When I cut, he will pass it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls me his little parakeet because he's feeding me. I'll
be his parakeet if he keeps passing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson has been the benefactor of Barkley's low-post largesse
for a month. But that's enough to put him in a very large club.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley gets his first assist tonight against the Cleveland
Cavaliers, he will become the third player in NBA history with
20,000 points, 10,000 rebounds and 4,000 assists. The others:
Kareem Abdul Jabbar and Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great compliment to be on that list,'' Barkley said.
``Those passes are hard when you're double-teamed. It looks easy,
but it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As an offensive philosophy, it sounds so simple, so basic. If a
player is double-teamed inside, putting two defenders on one scorer
should leave someone open.
</P>
<P>
   Pass to the open man and he'll have an open shot.
</P>
<P>
   But NBA teams, particularly the Cavaliers, have a way of making
that much more difficult. The Cavaliers are especially skilled at
double-teaming from different directions. They move quickly to
switch to the player left open or to the lane a low-post passer
will try to use.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Bullard said of Barkley, ``He's got great vision of
the court. He sees where the double team is coming from. Some guys
just pass out of the double team but it doesn't get a shot. Charles
has a knack of passing it directly to the guy who can get the shot.
Whenever I'm out there, I try to position myself so I'm that guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of times you're not as ready as you should be
With Charles, I'm always ready when he's got the ball. He's keeping
me around in this league. Being a shooter, having a guy like
Charles that can command the double team and score at will so they
have to double team him, really makes my job a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's averages have dipped since his return from knee
surgery to 16.9 points, 13 rebounds and 3.3 assists per game.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged four assists per game before he was hurt, matching
his career average.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his best passes do not result in assists because often
it's the pass after Barkley's that leads to the best open shot. A
better measure might be how often the Rockets' offense has worked
when it begins with Barkley in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rockets' first five games, before Barkley was sidelined,
the Rockets scored or drew a foul on 52 of the 98 plays begun with
Barkley posting up. That play's 53 percent success rate was far
ahead of any other play.
</P>
<P>
   It has worked 63 of 135 times (47 percent) since Barkley's
return, and and 55 of 94 times (59 percent) in the past four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounding is my greatest passion in life,'' Barkley said.
``Passing is something you have to do if they're going to double
you all the time. You've got to make the defense pay. There's
nothing better than getting your teammates easy baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   His passing success clearly begins with attitude, something
perhaps best seen in last week's win in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had seven assists before he took a shot,'' Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich said of Barkley. ``That says it all right
there. I had seven assists in my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees the floor. He understands where they're coming from.
He understands if there's two guys on him, we have another guy
going to the basket. That leaves three defenders (inside). We've
got three guys on the perimeter and they've got only two to defend
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high percentage play and a high scoring play because we
get 3-pointers of out of it. I've always said he's one of the best
ever passing the ball out of a double team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   The last could be as valuable as the passes themselves, because
Barkley can pull rank when it comes to allocating shots. But
choosing to emphasize team success sends a message as directly as
any bounce pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know what a great player he is,'' Dickerson said. ``But
that just shows he's not worried about his scoring, he's worried
about the team. He could have always said, `He's a rookie. He
doesn't need the ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I'm open, he passes me the ball. That says what kind of
guy he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley would argue that there is nothing noble about passing to
the open man. Doing well enough to join a club with only
Chamberlain and Abdul Jabbar merely proves something he said he has
known all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt great about my passing,'' Barkley said. ``It
gives me a lot of satisfaction being a great passer. I started my
second year in Philadelphia, when they started doubling me all the
time. I've just exceeded everyone's expectations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
