u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AIDS-NOTICE-NYT &LR;      03-12 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIDS-NOTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE SETS REGULATIONS ON HIV REPORTING AND PARTNER
NOTIFICATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After months of delay, New York state has moved one
step closer to implementing a new HIV reporting and partner
notification program by issuing long-awaited regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Those regulations appear to close loopholes in the new law,
disappointing some advocates for people with HIV who had hoped it
would limit those who would be identified in the state registry.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law approved by the state Legislature last June,
doctors and laboratories would be required to report the names and
addresses of HIV-positive people, but it was unclear whether the
new program would include those with previously diagnosed HIV.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations, which are to be officially released on
March 17, say that HIV reporting will result from a positive HIV
antibody test, and will also apply to patients who tested positive
before the law was implemented but were seeking routine HIV care.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed regulations from the state Health Department
require that the reports of HIV cases by doctors, clinics and
laboratories include the name and address of the infected person,
their demographic information and the names of any potential sexual
or needle-sharing partners known to the doctor or provided by the
patient.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations, which will undergo a 45-day public comment
period, will also require doctors and government health counselors
to administer a questionnaire to seek information about potential
domestic violence. The regulations also forbid the use of data
gleaned from HIV reporting and partner notification in criminal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the regulations allow hospitals, doctors and
clinics to provide HIV information, if it exists, from their
medical records to someone who has experienced a significant
exposure on the job in those health settings. But the rules do not
allow for someone to be tested for HIV without the person's
consent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new program, the government, health workers or doctors
will be responsible for seeing that partners of infected people
have been warned of their potential exposure to the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But state health officials anticipate that the majority of the
partner notification cases will be carried out by the government
workers. The notifications are to be done in person, with the
identity of the infected person who exposed them never to be
disclosed. The state projects that it will make 22,000 HIV partner
notifications annually.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the program say it is a huge, costly undertaking
with much of the burden falling on local health departments that
are already underfinanced and understaffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when resources seem to be increasingly constrained,
there is a question about how all of this is going to be done and
the quality of work,'' said Jeffrey L. Reynolds, the policy
director for the Long Island Association for AIDS Care.
</P>
<P>
   But even as many advocates for infected people agree that the
time has come to monitor HIV cases in New York state to better
track the epidemic, they say they are troubled by how the program
will be carried out. Some advocates fear that the regulations will
have the counterproductive effect of deterring HIV-infected people
from entering medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulations create significant barriers for people trying
to seek HIV care,'' said Michael Kink, the legislative counsel for
Housing Works, a social service agency for people with HIV. ``It's
a 10-foot-tall concrete barrier to getting care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
