<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LENNOX-     03-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LENNOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLYFIELD PLANNING TO MAKE LEWIS BELIEVE IN HIM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield has spent a good portion of his
career making believers of those who doubt his ability. They said
he would never successfully move up from cruiserweight to
heavyweight. Now, people argue whether he belongs among the top 10
heavyweights of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson's people predicted they would carry Holyfield out in
a coffin after their first bout. Instead, Tyson was the one who had
to be revived after a stunning 11th-round loss by technical
knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis is the latest candidate for conversion. And this
time, Holyfield is the one making the prediction, saying he will
knock Lewis out in the third round Saturday night. It has added to
the intrigue of this fight.
</P>
<P>
   A celebrity-studded sellout crowd of 19,000, more than 5,000
from Britain, Lewis' birthplace, will pack Madison Square Garden
for the fight and perhaps a million or more worldwide will tune
into pay-per-view to see if Holyfield, a slight favorite over
Lewis, can make good on his promise and become the first undisputed
heavyweight champion since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield (36-3), who is the IBF and WBA champion, is so
confident that he will deliver that third-round knockout that he
has not allowed himself to think of anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't have a Plan B,'' he said. ``Plan A has to work, because
I've torn down the bridge. There's nothing else. There ain't no
`What if?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis (34-1), a 1988 Olympic boxing gold medalist for Canada and
the WBC champion, probably cannot stop thinking ``What if?'' A
victory for Lewis would bring the kind of credibility in the
division that he has only dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   He has never faced an opponent with the credentials of
Holyfield, who has fought eight former world champions, and he has
never been involved in a bout of this magnitude. There are
questions about his heart, his courage, his stamina and his
psychological makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time I get to prove myself as the best fighter on the
planet,'' Lewis said. ``To show there's a reason why all those
fighters have been ducking me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said there were questions about Holyfield, who is 36 and
has been involved in several epic ring wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is definitely beatable,'' said Lewis, who is 33. ``His chin
is questionable. He hasn't been hit by a big heavyweight like
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is giving up 31 pounds to Lewis, but he has never
shrunk with fear in the face of a larger man. He won a 12-round
decision against George Foreman, even though Foreman outweighed him
by 49 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Knockout punches aside, the outcome of the fight will hinge on
which fighter is better able to impose his will on the other and
which fighter has more determination if it goes to the later
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has a tendency to sag in the middle rounds, but he is
very determined. Expect Holyfield to try to work inside of Lewis'
long reach, tying him up and trying to catch Lewis with uppercuts.
Holyfield is also a master counterpuncher.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield expects Lewis to try to work his jab and set him up
for the knockout by the right hand. Holyfield said he was not
worried about what Lewis would try to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not concerned about Lennox and what he does well,''
Holyfield said. ``Anything he does, I'm going to use against him.
If he moves well, I'll use that against him. If he doesn't move
well, I'll use that against him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
