<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIDWEST-NYT &LR;      03-12 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA TUMBLES TO OKLAHOMA BY A TOE AND A TIP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Had Michael Wright, Arizona's outstanding freshman
forward, been wearing something smaller than a size 14 shoe, the
Wildcats might well have advanced in the first round of the Midwest
Regional of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the fourth-seeded Wildcats were upset Friday, 61-60, by
13th-seeded Oklahoma, the last at-large team chosen in the 64-team
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (22-7), the 1997 national champion, had its hands full
with the Sooners (21-10). With 48 seconds left in the game, Arizona
had a 60-59 lead and, following an Oklahoma timeout, Wright tried
to throw the ball inbounds. He was about to get the ball to Richard
Jefferson, who turned his back and headed up court. A surprised
Wright had to quickly shift gears and tossed it to another
teammate. That was when misfortune struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``My momentum carried me a little too far,'' said Wright. The
referee's whistle blew and Wright was charged with stepping on the
line as he threw the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the line, oh, only about this far,'' said Wright,
measuring about an inch with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Forget it, Michael,''' said Jason Terry,
Arizona's all-America guard. ``I said, `We gotta stop 'em on
offense.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now Oklahoma had the ball. With around 16 seconds left, Eric
Martin missed a 3-pointer. Eduardo Najera rebounded the ball and
tried to put it back in. The ball seemed to linger on the rim when
the hand of Ryan Humphrey reached up to tap it in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely goaltending,'' said Terry, ``but it wasn't
called, so I guess it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright was his team's leading scorer with 16 points (on 6 of 13
from the field), its leading rebounder, with 12, had the Wildcats'
only two blocked shots and even managed a steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have been in the ball game without a great game
out of Michael Wright,'' said Lute Olson, the Arizona coach. ``He
did a great job, but he made a freshman mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the whole team made a freshman mistake, since there was
obvious confusion on the key play. After all, the Wildcats had just
come out of a timeout. A.J. Bramlett, the team's center, normally
throws the ball in, according to Olson, and the players didn't seem
to be cutting for the ball with purpose. ``But there was some kind
of miscommunication,'' Olson said. ``I'm not sure what exactly
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The upset was another blow for the Wildcats as they suffered
their fourth fourth first-round loss of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Humphrey gave Oklahoma the lead, there were still 10
seconds left in the game. Terry hurried the ball down court. He
shot and missed a fall-away 10-footer with 3 seconds left, Bramlett
missed a tip-in and Richardson put up an 8-foot air ball from the
lane as the buzzer sounded, causing the red-clad Oklahoma Sooners
to go wild.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first NCAA tournament victory for Sooner coach Kelvin
Sampson. ``To say this win was satisfying is an understatement,''
he said. He credited his players with not losing their composure
when they fell behind by nine points.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma will meet the University of North Carolina at Charlotte
in the next round of games here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   UNCC 81, RHODE ISLAND 70
</P>
<P>
   With Rhode Island behind by 60-56 with 4 minutes 31 seconds
remaining in regulation, Lamar Odom, the dynamic 6-10 sophomore,
made a free throw, a turnaround jump shot and tossed in another
free throw to tie the score at 60-60.
</P>
<P>
   The foul that sent him to the free-throw line was the fifth
committed by Galen Young, the 6-7 forward who had done a good job
defending Odom. Young was a force in other areas, as he was his
team's leading scorer, with 17 points, while grabbing 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tip Vinson then sank a 3-pointer to give the 12th-seeded Rams a
63-60 lead. It was frenetic at this point. Kelvin Price, the
muscular center for the fifth-seeded 49ers, put back a rebound to
make the score 63-62.
</P>
<P>
   After a Rhode Island miss, guard Jobey Thomas hit a 3-pointer to
give UNCC a 65-63 lead. With 13 seconds remaining in regulation,
Antonio Reynolds-Dean grabbed a rebound and laid in a shot to send
the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was all UNCC. Marlon Thomas scored the first 5
points and Rhode Island was all but finished. Odom finished with a
team-high 16 points. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
