<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON'T LET ADMINISTRATORS OFF THE HOOK WHEN THINGS GO
WRONG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn . )   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coaches and players had finished their games Thursday and
hurried back to their hotels to watch recaps of the day's upsets of
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament. Detroit
upset UCLA; Weber State upset North Carolina; Gonzaga upset
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   But for at least one coach, this was upsetting for a different
reason than the impact on the office pool. Five hours before
Minnesota's first-round game, Mark Yudof, the president of the
University of Minnesota, announced that two starters and two
reserves were suspended from the team. The action was taken pending
the outcome of an inquiry into allegations that from 1993 to 1998,
a former office manager in the university's academic counseling
unit did course work for at least 20 players in the basketball
program, including four on the current team.
</P>
<P>
   The four players sat at the end of the Gophers' bench during
Thursday's game, wearing matching black and white warm-ups instead
of Minnesota's maroon and gold. The only time they got on the court
was during timeouts, when they peeked in from the edge of the team
huddles. Television cameras moved in on the four, and commentators
discussed the unfolding allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the clip was shown, St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis
became increasingly annoyed. ``I was taught that you're innocent
until proven guilty,'' Jarvis said, ``so I have a problem when
these images are being shown as if you're looking at criminals.
They're not criminals. They're kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The former tutor, Jan Gangelhoff, said her role had evolved from
tutor to actually doing the players' assignments. Most disturbing
was Gangelhoff's admission that she did the work without being
asked. ``The kids didn't ask me, either,'' she told WCCO-TV. ``That
was a decision I made on my own. Basically because of time
constraints, it was just easier for me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an abdication of responsibility that makes her a
perpetrator as well. But NCAA regulations deal only with the
student-athletes, not with an administrator who took matters into
her own hands. We haven't seen Gangelhoff's photo with a scarlet
letter emblazoned across her forehead; we have just seen numerous
shots of four banned players bunched together at the end of
Minnesota's bench.
</P>
<P>
   The overt message is that there continues to be a problem in
this semipro industry. The subliminal message is that these faces
represent what is wrong with college athletes, that these faces
represent what is wrong with sports. But the players are only part
of the problem. The administrators share a large part of the blame.
Punish them. The coach, Clem Haskins, if he is found to have been
involved, should be harshly disciplined. Gangelhoff should be
punished, too.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, once again, the NCAA scapegoats the defenseless. The
players are hung out to dry. University presidents puff out their
chests and use high-profile sports teams to promote themselves. But
when something goes wrong, they put the players in stocks to be
pelted with eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is beginning to pay for the arrogant attitude that too
often treats players, and coaches, as afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last month a judge ruled that Charles Williams, a former
basketball player at the University of Cincinnati, may pursue a
defamation suit against the university. Williams, who played for
the Bearcats in 1996 and 1997, accused it of breach of contract, as
well, after an investigation of his eligibility grew into a
two-year inquiry into the men's basketball team. The NCAA found
that Williams had received under-the-table gifts while he was being
recruited and that Cincinnati's basketball staff improperly had
arranged for him to attend and receive passing grades in summer
school classes. Williams was suspended from the basketball team in
1997, and he later dropped out of college.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last April a federal judge awarded $80 million in damages to
three classes of plaintiffs who had held ``restricted earnings''
coaching positions earlier this decade and sued the NCAA for
illegally setting salary caps.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Monday a judge ruled that it is racially biased to use
minimum test scores to bar student-athletes from scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   So, the tournament is off and running: Weber State, Detroit and
Gonzaga won games they were supposed to lose. Minnesota lost a game
it was supposed to win.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering image of four ostracized Minnesota players,
dressed in black and white, is a poignant snapshot of March
Madness. What a rotten way to go. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
