<HEADLINE>
UTAH USES SIZE TO BURY ARKANSAS ST.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Making its first NCAA Tournament appearance,
Arkansas State had a ride in the fast lane that lasted about 25
minutes yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   After which, second-seeded Utah (28-4) methodically set the
inevitable in motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we kinda fell apart,'' said Indians coach
Dickey Nutt, after his team's 80-58 loss. ``Eventually, their size
just wore us down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians (18-12) did not go quietly, stunning the Utes and
the Superdome crowd with a 13-4 run to open the game, but were done
in by an erratic game and Utah's inside strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a scrappy team, and I was impressed with them,'' Utah
coach Rick Majerus said. ``If they can keep their program going the
way it is now, they'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Utes won their 23rd consecutive game with a 40-24 advantage
in rebounding and 40 points from forwards Hanno Mottola (22) and
Alex Jenson (18). And when they made a change to counteract the
efforts of Arkansas State's 5-foot-5 point guard, Chico Fletcher,
the Indians were done.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians lost the early lead when it went cold for eight
minutes while Utah went on a 19-2 run. In the second half, the
Indians were two points away (41-39) when they went cold again _
going six minutes without a point. By the time they scored again,
the Utes were out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the key was when we switched and put Tony Harvey on
Fletcher in place of Andre Miller,'' Majerus said. ``Tony ...
doesn't have the offensive responsibilities that Andre does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes Andre gets weighted down with having to move
everyone around on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher finished with 21 points, but only six came in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a matter of time,'' Jensen said. ``We were a
lot bigger than they were all across the front line.'' Kansas 95,
Evansville 74 The Jayhawks' victory was enlivened by the crowd
reaction at every appearance of Kansas forward Lester Earl, who was
the center of a scandal two years ago that landed Louisiana State
on probation.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciative fans demonstrated they have not forgotten, booing
Earl's every move while waving money and car keys at him.
</P>
<P>
   In the early going, the sixth-seeded Jayhawks (23-9) had a far
bigger worry _ Evansville guard Marcus Wilson, who scored 18 points
in the first eight minutes, pacing the Purple Aces (23-10) to a
26-15 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas coach Roy Williams then made a change, putting Marlon
London on Wilson, who scored only two more points in the half, as
the Jayhawks took charge. Wilson finished with 34, but this was
Kansas' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take away the first eight minutes, and we were awfully good,''
said Williams, after watching his team shoot 63 percent, forge a
45-15 rebounding advantage and cruise through the second half.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
