<HEADLINE>
MIAMI OF OHIO LEADER SCORES 43 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., N.Y., Utah, Ark.)  (mk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Chagrined by his losing performance in the
Mid-American Conference tournament final, Miami of Ohio's Wally
Szczerbiak came into the Midwest Regional looking to get the sour
taste out of his mouth. He did so by keeping the basketball in his
own hands.
</P>
<P>
   The senior forward from Long Island, N.Y., scored a career-high
43 points in the Red Hawks' 59-58 victory over Washington Friday in
the Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   Tenth-seeded Miami now faces No. 2 Utah on Sunday in a
second-round game. The Utes (28-4) steamrolled past Arkansas State,
80-53, for their 23rd consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, who played with a dislocated kneecap during the
conference final, may now be fighting arm soreness. He launched 33
of Miami's 55 shots, making 18 of them. He had 12 rebounds to lead
both teams. He played all but 33 seconds in the game. He hit the
game-winning shot. And he blocked what could have been the Huskies'
game-winner in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps as surprising as Szczerbiak's dominance was how
little special attention the seventh-seeded Huskies gave him
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the MAC, guys are always hedging on screens, chasing me up
and down the floor and bodying me up,'' he said. ``I was more open
than I've ever been today.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington coach Bob Bender agreed that his team did a miserable
job of getting around the screens Szczerbiak's teammates kept
setting for him. ``And once he got his confidence, he was that much
tougher to stop,'' Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Donald Watts said the Huskies had seen a number of guys
with Szczerbiak's offensive ability, but he lamented that they
could not keep him from finding a comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you let a player of that caliber get into his comfort
zone, he'll burn you,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Szczerbiak, a 6-foot-8-inch, 243-pound senior
forward, noted that he had a number of shots rattle in and out or
he might have exceeded the 54 points he once scored at Cold Spring
Harbor High School in Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak missed 13 of 17 shots in a painful 6-point loss to
Kent in the conference final, hampered by the kneecap. But on
Friday the points came early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the games I can keep up with how many points I have,''
he said. ``Today, I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, which ended its season at 17-12, stayed with a
box-and-one defense through much of the game, with Greg Clark
mostly assigned to Szczerbiak. Szczerbiak said he realized early on
that the Huskies' 7-foot center, Todd MacCulloch, would not be much
of a shot-blocking presence.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Szczerbiak had 21 points as 10th-seeded Miami, now
23-7, built a 29-26 lead. He scored the Red Hawks' winning basket
with 1 minute 10 seconds left, then made the crucial defensive stop
as time was running out. He blocked Clark's jump shot with three
seconds left, retrieved the ball, then threw the ball high in the
air after the game clock reached zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony Taylor did a great job of switching off and forcing
Watts to give the ball up to my man,'' Szczerbiak said. ``I knew
time was running down and I closed out. I didn't want to foul. I
stuck my hand up, got a piece of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And because of it, the Red Hawks live to play another day. But
they may not last much longer.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH 80, ARKANSAS STATE 53
</P>
<P>
   The opener essentially pitted a polished team against an
unpolished one. Utah, runner-up to Kentucky last year, fielded a
starting lineup of 22-year-olds except for the 20-year-old guard
Jeremy Killion. Arkansas State (18-12) may well have had an edge in
athleticism, but began to show chinks after taking a 15-7 lead 6:45
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out intense and we didn't match them,'' Utah forward
Alex Jensen said. ``When we matched their intensity in the second
half, we were able to pull away.''
</P>
<P>
   A 40-24 rebounding edge didn't hurt, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
