<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-EVERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS POWERS INTO EVERT CUP   FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIAN WELLS, Calif. _ With big sister on the singles sidelines,
little sister continued to bask in the limelight Friday as
17-year-old Serena Williams, apparently on a take-no-prisoners
mission to follow Venus into the top five, bullied her way into the
final of the Evert Cup with a 7-5, 6-0 victory over 12th-seeded
Sandrine Testud of France.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's final at Indian Wells, Calif., Williams, who
captured her first tour title two weeks ago in Paris, will face
Steffi Graf, the owner of 106 titles.
</P>
<P>
   The unseeded Williams promises not to be intimidated by Graf,
the 29-year-old icon. ``She's a good athlete,'' Williams said.
``She's fast. I'm fast. I'm a great athlete. It's going to be
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Things continued to be exciting for the underdogs at the men's
Newsweek Champions Cup event, where seven of the top eight seeded
players have vanished. Gustavo Kuerten, the Brazilian who captured
the 1997 French Open and fancies himself as more than a clay-court
contender, secured a semifinal berth against Carlos Moya of Spain
by ousting eighth-seeded Richard Krajicek, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The 550th-ranked Chris Woodruff, a qualifier from Knoxville,
Tenn., beat the seventh-seeded Tim Henman, who double-faulted at
match point. Woodruff reached his first semifinal since 1997 with a
6-1, 1-6, 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-seeded Moya, the highest-seeded player remaining on
the men's side, advanced with a 6-4, 6-4 victory over 12th-seeded
Karol Kucera. Moya, the 1998 French Open champion, can claim the
No. 1 ranking from Pete Sampras by beating Kuerten, against whom he
is 0 for 4 in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, a two-time Evert Cup champion at this dual desert event,
flexed her credentials in January at Sydney, Australia, in her only
prior meeting with the younger Williams sister. But lately,
everything Serena Williams touches has been trouble for her
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's 66-minute onslaught of power tennis against an
increasingly submissive Testud extended the teen-ager's undefeated
streak to a career-best 10 matches. Williams began the tournament
with a straight-set dismissal of second-seeded Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think I'm playing with a lot of confidence; who
wouldn't?'' said Williams, who is ranked 21st.
</P>
<P>
   At the close of her previous confrontation with Testud, a 9-7
third-set loss in the third round of the Australian Open, Williams,
furious about her failure to convert two match points, flung her
racquet at the net before flouncing off the court. But Friday she
was poker-faced concentration from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've finally realized it's not time to play around anymore,''
Williams said. ``Five years from now, there's going to be another
player who's going to be just great; it's not going to be my turn.
So now is the time.''
</P>
<P>
   After scrambling out of a 3-1 first-set deficit and breaking
Testud for 7-5, Williams wasted no time asserting herself in the
second set. Each mistake from Testud, who dropped eight straight
games from 5-5 in the first set, was punished with alacrity.
Williams reached double match point with a down-the-line backhand
pass delivered with a roar, and did a hop at the baseline after
Testud blundered a forehand beyond bounds. &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
