<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO CENTER HAS UCONN'S ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ After the Connecticut basketball players practiced at
McNichols Arena Friday, the two most talked about people were Jim
Calhoun and Kenny Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun is the coach who could not work for a second straight
day because of an intestinal virus, but who plans to be on the
sideline for Saturday's game versus New Mexico. Thomas is New
Mexico's mobile center who could be in UConn's face more than
Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas offered a dazzling display of muscles and moves before
fouling out with 20 points in New Mexico's 61-59 triumph over
Missouri on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Huskies watched part of the thrilling first-round
game that preceded their 91-66 conquest of Texas-San Antonio and
conceded that the 6-foot-8-inch, 260-pound Thomas surprised them
with his skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better than I thought he was,'' forward Kevin Freeman
said. ``He's got the shake and bake. He's got the nice jump shot.
It's going to be a tough matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Voskuhl, who is 6-11 and 245, widened his eyes when he was
asked about Thomas and, suddenly sounding like he was 5-11 and 145,
said, ``He's big.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Thomas big enough and bad enough to lead the ninth-seeded
Lobos (25-8) over the top-seeded Huskies (29-2)? Probably not, but
Thomas' versatility certainly got UConn's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-seeded Arkansas (23-10) will oppose fifth-seeded Iowa
(19-9) in the second game of the West Regional, with the two
winners advancing to Phoenix for the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   When Thomas was told that some Huskies had admired his play, he
coyly said: ``They're being humble. Come on, it's UConn. We just
want to be able to hang with them. If we lose by 10, I'll be
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters doubted Thomas, but he said: ``I mean it. If we lose
by 30 or 40, I don't want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaying UConn will take more than just Thomas, who averages 18.5
points and 9.9 rebounds. The Lobos could be susceptible to UConn's
pressure defense because John Robinson 2nd, a freshman point guard,
can be erratic.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico's defense does not frighten opponents and Thomas, who
has fouled out in four of his seven career NCAA tournament games,
must stay on the court or the Lobos are doomed. Still, Thomas,
contradicted his other comments when he said he was ``not worried
at all'' about the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, it seemed risky that Voskuhl, who has a stress
fracture in his right foot, played 24 minutes on Thursday,
including nine minutes in the second half. Voskuhl said he needed
the court time, but the Huskies would have been forlorn if he had
injured himself in a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to play,'' Dave Leitao, the associate head coach who
replaced Calhoun, said. ``I thought he needed to get a little bit
of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun's virus prevented him from coaching Thursday's game, and
the 56-year-old coach attended Friday's practice but was unable to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I 100 percent plan to be here at 12 o'clock tomorrow to face a
good New Mexico team,'' Calhoun said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
