<HEADLINE>
CINCINNATI CRUISES INTO SECOND ROUND MATCHUP WITH TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins finds his team as
intriguing as everyone else does.
</P>
<P>
   ``From minute to minute I don't know what to expect from these
guys,'' Huggins said Friday after the third-seeded Bearcats
defeated George Mason, 72-48, at the Fleet Center in the first
round of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Cincinnati will play sixth-seeded Temple, which also
grappled its way to the second round of the East Regional Friday
with a 61-54 victory over 11th-seeded Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins understands that there is a certain fascination with his
team, because Cincinnati (27-5) is the only team to have beaten
Duke this season. To that end, it is conceivable that even Duke,
seemingly invulnerable, is watching Cincinnati from the other side
of the East bracket with a wary eye.
</P>
<P>
   But if Duke knows which Cincinnati is going to show up _ the one
that beat Duke back in November or the one that lost three straight
games last month _ Huggins would like to know, too.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as Cincinnati made its eighth consecutive NCAA
tournament appearance, 14th-seeded George Mason shot so poorly that
it should have called itself the George Masons. Huggins did not
learn too much new about his team, not when the opposition made
just 16.1 percent of its shots in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that the Temple game on Sunday may enlighten
Huggins about his team. Good shots will not come easily in a match
of these defensive-minded teams, but victory would be especially
significant for Cincinnati, which has not survived the first
weekend of play in the NCAA tournament in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could come out Sunday and make virtually everything we
shoot, or miss everything,'' Huggins said with his usual humorless
delivery. ``We don't shoot it straight sometimes, but I think we're
one of the best defensive teams in the nation. That keeps us in a
lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Cincinnati does not get to at least a third tournament
game this year, it will become known as a great 1990s college
basketball program with a string of disappointing tournament
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati won 27 games last season and 26 the season before. As
a second-seeded team in 1998 and as a third-seeded team in 1997,
Cincinnati never got out of the second round. The trend is obvious
to all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get through the first weekend to show that we are
a respected program,'' the junior forward Ryan Fletcher said.
``We've had two good regular seasons and we have to show it's not a
fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Success this month would prove that Cincinnati's 77-75 victory
over Duke on Nov. 28 in the final of the Great Alaska Shootout was
also not a fluke. Cincinnati made 57 percent of its field-goal
attempts in that game and forced Duke into 17 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were relentless that day,'' Melvin Levett said. ``That's
what we have to remember. If we can just get that attitude back.''
</P>
<P>
   TEMPLE 61, KENT 54
</P>
<P>
   Temple coach John Chaney, whose team has been in the same NCAA
bracket with Cincinnati for five straight seasons, recognizes
Cincinnati's most enduring on-the-court characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob gets his team to play tough, bordering on arrogance,''
Chaney said, referring to coach Bob Huggins almost admiringly.
</P>
<P>
   Temple was nearly as tough, as Kent made just 34.5 percent of
its shots. Temple's backcourt of Pepe Sanchez and Rasheed
Brokenborough divided 30 points. Sanchez, who missed 10 of 11 shots
in his last game, sank 5 of 8 shots today, including three
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (Fla.) 75, LAFAYETTE 54
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Johnny Hemsley sank eight straight 3-point shots and
nine overall to lead second-seeded Miami to a rout of 15th-seeded
Lafayette in the evening session. Lafayette, the Patriot League
champion, held an early lead before Hemsley made the first of five
3-pointers, staking Miami to a five-point halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hemsley began the second half with another 3-pointer, the first
of 12 consecutive Miami points. He sank two more before missing,
then added another 3-pointer before leaving the game with three
minutes remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-12-99 2331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990312.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-12 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8935 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OKLAHOMA-     03-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-OKLAHOMA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S MISTAKES COSTLY  
 UA BLOWS LEAD TO OKLAHOMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ They didn't stick around long enough to enjoy a good
bratwurst.
</P>
<P>
   But then, there is a lot of that going around among Pac-10 teams
in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had talked a good game, about how it could draw strength
from its seniors, All-America point guard Jason Terry and
all-conference center A.J. Bramlett.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were certain that their successes in close games
all season would serve them well in the tournament, where the vast
majority of games become nail-biters.
</P>
<P>
   But holding a four-point lead and going to the line for two free
throws that could have clinched it with 1:02 minutes left Friday in
its Midwest Region opener against Oklahoma, Arizona conducted a
clinic on how to self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-seeded Wildcats were eliminated by the 13th-seeded
Sooners, 61-60.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inexperience finally caught up with us,'' UA Coach Lute
Olson said. ``That and a bad shooting game are a recipe for
disaster. I hate to see it end this way for our seniors, but we had
our chances and didn't close them out.''
</P>
<P>
   In that fateful final minute, Bramlett missed both free throws.
Then Sooners forward Eduardo Najera (17 points, 13 rebounds, three
steals, two blocked shots) swished a three-point basket over the
upraised arms of the 6-foot-10 Bramlett. That cut Arizona's lead to
60-59 with 48.2 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   UA freshman forward Michael Wright instinctively picked up the
ball to inbound it. Normally, that's Bramlett's job. Wright sets
the screen to free Terry to catch the inbound pass.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who otherwise played a dominating game around the basket
(16 points, 12 rebounds, two blocked shots), thought he could
quickly get it in to Richard Jefferson before the Sooners set up
their full-court defense. Just as Wright began to pass, Jefferson,
who wasn't expecting it, turned to run downcourt. Wright tried to
catch himself before throwing the ball away, but his momentum
caused him to step across the end line, a violation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners took the lead with 10 seconds remaining when forward
Ryan Humphrey rebounded a missed three-point try by Eric Martin and
put it back.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had one last chance. With the ball in the hands of
Terry, who brought a pile of national Player of the Year awards
with him to the tournament, they seemingly couldn't have been in
better position, even though it was not a vintage Terry
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Terry had the ball at the top of the key as the clock ticked to
five seconds. He drove on Alex Spaulding and put up a shot from 10
feet on the right wing. It missed.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson batted the ball and finally controlled it. His shot in
the lane over Humphrey came up short as the horn sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't get a piece of the ball, he got a piece of my arm,''
Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no call, and the Wildcats, just like fellow Pac-10
teams UCLA and Washington, took a first-round leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disbelief,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Sooners Coach Kelvin Sampson not only had dropped five straight
games in the tournament, he was 0-15 against the Wildcats during
his years as coach at Pac-10 member Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say this was a satisfying win does not do it justice,''
Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona ended the season with a 22-7 record. Terry, the Pac-10
leader in scoring, assists and steals, had carried the Wildcats,
but in this one, he made just 4 of 17 shots in scoring 15 points.
Bramlett, the Pac-10 runner-up in rebounding and double-doubles,
finished with 13 points and 12 rebounds, but missed the critical
free throws and failed to get to the rebound that Humphrey grabbed
to make the game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners aren't afraid to use 25 seconds off the shot clock
before firing away. After holding the ball, missing a three,
getting an offensive rebound (16 of their 38 rebounds were
offensive), holding the ball again, then scoring in threes while
the Wildcats (33 percent shooting) were misfiring, it didn't take
Oklahoma long to create a tempo to their liking against the Pac-10
scoring leader.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the Wildcats should have milked their advantage
harder in the low post with Wright and Bramlett, they concurred.
Arizona had an early nine-point lead until Bramlett picked up his
second foul and sat down with 8:34 left in the half. It took
Oklahoma only four minutes to tie the game with Bramlett out of
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were killing them in there,'' Bramlett said. ``We had a
stretch where we took a lot of long shots. We probably needed to be
more in tune with where our strengths and weaknesses were.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry, who spent the week trying to convince the freshmen that
there was no reason to be tight, denied that he was tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like I was hoisting up air balls,'' Terry said. ``I
took shots I normally take. A lot of times they rattled in and out
when I had a good look.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (21-10) moves on to the second round here Sunday
against North Carolina-Charlotte, a No. 5 seed that needed an
overtime Friday to dispatch 12th-seeded Rhode Island, 81-70. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
