<SLUG> BC-OBIT-POSTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT POSTEL, COUNCILMAN WHO RAN FOR NEW YORK MAYOR, DIES AT 59  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:   Pa., Mo., Fla.)   By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert I. Postel, a maverick Democratic New York City
councilman in the early 1970s who conducted a brief, unsuccessful
campaign for mayor, died on March 6 at Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center. He was 59 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Postel died after a 15-month struggle with cancer of the
esophagus, said his wife, Joan L.S. Postel.
</P>
<P>
   During his stint as a councilman at large in Manhattan starting
in 1970, Postel gained a reputation as a political gadfly. He often
embarrassed the Republican administration of Mayor John V. Lindsay
with self-publicized investigations into allegations of corruption
and patronage in government institutions, including the Housing and
Development Administration, the Spofford Juvenile Center and the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   His repeated assertions in 1971 that the Municipal Loan Program,
intended to help rehabilitate slum housing, had produced
multimillion-dollar fraud led to an investigation by the Manhattan
district attorney. Numerous officials and contractors were indicted
on charges stemming from allegations that they created fictitious
mortgages, offered kickbacks and paid for work not done. Only a few
of those charged were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Critics often accused Postel of making allegations that could
not be substantiated with the available evidence, leading to
well-publicized spats with officials from both parties. In the
Municipal Loan Program investigation, for example, Postel accused
the Lindsay administration of trying to hush him with the offer of
a city job. But a deputy mayor shot back that Postel was ``not
rational enough'' to be given a job in city government.
</P>
<P>
   On his official biography issued by the City Council, he listed
his interests as ``scuba-diving and, occasionally,
parachute-jumping.'' The morning after his wedding in October 1969,
he and his wife left their honeymoon hotel and handed out pamphlets
for his race for city councilman. In late 1972, Postel announced
that he would run for mayor and would refuse all donations from
real estate, banking or other major interests in the city. He
dropped out of the race in 1973 and ran instead for comptroller,
ending his career in politics when he lost.
</P>
<P>
   Born June 9, 1939, in New York City, Postel graduated from
Dartmouth College in 1960 and from Harvard Law School in 1967.
After he left politics, he founded the First Wall Street Co., which
specialized in converting rental buildings to cooperative
apartments and other real estate development in New York, Florida
and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a son, Darren, of
Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
