<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSP-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS ATTACK PATAKI'S PROPOSED BUDGET CUTS TO HOSPITALS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Attacking Gov. George Pataki directly for the
first time in four years, hospitals and health care workers began a
broadcast campaign Friday asserting that the governor's proposed
budget cuts would have dire consequences for health care, including
hospital closings.
</P>
<P>
   The effort began with a 60-second radio advertisement in the New
York metropolitan region and in Albany, and its sponsors say that
in trying to raise a public outcry to defeat the cuts, they are
prepared to expand the campaign to other parts of the state and to
television, and to spend millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in which he did not press for significant
changes in Medicaid, the health insurance program for the poor,
Pataki called this year for $800 million in cuts, despite a state
budget surplus expected to top $2 billion. Most of those cuts would
come in lower payments to hospitals and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy has never been better, the state has a huge
surplus, and so many hospitals are in financial trouble, why now
does the governor want to begin pummeling a major industry?'' asked
Kenneth E. Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, a trade group of 175 hospitals and nursing homes in
the New York metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, Pataki's press secretary, said: ``New York
spends more than $28 billion on health care, more than any other
state in the nation. The governor's budget maintains New York's
national leadership in health care.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's largest group of health care workers, and one of its
most politically powerful unions, 1199, the National Health and
Human Service Employees Union, remained neutral in Pataki's
re-election campaign last year. At the height of that campaign, the
president of the 120,000-member union, Dennis Rivera, stood by the
governor's side and praised him warmly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a coalition led by Rivera and Raske hopes to reprise its
effort of 1995, Pataki's first year in office, when it leveled an
advertising attack on the governor, his popularity plummeted and he
backed away from some of the deep cuts in Medicaid he was
proposing.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be much harder to damage the governor this time.
Four years ago, he was an unknown quantity, easily tarred as an
unfeeling archconservative. Today, he is much better known, highly
popular, widely seen as a moderate and fresh from a resounding
re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   Its sponsors say that the initial purchase of air time is
$125,000 for the first week, comparable to the spending in a
political campaign. The coalition says it is also sending mailings
to 250,000 homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
