<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOXING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXING MAKES A COMEBACK AT MADISON SQUARE GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM GERSHENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``One thing about the Sweet Science upon which all
initiates are in agreement is that it used to be better,'' wrote
A.J. Liebling in The New Yorker in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   So when heavyweight championship boxing returns to Madison
Square Garden Saturday night for the first time since 1992, it is a
safe bet that many will complain that the bout between Lennox Lewis
and Evander Holyfield can never live up to previous legendary bouts
at the Garden's various locations: Muhammad Ali vs. Joe Frazier or
Jack Dempsey vs. Luis Firpo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is little doubt that the fight has captured the
imagination of many in the city and signals that boxing may be
returning to its historic base. Nearly 21,000 tickets have been
sold for Saturday night's event _ a full house _ the first boxing
sellout at the Garden since Roberto Duran fought Davey Moore in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from $100 to $1,500, but the fight is
available on pay-per-view for $50, and it is being talked about in
the barbershops and bars, the taxis and sandwich shops of New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fights like this that make New York City the capital of
the world,'' said Mohammed Choudry, a taxi driver from Brooklyn who
has a miniature boxing glove hanging from his rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it will be hard to match the celebrity power of Frank
Sinatra, who sat ringside at the Ali-Frazier contest in 1971 and
took pictures for Life magazine. For Friday night's fight, the
Garden expects to counter with the presence of three New York
Knicks, two Rolling Stones, Jack Nicholson and Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the star-studded arena with all the silver
sparkles,'' Frazier said in a telephone interview from his gym in
Philadelphia this week.
</P>
<P>
   Oddsmakers see Holyfield, the WBA and IBF champion, as a slight
favorite, but some city residents remain skeptical. They wonder
whether Holyfield, the 36-year-old, 215-pound paladin who twice
defeated Mike Tyson, has the strength and stamina to defeat Lewis,
the WBC champion, who is three years younger and 30 pounds heavier,
but still relatively untested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't wager on either guy,'' said Dee Tu, the sushi chef
at the Hi-Life Bar and Grill on Amsterdam Avenue and 83rd Street.
``The fight's too close to call.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the past, the Garden stands alone as the site of
big-time boxing in New York. Many boxers prefer fighting in New
York, rather than in a ring assembled in a casino parking lot in
Las Vegas or Atlantic City. Local fans are considered
knowledgeable, and the blood and sweat spilled by former champions
in both the new and old Gardens lend the arena an undeniable
mystique.
</P>
<P>
   After sparring on Wednesday, Holyfield said that fighting Lewis
in the Garden would enhance his own legacy. ``You're happy to get
the opportunity to fight there,'' he said. ``That's how you become
a part of what they call history.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Garden history has been glorious. There have been nights
that diminished the sport. In February 1993, Ray Mercer was accused
of offering Jesse Ferguson $100,000 to lose _ in the middle of
their fight.
</P>
<P>
   Mercer was later cleared of the charge, but the taint on the
sport remained. With the scent of corruption lingering and the
competition from casinos intensifying, the Garden closed its boxing
department later that year.
</P>
<P>
   Even after it reopened in 1995, not every event went smoothly. A
July 1996 fight between Andrew Golota and Riddick Bowe dissolved
into a brawl that engulfed the arena, injured 23 people and led to
13 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis vowed that he would not let the Garden's history distract
him. ``I'll be thinking about that 20-by-20-foot ring, and that's
all,'' he said after a recent workout.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lewis' manager, Emanuel Steward, says he expects the New
York crowd to energize the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Garden makes people go crazy,'' the manager said. ``It's
the biggest crowd, the loudest fans, and all that electricity makes
everyone go cuckoo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
